<HEADLINE>
SMITH MULLED DEAL FOR FLAMES STAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Coyotes say they were in the  &UR; Theo
Fleury sweepstakes close to the end, but General Manager  &UR; Bobby
Smith said he would not give the Calgary Flames what they kept
asking for.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury, the Flames' all-time leading scorer, was dealt Sunday to
Colorado along with  &UR; Chris Dingman for role players  &UR; Rene Corbet,
 &UR; Wade Belak and future considerations, which likely will include a
prized prospect or an NHL player depending how far the Avalanche
advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked along those same lines,'' Smith said, ``with
compensation increasing as the team won playoff rounds. But I don't
think the deal we talked about was a good deal for us. We looked at
a couple different things, but they were pretty adamant in what
they wanted from us, and I wasn't going to give it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith would not say which players Flames General Manager  &UR; Al
Coates had his eye on, but he said the Coyotes definitely had
interest in Fleury, a right wing who is set to become an
unrestricted free agent this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Colorado definitely becomes a stronger team,'' Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix players weren't happy to hear the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``The West is strong, and everybody around us is obviously
making their teams better,'' said  &UR; Keith Tkachuk, the Coyotes'
captain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely doesn't help our chances,'' assistant captain
 &UR; Jeremy
 &UR; Roenick said. ``Fleury's a dynamic hockey player and he only makes
Colorado a stronger, more dangerous team.''
</P>
<P>
   Added  &UR; Rick Tocchet: ``Colorado was already a contender to win
the Cup. Getting Fleury just makes them the top favorites. But we
can't worry about that. . . . We've got to get our own problems
sorted out.'' &QL; 
Sullivan out again
</P>
<P>
   Left wing  &UR; Mike Sullivan went on injured reserve for the third
time this season on Sunday, this time with a separated right
shoulder suffered during the first period of Friday's 3-0 loss to
the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurt the last couple of days (leading up to Friday), and
then I went to hit a guy in the Rangers' game and it just got
worse,'' said Sullivan, who earlier this season missed three games
with a broken toe and 12 games with a broken rib. ``I thought I
could play with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said he didn't bother telling trainer &UR; Gord Hart about
it until the next day, after he had trouble sleeping. Now he'll be
sidelined for at least seven days. &QL; 
The mighty lucky Quint
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second period of Sunday's 4-1 loss to the Devils,
New Jersey enforcer  &UR; Krzysztof Oliwa skated hard from the red line
to body-slam Coyotes defenseman  &UR; Deron Quint into the corner
boards. The hit was so big, it knocked a whole sheet of glass into
the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that had been seamless glass, it would have killed me,''
Quint said. ``I'd have had no shoulders left and they'd be peeling
my face off the glass. Fortunately for me, it had some give to it.
He's a big man. It was a great hit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
