A2664 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NHRA-NOTEBOOK-AZR     03-01 0438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHRA-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHANDLER, Ariz. - Believe it or not, a victorious  &UR; John Force
was nearly speechless after stepping to the podium to collect a
71st career National Hot Rod Association Funny Car trophy Sunday in
the Checker Schuck's Kragen Nationals at Firebird International
Raceway Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``My tongue was stuck,'' said Force, who is not only terrificly
fast on wheels, but talks a mile a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Force blamed the temporary condition on a flu bug he's been
fighting all week.
</P>
<P>
   No problem.
</P>
<P>
   Force didn't need his mouth to reach the winner's circle. Just a
keen reaction eye at the starting line and a powerful Ford Mustang.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to stay away from taking some medication (Sunday), but
I finally had to take some stuff,'' said Force, who visited a Tempe
physician Friday and received a shot of antibiotics. ``I was
worried about my reaction time. My bones even tingled.'' &QL; 
All in the family
</P>
<P>
   With reigning Pro Stock champion  &UR; Warren Johnson sidelined after
losing in the second round, son  &UR; Kurt  &UR; Johnson carried the family
mantle.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Johnson, in a Chevy Camaro, prevented  &UR; Jeg Couglin from
posting a second straight win in an Oldsmobile Cutlass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the points leader for the first time in my career,''
Johnson said. ``I feel like (NASCAR Winston Cup's)  &UR; Mike Skinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we keep going down the track that we did (Sunday), I think
we've got a hot rod that will be a contender for the rest of the
season.'' &QL; 
Valley fever
</P>
<P>
   Valley racers fared well.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Keith Manogue of Glendale beat Glendale neighbor  &UR; Tim Landis in
the super street final.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Larry Marshall of Tempe won in super gas, and  &UR; Tom Yancer of
Chandler was runner-up in super comp. &QL; 
Speed demon
</P>
<P>
   Now that Top Fueler  &UR; Tony Schumacher has become the first driver
to surpass 330 mph, what's next?
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher didn't dare guess at what drivers might reach before
the season is over, but Goodyear's tires are believed capable of
withstanding speeds upwards to 350 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (innovative) five-disc clutch is a godsend,''  &UR; Eddie Hill
said. ``It's what is allowing us to go this fast.'' &QL; 
Pit stops
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's racing was tape delayed and will air next Sunday on The
Nashville Network. It also will be replayed March 14.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jim Epler of Phoenix lost to  &UR; Jerry Toliver in Funny Car's
first round.
</P>
<P>
   Several San Diego Padres players, including  &UR; Wally Joyner, were
guests of Top Fuel winner  &UR; Joe  &UR; Amato.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in four years, Pro Stock's  &UR; Jim Yates failed
to make Firebird's finals. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
