<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI VISITS MIAMI BEACH FOR FUND-RAISER AND SPEECH ON
EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH _ In a brief but lucrative visit, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani of New York City raised about $75,000 for his political
action committee at a fund-raising luncheon here on Sunday, then
called for more school choice programs in a speech to a Jewish
group.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's aides explained his trip last week by saying that the
group, Friends of Lubavitch, had invited him to speak at a dinner
for a yeshiva here. But the Republican mayor said on Monday night
that he had also come for the fund-raising luncheon, which cost
$1,000 per person, and for private meetings with people eager to
raise money for him if he decides to run for the U.S. Senate next
year.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor did not receive any money for his evening speech, his
aides said. But the proceeds from the luncheon, which drew about 75
people and was held at the home of Russell W. Galbut, a real estate
developer, will go to Solutions America, a political action
committee that Giuliani created last year to raise money for travel
and potential campaigns for higher office. The mayor has frequently
hinted in recent months that he would run for the Senate seat that
Daniel Patrick Moynihan will relinquish next year.
</P>
<P>
   Although Giuliani has been careful not to confirm that he would
run, he has appeared especially excited about the prospect since
Hillary Rodham Clinton announced last month that she, too, was
considering running for the seat.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has traveled out of state several times in recent
months to tout his record in speeches that have summarized his
accomplishments in New York City, including the drop in crime, the
reduction in the number of welfare recipients and his tax cuts. But
Monday night's speech was different because it focused on only one
concept, school choice, which he called ``the most important thing
that has to be done with education in America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have too many children in New York and all throughout
America who go to a school that they don't want to go,'' Giuliani
said on Sunday night to a group of 400 people, many of whom send
their children to the private yeshiva that the banquet was raising
money for. ``We are going to have a great public educational system
in America again, like we used to have 30 or 40 or 50 years ago,
when children are in the school that they want to be in.''
</P>
<P>
   After his 15-minute speech, Giuliani told reporters that he had
held three meetings on Saturday with ``people who were very
interested in raising money for me if I run for the Senate.'' All
of the potential donors _ whom the mayor would only describe as
``very strong supporters of the Republican party'' _ hoped that
Giuliani would run against Mrs. Clinton, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They believe they can raise a lot more money if she does enter
the race,'' Giuliani said. ``They would be very interested in
giving me a significant amount of support if Hillary ran for the
Senate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
