<SLUG> BC-GLF-TUCSON-FINAL-ROUND-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEDE WINS TUCSON `MATCH PLAY'  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ He is not ranked among the top 200 players in the
world, and hardly anybody can pronounce his name. Gabriel
Hjertstedt couldn't care less.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week some guy tried (to pronounce it) on the 10th tee at
Riveria (Country Club),'' the Swede said, referring to the Nissan
Open in Los Angeles. ``I felt sorry for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They butchered it a few times this week, too. But that's all
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Hjertstedt _ pronounced Yet-stet _ knows how to roll with the
punches, as well as the pats on the back. He experienced both
during the final round of the Touchstone Energy Tucson Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was up all the way, then I went straight down,'' he said of
Sunday's sudden-death victory over Tommy Armour III. ``I was
thankful to get a second chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The same hole that nearly cost Hjertstedt the tournament _ the
465-yard, water-lined 18th at Tucson National _ turned out to be
his personal winner's circle.
</P>
<P>
   The first time around, he suffered a double-bogey 6, blowing a
2-shot lead and certain victory when he 3-putted from 18 feet _ the
second putt lipping out from 2 feet. But in the one-hole playoff,
Hjertstedt bounced back to beat Armour with a 25-foot birdie that
found the cup on its last rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit three perfect shots,'' said Hjertstedt, who set up the
winning putt with a 2-iron from 226 yards into a crosswind.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the conclusion basically came down to a match-play
situation. Earlier in the afternoon, the more prestigious WGC Match
Play Championship, which bumped the Tucson tournament to satellite
status, also concluded in overtime when Jeff Maggert edged Paradise
Valley's Andrew Magee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it was just a good week for PING,'' said Hjertstedt,
who, like Maggert, represents the Phoenix-based equipment
manufacturer on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Hjertstedt, who shared the lead after the second round but
started the day 3 shots behind Armour and Barry Cheesman, closed
with a 4-under 68. His winning total of 12-under 276 was worth
$495,000 _ or $5,000 less than Magee received for his second-place
finish in the Match Play.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he would be back next year to defend his title
even if his world ranking eventually gets good enough to qualify
for the the Match Play, Hjertstedt offered a contrary opinion to
David Duval, who won this tournament last year but skipped out on
his defense for the $5 million jackpot in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always want to come back and defend a title. This event
deserves that kind of support,'' said Hjertstedt, 27, who splits
his time between homes in Helsingborg, Sweden, and Ponte Vedra
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Armour was philosophical after his 35-foot birdie attempt in
sudden death scooted 3 feet above the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't play golf for the money,'' said the grandson of the
legendary Silver Scot. ``But when you miss that many birdie putts _
and I made some good putts _ what can you do?''
</P>
<P>
   Armour, who collected $297,000, did have his chances. Five times
he had birdie opportunities inside 15 feet on the back nine but
could not connect.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Reid (69) and Scottsdale's Kirk Triplett (69) tied for
third, 1 shot out of the playoff. It was especially frustrating for
Triplett, who has yet to win in 10 years on the tour. He also had
it to 12 under down the stretch before bogeying the 18th hole.
</P>
<P>
   Cheesman was the victim of back-to-back bogeys on the final two
holes and ended up in a tie for fifth.
</P>
<P>
   The real hard-luck story on this day, however, was Steve Lowery,
who ended up in a tie for 20th place. After completing his round,
the Florida pro raced from the course in a panic after learning his
home in Orlando had burned to the ground. His family was not
injured, according to news reports.
</P>
<P>
   Hjertstedt, whose only previous victory was the 1997 BC Open,
gave a share of credit to his strength coach, Boris Kuzmic, and his
brother/caddie, Henric, for pumping him up for the playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've put a lot of hard work into the off-season, practicing
with Vijay (Singh), Jim Furyk and Duval. Boris has helped me add
about 25 yards off the tee, and I'm not tired anymore when I get
done playing,'' Hjertstedt said. ``I'm just trying everything I can
to get an edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Hjertstedt said Henric ``was working for free'' and would not
receive the usual 7 percent caddie fee. In fact, he wasn't even
going to buy his little brother a beer, even though Sunday was
Henric's 20th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not old enough,'' Hjertstedt deadpanned, showing that
some Swedes do have a sense of humor, even if most Americans can't
pronounce their names.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
