A2675 &Cx1f; tth-z
r S &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SWIFT-SP     03-01 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SWIFT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWIFT OUT TO PROVE HE'S STILL A KEEPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ Stan Williams gave up too soon. It was 1972, the
dying days of ownership's choker hold on players' salaries, and he
was tired of it.
</P>
<P>
   Williams still loved the game, but he felt he had to leave it to
make a decent living. Though he went 17-6 in his final two full
seasons, Williams never threw a pitch after his 32nd birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Williams spent one year in misery as a stockbroker. When he came
back to baseball as a Class AA manager, it was his most enjoyable
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``In retrospect, I wish I had stayed with it and pitched
longer,'' said Williams, the Mariners' pitching coach. ``I miss it
today. I still miss the competition.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Williams' pupils on the Mariners is Bill Swift, who
decided this winter to avoid such regrets. A 37-year-old
right-hander with a history of injuries, Swift attracted minimal
interest on the free agent market. Most teams said they'd get back
to him if they didn't get the pitchers they wanted most. It was an
invitation to retire.
</P>
<P>
   But Swift wasn't ready to leave. He was pleased with his 1998
season, in which he went 11-9 and made 26 starts, his most in five
years. So he accepted a minor-league contract from the Mariners on
Jan. 11, the last day the team could sign him before losing its
rights to him for months.
</P>
<P>
   Retirement had to wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was telling my wife about it,'' Swift said. ``How many guys
retire after having a good year? It's not that many. It's just in
you. When you do good, you just want to keep going back. Finishing
on a high note like Michael Jordan, he's an exception. But in
baseball, most of the guys retire once they stop getting guys out
or they can't hit anymore. We'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Swift is in camp as the leading candidate for the fifth spot in
the Mariner rotation, the oldest of six pitchers vying for the job.
He is eager for the exhibition games to begin because he wants to
find out how much he has left.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by last year, Swift should be useful. He grew tired at
the end, pitching only four innings in September, but he stayed
healthy all season for the first time since 1993. Swift went 21-8
that year for the San Francisco Giants, fulfilling the promise he'd
shown in Seattle before being dealt in the Kevin Mitchell trade
after the '91 season.
</P>
<P>
   Swift was on the disabled list seven times between 1994 and '97,
mostly with shoulder problems. The injuries robbed him of his best
stuff: the good, hard sinker that was his out pitch, and the
low-90s fastball he could throw with confidence when behind in the
count.
</P>
<P>
   On rare occasions, his former self comes back to visit for a
pitch or two. But Swift has learned to adjust, and it's the reason
he's still pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still missing that zip that I used to have,'' he said.
``It makes a big difference. I'm able to locate the stuff I have
now, but you lose that little extra that you can jam a guy with or
throw by somebody. It's not there, so I have to work on my other
stuff to counter that. I can tell it's just not the old Bill Swift,
but I'm getting older and it's not quite there.''
</P>
<P>
   Swift threw more than 103 pitches only once last year and never
worked past the seventh inning. Opposing hitters batted .306 off
him, and his ERA was 5.87. Still, he gave the Mariners more than
they hoped for when they signed him after a five-minute audition
last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who could have expected him to do what he did?'' said Woody
Woodward, M's vice president of baseball operations. ``He did an
excellent job for us. We didn't expect him to be that strong.''
</P>
<P>
   If the workout hadn't gone well, Swift said he likely would have
retired. The Dodgers wanted to see him pitch, but with a home in
Arizona, Swift didn't want to go to a team that trained in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to return this year to the Mariners, where coaches
know him and know he's effective when used regularly. Swift was 6-1
when pitching on four days' rest last year, and if he makes the
rotation, the M's will try to keep him on a set routine.
</P>
<P>
   The question, Swift knows, is health, and he does as much as he
can to keep fit. The Mariners administer a stress test in spring
training to measure what kind of shape each player is in, with
scores directly related to the amount of training a player does.
Swift trailed only Alex Rodriguez and Jamie Moyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given Billy's age, that's even more remarkable than Alex,''
trainer Rick Griffin said.
</P>
<P>
   But Swift will go only as far as his shoulder allows. He will
pitch if he's healthy, but he doesn't intend to finish his career
on a training table, constantly being worked on to keep pitching.
After making up his mind to continue his career, Swift wants the
game to tell him when he's done.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing is to go out in the games here and get people
out, show them I can still do that,'' Swift said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm out there and I'm struggling, then obviously I'll be
home when these guys go north. It's in the back of my mind, but I
don't worry about it. If I do retire, it's over and you start a new
life.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition season starts Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
