<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-HUSKIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS MOUNT FOR HUSKIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the matter of a month, the Huskies have gone
from exclamation points to question marks.
</P>
<P>
   Winning eight of nine Pac-10 men's basketball games during one
stretch, they were compared to the conference's best teams.
</P>
<P>
   You used to watch Washington in wonder. But the Huskies have
lost four of their past five games. Now you watch and wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Are they this bad? Were they that good? Will they make the NCAA
tournament? The NIT? Or will Saturday's game against Washington
State be their final game of the year?
</P>
<P>
   Of late, Washington has provided the best answers in the locker
room. On the court, the responses have been inaudible, inexplicable
and, to coach Bob Bender, inexcusable.
</P>
<P>
   ``With us, you never know which team is going to show up, the A
team or the B team,'' said reserve guard Bryan Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, the B team clashed with USC and UCLA and
committed 53 turnovers, shot horrendously and looked like strangers
to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, though, is still 16-11 overall and 9-8 in Pac-10
play. Everyone involved with the team seems to be banking on a
fourth-place finish being enough to sway the NCAA tournament
selection committee.
</P>
<P>
   But Washington must first beat WSU on Saturday. The factors that
favor the Huskies are these: they are playing at Edmundson
Pavilion, and the Cougars are the Pac-10's worst team.
</P>
<P>
   There are potential problems: In their first meeting, WSU
stunned Washington 72-71 in Spokane. The Cougars should be loose
and the Huskies tight, with everything to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Even if WSU wins, ESPN analyst Digger Phelps said Saturday
night, Washington deserves to go to the NCAA tournament if it
remains in fourth place. But Oregon or Cal, both 7-9, could still
tie the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   If Washington wins, UCLA coach Steve Lavin believes UW will
qualify.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten-and-8 in the premier conference in the country should be
enough to get to the tournament,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As baffling as the Huskies seem to be, the Bruins simplified the
take on Washington. It's not lack of effort, ballhandling and
perimeter shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a much better team at home than on the road,'' said
Travis Reed, who scored 10 points off the bench in UCLA's 79-62
victory on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Of Washington's last four losses, three were on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they're at home, they're more confident with their
shooting,'' Lavin said. ``All teams in our conference struggle
playing on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies shot 54.5 percent when they beat UCLA 93-83 on Jan.
31 at Hec Ed compared to 39.6 percent Saturday at Pauley Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Brown offered another theory _ complacency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got too comfortable,'' he said. ``We made a run and thought
we would coast right in. Obviously, that's not happening. We've got
to play through the whole season. Hopefully we'll come back and put
the punishment on Wazzu.''
</P>
<P>
   A trend is developing that is troublesome for Washington.
Opponents are crowding center Todd MacCulloch, preventing the
nation's leading field-goal percentage shooter from catching the
ball or attempting a shot. After scoring 26 points and hoisting 14
shots against UCLA at Hec Ed, MacCulloch was limited to 10 points
and five attempts on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Teams are collapsing on MacCulloch and conceding outside shots.
Washington is not retaliating, Deon Luton and Donald Watts only
sporadically foiling the strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're taking good shots,'' Bender said. ``They're just
missing.''
</P>
<P>
   The turnovers are something else. Washington can't cope with
full-court pressure. Bender drills his team, shows his players how
to break the traps. Some teams beat the pressure and create easy
buckets. Not Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The offense starts with point guard Senque Carey. He accepts the
challenge and responsibility but is struggling lately, unsure
what's wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to get other people involved early,'' he said.
``Maybe I'm not as aggressive. I'm getting tired, but that's not an
excuse at all. I'm going to fight through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what Washington must do now. Ultimately, these problems
could be beneficial if, for instance, they figure out how to
counter the MacCulloch defensive tactics. Also, Bender has been
searching for contributors _ reinserting Thalo Green into the
starting lineup, getting quality time from Greg Clark against USC
and Brown against UCLA. These discoveries will lengthen the
rotation and strengthen the team if the Huskies advance to the
NCAAs.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, looking like his father, former Sonic Fred, hit three
3-pointers and had two spectacular assists. He brought Washington
back from a 21-point deficit and nearly helped the Huskies make a
game of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``After he hit a couple, I was like: `Who's that?''' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't make the scouting report,'' Lavin said. ``But I knew
through the genes he was a good player.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington has many, according to Reed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pac-10 is rough,'' he said. ``They're still a legitimate
Sweet 16 team if they get on a roll, if MacCulloch starts to
destroy, if Luton and Watts start hitting.''
</P>
<P>
   So many ifs, so little time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
