</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-KITNA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KITNA ITCHING TO PROVE HE IS HAWKS' MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ Jon Kitna is pumped.
</P>
<P>
   That's nothing new, of course. The only remaining quarterback on
the Seahawks' roster was born fired up, and it is the excitement he
can generate and his own excitability that make it so easy for
fans, teammates and coaches to like him as a person and a player.
</P>
<P>
   But this is different, because so much about the Seahawks has
changed with the arrival of new general manager and head coach Mike
Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   There's a new offense, one that plays to Kitna's strengths.
There's renewed optimism that this team finally can make the
playoffs after a 10-year absence, the longest drought in the NFL.
There's the opportunity to be the starter that Kitna has longed for
since signing with the Seahawks in 1996 as an undrafted free agent
from Central Washington University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been this excited about football since probably
going into my junior year in college,'' Kitna said. ``I can't wait.
I cannot wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish the season started today,'' he added. ``I think I'd
have a pretty good chance to be the starter if it did.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitna punctuated that statement with a burst of laughter.
</P>
<P>
   It is funny how things have worked out. When veteran
quarterbacks Warren Moon and John Friesz were released last month,
it left only Kitna. That will change. Holmgren is looking to sign a
young veteran in free agency, select one quarterback in the draft
and then add a fourth by signing another college passer after the
draft.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren doesn't want to simply anoint Kitna the starter. It
could create too much pressure for a player who was a Seahawks fan
while growing up in Tacoma and has started all of six games in his
first three seasons _ the final five in 1998 and one in 1997. It
also isn't the way Holmgren does things. He wants Kitna to win the
job with his performances in minicamps and his play in the
preseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least I know I'm going to have a chance to compete and
that's all I've really asked for since the start _ just an open
chance to compete,'' Kitna said.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna has come a long way. Just three years ago, he was
preparing to be a high school math teacher and had to be talked
into going to a workout with the Seahawks. Two years ago, he led
the Barcelona Dragons to the World League championship. Six months
ago, he was No. 3 on the depth chart behind Moon and Friesz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just thinking about it the other day. I remember my
first interview in training camp (in 1996) and I was, like, `Why
are these guys interviewing me?' You know how thankful I was just
to be in that situation?'' he said. ``Now, it's more than that. I
know I'm going to have to take advantage of things and guys are
expecting me to perform.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitna also is excited about meeting that challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that helps me,'' he said. ``The last couple of years,
while I worked hard, I don't think I've worked as hard as I can,
especially in the offseason. I worked hard, but not as hard as I
could because I knew in the back of my mind, `Hey, they're not
expecting much out of me this year.'''
</P>
<P>
   Now the voices Kitna hears are those of his teammates and new
coaches saying they expect big things from him next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jon Kitna can play. He proved that this season,'' said running
back Ricky Watters, who played for Holmgren when the Seahawks' new
coach was offensive coordinator of the San Francisco 49ers.
``That's when Mike is probably at his best _ getting young
quarterbacks ready to be stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jon already has a lot of confidence. He already has a lot of
poise. He already has a good field presence,'' Watters said. ``But
anything that's missing, Mike will fill in those gaps.''
</P>
<P>
   The process already has begun. Kitna has been working out with
new strength and conditioning coach Kent Johnson, and meeting with
new offensive coordinator Mike Sherman and new quarterbacks coach
Mike Sheppard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just meeting with those guys and seeing the confidence in
their eyes, not in me, but just in themselves, it gets you fired
up,'' Kitna said. ``And just talking with coach Sheppard about
changing little things here and there that he thinks will help, I
can't say how excited I am. I hope we have five, six minicamps. As
much as I can absorb and learn, the better.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren's interest in free agents Doug Pederson (who signed
with the Philadelphia Eagles) and Gus Frerotte (who visited the
Seahawks last week) does not mean he is dissatisfied with Kitna.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jon Kitna has a lot of the good stuff,'' Holmgren said. ``I
like Jon's throwing motion, and he's got a good enough arm. In a
perfect world, I'd like him to get a little more juice on the ball
in some throws ... and you can work with a guy's hips and his steps
and his body mechanics to help that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to create a competitive situation, and Jon knows
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitna does understand that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely interested because those are the guys I'm going
to be working with,'' Kitna said of the team's ongoing search for a
free agent quarterback, ``but I don't rush to get up in the morning
to look at the paper and see who might be coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he is focusing his energy elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is my chance, I'm definitely looking forward to it and
planning to make the most of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
