<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UW BASKETBALL SQUADS TESTING SELECTORS' GRACES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It is extremely tough to be tough on the University of
Washington basketball programs. Girl Dawgs. Boy Dawgs. Whatever.
Former underdawgs still have a way of getting to you. The dangers
of sentimentality run amok.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, because of the Billy Joe Hoberts, the sanctions,
the Don James quitting, the Jim Lambright firing and Rick
Neuheisel's stinky little messes, we could dig at the football
program from now until the monsoons stop _ which could be never,
considering the downright Biblical hail storm that swept through
Seattle on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the UW football program can take it. It makes all
the money, packs the 72,000-seat stadium on Montlake, brings ABC to
town for key college football Saturdays, and generally, Husky
football stands as tall as any of this town's pro sports teams.
</P>
<P>
   Winter and spring at Washington, though, have been all about
trying to get somewhere remotely close to football's feverish
pitch. And certainly there is more than enough reason to extend
lofty expectations to basketball. Or so we thought.
</P>
<P>
   Husky basketball coach Bob Bender is seen as Superman, able to
resuscitate the respectability of the Marv Harshman years. UW
women's coach June Daugherty is bent on creating a run-and-gun
sequel to Chris Gobrecht's era of defensive prowess _ an 11-year
reign in which Washington was one of the NCAA's early leaders in
women's basketball popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Especially since Bender's arrival six years ago, the men's and
women's programs have been the Little Engines That Could, chugging
up the national RPI power rankings and giving us basketball junkies
hope that March, if not mad, certainly won't be a bust.
</P>
<P>
   So, then, what are we to make of all this disappointment this
season?
</P>
<P>
   The women (14-12, 10-7 Pac-10), who have for more than a decade
been trying to break through to a new level _ wasn't it just a few
years ago that Washington was aspiring to be an Elite 8 or Final
Four program? _ might have played themselves back into the good
graces of the NCAA tournament selection committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Husky women's 96-85 win Saturday over UCLA was good and
important, except that it put dreaded Oregon on top of the Pac-10
standings _ something no good Husky can claim as a laudable
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it should not be this close of a call for the women
Dawgs.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't get to the NCAA tournament with seniors Jamie Redd,
Amber Hall, Malinda Lynch and Molly Hills, what are Daugherty's
prospects next season?
</P>
<P>
   Redd, despite a rocky few years during the coaching change that
saw Husky women's basketball do a 180-degree turn in philosophy and
personality, is a gifted offensive player who can break open a
game. Hall, who has played through knee and ankle pains that would
have sidelined most NBA stars, made rebounding and junk points an
art form.
</P>
<P>
   But these women Dawgs are backing into March. Same for the men
(16-11, 9-8 in the Pac-10).
</P>
<P>
   If you can't breeze into the NCAA tournament with seniors Todd
MacCulloch and Donald Watts, what are Bender's prospects for
1999-2000?
</P>
<P>
   MacCulloch is a unique commodity. He is the national leader in
field-goal percentage. He's got the soft paws, as TV analyst Bill
Raftery marveled last March, when the Huskies got so inexplicably
hot, making it all the way to the NCAA Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   Watts, despite lapses in scoring, is as skilled a guard as
Washington will ever get, even though he was one of the Dawgs who
suffered third-degree burns in Los Angeles Saturday as Bruins
sensation Baron Davis went slam-crazy in a highlight festival of
sidewinders and behind-the-back passes to himself on eye-popping
fast breaks.
</P>
<P>
   All this at the expense of the poor Huskies, who finished the
weekend 0-2 in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few ugly questions to ponder as March dawns and the
only sense of madness we've got is why the Husky men or women
didn't do a better job of arriving at tournament time with more
solid ground under their feet?
</P>
<P>
   During this strange season, the men beat Arizona and UCLA, but
lost to Cal, Washington State and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   The women got in good jabs against Stanford and the Bruins, but
lost to Cal and Arizona State and twice to Arizona and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Coming down to the final week of Pac-10 action, the Husky men
and women each have one game left against Washington State. As long
as they beat the Cougars, the two Dawg teams probably have just
enough star power to squeeze out gracious nods from the selection
committees.
</P>
<P>
   MacCulloch and Watts are good TV, although now they might be
dealt to Carolina to take on Duke in some lambs-to-the-lions
first-rounder. The women, with their luck, will be in the region of
the No. 1 Boilermakers.
</P>
<P>
   Just getting in, by the skins of their teeth, is not what anyone
around here had in mind for the Dawgs, who should not be such
underdawgs anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-99 0032EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
