r n &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAPD-DUPED-2takes-LAD     03-01 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAPD-DUPED-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAPD DUPED ON GOLF FUND-RAISER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: This is a copyrighted story of the Los Angeles Daily
News) 
BY BETH BARRETT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's always embarrassing when one of the world's
most sophisticated law enforcement agencies _ a k a the LAPD _ gets
scammed at the very highest levels, but that's exactly what
happened, prosecutors say.
</P>
<P>
   And from a public appearances standpoint it could hardly be
worse, police acknowledged last week.
</P>
<P>
   William Patrick Bentley, 38, of suburban Tarzana so impressed
the top brass with his volunteer work over the years that one of
the department's charity arms, the Los Angeles Police Memorial
Foundation, never questioned a recommendation to pay him about
$60,000 to act as the first coordinator of its 28th annual
Police-Celebrity Golf Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   And what an event he supposedly lined up: Actor Tom Cruise was
to be host of the May 15 tourney, and Fox Sports was to broadcast
it live from the Rancho Park course in West Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Only it wasn't true, according to court records and interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Bentley was arrested and charged with three felony counts Feb.
12, including a grand theft allegation that he took about $30,000
in payments under ``false pretenses,'' and two forgery counts.
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview Friday with the Daily News, Bentley said he
has been unfairly accused and that his former supporters, Chief
Bernard C. Parks and Parks' wife, Bobbie, have ``cut me loose like
a red-headed stepchild.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he established a solid three-year track record as a
volunteer with the foundation and had arranged numerous celebrity
appearances in the past. He said the tournament agreement only
required him to get a host but did not state who the host had to
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a case of getting on several people's bad side,
and the chief and his wife are afraid to do anything about it
because of how it would look later on,'' Bentley said.
</P>
<P>
   While both the Parkses said they know Bentley, the chief said
the central issue was his conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``My take is that when you try to be open and to encourage
volunteerism, you, like other people, can get duped,'' Parks said.
``We weren't as astute as we could have been either in looking into
his background.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation that agreed to hire Bentley is made up of about
20 LAPD top commanders and civic leaders, with Parks its second
vice president, according to records and interviews. It has raised
over $6 million since 1972 to help the widows and orphans of slain
officers, as well as to provide crisis assistance to sworn and
long-term civilian employees.
</P>
<P>
   Parks was not present at last summer's meeting when the
foundation's current executive director, Alan Atkins, recommended
Bentley for the job, and the matter was decided without a formal
vote, said Atkins, a retired Los Angeles Police Department
sergeant. There was no contract, according to Atkins, but Bentley
disputes that, saying the contract was signed but that he never got
a copy.
</P>
<P>
   Bentley, whom police subsequently discovered had a Georgia
arrest record, is free on $20,000 bail, pending a March 12
arraignment in Municipal Court.
</P>
<P>
   His Los Angeles lawyer, Cathe Caraway, said Bentley's past brush
with the law was of no consequence and that the charges against him
were dropped almost immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot more to this story,'' she said, declining
further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Bentley said his prior arrest was in connection with a bad
check, which had been cleared up prior to the arrest _ and that the
misunderstanding was cleared up in a matter of hours, with an
apology. He said he even told the LAPD about the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Criminal defense attorney Ira Chester of Los Angeles, who has
spoken with Bentley but has not yet been retained, suggested an
LAPD investigation of alleged crimes involving its own memorial
fund _ laden as it is with emotional meaning for police officers _
is on its face improper.
</P>
<P>
   ``What police officer could investigate the widows and orphans
fund in an unbiased manner?'' Chester said. ``Then they present the
investigation to the DA, who they work with all the time. There is
an inherent conflict of interest, tainting the whole thing from the
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy District Attorney Gregson Somes said the decision to file
felony charges stemmed from the extent of the alleged deception and
amount of money involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look at the totality of the circumstances,'' added
Detective Steve Kirby, who handled the case in the LAPD's financial
crimes division. ``He deceived the people he was reporting to as to
what he had accomplished. It was theft under false premises and two
forgeries. This was not just some little slap on the hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Atkins and others said Bentley had a convincing style, both
personable and friendly. He made an effort to know police officers
and their families, and paid particular attention to Bobbie Parks,
one police source said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Atkins, ``Patrick was a very likable person, and there was
nothing to indicate it wouldn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Bentley said he and Atkins crossed paths over the golf
tournament but that he considered Bobbie Parks to be a ``good
friend, until this.''
</P>
<P>
   Bentley added he spent innumerable hours volunteering on ``a
whole cadre'' of jobs for the LAPD. As such, he was a common
presence at downtown's Parker Center, where he helped coordinate
events with department officials, police said.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
