<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPMEN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDNER MISS SINKS PEPPERDINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ Jelani Gardner missed a potential tying
3-pointer with six seconds left and the Pepperdine men's basketball
team lost 58-54 to Santa Clara in the semifinals of the West Coast
Conference Tournament on Sunday night at Toso Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine (19-12) was bidding for its first WCC
Tournament-final appearance since 1994. The Waves were burned by
hot 3-point shooting by the Broncos, who shot 77 percent (10 of 13)
from beyond the arc in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara, which advanced to tonight's championship against
top-seeded Gonzaga, improved to 14-14. The Broncos took the lead
for good, appropriately enough, from behind the arc. Delano
D'Oyen's 3-pointer made it 55-52 with 2:05 left.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves could only manage two free throws the rest of the way.
Gardner, a two-time All-WCC pick who could have played his final
college game, finished with 13 points.
</P>
<P>
   Kelvin Gibbs led the Waves with 17 points and seven rebounds. He
was a force offensively in the paint to start the second half,
scoring the Waves' first 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine came out better defensively than it did in its
first-round win over San Francisco. USF only had nine turnovers the
entire game on Saturday, but Pepperdine forced Santa Clara into
exactly that many in the first half and 17 for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Marc McDowell's 15-footer with five seconds left gave the Waves
a hard-fought 30-29 halftime lead. Despite the turnovers, the
Broncos led most of the half thanks to 3-point shooting; six of
Santa Clara's eight field goals in the half were threes.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara was 6 of 9 from beyond the arc in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine, as it did against USF, jumped out to a quick
first-half lead. Gibbs scored the first five points of the game and
the Waves eventually took a 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos, who sat on the visitors' bench in their home arena,
didn't have much offense in the game's first 7{ minutes: two
3-pointers from Nathan Fast.
</P>
<P>
   Fast, a junior guard and the Broncos' leading scorer in the
regular season, had a team-high 19 points. D'Oyen had 15, all on
3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara was playing without second-leading rebounder Todd
Wuschnig, who experienced an irregular heartbeat in Saturday's
first-round game against Loyola Marymount. The Broncos still
managed to outrebound the Waves 29-23.
</P>
<P>
   In the other WCC semifinal:
</P>
<P>
   __ Gonzaga 70, St. Mary's 57: The top-seeded Bulldogs (24-6)
built a 37-22 halftime lead and held on to eliminate the Gaels
(13-18), who got a tournament-high 31 points from guard Frank
Allocco.
</P>
<P>
   All 10 Gonzaga players scored, led by Matt Santangelo's 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
