<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2698 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     03-01 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Sequel to Rodzilla makes big box office
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Fran Blinebury
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Charles Barkley's complaint is NBC has
fallen in love with the Lakers and is trying to turn them into a
weekly series.
</P>
<P>
   And why not?
</P>
<P>
   The last time the network gave a handful of off-balance,
self-centered egos a regular slot in the lineup, Seinfeld became a
big hit and everybody went home fat and happy.
</P>
<P>
   So add Dennis Rodman to the most dysfunctional family this side
of daytime television, and the potential for weirdness could not be
quantified with the world's longest tape measure.
</P>
<P>
   Cross-dressing rebounders with bad memories _ today on the
Peacock.
</P>
<P>
   When his 26 minutes of action were completed with 10 rebounds,
two points and a bevy of elbows and shoves in the Lakers' 106-90
victory over the Rockets on Sunday, Rodman stopped for a chat at
midcourt with NBC's Ahmad Rashad that produced this sentimental,
post-Valentine keepsake:
</P>
<P>
   Rodman: ``I want to say hello to my wife uh ''
</P>
<P>
   Rashad: ``Carmen.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman: `` uh yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the NBA in the post-lockout, play-it-in-fast-forward
schedule and in the dawning of the after-Jordan Era of the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least, these are the 21st century Lakers so desperate for
leadership and direction they have turned to the guru of goofdom,
which is like going to see Dr. Kevorkian for an upset stomach.
</P>
<P>
   These are the days when the old Lakers _ Magic, Kareem and
Worthy _ must wish they were dead, so at least they could turn over
in their graves.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers of five championships in the 1980s used to be
Showtime. Then they became the Lake Show. Now they are the Freak
Show.
</P>
<P>
   But in Hollywood, nothing sells like way-over-the-top excess.
Which is why the roll call of celebrities at the Great Western
Forum went well beyond regulars Jack Nicholson and Dyan Cannon, who
are as permanent a part of the place as the plumbing fixtures.
There was Penny Marshall down along the baseline and Greg Kinnear
in a midcourt seat. Jon Lovitz inexplicably found a comfy spot on
the floor at Kinnear's feet, and Lou Gossett Jr. stood behind one
basket and pumped his fist.
</P>
<P>
   What, no Monica Lewinsky dancing with the Laker Girls?
</P>
<P>
   But there was Michael Jordan himself, ensconced in the place of
honor next to Nicholson, the king returning to see how the peasants
have been getting on in his absence.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the circus was in town, and there might have been a
shortage of rings. Not counting, of course, those in Rodman's ears,
nose and navel.
</P>
<P>
   This was a Lakers team that seven days earlier was in turmoil at
6-6, having just lost a third consecutive Sunday game on NBC. So
they spent the week firing head coach Del Harris, replacing him
with former Clark Kent look-alike Kurt Rambis, signing the bearded
lady in Rodman. They now have won three straight games, including
two against the Clippers and this one over the Rockets, who are in
the getting-acquainted, always-mending stage of development.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers got 21 points in 19 minutes off the bench from Rick
Fox, a decent inside game from Shaquille O'Neal and always have had
raw individual talent coming out their ears. But what they have now
_ or at least believe they have _ is a tough attitude about how to
play the game. Brought to them by Rodman, of all people.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to be a good basketball team, you have to be
unselfish,'' said the Nutty Professor. ``You have to bite your
tongue and your pride and just go out there and win.''
</P>
<P>
   The sermon from the mount.
</P>
<P>
   The questions are what will become of both these teams by the
time the playoffs arrive in May. By then, the Rockets should at
least know each other upon sight and will be healthy or a pile of
old bones. The Lakers are a tougher riddle, because every day will
produce another set of problems in the NBA's high-profile
kindergarten.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lakers are still not a championship team,'' Barkley said.
``A week ago, they were .500 and firing their coach. Now they have
about the same record as us. So they have Dennis. He gives them
rebounding. He doesn't make them the team to beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind playing against Dennis. I think he's funny the
way he plays everybody. The guy can cry on request. He's done it
before on Oprah.''
</P>
<P>
   Now though, only tears of relief from Hollywood, always starved
for a new wild act, convinced the freak show is for real.
</P>
<P>
   If there was any sense of nostalgia being back on the same court
with his former championship buddy Scottie Pippen in another
uniform or playing under the watchful eyes of Jordan, Rodman
wouldn't confess.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no special feelings,'' he said. ``I knew (Jordan)
was going to be here. We are all grown men.''
</P>
<P>
   That solves another mystery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
