A2733 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-USOLYMPICCOMMITTE     03-01 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL TO CRITICIZE USOC 
</HEADLINE>
 OLYMPIC COMMITTEE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The United States Olympic Committee, already
tarnished by association with the Salt Lake City scandal, will face
criticism Monday from an independent ethics panel for failing to do
more to prevent the abuses that have rocked the Games, sources
familiar with the report said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   No major new disclosures of wrongdoing are expected in the
report being issued by a five-member commission headed by former
Sen. George Mitchell of Maine. But by calling for an overhaul of
USOC practices, specifically tougher oversight of US cities bidding
to host future Games, the report is expected to demonstrate ways in
which earlier action by the USOC might have spared the Olympics
from the biggest crisis in its modern history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concentrating on making recommendations which, if
adopted, will prevent the kinds of abuses we've seen from happening
in the future,'' Mitchell said Sunday in a telephone interview. He
said the report would not be finished until late in the evening,
and he declined to discuss specifics.
</P>
<P>
   USOC officials said Sunday they had not yet seen the report, and
would have no comment until they could thoroughly review it.
Mitchell's commission, though independent, was assembled by the
USOC in December to provide an outside review. The USOC has
scheduled a news conference for Wednesday in Washington to respond
to Mitchell's findings.
</P>
<P>
   The Mitchell commission's report comes three weeks after a
separate ethics panel detailed the lavish inducements and
aggressive efforts by the Salt Lake Organizing Committee to win
votes from International Olympic Committee members in its
successful pursuit of the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   That 300-page report focused primarily on the actions of two
former Salt Lake Olympic officials, Thomas Welch and David Johnson.
But it also questioned USOC practices and internal controls.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Salt Lake ethics report detailed a 1995 e-mail
correspondence in which Alfredo LaMont, who at the time was
director of international relations for the USOC, discussed with
other senior USOC officials their ``debt to the Sudanese IOC
members.'' A later e-mail from LaMont said the debt was incurred
``to secure votes.'' Another top USOC official endorsed that
interpretation, writing an e-mail saying, ``Seems to me a deal is a
deal and Sudan delivered. . . . May need Sudan again in future.
Don't burn bridges.''
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail exchange represented the clearest suggestion to date
that USOC officials were more than passive observers in offering
inducements to win the votes of IOC members. In their defense, USOC
officials stressed that the issue being discussed involved a
promise of training programs for Sudanese athletes; they said that
should be viewed far differently than the excesses of the Salt Lake
organizers, such as scholarships to IOC members' children, Super
Bowl excursions for them, and shopping trips for their wives.
</P>
<P>
   USOC officials also noted that they adopted new guidelines for
bid cities in November 1997 _ a year before the scandal surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Lake ethics report also described how LaMont, while
working for the USOC, entered into private consulting contracts
with the Salt Lake bid committee that funneled money to an IOC
member from Barbados. LaMont resigned from the USOC in January when
his private business dealings became known.
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Lake ethics panel said the USOC should ``exercise
caution not to place bid cities in compromising positions. For
instance, it is clear that the USOC played a role in the (Salt
Lake) bid committee's commitment to train Sudanese athletes. While
there is nothing inherently improper about this kind of
expenditure, it may draw bid cities into . . . assistance programs
that are susceptible to abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   With regard to LaMont's consulting contracts, the Salt Lake
report also chided the USOC, saying the organization should
``ensure that its employees are not involved in private financial
transactions with bid committees,'' which it described as a
conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Although LaMont's activities were covered by the Salt Lake
ethics report, Mitchell's report is expected to focus on them as
well. USOC officials have said they believe existing disclosure
requirements for employees are adequate, and they said they had no
way to prevent secret side deals.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, reports also have surfaced about USOC members
accepting questionable gifts and hospitality from Salt Lake City
organizers before choosing the city as a candidate to host the 2002
Games.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Mitchell commission report has been eagerly
anticipated, Mitchell has sought to downplay its findings. Last
week, he cautioned the panel's job was made difficult by the
limited amount of time, as well as the refusal by some members of
the Salt Lake bid committee to speak with Mitchell's investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The release of Mitchell's report will kick off a month that
Olympic officials hope will mark the beginning of the end of the
turmoil that began in December. An IOC investigative panel spent
last weekend reviewing the Salt Lake City ethics report to decide
whether to recommend more expulsions of members at a March 17-18
meeting in Lausanne, Switzerland. Already nine IOC members have
resigned or been suspended; 10 more were implicated in the Salt
Lake ethics report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-99 0224EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
