<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 02:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2737 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-NOT     03-01 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-NOTREDAME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC LEAVES LASTING IMPRESSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. _ At the beginning of the season, they made it
their objective to prove everybody wrong. Picked to finish last in
a preseason poll of Big East coaches, the members of the Boston
College men's basketball team set out to prove they were better
than that. But after Sunday's 78-59 loss to Notre Dame before a
Joyce Center crowd of 9,043, the Eagles wound up proving everybody
right by staggering across the regular-season finish line _ in last
place.
</P>
<P>
   Undermanned and overmatched for much of the season, BC wound up
6-20 _ its first 20-loss campaign since 1989-90 (8-20) _ and 3-15
in the conference to land the dreaded No. 13 seed in the Big East
tournament at Madison Square Garden. The Eagles will face fourth
seed Syracuse at 1 p.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may be a last-place team, but if we're healthy and if a
couple of breaks go our way, then it might be a totally different
scenario,'' said junior forward Michael Cotton. ``If we weren't as
beat up and weren't as tattered as we are, we would've had a better
showing today. But Kenny Harley, I mean he carried us the whole
game.''
</P>
<P>
   With Cotton playing on a tender right ankle and freshman forward
Brian Ross battling foul trouble, and an aching back and ankle to
boot, sophomore guard Harley led the Eagles by tying his career
high with 21 points on 9-for-17 shooting, including 3 of 6 from
3-point range. However, it wasn't enough to overcome Notre Dame's
low-post tandem of 6-foot-9-inch freshman forward Troy Murphy and
6-11 senior center Phil Hickey, who combined for 38 points and 21
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Making his final home-court appearance on Senior Day, Hickey led
the Fighting Irish (14-15, 8-10), who had all five starters score
in double figures, by scoring 21 points and grabbing 9 rebounds.
Hickey's points matched his career high, set last Feb. 11 against
BC.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the last game so it's pretty emotional,'' said Hickey,
who helped the Irish avenge a 78-67 loss at Conte Forum Jan. 27,
marking the first of BC's three consecutive conference victories
this season. ``You kind of enjoy things more since it's the last
time we get to run out of the locker room. You just sit back and
appreciate how lucky you really are. Coach (John MacLeod) wanted us
to go out on a winning note, and that's what we did.''
</P>
<P>
   By halftime, however, it appeared to be a different story. The
Eagles went on a 10-0 run to rally from a 24-19 deficit to take a
29-24 lead on Harley's stop-and-pop jumper off a turnover. BC went
on to a 34-30 halftime lead and thrice increased it to 6 (36-30,
38-32, and 43-37) in the second half before going into a 4:52
drought between Jonathan Beerbohm's foul-inducing drive and
Harley's 3-pointer with 8:14 to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we played a good first 20 minutes,'' said BC coach Al
Skinner. ``But fatigue was a problem and foul trouble was a
problem, but we also missed some shots. We missed an awful lot of
open looks.''
</P>
<P>
   It enabled Notre Dame to take the lead for good, 47-46, on
Antoni Wyche's breakaway basket with 12:04 left. The Irish extended
it to 56-46 before Harley's trey snapped BC out of its doldrums.
After Murphy (17 points, 12 rebounds) threw down a follow dunk and
Hickey scored back-to-back baskets, Dwayne Pina got it to 62-54
with a free throw. But that was as close as the Eagles got after
Hickey helped extend Notre Dame's lead to 68-54 by tying his career
high when he banked in a leaner just before the shot clock expired
with 2:03 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like we're a 13th seed,'' Harley said. ``That's
why we're hoping to go to the Big East tournament and maybe get an
upset, because we don't play like a 13th seed. And we certainly
don't feel like it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
