<SLUG> BC-BKW-BIG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC WOMEN SENT PACKING 
</HEADLINE>
 EAST-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PISCATAWAY, N.J. _ It's not as if the Boston College women's
basketball team cherished the thought of meeting the University of
Connecticut in the Big East tournament semifinals Monday night. But
the alternative _ packing their bags and boarding the bus to ride
back to Boston _ certainly was more distasteful.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles had to settle for the latter, though, as Georgetown
defeated BC, 64-59, Sunday before 3,035 at Rutgers's Louis Brown
Athletic Center and eliminated the Eagles from the tournament. The
Hoyas will face UConn, who beat St. John's Sunday, 82-58.
</P>
<P>
   Things did not bode well for the Eagles (21-7, 12-7) before the
game as freshman Becky Gottstein hobbled to the bench on crutches.
On Friday she and teammate Brianne Stepherson were named to the Big
East all-rookie team; in Saturday's game she suffered a sprained
ankle in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   BC coach Cathy Inglese said the team definitely felt the loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Becky is one of those kids that what makes her so good is
she's so unpredictable,'' Inglese said. ``She gets rebounds and
goes after loose balls. We missed that the first half.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not all they missed.
</P>
<P>
   Georgetown (18-10, 11-8), which had lost to BC earlier this
season, went to work right away shutting down the Eagles' offense.
A 3-point shot by junior Alissa Murphy giving the Eagles a 7-4
lead. But it was short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   Georgetown sophomore Katie Smrcka-Duffy and freshman Sylita
Thomas went to work, and within two minutes the Hoyas had a 23-15
lead. When Georgetown wasn't hitting its first shots, it was
getting second and third shots, and BC shot just 29 percent for the
half. The Hoyas, who opened an 18-point lead, were led in the half
by senior Melba Chambers (15 points, including three treys), and
Smrcka-Duffy (12). No BC player scored in double digits and the
Eagles were down at the break, 41-24.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of confidence in this team,'' Inglese said. ``I
really felt we could win this ballgame, (but) obviously not playing
like we did the first half.''
</P>
<P>
   But confidence was not what BC needed, offense was.
</P>
<P>
   With the Eagles down by 18, Murphy hit a 3-pointer, followed by
a jumper by Jamie Cournoyer, and free throws by Nicole Conway and
Stepherson. BC had gone on a 8-0 run, but was still down by 10.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly Georgetown had cooled off from its 49 percent shooting
in the first half. When Murphy fired in a 3-pointer with 1:12 to
go, the Eagles had closed within 60-55. Stepherson then scored a
layup, and the Hoyas' lead had evaporated to 3 with one minute to
go.
</P>
<P>
   But Chambers charged the BC basket and her layup put Georgetown
in front by 5. Two more free throws would seal the win. ``Melba was
as hot as a firecracker today,'' said Georgetown coach Pat Knapp.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers and Smrcka-Duffy each finished with 19 points, while
Thomas had 16 points and 13 rebounds. Murphy, who made four of
seven 3-pointers, finished with 18 points for the Eagles. Center
Whitney Steele added 12, Stepherson 11, and Cournoyer 10.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that the Eagles were sent packing, their next
stop should be the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's absolutely no way we couldn't be in it,'' Inglese
said, adding that Gottstein should be ready then.
</P>
<P>
   The Hoyas, meanwhile, have to face UConn Monday night. The
Huskies, led by guard Shea Ralph's 30 points, defeated St. John's
despite a season-high 28 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Ashja Jones added 12 points, Tamika Williams 10, and Svetlana
Abrosimova 8 and six assists as the five-time defending champion
Huskies (25-4) beat the Red Storm (13-18) for the 22d time in 23
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our motto now is defend, rebound, advance,'' said Knapp. But
Georgetown might need more than a motto; UConn soundly beat the
Hoyas, 106-49 and 82-59, in their two meetings this season.
</P>
<P>
   In other games, No. 7 Rutgers shut down Miami for almost nine
minutes in a 79-53 victory.
</P>
<P>
   No. 10 Notre Dame took an 83-53 win over Villanova as Niele Ivey
hit two straight 3-pointers to ignite an early 16-3 spurt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
