<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-AMERICA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAINE LATEST NEW ENGLAND FALL GUYS 
</HEADLINE>
 EAST-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, Del. _ Now the fall is complete. On Friday night, Boston
University said an early goodbye in the America East tournament. On
Saturday, Hartford, Northeastern, and Vermont all made their
curtain calls for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday it was Maine's turn, completing a purge of New England
teams in three days, as the fourth seed Black Bears were blown away
by top seed Delaware, 90-73, at the Carpenter Center.
</P>
<P>
   The victory sends Delaware (24-5) into next Saturday's
conference final against Drexel, which got all of Mike DeRocckis's
game-high 16 points in the first half of a 55-37 defeat of Hofstra.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the New England entries, Maine figured to have the best
chance to make it to the final. The Black Bears (19-9) were coming
off a strong win over Hartford in Saturday's quarterfinals and were
relying on the combination of former Boston College players Andy
Bedard and Nate Fox to pull off the upset.
</P>
<P>
   The Black Bears also carried a sense of confidence, brought on
by a 70-59 win over the Hens at Delaware during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   But that was January, and now it is March, and Delaware showed
why it was the No. 1 seed in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not all that disappointed with our effort,'' said Maine
coach John Giannini, who could only watch in frustration as the
Blue Hens shut down the inside game of Fox (12 points, 10
rebounds). Bedard scored 24 points, but only 5 in the first half
when Delaware took control. ``It probably had as much to do with
Delaware,'' said Giannini. ``We just didn't have an answer for what
they were doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Delaware, which has won 12 straight and nine straight by 13 or
more points, had lots of answers Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It got them from league MVP Mike Pegues, who poured in a
game-high 32 points and dominated early; Maine transfer John
Gordon, who ran the offense and also scored 18 points; and center
John Bennett, who was instrumental in frustrating Fox all
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frustrating was the best way to describe it,'' said Bedard,
who was unable to stop the constant Delaware attack that produced a
43-30 halftime lead that climbed to 30 before the Black Bears cut
it down to the final margin. ``I was just terrible in the first
half. We just made so many mistakes and got ourselves into a
hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Delaware can do that. It has done that except for one stretch in
midseason when it lost three of four.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been pretty good all year,'' said Delaware coach Mike
Brey. ``Today we were very ready to play again. We're pretty good
offensively. We know how to use our offensive weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   Giannini was even more effusive. ``They play the game as well
together as any team in America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If Delaware is playing in its own building, at its own tempo, no
one could argue with that assessment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
