 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2524 - March 1, 1999   NEWS AND FEATURE
SUMMARY -- No. 2524 -- March 1, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. WILL MONICA EVER GET HER BLUE DRESS BACK? Monica Lewinsky's
infamous ``DNA-stained'' blue dress is just the latest scandal
artifact to be preserved in the National Archives' collection of
objects related to the Kennedy assassination, Watergate and the
various independent-counsel investigations that followed. As such,
the dress may come to be a part of the curious gallery of
anti-relics by which presidential fiascoes live on in glass cases
and the public imagination. By Thomas Mallon. From The New York
Times Magazine. 1,000 words.
________________________________________________________ 2. THE
PERSISTENCE OF POLYGAMY When 10,000 global journalists descend on
Utah to cover the 2002 Olympics, they may well be attracted to the
story of a heritage quite apart from the Mormon Tabernacle Choir
and the lovely snow - the existence of a kind of polygamy in which
women are the alleged victims of sexual crimes and the virtual
property of men - often uncles, cousins and other family members -
who openly boast of numerous wives and virtual impunity from the
law. By Timothy Egan. From The New York Times Magazine. Full-length
(3,700 words) + edited article available. 3. NEWT'S SHADOW The
Republicans in Congress, by and large, remain spellbound by the
GOP's right-wing base. This is the true end of Reaganism, the real
legacy of Newt Gingrich - and Speaker Dennis Hastert's everyday
nightmare. By James Traub. From The New York Times Magazine.
Full-length (4,000 words) + edited article available. 4. BLACK
MARKET ANTIBIOTICS AND RESISTANT GERMS When a Hong Kong woman who
entered hospital recently with a fever died weeks later despite
treatment with antibiotics, it sounded an alarm in the medical
community there and elsewhere. The indiscriminate use of
antibiotics and their easy availability on the Hong Kong black
market have raised fears that bacteria are becoming dangerously
resistant. Experts, however, say that a larger problem comes from
hospitals, where patients are sometimes left on antibiotics for
weeks at a time. From Der Spiegel. 650 words. (English translation
available.) 5. FOUND IN TRANSLATION An English version of Eugenio
Montale's work leads readers through the labyrinthine paths of
Italy's greatest modern poet. Reviewed by Nicholas Jenkins. New
York Times Book Review. 2,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
FROM NATURE NEWS SERVICE (N/A France and Spain) Embargo 19h00 GMT
March 3.
</P>
<P>
   A. THE FASHION FORMULA Why are there just a handful of knots in
everyday use for knotting a tie? The answer has now emerged - not
from a fashion house, but from the physics department of the
University of Cambridge. By Karen Southwell. 500 words. B. HOW TO
TICKLE A T-CELL Over the years, immunologists have been gradually
filling in the picture of how the immune system recognizes viral
infection and conveys this information to killer T cells. Now a
particularly useful and intriguing piece has been added to the
picture. By Eleanor Lawrence. 1,000 words. C. SPANISH FLU KEEPS IT
SECRETS Frozen tissue from a victim of the worldwide influenza
pandemic of 1918 who was buried in the Alaskan permafrost is
helping to identify the genome of a virus that caused one of the
most devastating outbreaks of epidemic disease in modern times. By
Eleanor Lawrence. 800 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
INTO THE NIGHT Bats have left few fossils behind, so their
evolution remains an enigma among researchers. One of the major
points of contention is which came first, echolocation or flight.
Carl Zimmer discusses the debate in the scientific community over
these unusual creatures. From Discover magazine. 1,000 words +
photos. 8. OLYMPICS - STADIUM PHOTOS Four colour photos are
available of the 110,000 seat stadium in Sydney that will be the
venue for the opening and closing ceremonies, football, track and
field events of the 2000 Olympic Games. From The Sydney Morning
Herald. 9. INITIAL LUSTRE OF NEW MONEY BEGINS TO FADE FOR EUROPE
Amid political interference, the euro has yet to foster a unified
monetary policy. By John Vinocur. International Herald Tribune.
1,000 words. Please fax to Paris 33.1.47.42.80.44 or
33.1.47.42.18.81 I am interested in story no. ______ from summary
