A2862 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBAC     03-01 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 7)  
(lb) 
 By SCOTT VEALE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BRIGHT ANGEL TIME &LR;  By Martha McPhee. Harvest/Harcourt Brace,
$13. Set in the 1970s, this first novel is narrated by a thoughtful
8-year-old girl who struggles to make sense of her family's chaotic
life on the road after her abandoned mother is lured to Big Sur by
an itinerant therapist to the well-to-do. The result is ``a hard
and shining artifact of personal and social upheaval,'' Walter Kirn
wrote in The New York Times Book Review in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONFEDERATES IN THE ATTIC: DISPATCHES FROM THE UNFINISHED CIVIL
WAR &LR;  By Tony Horwitz. Vintage Departures, $14. A former Wall Street
Journal reporter and Civil War buff takes up with a troop of
hard-core battle re-enactors, toughing it out in the field and
tracking down secession-related controversies and die-hard keepers
of the faith throughout the South. Last year the reviewer Roy
Blount Jr. found this to be a ``splendid commemoration of the war
and its legacy'' as well as ``an eyes-open, humorously no-nonsense
survey of complicated Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONCEIVED IN LIBERTY: JOSHUA CHAMBERLAIN, WILLIAM OATES, AND
THE AMERICAN CIVIL WAR &LR;  By Mark Perry. Penguin, $15.95. This
focuses on the eventful careers of two rival commanders at
Gettysburg _ one from Maine, the other from Alabama _ who started
as poor farm boys and wound up in politics. The result is ``an
ambitious ... history of the North and South from before the war to
the end of Reconstruction,'' Frederick Allen wrote in 1998. ``The
author reaches far beyond their own lives to capture the complex
spirit of the times.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AN INSTANCE OF THE FINGERPOST &LR;  By Iain Pears. Berkley, $7.99.
This intricate literary thriller about the murder of an Oxford don
in Restoration England _ and the far greater crime to which it is
linked _ unfolds through the voices of four very different
narrators. ``Pears, with a painstaking, almost forensic attention
to detail, constructs his world like a master painter of trompe
l'oeil,'' Andrew Miller wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE EDGE OF THE SEA &LR;  By Rachel Carson. Mariner/Houghton
Mifflin, $14. Seven years before the classic ``Silent Spring,'' the
author turned her formidable gaze on the narrow strip of sea bottom
that ebbs and flows with the tides, and the rich web of life
thriving along the Atlantic coastline. ``Carson's book is
beautifully written,'' Jonathan N. Leonard wrote in 1955. ``People
who get bored by too much lolling on beaches should read it as a
guidebook.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RACHEL CARSON: THE WRITER AT WORK &LR;  By Paul Brooks. Sierra Club,
$18. This book uses hefty selections from Carson's published and
unpublished writings to track her career as both a pioneering
environmentalist and a dedicated writer. In 1972 the reviewer
Josephine Johnson called this a ``rich and readable work.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A PATCHWORK PLANET &LR;  By Anne Tyler. Fawcett/Ballantine, $12.95.
Barnaby Gaitlin is a chronic underachiever who is estranged from
his family and driven by a hunger to peer into other people's
lives. Yet his inner turmoil is accompanied by sudden attacks of
clarity. Last year the reviewer Carol Shields called this a
``wonderful novel ... that repays our always delighted attention.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TENDER AT THE BONE: GROWING UP AT THE TABLE &LR;  By Ruth Reichl.
Broadway, $13. In recalling how a life of eating, waitressing and
cooking led her to become a food writer, the departing restaurant
critic for The New York Times (soon to be editor in chief of
Gourmet) focuses on the characters of those she loves: mainly her
flamboyant mother and her mild-mannered father. Praising this
``effortlessly entertaining'' memoir last year, Paul Levy wrote
that ``Reichl is ... witty, fair-minded, brave and a wonderful
writer.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NIGHT LETTERS &LR;  By Robert Dessaix. Picador USA, $13. In a hotel
room in Venice, a middle-aged Australian with a terminal illness
writes to a friend about his meandering journey through Europe and
his search for meaning. Last year the reviewer Patrick Farrell
admired ``the wry, chatty, surprisingly cheerful voice in which he
discourses on heaven and hell, seduction and sex.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE DAY OF CREATION &LR;  By J.G. Ballard. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
$13. In a parched central African nation, an obsessed British
doctor fulfills his dream of creating a ``third Nile.'' ``Ballard
constructs a moody and well-modeled landscape with as fine a
writerly intelligence as we might hope for,'' Samuel R. Delany
wrote in these pages in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WAR FEVER &LR;  $10. In this collection of Ballard's short fiction
reissued by the same publisher, Beirut becomes a laboratory for the
study of warfare and Ronald Reagan is recalled to the White House,
only to have news reports about his health overshadow World War
III. ``Far more rigorous and fastidious than Jorge Luis Borges or
Italo Calvino, Ballard keeps impeccably cool,'' Ursula K. Le Guin
wrote in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BONOBO: THE FORGOTTEN APE &LR;  By Frans de Waal. Photographs by
Frans Lanting. University of California, $24.95. A primatologist
explores the striking differences between these so-called pygmy
chimpanzees, who freely use sex to resolve tension, and their more
familiar cousins. In 1997 David Papineau called this an ``elegant
photo-essay.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
