<HEADER>
A2884 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN03-CO     03-01 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Hezbollah volunteers for Netanyahu's campaign
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   However horrid it might sound, the offensive by Hezbollah
guerrillas against Israeli soldiers in Southern Lebanon is the best
thing that could happen to Benjamin Netanyahu at this time.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu is in the political fight of his life, besieged to his
right by radical Israelis who detest any peace plan with the
Palestinians, reviled on the left by those in favor of the peace
process but who see Netanyahu as an obstructionist toward that end.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Hezbollah _ sensing retaliatory Israeli reaction
to any attack on its people or troops _ is running Israel's
political machine and, likely, its next election.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis already have struck back and will continue to do
so, tit-for-tat. Any thought of Israel withdrawing from Southern
Lebanon, an issue between the Israeli right and left, would appear
to be put on hold; Israelis don't run from a fight.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, while klutzy in some of his domestic and foreign
stances, is firm on one issue: Israel makes no peace under duress.
</P>
<P>
   While the action in Southern Lebanon is not Palestinian
connected so much as it involves the hands of Iran and Syria,
Netanyahu will be judged by how he handles the Hezbollah activity.
And, likely, he will handle it with force and with public
statements that Israel will not and cannot pull out of Southern
Lebanon as long as there exists a danger to Israel's northern
border.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere between the radicals of right and left in the Israeli
electorate lie the masses, turned emotionally by each and every
event in the Middle East. The Hezbollah attacks in Southern Lebanon
were designed to effect them, to bring them over to the Netanyahu
side, as that is the side that will not execute a peace plan with
the Palestinians or Arab states.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Hezbollah and its sponsors want: a continued
stalemate in the peace process, one so frustrating that Yasser
Arafat, despite U.S. urging not to do so, will declare an
independent Palestinian state, thereby enraging Netanyahu and
bringing to a close any hope of Israel carrying out the Wye River
peace accords brokered by Bill Clinton and Jordan's late King
Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   So delicate is the Middle East that a single act of terrorism or
warfare can turn Israel's malleable center into a revenge-demanding
mass that will stand behind Netanyahu's fist-clenching insistence
that no peace can be sought until all attacks upon Israel
terminate.
</P>
<P>
   Syria and Iran knew this about Netanyahu and the Israeli center
all along. What has happened in Southern Lebanon in the past few
days was calculated to be part of Israel's election campaign, not
that the Syrians and Iranians were invited to participate.
</P>
<P>
   But now that they are deeply involved. The glib Netanyahu will
take advantage of it, not only from his rostrum, but militarily as
well. He really has no other choice. Syria and Iran want Netanyahu
re-elected, not because they love him, but because they know that
as long as he serves as Israeli prime minister, there likely will
not be an accomplished, meaningful peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu felt pressured by Clinton to sign the Wye River peace
accords and, upon returning to Israel, had second thoughts about
it, especially when he met stiff resistance from his own Likud
party which, like the hard-line Arabs, have a too-expensive price
for peace.
</P>
<P>
   He easily can mount his platform and call for Arafat to stop the
Hezbollah in Southern Lebanon but he knows that Arafat has little
to no power over the Hezbollah. Arafat's albatross is the Hamas,
and he's not done well in slowing them down.
</P>
<P>
   It all points to a continued heating up in the Middle East, a
situation that will turn many of the dovish in Israel back into
Netanyahu's hands as he cries out against terrorism against his
people. That, and Netanyahu's military responses to Hezbollah, will
help him immeasurably in the coming election.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
