<HEADER>
A2887 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-Y2K-KAN &LR;      03-01 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-Y2K-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUMERICALLY SPEAKING, Y2K WILL BE TERRIBLE FOR EVERYONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1999 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oh-dear-oh-dear-oh-dear. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's the way all this alarming Y2K stuff has me feeling. The
world's going to end. And if it doesn't, then at least we'll all be
plunged into endless darkness and cold. And if that doesn't happen,
why, maybe we won't get to see our favorite shows on TV or
something. It'll be awful. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And what's worse, it's all inevitable because it's in the
numbers. I can't see how we can avoid catastrophe. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just recently this was all driven home to me when a friend sent
along a frightful column by one Gershom Gorenberg in a publication
called ``The Jerusalem Report.'' Gorenberg writes that a
prophet-like fellow named Jacob Oved stopped by recently to tell
him that the world will start coming to an end in the Jewish year
5760, which begins in September of this year, 1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oved says he used clues found in an ancient Jewish mystical text
to learn that ``240 years before the seventh millennium (that is,
in 5760), the waters will rise and cover the earth, and only the
Land of Israel will remain, like Noah's Ark.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Gorenberg learned from a letter writer to his magazine, an
old Jewish mystical text says the purification of the world will
begin in 5760 because a ritual bath must contain 40
(ital)se'ahs(end-ital) of water, each made up of 144 ``eggs,'' a
traditional unit of volume. And 40 times 144 is 5760. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are other ways of arriving at 5760, says Gorenberg. In
fact, he says, ``5760 is a multiple of so many numbers that anyone
who has sent in two boxtops for a junior kabbalist's kit can make
it mean anything.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kabbala, or cabala, refers to a religious philosophy developed
by certain rabbis in the Middle Ages based on a mystical
interpretation of scripture. It's become so trendy lately, in fact,
that even Madonna (and lots of other entertainment industry folks)
busies herself nowadays studying this matter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gorenberg, in fact, goes on to demonstrate his point about how
easy it is to come up with 5760 by predicting the return of Babe
Ruth and Jesus Alou to baseball in 5760 (1999 or 2000). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He points out that when the name Babe is translated into Hebrew
it has a numeric value of 24. Ruth hit 60 homers in one season,
which puts him at No. 4 on the all-time charts, behind Mark
McGwire, Sammy Sosa and Roger Maris. So 24 times 4 times 60 equals
5760. See? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it's all clear to me now. The reason the world is so
nervous about the Y2K arrival (which would be Y5.76K in Hebrew) is
that all signs point to its being simply momentous. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One recent day, for instance, the Dow Jones Industrial Average
rose 212.73 points. If you multiply that by my precise age when I
first bought mutual funds (27.076575), you come up with _ what
else? _ 5760. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'm not yet sure why a semi-decent Presbyterian like me should
be turning up personal end-of-the-world predictions that conform to
the Jewish calender, unless it has to do with the Jewish roots of
my faith, but there you are. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's more worrisome to me is that these predictions also are
showing up for the year expressed as 2000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For instance, through the end of the previous paragraph I'd
written 553 words in this column. If you multiply 553 times the
number of cookies I ate for breakfast time morning (3.6166365) you
get 2000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's uncanny. All signs point to disaster. But if I'm wrong and
the world doesn't end in 2000 (or 5760), I'm cashing in my mutual
funds and buying a pizza. If I have to wait around for the end, I
don't want to do it hungry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
