<DOCNO> NYT19990301.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 11:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2956 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECHNOBUDDY02-COX     03-01 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trojan horses may be running wild, tapping into your hard drive
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   How would you like to be an Internet celebrity? People all over
the world would know what you think and who you think about. Your
private e-mail correspondence would be widely read and admired.
Your financial records could be examined and discussed. Even the
text of letters you send through the U.S. mail _ as long as they
were created on your PC _ could be circulated around the Net like
an old-fashioned chain letter.
</P>
<P>
   My guess is you wouldn't like that kind of fame at all.
</P>
<P>
   But some of you who are reading this column right now _ not very
many, but some of you _ are already Internet celebrities. I know
this sounds a little fantastic, but there's a virulent form of
hacking growing in popularity that allows almost anyone to invade
your computer and read files, delete them or add new files ... all
from a remote computer while you are on the Internet. They don't
have to be a genius hacker to do it. Instead, they can download a
program from one of the many hacker sites on the Net and follow the
directions _ as easy as reading a cookbook to bake a cake.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works, once the hacker has the spying program. You
receive an e-mail with an attachment. Maybe it's supposed to be a
funny little program, or an electronic greeting card, or even a
video or photograph designed to be read from a file called
funny.exe or maybe porno.exe. It could have almost any name.
</P>
<P>
   When you open the attachment, it may work just fine. But along
with the picture or the card, your computer receives a tiny hidden
virulent program called a Trojan horse. The reason for the name is
fairly obvious _ the bad program comes disguised inside an
innocuous program.
</P>
<P>
   There are too many of these programs _ called backdoor programs
by some _ to name them all. Once transferred to your computer, they
allow it to be operated by remote control while you are on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   New programs like this _ and increasingly better ones more
difficult to find and remove _ are created every day. But two of
the best known are called Back Orfice and Master of Paradise. These
programs turn your computer into the equivalent of an Internet
server accessible by any other computer on the Net. So the bad guy
who sends the trojan horse can sit somewhere miles and miles away
and do almost anything he wishes with your data.
</P>
<P>
   Now before you pull the plug on your Internet connection, let me
explain most of you don't need to worry about programs like this.
To enter your computer _ even if you have a Trojan horse hiding
inside it _ the bad guy needs to know your address on the Internet.
This address isn't readily apparent when you log on to check your
mail or browse the Web. The real risk from these hidden spy
programs comes when you are logged on to one of the Internet chat
groups such as IRC. A simple command, while you are on IRC, will
reveal your address. Then, while you are logged on and chatting
away, another IRC user can invade your computer.
</P>
<P>
   So, if you aren't a regular on the chat channels, or one of the
game sites where your opponent connects to your computer using the
IP address of your machine, you are perfectly safe. And, even then,
you're still safe if you've never accepted an attachment from
someone you don't know and trust.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, even if you spend more time chatting than my Aunt
Sally, you're probably still safe. Most of these backdoor programs
I know about rely on your computer having a setting called
``sharing.'' Unless you are using your home computer on a network
with other machines in your home, make sure that setting is turned
off. Just open the icon in your Control Panel called Network. Then
click on the button called File and Print Sharing. Make sure the
two checkboxes are blank. If they are checked, click on the
checkmarks to disable sharing.
</P>
<P>
   OK. I didn't want to interrupt your chat. You just needed to
know you may be talking louder _ and to more people _ than you
figured.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tecbud(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Bill Husted writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
