<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   COMMENTARY: COLD BRINGS A NEW VOICE, A NEW LIFE
</P>
<P>
   By MARK LANE
</P>
<P>
   c. Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   I didn't always sound this way.
</P>
<P>
   My voice generally is a more uncertain instrument. On bad days,
it wavers into tonalities that have been explored by Mr. Rogers,
Barney Fife, the pizza-delivery boy on ``The Simpsons'' and many of
your finer hand-puppets.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, it does not. Today, it is a rich baritone. To
put it in starkly '70s terms, I went to sleep sounding like the Bee
Gees and woke up sounding like Barry White.
</P>
<P>
   (Yehhhh. Can't get enough of your love, bayhbe.)
</P>
<P>
   Upper respiratory infection was never so sweet.
</P>
<P>
   The February cold that settled in my chest lowered my voice a
good octave. Gave it resonance. New authority.
</P>
<P>
   Dogs obey me. Children fear me. Telemarketers apologize for
calling. Secretaries put my calls through. Women casually mention
their marital status in the course of conversations. Mechanics tell
me everything will be ready today. Waitresses refill my coffee cup
before its half empty. Cats carry out my commands and teenagers
listen respectfully.
</P>
<P>
   OK, the last sentence is a lie; nonetheless, it captures the
promise of this new condition. It is like having a whole new kind
of life. Like waking up and being someone else, someone familiar
but just a little shinier, a little better, a little easier for the
world to take.
</P>
<P>
   The Voice is no overnight sensation, either. It started
unbelievably low. Luke,-I-am-your-father low. Then it rose to Barry
White levels and then to an Elvis pitch. Even after I stopped
hacking like a seal, my chest cold lingered and with it my
new-found timbre.
</P>
<P>
   I no longer sounded sick, yet I stayed low. It was wonderful. I
started re-recording my answering machine and voice-mail
announcements.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Great Oz with his artificially low voice booming
through speakers, I now tell callers I cannot speak to them at this
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leave your insignificant message at the beep. The Great Oz
will then decide whether to take up your petition. Pay no attention
to that man you called last week.''
</P>
<P>
   Too cool.
</P>
<P>
   I had never before suspected how much my voice, the old voice,
may have damaged my life fortunes. Diminished my prospects. I found
people treat you better when your voice sounds resonate and
radio-ready.
</P>
<P>
   As someone who writes for a living, I have always thought that
words speak for themselves. You put them on paper and they mean
pretty much the same thing whether read out loud by Don Knotts or
James Earl Jones. That the right word means more than the right
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   No way. Well chosen words sound too clever to believe when
spoken high and reedy. Poorly chosen words sound too dumb to
believe. But in my new voice, I am utterly believable all the time.
I can read menus and sound like a philosopher. Read the fine print
on ant poison and sound like a poet.
</P>
<P>
   In my usual voice, I could recite the Gettysburg Address and
people would suspect I was selling time-share condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful this spell would wear off any moment, I started calling
friends out of town. I hoped to convince them that I was far
smoother and charming than they remembered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark Lane?'' answered a distant redhead. ``I have no earthly
idea why you'd want to claim to be that guy, but you can just keep
on talking as long as you like. You don't sound at all like the
kind of guy who disappears from the table when he sees a waiter
coming with the bill.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the next best thing to plastic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Like all good things, this is bound to pass. Already some of the
old squeakiness is returning. Fortunately, the first flush of warm
weather and its attending molds and pollens are just around the
corner. If my sinuses do their work. I can move seamlessly from
cold season to allergy season. I just may have a chance to ride
this out for awhile.
</P>
<P>
   I'm good until summer. After that, I'm just hoping medical
science come up with a breakthough. Vocal Viagra. I should ask
about it now. While doctors will still listen to me.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.)
ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-02-26-99 1427E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
