<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2959 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAC-REPORT02-COX     03-01 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAC-REPORT02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Apple says new software titles are in the pipeline, but where?
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a recent trade conference in Tokyo, Apple announced more than
1,500 new software programs for the Mac have been released.
</P>
<P>
   That's good news, I guess, except where do you find all these
new titles?
</P>
<P>
   They aren't showing up yet in stores, online sites or mail-order
catalogs. In fact, I'm still seeing a decline in titles for the
Mac. That's especially true for business software. There's now only
an electronic dictionary, and I see only three personal information
managers _ Act!, Consultant and InTouch _ advertised in the
mail-order catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   Some titles that have gone by the wayside in the last year or
two include WebArranger, Claris Organizer, Random House Electronic
Dictionary and Claris Emailer.
</P>
<P>
   WordPerfect, long the biggest challenger to Microsoft Office, is
debating whether to continue developing for the Mac.
</P>
<P>
   I'm hoping this gap between new software releases and what I see
for sale merely reflects a crossroads. Software production for the
Mac had nearly shut down last year, and then came the iMac. Its
success is sparking new interest in the Mac platform.
</P>
<P>
   I know it sounds like a stretch, but there is some evidence to
support such an argument. For one, some big developers that had
been on the fence about releasing new Mac titles have now decided
in the affirmative.
</P>
<P>
   Maxis is developing a Mac version of its new ``SimCity 3000,''
and Blizzard is doing the same for its popular war strategy game
``Starcraft.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a Japanese developer has released a Mac-only title,
``Yoot Tower,'' which is an updated version of ``SimTower.'' When
was the last time you heard a game developed first for the Mac
rather than the PC?
</P>
<P>
   The development of these games is not fun and games when it
comes to the Mac. It helps decide the Mac's future.
</P>
<P>
   With useful, entertaining and progressive software, the Mac will
thrive again. It won't matter how terrific a Mac looks if no one
wants to write software for the platform.
</P>
<P>
   Without developer support, the Mac will be like a jilted suitor,
all dressed up with nowhere to go.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
