</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990301.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2961 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN02-COX     03-01 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMMENTARY: Nature of playing has changed
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Long before Edison screwed in his first light
bulb, or Don Ameche invented the telephone, the word ``virtual''
meant that something was almost the same as the real thing, but not
quite. Today, ``virtual'' has become reality for a lot of solitary
kids tapping out life in front of a computer.
</P>
<P>
   They no longer need parents or playmates to have fun. Thanks to
high-tech genius, they can now join virtual people visiting a
virtual amusement park, and even go for a virtual ride on a
rollercoaster. Then, if they're still lonely, they can boogie on
down to the local toy store and buy a ``virtual family'' or a
``virtual friend'' with whom they may interact.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of generations ago when a few of us neighborhood kids
headed for a vacant lot and chose up sides for a ballgame, the
inevitable bickering over foul balls and stolen bases was our idea
of interaction. Today, the word has taken on an entirely new
meaning. Contemporary youth ``interact'' with computers and toys
designed for a single player. One toy company is introducing a
football that's flat on one end so a kid can throw it against the
wall and play catch with himself.
</P>
<P>
   Do-nothing dolls like the ones I used to cuddle and play house
with have been displaced by models that sing, tell jokes, and
pretend to be the young owner's best buddy.
</P>
<P>
   Imagination has given way to wires and batteries, and the idea
of calling a friend to come out and play now seems an antiquated
notion. Too bad. Toys, like ideas, were meant to be shared,
otherwise they're not much fun.
</P>
<P>
   My friend Tootie and I knew all about that. We shared our play
just like we shared the puffy cinnamon rolls her mom used to bake
on Saturday mornings.
</P>
<P>
   On warm days, Tootie and I would set up housekeeping on a
blanket spread under the old pear tree in my back yard. Often, we
spent more time setting up than we did playing. Out would come the
toy stove and the sink with real
</P>
<P>
   running water (as long as we kept the reservoir on the back
full). Tea sets, pots and pans, cribs and carriages - nothing was
overlooked in our quest to turn a collection of mismatched toys
into two little girls' dream home.
</P>
<P>
   It took both of us to move my round table and chairs under the
grape arbor. We set up the kitchen beside the sandbox since that
was where we ``cooked'' moist sand in miniature muffin tins.
Tootie's blue tin telephone would be conveniently wedged in the
crotch of the tree for when make-believe friends called inviting us
to pretend tea parties.
</P>
<P>
   The darkened garage the at the end of the driveway was our
``theater'' where we sometimes took the dolls for a Blondie movie.
Other days it was where we trod the boards as famous actresses and
invited neighborhood kids to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Rainy days drove us inside and to the dining room floor where we
built entire cities from the Lincoln Logs and assorted blocks I
kept in the huge cardboard box my father's new G.E. radio (the one
with the green tuning eye) had come in.
</P>
<P>
   Immersed in a project, we'd build for hours, swapping blocks and
sharing a vision. It made no difference to us that log cabins and
castles were incongruous neighbors on the adjoining squares in the
carpet.
</P>
<P>
   Late afternoons, just about the time we'd be roofing a cabin or
finishing up a moat, the inevitable would happen. Mother would haul
the empty box over and tell us to pick it all up so she could set
the table for dinner. Naturally, we'd complain we weren't finished
playing with it yet, but as we groused, we tossed. I remember the
sound of the blocks bouncing against the cardboard sides.
</P>
<P>
   Some days Tootie and I argued. Our spats never lasted long
because we needed each other. There was no retreat to a solitary
room to seek companionship in a hand-held virtual life. The
reality, whatever it was at the moment, was just
</P>
<P>
   too good to miss.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, our batteries never ran down.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
