<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ A motley of would-be drug policy reformers
clustered under an umbrella called the Network of Reform Groups
will issue a report Wednesday in which they will propose,
shockingly, that we stop simply fighting the war on drugs and start
instead trying actually to win it. (Teepen, Cox News Service).
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN _ Journalists struggled to find words to
describe their feelings about covering the great enigma: the year
2000 computer flaw, also known as Y2K. At a seminar Tuesday at the
Media Studies Center in midtown Manhattan, about 70 reporters from
around the country tried to figure out how to better cover what may
turn out to be one of the most significant events in modern history
_ or one of the biggest yawns in media history. (Geewax, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-COLUMN _ Pulitzer winner Michael Skube's weekly lifestyle
commentary. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Long before Edison screwed
in his first light bulb, or Don Ameche invented the telephone, the
word ``virtual'' meant that something was almost the same as the
real thing, but not quite. Today, ``virtual'' has become reality
for a lot of solitary kids tapping out life in front of a computer.
(Elizabeth Schuett, a teacher and writer in Gibsonburg, Ohio,
writes twice a week for Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ I didn't always sound this
way. My voice generally is a more uncertain instrument. On bad
days, it wavers into tonalities that have been explored by Mr.
Rogers, Barney Fife, the pizza-delivery boy on ``The Simpsons'' and
many of your finer hand-puppets. Today, however, it does not.
Today, it is a rich baritone. To put it in starkly '70s terms, I
went to sleep sounding like the Bee Gees and woke up sounding like
Barry White. (Yehhhh. Can't get enough of your love, bayhbe.) Upper
respiratory infection was never so sweet. (Lane, Daytona Beach
News-Journal) MOVED
</P>
