 &HT;    CONSUMER Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: A recent episode of ``Ally McBeal''ncluded a
scene where someone rented a blimp. Wouldn't that be a great way to
send a very special ``I Love You'' to my wife for her birthday? How
much would something like that cost? Is there an enterprise in
Central Texas that would rent out a blimp on an hourly basis?
</P>
<P>
   _ Robert St. John
</P>
<P>
   A: Once again television raises the bar a bit too high.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Lockhartof Blimp Photo &AMP; Video Services in Austin comes the
closest to a blimp message. The shape is the same; the message is
back-lit. Lockhart has a minimum price of $600 (plus $125 or so for
every banner). After the deed, the banners are yours. The $600 buys
you as much as six hours of air time.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I find out what my father's Social Security number
was? He passed away nine years ago, and I would like to have it in
case I need it when applying for college scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   _ Carla Helm
</P>
<P>
   A: To initiate a records search for an assigned Social Security
number you must present identifying information: your father's full
name, date and place of birth, and his parents' full names.
``Generally, the information may be disclosed in the case of a
deceased individual,'' says Social Security spokeswoman Sandra
Talbot. For further information call (800) 772-1213.Q: To what
address should I send condolences to the families and friends of
the firefighters who died fighting the church fire in Fort Worth?
</P>
<P>
   _ T.A.
</P>
<P>
   A: Send letters to: River Oaks Volunteer Fire Department, 4900
River Oaks Blvd., River Oaks, Texas 76114. A fund for the families
has been set up at Firefighters' Memorial Fund, c/o NationsBank,
River Oaks Banking Center, 5351 River Oaks Blvd., Fort Worth, Texas
76114-3302.Q: I purchase semisweet chocolate out of state in a
10-pound slab to dip chocolates. Are there shops in Austin to
purchase the slabs?
</P>
<P>
   _ Betty Schroeder
</P>
<P>
   A: Call Miss Janette's Cakes &AMP; Supplies (836-4826) to order
10-pound slabs of semisweet, milk or white chocolate. She will have
it in about a week.
</P>
<P>
   Many cooks prefer the slabs to the more convenient chips because
family recipes call for them. A tip from Miss Janette's: Real
chocolate must be tempered (handled delicately) to succeed in
dipping.Q: All of the ``mechanical'' parking meters in Austin have
been changed to ``electronic'' meters. The reason for these new
meters is that they are able to accept not only coins but
convenient, prepaid debit cards. Have you ever seen a prepaid card
for sale or tried to find out where to buy one? No one knows what
you're talking about _ including the people I have been passed
around to at the city. What is the great secret?
</P>
<P>
   _S.K.
</P>
<P>
   A: Parking meter debit cards are sold at one location only _ 701
W. Fifth St. (Public Works entrance _ look hard), Monday to Friday,
8 a.m. to 4:30 p.m., in amounts from $5 to $50. Cash or checks _ no
stamps, no credit cards. These debit cards are rechargeable, so do
not toss them when you have used their dollar value. Warning:
Public Works spokeswoman Celeste Cromack says these cards do not
work on meters in the state complex.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am an avid fan of jazz musician Oscar Peterson.Can you
locate a source or an address to get an autographed photograph?
</P>
<P>
   _Lowell J. Bethel
</P>
<P>
   A: Peterson is an adjunct music professor in Canada. Write to
him at: York University, McLaughlin, Room 130, 4700 Keele St.,
Toronto, Ontario, Canada M3J 1P3.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Several of my friends and I wonder about Ricky Williams'
hair. Who is his hairdresser? Is it real hair? Is it really dyed
orange?
</P>
<P>
   _Virginia W.
</P>
<P>
   A: Believe it or not, the NCAA's all-time leading rusher does
not think about his dreadlock hairstyle nearly as much as fans
apparently do. The slight orange tint? Simple case of sun bleach.
Hairdresser? His mom braids the back when it gets long.
</P>
<P>
   The style does not require a lot of maintenance _ could be why
he likes his signature locks so much.Q: I have a Chatty Cathy doll
of my daughter's that does not chat anymore. Are there any new (or
working old) voice boxes? Or who could restore mine for my daughter
by next Christmas?
</P>
<P>
   _Donna B.
</P>
<P>
   A: Most silent Chatty Cathys suffer from a brittle (albeit
original) rubber band or a broken pull string. If your Cathy has a
hexagon-shaped speaker on her chest, craftsman Donald Eliason is
the man for you.
</P>
<P>
   Call him at (360) 403-0260. Eliason can rebuild or replace the
voice box in many Chatty Cathys. There is a $25 minimum (including
a replaced rubber band or string), plus parts and shipping.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have information on how to get tickets for the Masters
Practice Rounds or the tournament itself?
</P>
<P>
   _L. Valdez
</P>
<P>
   A: Tickets to the 1999 Practice Rounds are sold out.
Applications for these tickets from Augusta National Golf Club were
due July 15, 1998.Tournament tickets are bought by those on the
patron list, which has been closed since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there any federal, state or local agency/law that
obligates the owners or operators of public phones to upgrade, so
that the phones would give back change?
</P>
<P>
   _ A. Medina
</P>
<P>
   A: No, but there might be soon.
</P>
<P>
   House Bill 83, relating to change due for payment made to a
public telephone, has been filed and referred to the Committee on
Economic Development. To support this bill sponsored by El Paso's
Norma Chavez, write your state representative.
</P>
<P>
   Currently a public-telephone owner may charge whatever the
market will bear.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Could you find out how many people were murdered in Texas in
1998?
</P>
<P>
   _ I. H.
</P>
<P>
   A: The Department of Public Safety has figures for 1997 (1,328
murders).
</P>
<P>
   Q:How do you go about applying for a hardship driver's license
for someone under 16? How hard does your hardship have to be to
acquire a license?
</P>
<P>
   _ S.R.
</P>
<P>
   A: Pretty hard, as in an unusual economic hardship, a
death-related emergency (``I'll kill him unless he drives himself
to practice'' is not what that means), illness or disability in the
family, or enrollment in a vocational, educational program
requiring a license.
</P>
<P>
   A Texan must be at least 15 years old to apply for a hardship
license and have completed an approved driver's education course
(includes the parent-taught one). This is occasionally waived and a
temporary license is issued, which is renewable every 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   Applicants must pass the driving exam (written and road). After
completing the basic license application and the minor restricted
application, an applicant interviews with an examiner _ a walk-in,
but wait in line like everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that many hardship licenses are issued _ only 8,156 in the
last fiscal year,'' says DPS's Tela Mange. It is the applicant's
responsibility to prove a hardship exists. Bring proof _ a
physician's statement, a letter from a school principal, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My daughter is getting married and I want to give her a
seasoned cast iron skillet. Since my well-seasoned one is more than
30 years old, I don't remember how I seasoned it.
</P>
<P>
   _D.D.
</P>
<P>
   A: Before Teflon, there were seasoned cast iron skillets. Call
(888) 881-TRAV to order from Lodge Manufacturing Company, maker of
cast iron cookware. Lodge recommends a four-step process.
</P>
<P>
   Wash, rinse and dry the skillet over a low flame to remove all
moisture. Use a paper towel to coat the entire surface of the pan
(inside and out) with vegetable oil (not butter). Bake the skillet
upside-down in a preheated, 350-degree oven for one hour. Place
aluminum foil on the oven floor to catch drips. Cool the skillet
completely in the oven before removing to wipe clean.
</P>
<P>
   When a pan is newly seasoned, avoid acid-rich foods like
tomatoes. It may be necessary to re-season the skillet at some
point. Several cooking gurus recommend a 325-degree oven, but all
agree abrasives are not good for a seasoned cast iron anything.
When storing the skillet, place a paper towel inside to absorb any
excess moisture.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I would like to know what the rules are about food handling
in restaurants. Every time I go to a certain McDonald's, I notice
that employees who handle the food don't wear gloves. They put
burgers together and food into boxes with their bare hands. It
seems to me that all food handlers are required to wear gloves. I
couldn't find the Department of Health on the Web, so I defer to
your vast resources!
</P>
<P>
   _Holly Smith
</P>
<P>
   A: Not all food handlers are required to wear gloves because
gloves get dirty, too. Austin/Travis County Health Department
spokesman Dan Pickens notes that gloves sometimes can be
counterproductive because they lull some food handlers into
thinking gloved hands are clean hands.
</P>
<P>
   According to the new food safety code, workers who deal only
with food items (the guy who slaps lettuce on burgers all day long,
for example) do not need to wear gloves. However, those at the end
of the assembly line who wrap or box the food must use gloves,
tongs, utensils or a hand sanitizer. It's the combination of food
and non-food items, which could result in cross-contamination, that
causes concern, Pickens says.
</P>
<P>
   A sink is required in food preparation areas to encourage
frequent hand washing (at least 20 seconds per wash). Restaurant
workers with open sores or cuts must not handle food without
wearing protective gloves.
</P>
<P>
   Call the manager's attention to the problem or report suspected
violations in Austin or Travis County (469-2015).Q: I've been
trying for seven months to get a missing street sign replaced. I
call the city's missing sign number, and the same guy answers
``sign shop.'' I tell him my story, he checks some resource and
then tells me they have no record of my request. Then he says he'll
record it and they'll get right on it.
</P>
<P>
   I've made four of these phone calls since August and nothing
happens. Is there some secret I don't know about getting the city
to respond ?
</P>
<P>
   _P.M.
</P>
<P>
   A: The secret is Kenny Moses, supervisor of the sign shop
(457-4879). He is the man with the master list. Moses says
currently there is a four- to six-week backlog of sign
replacements, although he is aiming to reduce that to one week.
Your request is in his capable hands _ with a bullet. Moses
supervises over 500,000 signs in Austin and annexed areas. Yikes!Q:
We're quite fond of an oven (Whirlpool RVE 455) that we believe
dates to 1952. Recently the door became a bit recalcitrant and
refused to open all the way, which made it difficult to get cookie
sheets and casseroles in and out.
</P>
<P>
   With the best of intentions and a very large hammer, my husband
sprang into action. The oven door now opens all the way but has an
interesting warp that prevents it from closing. I called some
service centers but the model has not been manufactured in decades!
Any ideas where to get the door replaced?
</P>
<P>
   _A.R.
</P>
<P>
   A: Glad you are keeping the husband. Ask him to lose the hammer.
Contact used appliance stores and let them know what you are
looking for. An old Whirlpool might come in and your troubles are
over!
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane S. Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, Texas 78767;
(512) 445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512)
445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   For copies of Jane's book, ``Thanks for Asking!'' _ a
compilation of more than 600 favorite questions and answers _ call
(800) 424-6291.
</P>
