</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-MEDIA02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Silicon Valley managers buck tradition
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What makes Silicon Valley companies so successful? Writer Karen
Southwick thinks she's figured it out in her new book, ``Silicon
Gold Rush.'' The book, published by Wiley, says tech entrepreneurs
have succeeded by turning traditional management structures upside
down. It profiles 23 companies as examples. Among them are 3Com,
Cisco Systems, Yahoo! and Novell. Southwick says any entrepreneur
can take the lessons of these companies and apply them to an
organization of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Can it be? Microsoft has released a new version of software
that, according to the March issue of Windows magazine, is actually
streamlined. The magazine says Web browser Microsoft Explorer 5.0,
now in a beta version, is ``lighter'' and easier to use. The
article features lots of graphic illustrations of how the latest
version of Explorer is trimmed down. You'll be able to download the
software at http://www.microsoft.com.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   War gamers, take note. Microsoft has released the latest in its
line of real-time war simulations.
</P>
<P>
   This one is called ``The Russian Front'' and features the Nazi
invasion of Russia in World War II. Part of the ``Close Combat''
series, ``The Russian Front'' offers command of units on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   You follow every soldier's fortune and can play either the
Germans or the Nazis. Parents beware. The game features graphic
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   Valentine's Day is long gone, but you can still hear love poems
recited daily on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   It's part of a national program to promote a love of poetry. To
that end, National Poet Laureate is sponsoring a Web site called
``My Favorite Poem.''
</P>
<P>
   The site features people reciting poems, especially love poems.
To hear these amateur poets and learn more about how you could
participate in the program, check out the site at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .favoritepoem.org.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
