<P>
   PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   COXNET-PTECH 0226 _ People love cookies and milk. People hate
cookies and computers. Harmless though they might be, most Internet
users have a knee-jerk reaction to anyone or anything trying to
gather information about them. The notion that merely typing in a
Web address opens up the opportunity for companies to find out
anything at all about them is distasteful. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TECH ISSUES -- The Internet carries ads for a burgeoning and
largely uncontrolled industry of ``information brokers'' that _ for
a fee _ will reveal the most intimate details of your life, right
down to that birthmark on your backside or ancient records of
psychological treatment. (Alexander, Cox Washington Bureau)
</P>
<P>
   TECH BRIEFS -- For those who think the generation gap is marked
in distance with PCs, with the young on one side of the chasm and
older folks on the other, take a look at a book from Intel that
hopes to bridge that gap. (Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY -- The Year 2000 problem is a subject that has
received enough ink to float a battleship. But there are still
smart people out there who are mixed up about the impact of the
problem. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet PTECH page for the current week. This
layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   TVGUARDIAN _ TVGuardian, The Foul Language Filter, monitors
television programs and videotapes and mutes the sound when
profanity appears on the soundtrack. Most nerd types think the
gizmo works by using some sort of sophisticated voice-recognition
system. They couldn't be more wrong says its inventor _ it reads
along on the closed captioning and when it sees a naughty word, it
shuts off the sound for a couple of seconds. James Cummings. With
photo. (Dayton Daily News). 25TECHNOPADS _ Confessions of a PDA
carrier. Why those of us with palmtop devices just can't put them
down. (Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
