<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 11:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2977 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECNOTAX02-COX     03-01 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECNOTAX02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Computers breathe life into taxes
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the computer age, and your taxes have just been colorized.
</P>
<P>
   Think about the traditional image the act of filling out your
tax forms by hand brings to mind: endless black and white forms.
Liquid Paper for your mistakes. Worries that you won't get a refund
_ you want to be in the black because being in the red is bad.
</P>
<P>
   Computers are opening up a much easier and friendlier way of
doing your taxes, with help available even if you still prefer
working out the forms with your trusty No. 2 pencil and a
calculator.
</P>
<P>
   Tax software and Web sites have become more useful as they've
evolved and, short of hiring an accountant, they're some of the
best resources for up-to-date tax information. And they've become
increasingly user-friendly: even the official IRS Web site has
become a colorful, photo-filled place to find information.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some resources to help make that April 15 deadline seem
a little less precipitous:
</P>
<P>
   Software
</P>
<P>
   Software that does your taxes for you used to be little more
than a fancy calculator. Now, software suites such as TurboTax and
Kiplinger's TaxCut do it all _ you can print tax forms, file
electronically, find current tax code information and look for
hidden deductions, depending on your financial situation.
</P>
<P>
   TurboTax has long been the favorite, but basic versions of both
are available at software stores for less than $20. This year's
version of TurboTax includes an interview feature that asks you
questions about your tax year and then fills out your forms
accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   For those with simple returns, such a software package even gets
the seal approval from a local accountant. Ron Lievens, a certified
public accountant, said he recommends software to clients who may
not need specialized help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recommend it to people all the time,'' Lievens said. ``If
they feel they can do it themselves, I recommend TurboTax.''
</P>
<P>
   More complex versions of TurboTax and TaxCut _ for business
owners or for those who have to file state taxes _ are also
available.
</P>
<P>
   While you're at it, this may also be a good time to start
tracking your finances using your computer. The latest versions of
Quicken and Microsoft Money are good ways to keep track of your
accounts and each program has features for online banking.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS' Web site also has a two-CD software set that includes
current tax forms and guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites
</P>
<P>
   Two of the best Web sites I've found for tax information provide
you with information on preparing your taxes as well as links to
other resources that may be more specific if you have additional
questions.
</P>
<P>
   1040.com (www.1040.com) is a basic, no-nonsense site that
features updated news, federal and state tax forms, addresses for
filing and a preparer's database. The site is good for general
information and is handy for quick answers.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS' own site (www.irs.gov) has gone through a massive
redesign that has made it easier on the eye and much easier to sort
through. Made to look like a daily newspaper (''The Digital
Daily''), the IRS site contains daily news stories, tax statistics,
filing instructions, tax information for businesses and links.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic filing
</P>
<P>
   The IRS site also has a list of recognized partners it has for
electronic filing. Included are well-known tax preparation
companies like H&AMP;R Block Inc. and Jackson Hewitt as well as
software makers. You can use TaxCut or TurboTax to file
electronically. Filing your return this way costs between $9.99 and
$19.99. However, if your refund is small, you may want to forego
electronic filing, especially if you're not in a hurry to save the
few weeks longer it might take to mail in your return.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the current state of the federal tax code, filing your
taxes has never been easier. Just boot up, log on and get yourself
on the road to getting another tax year behind you.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
