<DOCNO> NYT19990301.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2980 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TVGUARDIAN02-COX     03-01 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVGUARDIAN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cut the filthy language from TV, videos
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When people who design electronic devices for a living find out
how TVGuardian works they tend to slap themselves on the forehead
and ask how they missed such an obvious idea, said J. Richard Bray,
TVGuardian's inventor.
</P>
<P>
   TVGuardian, The Foul Language Filter, monitors television
programs and videotapes and mutes the sound when profanity appears
on the soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   Bray said most engineers who asked him about the product assumed
it had some kind of sophisticated sound recognition software
coupled with a system that would delay the sound and picture long
enough for the device to mute the sound before the offensive word
could be heard.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, TVGuardian simply reads the closed captions that
accompany most broadcasts and videotape programs. When it
recognizes a word on its banned list, the TVGuardian turns off the
sound for a second or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to overlook the obvious sometimes,'' Bray said.
``It's a problem a lot of people have been trying to deal with, but
nobody made the connection that they might be able to use the
closed captions.''
</P>
<P>
   Bray, 39, of Rogers, Ark., said he studied accounting in college
but discovered soon after graduation that he was more interested in
computers than in doing other people's income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   He went into the software business in 1985 and eventually
developed his own software products to be used in real estate
closings. His software did things like preparing deeds, calculating
trust account balances and preparing other documents associated
with the sale of homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something I was good at, but not something I enjoyed
that much,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Bray, who has children 11 and 13 years old, said he
had been frustrated for years by foul language in movies and
television programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be watching a video that had content that was fine for
the family, but we would be surprised by the language that would
pop up,'' he said. ``My wife and I both were taught there were some
things you didn't say, and we tried to pass that value to our kids.
But then we'd rent a video and language we wouldn't let them use
was on there. It was like we were sending a mixed message.''
</P>
<P>
   One day a few years ago after watching another irritating video
while on vacation, Bray said he started thinking about coming up
with a solution.
</P>
<P>
   He said he didn't like the idea of a V-chip, which would block
children from watching an entire program rated for older children
or adults. He wanted a system that would cut out the objectionable
language while letting the child see the rest of the program.
</P>
<P>
   Bray noticed that closed captions spelled out the profane words
he wanted to keep his children from hearing, and that the caption
flashed on the screen at the same time the words were spoken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew enough about software that I knew if I could read it, a
computer could read it and react to it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Confident that he was onto something, Bray sold the rights to
his real estate software to raise capital and dived into his
language filter venture full time.
</P>
<P>
   Bray started researching the idea on the Internet and was soon
convinced a device that blocked profanity by reading closed
captions was possible. But he didn't have the engineering expertise
or equipment to build the device he had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   He went back to the Internet looking for companies that could
build a prototype. He also did Internet research and bought some
books on intellectual property rights so he would know how to
protect his rights to profits from his idea.
</P>
<P>
   Within a year he had in hand a prototype that did exactly what
he expected it to do _ it monitored closed captions and blocked out
foul language.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great,'' Bray said. ``I watched movie after movie after
movie just so I could watch it work.''
</P>
<P>
   Today a market version of TVGuardian is available in Blockbuster
video stores in the Southwest and is spreading to other video
stores and Bible stores nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   It also sells for $149.95 by telephone order at (888) 799-4884or
via several Internet retailers. Information is available at
tvguardian.com on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The market version has two settings: strict and tolerant.
TVGuardian has an internal list of words it looks for in closed
captions, and the list on the tolerant setting pinpoints words
commonly considered profane.
</P>
<P>
   The strict setting catches profanity and other potentially
objectionable utterances such as ``sucks'' or ``butt-head.''
</P>
<P>
   The device also is able to use context clues to decide if words
like God or Jesus are being used as expletives rather than as
names.
</P>
<P>
   In cases where a profane word is needed to understand the
meaning of what is being said, TVGuardian will flash a less
offensive substitute word of similar meaning through the closed
caption system.
</P>
<P>
   According to a news release from the company, TVGuardian was
used on a videotape of the movie Speed and reduced offensive words
from 93 to four. E.T's 13 offensive words were reduced to one.
</P>
<P>
   The release said the device reduces profanity in many movies to
zero while muting less than 60 seconds of an entire PG or PG-13
movie soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids love it,'' Bray said. ``Movies we wouldn't let them
watch before, like Men in Black, they get to see now. It gives them
more choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Bray has a patent pending for TVGuardian, and it's the only
product his company Principle Solutions Inc. markets.
</P>
<P>
   TVGuardian won a ``Best of Show'' award at the International
Consumer Electronics Show in Las Vegas in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't really sink in what we had done until we got to the
electronics show and saw the competition,'' Bray said. ``There were
more than 20,000 products on display and only 13 were chosen for
best of show.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 13 products to win top prizes at the Consumer Electronics
Show, several were made by international corporations like Marantz,
Philips Electronics and RCA's parent company Thomson Consumer
Electronics.
</P>
<P>
   But just as many were virtually unknown companies such as Terk
Technologies, Axlon Electronics, Replay Networks and Bray's
Principle Solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big guys can pour a lot of money into high-tech projects
like building a better high-definition television,'' Bray said.
``We little guys can't compete in research, but we can compete when
it comes to innovations, new ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
