<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, March 1, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PARENTS-SEX (San Francisco) _ Even in this era of deadly
sexually transmitted diseases, parents still are so reluctant to
discuss the facts of life with their children that they leave them
wanting more. By DIANA WALSH.
</P>
<P>
   SURF-FORECASTING (San Francisco) _ Surf forecasting has become a
booming business, and some forecasters claim better than 90 percent
accuracy in predicting the big waves. The forecasts are so
reliable, in fact, that when a respected surf- caster forecasts a
big swell for Fiji, Hawaii, Peru or Tahiti, well-heeled
surf-seekers fly there to catch the wave. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   OIL-SPILLS (San Francisco) _ California may soon burn oil spills
from wrecked vessels as a way to save wildlife and prevent fouled
beaches. The state expects to adopt a policy by June that would
allow burning instead of trying to mop up tar-like spills that kill
seabirds and marine mammals and spoil the fragile coast. By JANE
KAY.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-GOP (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Despite calls to take a more
moderate path, state Republicans ended their convention here by
electing the most conservative anti-abortion candidates to lead
them and hosting a keynote speaker who said, ``Killing children is
the essential issue facing our nation today.'' By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-HOMETOWN (Park Ridge, Ill.) _ Voters in this
conservative, affluent suburb of brick homes and tree-lined streets
on the outskirts of northwest Chicago didn't vote for President
Clinton in 1992 or 1996. They did, however, vote for Rep. Henry
Hyde, the chief prosecutor in the impeachment trial. But Park
Ridge, it seems, is very much Hillary Rodham Clinton country. It's
where she grew up, and, should she choose to run for the U.S.
Senate in New York, many residents would put aside politics and
wish her well. By PHIL BROWN.
</P>
<P>
   MATH-CONTEST (San Francisco) _ They looked like typical middle
school kids _ baggy jeans, mouths full of metal and impossible to
quiet down in the cafeteria. No pocket protectors or taped-up
glasses. But watch out if you sit them down in front of a math
problem. By JULIE CHAO.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-BUTTERFLIES (Angangueo, Mexico) _ Peasant farmer
Francisco Ambrocia Martinez appears a little uncomfortable with his
new role as environmentalist. ``We've made the decision to protect
this place, so that it will still be here for our children,'' he
says. Ambrocia is standing in what is perhaps one of the most
unique places on Earth _ the winter home of Monarch butterflies. By
MICHAEL RILEY. (Photo available on NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TELEWORK (San Francisco) _ Telecommuting has become an
acceptable mode of work for millions of Americans. Since its
inception in the 1970s, many employees have found working from home
a flexible alternative to traveling to an office. At the same time,
more companies are beginning to allow regular telecommuting, hoping
to boost employee productivity and morale. By WENDY TANAKA.
</P>
<P>
   HIRED-GUN (Houston) _ Got an ex-wife demanding a little extra
cash in the child support payments this month? If a contract
killing is the only way out, then Gary F. Johnson might be the
right person to contact. But there's a catch _ Johnson is a senior
investigator for the Harris County, Texas, District Attorney's
office who specializes in the undercover art of posing as a hit
man. By STEVE BREWER.
</P>
<P>
   BIRD-NAME (Houston) _ Almost three years after a Texas
naturalist discovered it in Brazil's Amazonian rain forest, the
colorful little bird with the big voice still lacks a name. Soon
that is expected to change. On Friday the Texas Audubon Society
will mark its 100th anniversary by auctioning off rights to name
the new-found antshrike. Bidding starts at $200,000. By ALLAN
TURNER.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMBARIUM (San Francisco) _ His business card says Caretaker &AMP;
Historian, but he's more than that. Much more. ``I'm the painter,
the gardener, the maintenance man, the inurment man,'' said Emmitt
Watson. Inurnment? ``I put the ashes in the urns,'' he explained.
Some would say Watson is the San Francisco Columbarium, the
101-year-old building that is home to the ashes of about 30,000
people. By JULIE CHAO.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GAY-HOTEL (Galveston, Texas) _ The first hotel catering solely
to gay and lesbian visitors in this tourist city is scheduled to
open in the spring. The 21-room inn is called Hollywood at
Galveston, and each room will recall legends of entertainment such
as Marilyn Monroe, Clark Gable, Lucille Ball and Desi Arnaz, owners
Sherman Houck and Bob Wilkins say. By KEVIN MORAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (Sacramento, Calif.) _ The signs told the story. In
the lobby of the convention center where Republicans gave standing
ovations to a strident anti-abortion speech by Sen. Bob Smith of
New Hampshire, a sign outside the restrooms said: ``Women to left,
men to right.'' The majority of American women probably will be
heading leftward in the 2000 election, given the fact that all the
Republican presidential hopefuls oppose women's right to abortion.
By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Two supporters of Sen. Charles E.
Schumer of New York got hassled by police officers while they were
trying to get the new senator to autograph some campaign posters.
That's not surprising. There are a lot of people in upstate New
York who are none too happy with Schumer's supporter of the Brady
Bill. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
</TEXT>
