<SLUG> BC-NY-KIDNAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDNAPPERS FREE CHECK-CASHING WORKER FOR $40,000 IN RANSOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An employee of a check-cashing store in Brooklyn was
kidnapped on Friday evening and held overnight until her husband,
who works at another check-cashing store, paid a $40,000 ransom to
her abductors, the police said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The 29-year-old woman, whose name was withheld by the police
because her abductors remained at large, was kidnapped at 5:45 p.m.
Friday as she left work at a check-cashing store, said Detective
Joseph Pentangelo, a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Police gave this account of the kinapping: The woman was pulled
from her car by two men and taken to another car where a driver was
waiting. The three men drove off with the woman and then called her
husband to say that they had kidnapped his wife and children. In
fact, the couple's children were safe with a relative who regularly
picks them up from school.
</P>
<P>
   The kidnappers arranged a rendezvous, ordering the husband to
meet them at a White Castle hamburger restaurant. The kidnappers
met him there and forced him to take them to the check-cashing
store where he works. Once there, they forced the husband to give
them $40,000 in cash from the till. It was not clear Sunday whether
the store was open for business when the kidnappers and the husband
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The kidnappers then told the husband to return to the White
Castle to wait for his wife and children. But the woman was
released unharmed at an intersection in Cypress Hills.
</P>
<P>
   The check-cashing stores that the husband and wife work for are
among eight in Brooklyn owned by Avilda Associates, a
Brooklyn-based company, according to state banking records. No one
at Avilda Associates could be reached for comment Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   No arrests have been made, and the investigation is continuing,
the police said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
