<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHUMER FANS STAY LOYAL DESPITE POLICE ROUGHHOUSING 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The phone rang. Sen. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y.,
was on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, senator,'' I said. ``How is everything?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is good,'' he said. ``I'm in Newburgh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Too bad. You have my sympathies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, no. Newburgh is nice. Anyway, here's why I called: I
read your column ... I just wanted to let you know that I spoke to
Bubbles this morning.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when Schumer told me that it had all been a mistake _
that he hadn't known a thing about the shameful treatment accorded
my friend Bubbles and his bride, Mrs. Bubbles, when they'd gone to
see Schumer during one of his swings through upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   I'd told the story in a recent column. The Bubbleses were big
Schumer backers in last November's election _ about the only ones
in a tiny village called Burdett, a few hundred miles west of
Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Burdett is a bend in the road in Schuyler County. Saying that
the place tilts Republican is like saying that Mike Tyson is moody.
When Franklin Delano Roosevelt died in office in the midst of World
War II, one Burdett resident went roaring up and down the main
street blasting his car horn in celebration.
</P>
<P>
   When that guy died, somebody pulled a car into his driveway and
blasted the horn. Bubbles didn't live there then. If he had, he
would have been everybody's prime suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Bubbles and Mrs. Bubbles operate a fine gourmet food business
that involves weekend trips to New York City to sell their
mustards, jams and other good stuff at the Union Square Green
Market in Manhattan and at the market at Grand Army Plaza in
Brooklyn. They'd met the senator at the Brooklyn market back when
he was a congressman, before he'd knocked off Sen. Alfonse D'Amato
in November.
</P>
<P>
   Bubbles had taken an intense interest in that race. He'd gone to
Syracuse University with D'Amato. His dislike for D'Amato dates
back to when Jack Paar was the biggest thing on television. So
Bubbles and Mrs. Bubbles had transported Schumer posters from New
York City to Burdett, displayed them prominently and, generally,
done whatever they could to promote Schumer's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, basking in victory's glow, they'd gone to Elmira
to see the new senator. They'd wanted his autograph on a few of
their posters and, incidentally, to give the senator a jar of Mrs.
Bubbles' really out-of-sight Ebbets Field mustard. But after they'd
approached the senator as he toured downtown Elmira, the local cops
had chased the Bubbleses out of town _ and rather rudely, too.
Schumer told me when he called that he hadn't had a clue that had
happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bubbles came up to me,'' Schumer said, ``and he had all these
posters. He said to me, `I'd like you to sign some posters.' I
said, `Sure, I'd love to.' And, immediately, these police officers
came over and said, `No, no, no, we've got to do that later.' I was
being followed around by them. So, I said, `Fine.' And then I had
no idea that they kept him away from me the rest of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   In his phone call to Bubbles, Schumer made arrangements to sign
the posters. He feels terrible that Bubbles got such grief from the
cops. Bubbles, on the other hand, feels pretty good after the
senator's phone call. He always knew that Schumer was a good guy,
and Bubbles did take the occasion to offer Schumer some sage,
detailed advice on a wide variety of public policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   Bubbles isn't even that mad at the Elmira cops any more. After
all, he told me, upstate New York contains a good many people who
might strike cops as a bit suspicious when they're guarding a U.S.
senator who backed the Brady Bill. Bubbles fully understands that.
</P>
<P>
   Those are his neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
