<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GRAND OLD DYSFUNCTIONAL PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ The signs told the story. In the lobby of
the convention center where Republicans gave standing ovations to a
strident anti-abortion speech by Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire, a
sign outside the restrooms said: ``Women to left, men to right.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority of American women probably will be heading leftward
in the 2000 election, given the fact that all the Republican
presidential hopefuls oppose women's right to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Past the restroom signs was a large room devoted to the oddities
of last weekend's California Republican Party convention. There
were booths where you could buy Clinton pinatas, bumper stickers
like ``Lorena Bobbitt for White House intern'' and matchboxes
containing tiny berets, cigars and blue dresses. There also were
women like Beth Rogers of the Seneca Network who try to give money
and visibility to Republican women candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Seneca, N.Y., is where the women's suffrage movement got its
start in 1848 and, said Rogers, ``Our motto is that women's
suffrage is not complete when women get the vote, but when they are
at the policy table.''
</P>
<P>
   They'd like to have some say in the abortion debate within the
Republican Party, in other words.
</P>
<P>
   The Seneca Network booth was right behind the fellow with the
Clinton pinata, a guy who still believes Vince Foster was murdered.
It was as if activist Republican women had been marginalized with
the wackos.
</P>
<P>
   Another booth had materials by a group called Republicans for
Choice, but when I visited it, no one was there.
</P>
<P>
   There were other signs of hard times for Republicans, signs that
they are behind the times.
</P>
<P>
   This was a party divided by a lot of talk about unity. Two lapel
stickers distinguished moderates from conservatives: ``It's the
women, stupid'' and ``I'm conservative. Is your tent big enough for
me?''
</P>
<P>
   Both were really pathetic, each in its own way.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans should have discovered women were important
decades ago, and realized that a pro-life position would never get
them more than a third of the women's vote.
</P>
<P>
   When conservative Republicans sardonically use the ``big tent''
metaphor of inclusion, asking if it's big enough for the
traditional rulers of the party, it sounds like a whiny version of
``My way or the highway.''
</P>
<P>
   It is their way or the highway when it comes to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   You can't make it in the party unless you swear you're pro-life,
and you'd better mean it because a lot of fanatics will be checking
up to see if you're a secret baby killer.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican candidates for president run the gamut from N to
O on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona says he's personally pro-life, but
thinks there's room in the party for those who aren't.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, the magazine publisher, seems to have found
religion on the issue, calling for a ``national dialogue'' on
abortion, and making it a bigger part of his spiel than last time
around.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative activist Gary Bauer says that ``mere words aren't
enough,'' and if a Republican is elected president, he or she
should actually work to make abortion illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Do we really want presidents of the United States dabbling in
uterine politics? The Grand Old Party would do better to
concentrate on starting a national dialogue on traditional
Republican issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to move on to educational issues and tax issues,''
said Julie Schaefer, a member of a conservative group called Soccer
Moms with a Brain. ``They've got to lighten up and liven up.''
</P>
<P>
   John McGraw, a pro-lifer, beat moderate Nicholas Bavaro in the
election for head of the state party. Bavaro was ecstatic to get 40
percent of the vote, though, and took this as a sign of hope that
Republicans could sit down and talk about beating Democrats instead
of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an amiable personality, and want to get out the message
that happy days are here again.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he is amiable, and there are many good people in the
Republican Party on both sides of the abortion battle. But how can
I say this? A very un-Reaganesque bitterness and meanness kept
bubbling to the surface at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday morning, a flier was found under delegates' hotel
doors, attacking Brooks Firestone, the moderate tire fortune heir
and winery owner who ran for vice chairman of the party. The flier
showed an old woman walking toward a bunch of grapes and said:
``Firestone's Hispanic Outreach: Pick My Grapes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic delegates were outraged. Tim Sanchez, an Oakland
delegate who is president of the Republican National Hispanic
Assembly, said: ``The tent of this party is large, but the tent is
not big enough for the bigots who put out this kind of crap.''
</P>
<P>
   The souvenir vendors hawked all too many T-shirts, hats and
bumper stickers with ugly slogans about Bill and Hillary Clinton
and Monica Lewinsky. One delegate foamed at the mouth about
Democratic rapists, and when a Republican woman tried to calm him
down he brusquely dismissed her.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of dissing going on in the Republican Party. Make
that ``dyssing,'' for dysfunctional.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-99 1306EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990301.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3040 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-BHUTTO-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     03-01 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-BHUTTO-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 KARACHI: ... Mother Teresa.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I see a contradiction in many ways. She was educated in modern
ways, but has a typically feudal outlook and autocratic behavior,''
said Abid Hasan Minto, president of Pakistan's Supreme Court Bar
Association. ``She thinks all organizations are outfits for the
purpose of keeping her in power. . . . Although she is a product of
the struggle against martial law, she has not learned democratic
ways at all.''
</P>
<P>
   So who has remained loyal to Bhutto? Hard-core party workers or
``jiyalas'' _ the ``shirtless masses'' _ form the backbone of her
party. Her members of parliament, reduced to a small minority in
both houses, represent liberal voices and some of the country's
brighter intellects. But even some loyalists concede they stay not
because they think she is clean, but because the alternative _ the
ruling party _ is both corrupt and reactionary.
</P>
<P>
   What remains of her star appeal pales next to her stature in
1986, when millions lined the roads to welcome her from exile in
the biggest outpouring in Pakistan's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to idolize her, and now I feel so stupid,'' said Amir
Mateen, former chief reporter of The Nation newspaper. ``We were so
forgiving. She was given a second chance. There was so much hope.
But in a matter of months, she was back to the same things, even
worse. She didn't learn any lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bhutto era, he said, was ``a great betrayal of her promise.
Intellectual betrayal is a luxury. But think of all the physical
betrayal: people who went to jail, were lashed, thousands who died
in the struggle against dictatorship. And for what?''
</P>
<P>
   It is perhaps her most idealistic supporters who feel most
bitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her biggest failure is that she never really conceptualized
what she could do for this country,'' said one disaffected adviser.
``She stood for modernism, liberal Islam, democracy, social
welfare, care for the poor and dispossessed. But there's no major
policy success of either of her administrations. I'm not even
talking about corruption. I'm talking about bad governance.''
</P>
<P>
   Bhutto was once the darling of liberal governments the world
over. Now her image is also sullied among the diplomatic corps in
the capital city of Islamabad. ``It's hard to understand her hold
on the party when she seems like tainted goods,'' said one senior
Western diplomat. ``Even if you ignore the charges against her,
look at her record. Promising talk, but little delivered.''
</P>
<P>
   But liberals here have nowhere else to go. Asma Jehangir,
chairwoman of the Human Rights Commission of Pakistan, criticized
Bhutto when she was prime minister for arresting Sharif's relatives
and allowing extrajudicial killings in the crime-ridden city of
Karachi. ``By no means is she ideal,'' Jehangir admitted. But
``without a doubt I can say Benazir Bhutto is better for this
country (than Sharif) as far as respect for human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Jehangir recounts tales of a compassionate Bhutto who took
interest in domestic violence victims, banned whipping of women,
and supported the crusade against bonded labor.
</P>
<P>
   Without doubt, Bhutto is the most important symbol for women in
this male-dominated society. At a recent legislative conference,
ruling party Cabinet minister Goyar Ayub Khan stood next to Bhutto
and spoke condescendingly of a tendency to elect widows and
daughters of martyred leaders out of ``sympathy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you hear what he said?'' Bhutto fumed afterward on her way
to a rally for press freedom. ``I'm a woman leader who broke male
taboos. There's a lot of male rage against me and my husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, she smiled sweetly and waved as crowds chanted,
``Benazir is our prime minister! We want Benazir!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Inshallah, by God's grace, we shall win!'' an admirer shouted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inshallah,'' she replied with a Mona Lisa smile.
</P>
<P>
   Bhutto contends that the case against her is politically
motivated, and it is true that Pakistan has a history of
governments persecuting their political opponents. But her
supporters concede that she did the same to her rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Bhutto says that documents alleging that she profited by fixing
contracts for customs inspection, tractors, gold, and submarines
are ``fabricated, forged, or taken out of context.'' Ali Sibtain
Fazli, chief prosecutor of three cases, scoffs at such talk. ``That
would mean the Swiss government was involved in forgery,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Her lawyers say they have been kidnapped, arrested, and
harassed. Some defense documents, they say, have been stolen. Cases
have been lodged against her mother, father-in-law, brother-in-law,
sister-in-law, political secretary, hairdresser, even the man who
serves her tea.
</P>
<P>
   Bhutto accuses not only Sharif, but Saifur Rehman, the senator
running the government's Accountability Bureau, of tax evasion,
loan defaulting, and graft, and there is plenty of evidence to
support those claims.
</P>
<P>
   Even if her trials are politically motivated, Azmat Saeed,
another prosecutor, says, ``That doesn't mean a crime hasn't been
committed.''
</P>
<P>
   Circumstances have changed since the charges were filed in 1997.
Despite piles of evidence, the government has had problems proving
the source of many of her supposed assets. And it has not been able
to convict her.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, said Zahid Hussain, senior editor of Newsline magazine,
``Domestic political developments in the last year and a half have
worked in her favor. She's no longer totally isolated. It doesn't
mean people have started liking her. They are disappointed with
both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Pakistanis blame themselves for the system that fostered
the Bhutto disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real problem in Pakistan is the elite, and I am a member
of that class,'' said Ahmed Kapadia, director of Evernew Studios, a
leading film agency. ``They control everything, and in their
short-term thinking, they believe if they disturb the status quo,
they will lose. They don't know that eventually, it will change and
they will be destroyed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
