u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-DAYCARE-BOS &LR;      03-01 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DAYCARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY SAYS WORKING MOTHERS DON'T CAUSE CHILDREN HARM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mothers who work outside of the home during the first three
years of their children's lives do not harm their youngsters'
behavior, mental development, or self-esteem, suggests a new study
involving thousands of families followed for years.
</P>
<P>
   And the two small negative effects that the study found in some
3- and 4-year-olds whose mothers went to work _ a tendency not to
comply immediately with instructions, and slightly lower
achievement test scores _ disappeared by the time they turned 5 or
6.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working mothers have a lot of guilt. I hope this study will
alleviate some of that guilt,'' said Elizabeth Harvey, assistant
professor of psychology at the University of Massachusetts at
Amherst and author of the study in the current Developmental
Psychology.
</P>
<P>
   The study is the first to look at this often-controversial issue
with as many families over as long a period of time, until some of
the children reached age 12.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey compared the children of women who worked outside the
home within the first three years of giving birth, to those whose
mothers did not go to work until after three years, if at all. She
also looked at whether fathers' employment status and working hours
have a negative effect on children, and found no significant
impact.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier studies have found conflicting results about children
whose mothers work outside the home, and this one certainly won't
be the last word. ``This study alone doesn't solve it,''
acknowledged Harvey, who was at the University of Connecticut when
she conducted the analysis.
</P>
<P>
   While the study's follow-up and its sheer size _ more than
12,000 people _ are among its strengths, its limitations include
the fact that it is based on a long-term national survey and not on
in-depth, face-to-face interviews, and that it does not take into
account the quality of child care.
</P>
<P>
   The quality of child care, whether provided by parents,
grandparents, or outside day-care providers, is considered a
significant factor in children's development. Harvey's study could
not assess variations in childen's development based on the quality
of care because it was based on surveys, not in-depth visits.
</P>
<P>
   An ongoing National Institute of Child Health and Development
study, which assesses child care and uses in-depth interviews, has
also found no measurable difference between children whose mothers
work outside or stay at home _ as long as the quality of child care
is good, whether provided by an outside day-care center or the
mother herself _ said Kathleen McCartney, a University of New
Hampshire professor and director of the UNH Child Study and
Development Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more research we have on the hours of employment, the more
we're finding no effects,'' said McCartney, who along with Nancy
Marshall of Wellesley College is following about 130 children in
Greater Boston as part of the NICHD study.
</P>
<P>
   Another participant in the NICHD study, and author of some of
the earlier research finding that a mother's absence from the home
has negative effects on children, reserved judgment, however.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Belsky, professor of human development at Pennsylvania State
University, said that even though Harvey's study found that the two
minor negative effects disappeared by age 5 or 6, and didn't
reappear by age 12, ``Does that mean they won't ever be evident
again?''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Belsky said, the study sounds ``exceedingly
meritorious.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over mothers who go to work and place their
children in day care or with other caregivers seems almost as
American as motherhood and apple pie. A 1997 Bureau of Labor
Statistics survey showed that 64.8 percent of mothers with children
6 years old or younger worked outside the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to have a profound ambivalence about child care in
our culture,'' said UNH's McCartney, while in places like western
Europe day care is more accepted and the main question is over how
society can make it better.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey said the findings support either child-rearing decision.
``I think the take-home message is that there's no one right way to
do it. Being employed during the early years (of a child's life)
and being at home during the early years can both be good choices
and can lead to healthy development for children,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The reactions of Boston-area mothers to the study reflect the
range of opinions. For three mothers who work outside the home and
leave their children at Bright Horizons Family Solutions Child Care
Center in Quincy, the study supports what they already feel is the
right decision for them and their family.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's good news,'' said Janet Page, 37, of the study's
findings. Her 15-month-old daughter, Kristen, is cared for at
Bright Horizons, and her 5-year-old daughter, Kathryn, at Meeting
House Montessori in Braintree, while she works as a CitiBank
accounts manager and her husband as a Turner Construction projects
manager. ``I feel comfortable with our decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Agreed Rosemary Ruggles, a 37-year-old single mother who runs a
medical management company at Quincy Hospital and drops off her 2
1/2-year-old daughter, Paige, at Bright Horizons: ``I've had no
regrets at all.''
</P>
<P>
   And Gail Schroth, 42, sees her 5-year-old son, E.J., developing
new social skills since he started going to the day-care center.
``This is the best thing for him, without a doubt,'' said Schroth,
who works as a hospital financial services director, and whose
husband is an engineer.
</P>
<P>
   But for one stay-at-home mother of four, who is trained as an
obstetrician/gynecologist, the study can't answer all the questions
about possible long-term effects on children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kinds of problems I would look for, not that I'm saying
there are those problems: How they do in their marriage, the rate
of teen pregnancy and drug use, all those things that are much more
complex and subtle,'' said Dr. Amy Tuteur, who has three boys and a
girl, ranging in age from 4 to 11 1/2, and whose husband works as
an attorney.
</P>
<P>
   In describing her decision to stay at home, Tuteur said: ``I
feel like it's my obligation. I couldn't stand the feeling of guilt
like I was missing something, that there'd be a school play and I
wouldn't be able to be there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-99 1322EST &QL; 
