u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-01 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDGETING YOUR WAY TO FITNESS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lately I been reading books about exercise in the hope of
inspiring myself to actually do some because I have reached a point
in life when a harsh choice must be made, i.e., get moving or die.
</P>
<P>
   You might think this would be motivating, but it's not that
simple. The specter of untimely death must be weighed against the
prospect of getting my rear end in gear and walking or swimming or
biking at a fairly swift pace three or four times a week for a
minimum of 40 minutes. I am weighing the pros and cons. Meanwhile,
I gather from my reading that in order to truly appreciate being
fit you should first be unfit. So in a sense I'm already halfway
there.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday I came across another piece of good news: The fatter you
are the more calories you burn when you exercise. A chart in
Tamilee Webb's ``Workouts for Dummies,'' recommended to me by a
fitness professional, for obvious reasons, indicates the number of
calories burned per hour by body weight for various activities. For
example, a 198-pound person burns 960 calories per hour jogging, a
110-pound person burns just 535.
</P>
<P>
   The chart lists more than 40 activities, among them the usual _
running, swimming, tennis, etc. _ and the unusual _ sailing,
horseshoe pitching, croquet, golf (with cart), among others. I find
it difficult to believe that some of these activities burn the
stated number of calories.
</P>
<P>
   Archery, for example. According to the chart, a 154-pound person
burns 210 to 280 calories an hour engaging in archery, which I
happen to know firsthand is slightly less strenuous than deep
breathing.
</P>
<P>
   And fishing. The chart claims a 154-pound person burns up 140 to
280 calories per hour fishing. Maybe, if she's in the water
wrestling a man-eating shark.
</P>
<P>
   But I shouldn't be too quick to discount these figures, because
a recent study revealed that moderate exercise, even doing
housework or walking the dog, can be just as effective as the more
strenuous variety. The survey said nothing about cats, which
surprised me because I know that cleaning up after them constitutes
a workout. Lifting 20-pound sacks of litter off the supermarket
shelf, heaving them onto the checkout counter, wrestling them into
the car, lugging them into the house. And that's before I even
think about changing the boxes.
</P>
<P>
   The semi-weekly total change of two separate litter boxes could
be an Olympic event. Empty used litter into plastic bags. Scrape
boxes. Carry plastic bags to trash. Sweep up surrounding area.
Scrub boxes with Lysol-laced hot water. Drag 20-pound bag of cat
litter to boxes. Lift. Pour litter. Smooth and distribute litter in
attractive manner to please highly critical cats. I'd be willing to
bet this whole routine burns more calories than the most strenuous
game of croquet.
</P>
<P>
   Another recent study found that people who are naturally fidgety
burn more calories than those who aren't. According to this study
there is no way to train yourself to be fidgety if you're not
inclined to be, although I suppose that won't stop somebody from
writing a bestseller, ``Fidget Your Way to a New You!!!''
</P>
<P>
   For reasons that are not exactly clear, the fidgeting finding
leads me to wonder if negative emotions rev up the metabolic
engine. That's been my experience. For instance I'm sure that in
the last week I've burned off hundreds of calories envying a friend
who invested $2,000 in Amazon.com two years ago and is now skiing
in Italy, expending thousands of dollars and calories on the
slopes, while I sit here trying to figure out if there are any
circumstances under which unloading the dishwasher could possibly
be construed as an aerobic exercise. It's got to be as strenuous as
golf (with cart), no?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
