<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROTH IRA IS THE BEST BET AGAINST HIGHER TAXES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. The Roth IRA is being promoted on the basis of reduced tax
liability. This tax structure raises my concern about the Roth IRA
at the time of retirement. Is there anything in the legislation
preventing government from changing the rules in 40 years? My
concern arises from the following example: Consider $1 of taxable
income and a 28 percent tax bracket. Suppose I invest in something
that grows tax-deferred by a factor of 100 over some investment
period. With the traditional IRA, my dollar eventually grows to
$100, and upon withdrawal I get to keep $72 while giving the
government $28. With the Roth IRA, I give away 28 cents upfront and
invest only 72 cents. With the same growth rate, I have the same
$72. However, with the Roth I have given the government only 28
cents in taxes, instead of the $28 it would have received if it had
invested its share along with mine. Wouldn't this leave me as
vulnerable to additional taxation as semi-employed FICA recipients
are today? I like the traditional IRA because the government gets
its $28 when I get my $72, and there is less chance for a rule
change by Congress if the government hasn't already consumed its
share.
</P>
<P>
   G.S., Lynnfield, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I suppose you can argue that anything is possible in
Washington, but I think that the prospects of Congress reneging on
the Roth IRA are very dim _ simply because changing these rules
would represent such a spectacular breaking of a promise that it
would likely constitute political suicide.
</P>
<P>
   But much more important is another factor that you don't
mention.
</P>
<P>
   The rules for the traditional IRA specify simply that money
stashed away in a traditional IRA accumulates on a tax-deferred
basis, and the rules say nothing about the tax structure upon
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   The popular theory is that when the money is saved, the owner is
working and is in a relatively high tax bracket, whereas when it is
finally withdrawn the owner is likely to be retired and in a lower
bracket. If it works out that the person is in the same bracket at
both times, as you point out, the eventual amount of taxation is
the same.
</P>
<P>
   But what happens if tax rates in general are higher in the
distant future? Suppose you defer paying a 28 percent tax now, only
to face a 38 percent tax levy 30 years from now when you withdraw
money from your IRA?
</P>
<P>
   If you think a 38 percent tax is unthinkable, reflect on the tax
rates in many European economies. Also reflect on the
much-discussed problems with Social Security and other entitlement
systems that are projected to be very real at that time.
</P>
<P>
   Let's suppose the situation is critical enough so that something
has to be done. It seems to me most likely that Congress would find
it easier to gradually crank up tax rates in general, rather than
break the promise that is inherent in the Roth IRA.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, I consider a major attraction of the Roth IRA
the fact that it represents an insurance policy against possible
higher tax rates in the future.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a 50-year-old divorced woman and I have only been in the
work force for the past seven years because I was at home for 15
years raising my children. I have money invested in the following:
Scudder Massachusetts Tax-Free Bond fund, $1,646; a Fidelity
rollover IRA with $5,531 in Puritan, $11,709 in Fidelity Growth and
Income, and $4,633 in Fidelity Low-Priced Stock funds; and a 401(k)
program begun last July with my current employer, containing $866
in a common stock fund, $200 in money markets, $416 in a balanced
account, and $623 in an aggressive stock fund. I have 10 percent of
my salary withheld for the 401(k) each week, and my employer also
contributes, adding $356 last year. I also have some money in a
previous employer's 401(k) that I will need to put in the Fidelity
IRA and need to know where to invest it. I don't know if I am
investing wisely, especially in the Fidelity IRA. I need to know if
I should shift some of the money to other funds. If I do so, will
it cost me money? Am I having enough withheld from my paycheck? Am
I on the right track?
</P>
<P>
   M.C., Winthrop, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think in general you're doing pretty well. I'm not
enthusiastic about that $200 in the money markets, and while $200
isn't a whole lot of money, it's nearly 10 percent of the 401(k),
and as the account builds, further contributions there will create
a substantial drag on the account's growth.
</P>
<P>
   I'd move that money to the balanced account, and if you are
making ongoing contributions to the money market account, I'd move
those either to the balanced or the common stock account, depending
on how aggressive you want to be.
</P>
<P>
   I have less concern about the Fidelity funds, all of which are
excellent performers. You don't specify how big the 401(k) account
from a previous employer is, but you don't want to add the proceeds
to the rollover IRA _ you want to start a separate rollover IRA for
that money.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for this is that the only advantage of a rollover IRA
is that it allows you to transfer the account into a future
employer's 401(k) or another qualified retirement plan, should you
desire. Once you add funds, though, you can no longer make such a
move.
</P>
<P>
   I can see no good reason to make such a move at this time, but
you'll want to keep your options open, which is easily done simply
by opening another rollover IRA account with Fidelity and putting
the money there.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Select Health Care would be a good choice for this
money, provided that it amounts to less than $3,000 _ in which case
such an investment might represent too large a bet on that risky
but potentially very rewarding sector. If the amount is more than
$3,000, why not divide the rollover account between Fidelity Select
Health Care and Fidelity Overseas funds?
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't cost you anything to diversify the money in the
Fidelity IRA, but I think you have it nicely allocated and don't
think you'd gain much by changing.
</P>
<P>
   Are you saving enough? Well, I did some backward calculations _
which included some guesses _ and came up with an estimate of an
annual salary of about $30,000 and monthly contributions to the
401(k), including those of your employer, of $308.33. Now, if we
assume average 10 percent annual growth throughout the portfolio,
those contributions over the next 15 years would take you to
$230,028. This calculation doesn't include the unspecified amount
of money in that old 401(k) account.
</P>
<P>
   Should you save more? You'll have to look at your budget and
your likely needs in retirement. Here are a couple of projections,
though, just to give you a sense of how the numbers would work.
</P>
<P>
   If you added $50 a month to your 401(k) contributions, the
account would grow to $249,972. If you added $100 a month, the
projection would be $269,916.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, if higher contributions on your part would
trigger higher contributions on the part of your employer, the
numbers would be even higher.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
