<HEADER>
A3052 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-EVENSONG-BOS &LR;      03-01 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-EVENSONG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WORLD INTRUDES ON MINISTERIAL ORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
EVENSONG 
By Gail Godwin. Ballantine. 
407 pp. $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With its trails marked by the shadows of the past, the world of
Gail Godwin's fiction is usually a place where love and memory
collide _ where a daughter can forgive, just barely, a parent's
former wrongs, and that act of mercy can lead to her own
transformation. These interstices between obligation and charity
(or even, you might say, between a moral life and a happy one) are
the deepest concerns of Godwin's novels; though she belongs to the
school of what I call somber realism, those day-by-day studies in
family portraiture are mostly intent upon delivering their
characters from the inside out. One of the best of these stories
was the 1991 novel, ``Father Melancholy's Daughter,'' in which a
beloved, sorrowful Episcopal priest, raising his young daughter
alone, shared his heaven-bound petitions with her each night.
``I've had my lows,'' he says to God and girl alike one evening.
``God knows I've had my lows, but together we have held the fort.''
</P>
<P>
   The girl was Margaret Gower, and by the end of that story she
was a young woman on the verge of seminary. That she was also
reading ``Middlemarch'' seems prescient as well, because in
``Evensong'' _ a sort of sequel to ``Father Melancholy's
Daughter,'' though a story that easily stands alone _ she has
married a benign version of Casaubon. Now the Reverend Bonner, head
of an Episcopal parish in the North Carolina mountains, Margaret is
a thoughtful, funny, headstrong woman in her early 30s: what you
might call a good woman, whether you met her in the hardware store
or in the receiving line after Sunday services. Adrian Bonner, 20
years her elder and an associate of her father, is her devoted but
remote husband, a former Jungian who's the chaplain at High
Balsam's Fair Haven School, where wayward youth go to thrive.
Together, the Bonners minister to the sick and deprived or depraved
with equanimity and courage, but when ``Evensong'' opens, they're
having more luck with their constituencies than they are with each
other. This is a marriage warmed by God and a mutuality of mind,
but somewhat cool to its own touch. That lonely paradox is the
emblematic center of the novel, which will travel through half the
individual sagas in High Balsam before its journey is complete.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with its name, ``Evensong'' is a deeply considered,
even dignified novel, and it admirably limns the actual workings of
a godly inner life _ how Margaret perceives the world and her place
in it through the daily, overlapping narratives of prayer and
thought. But the novel also creaks from its opening pages:
Stylistic grace and delicacy are not part of Godwin's assets, nor
is unobtrusive dialogue. What she can do is set up an old-fashioned
story with a cast of intriguing and screwball characters, and
``Evensong'' provides that with much ado, from a young delinquent
in Adrian's charge to a couple of mysterious strangers at the door.
One stays engaged with the story for sheer narrative hook: As with
story lines from Dickens to ``Guiding Light,'' you simply want to
find out who does what to whom.
</P>
<P>
   The tacit disarray of Margaret and Adrian's marriage belongs
mostly to wounds of the past, and the novel dips between their
courtship and the present to heighten the consequences of both.
Thrown into an orphanage when he was 6, Adrian had a youth shaped
by cruel taskmasters and too little love before he put his trust in
God and the acrobatics of the mind, both of which could leave
earthly pains behind. Raised by her father after her mother fled
the trials of marriage and children, Margaret understands firsthand
her husband's early loss, but their shared heartache doesn't always
make them closer _ common injury rarely guarantees rescue. What
each of them possesses is the sustenance at the end of the day
provided by good works: Her enduring ability to stand tall in the
face of other people's pain; his sweet authority with the troubled
students at the school. Thanks to Godwin's intensity of focus upon
their quotidian emotional life, you can feel the way these bonds
and advances help the Bonners to survive _ the way a prayer in the
morning, which may have felt as though it were falling in a desert,
can give you a little rain when you'd all but given up.
</P>
<P>
   Through these daily trials march a number of well-drafted
characters with their own lots to contemplate: Tony, a sweet
octogenarian who shows up from a neighboring monastery, carrying
handrolled cigarettes and an uncertain past; Chase, the Peruvian
teenager whom Adrian loves and who has just left alcohol rehab;
Margaret's best friend, Gus, a strong-hearted architect who's
trying to figure out, in her middle 40s, how to share her life with
somebody else. Least appealing but most demanding is a ``freelance
apostle'' named Grace Munger, wrapped in a formidable red cape (and
God's will, or so she believes), organizing a Millennium Birthday
March for Jesus through High Balsam in this Advent week of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose the millennium has to rear its head in contemporary
fiction, but its presence here serves little purpose _ like Grace's
parade, it feels like a contrived effort to manipulate the unruly
elements of human happenstance. In fact, for all its fine attention
to the presence of God, a number of dei ex machina crash around
onstage in ``Evensong,'' which ought to have just taken its chances
with the secular unfolding of time and space. As it is, the
atmosphere of High Balsam _ its class tensions and human frailties
_ are introduced with peripheral melodramas (a shooting over a
parking place) and villainous characters (a reporter who, in real
life, would never be given a job). These devices make ``Evensong''
feel heavy-handed and overly determined, when the emotional ballast
and simplicity of its central story would have sufficed.
</P>
<P>
   For, as Margaret or Adrian either one could tell you, all you
really need is faith in the power of narrative _ the rest is all so
much external trappings, which only clutter things up. What's
lovely and lasting about ``Evensong'' is that straightforward
knowledge: Adrian's belief that God appears in ``the answering
silence,'' Margaret's beautiful description of prayer to a young
lost girl: ``The amazing thing is, this constant accounting of
yourself to an unseen other does make you change and grow.'' The
final beauty of ``Evensong'' is its ability to address God _ to
address the mystery of faith _ by comprehending, then embracing,
this premise of uncertainty itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
