<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-BHUTTO-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TRIALS OF BENAZIR BHUTTO 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KARACHI _ What happened to Benazir Bhutto?
</P>
<P>
   Eleven years after being swept to power on the hopes of
millions, she spends more time these days in courtrooms fighting
corruption charges than in parliament battling for her people.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, the beautiful young Bhutto embodied the struggle
against military dictatorship and championed the poor, illiterate
majority of her 130 million people. In 1988, she became the first
female leader of an Islamic nation, only to be dismissed two years
later for graft and abuse of power. She was acquitted and reelected
in 1993, but drummed out again in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Today &LR; , accusations that were largely discounted in 1990 are
widely believed. Courts in Pakistan and Switzerland are
scrutinizing documents from overseas firms, banks, and alleged
front men that purportedly map a trail of $1.5 billion in kickbacks
to Bhutto and her family. A guilty verdict on any of six cases
against her could mean fines, prison, and a ban from politics.
</P>
<P>
   The fall from grace of Benazir Bhutto, or ``BB'' as she is known
here, is in many ways a tale of squandered promise. It is betrayal,
say disillusioned followers, of her tremendous potential to change
this impoverished nation and of the near-religious faith people had
in her.
</P>
<P>
   Bhutto, head of the People's Party of Pakistan, maintains that
she is the victim of a conspiracy by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif to
eliminate his only serious opposition. She also attributes her bad
name to ``the unhealthy relationship between the mass media, the
public, and elected representatives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think President Clinton, Princess Di, and I have been the
most tragic victims of that in the last decade,'' Bhutto concluded.
</P>
<P>
   In court appearances, rallies, closed-door party meetings,
public engagements, and interviews with the Globe over five days,
the 45-year-old Bhutto was by turns charming and arrogant,
convinced she will prevail in court and determined to regain the
prime minister's seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The accusation that I stole even one cent is false,'' she said
indignantly when asked about documents admitted in court linking
her and her husband, Asif Ali Zardari, to bank accounts and lavish
properties in the United States, Britain, France, and Switzerland.
``One may or may not have a house, a bank account, or money. But
there must be a link to corruption. Where is the link?
</P>
<P>
   ``I know kings and presidents and prime ministers and first
ladies and human rights people and women leaders who respect me and
admire me,'' she declared, her voice thick with outrage. The
current government ``had no right to drag my name in mud and say .
. . I'm a common criminal!''
</P>
<P>
   So who is the real Benazir Bhutto?
</P>
<P>
   Along the stairs in one of her homes hangs a yellowing set of
drawings from the 1980s by a Pakistani political cartoonist. Bhutto
is shown gazing at a portrait of her father, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, a
charismatic prime minister who was hanged in 1979 by military coup
leaders. She spent four years in prison under military rule.
Another sketch shows her late father's home, where she lived while
campaigning for democracy, with the caption: ``Liberty has still a
house to live in. Wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   A more prescient drawing shows the future leader gazing in a
mirror, with the warning below, ``Caution: Fame is a magnifying
glass.''
</P>
<P>
   Fame would put the life of any two-time prime minister under a
microscope. But detractors _ and there are more now than defenders
_ say that power and a cabal of self-serving sycophants corrupted
the promising young leader.
</P>
<P>
   The eldest of two daughters and two sons of an affluent
landowning family, Bhutto was her father's favorite. The elder
Bhutto did not bow to the male chauvinism of a Muslim society, and
tapped his daughter as his protege. He may have also been intrigued
by the father-daughter team of Jawaharlal Nehru and Indira Gandhi
in neighboring India.
</P>
<P>
   Educated at Harvard and Oxford, the aristocratic BB was feted by
politicians from Cambridge to Capitol Hill and canonized by the
Western media. Before serving as principal speaker of Harvard's
1989 commencement ceremony, the woman known as an undergraduate as
Pinky was hailed by Harvard friend _ and future US ambassador _
Peter W. Galbraith as a liberator of women and political prisoners
who ended her nation's death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   In Pakistan, she was embraced as a liberal who triumphed over
tragedy and could lead a poor nation out of its feudal past.
</P>
<P>
   The real Bhutto is full of incongruities. She preaches
democracy, but insiders say she won't take advice or criticism. She
espouses modern values, but wears a headscarf in public _ rare
among educated women. She agreed to an arranged marriage her mother
pushed, to a man with a shady reputation. And she has stood by him
even when advised that a divorce would clear her name.
</P>
<P>
   Though her reputation has undoubtedly been sullied, Bhutto still
enjoys movie-star status here. She is thronged by bone-crushing
mobs wherever she goes. Yet she seems to take her popularity for
granted.
</P>
<P>
   She can also switch instantly from sweet to imperious if anyone
dares criticize her. She is hailed as a champion of the poor, yet
her regal bearing and the fawning attention of her inner circle
strike more parallels with the Queen of England than Mother Teresa.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
