A3056 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-HATRED-BOS &LR;      03-01 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-HATRED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP STUDENT, NOW SUPREMACIST, DENIES HIS PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTWOOD, Mass. _ Before his dark transformation, he was Andrew
Britt Greenbaum, a crackerjack student who drove too fast, played a
mean game of chess, and spent long hours reading alone in his room.
</P>
<P>
   Like high school kids do everywhere, his classmates labeled him:
Greenbaum was a brainwave, or a nerd, or a radical. He played with
swords. He took Civil War history a little too seriously. He did
not hang out at the mall.
</P>
<P>
   Only the few who knew him better than casually caught glimpses
of something more chilling.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd talk about how other races were inferior and all that
crap,'' said Tarleton Hill, a classmate.
</P>
<P>
   Within days of graduation from Westwood High School in 1996,
Greenbaum drove down Route 109 to Dedham, walked into the busy
probate court there, and began the process that would legally
change his name to Davis Wolfgang Hawke. It was a more fitting
appellation, he believed, and it helped complete the transformation
of what he had become: a hatemonger, a pariah, a disciple of Adolf
Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really despise Massachusetts,'' said Hawke, now a junior at
Wofford College in Spartanburg, S.C. ``It's a very liberal state.
It's a very Jewish state. It's a very black state. There's nothing
in that state for me. And I'll never be back.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Hawke is the leader of the Internet-launched Knights of
Freedom, a neo-Nazi organization he operates from a dorm-room
computer at a school that is horrified and embarrassed about a hate
group that is testing the limits of free speech and drawing close
attention from human rights organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this kid had the potential to be a real leader,'' said
Mark Potok, a spokesman for the Southern Poverty Law Center, which
tracks hate groups nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The white supremacist movement in this country in general is
very much seeking out the leadership cadres of tomorrow,'' he said.
``There is a real interest in looking for kids with charisma like
Davis Wolfgang Hawke.''
</P>
<P>
   But human rights leaders say he is now under suspicion among
white supremacist groups because of the name he had hoped to bury
in the dense files of a Dedham courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Greenbaum-cum-Hawke's journey from this
well-groomed, affluent Boston suburb to a Deep South dormitory room
decorated with swastika flags and authentic-looking Nazi uniforms
is the tale of squandered promise, icy intolerance, and the irony
of an anti-Semite haunted by the Jewish name on his birth
certificate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have to engage in violence to cause pain and to
cause harm,'' said Leonard Zakim, executive director of the
Anti-Defamation League's New England office. ``The quicker you blow
him out of the water, the better. This is a guy who should be
exposed.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenbaum was born Oct. 21, 1978, in Newport, R.I., the son of
Hyman Andrew Greenbaum, a Georgia native, and the former Peggy
Amber Davis of New Mexico, according to a copy of his birth
certificate on file at the Dedham courthouse. The family moved to
Lakeville, Mass. when Andrew was still a toddler and he attended
grammar school in southeastern Massachusetts before the Greenbaums
resettled into a neat, modest home here.
</P>
<P>
   The tidy blue house with cream trim backs onto a cemetery and is
just a short walk from the local high school. School officials
would not be interviewed for this story, but his classmates
invariably mention two things about Greenbaum's high school days:
He was remarkably bright, and he was more than a little bit
different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Loner is a good word for it, but he had a little crowd,'' said
Arthur H. Ellis Jr., who graduated with Greenbaum. ``He was smart
but everyone knew he had a little weird thing going on _ kind of
like an intellectual radical.''
</P>
<P>
   What his classmates saw as loneliness, Greenbaum called
determined reflection. There was no single trigger, no defining
moment, no epiphany that propelled him toward hatred. It was, he
said, an acquired taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a gradual evolution,'' he said, one that occurred in
the stacks of the local library and under the reading lamp in his
bedroom. He read and re-read Hitler's manifesto, ``Mein Kampf,''
and studied the tenets of socialism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pretty much kept to myself, but I'm not an introvert,''
Hawke said last week. ``I'm a leader and a leader can't be an
introvert. I'm interested in being a leader, not being someone's
friend. In any social relationship, I have to be the superior.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawke, who ran unsuccessfully for class president his junior
year, said if his Westwood classmates were uncomfortable with him,
the feeling was mutual.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a Jewish town,'' he said. ``Not only was it Jewish, but
they felt the need to bus in a large number of Negroes from
inner-city Boston. Every teacher there was a radical left-wing
liberal.''
</P>
<P>
   His high school yearbook said Greenbaum held the top spot on the
chess club: ``That came as no surprise since he's the best in the
state.'' Hawke said he found chess ``a good metaphor for war.''
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a skull-adorned T-shirt and a dark cowboy hat, Greenbaum
posed for a yearbook picture in his neighborhood's cemetery
standing over a gravestone etched with the name Sherman _ an
intended reference to the Civil War Union general's march through
the South, which still draws Confederate scorn. Beneath the photo,
where other students would have inscribed silly nicknames and tales
of sporting triumphs, Greenbaum wrote: ``The rock, the vulture, and
the chain; all that the proud can feel of pain.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day Westwood handed diplomas to its class of 1996,
Greenbaum never showed up. Within days he was in the Dedham
courthouse, seeking to bury his past.
</P>
<P>
   In papers filed to support his application for a change of
identity, Greenbaum was asked to state his reason for the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always responded to a different name and I wish to
formalize my name prior to attending college in the fall as to
avoid confusion,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is not that benign.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-99 1330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990301.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3058 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-HATE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     03-01 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-HATE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 WESTWOOD, Mass.: ... that benign.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the time the court granted his request, Greenbaum had already
been detected by the Anti-Defamation League, which spotted him on a
Norwood street corner handing out Knights of Freedom fliers,
decrying rising immigration, US financial support for Israel, and
gays in President Clinton's administration.
</P>
<P>
   Hawke acknowledged handing out hate literature in his high
school as well as in ``mainly blue-collar'' neighborhoods near
Westwood. And Hawke knew the credibility of his views, including
sterilization for Jews, was undermined by his surname. ``I didn't
want people to think I'm Jewish, when I'm not Jewish,'' said Hawke.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to reach Hawke's parents were not successful. Telephone
calls, knocks at their door, and notes left at their address,
seeking comment, went unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   Hawke said they oppose his activities. ``But what can they do
about it? It's my life, not theirs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hawke insists Hyman Greenbaum is his stepfather. He said he is
the ``illegitimate'' son of a man his mother did not marry and he
does not know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no Jewish blood in me,'' he said. ``I can't help the
fact that my stepfather is a quarter Jewish.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the truth of his lineage, when Davis Wolfgang Hawke
arrived in South Carolina for his freshman year at Wofford, an
expensive and mostly white college affiliated with the United
Methodist Church, he left Andrew Britt Greenbaum behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Carolina is very conservative, so I thought it would be
more receptive to my beliefs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He kept largely to himself, accumulating a 3.8 grade-point
average studying German and history. College officials said he has
complied with authority and, until recently, presented no problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say hello and he'd always returned the greeting,'' said
Dan Maultsby, Wofford's dean. ``But I never had a personal
conversation with him. That embarrasses me now. I wish I had. It's
an embarrassment to a small college that he's been here for 2 1/2
years and now we find out about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Knights of Freedom, a fledgling outfit with about 20 followers
until it blossomed via the Internet last summer, became a campus
flashpoint earlier this month when the Spartanburg Herald-Journal
newspaper ran a story about Hawke's dorm-room operation. Three
hundred students turned out for a recent candlelight vigil
condemning Hawke and his beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was a considerable amount of fear by people who
thought it might escalate into something violent,'' said Kris
Neely, a Wofford sophomore who organized the vigil. ``We're working
to answer questions about whether we need to be a more diverse
student body.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawke, however, is enjoying the attention. He's posted a press
release on his Web page that states: ``Remember that all coverage
is good coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   On that Web page, Hawke, a soft-spoken and articulate
20-year-old, uses florid prose to denounce ``Jewish tyranny'' and
federal taxes, and to espouse an Aryan homeland and the confinement
of minorities to Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Davis puts everything on the line,'' said Matthew O`Connor,
who identified himself as a Knights of Freedom member from southern
New Jersey. ``Basically, he's our last chance. And I truly believe
that. I'll follow him right down to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   For $5 a month, Hawke's members _ estimated at about 200 despite
his claim of many more _ receive a newsletter, videotapes, copies
of hate speeches, a certificate of rank, an armband, a picture ID,
and a mail-order catalog.
</P>
<P>
   He talks grandly of an upcoming march on Washington, the
imminent influx of about $700,000 from an unnamed source, and the
planned purchase of a party ``compound'' in Wyoming or Montana.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the United States of America, we have something called the
First Amendment, which gives me as much right to express my beliefs
as anyone else,'' said Hawke.
</P>
<P>
   True enough, say Wofford officials who are monitoring his
activities. They agree that Hawke is abiding by the letter of the
school's student code: He uses his personal computer linked to a
commercial Internet provider, and the address on the Web site is
listed as Walpole, Mass., a commercial postal box where he said
letters are collected and forwarded to him.
</P>
<P>
   The publicity Hawke so dearly covets will be his undoing,
hate-speech specialists said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a kid who thinks because he has fairly good SAT
scores, he's going to rule the universe like some character out of
a Batman comic book,'' said Potok, whose Montgomery, Ala.-based
organization reported last week that hate groups on the Internet
had grown by about 60 percent, from 163 in 1997 to 254 at the end
of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a wannabe fuhrer _ a boy who wants to be a big man,''
Potok said. ``But his darkest secret, that he is the son of Hyman
Greenbaum, is very likely to destroy him.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Tom Metzger, leader of the California-based White Aryan
Resistance, said Sunday, ``If he were, in fact, a product of Jewish
parents, and he was a Jew, he would not be eligible to lead any
struggle we're involved in.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Kaiman, southeast regional director of the Anti-Defamation
League, said it is chilling that Hawke has gone unnoticed for so
long.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want him hiding in his dorm room in an SS uniform,''
Kaiman said. ``We want to out him. We want to get him out of his
dorm room and then let him stand up and say what he believes. He's
a coward.''
</P>
<P>
   And an unfitting symbol for this town and a school known for
hockey heroics and stellar scholarship, residents here say.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's obviously a kid with a lot of problems. Pretty messed
up,'' said Lindsay Rose, president of Westwood High's Class of '96.
``It's so unbelievable that he came out of such a nice town. You
just never know what's going on in some people's head.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
