<SLUG> BC-PERSONAL-TOUCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU WANT SERVICE WITH YOUR SMILE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER S. CANELLOS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the age of chain-store blandness, when every stretch of Route
1 wears the same colors and stripes from Boston to Baton Rouge, the
``personal touch'' is making a suspiciously timed comeback in
retail stores and service outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the young teenager, uniformed in a red shirt and
floating black pants, who addressed the tired crowd filing out of
Loews Nickelodeon Cinema the other evening: ``Thank you for coming
to Loews,'' he croaked, as if hoping to swallow the words.
</P>
<P>
   The ``thank you,'' repeated robotically to each customer, seemed
insincere on its face: The clerk's expression never wavered from
person to person _ not if the customer was dazed, annoyed, or
slumping with fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the only recognizably human aspect of the entire
exchange was the embarrassment of the clerk, commanded by his
corporate employer to present a facade of friendliness.
</P>
<P>
   From taco stands to muffler stores, chains seem to have resolved
in unison to take on one of the conundrums of the service economy:
The lowest paid, least trained workers are the ones who interact
with the consumer. But instead of raising their workers' status, or
training, or pay to make them either more capable or more inclined
to impress the public, they've simply asked them to repeat certain
sugary phrases.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sort of `Stepford Wife' quality about it,'' says
Ralph Whitehead, a social critic and professor of at the University
of Massachusetts at . ``Twenty years ago it was enough to get these
people to put a button on their shirt with a happy face. Now they
have to be the happy face.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitehead believes that companies simply want a leg up on their
competitors, and that they think courtesy is the key to brand
loyalty: A warm hello from a McDonald's clerk on the highway in
Pennsylvania keeps customers from going to Burger King once they
get home to Dubuque.
</P>
<P>
   Still, can it be a coincidence that employee ``friendliness'' is
on the rise at just the moment that chain-store ownership has
washed any mark of local color or distinctiveness from the service
landscape? And is the true competition not between chains but
between the entire chain-store mentality and customers' memories of
the individual stores now vanished?
</P>
<P>
   Like the actors who play that loving, long-married couple
shopping for their grandchildren in those ubiquitous Wal-mart TV
ads, many employees have become props in a campaign to pretend that
today's retail marts are just as homey as the mom-and-pop stores
they drove out of business.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, for instance, moviegoers of a sufficient age remember
the original Nickelodeon Cinema or its predecessor, the Abbey
Cinema, the quirky art house near the Boston University campus that
was a distinctive part of the local movie scene, linked in memory
to the masterpieces of the early '70s: ``Mean Streets,'' ``The
Conversation,'' and many others.
</P>
<P>
   They might also remember the Nickelodeon in its second
incarnation, as part of the Boston-based Sack chain. When the
theater moved to new quarters and shifted to more conventional
fare, many locals directed their displeasure toward the home-town
mogul who controlled Sack cinemas, A. Alan Friedberg. The operative
presumption, at least, was that Friedberg, who was active on the
local social scene, cared what his customers thought.
</P>
<P>
   For the past decade, however, the Nickelodeon has worn the logo
of the multinational Sony chain and now carries the Loews tag.
There is no local ownership, no face, no name other than the
corporate moniker.
</P>
<P>
   And yet despite, or perhaps because of, its corporate parentage,
Loews is anxious to persuade people it cares.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, explains Marc Pascucci, senior vice president of
marketing, ``When we open a new theater, we have a team of
corporate trainers who come into a marketplace. We also have
training manuals, videos, that type of thing to be read or watched
by an employee.''
</P>
<P>
   The phrase ``Thank you for coming to Loews'' is called ``an exit
greeting,'' Pascucci explains. ``There are four factors that are
part of our training, to make people feel welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we train to do is, at the ticket booth, say `Welcome to
Loews.' And then you come to the concession stand and they say,
`Welcome to Loews Theaters. Would you like a super bucket combo
special?' And when you reach the ticket taker, it's `Welcome to
Loews. Your theater is on the left.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Pascucci says the training regimen draws only occasional
complaints from the employees. ``I think you might have an employee
who's shy, and might have trouble getting used to it,'' he says,
adding, ``It's a small thing to ask. We're in an interactive
business.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a flaw in the program, however: Nonstop friendliness
isn't natural or engaging. No one remembers the old Nickelodeon for
the happy grins of its employees. Rather, it was what they gave to
the place that lingers in memory: The individual sensibility behind
the choice of movies, the animated conversations that went on
behind the counter, the sense of community that was built when
people who loved movies ran a theater for customers who loved
movies.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the enforced good will of the Loews employees is as
implausible as the satisfied faces of the gray-haired druggists in
the CVS ads, who ask viewers to believe that they're just as happy
punching the computer at a chain store as they were when they ran
their own pharmacies.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, friendliness doesn't equal good service.
</P>
<P>
   At Staples, the office-supply giant, employees are strictly
assigned, corridor by corridor, to a particular part of the store.
Store rules restrict them to their own zones. In baseball, the left
fielder can sometimes sprint into center to make a play. But not at
Staples, where employees explain that they can't leave their posts
even when no customer is in sight in their zone, to help someone in
the department six feet away.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, in an area Staples store on a recent Saturday, about a
half-dozen customers waited in frustration in the area selling
office chairs, while workers in the adjacent sections looked on
numbly.
</P>
<P>
   Once a customer finally got served, and made his way to the
counter, the young woman behind the register repeated her own
``exit greeting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Was everything all right?''
</P>
<P>
   No, he explained, it wasn't: It took forever to get help, while
workers stood by, listless.
</P>
<P>
   The young woman was taken aback, as if to suggest that ``exit
greetings'' aren't supposed to elicit responses.
</P>
<P>
   Then she whispered her response.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know,'' she said, in conspiratorial silence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
