<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE NEEDS CAN-DO MEEHAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It might seem a long stretch to try relating 29 miles of scenic
and fragile rivers in Massachusetts to the essence of reality in an
often unreal place called Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But it's worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, with the puny notice that accompanies most things
that happen on Capitol Hill, a decade-long effort to help protect
these 29 miles took a major stride forward.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, the person who made it happen in the
post-Gingrich House of Representatives, Marty Meehan, should have
learned something about a situation he mistakenly views as a
predicament.
</P>
<P>
   The Lowell Democrat is a chronic straight arrow, and he is not
mistaken to take seriously the fact that while campaigning for the
seat in 1992 he said that his intention was to hang around here for
no more than four terms.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be ridiculous for Meehan's constituents not to have
the chance to evaluate (at the ballot box next year) a change of
heart that is every bit as much in their own interests as in
Meehan's.
</P>
<P>
   The story of those 29 river miles is an instructive example of
why his style of work down here is going to be pivotal in a
Congress that is likely to be narrowly divided by party no matter
which one is nominally in the majority. Getting things to happen,
big and routine, is going to require congressmen who can work
across the partisan aisle, which in turn requires know-how,
patience, and extremely hard work in today's hothouse climate.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of work has become a Meehan specialty.
</P>
<P>
   The 29 miles refer to segments of the Sudbury and Assabet rivers
that come together at a place called Egg Rock to form the Concord
River. The area north and west of Boston is as well-known to
fishermen, canoers, and nature lovers as it is sacred in American
history and storied in literature.
</P>
<P>
   But it also lies in uneasy proximity to bustling modern life,
and protecting it has been the focus of activism in the surrounding
communities for years. The preferred mechanism is designation of
the three river segments as part of country's Wild and Scenic
Rivers system.
</P>
<P>
   Senators Edward Kennedy and John Kerry, back in 1990, arranged
for the money that produced an Interior Department study strongly
recommending the river segments' inclusion in the system. Ever
since, actually getting it done has been a mini-classic example of
what it takes to move something through Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Since his election, Meehan has made the project a priority (as
it was for his predecessor and opponent in '92, Chet Atkins), and
last week his work bore fruit. Because the Republicans are in
control, the authorizing legislation, which passed with only 22
dissenting votes, needed a provision mollifying the property rights
champions of the conservative movement by forbidding use of the
government's eminent domain powers to purchase private property
along the rivers.
</P>
<P>
   The designation would also permanently protect them from
federally licensed or other water projects that might affect their
free flow. And since the legislation establishes a joint
administration of the 29 miles between the Interior Department and
a council from eight affected communities, the leg up given to
conservation values is huge.
</P>
<P>
   The teeth-pulling work all this took is not for rookies or lazy
hacks. The chairman of the House Resources Committee, Don Young, is
a veteran oil industry supporter from Alaska. But the Republican
running the relevant subcommittee is Jim Hansen of Utah, who joined
with Meehan last year in sponsoring the House's legislation to put
a stiff tax on cigarettes and let the government regulate nicotine
as a drug; they plan a fresh proposal this year.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan's partnership with Hansen on tobacco is matched by a a
much better-known alliance with GOP neighbor Chris Shays of
Connecticut in the crusade for campaign finance reform that Meehan
has helped lead for five often lonely years. Against all odds, they
beat Newt Gingrich in his own House last year and refiled their
bill just last week.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to the impression left in one-dimensional press
acounts, Meehan did not run for Congress as a term-limiter. Unlike
so many Republicans elected in their revolution two years later, he
never embraced that movement, leaned on it for support or made
commitments to its goals of taking the question of length of
service away from voters and those who run for office.
</P>
<P>
   But he did say as that four terms was his plan, and he has
flirted with seeking constitutional office in Massachusetts in the
years since.
</P>
<P>
   It was a mistake in 1992, and Meehan admits as much now. If he
were some go-along mediocrity, he could stand or fall in an attempt
for a fifth term, and the result wouldn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   But Meehan is different _ and has been from the beginning. Off
his record and potential, the only disappointment would be if were
not to make a real commitment to the House. If he does, I don't
think there's much question what the response will be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
