<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT BETTER THAN HIS BROTHER JOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The veterans committee of baseball's Hall of
Fame announces its choice for enshrinement at Cooperstown this
week. The panel has examined several good candidates, but none
better than Dominic DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   If DiMaggio isn't chosen, he probably won't complain, because he
is a typical member of what Tom Brokaw's book calls ``The Greatest
Generation.'' He turned 82 last month with no complaints about
losing three seasons to military service in World War II. In 1942,
when the draft rejected him because he wore eyeglasses, he found a
way to volunteer for the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   Dom DiMaggio's election would be a triumph for the other guy,
recognizing the millions who excel but are still overshadowed.
Dominic's brother Joe was the most celebrated athlete of his time,
rivaled only by Dominic's friend and teammate, Ted Williams. At 5
feet 9 inches, he was also smaller than many athletes and
bespectacled, thus earning the nickname ``the Little Professor.''
These circumstances would qualify him for round-the-clock
psychological counseling in today's alibi culture.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, DiMaggio's life story is American pluck personified.
The son of an immigrant fisherman, he grew up in the North Beach
neighborhood of San Francisco, worked at odd jobs, and followed his
brothers Joe and Vince into Major League Baseball, hitting .301 in
his rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   His lifetime batting average was .298, the same as Mickey
Mantle's. He was a lead-off batter and ``setting the table'' for
Williams meant that he led the league in runs scored in 1950 and
1951. In a rare feat for anyone in a Red Sox uniform, he also was
the league leader in stolen bases in 1950, just 15 in that
slugger's era.
</P>
<P>
   He was an All-Star seven times in his 11-year career, equaling
that of last year's choice of the veterans committee, Larry Doby,
whose lifetime batting average was .283. Statistics do not measure
fielding skills. Had Dom DiMaggio played his home games somewhere
other than Fenway's cozy confines, his fleet-footed catches might
have matched his brother's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Hemingway wrote about Joe in ``The Old Man and the Sea.''
Simon and Garfunkel sang about him in ``Mrs. Robinson,'' but for
heartfelt, if occasionally off-key, street chanting, nothing could
match the ode that New England urchins sang in the 1940s to the
tune of ``O, Tannenbaum'':
</P>
<P>
   He's better than his brother Joe,
</P>
<P>
   Dom-in-ic Di-Magg-io.
</P>
<P>
   Few of us really believed it, but being a Red Sox fan means
subscribing to a set of preposterous cultish beliefs for which no
successful deprogramming has been devised. Williams and Bobby
Doerr, both in Cooperstown, playing on the same field with two
great center fielder brothers formed a phalanx of greatness that
may explain why I never heard anyone boo Joe DiMaggio at Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Dom wrote a memoir not of his own career but a salute
to the season when his brother hit successfully in 56 games and his
teammate hit .406, the last major leaguer to hit .400.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1941, for the fans and players, too, there was a reassuring
quality, a dependability about baseball,'' he wrote. ``We loved
baseball not only for itself but for the secure feeling of
continuity it gave to you. We felt a loyalty to baseball because it
was loyal to us.''
</P>
<P>
   He called his book ``Real Grass, Real Heroes,'' and Ted Williams
wrote the foreword, summing up his ``respect and fondness for Dom''
by saying, ``There is no finer person on earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Their friends might also say that about Orlando Cepeda, Bill
Mazeroski, Mel Harder, and Gil Hodges, all being considered for
Cooperstown. If statistics matter, John B. Holway and Bob Carroll
argue in ``Total Baseball'' that ``Dom was about 90 percent Joe's
size and he was about 90 percent the player Joe was. But 90 percent
of Joe DiMaggio is better than 100 percent of most of the guys
who've drawn major league salaries.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
