<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3074 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-MTBE-BOS &LR;      03-01 1644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MTBE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAS ADDITIVE DEBATED FROM TAHOE TO MAINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH LAKE TAHOE, Calif. _ Up here on top of the world, you'd
think it would be tough to spoil the environment. Nothing but
snow-capped granite cliffs surround the town and its famous lake,
with water so clear that you can see a white plate 75 feet
underwater.
</P>
<P>
   But this mountain resort community has become a pollution hot
spot in the rebellion against a new ingredient in gasoline that,
ironically, was supposed to improve the environment. Beneath the
ground, streams of foul-smelling MTBE from tank leaks and pump
spills at gas stations have forced the closure of a third of South
Lake Tahoe's wells, and the plumes are heading for the lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day, every week, every month that MTBE is in the gas,
our plumes get larger. It's as plain as the nose on your face,''
said Chris Strohm of the South Tahoe Public Utility District, which
is suing just about every company connected with bringing the
chemical additive MTBE, or methyl tertiary butyl ether, to town.
``We've been harmed, really harmed.''
</P>
<P>
   From Lake Tahoe to Litchfield, Maine, angry well owners are
cursing the day MTBE was added to gasoline to reduce air pollution,
in what some are calling a classic case of the law of unintended
consequences. Though MTBE is less toxic than the chemicals it
replaced, MTBE spreads more swiftly when spilled, giving water a
turpentine taste and odor at low concentrations.
</P>
<P>
   At least traces of MTBE have reached thousands of wells and
surface water supplies across the country, including 137 in New
Hampshire, 23 in Massachusetts, and more than 100 in Maine. Though
most contamination is low, some wells have had to close. A
Glenville, Calif., couple blame their flu-like symptoms, seizures,
and asthma attacks on MTBE in their well that is more than 250
times above the federal health advisory level.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as a federal panel in Boston considers the future of MTBE,
horror stories such as Lake Tahoe's and Glenville's are providing
momentum to get rid of MTBE only four years after its debut in
cleaner-burning ``reformulated gas'' that is sold in 20 states,
including most of New England.
</P>
<P>
   Maine regulators decided last week to sharply reduce MTBE in its
gas this summer, and California Governor Gray Davis, pushed by
Tahoe politicians, is under pressure to phase out MTBE entirely. In
Washington, key senators in both parties are suggesting a two-year
waiver of the federal law that greatly increased the use of MTBE in
gas.
</P>
<P>
   The makers of MTBE say their product is a victim of hysteria,
such as irresponsible claims that the chemical causes cancer when
the evidence is limited to questionable animal studies. Reports
that MTBE fumes cause nausea or other symptoms have not panned out
in large-scale studies, they add.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own personal view is . . . that MTBE is going to prove in
retrospect to have been a tremendous set of concerns over something
which in fact did not justify it,'' said Jonathan Borak, associate
clinical professor of medicine and public health at Yale University
who consults for the leading MTBE maker, Lyondell Chemical Co.
</P>
<P>
   But the exact toxicity of MTBE may not be the most important
issue _ everyone agrees it is toxic at some level. Daniel
Greenbaum, who chairs the federal blue-ribbon panel studying MTBE,
said most people speaking to his group seem most concerned that
``this is an unknown substance and, when it gets into the drinking
water, it has a foul odor and a taste.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenbaum said he thinks that promoters of MTBE _ he was one
when he was Massachusetts Department of Environmental Protection
commissioner _ helped create the controversy by introducing MTBE to
40 percent of US gasoline before its health and environmental
effects were widely understood.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Greenbaum said, MTBE may be remembered as ``the
perfect case study in how not to introduce a new product.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At first blush, Lake Tahoe _ land of ruddy-cheeked skiers,
postcard views, and swank casinos just over the Nevada line _ is an
unlikely seat of environmental rebellion. At 6,229 feet above sea
level, Tahoe seems to be a playground away from the troubles of the
world below.
</P>
<P>
   But residents are aware of their fragile environment, attracting
President Clinton in 1997 for a forum on contaminants that reduce
the lake's clarity. When MTBE started reaching wells, people
displayed bumper stickers that read, ``Help Make Tahoe MTBE Free.''
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that Tahoe was a sitting duck for MTBE, which
refiners began adding to South Tahoe gas in large quantities in
1996 as an ``oxygenate'' to boost the fuel's octane level. Unlike
the other ingredients in gas, MTBE dissolved in water, allowing it
to move swiftly in ground water.
</P>
<P>
   In South Tahoe, MTBE did not have to go far to reach wells. With
little land flat enough for development, gas stations were built
practically atop aquifers, which were not far underground to begin
with. By 1997, MTBE began reaching wells after even minor spills
such as over-filling a gas tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before MTBE, we had leaks at gas stations, but we really
didn't have any impacts to ground water,'' said Lisa Dernbach,
geologist at the state Regional Water Quality Control Board, who
now spends much of her time working with gas stations to control
the spread of MTBE.
</P>
<P>
   South Tahoe Public Utility District ordered wells closed as soon
as MTBE was detected rather than waiting for the concentration to
reach the federal health advisory level. But water manager Rick
Hydrick saw the 13 well shutdowns as a fire wall against an
escalating problem. Twenty of the 26 gas stations in South Tahoe
and neighboring Meyers have spilled MTBE into the ground water
already, and 11 MTBE plumes were bearing down on South Tahoe's
drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some of the best-quality ground water in the world,
but there's a million ways, it seems, that these releases can
occur,'' said Hydrick, who estimated the district has spent $2
million on MTBE cleanup and related costs. ``That's why the
district wants MTBE out.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, concern over MTBE in Lake Tahoe spurred officials to
ban personal watercrafts and other boats with polluting two-stroke
engines. Though other chemicals in gas are a bigger health problem,
MTBE spreads most widely, showing up at drinking water intake
pipes.
</P>
<P>
   MTBE industry officials, led by Houston-based Lyondell, agree
that Tahoe's problems are real, but say they should not be used to
discredit their product, which has brought measurably cleaner air
to regions such as New England.
</P>
<P>
   Lyondell officials say the contamination of South Tahoe's water
has more to do with the national problem of leaking underground
storage tanks than MTBE itself, while polluting motorboats _ not
MTBE _ should be blamed for the lake pollution. Wherever MTBE shows
up, the industry argues, other chemicals in gasoline will follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to educate the public that gasoline is a dangerous
substance that belongs in cars and doesn't belong in our ground
water,'' said Lyondell spokeswoman Karen Schwartzman.
</P>
<P>
   But some say the petro-chemical industry pushed MTBE on the
nation, even though companies knew the risk to water supplies.
Several of the six lawsuits filed against the makers or
distributors of MTBE, South Tahoe's included, argue that the
industry knew by 1986 about the risk to water from MTBE, but
marketed the product as an environmental improvement anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry knew this was coming and yet did nothing to avoid
the problem,'' said South Tahoe's attorney Victor Sher, who is
seeking tens of millions of dollars in damages from MTBE makers,
refineries, and gas stations.
</P>
<P>
   MTBE industry officials regard some of these lawsuits as little
more than harassment, especially a lawsuit filed on behalf of two
Maine well owners that targets industry representatives. MTBE is no
more defective than other ingredients in gas, argue MTBE makers,
and the refiners who bought MTBE were told of its water solubility.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, they say federal regulations, not industry coercion,
opened the door for widespread use of MTBE. Senator Thomas A.
Daschle, the South Dakota Democrat, led the charge for the rule,
not to help the oil industry but in hopes that a rival product made
from corn, called ethanol, would be widely used to increase the
octane of reformulated gas.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, most refiners chose MTBE, derived from natural gas,
because it was less expensive and easier to transport.
</P>
<P>
   However, even if MTBE makers win the legal debate, they are
losing the political one. California has seen such a proliferation
of MTBE contamination cases _ and a major study suggesting MTBE is
not worth the cost _ that legislators say they can pass a ban on
MTBE if Governor Davis does not do it first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kick MTBE out of California now!'' demanded Senator Tim
Leslie, who represents Lake Tahoe, at a rally last week.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, even ARCO, the oil company that invented MTBE, is
calling for its removal from gasoline, as long as the government
finds an alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand where the public is coming from and the public
perception is that MTBE is bad and it's time to look for something
different,'' said ARCO spokesman Paul Langland.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the blue-ribbon panel that meets at the Hyatt Regency
Harborside in Boston must decide whether cleaner air is worth the
water risk for the rest of the country. The issue could be tougher
in the Northeast than California, since cars need more of an octane
boost in cold weather, but the pressure for action on MTBE is
growing here, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real challenge to figure out what is the right
answer,'' said Greenbaum. ``We're just starting to get our teeth
into that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
