<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ROCKET-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RADICAL SPACESHIP SPINS, WHIRLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOJAVE, Calif. _ This morning, at the oversized airport of this
small desert town, the doors of a huge hangar will rumble open, and
an odd-looking craft _ picture a 63-foot-tall white megaphone _
will slowly roll into view before a crowd that should vastly
outnumber Mojave's registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   The craft is a test vehicle for a new kind of rocket that its
supporters hope will mark a dramatic advance in space-age history,
opening up the space frontier to regular, routine travel for
tourism and commerce in much the same way that the DC-3 opened up
aviation.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the innovative Roton rocket could turn out to be
more like Howard Hughes's famous 219-foot seaplane of 1947, the
Spruce Goose: a cutting-edge attempt to push the boundaries of
aviation technology that never quite got off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is rocket science,'' said Edward Crawley, head of
the Aeronautics and Astronautics department at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology. The Roton design is ``an interesting
concept,'' he said, but many aerospace engineers question whether
it is even possible to build a rocket that can make it into orbit
with a single stage, as the Roton is planned to do. ``The
detractors say you'll never be able to do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Tim Kyger, a spokesman for Universal Space Lines, a company
that hopes to operate a fleet of commercial, reusable spacecraft,
is much more optimistic. ``I think it's brilliant,'' he said of the
Roton design, adding that he thinks it is the likeliest to succeed
of the many concepts being touted for single-stage-to-orbit
rockets. His company hopes to use rockets built either by one of
its own subsidiaries or bought from another company. The Roton's
component parts, he pointed out, are ``all off-the-shelf or pretty
low-tech, but they're put together in a new way.''
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle unveiled Monday is not, in fact, a rocket at all.
It's really the world's most peculiar helicopter, designed to test
the structure and the landing system of the planned Roton rocket.
In that sense, it is like the original space shuttle Enterprise, a
test vehicle without rocket engines that was used to try out the
shuttle's landing systems.
</P>
<P>
   Later this year or early next, a new prototype version that
includes the actual rocket motors will undergo its first tests. If
all goes well, the California-based Rotary Rocket company, builders
of the unique craft, hope to begin regular commercial
satellite-launching service to space by the end of next year _
without a dime of government funding.
</P>
<P>
   If they accomplish that feat, it will be the first launch
vehicle ever built entirely with private financing _ and the first
to reach orbit and return without discarding any parts.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the key to the hopes of this company _ and a few
others working on related plans _ to bring about a drastic
reduction in the cost of flying into space by building totally
reusable rockets. As Rotary Rocket's chief engineer, Dan DeLong,
put it, comparing the cost of throwaway rockets with that of
commercial aviation, ``the ticket is cheaper if you don't throw the
747 away after every flight.''
</P>
<P>
   While several other companies are also struggling to develop
totally reusable spacecraft, Roton is the only one that has raised
substantial private capital _ at least $30 million so far, $1
million of it from author Tom Clancy _ to develop a truly visionary
new craft. The company says it needs a total of $150 million to
inaugurate commercial service.
</P>
<P>
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration is strongly
supportive. Administrator Daniel Goldin has said that he aims for
the agency to get out of the rocket-building business and hopes
that new rockets will be designed and built by private companies so
that the national space program can simply order them like any
other customer.
</P>
<P>
   In a strong show of support, NASA's chief engineer was the
keynote speaker at the grand unveiling of the Roton ATV-1 test
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   There are three other companies with enough money to do
substantial development work on new types of rockets, and their
approaches are all very different. Aerospace mega-company
Lockheed-Martin won a $941 million NASA contract in 1996 to design
and build a test vehicle for another version of a
single-stage-to-orbit craft, but that project, called the X-33,
will not lead to a craft that can actually make it to orbit. That
would fall to a followup called VentureStar, which would cost at
least $5 billion more to develop _ money few observers think will
be forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   The other two companies, both startups, are aiming to develop
lower-cost alternatives. Kistler Aerospace, which has already spent
$250 million and says it needs $500 million more, plans to use
conventional two-stage throwaway rockets outfitted with parachutes
and airbags so they can be recovered and reused . And Beal
Aerospace, funded with $250 million from founder Andrew Beal's
personal fortune, aims to design simple, cheap throwaway rockets.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Roton as the only new rocket that aims to fly to
space and back in one piece. If it succeeds, space flight might
finally catch up to science-fiction's early visions, making it
possible to reach orbit inexpensively, routinely and on short
notice in a craft that, as in the old movies, takes off and lands
vertically.
</P>
<P>
   But that's about the only resemblance the Roton has to any other
rocket, real or fictional. Both its rocket engines and its landing
system are quite unlike anything else.
</P>
<P>
   The design is the brainchild of self-taught aerospace engineer
Gary Hudson, president of Rotary Rocket, who has been pushing the
idea of single-stage-to-orbit rockets for three decades. The
company's name is indeed apt: Both its takeoff and landing rely on
motors that spin furiously, like whirling dervishes.
</P>
<P>
   The takeoff is to be propelled by something like a huge
Catherine wheel: a disk of 72 small rocket nozzles spinning at 720
revolutions per minute. The disk will be spun up by a turntable on
the launch pad, and then will continue spinning as the rockets fire
because each nozzle is slightly tilted to the side.
</P>
<P>
   The spinning is an ingenious way around one of the biggest
engineering challenges of rocket design: pumping fuel to the
engines at a prodigious rate. Other rockets require high-tech,
expensive, heavy turbopumps, but in the Roton the fuel will be
pulled into the engine by the centrifugal force of the spinning
22-foot diameter wheel. In a sense, the whole engine is one big
pump.
</P>
<P>
   No, the pilot and passenger aboard the Roton won't be getting
hopelessly dizzy. The body of the rocket will not spin. It will be
connected to the spinning engines through an off-the-shelf
commercial thrust bearing, the same kind used to attach the
propellers of large ships.
</P>
<P>
   Once in orbit, the craft will open its payload bay doors and its
cargo satellite will slide out to be released in orbit. Then, the
rocket will fire small thrusters to begin its reentry.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the other unique rotating aspect of the flight: a set
of helicopter blades, until then folded snugly along the sides of
the rocket, will pop out into position, allowing the craft to make
a slow, gentle landing on the same pad where it took off. In an
emergency, it would be able to land on any convenient hard surface,
just like a helicopter _ only with its rotors powered by small
rocket thrusters at its tips.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson is used to facing a lot of skepticism. From the
beginning, he said, many engineers doubted such a vehicle was even
possible, much less practical. But that has begun to change, thanks
to a combination of technical progress and various engineering
studies showing different approaches that could do the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``By 1990, Boeing, McDonnell Douglas, Rocketdyne, and General
Dynamics all proposed single-stage vehicles'' as part of NASA's
competition for its X-33 project to develop a prototype, Hudson
pointed out. And others, including Hudson, have done analyses that
show that even some present rockets and rocket engines, combined in
slightly different configurations, could make it to orbit in a
single stage right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it remarkable that engineers still argue about whether
single-stage to orbit is possible,'' Hudson said. ``I have very
little doubt that this vehicle, right out of the box, will make it
to orbit in a single stage,'' although possibly with less payload
capacity than the 3 1/2 tons the company now hopes to be able to
carry _ at a record low price of $7 million per launch. Additional
boosters could be strapped on to increase its capacity without
drastically affecting its costs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Lurio, a Boston-area aerospace engineer and longtime
booster of low-cost launch vehicles, thinks making the system work
as planned will be a definite challenge. But if it does work, he
said, it will revolutionize the space business.
</P>
<P>
   One strong point in Roton's favor is that its design lends
itself to a cautious, one-step-at-a-time development process during
which any obstacles can be worked out at relatively low cost.
``They're taking an excellent approach in terms of their
incremental development,'' Lurio said.
</P>
<P>
   The big problem, he said, is convincing investors it has enough
of a chance of success to be worth the gamble. Lurio is convinced
that new designs can achieve at least a tenfold reduction in the
cost of access to space _ but only if someone can break through the
logjam of skepticism and raise the needed funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Gary succeeds, then the Gordian knot has been cut,'' he
said. ``But there are other alternatives if this one doesn't
work.''
</P>
<P>
   MIT's Crawley agrees that the potential impact of a new system
like the Roton is enormous. ``The economics of spaceflight are so
sensitive to the launch costs that whoever builds a system that
reduces the launch costs will immediately get almost all the
market.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Roton or one of its competitors can achieve a significant
reduction, he said _ even if is far less than the company expects _
``everybody in the world would go to them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
