<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE ROAD WITH PRISSY MR. FUSSY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (With apologies to Roger Hargreaves, creator of Mr. Fussy, Mr.
Nonsense, Mr. Busy, and 42 other delightful children's book
characters.)
</P>
<P>
   Mr.Fussy is going on a trip.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Fussy is very upset, because he has been delayed. In Mr.
Fussy's ideal world, there would be no weather, not even any
sunshine. Because we now know that sunshine is dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Fussy made his airline reservations three months ahead of
time. When the lady on the phone inquired ``Where would you like to
sit?'' she said that the whole plane was still available. Mr. Fussy
was very happy to be ahead of the crowd, and booked his favorite
window seat.
</P>
<P>
   Since 10 weeks remained for the airline to prepare him a special
meal, the lady asked if he had any ``dietary concerns.'' Yes, I'm
too fat, he felt like saying, but he knew that wasn't what the lady
had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Fussy keeps his dozen or so Frequent Flyer membership cards
in a neat little stack on his bureau, and he had the 600-digit
number/letter/ideograph sequence ready when the lady asked.
</P>
<P>
   Then Mr. Fussy called the hotel. This was less exciting than it
might have been, a., because it was a Holiday Inn, and b., because
he remembered seeing it on previous visits, and it was shaped like
a stack of concrete pancakes. Was that ``architectural modernism''?
Mr. Fussy wasn't sure. The young man asked if he wanted a room that
smelled like tar, nicotine, and phlegm, or another kind of room.
Even for Mr. Fussy, that wasn't a hard choice.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion with the rental car agent was brief. Mr. Fussy
knew that even the fussiest of travelers get euchred by the rental
car companies. He got euchred.
</P>
<P>
   Nine weeks before leaving, Mr. Fussy decided to call some old
friends at his destination. ``Mr. Fussy! How nice to hear from
you!'' they said. They had no idea where they'd be nine weeks hence
_ they were Californians _ but if they were in town, they'd be
delighted to see him!
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Fussy remembered Being Young. He recalled the time when he
had nowhere to go during spring break, so he and his college
roommates drove out to Oklahoma to see a friend. Straight through,
of course, on coffee and No-Doz. Then Mr. Fussy hitchhiked back to
Smoky Mountain National Park and climbed Mount Leconte in his
sneakers, which wasn't very smart. He woke up covered with snow. As
a grown-up, Mr. Fussy would have been better prepared _ had
sensible shoes! But, Mr. Fussy reflected sadly, as a grown-up, he
wouldn't have climbed a 6,600-foot-tall mountain just because he
felt like it . . .
</P>
<P>
   That was then. Now, eight weeks before leaving, Mr. Fussy
decided to set up a few interviews at his destination. Some people
just laughed. Some people didn't return his calls. Some people
said, ``Sure, I'll put you on my calendar, but give me a number in
case I get called away to Hawaii, ha, ha!'' These people didn't
lead orderly, planned lives, and deep down Mr. Fussy felt a little
bit contemptuous of them.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days before leaving, Mr. Fussy started to pack. If only
weather reports functioned several weeks in advance, he would know
what to wear. So he packed for any eventuality. Mr. Fussy knew that
in some of their friends' households, the wife packed for the
husband. But Mr. Fussy didn't want his wife packing for him. (The
feeling was mutual.) Suppose Mrs. Fussy accidentally packed the
Gore-Tex-lined Glide floss, which didn't generate the necessary
friction against his tooth enamel, instead of the mint-flavored
waxed floss? Or put in Crest instead of Sensodyne? (Mr. Fussy was
very, very fussy about his teeth.)
</P>
<P>
   Or suppose Mrs. Fussy forgot to include his earplugs, or his
bewildering array of allergy pills and asthma medications? You
never know when you might encounter a barking dog, or a shedding
cat. Eight years previously, Finnair had lost Mr. Fussy's luggage
(vanished into Finnair!) and forced him to survive for a week in
St. Petersburg without his medicines. Oddly, Mr. Fussy did just
fine.
</P>
<P>
   Thank heavens that Mrs. F. and the children were staying at
home. Especially the children. They weren't at all fussy about
packing. Sometimes they even left their toothbrushes and floss and
mouthwash at home, during an entire vacation! And when Mr. and Mrs.
Fussy called this to their attention, they didn't care! How strange
. . .
</P>
<P>
   Bon voyage, Mr. Fussy!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
