<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3077 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     03-01 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 RIVIERA APUANA, Italy: ... and Mirandolese.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Concordiese provides a difficult test in the opener. They seem
to have inherited some of the Count's ability to defend and present
paradoxes. Such teams are accustomed to confronting physically
superior opposition, and they retain their composure and
organization. Moore's perfectly placed free kick from 25 yards
decides the match in the 27th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Mirandolese is reinforced by Giuseppe Accardi, who played for
Inter and Torino, and 43-year-old midfielder Carlo Trevisanello,
who had a 23-year career, mostly with Ascoli and Verona. A 0-0 tie
is sufficient for the Revolution to win the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, everyone returned to the Hotel San Silvestro for a
banquet. Former Inter player and Italian national team assistant
coach Sergio Brighenti and others pay tribute to Zenga and Ragazzi.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great experience to watch these excellent athletes,''
Ragazzi said. ``I welcome you to this magic place, Emilia Romagna,
home of tagliatella, mountains, and beautiful women.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the night, Zenga is arm-in-arm with the emcee and
Ragazzi in a rendition of a song by Nomadi (Nomads), accompanied by
an electric synthesizer.
</P>
<P>
   Accardi, a Sicilian who now works in management for Torino
Sportivo, and Brighenti are surprised that Zenga has become a
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagined him more as a general manager than a coach,''
Accardi said. ``But goalkeepers can be very good coaches. Look at
(Italian national team coach) Dino Zoff. Yes, he can be a very good
coach. He can do everything, because he is very intelligent.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a player, he was a phenomenon. For 10 years, he was the
best goalkeeper in the world. He has incredible character, a great
personality. Athletically, he was a phenomenon, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1990, Italy was the best team in the world. The team lost
to Argentina. But they way (Zenga) played, and the way the team
played, they deserved to win. Why didn't they? Sometimes, soccer is
strange.''
</P>
<P>
   When Italy hosted the World Cup, the national team was expected
to take the title. The Azzurri players included some strong
personalities, such as Gianluca Vialli, who soon was excluded from
the team but continued to excel on the field and now has become a
successful player/coach in England. Zenga, also, soon was removed
from the team, though he continued to excel at the club level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult to find a coach who also has interests outside
of soccer,'' Brighenti said. ``Vialli is also an excellent coach,
but to become this he had to change. And Walter also has had to
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be impossible for them to do this in Italy, because
you need a coaching license. You can't just become a coach like
that. I would say that in the US, soccer is a little more of an
amateur affair. In England, too, you do not need a coaching
license. But Vialli is an exception, not the rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vialli was temperamental, a real battler with a lot of grit.
Walter also had a lot of personality as goalkeeper, like Dino Zoff.
But Zoff was taciturn, he allowed no distractions, was always
concentrating on soccer, always studying the opposition and the
game. Walter was the same, on the field. But off the field, he was
extroverted, always dreaming about affairs extra-calcistica
(outside soccer). I really didn't think either one would want to
become a coach.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution players study the scene like cultural
anthropologists who have discovered an exotic species. They are
weary, and want to rest up for the next afternoon's match.
</P>
<P>
   Among those in the audience, Julian Horbury is probably the most
unhappy. Zenga gave an unsatisfactory interview to Futbol Mondial
and, after the game in Mirandola, had the nerve to order away his
cameraman, said Horbury, a producer for the show.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga is much more comfortable with Italian journalists. That
night, a television interview included some esoteric and inane
questioning about Modena's volleyball team. Zenga did not seem to
mind.
</P>
<P>
   The next day's game is in Modena, home of balsamic vinegar,
Ferrari, Maserati, Pavarotti.
</P>
<P>
   Revolution midfielder Jesse Van Saun had played here seven years
ago, recruited by the Brooklyn Italians for the Enzo Ferrari
tournament, along with Giovanni Savarese's younger brother, Ugo.
They defeated Sampdoria's youth team and advanced to the
semifinals. And they had time to visit the Ferrari museum. The
Revolution settle for a plastic model Ferrari, a gift from the auto
manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution are joined on the bench by Giuseppe Galderisi, an
original member of the team. Galderisi seems to fit in well, a good
foil for Zenga, who is not only player/coach, but also tour
director.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Revolution need me, I would be happy to help them,''
said Galderisi, who is taking coaching courses at Coverciano,
headquarters of the Italian federation.
</P>
<P>
   Modena wins the match, 3-1, as the Revolution surrender a late
first-half goal on a mixup involving non-roster goalkeeper Anthony
Latronica, then fail to carry out their ``pressing'' tactics in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``They aren't into their season, yet, so their conditioning is
not at optimal level,'' said Modena's Fausto Pari, a former Zenga
teammate at Sampdoria. ``But the level of American soccer in
general is improving, judging from the play of the national team.
They need to have more professional teams, play more outside
competition, to improve their level of experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the number of players you have, it can only grow. But
it's a different culture, and to arrive at the top, you have to
adopt the right mentality. It's a good level, as they showed here.
They did not win, but at this stage of training, it's normal. I
talked to Walter before the game, and he said he is using this
month away from the US purely as preparation for the season.''
</P>
<P>
   The preparation continues in Sicily this week. The Revolution
then return here, hopefully improved and prepared to face a higher
level of opposition. They return to Boston March 17.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
