<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3078 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLUMBARIUM-HNS &LR;      03-01 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMBARIUM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORYTELLER FINDS LIFE AMONG THE ASHES OF DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ His business card says Caretaker &AMP; Historian,
but he's more than that. Much more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the painter, the gardener, the maintenance man, the
inurnment man,'' Emmitt Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   Inurnment? ``I put the ashes in the urns,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Watson is the caretaker of the San Francisco Columbarium, the
101-year-old building that is home to the ashes of about 30,000
people. For 12 years, he has not only kept the place looking good,
he has kept the stories of the dead alive and kept the living
feeling good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I speak for the dead,'' he said. ``Nobody speaks for the
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson, 43, said his career as the columbarium storyteller began
out of curiosity _ who were all these dead people and who were the
people who came to visit them, he wondered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally when people come and I don't know them, I follow them
to see where they go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then he waits until the next time they come and approaches them,
gets to talking and learns their stories _ why one man is contained
in a W.C. Fields piggy bank and another in a silver martini shaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can bring a little life with death, instead of just a
tombstone with the name and date of death, which is so sad,'' he
said. ``Cemeteries are very cold and sad. This place would be the
same way if I didn't learn the stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson has nicknames for his favorite occupants of the domed,
neoclassical building _ the Gambler, the Jazz Singer, the Ocean
Hero, the Greedy Man (inurned with his son, daughter, first wife
and second wife).
</P>
<P>
   ``This place is full of history,'' he said. ``All the streets
you see in San Francisco _ Taylor, Post, Folsom, Eddy _ they're
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The columbarium was once surrounded by a 167-acre cemetery. But
as San Francisco expanded, city planners decided they needed the
land for homes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1910, a law was passed putting an end to cremations within
city limits. Nine years later, the city banned burials altogether.
Over the next decade, it undertook the slow process of transferring
the bodies to other cemeteries.
</P>
<P>
   From 1934 to 1979, the columbarium was forgotten, Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were raccoons running around, pigeons roosting in empty
niches, mushrooms growing out of cracks,'' he said. ``It was
scary.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Neptune Society purchased it in 1980, Watson was hired
with a crew of men to paint the outside. The manager saw he was a
good worker and hired him to paint the inside. Then he hired him as
the maintenance man and he's been there ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Watson is married and has two sons, 18 and 22, who have both
worked summers at the columbarium. One quit when he couldn't get
promoted.
</P>
<P>
   The columbarium has been almost completely restored and its
6,000 or so niches are 90 percent full.
</P>
<P>
   The most inexpensive rate is a flat fee of $1,600 for a
community niche, which fits about a dozen urns. Individual niches
cost up to $7,000.
</P>
<P>
   The owners have grand plans for the landmark building. They have
broken ground for a new office and will build an 8-foot marble and
granite wall around the perimeter of the grounds to hold another
6,000 niches. They hope to complete work in about 2 1/2 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the restoration work is ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   Watson has taken on the time-consuming task of painting the
architectural details and moldings in different color schemes using
a paintbrush ``the size you use to do your eyebrows.''
</P>
<P>
   He has put less time into the domed ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``That part is so far you can't see the ugliness,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Watson is so intimately familiar with the space that no detail
goes unnoticed. He knows he is unusual and he's an old hand with
the news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done CNN, `Evening Magazine,''' he said. ``I've still got
``Dateline.'''
</P>
<P>
   Watson said he was motivated to tell stories of the dead by the
smiles he brings to the living.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time I put somebody in the wall, I adopt them as part of
my family,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
