<HEADER>
A3079 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRLINES-PASSENGERS-B     03-01 1546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-PASSENGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW SPIN ON AIR PASSENGERS' RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New Year weekend's snafu at Detroit Metropolitan Airport has
spawned more than horror stories about passengers imprisoned for
hours on snowbound Northwest Airlines jets, unable to take off and
unable to return to the gate.
</P>
<P>
   It has given rise to a seeming stampede of politicians trying to
enact legislation ensuring that passengers on commercial airlines
will be treated with a modicum of respect. And that political
frenzy has caused considerable angst in airline boardrooms, and in
lobbyists' offices in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I would put this in as a shot across their bow and
it may go nowhere,'' says US Representative Bud Shuster, a
Pennsylvania Republican who is chairman of the House Committee on
Transportation and Infrastructure and the author of the so-called
``Airline Passenger Bill of Rights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But, boy, we struck a raw nerve.''
</P>
<P>
   While high-ranking federal aviation officials say privately that
the so-called passenger rights movement smacks of demagoguery, and
airline officials say it offers simplistic _ and expensive _ fixes
to a very complex system, it has resonated with the millions of
Americans who have had, at one time or another, a less than
pleasant experience dealing with airlines.
</P>
<P>
   By some accounts, never have so many Americans been angry at the
airlines; consumer complaints rose 25 percent last year. Of course,
never have so many passengers been flying. Last year, some 608
million people flew, up from 275 million in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to how consumers are treated, ``There are
practices tolerated in the airline industry that are not tolerated
in any other American industry, and that is quite odd because this
is supposed to be a service industry,'' says Paul Dempsey, a
professor of law and director of the Transportation Law Program at
the University of Denver.
</P>
<P>
   At least three bills _ two of which are already slated for a
hearing next month _ have been introduced; the Senate version is
sponsored by US Democratic Senator Ron Wyden of Oregon, and John
McCain, an Arizona Republican, who is the powerful chairman of the
Senate Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee. There is
Schuster's bill, and a second House bill, sponsored by US
Representative John Dingell, the Michigan Democrat who is a ranking
member of the Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   While they vary somewhat, the three bills would give consumers
protection against common problems ranging from getting bumped from
oversold flights to having baggage lost for days. The two House
bills would impose penalties on airlines for flights delayed more
than two hours, raising concerns that some safety issues may be
overlooked in order to avoid a hefty fine.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the bills would legislate some ticket pricing by
permitting the use of splitting two round-trip tickets that include
a Saturday night, to avoid paying higher midweek fares. They would
also provide better information about airline frequent-flier seat
availability (something airlines tend to consider proprietary) and
about why planes are delayed.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that hearings are scheduled on the bills suggests that
``this is not some frivolous thing,'' says former US senator Alan
Simpson, director of Harvard's Institute of Politics at the John F.
Kennedy School of Government.
</P>
<P>
   ``They saw they could put together a Taxpayers Bill of Rights
with the IRS, and this may take a while _ nothing may happen this
session _ but there is enough real stuff out there to create honest
interest in this legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   So, instead of celebrating just completing a year in which there
was not a single fatality on a commercial airline, the industry is
sweating over a looming battle that many believe will lead to
higher ticket prices.
</P>
<P>
   While the Air Transport Association, the trade group
representing the major airlines, has yet to take a position on the
bills, spokesman David Fuscus says, ``I don't think you really want
the government in customer service, and pricing is probably not a
good place for them to be in. Tickets are 36 percent less expensive
than they were 20 years ago,'' he says. (The industry was
deregulated in 1978).
</P>
<P>
   And at least one major passenger group agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The politicans are trying to attack indirectly what they
should attack directly _ the lack of competition and the
alternatives for passengers,'' says David Stempler, president of
the Washington-based Air Travelers Association. ``Secondly, we are
fearful that when the heavy hand of government comes in, we, as
passengers, will end up paying for it at the end of the day. The
law enacted most frequently in this town is the law of unintended
consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Stempler says much of the hostility directed at the airline
industry these days stems from airplanes being more crowded. The
days of having the middle seat empty and a lunch or dinner served
on a flight to Chicago seem like a pleasant memory.
</P>
<P>
   And, says Dempsey, unlike other purchases, buying an airline
ticket does not give someone the opportunity to inspect the product
before purchasing it. ``You don't know until the plane leaves, if
it will depart on time; you don't know if it will be clean, if the
food will be edible, whether the flight attendants will be surly,
or if you will be seated in the middle between two obese human
beings in palm tree T-shirts and poor hygiene.''
</P>
<P>
   And Stempler notes that ``airlines are not immune from the
environment that we are all generally experiencing in the '90s _
the pressure and tension of time. Everyone is under pressure, that
is why there is so much road rage, and then you have this crowding
of airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the only time I can remember as much discontent was in the
days of air traffic control when planes were circling over cities
waiting to land. We resolved that with flow control, and hopefully,
the marketplace will solve some of the current problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither the FAA, nor the Department of Transportation, which
have oversight over the airline industry, have taken positions on
the proposed legislation. The department tracks passenger
complaints regarding airlines on everything from problems with the
flight to smoking. And although complaints in 1998 were up 25
percent over 1997 _ a fact politicians like Shuster use to bolster
their arguments _ the number of passengers who file complaints is
still relatively small. Of the 608 million passengers who flew last
year, 9,606 of them took the time to file formal complaints with
the Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``These bills are just not well thought out,'' says Darryl
Jenkins, executive director of the Aviation Institute at George
Washington University and a professor of airline management. He
says he's never seen a time when so many people are angry at the
airlines, and ``the airlines need to do something, but these bills
are not a step in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins says all the bills indicate a lack of understanding of
the complexity of the airline industry as well as the flexibility
it requires. Something as seemingly innocuous as the requirement to
announce to would-be passengers that a flight is oversold is
fraught with difficulty. Most flights are not oversold until the
day before the flight. Sophisticated computer programs record the
flight history and can predict quite well how much a flight can be
technically oversold _ but still, on the day of travel, have enough
room for everyone, because some people don't show up at the gate.
Such practices help keep prices down, by helping ensuring that all
seats are filled.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, says Jenkins, if a flight crew going to Asia
realizes on the day of its departure that a storm in the Pacific
will increase the amount of head winds the flight will encounter, a
plane that is not technically oversold, but simply full, becomes
oversold because it will have to use more fuel and weigh less to
arrive safely.
</P>
<P>
   Announcing the causes of delays seems to be a good idea, Jenkins
says, because about 65 percent of all delays are caused by the
antiquated air traffic control system. ``If they inform passengers
accurately and truthfully about delays, the pilot will say, `This
delay is brought to you by the US Government,' maybe then Congress
will finally update the air traffic control system.''
</P>
<P>
   But fining airlines for delays raises troubling safety concerns,
according to aviation specialists. Take the case of a flight that
has gone through de-icing, and then has to wait 30 minutes before
it can take off. By that time, the pilot might well think it is
prudent to pull out of the takeoff queue and get de-iced again. But
if the airline has to pay tens of thousands of dollars in fines to
passengers because of the delay that causes, will the crew gamble
with the flight's safety?
</P>
<P>
   ``We never argue about the blacks and whites of safety,'' says
Stempler. ``It is the gray area in the middle that you have to
worry about. And you can't legislate against stupidity or bad
decisions, and that is really what happened in Detroit. They made
bad decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Matthew Brelis is the Globe's Focus writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
