<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTIOLN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAINING IN ITALY A KICK FOR REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIVIERA APUANA, Italy _ All is quiet in the big resorts. It is
fuori stagione (offseason), and nearly everything is empty in Forte
dei Marmi and neighboring Cinquale, except for the 50-room,
four-star Hotel Undulna, named for a poem by Gabriele D'Annunzio,
favorite son of the Versilia area.
</P>
<P>
   Revolution coach/goaltender Walter Zenga has booked the hotel,
which was built with the marble of Massa Carrara, Michelangelo's
favorite site, at low rates for the team's preseason training.
There is a new practice facility nearby, and Zenga has persuaded
the construction crew to build a ramp for hill training. There are
several professional teams in the area to provide competition, and
Zenga knows the coaches and directors, and the shortcuts to the
stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever the team goes, Zenga's friends and former teammates
appear. Fans of all ages request autographs and pose for pictures
with Zenga. In Modena, the Inter club is named for Zenga, and
hundreds arrive for the midweek afternoon exhibition, mostly to pay
tribute to him. After another game, a newspaper notes that fans
were disappointed because Zenga did not play (he stuck to coaching
duties that night) and his fiancee, Hoara Borselli, did not appear.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the games are essentially glorified training sessions.
Soccer is ritualistic in Italy, and the club games that draw the
most interest are weekend matches between eternal rivals.
</P>
<P>
   One Revolution practice was attended by Marcello Lippi, former
coach of Napoli and Juventus and heir apparent at Inter. This
impressed a reporter from Il Resto del Carlino of Bologna, who
noted, ``One Lippi watching your team is better than a thousand
spectators.''
</P>
<P>
   Many were curious about the Revolution. They wondered why the
team was called ``New England'' instead of ``Boston,'' and
newspaper accounts often referred to the team as the ``Boston New
England Revolution di Zenga.'' But they judged the team on merit.
Joe-Max Moore and Leighton O'Brien impressed observers with their
touch. When nonroster forward Ze Rodrigues dribbled past three
defenders in Modena, a journalist shouted, ``Would you look at
that. He's dancing with the ball and they can't touch him.''
</P>
<P>
   But most of the reviews were less enthusiastic. Said one, ``The
team has three players from the `stelle e strisce' (Stars and
Stripes, or national team), but evidently this is not enough to
give it a clear identity. If this formation plays in the top level,
we would venture to say that the Serie A of Uncle Sam is comparable
to our high amateur divisions.''
</P>
<P>
   And that was after the Revolution's only victory of the first
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The preseason is still young, though, and Zenga is concentrating
on organizing the team's defensive schemes. The Revolution won only
once but remained in contention in all but one of their first six
matches. They have displayed enough spirit and ability to provide
hope for the Major League Soccer regular season, which begins March
28 in Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's jelling, everyone looks sharp,'' defender Richard
Goulooze said. ``Everyone realizes that last year was everyone's
responsibility. Everyone realizes that they have to work as hard as
possible. It's a good atmosphere. Walter wants everyone to take
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``In practice, Walter stops everything and tells you what he
wants. His English is not perfect but you can tell what he means.
He tells us to work hard and be proud, don't give up goals. And
don't lose.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, the team took a bus ride through the Apuane Alps
on Superstrada A12 north. Outside Parma, there are several
spray-painted signs of separatists seeking to establish the state
of Padana.
</P>
<P>
   After 2 1/2 hours, the Revolution arrive in a town of 30,000
known to Renaissance buffs as the home of Giovanni Pico, count of
Mirandola and Concordia, an adviser to the Medicis once described
as ``precocious disputant and aristocratic mystic, enchanted
scholar.'' In 1486, Pico challenged the world to a public debate
upon 900 theses in Rome, but ``so many seemed likely to be
paradoxes against the true faith, too brilliantly defended, that
the Pope forbade the contest,'' according to E.V. Lucas. ``He
dabbled in the black arts, wrote learnedly on Mosaic law, was an
amorous poet in Italian, a serious poet in Latin, and in everything
he did was interesting and curious, steeped in Renaissance culture,
inspired by a wish to reconcile past and present and humanize
Christ and Fathers . . . He gave most of his fortune to a fund for
marriage portions for penniless girls.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution arrived at Stadio Libero Locci, a 1920s
construction in the grand Mussolini style with Roman columns
supporting a cantilevered covering for the stands. The columns give
the 5,000-capacity stadium a classy feel but block the view from
the press box.
</P>
<P>
   This tournament is sponsored by Cesare Ragazzi, a
hair-restoration expert from Modena. The Centro Cesare Ragazzi's
motto is ``because hair is beautiful.'' The connection with Zenga,
whose mop appears to have thickened since he was playing for the
Revolution in 1997, became more obvious as the night proceeded.
</P>
<P>
   But first, there was the tournament, with teams at the amateur
level.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they lose to these teams,'' said a stadium official, ``they
are going to have to come here and play in Promozione (equivalent
of the Serie F, the sixth division). And our team is going to
replace them in the Serie A Americano.''
</P>
<P>
   The opposition represents the descendants of Pico's
constituency: Polisportiva Concordiese and Mirandolese.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
