<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Short Takes: PBS goes for ratings
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Washington Week in Review,'' PBS's long-running public affairs
program, is a stolid, dependable performer which features capital
reporters talking about current events, adding a bit of information
when that seems called for. The worst thing you can say about
``Washington Week'' is that it is stolid and dependable. The best
thing you can say about ``Washington Week'' is that it is stolid
and dependable. It is, in other words, virtually harmless.
</P>
<P>
   Its devotees think ``Washington Week'' is deep. It is, but only
as you compare it to the political food fights that take place
elsewhere on the television dial. ``Washington Week,''
nevertheless, is going through a bad time. Its producers want to
pep it up, give it more liberal vs. conservative attitude, get
panelists to be bolder, edgier.
</P>
<P>
   In service of this more lively vision, ``Washington Week'' is
now without its moderator, Ken Bode. The producers are temporarily
bringing back Paul Duke, the previous moderator, who, if anything,
is even more stolid and dependable. Curious thing, TV.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, it seems, we are destined for yet another left
versus right tag team match to teach us, once again, that we have
only two choices in our political life: evil and even worse evil.
Swell.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
