<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3086 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-DOCTOROW-BOS &LR;      03-01 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-DOCTOROW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW `RAGTIME' MADE IT FROM THE WALL TO THE STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This story begins with a wall. There's no hidden metaphor here,
no nod to Robert Frost or hats off to Pink Floyd. We're simply
talking about one author, one case of writer's block, and one
ordinary wall.
</P>
<P>
   The year is 1972, and the scribe in question is E. L. Doctorow.
He's fresh off the success of his novel ``The Book of Daniel,'' and
he's supposed to be writing the next one. Instead, he stares at the
wall. The wall stares back. The vertical structure is attached to a
house built in New Rochelle, N.Y., circa 1906, and the house
eventually inspires scenes and characters, syncopated music, the
setting for a novel, and a certain mood. The novelist writes, and
then there is a book. It's called ``Ragtime.'' Then there is a
movie (a flop), and then there is a musical, a Broadway hit. A
touring production of the musical wends its way to Boston, where it
is selling out at the Colonial Theatre. The novelist is happy _ to
a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fairly painless, actually,'' Doctorow, now 68, says of
his involvement with the musical adaptation. The author has never
hidden his aversion to director Milos Forman's screen adaptation of
the novel _ or to movies in general. ``Films tend to be very
literal-minded,'' he says. And he has never been a passionate fan
of musicals, either. ``Of course, I've gone to them all my life _
`Threepenny Opera' and `Guys and Dolls' and Bob Fosse's stuff. But
I have never been creatively lured into thinking in terms of the
musical theater,'' Doctorow says. ``The form just never appealed to
me as a writer. And as with all forms, there is a lot of bad work
that has been a repository for stock sentiment and piety.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Wide distribution &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And Doctorow certainly didn't need to dust off the novel. Since
it was published, in 1975, ``Ragtime'' has been translated into
more than 30 languages and has sold more than 4.5 million copies in
English alone. But he was intrigued when impresario Garth Drabinsky
of the Toronto-based Livent Inc. came calling a few years ago to
cajole him into approving a musical adaptation. ``I was given the
right to approve the people who would be involved, the composer,
the lyricist, the librettist, the director,'' Doctorow recalls
during a recent telephone interview. ``I thought it would be a nice
kind of adventure. It was a gamble, but it worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, the gamble worked out creatively, but not necessarily
financially. Last year, Drabinsky was fired from Livent and charged
with conspiracy and fraud, and the company filed for bankruptcy in
November. Doctorow and ``Ragtime'' playwright Terrence McNally,
lyricist Lynn Ahrens, and composer Stephen Flaherty are suing
Livent for back payments. Doctorow is seeking $137,461 in back
royalties; McNally and his collaborators are claiming $385,743.
</P>
<P>
   The novelist has been on the same page as his collaborators all
along, from the drawing board to bankruptcy court. Back in the
development phase, Doctorow listened to demo tapes by five composer
teams. ``Some of it was very nice, but it wasn't ragtime. It was
regular Broadway stuff,'' he says. ``I almost decided there was no
point in going on.''
</P>
<P>
   But after he heard the Flaherty-Ahrens music, he gave his
approval. ``They had found their way into the spirit of the book,''
Doctorow recalls.
</P>
<P>
   It reminded him of the revival of Scott Joplin and ragtime that
was going on back in the days when he had that original encounter
with the wall. Thanks to the soundtrack to ``The Sting,'' which
reintroduced Joplin to the masses, and to recordings by pianist
Joshua Rifkin, ragtime was all the rage in the '70s. ``I bought the
sheet music, and I found Joplin's advisory: `Do not play this piece
fast. It is never right to play ragtime fast,' '' Doctorow says.
``I used that as the epigraph for the book, in the event that
people finding it very, very accessible might be inclined to think
it was a lightweight piece with no serious intention. I thought
that was a nice analogy between Joplin's effort to impress people
with his music and my effort to sort of bridge the gap between that
which is thought of as serious and that which is thought of as
popular.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Serious themes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Ragtime'' is enormously entertaining, on the page as well as
on the stage. But its themes are hardly lightweight. Doctorow
interweaves the stories of three distinctly different American
families _ one black, one white, one newly immigrated from Latvia _
with such historical figures as Emma Goldman and Evelyn Nesbit,
Harry Houdini and Henry Ford. The novel, which is chock-full of
what Doctorow has described as ``the best facts I can dream up,''
sort of takes the reader by the hand and pulls him along on a mock
historical adventure. By now, the technique is hardly unique: It's
been used by such authors as Don DeLillo and Carlos Fuentes, and it
has also been adopted by Hollywood in such films as ``Forrest
Gump.'' ``Is that the one where they showed him talking to
Kennedy?'' Doctorow asks about the award-winning blockbuster. ``I
read about it, but I didn't see it.''
</P>
<P>
   The author of eight novels, it seems, would rather stare at a
wall than at a film or video screen. But this bookish man was
intrigued with the theatrical process, and he sounds downright
delighted by the ingenuity of dramatic devices. The ``Ragtime''
creators sum up pages and pages of narrative with an ingenious
prologue, in which all the characters introduce themselves with a
brief character synopsis. The historical figures serve as a sort of
Greek chorus, moving the action along with their detached
commentary. At one point in the rehearsal stage, Doctorow was
concerned that the character of J. Pierpont Morgan needed a higher
profile. ``He wasn't coming through, and my solution as a writer
was to write a new scene, but they solved the problem by having him
walk across a beam and press down on the immigrants below. That's
just staging, and it doesn't take much time.''
</P>
<P>
   The novelist isn't entirely new to the theater. In 1952, he
spent a year as a graduate student studying drama at Columbia
University. ``After one year, I figured out something very simple:
When you finish writing a play, it's not finished. In other words,
it has to be produced, and it doesn't come into being until other
people get their hands on it. When you finish a novel, it's done.
Period.'' Doctorow did return to the theater once, back in 1978,
when his play ``Drinks Before Dinner'' debuted at New York's Public
Theatre. Intensely cerebral, the play left many scratching their
heads. Writing in The New York Times, Richard Eder described it as
``an endless epigram, a butterfly that turns into a centipede.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctorow isn't about to give up his day job: Any aspiring writer
would salivate for such a career. But he seems pleased about the
relatively painless process behind ``Ragtime'' (except that little
problem known as ``The check's in the mail.'') Sure, he might have
done a few things differently. The musical barely brushes on what
he calls the ``satirical eroticism'' of the novel. ``The other
thing that's missing is a sense of the surreality of American life,
a true madness,'' he says. ``But that's OK. That's fine. Anyone who
adapts a novel does a reading of it, and this reading is certainly
a lot better than the film people did.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Ragtime'' adventure was fun, but it's back to the wall for
Doctorow, back to the blank pages of the next novel. ``When you
write a novel, you are the director, the scenic designer, the
lighting specialist, the costumer. You're everything,'' he
concludes. ``And for those of us who find it difficult to delegate
responsibility, that's a suitable form, isn't it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
