<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TEENS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALL IT TEEN SPIRIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All the prestige fall movies _ the ones with war, death, and
Meryl Streep accents _ have made their big splash. The warm, fuzzy
holiday movies are as forgotten and stale as a December fruitcake.
And we're still a month shy of the Academy Awards, which will, in
theory if not in truth, honor the best films of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   That means we're smack dab in the middle of the mediocre movie
season.
</P>
<P>
   Between January and April, lousy films clog up the cineplex like
hair in a bathroom drain. There are, of course, worthwhile films
like ``The Thin Red Line'' and ``Affliction,'' which are just
finding their way to smaller cities after opening late last year in
New York and Los Angeles to be eligible for Oscar consideration.
</P>
<P>
   But these are the exception and not the rule during these months
that have become Hollywood's version of the town dump. Mostly
there's Kevin Costner looking forlorn and mumbling his way through
the goopy romance of ``Message in a Bottle,'' and Mel Gibson in the
ultraviolent ``Payback,'' the film with that dumb-as-a-brick ``Get
Ready to Root for the Bad Guy'' campaign. (Both are hits, which
speaks volumes about the need some folks have to see something,
anything at the movies.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, the most discernible trend during this winter of
moviegoing discontent is the sudden deluge of teen movies.
</P>
<P>
   Since January, there's been ``Varsity Blues,'' with teen
heartthrob-of-the-week James Van Der Beek; ``She's All That,''
starring Freddie Prinze Jr.; ``Jawbreaker,'' with the future Mrs.
Marilyn Manson, Rose McGowan. This week, ``Cruel Intentions,'' with
Sarah Michelle Gellar, Ryan Phillippe, and Reese Witherspoon,
arrives in theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the big screen is percolating with prom queens,
letter-jacket-wearing jocks, and not-so-ugly ducklings blossoming
into swans just in time for the big dance. Not since John Hughes
created such films as ``The Breakfast Club'' and ``Sixteen
Candles'' in the mid-1980s, and made brief stars of
where-are-they-now subjects Anthony Michael Hall and Molly
Ringwald, have moviegoers been so inundated with adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   Since most of us experienced high school _ and may still bear
its scars _ the adolescent years are ever-green for filmmakers.
Some wonderful films have been made about teenagers _ ``Blackboard
Jungle,'' ``The Summer of '42,'' ``To Sir With Love,''
``Heathers,'' and, more recently, ``Clueless.'' Even some of
Hughes's films have held up far better than they ever should have.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Formula wearing thin
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But it's highly unlikely anyone will ever say the same about the
current crop of teen movies _ although it has inexplicably yielded
a few hits.
</P>
<P>
   Immune to the slings and arrows of critics, both ``Varsity
Blues'' and ``She's All That'' debuted as box office champs. Both
were fairly innocuous films with blandly attractive leading mannish
boys _ Van Der Beek, best known from TV's ``Dawson's Creek,'' and
Prinze, already on teen radars after ``I Know What You Did Last
Summer'' and its terrible sequel. And ``She's All That'' could even
boast as its inspiration George Bernard Shaw's ``Pygmalion,'' even
though it's unlikely its target audience has ever heard of Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the formula _ simplistic plots, attractive actors
with cheekbones to die for and 5 percent body fat, and the
all-important killer soundtrack _ is wearing thin. ``Jawbreaker,''
which opened earlier this month to near-unanimous pans, is as
stupid a film as anyone is likely to make this year. A blatant
rip-off of the far superior ``Heathers,'' it's a mean little story
featuring the most popular harpies at Reagan High School
accidentally offing their prom-queen pal by jamming a jawbreaker
down her pretty little throat.
</P>
<P>
   Even songs by the Donnas and Veruca Salt can't save this
worthless endeavor. Fortunately, the film got what it deserved: It
flopped at the box office, unable to even eke out a spot in the Top
10.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking style, ingenuity, and, in some cases, actual teenagers,
many of today's teen films, like ``Jawbreaker,'' are the product of
Hollywood at its most cynical. Recognizing the considerable clout
of teenage girls _ how else to explain the success of ``Titanic''
and 'N Sync? _ studio suits are churning out trifles, and trying to
pass them off as interesting films. They insult the intelligence of
the very audience they seek to entertain. After all, isn't being a
teenager difficult enough without a bunch of 20-something actors in
insipid films misrepresenting your trials and tribulations?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
