<HEADER>
A3093 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-PEOPLE-BOS &LR;      03-01 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PEOPLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OUR KIND' ONLY CRACKS OPEN DOOR ON BLACK ELITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
OUR KIND OF PEOPLE 
Inside America's Black Upper Class 
By Lawrence Otis Graham 
HarperCollins, 418 pp., illustrated, $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Our Kind of People'' is the kind of book you want to fling
across the room, when you aren't calling your friends to rant and
rave about its endless details and dish.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Otis Graham's look _ it can't be called anything so
analytical as an examination _ at America's black upper class is an
exasperating book about a group that has existed in shadow for more
than a century.
</P>
<P>
   This is not simply a story about black folks with money; you'll
find no tender words for millionaire basketball players or rappers
who make it and move from the 'hood to the Hamptons. This is the
story of the black haves, people who _ insulated by privilege,
divisive standards, and an unconscious self-hatred _ have all but
shed their connection to the African-American community at large.
Graham clarifies the distinctions in the book's opening:
</P>
<P>
   ``Bryant Gumbel is, but Bill Cosby isn't. Lena Horne is, but
Whitney Houston isn't. Andrew Young is, but Jesse Jackson isn't.
And neither is Maya Angelou, Alice Walker, Clarence Thomas, or
Quincy Jones. And even though both of them try extremely hard,
neither Diana Ross nor Robin Givens will ever be.''
</P>
<P>
   See, it doesn't matter that Angelou is an acclaimed poet, or
that Thomas is a Supreme Court justice. Both hail from hardscrabble
backgrounds that will forever bar them from the black aristocracy.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, they're just too dark-skinned.
</P>
<P>
   As described by Graham, a long-standing member of the black
elite, these upper-class folks are just as concerned with skin
color _ and can be as hateful and haughty _ as the snooty whites
whose bigotry drove the black elites to establish their own
exclusive clubs in the first place (it's the Boule for men, the
Links for women, and Jack and Jill for children). Certainly, it
helps to be an alumnus of Howard, Spelman, or Morehouse, the three
predominantly black colleges that sparkle in the eyes of the elite
(Harvard will also suffice). But it's just as important that you're
light-skinned with straight hair.
</P>
<P>
   Graham (no relation to this reviewer) deserves some credit for
telling tales on his own. He conducted hundreds of interviews for
the book, though he need not have looked any further than his own
family tree. He recalls summers in Oak Bluffs, the Martha's
Vineyard enclave long popular among rich blacks, with his
great-grandmother Porter _ a ``well-educated, light-complexioned,
straight-haired black southern woman'' _ who would scold him for
spending too much time in the sun, lest he get too black. She would
thumb through Ebony magazine, dismissing the black entertainers
with the same racial epithet she surely heard as a black daughter
of the South. Even when Sidney Poitier won a best actor Oscar in
1963 for ``Lilies of the Field,'' Porter's pride was tempered
because she thought Poitier too dark-skinned.
</P>
<P>
   Such attitudes were born from the horror of slavery.
Light-skinned blacks often received better treatment, such as house
jobs instead of harsh field chores, than did their darker brethren.
It was also more likely for light-skinned slaves to be freed, since
they were the master's children. After the Civil War, these blacks
began to establish organizations to foster their sense of
privilege.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my life, for as long as I can remember,'' Graham writes,
``I grew up thinking that there existed only two types of black
people: those who passed the `brown paper bag and ruler test' and
those who didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The tests pass judgment on skin color and hair texture. If the
complexion is lighter than a paper bag, and the hair is as straight
as a ruler, you're in. If they're not, you're not. Such eligibility
requirements are still common.
</P>
<P>
   That Graham presents all of this in an uncritical,
this-is-how-we-do-it tone, is the book's great failing. The voyeur
within us can't help but read with fascination about the tony
cotillions and coming-out dances. But Graham never gets beyond the
material fabulousness to the hollowness within his subjects' souls.
He has gone inside, but not under the skin, and what's left is a
breathy chronicle of how the black elite meet and greet; he airs
their dirty laundry without considering its stain on the larger
black community.
</P>
<P>
   Overlooked here is any dissection of the warped psychology of
black people shortsighted enough to believe good breeding and the
right socially incestuous connections have allowed them to
overcome.
</P>
<P>
   James Baldwin once wondered how black folks might behave if they
were relieved of their oppression and granted the status of whites.
``Our Kind of People'' unwittingly offers one sad, disheartening
answer to that question.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-99 1357EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990301.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3094 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-BLONDIE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     03-01 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BLONDIE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... at Burke.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It was terrible, it was towards the demise of the band,'' says
Burke, recalling the date.
</P>
<P>
   What triggered the assault? ``It could have been stress. Things
were not going good. We took two years off from the road, we went
into large venues and these (separate) limousines and a private
jet, where we were all on top of each other. People had different
agendas; Chris was ill; the business was in disarray.'' Blondie had
been together eight years.
</P>
<P>
   The band splintered. Harry helped get Stein through a
debilitating skin disease called pemphigus vulgaris. (The disease
is sometimes fatal, but Stein is well now.) They continued to work
together musically, but they split as a couple. Burke did session
and tour work for Eurythmics and Bob Dylan, among others. Blondie's
bassist at the time, Nigel Harrison, went into the business side of
music. Guitarist Frank Infante had fallen out with the band a long
time before (he was not on the last tour). Destri did limited
production and worked as a contractor. Infante and Harrison are not
part of this reunion; they weren't invited and are, in fact, suing
the others. (Stein calls it a personality clash; Burke opts for the
other usual suspect: artistic clash. Neither cares to expound.) The
touring band includes bassist Lee Fox Boston and guitarist Paul
Carbona.
</P>
<P>
   Harry carried on with a solo career that sputtered along at a
low level. She acted in cult movies such as ``Videodrome,'' ``Union
City,'' and ``Hairspray.'' She sent herself up, playing a faded pop
star on the ``Wiseguy'' TV series. In the '90s, she joined the Jazz
Passengers, which she says was an important step, as well as a
bridge (albeit an inadvertent one) back to Blondie.
</P>
<P>
   Harry calls it ``a stretch musically and more responsibility as
a musician in a band situation. I was not the `front person.' I
would say a singer-with-a-band, in some cases just an instrument,
perhaps like a flute or a violin. The latter half of my recording
with them, there were songs I had written, so that had a little
more personality, of course, for me. But I focused on singing in an
ensemble situation, a much different environment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the opposite of what they kept saying the first
time around with Blondie,'' adds Stein. ``They only talked about
her attitude and stance. No one ever thought about Debbie singing,
and the Jazz Passengers is the total opposite of that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meet the new Blondie. Same as the old Blondie?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still the same people,'' says Burke. ``It feels like
some weird time capsule we came out of. We've all been through some
therapy. We're still a pop band on the verge of a nervous
breakdown. But everyone's a little older and wiser, and we can
tolerate each other and the outside forces.''
</P>
<P>
   From a responsibility standpoint, he admits, ``the brunt is on
Debbie's shoulders, really, even though we choose to represent it
as a group. We talked about this before we went public with it. We
feel like we're in the driver's seat right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, that can be a precarious perch for rockers in their 50s,
as Stein and Harry both are. (The others are slightly younger.) The
muse has continued to inspire veterans such as David Bowie and Neil
Young, but many more times the pop musician of that age finds
creativity has long played itself out. With ``No Exit,'' Blondie
comes down on the plus side of the chasm.
</P>
<P>
   The copilot on this comeback flight is manager Allen Kovac, who
has worked comebacks for Meat Loaf and Duran Duran. ``We call him a
visionary,'' says Stein. ``He deals with the logistics of
marketing, applying different techniques that haven't been used in
the music business before.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the world of Blondie,'' says Burke. ``It was always
part of our identity; I was always Clem from Blondie. I actually
don't get out much to feel this new adulation but certain people
keep calling you again, long-lost relatives start turning up. The
easy part was making the music. In the studio, it just felt like a
bunch of musicians making a record _ no deja vu or nostalgia
involved. The catharsis came when we completed the record.''
</P>
<P>
   Blondie has been all over television of late _ ``The Tonight
Show with Jay Leno'' and ``The Late Show with David Letterman'' in
the past two weeks. An hourlong concert taped Tuesday in New York
was to air Sunday night at 10 on VH1. There's a spot on Rosie
O'Donnell's show next Tuesday. The band's music is featured in the
film ``200 Cigarettes,'' which opened Friday. Tour plans are yet to
be finalized. The group has played about 35 dates in Europe and
Australia and is capable of a two-hour show _ four or five songs
from ``No Exit'' and a variety pack from the catalog. They are
gearing up for a US tour later this year. They may play mid-size
theaters; they may hold off for a shot at the summer shed circuit.
</P>
<P>
   As to goals, Stein hesitates. ``I don't know, I am looking to do
something that will sort of break through and I don't want to go
out doing more of what is already out there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris has become very philosophical about what he went
through,'' says Burke. ``He almost enjoyed it, being right on the
edge, facing mortality, and the good thing is he came back. He
doesn't take things for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry: ``I think that sometimes it seems like there is really
nothing new under the sun, but then something comes along. I guess
(my goal) would simply be to have this record go down well and be
in the position to do another, to take it a little further out.''
</P>
<P>
   Is the reunion permanent?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing,'' says Harry, ``is permanent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
