<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3095 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-HOUSTON-ART-BO     03-01 1333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-HOUSTON-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ARTIST CAPTIVATED BY THE SOUL OF THE ICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; STONINGTON, Conn. _ James Houston ``went in'' to the Arctic in
1948 ``with just a sleeping bag and a lot of sketchbooks,'' he
says. And, in a sense, he never ``came out.''
</P>
<P>
   Note those two expressions: ``went in'' and ``came out.''
They're invariably found in the great accounts of exploration and
adventure in distant places. And they are expressions that Houston
_ now a bluff and ruddy 77 with a firm grip and far-seeing eyes _
uses as casually in conversation as you or I would the more usual
``went to'' and ``came from.''
</P>
<P>
   And well he should.
</P>
<P>
   Houston had just returned from World War II and art school in
Paris when he hitched a ride on a medical emergency flight into the
Canadian Arctic, landing in a native settlement on the northeast
coast of Hudson Bay. When the plane departed, Houston stayed
behind. ``I had found the place that I'd been looking for,'' he
writes in his autobiography, ``Confessions of an Igloo Dweller.''
It was a place where he would live for 14 years _ and a place that
he would capture in drawings and glass sculptures and in more than
two dozen books, most recently a novel, ``The Ice Master.''
</P>
<P>
   In all these varied art forms, Houston's purpose has been, as he
puts it, ``to reflect the historic Inuit vision of a world where
man and nature are locked, not in perpetual battle but perpetual
partnership, a world where fish and animals offer their flesh to
worthy hunters in an act of sublime generosity and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   But Houston was to do more than celebrate that vision on his
own.
</P>
<P>
   On his first full day in Inukjuak, on that first trip into the
Arctic, he made a sketch of an Inuit man's wife. In return, the man
gave him a small stone carving of a caribou. Houston was given
similar carvings in the days that followed.
</P>
<P>
   When he learned that these were recent carvings, not the work of
a long-vanished Arctic civilization, it led to Houston playing a
major role in introducing the art of printmaking to the
artistically skilled Eskimos. The West Baffin Eskimo Co-Operative,
which he established at Cape Dorset on Baffin Island, has become a
center of Inuit art and culture. The works of its printmakers are
sold and exhibited widely.
</P>
<P>
   Houston now lives half the year in his 18th-century sea
captain's house in Stonington and half the year on an island off
British Columbia _ with an annual visit to his old art school in
Paris for a month of drawing. He has made 27 trips back into the
Arctic, most recently with his two sons to scatter his first wife's
ashes in West Baffin.
</P>
<P>
   After his initial trip, Houston returned to Ottawa, quickly
landing a post even farther in, as northern service officer and
civil administrator for West Baffin. He also married. When he went
back with his new bride, the trip took 40 days by dog sled over
frozen land and water.
</P>
<P>
   Unconventional as Houston's career already was _ as artist,
teacher, promoter, and government agent _ a radio message he
received in 1959 would lead to new careers as glass sculptor and
writer.
</P>
<P>
   The message was that an American named Houghton wanted to come
up to Cape Dorset. ``I thought nothing of it,'' Houston said,
``until I got a second message with instructions to have clothing
made for the people who would be coming with him _ and giving their
arm and foot sizes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see they were getting serious,'' Houston said. His
wife quickly organized the local people to make tents and clothing,
and to prepare for the arrival of a party that included, in
addition to Houghton _ who turned out to be Arthur A. Houghton Jr.,
president of the Metropolitan Museum of Art and of Steuben Glass _
two pilots and a cook. Despite his earlier misgivings, Houston
said, ``it was the least foolish bunch you'd ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   And ``they were overwhelmed,'' said Houston, recalling that
Arctic poppies were in full bloom and carpeted the ground inside
the tents.
</P>
<P>
   When Houghton left, he presented Houston with a piece of Steuben
glass _ a whale. Houston suggested that Houghton send a crew up to
Cape Dorset, where there was a good supply of clean sand, a key
element in glassmaking. ``Our guys,'' he said, speaking of the
local Inuit artists and craftsmen, ``could have tickled this up in
no time.'' Houghton countered with an invitation for Houston to
come to New York.
</P>
<P>
   So in 1962, with the Cape Dorset cooperative well-established _
and his wife having taken their two sons to London for school _
Houston wound up his tour as administrator and service officer in
the Arctic and headed for New York.
</P>
<P>
   His first experience as a sculpture designer was not auspicious.
As he recalls in ``Fire and Ice,'' a lavishly illustrated account
of his years at Steuben, on his first day on the job, he stood in
front of one of the red-hot furnaces that were ``roaring like a
herd of walruses,'' clutching a drawing of a polar bear. He felt,
he says, ``as small as a piece of butter beginning to melt.'' And
the polar bear, which on paper had looked so easy to make, ended up
as scrap.
</P>
<P>
   But as he learned the art and craft of glass sculpture, Houston
saw the affinity between glass and ice _ even comparing the
``delicate tinkling'' of upright-floating ice candles brushing
against each other to that of crystal glasses being clinked
together.
</P>
<P>
   Houston grew successful as a glass sculptor, but he continued
making sketches of Inuit scenes from memory. These came to the
attention of artist Fritz Eichenberg, who encouraged Houston to
write some articles on Inuit art. A weekend visit to Eichenberg on
Nantucket brought Houston to the attention of children's book
editor Margaret K. McElderry, who commissioned him to write and
illustrate a book based on Inuit myths.
</P>
<P>
   Written over a long weekend _ and illustrated the next _ it was
published as ``Tikta'liktak,'' the first of 17 children's books by
Houston, three of which have been Canadian children's book of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If writing is as easy as that,'' Houston remembers thinking,
``then I'm all set.'' So he tapped out a novel that was published
as ``White Dawn'' and was subsequently made into a motion picture
by Paramount. It was filmed in the Arctic, with Houston as
assistant producer.
</P>
<P>
   Following the success of ``White Dawn,'' Houston and his second
wife, Alice, a Connecticut native, bought a sheep farm in Exeter,
R.I.
</P>
<P>
   They eventually sold the farm and bought the house of
18th-century sea captain Amos Palmer 15 years ago. It's a house
rich in history: a target for naval gunners when the British raided
Stonington during the Revolution and, later, the residence of
``Whistler's Mother,'' the subject of the painting by her son,
James McNeill Whistler.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also a personal museum of sorts, reflecting Houston's
careers as artist, promoter of Inuit art, glass sculptor, and
writer. Display cases exhibit stunning examples of Inuit stone and
ivory carving, pieces of Steuben glass, and 18th-century powder
horns and insignia and whaling gear that Houston has collected
while writing books on those subjects.
</P>
<P>
   In the front parlor, drawing a visitor's eye away from the
period antiques, is the spiraled tusk of a narwhal, a small Arctic
whale, close to 7 feet long with a satiny sheen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was walking along the beach on Coats Island one day,'' said
Houston. ``It was lying there, half buried in the sand and still
attached to the skeleton, which I had to leave behind.'' Houston
pulled out a map to point out Coats Island at the northern end of
Hudson Bay. Then, recalling that day as if it were yesterday _ and
he had ``come out'' for a brief visit _ he added in a quiet,
faraway voice, ``I don't imagine anyone had walked on that beach
for 25 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
