</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S. (Beijing) _ Developments on Secretary Albright's trip
to China: Despite arguments on human rights, she says these issues
won't block talks on getting China into World Trade Organization.
By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-OBASANJO (Lagos) _ A Man-in-the-News profile: Nigeria's
next president, Gen. Olusegun Obasanjo, is a man of contradictions.
By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-VOTE (Lagos) _ As Obasanjo is formally declared winner
of the presidential election, his opponent tells electoral
commission he can't accept the results because of ``monumental''
fraud. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LEBANON (Jerusalem) _ Developments in the wake of the
Israeli bombing of guerrilla strongholds in Lebanon. By Deborah
Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Pristina) _ Developments in the restive Yugoslav
province. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-UNREST (Jakarta) _ In a dangerous escalation of the
sectarian violence that has hopscotched across this far-flung
nation, nine people died Monday in the remote provincial capital of
Ambon after police opened fire on a crowd outside a mosque, several
witnesses told Reuters. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ Developments at the Supreme Court: The
high court might take big immigration case; argument on a civil
rights case over the extent of damages a plaintiff can get under
Title VII, which bars race and sex discrimination in the workplace.
The new revision of the law provided for the first time a way to
get punitive damages, but left unclear what the threshhold would
be. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
