<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Bonds continue to slide. At midday, the long
bond was down 1 3/32 point, with the yield at 5.66 percent. The
industrial average was down 45 points, or half a percent, and the
Nasdaq index was down 19 points, or 0.8 percent. Elsewhere, prices
fell 1 percent in Tokyo and rose 1.6 percent in Hong Kong. They
fell 2.6 percent in Frankfurt, 2.2 percent in London and 0.3
percent in Mexico. Stocks in Brazil gained 1.2 percent. By Kenneth
N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   BANANA-TRADE (Dateline to kum) _ With the threat of sanctions
hanging over its head, the European Union is weighing changes
suggested by the United States to the 15-nation group's
banana-import policy. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-DEBT (London) _ Banks that hold Russian Treasury debt
meet today. In recent days, Deutsche Bank and Chase broke ranks
with other creditors and accepted Russia's terms of a debt
restructuring. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   OLIVETTI-TELECOM (Rome) _ The shares of Olivetti and Telecom
Italia rise on the heels of a weekend ruling that Olivetti's
renewed takeover bid is legitimate. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   ADOBE-QUARK (San Francisco) _ When Adobe Systems' shares hit a
four-year low last year, Quark floated an informal, and unwelcome,
offer to buy the company. On Tuesday, Adobe will return the favor
with the introduction of a program that some are calling the
Quark-killer. Adobe executives do not use that term themselves, but
they make no bones about attacking Quark in its core market for
high-end page-layout software. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBLIC-BANK (New York) _ Republic New York restructures. It
says its derivatives market-making operation and its prime
brokerage arm, Republic New York Securities, did not meet the
bank's goal of a 15 percent return on risk-adjusted equity and
therefore will be dismantled. The bank plans to invest in
businesses like private banking that it deems strategically
important. The plan will affect 560 jobs and result in a pretax
charge of $97 million. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   EBAY-INQUIRY (Undated) _ Federal authorities are looking into
potentially illegal transactions on Ebay's Web site. By Lisa
Napoli.
</P>
<P>
   TRINITY-MIRROR (London) _ Trinity, a British publisher of
regional newspapers, says it is prepared to make an offer of 959
million pounds, or $1.5 billion, in cash and stock for Mirror
Group, which calls the proposal inadequate. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
