<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; !!! &LR;  1/2 ``Another Day in Paradise'' Larry Clark's
lowlife-crooks-on-the-lam movie gives James Woods his best role in
years as a yappy, wired thief, and gives Melanie Griffith her best
role since ``Working Girl'' as his tough, loyal junkie consort. You
find yourself hoping the sweet dumb kids (Vincent Kartheiser,
Natasha Gregson Wagner) they hook up with will get out of their
gritty pop odyssey alive. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; !! &LR;  ``Eight Millimeter'' What could have been a scalding
indictment of the outwardly respectable consumers who have turned
porn into big business is bypassed in favor of a dark-looking but
superficial thriller. Nicolas Cage plays a private eye turned
avenging angel when he descends into the porn underworld to find
out what happened to a runaway girl he saw in a snuff film. (R)
</P>
<P>
   (FR)  &UR; !!! &LR;  ``The Last Days'' A moving and eloquent documentary.
Five Holocaust survivors relive their harrowing stories when they
revisit the death camps and their native Hungary, where Hitler,
knowing the war was lost in 1944, diverted military resources from
battle into exterminating as many Jews as he could ship out in
boxcars, more than 440,000. (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; !! &LR;  ``The Other Sister'' Juliette Lewis and Giovanni Ribisi are
appealing as mentally challenged people who fall in love. But this
would-be romantic comedy with heart has been sugarcoated. What
should have been a sensitive and tender story is sweetened with
simplistic sitcom ingredients; now we see two-dimensional
characters, with an uptight mom as the only problem facing the
couple. (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! &LR;  1/2 ``200 Cigarettes'' Wildly uneven, mildly entertaining film
set on New Year's Eve 1981 in New York. The script is riddled with
dead spots, and despite a few sparkling moments, the cast _ which
includes Courtney Love, Martha Plimpton, Christina Ricci, and
Janeane Garofalo _ is largely wasted. (R) (Renee Graham)
</P>
</TEXT>
