<DOCNO> NYT19990301.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3098 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TIPS-BOS &LR;      03-01 0216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TIPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``November 1916'' by Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn (Farrar, Straus &AMP;
Giroux, $35). The second installment of the Russian writer's
monumental fiction cycle, meant to recast his country's
revolutionary history. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Crime of Sheila McGough'' by Janet Malcolm (Knopf, $22). A
unique reporter recounts the trials of an innocent found guilty of
14 felonies. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Diary of Vaslav Nijinsky,'' edited by Joan Acocella
(Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $30). The soaring dancer's tragic mental
collapse, in his own words. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Empress of the Splendid Season'' by Oscar Hijuelos
(HarperFlamingo, $25). An upper-class Cuban woman, reduced to
cleaning posh New York apartments, encounters wealth from
underneath. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitler: 1889-1936: Hubris'' by Ian Kershaw (Norton, $35). A
massive and highly readable account of the rise of the tyrant. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Law of Similars'' by Chris Bohjalian (Harmony Books, $23).
A prosecutor falls for a sexy homeopathist, with dangerous results
when she is suspected of malpractice. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
