<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBATES OFTEN TOUGH TO REALLY GET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN SIDENER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Rebate.
</P>
<P>
   Ahh. It sounds like a nice word, doesn't it? It conjures up
mental images of cash back in your pocket after making a purchase.
And cash in your pocket is always nice.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, these days the term ``rebate'' has become a dirty word,
especially among computer users who are inundated every day with
rebate offers on television, on radio, in magazines and in
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Surely you've seen the offers. Many, for example, offer $30, $40
or more in rebates if you buy software or hardware at full price
and then mail in the rebate application with your proof of purchase
(and, sometimes, the bar code from the box).
</P>
<P>
   Some offers go so far as to promise consumers that their final
cost _ after they receive their rebate _ will be zero.
</P>
<P>
   Who can pass that up? Not many.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's why law enforcement agencies, corporate
executives, consumer groups and media outlets across the country
are getting complaints from consumers angry over rebate offers gone
bad.
</P>
<P>
   The gist of most complaints: Somebody bought something, sent in
the required information but never received any rebate.
</P>
<P>
   Some consumers tell tales of waiting six to nine months with no
sign of a rebate. Some have documented countless telephone calls,
faxes, certified letters and other efforts to claim the money they
are owed.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the tale of Barry, a Valley resident who bought three
items at a Tempe electronics store nine months ago. All three came
with rebate coupons. He applied for all three rebates, but has yet
to receive anything.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to resolve the situation by dealing directly with the
Tempe retailer, Barry says he has run into constant roadblocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I told (the store's representative) that I would be
filing this matter in small claims court, she took that information
to her superiors,'' Barry wrote in an e-mail to me last week.
``Their response was (and I'm quoting her), `So that's what he'll
have to do then.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Barry said he's had trouble getting rebates before, but it was
nothing like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the ones that I have sent in, I have had to chase over 60
percent of them with repeated phone calls to get them to finally
deliver,'' he wrote. ``But I have never encountered a company that
has just outrightly snubbed their nose and said, in effect, `Go
pound sand.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The easiest explanation for the trouble Barry and others have
encountered is that rebate offers are just too popular. Too many
people are asking for too many rebates, and the companies hired to
handle much of the job, called ``fulfillment houses,'' are
overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question rebate programs work. That's why we see so
many of them, whether they're attached to the sales of computers,
dishwashers or travel packages. I found an online reference to one
offer that forced a company in the computer business to cough up
$75,000 in rebates in just one week.
</P>
<P>
   But, as you might guess, there's more to the story than just
overwhelmed fulfillment houses.
</P>
<P>
   First, many rebate programs run into trouble due to scam
artists. CNNFN reported that rebate fraud costs American businesses
upward of $500 million every year. A U.S. Postal Service fraud
investigation a few years ago found up to 75 percent of rebate
claims it reviewed during the investigation were fraudulent.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to legitimate rebate requests, many end up in the
trash heap because the consumer failed to follow the rules, usually
by not filling out the rebate form properly or by missing a
deadline for rebate requests. The smallest error can be enough
reason to deny a request.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are rebate offers that nobody intended to honor.
I can't name names. Law enforcement authorities are tight-lipped
when it comes to discussing ongoing investigations. But some of the
rebate horror stories I've heard and read about leave no other
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of rebate problems fall into a huge gray area.
These involve rebate requests that disappear in the mail, never to
be heard from again. Sometimes, fulfillment houses claim they never
received the paperwork. Sometimes, consumers are told to be
patient, that rebates will arrive in another six or eight weeks. Of
course, they usually don't.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, many consumers forget about the rebates or just give
up in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who suggest that's exactly what some companies
want consumers to do _ give up. And that could be true. It's been
suggested by industry insiders that some companies purposely make
it difficult to redeem rebate coupons in order to save themselves
money.
</P>
<P>
   Another explanation could be that the companies in question
simply turned over their rebate programs to the cheapest
fulfillment house they can find, and then fail to monitor whether
the fulfillment houses are doing their jobs properly.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reasons, you have to admit that applying for and
actually getting a rebate these days takes attention to detail, a
lot of patience and a bucket of luck.
</P>
<P>
   When rebate offers go bad, consumers across the country are
starting to seek legal help. The Arizona Attorney General's Office
reports that 212 people filed rebate-related complaints in the
state in 1998. And 27 more have been filed this year.
</P>
<P>
   Where will the complaints end up? That's hard to say.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Attorney General's Office won't comment on
particulars of any case, and won't confirm whether it's
investigating anything. My guess is that the office is busy with
big-ticket crimes and isn't spending a whole lot of time on Mr.
Consumer's complaint that he's owed $25 in rebates.
</P>
<P>
   So what's a consumer to do? Here are some basics I've put
together after researching this topic online and talking with
experts in consumer issues and with the Arizona Attorney General's
Office:
</P>
<P>
   - Don't count on a rebate to make a purchase worth your while.
If you really need a new hard drive, look for one with a sticker
price you can afford. Then, if it comes with a rebate, and you
actually get the rebate, great.
</P>
<P>
   - If you buy something with a significant rebate attached, don't
leave the store until you've asked about the rebate process. Do
they handle it themselves? Do they farm it out to a fulfillment
house? Who do you call if there are rebate problems?
</P>
<P>
   - Read rebate instructions carefully before you buy. Make sure
the deadline has not yet passed. And watch out for other tricky
requirements. Some rebate offers are honored only if the product is
purchased from authorized resellers, and not every retail store is
authorized to resell everything.
</P>
<P>
   - Fill out the rebate form carefully. Print your name, address
and other information so it can be easily read.
</P>
<P>
   - Don't forget to include required documentation, such as sales
receipts and/or the bar code from the box.
</P>
<P>
   - Make copies of everything. If the rebate disappears, you'll
have nothing to go on if you mailed off the originals and didn't
make copies.
</P>
<P>
   - Does the rebate offer require the original receipt? If so,
make sure the retail store will accept a copy of your receipt as
proof of purchase should you have to return the product.
</P>
<P>
   - If the rebate never materializes, contact the retail store.
They might not even know that their customers are having problems
with the rebates. Another reason to call is the chance that the
store might step in and pay you your rebate if it doesn't come
after a reasonable period.
</P>
<P>
   - If you run into problems, keep good records of every effort
you make to resolve the issue. Note any phone calls, letters or
other steps you take.
</P>
<P>
   - If trying to resolve a rebate problem, make sure you are
calling the correct place or sending e-mail to the correct person.
Misdirected communication is often ignored.
</P>
<P>
   - Don't hesitate to contact authorities if you feel you have
been defrauded. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Hoye can be reached at dhoye(at)home.net by e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
