<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GOP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA GOP STRUGGLES TO RETAIN WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ ``It's the women, stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Battered by the November elections, the California Republican
Party spent much of its weekend convention trying to figure out
where all the women had gone.
</P>
<P>
   The most prominent woman in national politics, Elizabeth Dole,
didn't show up here because of a scheduling conflict. But the
problems for the party run deeper than just getting Dole to
Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular political paraphernalia at the state convention
was a tiny yellow sticker plastered to blouses, shirts and sport
coats everywhere. It read: ``It's the women, stupid.'' A special
90-minute seminar focused on the issue Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: Many Republicans here are fearful that another open
fight over abortion rights will alienate more women. In the
November gubernatorial election in California, the Democratic
candidate, Gray Davis, won 61 percent of all women voters and sent
the GOP candidate, Dan Lungren, to a resounding defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Davis' huge lead among women can be tied to
Lungren's anti-abortion views, although Davis also focused on
issues such as education and health care and Lungren ran a largely
scattered, unfocused campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican Party needs to lighten up and liven up,'' said
Julie Leitzell of Larkspur, a partner in Common Sense Activism, a
group that tries to get media attention on GOP issues that she says
appeal to ``soccer moms with brains.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to appeal to women on education issues,'' she said.
``Our kids can't spell, they can't add. If the Republican Party
can't figure out how to get that issue on the front page with the
disaster (in education) that is happening to California, the party
is doomed.''
</P>
<P>
   Among high-ranking elected Republican officials in California,
only 8 percent are women, compared to 35 percent among Democrats.
There are no highly visible Republican women from California, with
the exception of Rep. Mary Bono of Palm Springs, who succeeded her
husband, Sonny Bono, when he died in a skiing accident last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are not identifying with the party,'' said Beth Rogers,
president of the Seneca Network, the New York organization that
raises money for Republican candidates who are women. ``We maintain
that you can never be a majority party in an era when you have one
party that is half men and half women (Democrats), and another
party that is all men. Women are sensing this.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers and other Republican women say linking the party's
failure simply to abortion is too simplistic. Women identify with
candidates on all sorts of issues, they said, and focusing on a yes
or no answer when it comes to abortion masks what the debate is
truly about: women don't want men in power to tell them what they
can or cannot do.
</P>
<P>
   Despite calls to take a more moderate path, state Republicans
ended their convention Sunday by electing the most conservative
anti-abortion candidates to lead them.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,200 state GOP delegates voted to elect Silicon Valley
executive John McGraw their new chairman. McGraw drew fire from
moderates in the party for telling a Catholic newsletter that
``killing our babies ... is the issue of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   But McGraw pledged to unite the party.
</P>
<P>
   Some women contend that the party that stands for less
government intervention in personal lives ought to be wary of
government involvement in abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They talk about less government,'' said Debra Madison, a
Sacramento artist and self-described centrist Democrat who attended
the convention. ``But I think to legislate what a woman would do on
abortion is creating huge government ... It's the one big problem I
have with the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that Republicans are having trouble attracting all
sorts of diverse groups. Only a few blacks and Hispanics were
spotted at the state convention. Some believe reaching women is the
first step to regaining control in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is focusing on the Hispanic, Asian and
African-American vote,'' Rogers said. ``That's the new market for
the party. But we keep saying that Asians, Latin-Americans and
African-Americans come in boys and girls.''
</P>
</TEXT>
