<SLUG> BC-GAY-HOTEL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENOVATED HOTEL IS FIRST IN GALVESTON TO CATER TO GAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KEVIN MORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALVESTON, Texas _ The first hotel catering solely to gay and
lesbian visitors is scheduled to open on Seawall Boulevard here
this spring.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-room inn is called Hollywood at Galveston, and each room
will recall legends of entertainment, such as Marilyn Monroe, Clark
Gable, Lucille Ball and Desi Arnaz, owners Sherman Houck and Bob
Wilkins said. The decor will include unusual furnishings, such as a
huge kettle drum made into a table.
</P>
<P>
   Houck and Wilkins, longtime Baytown, Texas, residents, will be
resident managers of the inn, a two-story, 1946 building formerly
known as the Silver Sands Hotel. The inn, at Seawall Boulevard and
30th Street, was ragged and rundown when it closed several years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a number of homeless people living in the building
when we bought it,'' Wilkins said. ``There was garbage and trash
all over and green slime in the pool.''
</P>
<P>
   Mother Nature hasn't helped much since the men purchased the
building in December 1997 and began the tedious restoration job. In
September, Tropical Storm Frances, which caused heavy erosion along
Galveston's West Beach, also caused the collapse of an exterior
wall of the building.
</P>
<P>
   Houck and Wilkins decline to say how much money they have put
into the project, but they said that it already is more than they
had planned.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels serving gay tourists and business travelers are not new
in the country, they said. Their idea for such a resort in
Galveston was born after they saw the 250-room Habana Inn resort in
Oklahoma City, run by a friend's relative and catering to gay
travelers, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just happen to be the first one on the island,'' Houck
said.
</P>
<P>
   At least two other Texas inns _ the Montrose Inn in Houston and
The Upper Deck on South Padre Island _ have catered to gay
travelers for years, Wilkins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gay people spend $20 billion a year on travel,'' he said.
``Gay people have considerable disposable income.''
</P>
<P>
   He named Florida and Palm Springs, Calif., as two areas where
many hotels cater to gay crowds, and noted that cruise lines
schedule numerous exclusively gay trips.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is that what's noteworthy here is the fact that
we're renovating an old building in Galveston,'' Wilkins said,
adding that virtually all of the building's original interior
woodwork has been preserved.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the Galveston project has spread quickly in gay circles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've probably got 150 or 200 people on a waiting list who are
anxiously awaiting our opening,'' Wilkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Some people on the list who have visited Galveston recently have
stopped by to check progress, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A rainbow banner, symbolic of gay pride, has adorned the old inn
since work began early last year and, except for a couple of
hostile notes to the inn's Web site, the plans for the property
have elicited no significant complaints, Houck and Wilkins said.
</P>
<P>
   While the inn's pool area was walled off from view from the
seawall, Wilkins said it is unlikely that the pool area will be
clothing-optional because he and Houck expect a mixed male and
female clientele. Guests will have a great view of the Gulf of
Mexico and activity along busy Seawall Boulevard from the
second-floor deck of the inn.
</P>
<P>
   The Hollywood will be a place where gay people can feel
completely comfortable holding hands and showing affection, the
owners said.
</P>
<P>
   Guests will have key cards to enter electronically controlled
outer doors to the property; other people will be screened before
they are admitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're targeting gay couples, such as Bob and I, who have been
together several years and who really enjoy traveling where they
can feel comfortable,'' Houck said. ``Gay couples have been
visiting Galveston Island for years and years and years.''
</P>
<P>
   Late March is the target opening. Room rates will run from about
$70 on weeknights to about $120 on weekends, Wilkins said. Winter
weekday rates may be lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the sun's out on weekends, people come out of the
woodwork to Galveston,'' Wilkins said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
