<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIRD-NAME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHT TO NAME JUST-DISCOVERED BIRD TO BE AUCTIONED OFF, BUT NOT FOR
SONG 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost three years after a Texas naturalist discovered it in
Brazil's Amazon rain forest, the colorful little bird with the big
voice still lacks a name.
</P>
<P>
   Soon that is expected to change.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday in Fort Worth, the Texas Audubon Society will mark its
100th anniversary by auctioning rights to name the new-found
antshrike.
</P>
<P>
   But that privilege will cost a lot of bird seed _ bidding starts
at $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The winning bidder will have an indelible link to a living
organism,'' said Brett Whitney, who discovered the bird in Brazil's
western Acre state in July 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from Brazil, Whitney said, ``This is a
way to honor significant contributors to conservation. It's like a
person who contributes a large sum to a hospital and then has a
wing of a building named after him.''
</P>
<P>
   The winning bidder may name the bird for whomever he pleases.
``They can name it for their dog or their grandmother,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   John James Audubon, the 19th-century naturalist and artist for
whom the society is named, frequently named birds in honor of his
friends' children.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no intrinsic value in the name,'' added Noreen
Damude, bird conservation director for Texas Audubon. ``But the
namer will be immortalized. As long as there are birds and
ornithology, the name and the story of who gave it its name will be
in the literature.''
</P>
<P>
   Also to go on the auction block at the society's centennial gala
will be birding tours, a set of bird prints by Fort Worth artists
Stuart and Scott Gentling, birdhouses and feeders and other bird
paraphernalia.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Audubon Society was founded in March 1899 by two
Galveston women who were eager to rescue birds from the altar of
fashion. Women's hats of the era bristled with feathers.
</P>
<P>
   Today, said spokeswoman Pamela McCroskery, the organization
claims 40,000 members in 20 chapters statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney, 43, trained in biology and co-owner of an Austin
eco-tourism agency, discovered the new antshrike while surveying
wildlife with Brazilian bird experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in a very poorly explored region about three days from
the nearest settlement,'' he said. ``We had traveled down shallow
rivers into the rain forest, and had camped on a ridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I awoke at the crack of dawn to the song of a bird I couldn't
recognize. I'm acknowledged as an expert in bird song, and this one
was very unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitney _ who previously had discovered unknown birds in South
America and Madagascar _ tape-recorded the song, then played it
back to lure the bird into sight.
</P>
<P>
   Within a day, he had captured two birds. The 7-inch-long male
was blue-gray, while the female was splashed with orange from
throat to belly. Both had dramatically hooked beaks for capturing
insects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often, people think they have discovered a new species only to
later find that it already had been recorded,'' Whitney said.
``There was no way a specimen of this bird was lying around in some
museum. It was too distinctive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very emotional experience for me. This was
tremendously exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, discoverers of new species name them when they
report their findings in scholarly journals. Whitney assigned
naming rights to the Audubon Society to promote its conservation
efforts. The winning bidder will designate the bird's formal Latin
name and suggest a popular English name.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the top bidder will receive a tape-recording of its
song, photographs and a painting of the bird.
</P>
<P>
   Damude said three-fourths of the money raised through the
auction of the bird's name will be used to finance her group's
Texas Important Bird Areas Program.
</P>
<P>
   Through that effort, Audubon officials hope to identify critical
habitats of many of the 613 bird species that live in or pass
through Texas and work with private and public landowners to
preserve them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a completely voluntary program,'' Damude said, noting
that her organization's role largely will be providing preservation
expertise. ``There is no pressure, no regulation. My experience is
that land owners are proud of their land, their native animals and
plants. It's the joy of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``For them and us, this could be a win/win situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The auction will be 6 to 9 p.m. CST Friday at the Bass
Performance Hall in Fort Worth. Out-of-town residents may submit
bids by telephone by calling (512) 426-5768 during the hours of the
auction.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
