<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIRED-GUN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDERCOVER TEXAS `HIT MAN' SNARES THE DESPERATE IN THEIR OWN WEBS
OF EVIL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE BREWER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Want somebody dead?
</P>
<P>
   If so, Gary F. Johnson wants your business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I offer them not only a quick solution,'' Johnson says, ``but
I promise them they won't get caught.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a catch, however. Johnson is a senior investigator for
the Harris County district attorney's office who specializes in the
undercover art of posing as a hit man in the Houston area. Go to
him with a problem and you could end up wishing you were dead.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, Johnson has played the role of hired killer
in more than 300 cases. Just 57 of them have resulted in
convictions, but he says that's because many people aren't serious
or come to their senses and back out before it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   The ones who didn't are now in prison, providing Johnson with a
list of grim anecdotes, some funny, some sad.
</P>
<P>
   Jealous husbands and wives, scorned lovers, bitter ex-spouses,
disgruntled business partners, people looking to get rich or get
rid of a witness, gang members and drug dealers wanting to send a
message to a rival or a snitch. Whether they're from the affluent
River Oaks area in Houston or a trailer park they all have one
thing in common _ desperation.
</P>
<P>
   Some have offered big money, family heirlooms and other
valuables. One woman who had embezzled $1 million needed a business
associate dead. She offered Johnson an expensive racing boat that
had been reported stolen in an insurance scam.
</P>
<P>
   Others have offered next to nothing. One teen offered him three
$1 bills, $2 in change and some old Atari video games to kill a
former classmate he thought might one day date a girl whom he might
want to date.
</P>
<P>
   There was another teen who offered a cheap stereo and whatever
money he could raise if Johnson would choke his mom, revive her,
choke her, revive her, and so on until finally strangling her, so
she would ``die five or six times.''
</P>
<P>
   Coy Wayne Wesbrook, who killed five people in November 1998 and
is now on death row, told a cellmate as his capital murder trial
started last summer that he needed a hit man to kill five people
for him, including three witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Wesbrook's cellmate talked to authorities and led him to believe
that Johnson would kill the five for nothing because he owed the
cellmate a favor.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Johnson and Wesbrook talked on the phone and Wesbrook set
up the deal. But their conversations were taped, and then used in
Wesbrook's trial.
</P>
<P>
   Contracting a hit with someone you've never met, maybe through a
cellmate you've just met, may seem illogical and desperate, but
Johnson says it is not atypical of his ``clients.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``We want something and we want it now. We hire somebody to
pick up our garbage, and we hire people to fix our TVs,'' Johnson
said. ``We want our problems solved now. And when people become
frustrated, their cognitive skills diminish. They become blind to
other options.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just concerned with eliminating the pain in their
life, whatever it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Johnson knows how to handle those people and can deliver
a good case without entrapment, he's in high demand from
authorities in Texas and other states.
</P>
<P>
   The former Louisiana and Port Arthur, Texas, lawman has a
master's degree in psychology and knows what juries want and what
makes defense attorneys wince, prosecutors say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary is always thinking of the courtroom while he's playing
the undercover role,'' said Ted Wilson, chief of the district
attorney's office major offenders division. ``He knows what a jury
is going to have to decide and always keeps that in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who has been with the district attorney's office since
1981, says he follows some simple rules:
</P>
<P>
   _ The person always has to come to him. Whether first contact is
made through a snitch or an undercover officer for another agency,
Johnson never makes the first call.
</P>
<P>
   _ He doesn't make the hit seem so risk-free or appealing that
the person couldn't possibly refuse. The target gets lots of
chances to back out.
</P>
<P>
   _ And Johnson, an expert in high-tech surveillance, videotapes
or records every meeting with a target. That leaves nothing to
chance in court, and jurors are often treated to dialogue usually
heard only in bad movies.
</P>
<P>
   Like the time an offshore oil worker wanted his wife dead. He
had taken her to a clinic and told doctors she was suicidal, though
she wasn't. He then hired Johnson to slit her wrists and comfort
her as she died.
</P>
<P>
   Then the husband, with a solid alibi provided by his work, was
going to claim the insurance money and sue the clinic that said she
wasn't suicidal.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said Johnson does so well because he doesn't talk too
much, ``a rookie mistake.'' He lets the clients do most of the
talking, doesn't intimidate them and projects an understanding,
sympathetic demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   That's important, Wilson says, because a defense attorney might
argue that a client became afraid that if he didn't go through with
the scheme, Johnson would turn on him.
</P>
<P>
   When he's being himself, Johnson is polite, thoughtful and
humorous, a thin man who looks nothing like your stereotypical
thug. He admits to being a bit eccentric, and his dark office is
full of enough high-tech electronics to make a 14-year-old drool.
During a recent visit, Willie Nelson was singing in the background.
</P>
<P>
   But adjust the clothes, change the attitude and Johnson looks
like a character you might meet in an Elmore Leonard novel, the
perfect undercover man, with a forgettable face and a low-key
manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the most nondescript person in the world,'' he said. ``I'm
the guy who goes to a party and people don't even know I was
there.''
</P>
<P>
   When he has to testify, Johnson slips in and out of the
courthouse without making a ripple. He does his bit on the stand,
then melts into the group of troubled souls who walk the halls.
</P>
<P>
   And he makes sure his face doesn't show up on the television
news or in the newspaper. The reason should be obvious _ he never
knows what his next role will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I adapt to different situations well. It's a rush,'' he said.
``It's the closest to being in the zone that you can get. You know
you're a good undercover officer if they don't clap. If they
applaud, you're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean Johnson can't have a little fun. One man had
tried, in vain, to beat someone to death with a metal pipe and was
out on bail. He wanted Johnson to finish the job.
</P>
<P>
   So there was no mistake, Johnson told an intermediary to have
the man meet him in a diner, where he would be at the counter
eating a piece of pie.
</P>
<P>
   ``That looks like good pie,'' the man would say.
</P>
<P>
   ``All pie is good pie,'' was Johnson's prearranged response.
Then, they would talk business.
</P>
<P>
   And it happened just that way. Just like in a bad movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe he said it,'' Johnson said. ``I wanted to
laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a pro, he didn't. The man offered him $1,500 for the job
and more if he wasn't questioned by police. The man was arrested
later.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson says the work has also reinforced some of life's grimmer
lessons, especially how low the human soul can creep.
</P>
<P>
   One girl offered him her grandfather's wedding band if he would
kill a woman who was dating her ex-boyfriend. Nothing special about
that, but she insisted that Johnson should also kill the woman's
baby.
</P>
<P>
   The girl explained to Johnson that she was trying to consider
the best interests of the child. After all, with mom dead, the baby
would be an orphan.
</P>
<P>
   ``She also offered me $80 of her child-support money if she
could watch,'' Johnson said. ``It was the first time I think I was
ever offered a bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
