so many presidential candidates find appalling? It's
``compassionate conservatism.'' By Michael Kranish. 1340 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BLACKS-JAILED (Undated) _ By the Millennium, roughly 1 in 10
black men will not have a job or pay taxes, or be a father to their
children. What is most alarming, say specialists, is the disparity
between the number of whites and blacks in prison has widened
dramatically. By Louise D. Palmer. 1385 words. GRAPHIC: 25 picas x
5 inches, ``Prison population.''
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-HATRED (Westwood, Mass.) _ He grew up as Andrew
Greenbaum, a small, shy kid. Then he became Davis Wolfgang Hawke,
designed a chilling web page, and founded the neo-Nazi Knights of
Freedom. By Thomas Farragher. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   PRESIDENCY-BUCHANAN (Manchester, N.H.) _ When Pat Buchanan
announces a third run for president, his style will be familiar,
but his staff, many now working for Steve Forbes, won't. By Jill
Zuckman. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL-TOUCH (Undated) _ In the age of chain-store blandness,
the ``personal touch'' is making a suspiciously timed comeback in
retail stores and service outlets. By Peter S. Canellos. 1235
words.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINES-PASSENGERS (Undated) -- The seeming stampede of
politicians trying to enact legislation ensuring that airline
passengers are treated with respect is causing angst in airline
board rooms. By Matthew Brelis. 1630 words.
</P>
