 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of TUESDAY, March
2:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FASHION &LR;  (``l'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MILAN-FASHION (Milan) _ Review of Milan fashion collections by
D&AMP;G, Versus, Philosophy, Narciso Rodriguez, Emporio Armani,
Laurence Steel and Prada. By Cathy Horyn.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   PATTERNS-FASHION (Undated) _ News and notes on fashion. By
Constance White.
</P>
<P>
   PATTERNS-FASHION (Undated) _ Milan designers, counting on a cold
winter the end of this year, are showing warm woolly scarves,
turtlenecks and high funnel necklines. A short, by Anne-Marie
Schiro.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other fashion
stories from our partners: Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox
News Service, Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona
Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles
Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NEW-PLANETS (Undated) _ At last count, astronomers in the
United States and Europe have observed 18 nearby sunlike stars
showing telltale motions from the gravity of large, unseen planets
orbiting them, and they fully expect to find more. Yet they suspect
they have seen enough to begin rethinking how nature creates and
destroys planets and choreographs their orbital minuets. By John
Noble Wilford. (2350 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SMOKING-CESSATION (Undated) _ A new approach combining an
anti-depressant, nicotine-replacement and counseling is sharply
increasing the chance of success of people who are trying to give
up smoking. By Holcomb B. Noble.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LOWCOST-ROCKETS (Washington) _ An experimental rocket that
is at the heart of NASA's plans to develop a low-cost, reusable
vehicle that might eventually replace the space shuttle has fallen
more than a year behind schedule for its first flight because of
mounting technical problems. By Warren E. Leary. (1625 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EARLIER-SPRINGS (Undated) _ Separate studies using different
methods in the last three years have found that as the earth's
atmosphere warms, spring is arriving earlier and autumn is coming
later in the Northern Hemisphere. But much of the evidence has been
indirect. Now a direct examination of the actual behavior of plants
across Europe appears to confirm the earlier findings. By William
K. Stevens. (1220 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FEAR (Undated) _ An examination of what psychologists call
the fearful by nature. It's not a disease, but a temperamental
flavor. An essay by Natalie Angier. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Short items on science: preparing air,
food and water in space; carbon dioxide around a moon of Jupiter; a
tough new glass. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column:
Researchers have discovered that many elderly people suffer health
problems because of bad nutrition. Partly as result, the Department
of Agriculture has devised a food pyramid for people over 70. By
Jane E. Brody. (1300 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OCTUPLETS-EYES (Undated) _ Doctors treating the seven
remaining octuplets are on the lookout for retinopathy of
prematurity, a condition that could leave them blind. While they
are all doing well, the status of their eyesight will be in doubt
for weeks. Doctors are using lasers to help prevent the retina from
detaching, but that carries the risk of limiting the victim's side
vision. By Lawrence K. Altman. (1675 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CIRCUMCISION (Undated) _ The American Academy of Pediatrics,
which issued a new circumcision policy yesterday, has had three
different policies in as many decades. In the 1970s, the academy
said there was no ``medical indication'' for circumcision. In 1989,
it reported ``potential medical benefits.'' Now, the 55,000-member
academy has concluded that while there are potential benefits, the
data are ``not significant enough'' to recommend routine
circumcision. By Deborah Stead.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-BLACKS (Undated) _ Ministers and imams in conservative
denominations with black parishes are beginning to talk about AIDS
to their congregations, though in limited ways. By Nadine Brozan.
(1233 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ Shorts on health and fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ A new study suggests that tangeretin, a flavonoid in citrus
fruits as well as in certain processed foods and dietary
supplements, may sometimes be harmful because it negates the
benefits of tamoxifen, the breast cancer drug. The finding came as
a surprise, since in vitro studies showed that tangeretin acted
like tamoxifen to inhibit mammary cancer cells. (400 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Although mouth guards can prevent dental injuries that occur
during contact sports, a University of Minnesota study says that
few athletes are wearing them. (275 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science questions answered: How can we get
rid of the crows that have invaded the big garden in our city
apartment complex, where we used to get songbirds? ``Short of
exterminating all the crows in town, there is not much chance.''
(300 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BREAST-CANCER (Undated) _ The American Cancer Society and
the National Comprehensive Cancer Network have published
breast-cancer treatment guidelines that they say are the first ones
specifically written to give patients information on
``gold-standard cancer treatment.'' By Denise Grady. (550 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (``e'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-HOUELLEBECQ (Paris) _ A profile of Michel Houellebecq,
enfant terrible of French literature. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   EARTHA-KITT (New York) _ She slithers across the stage at the
Cafe Carlyle, catlike, 72 years old, with the muscles of an
adolescent boy _ Eartha Kitt, whom Orson Welles called ``the most
exciting woman in the world'' and the CIA reportedly called ``a
sadistic sex nymphomaniac,'' after she stood up at a White House
luncheon and criticized the war in Vietnam. A profile by Dinitia
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   LECARRE-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Single and Single,'' by John
LeCarre (Scribners). Reviewed by Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
<P>
   TV-STOLEN-REVIEW (Undated) _ On PBS, ``Stolen Years'';
first-person accounts by 11 people who survived Stalin's labor
camps. Reviewed by Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS &LR;  (``s'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ARATON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column. By Harvey
Araton.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-KNICKS-CAVS (New York) _ Cleveland at the Knicks, 7:30 p.m.
ET start. By Mike Wise.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-NETS-CELTICS (Boston) _ N.J. Nets at Boston, 7 p.m. ET
start. By Chris Broussard.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-REPORT (Undated) _ A ``culture of gift-giving'' starting at
the top of the Olympics led to the biggest scandal in the history
of the games, an elite ethics panel said Monday. A commission
headed by George Mitchell, the former Senate Democratic leader,
said reform was needed from the International Olympic Committee on
down to avoid a repeat of the million-dollar bribery case that has
tarnished Salt Lake City's winning bid for the 2002 Winter Games.
By Richard Sandomir.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other stories
from our partners: Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox News
Service, Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona
Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles
Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
