<SLUG> BC-MATH-CONTEST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATH COMES EASILY FOR THESE HUMAN CALCULATORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ They looked like typical middle school students
_ baggy jeans, mouths full of metal and impossible to quiet down in
the cafeteria. No pocket protectors or taped-up glasses.
</P>
<P>
   But watch out if they tackle a math problem. And no calculators,
please.
</P>
<P>
   What is the square root of 120 times the square root of 30? It
took seconds for the kid to come up with the correct answer: 60.
</P>
<P>
   The annual MathCounts competition Saturday pitted teams from 10
public, parochial and private middle schools in San Francisco in
grueling and fast-paced tests of logic, skill and strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The competition has been sponsored by the National Society of
Professional Engineers since 1983. The top two teams, plus an
all-star team made up of the top four individuals, will go onto the
state competition next month at the University of California at
Davis. If successful, they could then proceed to the nationals in
May in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Vadim Keyfes, an eighth-grader at Presidio Middle School, said
he likes the logic of math.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always the same. One plus one is always two,'' he said.
``It's not like literature.''
</P>
<P>
   The morning session, which included 20 minutes for the team to
solve 10 problems and 40 minutes for individuals to solve 30
problems, can be humbling, said Armen Sedrakian, math teacher at
Presidio Middle School.
</P>
<P>
   ``The students come out shell-shocked,'' he said. ``Everybody
thinks they did terribly.''
</P>
<P>
   Calculate this: What is the sum of the two least prime numbers
greater than 100? Answer: 204.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're used to being the smartest'' at their school, said
Richard Meyers, the math coach from Visitacion Valley Middle
School. ``Suddenly they realize there's more out there.''
</P>
<P>
   While many of the students prepared for the contest all school
year, few admitted to any special pre-competition rituals.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Luo of A.P. Giannini Middle School honed his mind Saturday
morning with television. ``I watched cartoons,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His team came in first place.
</P>
<P>
   Bryce MacMartin, an eighth-grader at San Francisco Community
School, said he did a chant with a couple teammates to prepare
himself mentally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said `Get pumped!' and slapped each other in the chest,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He came in third place in the afternoon round.
</P>
<P>
   Rena Kuliyeva, an eighth-grader at Giannini Middle School, knew
her strengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like geometry with triangles and I like equations, but I
don't like prime numbers or probability,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
