<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICHELLE-PFEIFFER-IN-THE-DEEP-END-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHELLE PFEIFFER AND A MOTHER'S NIGHTMARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Michelle Pfeiffer with Treat Williams in
a scene from ``The Deep End of the Ocean.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Michelle Pfeiffer was 5 when she disappeared.
 &HT;    It was midnight in Santa Ana, Calif., and the prettiest little
girl on the block had decided to go for a walk. Alone.
 &HT;    ``I remember I loved being at my neighbor's house down the
street,'' the actress recalls, ``so I went over there determined to
wake up my little friends. The children answered the door, and I
asked them to hide me so my parents wouldn't find out what I had
done.''
 &HT;    The Pfeiffers were having a poker party that night, but almost
instinctively Michelle's mother decided to check on the oldest of
her four children.
 &HT;    ``My mom saw my empty bed,'' Pfeiffer recalls, ``and she was
literally in a panic.''
 &HT;    It was 1963, but a missing child was no less heart-stopping than
today. But a quick search of the block produced a sleepy, smiling
Michelle, who promised never again to go visiting on her own.
 &HT;    Over coffee on an early morning at Los Angeles' Four Seasons
Hotel, Pfeiffer looks back on the incident wistfully.
 &HT;    ``As much as I scared my folks that night,'' she says, ``I still
don't think my parents had the same fears I have now. As a child, I
would run barefoot through my neighborhood. I could knock on any
neighbor's door and not be afraid. My kids can't do that, which is
sad.''
 &HT;    A disappearing child figures in Pfeiffer's new film ``The Deep
End of the Ocean'' opening March 12. Based on Jacqueline Mitchard's
best-selling book, it stars Pfeiffer _ who also co-produced the
film _ as a young mother whose child vanishes in a crowded hotel
lobby, not to be seen again for years.
 &HT;    Pfeiffer admits that acting out every mother's worst nightmare
made her heart pound.
 &HT;    ``When I decided to do this movie, I had to allow myself to go
beyond that point where as a mother you say, `What if?''' the
actress says. ``It was actually so unpleasant for those first few
weeks of shooting that I really questioned why I chose to do this
at all.
 &HT;    ``After all, I am the mother who walked out halfway through the
movie `Ransom' because I couldn't take it anymore.''
 &HT;    The effect has lingered for Pfeiffer, who is married to
television producer/writer David E. Kelley, creator of ``The
Practice'' and ``Ally McBeal,'' and has two children.
 &HT;    ``A few weeks after filming the scene where Ben disappears, I
was in a store and I told our 6-year-old daughter Claudia to hold
our 4-year-old son John's hand,'' she recalls. ``Suddenly I had a
cold chill _ I realized this was the exact line from the movie.
`Hold his hand.'
 &HT;    ``Now, after doing this movie, I never let my kids out of my
sight,'' she says. ``I think I've become a bit paranoid.''
 &HT;    If expert opinion counts for anything, ``Deep End of the Ocean''
ought to do well: An industry magazine recently named Pfeiffer as
the female star who has the most appeal at the box office. Not bad
for a former supermarket-checkout girl and beauty queen who first
caught the public eye parading around in hotpants in ``Grease 2''
(1982).
 &HT;    ``My new ranking raises a few eyebrows, don't you think?''
Pfeiffer says bemusedly. ``I mean, when they say highest-paid
actress in Hollywood, it's not me. It's Julia or Jodie.
 &HT;    ``I think they sort of figured out whose movies never make
money,'' she says, laughing. ``And then they looked at me and said,
`Hey, she's still doing fairly well. She's still here.'''
 &HT;    And how. Her upcoming projects include ``A Midsummer's Night
Dream,'' with Kevin Kline and Calista Flockhart, due out this
spring. She's currently filming ``The Story of Us,'' a comedy about
a marriage on the rocks which co-stars Bruce Willis. Next up is
``What Lies Beneath,'' a supernatural thriller with Harrison Ford.
 &HT;    ``I'm over 40,'' she says with a laugh. ``Can you imagine? I
didn't think Hollywood allows women all this good fortune when you
hit that number.''
 &HT;    It represents an almost-literal dream come true for Pfeiffer,
who had wanted to be an actress since even before she won a Miss
Orange County beauty pageant.
 &HT;    ``I remember working at that supermarket, knowing that I wanted
to do something else,'' she recalls. ``I knew that, of everything
in the world, acting was what I wanted to do, although it seemed
like a ridiculous dream at the time. But I thought, `Why not?' I
was naive enough not realize the kind of hurdle I was trying to
climb.''
 &HT;    The road to success included ``embarrassing TV shows'' such as
``Delta House'' (1979) and ``movies that were even worse,''
including ``The Hollywood Knights'' (1980).
 &HT;    ``I think the real turning point for me was when I did a TV
movie called `The Children Nobody Wanted' (1981),'' she says. ``It
was the first project where I couldn't wear any makeup and had to
look as bad as possible. That was huge for me _ I was actually
hired for my acting ability and not my looks.
 &HT;    ``And then I did `Grease 2,' which gave me exposure _ for better
or worse.'' She sighs. ``That movie made me vow to never wear
hotpants in public again.''
 &HT;    Movies including ``Scarface'' (1983), ``The Witches of
Eastwick'' (1987), ``Married to the Mob'' (1988), ``The Fabulous
Baker Boys'' (1989) and ``Batman Returns'' (1992) put Pfeiffer on
the map, and suddenly she was an A-list star.
 &HT;    ``The bad part of becoming a movie star is that I'm still shy,''
she says. ``It is still hard for me to overcome my fear of
strangers. I remember early on my publicist telling me, `Michelle,
don't run from the press _ it makes it worse. Just stand there and
let them take your picture.'
 &HT;    ``Meanwhile, I would be hyperventilating thinking, `OK, OK, OK.'
And then I would literally run. I wanted to run away.''
 &HT;    Nowadays, Pfeiffer says, the tabloids leave her alone.
 &HT;    ``I'm married, which equals `boring' for them,'' she says with a
laugh.
 &HT;    Her marriage to Kelley followed a failed first marriage to Peter
Horton (Gary on ``Thirtysomething''), as well as relationships with
Michael Keaton, John Malkovich and Fisher Stevens. Pfeiffer also
briefly dated Eric Clapton and Val Kilmer.
 &HT;    Then she met Kelley on a blind date.
 &HT;    ``I just knew. Of course, I didn't know right away, because
David didn't talk on our blind date and I didn't talk,'' she says,
laughing. ``So it took awhile for us to get to know each other. But
he's very internal, just like me. People might think David doesn't
like them, but he's just an observer.''
 &HT;    In 1993, Pfeiffer adopted Claudia as a single mother. Two weeks
later, friends invited to Claudia's christening got an extra
surprise: Kelley and Pfeiffer's wedding vows.
 &HT;    ``My family all sort of came together at once,'' the actress
says with a laugh. ``Suddenly we were this team.''
 &HT;    Amid the challenges of combining two high-powered careers with
parenthood, Pfeiffer says that her 40th birthday passed virtually
unnoticed.
 &HT;    ``For me, I think turning 39 was actually a little worse,'' she
says. ``It was the anticipation. I spent the next year agonizing
over it, but then 40 came and I was over it.''
 &HT;    Of course, it helps that she looks better than most
30-year-olds.
 &HT;    ``Oh, I look in the mirror and see a little line here or
there,'' she says, smiling. ``For a working mother, I think I'm
holding up pretty well.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR;
