w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BILLY-JOEL-IN-THE-ROC     03-01 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILLY-JOEL-IN-THE-ROCK-HALL-OF-FAME-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILLY JOEL: IT'S STILL ROCK 'N' ROLL, BUT HE'S LOOKING FOR MORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of rock singer/songwriter Billy Joel. 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Billy Joel has had his share of idols and musical inspirations
since he started writing songs more than three decades ago. You can
guess most of them _ Jerry Lee Lewis, Elvis Presley, Ray Charles,
John Lennon.
 &HT;    But these days, the 49-year-old musician finds a more appealing
model in the composer George Gershwin.
 &HT;    ``He wrote a lot of great popular music and then turned to
writing classical music, and then continued to write popular songs
very, very well,'' Joel explains.
 &HT;    ``I don't think he felt one genre couldn't live without the
other,'' he adds. ``I think you have to go with what you're
feeling. If I was motivated to write a lot of songs right now, I
definitely would not stop myself _ I'd go with it. But at the
moment I'm inspired to write this kind of music.''
 &HT;    ``This kind of music'' is all-instrumental, classically oriented
piano pieces that the Piano Man has been working on for the past
four years. What began as an experiment has become an obsession,
and in 1997 Joel surprised his fans by announcing that he had given
up writing lyric-driven pop songs in favor of sweeping instrumental
melodies.
 &HT;    And now the man who on March 15 will be inducted into the Rock
and Roll Hall of Fame is enjoying the best of both worlds. While he
hasn't produced a pop song since 1993 _ when he wrote the
ironically titled ``Famous Last Words'' _ he continues to dust off
his past hits for periodic concert tours while devoting his
creative energies to classical music.
 &HT;    ``I used to get the same kick out of writing a song,'' he says.
``As the years went on, I started getting frustrated by the
confinements of pop songwriting. You can't develop a melody more
than a certain amount of notes before you end the first verse and
you've got to start the second verse. There are time constraints,
attention spans. There are certain instruments that define it as
rock 'n' roll.
 &HT;    ``None of that has anything to do with composition except for
basic, basic composition,'' Joel says. ``And it became frustrating.
I want to take a melody and see how far I can develop it ... as
opposed to thinking `How is this going to be sung?' or if it's
going to be played on the radio or do I have to make a video?''
 &HT;    The Long Island-born Joel, who gave up boxing as a youth to
pursue the musical ambitions that launched him to stardom with the
multi-million-selling album, ``The Stranger'' (1977) _ says that
he's finished about eight classical pieces so far.
 &HT;    Stylistically, most of them draw on mid-19th-century
romanticism, he says, ``which is really where most songwriters
hearken back to, anyway, in terms of the kinds of melodies we
write. I think we all go back to Schubert.''
 &HT;    So far, he adds, the joy has been in the composing of his new
music rather than performing or recording it. In fact, despite
frequent inquiries from his record company and various orchestras,
he has no current plans to have the music performed at all.
 &HT;    ``It's the writing of it that's jazzing me,'' Joel says. ``I'm
not necessarily the guy to perform this stuff _ although it would
make it easier for Columbia Records to market it if I was
performing it.
 &HT;    ``I think the best way to have it presented, if I'm going to
present it at all, would be to have a hired gun, a pistolero,
somebody who is classically trained,'' he adds. ``I am not by any
stretch of the imagination an accomplished virtuoso concert
pianist. In rock 'n' roll, I'm great _ but in terms of classical
music, I stink.''
 &HT;    For the record, Joel actually has written one pop song during
the past year. Inspired by his past sojourns in France, it was
called ``Champs d'Elysee.'' But his enthusiasm for it was quashed
when he brought it in to rehearsal and his guitarist looked at it
and said, ``Are we doing a song called `The Champ's Eyelashes?'''
 &HT;    ``You can't beat that,'' Joel says with a laugh. ``No matter
what I ended up writing about, it will forever be known as `The
Champ's Eyelashes.' It was kind of a wake-up call _ I might as well
be writing about the champ's eyelashes.''
 &HT;    But Joel's new musical path doesn't mean he's abandoning his old
repertoire. His entire catalog was recently remastered and
reissued, with video clips added to the enhanced CDs. And Joel has
no problem singing those songs on tour, even if his new material is
of an entirely different ilk.
 &HT;    Actually, he says, assembling a good touring show is an art of
its own, involving a balancing act between popular hits and the
music that he or his musicians may more enjoy playing.
 &HT;    ``I think you have to do a certain amount of songs that the
audience would be disappointed if you don't do, like `Piano Man'
and a couple of other known songs,'' he says.
 &HT;    ``What makes for a good cohesive show is a certain amount of
songs that are familiar, a certain amount of songs that are purely
indulgent on the musicians' part and then the songs that hold
everything together,'' Joel adds. ``There has to be a tradeoff _
you can't just do every single song that only the audience wants. I
think you've got to balance it.''
 &HT;    Not that Joel doesn't appreciate his hits, the 30-something Top
40 favorites such as ``Only the Good Die Young,'' ``Just the Way
You Are,'' ``My Life'' and ``It's Still Rock and Roll to Me'' that
have led to nearly 100 million albums sold worldwide and, of
course, the Hall of Fame enshrinement which, he admits, is an honor
that he savors.
 &HT;    ``Rock 'n' roll really saved my life,'' he says, ``and even
though I'm not writing it right now, the major part of my life was
spent writing, recording and playing rock 'n' roll.
 &HT;    ``I know people may have an image of me as this guy playing in a
piano bar,'' Joel says, ``but I only did that for six months. And
ever since I became a professional musician when I was in my late
teens, that's really what I've been doing up until about four years
ago. It's the majority of my life.
 &HT;    ``So, yeah, it will be nice to be there.''
 c.1999 Gary Graff  
