<HEADER>
A3217 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KYLE-CHANDLER-IN-EARL     03-01 1352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KYLE-CHANDLER-IN-EARLY-EDITION-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE INSIDE SCOOP ON KYLE CHANDLER 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Kyle Chandler in a scene from ``Early
Edition.'' 
 By CHRISTOPHER LOUDON  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call it the little television drama that could. CBS' ``Early
Edition'' has overcome seemingly insurmountable obstacles to emerge
as, if not a blockbuster, at least a solid middle-of-the-pack hit.
</P>
<P>
   It had to overcome its title, an ill-chosen moniker which to
most people sounds like some ``60 Minutes'' clone.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's its time slot, an early-evening berth in that
television netherworld known as Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   That's not even mentioning its premise, a farfetched fantasy
about a Chicago saloonkeeper who somehow gets tomorrow's newspaper
today and, rather than lining his pockets with lottery winnings,
uses the advance knowledge to avert disasters and help people out.
Sort of a reluctant, latter-day Superman, sans tights.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such challenges, ``Early Edition'' ended its first year
as the most popular new drama of the 1996/97 season, and has kept
its momentum ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Most observers boil its secret down to two words: Kyle Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   You may remember the strapping 33-year-old from the critically
acclaimed, early-1990s drama ``Homefront,'' or from his
award-winning Broadway run in ``Picnic'' (1994).
</P>
<P>
   He's undeniably handsome, but in a nonthreatening, all-American
way that's reminiscent of William Holden. His portrayal of Gary
Hobson, ``Early Edition's'' intrepid everyman, suggests the
aw-shucks humility of filmdom's finest antiheroes, James Stewart
and Gary Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   Relaxing between takes on ``Early Edition's'' Chicago set,
Chandler acknowledges the oft-made comparisons to such screen
giants. In fact, he says, he grew up fascinated by golden-age
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Buffalo and raised in the affluent Chicago suburb of
Lake Forest, Chandler's childhood was turned upside down in 1977
when his family relocated to a 22-acre farm in rural Georgia. Soon
afterward his father died, leaving the lonely, uprooted lad,
``looking for role models.''
</P>
<P>
   He found them on an Atlanta television station that specialized
in classic films.
</P>
<P>
   ``That station became my baby sitter,'' he recalls, ``and all of
a sudden I was finding heroes in my life. I watched all these old
John Wayne movies, all the Cary Grant and Gary Cooper deals. I was
14, and had an imagination that was just ready to roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what happened was that I would head out into the woods and
take those movie characters with me,'' the actor says. ``I'd
imagine that they were beside me as we charged up a hill to attack
the Nazis or tried to escape a Vietnamese jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were defining moments for me, though I didn't realize it
til much later. Because to this day a lot of those imaginary
friends are constantly with me, in my work and in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of actors have had to struggle for years before being
recognized, but that wasn't the case for Chandler. In 1988, while
attending the University of Georgia in Athens, he was spotted by an
ABC scout and recruited for the network's new-talent program.
Within a year, he'd landed a recurring role in the short-lived CBS
Vietnam drama ``Tour of Duty.''
</P>
<P>
   He was then tapped for a larger part in ABC's ambitious
``Homefront,'' playing a World War II veteran trying to adjust to
postwar life in a small Ohio town. Despite the series' heavy
premise, it also offered Chandler a chance to exercise his comic
skills, making romantic Tracy-Hepburn sparks fly with co-star Tammy
Lauren.
</P>
<P>
   Two years after ``Homefront'' was canceled, CBS lured him back
with ``Early Edition.'' At first, he admits, he found the premise
``pretty silly.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a movie or a pilot I could see it very clearly,'' he says,
``but I thought it would be almost impossible to do as a series. I
really don't think anyone thought it was going to make it out of
the gate but, to the credit of the writers and producers, they've
brought it a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   The actor takes particular pride in the evolution of his
character into more than a cardboard superhero.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to get a lot of notes from the producers saying they
wanted Gary to be The Hero,'' he says. ``And I said, `No, I don't
want him to be just some two-dimensional do-gooder.'
</P>
<P>
   ``My take on it was to make this guy completely human, to make
him full of flaws and let some of that comedy and timing I learned
as a kid fall into it,'' Chandler says. ``And that's what I now
love about the show. Sometimes Gary's very intelligent, other times
he's a complete idiot. He's got a big heart one moment, and the
next moment he's yelling at a kid on the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so many different things, and he's such a reluctant hero,
that he's tremendous fun to play.''
</P>
<P>
   He also appreciates the producers' commitment to making ``Early
Edition'' appropriate viewing for the whole family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no problem with sex _ in fact, I happen to really like
sex,'' he says, grinning. ``But this is not the show for it. This
is also not the show for violence, for blowing people away.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I don't believe in preaching to an audience,'' he adds.
``I don't think people tune in to be lectured about political
unrest or gun control or whatever the issue of the moment happens
to be. I'm proud that we stay away from all that and simply deliver
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're telling a story about a guy who gets tomorrow's news,''
Chandler concludes. ``It's not brain surgery. It's fun to shoot,
it's fun to watch and it is what it is. We're just here to create
fantastical little tales that anybody can enjoy.''
</P>
<P>
   Offscreen, his colleagues say, the actor is even more likeable
than his character. Loucas George, the executive producer, calls
Chandler ``one of the nicest guys you'll ever meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Another co-worker agrees, recalling an episode last winter when
the show's makeup artist locked her keys in her car. A severe
snowstorm was raging, and everybody but Chandler had left for the
night. He spent five hours waiting with her until the auto-club
truck arrived, then followed her home to be sure she made it
safely.
</P>
<P>
   Reminded of the story, Chandler smiles sheepishly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I had to help her,'' he says. ``If I didn't, who was
going to do my makeup the next morning?''
</P>
<P>
   The show's Chicago setting would put off some actors, but
Chandler _ who lives in the Windy City with his wife, screenwriter
Kathryn Chandler, and their daughter Sydney _ enjoys it precisely
because of its distance from the Los Angeles spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm completely removed from Hollywood,'' he says, ``and it's
sort of nice. For me, it's never been about how many people know
who I am, how big my trailer is or how huge my paycheck is. My
father was a very simple man who loved to laugh and loved life. He
was never the kind of guy who liked all the trappings _ he loved
the real things in life, and I think I got that from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I've got a family to support, but I've also got a
job that I love to do and I've got great people to work with every
day. Right now, I couldn't ask for anything better.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Christopher Loudon is the editor of TV Guide Canada, based in
North York, Ontario.) &LR;
</P>
