<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMILY-BERGL-IN-THE-RAGE-CARRIE-2-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEET, YOUNG AND SAVAGE: EMILY BERGL ON `THE RAGE,' THE STAGE AND
THE WAGES OF STARDOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Emily Bergl in a scene from ``The Rage:
Carrie 2.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Talk about a coming-out party.
 &HT;    On March 11, Emily Bergl makes her Broadway debut, co-starring
with Laurence Fishburne and Stockard Channing in ``The Lion in
Winter.'' The very next day she makes her feature-film debut in
``The Rage: Carrie 2,'' the sequel to Brian De Palma's 1976 horror
hit.
 &HT;    ``It's going to be a weekend like no other I've experienced,''
the fair-skinned redhead says over breakfast at a greasy-spoon
diner in the Hell's Kitchen section of Manhattan. Bergl ate here
often when she lived in the area last year, a fact attested to by
the lipstick mark on her right cheek, supplied by a waitress who
remembered her fondly.
 &HT;    ``It's good, exciting and, I suppose, a dream come true,'' she
says. ``I never actually had this specific dream. I only hoped to
be working at this point, and not waitressing. I never had any
concrete aspirations beyond just working.''
 &HT;    And make no mistake, acting is work _ especially in ``Carrie
2,'' which casts the 23-year-old as Rachel, a teen-ager with latent
telekinetic powers which are unleashed when her fellow students
push her too far. Also on hand for the fun is Amy Irving as Sue
Snell, the only survivor of ``Carrie's'' prom-night bloodbath, who
20 years later is working as a guidance counselor.
 &HT;    ``What was most important to me is that the protagonist is a
very strong female,'' Bergl says. ``Rachel has terrible things
happen to her, but she's not a victim. The movie is not about her,
half-clothed, being chased around by some guy with a knife.
 &HT;    ``It's not a movie solely about shock value,'' she adds. ``It
talks about inner psychological fears, becoming a woman and about
dealing with high school.''
 &HT;    Pouring hot sauce onto her eggs, Bergl says that her goal was to
create a believable character with real-life problems, family
concerns and even a love story, involving a sympathetic football
star (Jason London).
 &HT;    ``It was very intimidating,'' she says. ``Not only did I go to
work every day thinking I had a $20 million budget riding on me,
but I also felt the movie itself rode heavily on my performance.
Really, if you don't sympathize with Rachel, the whole movie
doesn't work.
 &HT;    ``The script helped me, though, because you see parts of her
life that make her seem like a real person, someone young people
can relate to,'' the actress adds. ``You see her at a job, you see
that she's not wealthy and doesn't have a car. She lives with a
foster family and has problems to deal with. We've also got a
genuine love story, between me and Jason London.
 &HT;    ``So there's more in this script than you see in the typical
horror film,'' she concludes. ``In terms of my acting, I made an
effort to be truthful about what I thought was going on in this
girl's head.''
 &HT;    The film builds in intensity via drama, not gore, Bergl reports.
However, the film's climax lives up to the chaotic finale of
``Carrie,'' she says.
 &HT;    ``What happens to Rachel is even more humiliating than what
happened to Sissy Spacek, but I don't want to give it away because
it's one of the film's big shocks,'' Bergl says. ``It was a tough
scene to shoot, though, because it was me laying on the ground for
days and days and days.
 &HT;    ``I had all these kids yelling at me, and after a while I could
feel some of their spit landing on me. By the end of it I was ready
to really kill everyone in the room.''
 &HT;    Well, everyone except Amy Irving.
 &HT;    ``Having her around was a blessing,'' Bergl says. ``Meeting her
was one of the great things about doing the film. It's important to
work with more experienced actresses, to learn from them.
 &HT;    ``Watching her work and sharing scenes with Amy was a big
influence,'' she adds, ``but it was also great to soak up all her
knowledge when we were just hanging out together on the set.''
 &HT;    The magnitude of it all hit home for the young actress on
Christmas.
 &HT;    ``I was home with my parents in Chicago,'' she says. ``We knew
the `Carrie 2' trailer would be playing before `The Faculty.' We
had Christmas dinner, then went to the movie theater. We went up
this big escalator, and at the top there was this `Carrie 2'
poster, which I hadn't seen yet. We all just freaked out.
 &HT;    ``Then we went into the theater,'' she continues. ``We watched
the `Carrie 2' trailer and left. It was the first time I'd ever
seen myself on screen.
 &HT;    ``It was very cool, but surreal, too. I almost didn't believe it
was me, but it was.''
 &HT;    In its own way, ``The Lion in Winter'' is equally overwhelming.
Bergl plays Alais, the French princess who is also the mistress of
England's Henry II (Fishburne).
 &HT;    ``It scared me to take that on,'' she admits, ``and it still
scares me now. I'm totally scared, but I know myself and I'm always
scared at this stage of the process.
 &HT;    ``Alais is an interesting character,'' she says. ``She's the
lover of a king, and she's got a quiet power to her that I really
appreciate, that I'm trying to bring out in the character.''
 &HT;    Fishburne and Channing are both formidable performers known for
their exacting standards of professionalism, but Bergl sounds as if
she's holding her own.
 &HT;    ``They don't suffer fools lightly, but they're also two of the
most professional actors I've ever worked with,'' she says.
``There's none of that star B.S. I'm learning a lot from them. They
just won't sacrifice the quality of the work.''
 &HT;    The same apparently can be said of Bergl, who was born in
England, grew up in the Chicago area and studied English and
theater at Grinnell College in Grinnell, Iowa.
 &HT;    After graduating, she moved to Manhattan and quickly landed a
job as an understudy in a Lincoln Center production of ``Ah,
Wilderness.'' More recently, she starred as Juliet in a
six-week-long run of ``Romeo and Juliet'' at the Old Globe Theater
in San Diego.
 &HT;    In short, everything seems to be coming together at once for
Bergl.
 &HT;    ``Every actor doubts they'll find work,'' she says. ``I worked
once with a woman who's worked steadily for about 35 years, and she
said that after she finishes every job she's afraid she'll never
work again. She thinks they'll find out she's no good.
 &HT;    ``I had a lot of fears that I wouldn't find work,'' Bergl
admits. ``I'm really lucky. I've paid some dues, but come on, most
people I know who've graduated from college aren't working, and a
lot of people don't work for years.''
 &HT;    But now that she's got her foot in the door, Bergl doesn't plan
to ease up.
 &HT;    ``I definitely see myself doing this for the long haul,'' she
says. ``Of course, like anyone else, I have career anxiety. But I
think I have less career anxiety than a lot of people I meet. Like
I said, I really only ever hoped to be an actor _ I've never wanted
to be a movie star, I never aspired to that.
 &HT;    ``I hope to do films,'' Bergl hastens to add. ``I hope people
like `Carrie 2.' But I'd be happy just to work in regional theater,
doing good Shakespeare, Ibsen or even good Christopher Durang.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
