<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3245 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHL-REPORT-TEX     03-01 1329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATES GAIN WHILE JAGR PLAYS LIKE BEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Jaromir Jagr wins the Hart Trophy for being the NHL's MVP,
you'll have to give Kip Miller an assist.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be a nice twist of irony, seeing that Jagr has been the
one handing out assists all season.
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins' winger has been spectacular, leading the NHL in
scoring and dishing out a league-best 60 assists through Thursday.
But those numbers alone don't rank Jagr as the league's MVP. Nope,
he needs Miller for that.
</P>
<P>
   You see, Kip Miller, while a fine individual, is a journeyman
center who before this season had played all of 90 NHL games over a
span of eight seasons. During that time, he had rung up 14
memorable goals.
</P>
<P>
   But early in January, Miller was placed on a line with Jagr to
give the Penguins more balance. Rookie Jan Hrdina also was added to
the mix, and Jagr was asked to basically carry two players who had
done very little to prove they were first-liners in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, Miller has scored 11 goals in 13 games with Jagr,
and Hrdina has pushed himself into the rookie of the year race with
29 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call him one of the top two or three \Rplayers in
the league\S, I'd say he's the best player in the league right
now,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said of the magical Jagr. ``If you
look at other teams, they have two or three players together _ Jagr
is doing it on his own.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Jagr, the Penguins now have a strong second line and
have bought into coach Kevin Constantine's philosophy of two-way
hockey, producing a stunning achievement when you consider this
team is playing under the shadow of bankruptcy. In other words,
Jagr's dedication has been contagious.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is Eric Lindros has John LeClair in
Philadelphia, Paul Kariya has Teemu Selanne in Anaheim and Mike
Modano has Brett Hull in Dallas. Jagr is making stars of Miller and
Hrdina.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, he's smiling while he's doing it. Many expected
Jagr to balk at Constantine's demand to play more defense, to
involve himself more strongly in a two-way game. After all, the
headstrong Czech had been raised by Mario Lemieux, a player who
often felt the system should fit him and not vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Jagr is the antithesis of Lemieux. Jagr loves
hockey, loves the rink, loves to just hang out with his teammates.
He is an engaging character with the media and has the makings of a
pretty darn good captain.
</P>
<P>
   And that means it could be time for Jagr to finally step forward
and earn his first MVP trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The obvious thing is people didn't expect that team to be
doing as well as they are,'' Hurricanes GM Jim Rutherford said.
``Not to take anything away from their other players, but it's
obvious Jagr has shifted to another gear. And I'm not sure anybody
else has that gear.''
</P>
<P>
   SPOTLIGHT ON...CHRIS CHELIOS
</P>
<P>
   First he told Philadelphia Flyers' GM Bob Clarke to shut up.
Now, he's telling his teammates to put up. That's the great thing
about Blackhawks defenseman Chris Chelios, he's never at a loss for
words.
</P>
<P>
   This week, however, he is at a loss for pride. The Blackhawks
captain, who was born in Chicago, is fighting mightily to stay in
the Windy City. And he might be out of luck there. The Blackhawks
will miss the playoffs for the second year in a row and have a
payroll of $35.8 million. Something has to give. Management has
done a tremendous job of bumbling Chicago's situation. All the way
from owner Bill Wirtz to GM Bob Pulford, the Blackhawks have been
cheap at the wrong times, losing Ed Belfour and Jeremy Roenick and
have been foolish at the wrong times, spending far too much to get
center Doug Gilmour.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a team that can't compete, but is too old to
rebuild. The only answer then is cutting salaries and starting
over. That's something Chelios, 37, doesn't want to hear about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to stay and I want to win here, I want to be a part of
that,'' Chelios said.
GRETZKY RETURNS?
</P>
<P>
   Not that anyone thought he was ready to leave, but Wayne Gretzky
offered a strong hint last week that he will be back for another
season with the Rangers. After a 6-2 loss to the Calgary Flames in
Calgary, Gretzky speculated about the Rangers possibly going after
free-agent-to-be Theo Fleury.
</P>
<P>
   ``One area where we have a cushion where Calgary doesn't: On
July 1, we have a lot of money that \Rmanagement\S can spend,''
Gretzky said. ``And I would hope that they would get into the
free-agent market. They didn't last year.''
</P>
<P>
   You boys at Madison Square Garden listening?
</P>
<P>
   FLEURY HYPE
</P>
<P>
   Is he going?
</P>
<P>
   Is he staying?
</P>
<P>
   The hype surrounding Fleury continues to get more intense every
day.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Fluery told ``The Calgary Sun'' that he turned down
an offer of $25 million over four years from the Los Angeles Kings,
who were trying to trade for him but wanted him to sign a new
contract before making the trade.
</P>
<P>
   The potential trade bait? Pavel Rosa and Yanic Perreault. Shows
what kind of offers the Flames are getting, huh?
</P>
<P>
   The best bet now is Calgary, which has made a 5-0-2 run to get
into playoff position, will keep Fleury for a potential postseason
run.
</P>
<P>
   HARVEY OUT
</P>
<P>
   Former Stars winger Todd Harvey, meanwhile, continues to battle
bad luck. Harvey, who was hoping to play for the first time against
the Stars on Tuesday, is expected to be out the next three months
with a broken thumb. He already has missed 21 games this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these freak injuries; what the heck am I going to do,''
Harvey said. ``Slashes on my thumb, my knee gets in a rut, I get
hit with a slap shot in the elbow. I think I'm going to see a witch
doctor and have the spell taken off.''
</P>
<P>
   Anybody worried that Harvey is a Gary Roberts, Kevin Stevens
type of player that might be playing too tough for his body?
</P>
<P>
   GILCHRIST IMPROVES
</P>
<P>
   Former Stars winger Brent Gilchrist said he could be ready to
play this week. Gilchrist, who has missed the entire season with
various abdominal injuries, said he would like to play March 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a situation right now where I'm feeling stronger and more
comfortable every day,'' Gilchrist said. ``I'm pushing it and not
feeling pain. I accelerate and wait for something to hurt, but it
doesn't.''
AROUND THE LEAGUE
</P>
<P>
   Check out the scene in Detroit. Red Wings captain Steve Yzerman
has volunteered to move from center to left wing so that Sergei
Fedorov would be more comfortable at center. That would be like
Mike Modano volunteering to move to a wing. Brendan Shanahan also
is playing out of position on the right wing for the Red Wings. ...
Speaking of the Stars, guess who else held a bag skate recently.
Kings coach Larry Robinson sent his lads out without pucks after a
5-1 loss to the Blues last week _ skating them in sprints only. The
Kings responded with a 3-2 victory against the Red Wings the next
night, outshooting Detroit, 40-26. Funny, the players didn't seem
tired. Maybe Ken Hitchcock knows what he's doing, after all. ...
Assistant coach Lorne Molleken is now the interim coach in Chicago
now that the Blackhawks fired Dirk Graham. But don't expect
Molleken to be a head coach. The Hawks will look for an experienced
hand. ... The Red Wings still struggle against the good teams. They
are 3-13-2 against teams with winning records. ... Since the new
year, the Devils are 11-11-4. ... The Avalanche followed their
12-game winning streak with an 0-3-4 run. ... Tommy Salo wants off
of Long Island again. The disgruntled goalie would be a great find
for a team in need.
THE WEEK AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday: Avalanche at Panthers _ Joe Sakic, Peter Forsberg and
Pavel Bure on the ice at one time. Friday: Red Wings at Coyotes _
The makings of a good rivalry is bubbling below the surface here.
Saturday: Maple Leafs at Senators _ Canada's two best teams square
off in a key Northeast Division rivalry. This is one reason
realignment is good.
</P>
</TEXT>
