<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PENDERS-VS.-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOM PENDERS: GONE BUT NOT FORGOTTEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Munching on a muffin one recent morning, Tom
Penders looks happy and content in his office, a converted
townhouse only a 10-minute subway ride from the White House. His
George Washington basketball team is 17-7 and vying for a berth in
the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been kind of a rebirth,'' Penders said. ``I couldn't have
written a better script.
</P>
<P>
   Appearances can be deceiving. Although he said he has put the
past behind him, Penders still has not forgotten the way his
10-year tenure at the University of Texas ended last March. It was
a messy divorce, and the resentment festers almost a year later.
</P>
<P>
   Penders reached into a desk and pulled out an exhibit to support
his contention that his ouster was orchestrated.
</P>
<P>
   During a taxing two-week period at the end of a disappointing
season in Austin, Penders was confronted by a player revolt over
alleged coaching abuse and the suspension of highly regarded
freshman Luke Axtell, whose grades were faxed to a local radio
station in violation of federal student privacy laws.
</P>
<P>
   Penders said The Axtell Affair involved an immature freshman who
refused to attend study hall and tutoring sessions. Penders alleges
that Axtell lied about his absences.
</P>
<P>
   Axtell's family said that Penders suspended Luke Axtell out of
spite after their son announced he was transferring to Kansas.
Penders still denies he had anything to do with the faxing of
Axtell's academic progress report to an Austin radio station.
Assistant coach Eddie Oran, who is now selling cars in Austin,
admitted to sending the fax.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Axtell family is suing radio station KVET, which
released Axtell's grades. Sheri Rasmus, the Axtell's lawyer, is in
the process of deposing witnesses for the suit. The case is
scheduled to go to court in mid-March.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of his health and his five-day hospital stay brings the
memories flooding back for Penders. The Longhorns were coming off a
Sweet 16 appearance in the 1996-97 season and had the best
recruiting class in school history.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was going to be the year we were going to make a run at
the Final Four,'' Penders said. ``But DeLoss Dodds meddled.''
</P>
<P>
   Penders' relationship with his boss at Texas, Dodds, the
athletic director, began to falter in March 1997 when Penders
considered a coaching offer from Rutgers, one of a dozen openings
he was linked to in his time in Austin. Penders said that Dodds was
resentful and wanted him out.
</P>
<P>
   Dodds declined to comment specifically about Penders or his
claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to put this all behind us and move on,''
Dodds said. ``We appreciate all the good things Tom did while he
was at Texas, and we all wish him well at George Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he felt Penders had been treated fairly, Dodds said,
``I'm not going to get into whether he was treated fairly or
unfairly. That's all in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   When Penders left, his settlement with the university was for
approximately $900,000. It included a clause preventing lawsuits
from either side.
</P>
<P>
   Penders appeared headed for a radio-television career. He had a
four-year, $350,000 deal with Host Communications and was
auditioning for ESPN. Then, an old friend called.
</P>
<P>
   George Washington athletic director Jack Kvancz needed a
basketball coach. Last May, St. John's hired GWU coach Mike Jarvis
and Kvancz decided to call Penders, whom he knew from their days as
high school basketball rivals in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was adamant that he wanted somebody to trust, and that's
why he was interested in this job,'' Kvancz said. ``What we have
here is a situation that makes Tom feel very comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did a lot of homework and nobody's talking about what
happened \Rlast March\S. Tom feels like he got undercut a little. I
think he was hurt, wounded by what happened at Texas. Within two
weeks of being up here, I think he had put all that stuff behind
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's over it, and I don't think he'll ever be
over it,'' said Tommy Penders, who is an assistant for his father
at George Washington. ``And I don't blame him. He is Texas
basketball, and they basically spit on him and didn't acknowledge
what he did. I think that's a reflection on the administration
there.''
</P>
<P>
   As he did at Rhode Island and Texas, Penders is primed to again
prove that he's Mr. March.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the time comes, we're going to be there,'' said 5-4
senior point guard Shawnta Rogers, who has flourished under
Penders' open-court offensive system. ``Coach Penders won't let us
slip. He's a player's coach. He lets you go out there and play your
game. People aren't nervous playing for him.''
</P>
<P>
   At Penders' other coaching stops, he was faced with building or
rebuilding a losing program. Not so here. George Washington
averaged 19 victories the past five seasons and last season won 24
games. Penders' let-players-play coaching style has been a hit with
the Colonials.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Penders, it's like a computer _ wysiwyg _ what you see is
what you get,'' said senior forward Yegor Mescheriakov. ``He's
always straightforward. If you have a bad game, he tells you. I
appreciate that. He's aware of the time of the season, how tired we
are, how much we need to practice. I like his composure during
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Penders doesn't believe the Colonials' success this season
vindicates him. But then, the past pops up like wreckage from a
sunken ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no regrets because everything I did at Texas was from
my heart and with honesty,'' said Penders, who is 495-326 in 28
seasons. ``I can look anybody in the eye. But there are a few
people who can't look me in the eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have I put it in the past? Yeah. But, I'm still waiting for a
phone call from Dodds, an explanation. He claimed to be great
friend of mine. I've written him, he hasn't answered me. He can't
look me in the eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he doesn't own me any more. That's the one thing he didn't
count on. He thought he could ruin my career.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
