<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S MORE THAN ONE WAY TO LIMIT POLITICIANS' TERMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bad news: Members of Congress who promised to limit their own
terms are having second thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Good news: There are only four of 'em.
</P>
<P>
   The headline in my paper on Friday made it seem worse:
``Republicans rethinking pledges for term limits.''
</P>
<P>
   For a moment there, I thought that all Republicans were reneging
on their term-limits promises. And I thought that all those who
were reneging were Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out that four of 10 House members who were elected in 1994
on pledges to serve no more than three two-year terms are now
having second thoughts. And one of the four is a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   That's not too bad at all, when you stop and think about it.
Generally speaking, if you put 10 politicians in a room and extract
a promise from each of them, you can figure that the first nine
will be breaking the promise before the last one is finished making
it.
</P>
<P>
   These term-limits promises were part of the Republicans'
Contract With America back in that '94 election that saw the GOP
seize control of Congress for the first time since ... well, since
dinosaurs roamed the Earth or some such.
</P>
<P>
   A few Democrats also bought into the idea, including
Massachusetts Rep. Marty Meehan _ whom some Americans might
remember as one of the House Judiciary Committee's leading
defenders of President Clinton during the impeachment hearings last
year. Meehan is one of the four House members who promised in 1994
to step down in 2000 but is apparently reconsidering.
</P>
<P>
   The others are Republican Reps. George Nethercutt of Washington,
Scott McInnis of Colorado and Tillie Fowler of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   All this information comes to us, by the way, courtesy of the
Knight Ridder News Service, which quoted Nethercutt's chief of
staff as saying that the Washington congressman would make a
decision based on ``consultation and conversation with the people
of Washington state.''
</P>
<P>
   Interesting. Didn't Nethercutt already consult and converse with
the people of Washington state on this question? Didn't his 1994
campaign promise eliminate the need for any additional consultation
and conversation on the subject of self-imposed term limits?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently not.
</P>
<P>
   The other potential promise-breakers, according to Knight
Ridder, ``have yet to announce their intention to retire.''
</P>
<P>
   This is why lots of folks support the idea of legally mandated
term limits _ because even candidates who vow to impose term limits
on themselves cannot be trusted to make good on their promises. If
we can't count on them to do what they say they'll do, some voters
figure, we need laws that leave no room for such double-dealing.
</P>
<P>
   Such frustration is understandable. But it is unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   The American people don't need mandatory term limits to force
elected officials out of office once they've worn out their
welcome. We don't even need to count on politicians to keep their
word _ which, of course, is an exercise in futility under almost
any circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   No, we the people have the power to limit the terms of every
elected official at every level of government. We can limit
officeholders to three terms, two terms, one term _ or we can allow
them to serve 20 terms, if we like the job they are doing.
</P>
<P>
   That's the beauty of our system. The voters get to decide who
serves and how long they serve.
</P>
<P>
   We have the power to establish term limits. And we get to make
up the limits as we go along. No etched-in-concrete statute can
guarantee such flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   If those four House members who are waffling on their term-limit
promises believe they can get away with double-crossing their
constituents, they have every right to try. And the constituents
have every right to send the double-crossers packing.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's disappointing that some of these politicians who
boldly vowed to vacate their congressional posts after six years
may turn out to be hypocrites. It's no fun being lied to.
</P>
<P>
   But guess what, voters? Involuntary retirement is every bit as
effective as voluntary retirement.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
