<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3262 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARRAL-COLUMN-TEX     03-01 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRAL-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEING A SLANT IN STORIES AND STYLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL K. HARRAL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I hear this in telephone calls weekly, if not daily, and read it
in letters and e-mail messages: Some newspaper readers think the
stories we write and the way we write them are influenced by the
biases of the journalists involved.
</P>
<P>
   And some believe we follow a specific agenda. Just what that
agenda is depends greatly on the viewpoint of the caller.
</P>
<P>
   So it is not a surprise that the same issue surfaced in last
year's American Society of Newspaper Editors study on newspaper
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   The report labeled this ``major finding No. 3'' and stated it
this way: ``The public suspects that the points of view and biases
of journalists influence what stories are covered and how they are
covered.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the numbers: 78 percent of those surveyed felt
that there was bias in the news media. The good news for those of
us in print is that 42 percent see television as the worst
offender. The bad news is that 23 percent think newspapers are.
</P>
<P>
   I'm beginning to believe that it doesn't make much difference _
sources of information are so lumped together that people awash in
information have trouble keeping them separated.
</P>
<P>
   Readers' and viewers' opinion of television news colors their
opinion of print news. They clearly know the difference between
supermarket tabloids and daily newspapers, but screaming headlines
about Liz Taylor's latest problems cannot help but take a toll on
our credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Not helping in all of this is the star system among national
reporters. And it's not just confined to television reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Readers clearly know the difference between editorials and
columns, but they are rightfully skeptical when they see a print or
broadcast journalist who is charged with being neutral express an
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   The authors of the ASNE study concluded that at the core, ``it
seems that the public most commonly defines the foundation of bias
as a lack of neutrality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They see the editorial page as the only home for opinion or
suggestion,'' the report said. ``The public believes that the
reporter's job is to report the facts _ completely, insightfully
and without spin (even if the spin makes for a better read), and
clean of any intent to sway or convince.''
</P>
<P>
   The study found at least three interpretations of what bias is:
</P>
<P>
   _30 percent of adults see bias as not being open-minded and
neutral about the facts.
</P>
<P>
   _29 percent say that it's having an agenda and shaping the news
report to fit it.
</P>
<P>
   _29 percent believe that it's favoritism to a particular social
or political group.
</P>
<P>
   _8 percent say bias in the news media is all of these.
</P>
<P>
   There's some indication that the perception of bias is a
self-fulfilling prophesy.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that the results ``suggest that once an
individual begins to question newspaper credibility, he or she is
far more likely to behave in a way that reinforces that belief
rather than dispels it.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, more than two-thirds of adults say that ``their
perception of bias in newspapers does not represent a major
obstacle to being able to trust newspapers as a source of news _
perhaps because they believe they've built sufficient filtering
mechanisms to identify and neutralize it when they think they see
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The researchers asked people what groups they thought could
influence news decisions, and they named the usual suspects:
``politicians or government officials, big business and wealthy
individuals.'' Half of those surveyed felt that ``there are
individuals or groups that get a special break and enjoy overly
favorable coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   But 45 percent believe that some groups get overly unfavorable
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here the presumption of a negative bias is primarily ethnic or
racial, with significant proportions of the public volunteering (on
an unaided, top-of-mind basis) that African-Americans,
Hispanics/Latinos, conservatives, the poor/people on welfare and
religious organizations (especially born-again Christians) don't
get a fair shake in the media,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   I've often told people that publishing a newspaper daily is
difficult enough and that adding something as complex as a
conspiracy would bring the process to a halt. But this is a case
where perception might as well be reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether a newspaper's `agenda' is consciously articulated,
subliminally active or nonexistent, then, a large proportion of the
U.S. public believes that there is one, and they believe that it
can influence the news they see or don't see,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Defining ``news'' is a difficult assignment. What I find
interesting may bore you to tears. You may think a story short at
100 inches because it involves a favorite topic, while I can't get
past the third paragraph because I don't care much about that
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Some perception of bias probably is linked to this: There's
never enough in the paper about your favorite causes, and there's
always too much in the paper about causes you dislike.
</P>
<P>
   But we can all survive these kinds of debates if we have
persuaded you that what we select for print and the way we write it
is fair and evenhanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reputations for credibility are hard to win and easy to
lose,'' the report said. ``Most dangerous, of course, is the short
distance between the public believing that there is an agenda
within the newsroom, and to them seeing that agenda expressed as
opinion within the news report.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the public senses this, it's a severe threat to
credibility _ irrespective of whether the intention of the agenda
they see is noble, or whether the expression of its voice is
skillful,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   (Paul K. Harral is reader advocate for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. His e-mail address is harral(at)star-telegram.com.
You may telephone him at (817) 390-7692 or write him at P.O. Box
1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
