<HEADER>
A3265 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN     03-01 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RELIGIOUS RIGHT' HAS ITS USES, LIBERAL SCHOLAR SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ``religious right,'' considered dangerous by some liberal
politicians and theologians, isn't all bad, one liberal scholar of
religion says.
</P>
<P>
   Religious conservatives have forced Americans into deeper
discussion about morality in politics, personal life, family life
and the original meaning of separation of church and state, said
Ron Flowers, director of the department of religion at Texas
Christian University in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers made that point to journalists and religion scholars
during a two-day ``Religion in the News'' conference in Fort Worth
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the religious right is wrong,'' Flowers said in an
interview. ``Still, it has been very useful in bringing heated
debate on separation of church and state, abortion, public morality
and the content of TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Flowers is president of the North Texas chapter of Americans
United for Separation of Church and State, and author of ``That
Godless Court? Supreme Court Decisions on Church-State
Relationships.'' He was one of several speakers at the Fort Worth
conference aimed at improving coverage of religion in the news
media.
</P>
<P>
   The TCU workshop was one of a series throughout the nation
spearheaded by Mark Silk, a former Atlanta Constitution reporter,
editorial writer and columnist who directs the Center for the Study
of Religion in Public Life at Trinity College in Hartford, Conn.
Financial support for the workshops is provided by the Lily
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth event was co-sponsored by TCU's religion
department and the American Academy of Religion, Southwest Region.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have several goals, including letting supervising editors
get an idea of what the religion beat is like, or should be like,''
Silk said. ``Also, it helps news people get acquainted with
religion scholars who have the expertise to help with news
stories.''
</P>
<P>
   The Christian conservatives' call for moral correctness
continues to be newsworthy, Flowers said at the workshop,
</P>
<P>
   Personal morality has been shoved even further into the
forefront lately by President Clinton's misadventures with Monica
Lewinski and his subsequent impeachment trial, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a liberal who voted twice for President Clinton, but I was
completely undone by his behavior,'' Flowers said.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers of the religion scene believe the president's
misbehavior offers an opportunity to reflect on America's moral
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   United Methodist Bishop Felton E. May, leader of his
denomination's Baltimore-Washington conference, issued a statement
saying Clinton had apparently grown spiritually because of his
ordeal. And he urged the president to speak up for a higher
morality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a world where consumption, hedonism and
self-gratification have increasingly become normal and even
celebrated,'' May said. ``I believe President Clinton now has a
unique opportunity to call a world from selfishness to Christ-like
love and service of others.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Flowers said he agrees that the nation should seek a
higher morality, he said the Christian right is seeking to enforce
its own brand of morality on others. He said that as much as he
abhors Clinton's conduct, he believes that the investigation of the
president was politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe Hillary Clinton was more right than wrong when
she said the whole thing was initiated by the right wing to remove
him from office,'' Flowers said.
</P>
<P>
   Religious conservatives are better organized than they were when
they emerged on the American political scene in the 1980s. They
still are pushing for anti-abortion laws, school-prayer bills and
tuition voucher legislation, which Flowers said gets the church too
involved with the state.
</P>
<P>
   And although Flowers praises Christian political conservatives
for bringing up moral questions, he will spend the next few years
opposing their views.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my judgment, we still have great cause to be alarmed by the
religious right,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Contact him at jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
