<HEADER>
A3332 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SURF-FORECASTING-HNS &LR;      03-01 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURF-FORECASTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCHING FOR BIG WAVES? TRY SURFING THE NET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Surf forecasting has become a booming business,
and some forecasters claim better than 90 percent accuracy in
predicting the big waves.
</P>
<P>
   The forecasts are so reliable that when a respected forecaster
predicts a big swell for Fiji, Hawaii, Peru or Tahiti, well-heeled
surf-seekers fly there to catch the waves.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a forecast of high waves sent 20 big-wave riders
from around the world to Mavericks, the surf break along the
California coast, for the first ``Men Who Ride Mountains'' contest.
The victor, Darryl Virostko of Santa Cruz, Calif., won $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years surfers have become completely dependent on surf
forecasts, said Evan Slater, editor of Surfer Magazine in San Juan
Capistrano. Forecast accuracy is ``about 90 percent and higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Surf forecasters use data from the National Weather Service,
satellites, scientific buoys, paid surf-watchers at different
beaches, video monitors of various coastlines, and other sources to
predict the surf conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now in the summertime, when storms are coming out of the
Southern Hemisphere, we're telling people a week and a half in
advance (about swells). We can predict a swell right on the
button,'' said Chris Borg, a 12-year veteran of surf forecasting.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a downside to surf science: It has robbed surfing
of much of its former mystery. In the 1960s, the golden age of
surfing popularized by Hollywood movies starring Annette Funicello
and Frankie Avalon, the inexplicable comings and goings of ocean
swells inspired cosmic reveries and poetic musings.
</P>
<P>
   While most beach films were teen-oriented showcases for pop
music and bikinis, critics recognized at least one surfing film _
``The Endless Summer'' _ as a thoughtful depiction of a
counterculture lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Now the mystery is gone. The ocean is constantly scrutinized by
orbiting satellites which relay wind, storm, sea-level and other
measurements by the National Weather Service, the National Data
Buoy Center and other agencies. The data are dumped into the
Internet, where anyone with a computer can access the information.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 weather-watching buoys around the world are monitored
by the National Data Buoy Center, a branch of the National Weather
Service. The center is based at NASA's Stennis Space Center in
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   A leading surf forecaster, Sean Collins of Surfline/Wavetrak in
Huntington Beach, Calif., bases predictions on the time periods
between swells and other factors, which indicate whether wave
intensity is growing or ebbing.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters also rely on weather maps, which reveal the position
and strength of storms. From the Internet, they get data from
floating buoys, which show how high swells are.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the intensity of a wave may vary according to the angle at
which it hits a coastline. So in calculating the effects for each
beach, surf forecasters must take into account the shape of the
coast.
</P>
<P>
   They must also take into account factors below the water's
surface. Submerged islands, for example, can disturb an otherwise
strong swell.
</P>
<P>
   Some old-time surfers lament ``the death of mystery'' as surf
forecasting becomes routine and reliable, Slater admits. ``Now it's
all through the Internet. You almost are disappointed the next
morning if the forecasts don't live up to expectations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-99 1622EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
