<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3334 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX     03-01 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAD WEIGHT AND TAXES: THE NATIONAL DEBT AND SOCIAL SECURITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Taxes are the price for all the things we do together as a
nation, their adequacy a mark of our maturity and their fairness a
test of our wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-three years ago, a cynical old pro of Texas political wars
offered me (then a first-time candidate for the Texas Legislature)
what he guaranteed was a sure-fire, can't-fail recipe for perpetual
re-election: Vote for all appropriations and against all taxes! The
latter in any form, he opined, were simply anathema to voters.
</P>
<P>
   So it seemed to make superficial political sense to GOP
congressional leaders, looking for something popular with big
contributors and salable to voters, to promise an
``across-the-board tax cut.'' To the surprise of the plan's
promoters, the public began telling pollsters and at least some
Republican congressmen that instead of that tax cut, they'd prefer
applying the $63 billion federal budget surplus to protecting
Social Security and paying down the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   All of this tends to confirm my long-held conviction that the
public is generally more sensible, more responsible and less greedy
than politicians quite often give people credit for being. It
validates some much better political advice I got, also about 50
years ago, from a Weatherford, Texas, lawyer and longtime mentor
named George McCall. His admonition: Never overestimate the
public's information, but never underestimate the public's
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, the people seem to understand that this
proposed ``across-the-board'' reduction in taxes _ slicing
everyone's tax rate by a flat 10 percent _ would be a lot less
egalitarian than it sounds. A study by the Joint Committee on
Taxation concludes that the bill would shower its greatest benefit
on the nation's very wealthiest _ those who obviously need it the
least.
</P>
<P>
   During the first full year of the proposed rate cut, one-third
of the rebate would go to the most affluent 1 percent, and more
than half would inure to taxpayers with incomes exceeding $100,000
a year. Only 17 percent of the cut would be enjoyed by the middle
and lower two-thirds of America's families who make less than
$50,000 annually. The bottom third of all taxpaying households
would get virtually no benefit at all.
</P>
<P>
   This plan is identical to the tax cut successfully pushed by
President Reagan in 1981, except that it just doesn't ask for two
more layers of 10 percent cuts in succeeding years. It was that
very plan, sold as an economic panacea by the winsome old
persuader, that set us on the path of rising deficits and soaring
national debt.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, our national debt stood at just under $1 trillion, the
cumulative result of 200 years of nationhood and 39 presidential
administrations. The Reagan tax cut, spun out principally to
America's wealthiest 10 percent while we were doubling military
expenditures, more than tripled the national debt in one short
decade.
</P>
<P>
   As result of that prodigal economic policy, our annual interest
payment on the debt _ the amount that taxpayers have to shell out
every year just to service the debt _ skyrocketed from about $50
billion in 1980 to approximately $267 billion today.
</P>
<P>
   Focus on that figure for a minute. It is dead weight. It buys us
nothing. It doesn't pave a single mile of road, buy a single
schoolbook or build a single airplane. Interest on the debt is not
optional. It's automatic. It must be paid first, before we can buy
anything else. This year, it amounts to almost exactly $1,000 per
capita _ man, woman and child.
</P>
<P>
   And the only conceivable way to reduce this ubiquitous drag on
our national pocketbook is to start paying down the debt. Take part
of that $63 billion surplus and use it to reduce our level of
indebtedness.
</P>
<P>
   People who'd offer big tax cuts to those who don't need them in
times of prosperity rather than paying on the debt are not, in the
classic sense, conservatives. For years they've been boisterously
blaming the debt on ``the tax-and-spend crowd.'' They're wrong. At
fault is the borrow-and-spend crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years ago, in 1959, I proposed that we begin paying off
the national debt at the rate of 1 percent a year. Some thought
that whimsical. According to an amortization table we worked out at
the time, within 18 years we'd have been paying less in principal
and interest combined than we were then paying annually in interest
alone. In 1959, interest on the debt cost us about $11 billion, and
I thought that was a lot. That was 20 years before Reagan's tax
cut.
</P>
<P>
   It is mistaken _ absolutely wrong _ to say that the working poor
``pay no taxes'' when their total earnings fall below the income
tax threshold. They pay a far bigger percent of their meager
incomes on sales and excise taxes than do we who get to save and
invest a portion of ours. Moreover, these lower-income wage earners
feed the Social Security trust fund with payroll taxes deducted
regularly from their salaries.
</P>
<P>
   To complain, therefore, about the progressivity of the income
tax is to ignore the regressivity of most other taxes. To complain
against using the biggest portion of any budget surplus to buttress
the Social Security trust fund is to ignore the several decades in
which we've borrowed from that fund to mask our budget deficits.
</P>
<P>
   To fail to make a serious start on these problems this year when
good fortune has given us a surplus would be unforgivable folly.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright(at)tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
