<DOCNO> NYT19990301.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3341 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-LOWCOST-ROCKETS-A     03-01 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-LOWCOST-ROCKETS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS SUBSTITUTE FOR SHUTTLES, NEW ROCKET FALLS SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By WARREN E. LEARY 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An experimental rocket that is at the heart of
NASA's plans to develop a low-cost, re-usable vehicle that might
eventually replace the space shuttle has fallen more than a year
behind schedule for its first flight because of mounting technical
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The rocket, called the X-33, represents a radically different
approach to launching space payloads that proponents say could
drastically reduce costs and expand access to space for new types
of uses, including tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Critics charge that the X-33, a half-scale prototype that is to
demonstrate an array of new technologies for future launchers, is
behind schedule and under budget pressures because it was designed
to do too much under a tightly limited program.
</P>
<P>
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration and the
project's lead contractor, the Lockheed Martin Corp.'s Skunk Works
Division in Palmdale, Calif., acknowledge that unexpected technical
problems have delayed the experimental rocket project. But they say
such troubles are expected with a cutting-edge program and are the
price of innovation.
</P>
<P>
   Problems affecting the X-33 include difficulty in manufacturing
its engines, a new design that has never flown before; trouble in
making its lightweight, graphite-reinforced plastic fuel tanks, and
excess weight that will reduce the craft's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we picked this X-33 concept in the summer of 1996, we
knew this design was brand new and nothing like it had been built
before,'' said Gary Payton, head of NASA's re-usable launching
vehicle program. ``When you choose an aggressive and daring
project, you know you will run into problems,'' he continued,
``That's one way of knowing you're really pushing the technology,
which is what we wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The X-33 program is a cooperative government-industry effort to
demonstrate that it is possible to make a rocket that is cheaper
and easier to operate and maintain than anything now flying. It
costs about $10,000 per pound to orbit payloads with the space
shuttle and one of the goals of the new rocket would be to reduce
this to $1,000 a pound, or less.
</P>
<P>
   NASA has committed $941 million to the project and Lockheed
Martin and its industry partners have put up about $230 million.
</P>
<P>
   The envisioned vehicle is called a single-stage-to-orbit rocket
because it would fly into space and return to Earth in one piece,
much like an airliner. Conventional rockets, even the space
shuttle, are not totally reusable because with each use they
discard parts, like fuel tanks, booster rockets or spent lower
stages.
</P>
<P>
   NASA and Lockheed Martin hope a successful X-33 program will
prove the feasibility of building a larger rocket, called the
Venture Star, which would be able to carry space shuttle-size
payloads into space at much reduced cost. The plan calls for the
company to seek private investment of more than $5 billion to build
two Venture Stars that it would own and operate, selling launching
services to government and commercial clients as early as 2004.
</P>
<P>
   But some observers are skeptical about the program's chances for
success. John E. Pike, director of space policy for the Federation
of American Scientists in Washington, said developing a
privately-owned space launcher of this scale would take more time
and money than proponents acknowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think a dozen flights of a sub-scale vehicle will give
you a firm handle on the reliability and flight rates of a Venture
Star that you can take to investors,'' Pike said, ``The main
challenges of Venture Star are not technical, but economic.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Vanderbilt, a spokesman for the Space Access Society, a
national advocacy group for cheaper space flight, said the designs
of the X-33 and Venture Star were too complex to reduce costs
enough to open space to small businesses and individuals. And
failure of the project could cause potential investors to turn away
from other, more promising, low-cost rocket proposals, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a tragedy if Venture Star made people think the
single-stage-to-orbit concept can't work,'' Vanderbilt said.
</P>
<P>
   The winning Lockheed Martin design, the most ambitious of three
candidates proposed in 1996, is a vehicle shaped like a flat
arrowhead with fins at the bottom. It is designed to take off
vertically using a new type of nozzleless rocket engine, to
re-enter the atmosphere protected by a novel metallic thermal
covering, to fly back horizontally with the help of lift generated
by its flat body, and to land on a runway like an airplane.
</P>
<P>
   Standing 67-feet-tall and measuring 68-feet-wide at the tail,
the unmanned experimental craft is not designed to reach orbit with
its two engines powered by liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen. But
engineers say it should be able to fly 50 miles high at hypersonic
speed, more than enough to prove its design and test its components
under the harshest conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The X-33 was originally to begin a series of 15 test flights
this month, but a number of manufacturing and engineering problems
forced the first launching date to slip, first to July, then to
December. Program officials said last week that the new target date
was July, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Austin, NASA's X-33 program manager, said project delays
were attributed to a range of problems, including late delivery of
parts by suppliers and difficulties in assembling components. For
example, trouble bonding high-temperature engine parts at the
Boeing Co.'s Rocketdyne engine division added $36 million to
project costs and pushed the schedule back several months, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The X-33 and its successor are to be powered by linear aerospike
engines, which save weight and complexity by forgoing the moveable,
bell-shaped engine nozzles used for conventional rocket engines.
Each of the X-33's engines, which generate 205,000 pounds of
thrust, has small combustors, or thrust chambers, that fire along
curved open exhaust ramps instead of through a nozzle.
</P>
<P>
   The two ramps form a V-shape with thrusters, aligned along the
top outside surface of each side, that fire downward toward the
point.
</P>
<P>
   The ramps are made of a copper alloy sheet milled to include
internal passages through which coolant is circulated. The copper
is backed by a brazed-on steel sheet, but temperature differences
throughout the ramps and other problems made the bonding much more
difficult than expected, Austin said.
</P>
<P>
   In a problem related to the engine, which has been tested
extensively on the ground since the 1970s but never in flight, NASA
and Lockheed Martin announced in November that they had given up on
a more than three-year effort to test-fire a small aerospike engine
atop an SR-71 research plane during high-speed runs.
</P>
<P>
   During the $27 million program, known as Lasre for Linear
Aerospike SR-71 Experiment, a small engine carried in a one-tenth
scale model X-33 flew aboard the former reconnaissance jet seven
times, but was never fired.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Rising, the Lockheed Martin executive in charge of the
X-33 program from the beginning, said persistent fuel leaks in the
test model's plumbing system made live firings dangerous and the
company felt it was not worth spending more money to fix the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel flow tests during the flights and ground firings of the
engine helped the company validate computer predictions of how the
aerospike's hot, open exhaust plume would behave in flight, he
said, and further investment in Lasre was not warranted just to
fire the engine in the air.
</P>
<P>
   A bigger problem arose in December when part of one of the
X-33's two liquid hydrogen fuel tanks came apart when it was being
heat cured. A 28-foot-long section of the tank's skin, made by
laying sheets of composite material, pulled apart from its inner
surface and has to be completely replaced, engineers said.
</P>
<P>
   Rising said that it would cost $6 million to make and replace
the damaged tank skin, but that there were no estimates of the
total cost of correcting the snag.
</P>
<P>
   The X-33 also has had a weight problem, at one point growing
from its intended 65,000 pounds to 78,000 pounds, Rising said. The
craft's mass is now down to about 75,000 pounds, he said, but the
company has decided not to invest in a severe weight-reduction
program because it would be costly and most of the rocket's flight
objectives can be reached without being lightened further.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are already taking what we are learning with X-33 and
applying it to the design of the Venture Star, and that's where we
are making the weight-reduction measures,'' Rising said.
</P>
<P>
   Weight is one of the reasons the X-33 will not meet an original
program goal of flying at a top speed of Mach 15, or 15 times the
speed of sound, a little more than 11,000 miles per hour. Rising
confirmed that the craft's maximum speed is now down to Mach 13.8,
about 10,000 mph, but said this was sufficient for the craft to
meet all its test objectives.
</P>
<P>
   Launched vertically from a recently completed site at Edwards
Air Force Base in California, the X-33 is to make test flights in
which it would land at military bases in Utah or Montana and then
be brought back to California by truck. Early flights will be to
the Dugway Proving Ground in Utah, and higher, longer-ranged tests
will take it to Malmstrom Air Force Base in Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Rising said the problems with the X-33 should not distract from
the program's accomplishments so far, including completion of its
launching site ahead of schedule, certification of its metal
heat-shield system as flight-ready, successful testing of the
systems that pump fuel to the engines and control their thrust, and
completed verification testing of the system of small rockets that
will control the spacecraft at high altitudes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
