<SLUG> BC-FILMS-MITCHELL-COLUMN-1200(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUIET ANNIVERSARY BELIES CONTROVERSIAL PAST OF `THE WARRIORS'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``These are the armies of the night,'' screamed a movie poster
20 years ago. ``They're out to stop the Warriors.'' And so,
director Walter Hill's crowning B-picture classic, ``The
Warriors,'' was issued into America.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike ``Grease,'' or ``The Godfather'' _ or the ``Star Wars''
trilogy _ ``Warriors'' will not receive a grand rerelease, even
though it was the generation's most influential action movie. There
won't even be a salutatory ``20-year anniversary'' sticker on its
videocassette box.
</P>
<P>
   That's because ``The Warriors'' was also one of the most
controversial movies of its time. Outbreaks of violence at theaters
prompted a nervous Paramount Pictures to withdraw the film shortly
after its 1979 release, while it was still making money.
</P>
<P>
   An exciting and too effectively lurid trailer spelled out the
picture's story: The gangs of New York have decided to unite to
take over the city. It was a great paranoid premise, one that sent
a chill through a nation made uncomfortable by the rise of gangs.
And New York was at its dangerous, deteriorating peak _ four years
earlier, a New York Post headline had bellowed the president's
response to the city's appeal for federal aid: ``Drop Dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie's story line, from the novel by Sol Yurick, followed
what happened at the big gang convocation. Cyrus, the head of the
Riffs and the charismatic figure behind the takeover idea, is
assassinated. The Warriors are blamed, even though they're not
responsible. And they have to fight their way back from Manhattan
to their home in Coney Island, with every gang in the city out to
stop them. (Yurick's novel followed the Greek legend of Xenophon
and the 10,000; after their leader is killed in Persia, Xenophon
and his band have to battle their way home.)
</P>
<P>
   Hill staged the film in a manner new to American action films,
with fight sequences inspired by the Hong Kong kung-fu movies of
the early '70s. Hill's action-choreography had a high-flying
clarity that hadn't been exploited in American films before; it was
scored with throbbing Euro-metal music, and a few bad, but
stirring, songs.
</P>
<P>
   Each fight was like a rousing show-stopper number in a musical;
after a tense, dazzling throw-down in the confined space of a
subway men's room, the audience I saw the movie with was on its
feet, stomping and applauding. Also, each fight was like a
miniclimax, advancing the narrative and increasing the adrenaline
level.
</P>
<P>
   The turnout must've caught the studio off guard, because
``Warriors'' shot right through the pipeline, playing to just the
wide-awake, juice-hungry crowd that might cause trouble in movie
theaters. If violence were to break out in a theater these days, a
movie company would likely hire extra security and put a
public-relations spin on the episode to mitigate negative
publicity. (This was done after a few incidents connected with
``New Jack City.'') But in 1979, panic _ and a few shrill
editorials with the usual end-of-Western-Civilization bent _ caused
exhibitors to begin withdrawing ``Warriors'' from their movie
houses.
</P>
<P>
   Before studios realized, and exploited, the ability of TV to
speak directly to the prime moviegoing audience _ kids ages 15 to
19 _ newspapers were the main source of advertising and publicity.
As such, papers wielded enormous power. An editorial attack on
Stanley Kubrick's ``A Clockwork Orange'' by The Detroit News, and
its subsequent ban on ads for X-rated movies, had already helped
kill the adult art movie in this country.
</P>
<P>
   So, as ``Warriors'' didn't have much support from movie critics,
it was easier to slip it from theaters _ no one was going to make
much of a case for it. And whereas other gang films were steeped in
a stereotypical liberal bias that attempted to explain the social
roots of gang violence, ``Warriors'' was just a straight-ahead
action movie with hints of European existentialism. The characters
were realized through movement, rather than through dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
