<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3360 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-01 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CHAPTER IN JUDICIAL CAMPAIGN FINANCING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In the never-ending saga of Texas judges
attempting to survive the political process without appearing to be
politicians, we have another chapter.
</P>
<P>
   A study committee appointed by the Texas Supreme Court has
issued a mixed bag of recommendations on financing judicial
campaigns, including the oh-so-bold proposal that judges be
required to recuse themselves from cases involving people who gave
them illegal campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The mere fact that such a requirement isn't already the law of
the land speaks volumes about the potential for abuse inherent in
Texas' elected judicial system.
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis is on the word ``potential.'' This is intended as
no broadside against the ethics of most Texas judges, despite
outspoken critics who argue that if justice isn't ``for sale'' in
our state, there certainly is a perception that it is.
</P>
<P>
   Many would-be reformers are urging the Legislature once again
this year to replace the partisan election of judges with a system
of gubernatorial appointments and retention elections. But with
that prospect remaining a long shot _ partly because most Texans
want to elect their judges _ the Supreme Court asked the committee
to see what could be done to improve the present system.
</P>
<P>
   Since the quest for reform isn't exactly virgin territory, the
panel of nine lawyers and judges, chaired by Houston attorney Wayne
Fisher, had plenty of previous studies to guide it, including a
report commissioned by the American Bar Association just last year
on lawyers' political contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the committee's recommendations may be adopted
administratively by the Supreme Court, which has disciplinary
oversight over Texas judges. Others would likely require
legislative action.
</P>
<P>
   The committee recommended that more teeth be put into campaign
contribution limits imposed on judges and judicial candidates a few
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the campaign limits, the law doesn't require a judge to
step down from a case if it involves a lawyer or a litigant who
gave him or her an illegal, excessive contribution. The study
committee recommended that judges be required to recuse themselves
in such cases and that judges who knowingly violate the law be
subject to disciplinary proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The panel recommended the same requirement be imposed on judges
who benefit from major expenditures, such as billboards, made
independently by interest groups on the judge's behalf. Current law
doesn't even limit those independent expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also recommended the recusal requirement be imposed on
justices of the peace, who aren't covered by the statutory campaign
contribution limits. And the panel proposed that campaign finance
limits imposed on law firms also apply to other entities.
</P>
<P>
   The contribution limits, as set out in law, vary according to
the size of the geographic area from which the judge or judicial
candidate is running. The limit for a Texas Supreme Court justice
is $5,000 from an individual or $30,000 from a law firm.
</P>
<P>
   But since the limit is for each election, a Supreme Court
justice who has a contested primary race, a contested runoff and an
opponent in the general election could receive as much as $15,000
from one person or $90,000 from one law firm in an election year.
</P>
<P>
   Whether those limits _ the only fund-raising limits imposed on
any state political candidates in Texas _ are too high will still
be debated.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also recommended that judges' campaign finance
reports be filed electronically so that they can more easily be
read by many Texans and that more voter guides on judicial races be
developed and distributed to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The panel didn't address the questionable practice of winning
judges and judicial candidates soliciting ``late train''
contributions after an election. But it did propose that limits be
imposed on judges' ability to hoard political donations between
elections.
</P>
<P>
   It also recommended that judges and judicial candidates be
prohibited from donating part of their campaign funds to political
parties or political committees that endorse candidates. The latter
practice has frequently been criticized as a way for judges to buy
political support.
</P>
<P>
   Judges will have a chance to air their views on the report in a
hearing before the Supreme Court this week. The court will have
another hearing _ for everybody else _ March 10.
</P>
<P>
   Supreme Court Chief Justice Tom Phillips predicted that the
limits on saving campaign ``war chests'' between elections and the
prohibition against sharing campaign funds with other political
organizations will probably be the most controversial among judges.
</P>
<P>
   Three judges on the study committee, in fact, dissented from the
latter recommendation, signaling that the road to reform will
remain rocky.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
