<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MITCHELL-COLUMN-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: through dialogue. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This was probably a good thing, because the dialogue (and much
of the acting) was barely serviceable. Taking in the speeches in
``The Warriors'' is like watching badly subtitled kung-fu movies,
with dialogue of the ``My-master-can-defeat-all-of-you-jokers!''
variety. Except that it's not delivered with that much emphasis.
</P>
<P>
   Which may explain why almost none of the actors went on to much
in acting. Of the Warriors, only James Remar continues to work
regularly. (One bit player, though, went on to win an Oscar:
Mercedes Ruehl, who made her film debut as an undercover cop.) And
the DJ, an ominous presence who provides a running commentary _
although all we see of her is a pair of rouged lips _ was played by
Lynne Thigpen, the clue-giving chief on ``Where in the World Is
Carmen Sandiego?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Warriors,'' though little heralded at the time, has become
one of the most influential action movies of all time. Directors
John Woo and Quentin Tarantino have cited the movie as being hugely
inspirational. Director Walter Hill has gone on to other seminal
action films lacking conventional morality, such as ``48 HRS.''
(You almost get the feeling that he made that film to show he could
direct actors who had to talk.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Warriors'' producer Lawrence Gordon also produced ``48 HRS''
and several other pictures with Hill. Gordon's then-assistant, Joel
Silver, is now the reigning impresario of action movies. He has
produced the ``Die Hard'' series (with Gordon) and the ``Lethal
Weapon'' movies, and is such an iconic show-biz figure that he has
been parodied in several movies. (Steve Martin did him in ``Grand
Canyon.'')
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, ``The Warriors'' seems quaint now. It lacks the
head-punching noise and music that are staples of the genre it
helped to redefine. And for which it raised the stakes: After its
release, action movies were never the same.
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
