<HEADLINE>
ECONOMY ISN'T BRAKING FOR BONDS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In December, economists were saying that the economy was going
to slow in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Bond investors liked that news because a fast-growing economy
can lead to inflation, which erodes the value of long-term bonds.
</P>
<P>
   But lately, bond fans have had a jolt.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a rally Friday, U.S. treasuries in February suffered
their biggest monthly losses since 1980, according to Ryan Labs, a
New York money management and bond research firm.
</P>
<P>
   For the month, this fall in price reduced the face value of a
$1,000 investment in a 30-year U.S. Treasury bond by about 8
percent, which pushed up the yield about 0.57 percentage points to
5.57 percent Friday, enough to catch the eyes of investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been burned severely,'' said Kevin Kennedy, who
helps oversee $32 billion of bonds at Citibank Global Asset
Management in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds sank in February as evidence piled up that a long-awaited
economic slowdown isn't about to arrive. Bond buyers had hoped the
economy would slow and spark the Federal Reserve Board to cut
interest rates again and push up the value of bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Reports on jobs, manufacturing and gross domestic product all
indicated that the economy is humming along.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the government reported that the U.S. economy grew at
a faster pace than previously estimated during the fourth quarter,
led by enthusiastic consumers and an improved trade picture.
</P>
<P>
   Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan made bond investors really nervous
last week when he told Congress that the central bank has to
evaluate whether its three interest-rate cuts last year remain
``appropriate'' now that stability has returned to world financial
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds also have lost some of their luster because investors no
longer see a need to flee to them as a safe haven from
international economic turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of Asia, such as South Korea, are improving economically,
and the Russian meltdown seems like a distant memory.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
YIELDS ARE INVITING &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The upside of all this is that bond yields look sweet, compared
with inflation, which rose just 1 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   So if you agree with Greenspan when he said the stock market
looked overvalued, it may well be time to move into bonds.
</P>
<P>
   A five-year treasury note is yielding about 5.20 percent. That
means the inflation-adjusted yield is 4.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a pretty good level on an historical basis,'' said
Thomas Donne, senior portfolio manager in fixed income at Bank One
Investment Advisors. ``On an historical basis, you shouldn't be
able to get more than 2.5 to 2.75 percentage points over
inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   With yields that fat, the stock market tends to suffer because
the risk-free yield is so appealing.
</P>
<P>
   What makes it even more tempting is that not many people believe
inflation is on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inflation is still very tame,'' said Steve Ward, chief
investment officer at Charles Schwab Investment Management. ``It's
only fear about future inflation that's driving interest rates
up.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine that the United States will soon see
inflation when the rest of the world's economies are slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deflation seems to be the major anxiety outside of the United
States,'' Donne said. ``How long can we remain unaffected by the
slowdown in the global economy in general?''
</P>
<P>
   Most central banks in other countries are leaving interest rates
alone or even lowering them, said Bob Alley, senior vice president
in fixed income at Aim Capital Management, a Houston mutual fund
firm.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FALL FRAYS NERVES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But for those folks who saw their bonds fall about 2 percent
last week, these are scary times, and these securities are likely
to continue swinging.
</P>
<P>
   This means it wouldn't be a good idea to pour all your money
into bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment statistics are due out this week, and those numbers
have been known to make or break bond prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the most important market-moving numbers that the
bond market experiences on any regular basis,'' Donne said.
</P>
<P>
   If more people found jobs than economists projected, that would
indicate that the economy is still doing fine, which would jar the
bond market. On the other hand, if the numbers come in below
expectations, bond investors may see bonds as dirt-cheap and snap
them up.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to buy bonds, buy them a little at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could buy a bond and could see the price fall later,''
Ward said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Pamela Yip can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to pamela.yip(at)chron.com, or call
(713) 220-2000 and enter access code 1003. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
