<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELLYWILLIS-CD-1500(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KELLY WILLIS DESERVES, AT LONG LAST, A LISTEN
</HEADLINE>
 By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Kelly Willis was supposed to be a star. Assured,
sexy, with a voice angels might envy, Willis cultivated a coterie
of fans who still swoon over her way with a country song. Critics
adore her. She was named one of People magazine's 50 most beautiful
people in 1994. Her first label (MCA-Nashville) invested more than
$1 million in her.
</P>
<P>
   Her one, enormous problem: She didn't sell records.
</P>
<P>
   MCA let her go. Her next label, A&AMP;M, released one EP and wasn't
crazy about it _ which led her to think that the label would try to
change her into something she wasn't, another cookie-cutter
Nashville songbird.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, she decided to leave it all behind _ being a
can't-miss-but-did critic's darling was just too painful a way to
make a living. She figured she would go back to school, settle down
in Austin, Texas, and try to be happy. Her one stipulation: She
would record one more CD. A final statement, a farewell, and then,
real life for a change. Only then could she walk away with her head
held high.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the motivation _ the way I persevered,'' said Willis,
nibbling on a muffin and drinking coffee at Quack's, a quiet
bakery/coffee shop in a working-class neighborhood north of the
University of Texas campus. ``If I didn't finish it, I would have
felt incomplete, like I didn't do something I had to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else will be your goal?'' she added, sitting slightly
forward in her chair. ``Selling millions of records? That doesn't
make you happy. You have to get down to what makes you happy.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Kelly Willis knows happy. She turned 30, she's
married to singer/songwriter Bruce Robison, and she's just released
``What I Deserve,'' a gently luminous set of songs that may well be
the benchmark CD of her stop-and-start career.
</P>
<P>
   Released Tuesday, ``Deserve'' is a beautiful record about
troublesome boyfriends, loneliness, aching confusion, the sweet
pang of attraction _ and, finally, soul mates. It is, Willis said,
truly her record in ways that three CDs for MCA between 1990 and
1993 and an EP, ``Fading Fast,'' for A&AMP;M (1996) never were: She had
a greater hand in the arrangements than ever before (''I was
telling musicians exactly what to do for the first time'') and she
wrote or co-wrote more songs on it (six out of 13) than on any
previous CD.
</P>
<P>
   It is, in other words, what it was supposed to be: her
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the songs on this CD were about struggle and what I've
been through the past five years,'' she said. ``I think they all
have to do with self-discovery.''
</P>
<P>
   For all her confidence onstage, Willis is shy; she doesn't
regard being interviewed as big fun. She is forthright, though,
even when discussing the hard times: the past two years in
record-company limbo, becoming tabloid fodder when she was briefly
linked to the then-married Lyle Lovett in 1994 _ and her youth,
which was marked by a solitary, shut-in period.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Oklahoma and raised in Virginia, Willis was devastated
at age 9 when her mom left the family. Willis simply went to her
room and stayed there. For years. ``I was pretty shy, but lonely
was the biggest thing,'' she said. ``My dad had a lot to handle. It
was hard for me. I wrote some bad teen-age poetry _ really bad. ...
I drank and smoked pot for a year, but I got over that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still in her teens, she had begun singing in a rockabilly band,
Kelly and the Fireballs. The plan was to major in drama at Virginia
Tech, but instead the band moved to Austin in December 1987. Willis
enrolled in Austin Community College, but she was really there to
make music. The band evolved into Radio Ranch and then into Willis
as a solo act.
</P>
<P>
   And after impressing MCA head Tony Brown with a showcase
performance at South by Southwest, she was signed to MCA and
recorded her debut, ``Well Traveled Love.'' The follow-up, ``Bang
Bang,'' was released in 1991, and in the next few months Willis
looked poised for stardom: She had songs on the soundtracks to
``Thelma and Louise'' and ``Boys,'' she'd had a small role in Tim
Robbins' 1992 political satire ``Bob Roberts,'' and she'd modeled
in Rolling Stone and Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
