A3373 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUMBLE-KILLER-TEX     03-01 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUMBLE-KILLER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL TEXAS TOWN HOODWINKED BY MAN WHO TURNS OUT TO BE MURDERER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By BILL HANNA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLNEY, Texas _ When Faryion Wardrip showed up in Olney a year
ago wearing an electronic monitoring device on his ankle, residents
didn't ask any questions.
</P>
<P>
   They took him at his word when he said he had been paroled after
he was convicted of accidentally killing a woman in an automobile
accident and had paid his debt to society.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Wardrip was a newly married Sunday school teacher who
never missed a day of work and fed scraps to the crippled dog at
his workplace.
</P>
<P>
   But what Wardrip didn't tell folks in this town 93 miles
northwest of Fort Worth was that he had been convicted of murder.
And two weeks ago, police said he has admitted killing three other
women _ including one in Fort Worth _ more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He definitely lied to us, that's for sure,'' said Brad Duncan,
whose family owns Olney Screen and Door where Wardrip worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I guess I can understand why. If we knew he was a
convicted murderer, there's no way we would have hired him. If I
had just thought about it, I would have figured out he wouldn't
have done that kind of time for that type of offense, but I never
did. I guess we all wanted to believe in him.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Wardrip's arrest Feb. 12 in the December 1984 death of a
Wichita Falls, Texas, woman who was raped and stabbed in a friend's
home, Olney residents have learned the grisly truth about him.
</P>
<P>
   They found out that he admitted years ago to suffocating a
Wichita Falls woman in 1986. And four days after last month's
arrest, authorities say he admitted three other slayings, including
the March 1985 death of Debbie Taylor in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Before Wardrip's confessions, Olney had mostly been known as the
home of the One Armed Dove Hunt, an annual shooting event for
amputees. Residents are stunned that their quiet town has become
known as the home of a killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely came as a shock to people in this town,'' said
Wilbur Carraway, managing editor of the Olney Enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pretty nice little town where, even though he was an
ex-con, people welcomed him, gave him a job and accepted him,''
Carraway said. ``But very few people knew him other than the people
who lived, worked or went to church with him. He wasn't really part
of the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Wardrip, 39, apparently moved to Olney because his parents lived
there and could help him land a job. He was about to celebrate his
first anniversary at Olney Screen and Door when he was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was grooming him to sit in my desk and do my job so I could
go on vacations for two weeks if I wanted to,'' said Dave Collard,
who was Wardrip's supervisor. ``He was one of the most reliable
people I had working for me. He was the last person who worked here
you would think of that would be capable of this sort of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Collard said Wardrip enjoyed his time at church and his weekly
trip to a Bible study program in Wichita Falls.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was someone who was at that church every time the door
opened,'' Collard said. ``That was a critical part of his life. I
really think he came out of prison a changed man. He told me on
more than one occasion that I wouldn't have wanted to know him
before he went to prison. He said there were a lot of drugs, a lot
of drinking.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hamilton Street Church of Christ, which has a sign out front
saying, ``You Are Welcome Here,'' apparently welcomed Wardrip.
</P>
<P>
   He taught Sunday school and occasionally read Scripture during
services, and he married Glenda Diane Kelly, 45, in the church last
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Most church members were reluctant to talk about Wardrip, and
minister Scott Clark declined an interview request. But Wardrip has
apparently tried to make amends, writing to the church to help
explain his actions, Collard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not seen the letter, but it is my understanding he
apologized,'' Collard said. ``I think that is helping many of the
church members who helped him. ... I think it gives them closure.''
</P>
<P>
   Wardrip kept a low profile at the small apartment where he lived
on the southern edge of town. Most of his contact with neighbors
came from his wife baby-sitting for others in the complex, said
Gary King, a neighbor and maintenance man for the apartment
complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was this humble man who you wouldn't think would hurt a
fly,'' King said. ``This is a place made up of senior citizens and
families with their little kids, and he misled us all, and I know
I'm pretty angry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Collard, his supervisor, said he believes that Wardrip
underwent a conversion to Christianity in prison. Still, Collard
said, he deserves the death penalty if he committed all of the
crimes to which he's confessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a true Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde type of thing,'' Collard
said. ``I truly think this is a man who changed and came out of
prison a different man. That can't change what he did 14 years ago,
and I think he knows that. He changed the lives of five families
forever and he will have to pay the price.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-99 1650EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990301.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3374 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KELLYWILLIS-CD-2ndTak     03-01 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELLYWILLIS-CD-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
AUSTIN, Texas: and Vogue. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although her first two CDs had not sold, Brown had shown
considerable faith in her, co-producing the third CD with big-time
star-making producer Don Was, who had already worked with the likes
of Willie Nelson and Bonnie Raitt.
</P>
<P>
   The same people who loved left-of-center, edgier country artists
such as Steve Earle and Lucinda Williams loved Willis' CDs, but
mainstream country radio and record buyers never caught on. Willis
was a cult item, a beautiful woman who made haunting, bare-boned
country music but who couldn't sell even 100,000 records when a
half-million was what Nashville considered a success.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, after ``Kelly Willis'' fared no better than her first
two CDs, she got her walking papers. In return, the label forgave a
debt of more than $1 million it had invested in her for promotion
and tour support. Not long after she landed on the People magazine
list, tabloids hounded her any time she and Lovett were seen dining
together. Willis became a pop-culture footnote, known as the tiny
blonde with whom Lovett was stepping out.
</P>
<P>
   Only, she said with quiet firmness, there was nothing going on
besides friendship and him working with her on a demo tape.
Nevertheless, the experience terrified her. ``I was really afraid
if I acknowledged it (the tabloid attention), I'd be Jessica Hahn
the rest of my life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Willis tried to get back on track. She released
``Fading Fast,'' a four-song EP recorded with members of the
Jayhawks, Son Volt and 16 Horsepower, on A&AMP;M Records. But A&AMP;M execs
weren't happy with it, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Chagrined, and worried that a second label would try to mold her
into something she wasn't, she asked to be dropped. ``I didn't want
to have to change myself to make everyone else happy,'' she said.
``At the time, I thought it was a great move _ but it wasn't as
easy to get back to making a record as I thought it'd be.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as Dwight Yoakam sang, things change. Willis pushed herself
to write great songs. Her confidence was bolstered by a personal
decision: She married Austin singer Bruce Robison in 1997. The
union, she said, has made her content. ``Bruce is a really strong,
positive force in my life,'' she said. ``He's always made me feel
what I do is worthwhile. I might have given up without him.''
</P>
<P>
   In mid-1997, she hooked up with producer Norman Kerner, who
offered to let her use his San Francisco studio and to pay half the
recording costs. She flew to San Francisco in August 1997 and began
recording.
</P>
<P>
   It was wrong from the start. She and Kerner didn't see
eye-to-eye on the music, she didn't like being away from Austin,
and the songs weren't turning out the way she wanted. She was
having anxiety attacks back in the hotel room at night.
</P>
<P>
   Willis played her last card. Just before the recording had
begun, she had gotten a call from Geoff Travis, founder of
England's Rough Trade Records. Now she accepted Travis' offer and
came home. ``Geoff came to my rescue,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   This time, finally, everything clicked. She knocked out
``Deserve'' in a couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them (the songs) are personal, such as `Talk Like
That,' which is about my family,'' she said. `` `What I Deserve' is
about trying to figure out your place in the world and what
acceptance means. `Happy With That' is sort of about thinking
everyone has it better than you.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Willis hopes ``What I Deserve'' will sell well; she
said she's ``in the mood to work'' and will be on the road a long
time. While she'd love to tour with Son Volt, Emmylou Harris or
Wilco, she also expresses interest in playing stadium shows with
George Strait. ``I don't have a hell of a lot of pride,'' she said
with a laugh. ``I'll play anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask Kelly Willis what her favorite song is on her new CD, and
she doesn't mention the title track, a wonderful song of hope and
self-examination that she wrote with Jayhawks leader Gary Louris.
Nor does she name the spritely gem ``Wrapped,'' one of two songs
Robison contributed to the CD.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she points to ``Time Has Told Me,'' a haunting but very
tender love song by the troubled English folk musician Nick Drake,
who overdosed on anti-depressants in November 1972.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Time has told me
</P>
<P>
   You're a rare find
</P>
<P>
   A troubled cure
</P>
<P>
   For a troubled mind
</P>
<P>
   And time has told me
</P>
<P>
   Not to ask for more
</P>
<P>
   Some day our ocean
</P>
<P>
   Will find its shore''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a love song to Bruce _ it gets to the basics of what life
is and what love is,'' she said softly. ``Success doesn't mean much
if you don't have someone to share it with. ... That's why that
song is so comforting to me. And that's what I look for in music,
to be comforted.''
</P>
<P>
   And what, given a chance, she gives back.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is music critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Contact him at dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
