<HEADER>
A3395 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLISONNOVEL-TEX     03-01 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLISONNOVEL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RALPH ELLISON'S ELUSIVE `JUNETEENTH' TO SEE PRINT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On June 19, Random House will publish ``Juneteenth,'' the second
and last novel we will ever get from Ralph Ellison. Because
Ellison's masterwork, ``Invisible Man,'' was published in 1952, and
because his second novel has been anticipated since he began
working on it in 1954, it seems almost cruel that the publisher
will make us wait any longer for ``Juneteenth.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet its publication date is appropriate, too; the book's title
refers to June 19, 1885, the date when slaves in Texas first
learned of the Emancipation Proclamation. And after this long,
what's another three months?
</P>
<P>
   Ellison never really completed ``Juneteenth,'' at least to his
satisfaction. He died in 1994, having spent much of his past 42
years trying to get everything in ``Juneteenth'' just right. There
had been false alarms; in the mid-1960s, publication seemed like a
serious possibility. But Ellison pulled it back, and only now has
Random House determined that readers can see the novel.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary information from Random House indicates that
``Juneteenth'' is the tale of a proudly racist U.S. senator who is
shot by a young black assassin. Dying, the senator summons a black
preacher to his side; ``Juneteenth'' mostly examines their past
relationship. This plot sounds, at least, as though it will be much
more direct than ``Invisible Man.'' But Ellison was a daunting
intellect who, in his first novel and later essays, seemed to want
readers to have to work for his message.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipation of this book is fueled by ongoing literary
allegiance to ``Invisible Man.'' Ellison burst into the public
consciousness with that book, which in convoluted, challenging
terms presented the frustration and fear of those socially
determined to be invisible _ blacks, certainly, but in perhaps a
larger sense the physical and financial unlovelies whose existence
would never be accepted by the powerful.
</P>
<P>
   Because Ellison was a compatriot of influential African-American
writers Richard Wright and Langston Hughes, critics at first missed
the real influences on his writing _ Fyodor Dostoyevsky and Franz
Kafka. Critics now routinely link ``Invisible Man'' with
Dostoyevsky's ``Notes from the Underground,'' and many college
literature courses require students to read these two works one
after the other.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison is a fascinating study. The grandson of slaves, he was
born in Oklahoma City in 1914. When the child was 3, his father
died and his mother went to work as a maid. She was determined her
son would get the best education possible; Ellison eventually
attended Tuskegee Institute in Alabama but left without completing
degree requirements. Burning to write, Ellison participated in
federally subsidized writing programs until entering the merchant
marine during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Ellison received a grant and devoted himself to
writing ``Invisible Man.'' That novel's success enabled him to
spend the rest of his life teaching and writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juneteenth'' often stymied him. He frequently interrupted that
frustrating task to write essays and short stories. But in the
1960s, Ellison's work came under fire from some political radicals
who believed his work did not reflect harshly enough on
white-dominated society.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967, Ellison believed he had ``Juneteenth'' just about ready
to go, but a fire destroyed his home and the pages of revisions on
which he'd been working. Ellison spent the next 27 years trying to
recapture what was lost. He died at age 80.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, there was some movement among literary circles to
have Ellison awarded the Nobel Prize. That never happened. Ellison
himself, though not a recluse, preferred to stay out of the
spotlight. He sometimes taught at New York University. Otherwise,
he believed whatever he had to say could best be discovered in what
he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Even if ``Juneteenth'' disappoints critics, it is certain to get
lots of attention. Perhaps the best way to approach the book is
realizing that ``Invisible Man,'' by its very excellence, must make
it one of a kind. Ellison may catch literary lightning in a jar
again, but it will have to be a different jar. Perhaps that
knowledge is what made it so difficult for him to complete
``Juneteenth'' to his satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-99 1707EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
