<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-WORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPROVING THE QUALITY OF CHILD CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILIAN MINCER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three years ago, the Ewing Marion Kauffman Foundation took the
first step toward improving the quality of child care in Kansas
City by providing hundreds of college scholarships to child-care
providers.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the city moved even closer to that formidable goal.
The Kauffman Foundation was joined this time by the Francis
Families Foundation and the Bank of America Foundation, the
philanthropic foundation of the newly merged NationsBank and the
Bank of America.
</P>
<P>
   The three have established a $1.2 million fund that will be used
by child-care centers to help at least 100 of them become
nationally accredited by the end of 2002. The Heart of America
United Way will oversee the fund.
</P>
<P>
   The Heart of America Family Services already provides technical
assistance to programs to help them complete the accreditation
process.
</P>
<P>
   But now, child-care centers _ which are run on notoriously tight
budgets _ will be able to use this new fund for teaching materials,
equipment and minor remodeling projects they need to meet
accreditation standards.
</P>
<P>
   Why the big push for accreditation?
</P>
<P>
   A recent study funded by the National Institute of Child Health
and Human Development found that half of the day care provided to
the youngest children in this country is considered only fair.
Fewer than one-third of the children receive excellent care and 8
percent of the care was considered poor.
</P>
<P>
   One way to significantly improve the quality of child care is to
get centers to meet national accreditation guidelines. Today, only
23 of the approximately 500 early-childhood centers in the
metropolitan area are accredited by the National Association for
the Education of Young Children. While states can accredit and
license centers, the national association is considered the
premiere standard in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Licensing provides the floor of quality,'' said Carol Scott,
manager of the Metropolitan Council on Child Care. ``Accreditation
takes you almost to the ceiling. A nationally accredited center is
not only a healthy and safe environment, it is a place where you
get support for everything the child will need to reach her
potential.''
</P>
<P>
   The long-term goal is to have 80 percent of the centers in the
city meet national accreditation by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers are trying to raise an additional $300,000 for the
fund. The Kauffman Foundation, Francis Families Foundation and
NationsBank have long supported programs that help Kansas City
children. Hopefully, others will follow their example and recognize
that what we invest in children when they are young determines what
kind of people they will be as adults.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-99 1724EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
