</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUILDING A LIFELINE ON MARS  
 INTO THE THINNEST AIR  
 BREAKING GLASS, SLOWLY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ariz., Pa.)   (af)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If humans are ever to visit other planets in this solar system
or beyond, most of the air, food, water and fuel for survival will
have to be produced on site. After all, space travel is no picnic _
it is impractical to bring your own.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a team of engineers at the University of Arizona is taking
a small step toward self-sufficiency in space. They are building an
instrument that when it arrives on Mars as expected in January 2002
will be the first to produce one of the necessities for life from
other-worldly sources.
</P>
<P>
   The device is a tiny generator that will produce oxygen from
carbon dioxide in the planet's atmosphere by electrolysis. It will
be aboard the unmanned Mars Surveyor lander that is due to be
launched in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The generator is an experimental one, and the small amounts of
oxygen produced _ about a cubic centimeter per minute _ will not be
put to use. But the project developers hope that bigger models on
future space probes will provide enough oxygen to power a drill to
take core samples or even help fuel a rocket to return samples to
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   And the same technology, on a much bigger scale, could
eventually help humans colonize Mars and other planets. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Future colonizers, however, might want to skip Callisto, one of
Jupiter's moons. New research shows that the moon has a carbon
dioxide atmosphere, but one with a surface pressure less than
10-trillionths that of Earth. Such thin air would leave even an
oxygen generator gasping for breath.
</P>
<P>
   The study, by a scientist at the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration's Jet Propulsion Laboratory, used a spectrometer
aboard the Galileo spacecraft to determine the composition of the
atmosphere, finding evidence of carbon dioxide up to 60 miles above
the moon's surface.
</P>
<P>
   The researcher, discussing the findings in a recent issue of
Science, noted that the carbon dioxide may be coming from
Callisto's interior, or by radiation's acting on carbon-bearing
compounds on the surface. Or the gas may have been the result of
bombardment by meteors and comets over the eons.
</P>
<P>
   The researcher calculated that whatever the source, without
constant replenishment the atmosphere would last only about four
years, as the ultraviolet radiation ionized the carbon dioxide
molecules and the ions were swept away by Jupiter's magnetic
field. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Normally, breaking a piece of glass is an all-or-nothing thing.
Either the glass withstands the pressure applied to it, or it
develops cracks that lead almost instantly to breakage. This is
especially true of tempered glass, which has been treated to make
it handle more strain, but breaks catastrophically when the stress
exceeds a certain level.
</P>
<P>
   Now a team of researchers has designed a way to temper glass
that allows cracks to develop and propagate in a stable manner,
without total failure. Panes of glass tempered in this way can be
examined for cracks and replaced before breakage occurred.
</P>
<P>
   With their method, the researchers, from Pennsylvania State
University, Caterpillar Inc. and the University of Trento in Italy,
turn normal chemical tempering of glass on its head. In the usual
process, sodium atoms in the surface layer of the glass are
replaced by potassium atoms.
</P>
<P>
   The potassium atoms, being slightly larger, make for a tighter
fit among the glass molecules, compressing them. (And compressed
glass can handle more stress trying to pull it apart.)
</P>
<P>
   In the new process, the researchers used potassium replacement
throughout the glass, and then added sodium atoms back, but only on
the surface. The result is glass with its compressed layers within.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, who described their technique in the journal
Science, noted that with the new glass, when a crack begins in the
surface, it reaches a compressed layer and stops. Many cracks can
form in this way before an ultimate crack that will shatter the
glass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
