<SLUG> BC-BANKRUPTCY-FILINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL BANKRUPTCY FILINGS BREAK RECORD IN 1998 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A record number of Americans filed for bankruptcy
in 1998, but the rate of the increase slowed sharply, according to
federal court figures released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The number of personal and business bankruptcy filings in 1998
was 1.44 million, which was an increase of 2.7 percent over 1997.
Individuals filing for protection under federal bankruptcy laws
accounted for the bulk of the increase, with business bankruptcies
actually declining.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's increase contrasted with the 19.1 percent increase
in 1997 and double-digit rises from 1994 to 1996, according to the
Administrative Office of the U.S. Courts.
</P>
<P>
   The number of personal bankruptcy filings in 1998 totaled 1.4
million, up 3.6 percent from 1997. The number of individuals filing
for Chapter 7 bankruptcy rose 4.7 percent in 1998 while the number
of Chapter 13 filings fell by 1.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Chapter 7 bankruptcy allows people to eliminate most of their
debts, while Chapter 13 requires people to repay all or a portion
of their debts through a court-administered plan. About 70 percent
of individuals who file for bankruptcy file under Chapter 7.
</P>
<P>
   Business bankruptcy filings dropped 21.8 percent to 44,367 in
1998 from 54,027 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The bankruptcy figures coincide with a renewed congressional
push to enact legislation that would make it harder for individuals
to eliminate all of their debts when they file for bankruptcy
protection in federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which failed to become law last year, would
require more people to file under Chapter 13 of the U.S. Bankruptcy
Code.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rick Boucher, D-Va., said the current bankruptcy code
``encourages people to walk away from their debts regardless of
whether they have the ability to repay any portion of what they
owe.'' Boucher is one of 34 co-sponsors of a bankruptcy bill that
was reintroduced in the House last week.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved the same legislation last year with
bipartisan support. Similar legislation is pending in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Credit card companies, which lose millions of dollars annually
when people file for bankruptcy protection, have been pressing
Congress to change the bankruptcy code.
</P>
<P>
   This year's bill would establish a formula that would make it
difficult for people earning more than the national median income,
which is $51,000 for a family of four, to file under Chapter 7.
People earning more than the national median income and who can pay
off at least 20 percent of their debts in five years would, in most
cases, file under Chapter 13.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has said the formula is too rigid and
has threatened to veto the legislation in its current form, but
isn't opposed to making it harder for people to walk away from most
of their debts.
</P>
<P>
   Organizations such as the Consumers Union oppose the legislation
and blame the rising number of personal bankruptcies on the credit
card companies. Consumer groups argue that the millions of credit
card solicitations that are sent out each year unfairly entice
people to take on more debt.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would require credit card issuers to give
consumers more information about the effect of only paying the
minimum amount per month, which may not even cover a monthly
interest rate of 19 percent. For example, if a person had a $2,000
credit card bill it would take more than 10 years to retire the
debt only paying the minimum amount of $10 or $15 a month without
ever adding to the debt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
