<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-STEVIA-SWEET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVIA: A SWEETENER THAT'S NOT A SWEETENER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(The Science Times) 
(HLW) 
 By JOHN O'NEIL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For centuries, sweet has meant sweet as sugar. Now a growing
number of diet-conscious Americans are turning instead to stevia, a
shrub native to South American containing sweeteners that are
essentially calorie free.
</P>
<P>
   One leading stevia supplier, Now Foods of Bloomington, Ill.,
estimates $10-million worth of the substance was sold nationwide
last year. But its market is restricted to use as a dietary
supplement, and it cannot be used in other foods or sold as a
table-top sweetener. That limitation has led to a number of clashes
with the Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jim Brandle, a Canadian agriculture department researcher
developing stevia as a commercial crop, said the leaf of Stevi
rebaudiana contained seven sweetening compounds.
</P>
<P>
   The most potent, stevioside, is almost 300 times as sweet as
sugar. It does contain calories, he said, but the amount needed to
match sugar's sweetness is next to zero, or equivalent to
artificial sweeteners like saccharine or aspertame.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, some herbal companies began to use stevia. But in
1991, the federal agency blocked the import of stevia, which now is
grown primarily in China, calling it an unapproved food additive.
The American Herbal Products Association and the Thomas J. Lipton
Co. unsuccessfully petitioned for a ``generally recognized as
safe'' exemption to stringent food testing requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. George Pauli of the FDA said that the petitions failed
either to prove widespread historical use or to present a
persuasive body of evidence. ``We were talking about ceremonial use
by Indians in the 15th century,'' he said. ``And from a scientific
standpoint, the data available were nowhere near what we expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ryan Huxtable, a professor of pharmacology at the University
of Arizona, gave a mixed assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the plus side,'' he said, ``it has been widely used in
South America and Japan and no health issues have raised
themselves. But there are a lot of gaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``For instance, animal tests have shown that at high levels
stevia can interfere with energy metabolism. Whether that takes
place in humans is unknown.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevia returned in 1994 after Congress voted to allow some
unapproved substances to be sold as dietary supplements, although
as a sweetener it was vastly different from most supplements used
as herbal medicines. ``It's 300 times sweeter than sugar, there's
really only one use for it,'' said Lynda Sadler, president of
Traditional Medicinals, a California teamaker.
</P>
<P>
   Stevia is sold in leaf form, as liquid extracts that can sweeten
with a few drops, and in tea blends, like Ms. Sadler's Mucho Mate.
Stevia has a slight aftertaste, described by some as licorice-like
and others as bitter.
</P>
<P>
   Now Foods sells stevioside powder in what look like standard
sugar packets. But selling stevia as a sweetener would be illegal,
which is why every packet bears a tiny supplement label. ``We're
walking that line a little bit,'' acknowledged Dan Richards, sales
manager for Now Foods.
</P>
<P>
   The Stevita Co., of Arlington, Texas, tripped over that line
last year after the food agency found it to be in violation of
labeling laws for displaying books with stevia recipes next to the
herb. Pauli said that the 1994 law had created a host of ``gray
areas'' for herbal manufacturers and regulators alike.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the legal issues, sales of stevia are growing, Richards
said, adding that ``We haven't scratched the surface yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
