<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Tuesday, March 2, 1999, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LOCKHEED-UNION _ Lockheed Martin Aeronautical Systems said it's
willing to resume negotiations with union members at its Marietta,
Ga., plant to avert a threatened strike. More than 4,000 members of
Local 709 of the International Association of Machinists and
Aerospace Workers said they are ready to walk out after rejecting a
contract proposal Sunday. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (f) financial and (a) general news categories.
</P>
<P>
   UTILITY-BILL _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Sen. David Sibley (R-Waco)
announced Monday he will amend his electric deregulation bill to
allow utilities to collect the full cost of new pollution equipment
_ up to $1.4 billion _ from ratepayers, who will end up paying (he
said) no more than $1 a month. Bush likes the idea, too, and it is
supposed to help clean up the state's air. (HIght, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   WEEKS-DUKEREALTY _ Weeks Corp. has agreed to be acquired by
Indianapolis Duke Realty Investments Inc. for $1.7 billion. The
combined company, which will be called Duke-Weeks Realty Corp. and
is to be based in Indianapolis, will control more than 90 million
square feet of property, primarily for industrial and office use,
and nearly 4,650 acres of undeveloped land. Annual revenues will
top $500 million. (Salter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CCE-FRANCE _ Coca-Cola Enterprises will buy bottling operations
in southern France for about $100 million in debt, allowing it to
distribute Coca-Cola drinks across all of France. Sud Boissons SA
and Societe Boissons Gazeuses de la Cote d'Azur had $70 million in
revenue and sold 18 million cases of soft drinks last year.
Coca-Cola Co. is consolidating its bottling among a few big
companies worldwide to better direct its expansion.
</P>
<P>
   DELPHI _ J.T. Battenberg III, chairman, president and chief
executive of Delphi Automotive Systems, gives one of the more
important presentations of his professional career Monday at the
Society of Automotive Engineers Congress in Detroit. His comments
could have a big impact on Delphi's future performance. (Wagner,
Dayton Daily News). 15-20.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH _
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   COXNET-PTECH 0226 _ People love cookies and milk. People hate
cookies and computers. Harmless though they might be, most Internet
users have a knee-jerk reaction to anyone or anything trying to
gather information about them. The notion that merely typing in a
Web address opens up the opportunity for companies to find out
anything at all about them is distasteful. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   w/TECH ISSUES -- The Internet carries ads for a burgeoning and
largely uncontrolled industry of ``information brokers'' that _ for
a fee _ will reveal the most intimate details of your life, right
down to that birthmark on your backside or ancient records of
psychological treatment. (Alexander, Cox Washington Bureau)
</P>
<P>
   TECH BRIEFS -- For those who think the generation gap is marked
in distance with PCs, with the young on one side of the chasm and
older folks on the other, take a look at a book from Intel that
hopes to bridge that gap. (Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY -- The Year 2000 problem is a subject that has
received enough ink to float a battleship. But there are still
smart people out there who are mixed up about the impact of the
problem. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet PTECH page for the current week. This
layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   TVGUARDIAN _ TVGuardian, The Foul Language Filter, monitors
television programs and videotapes and mutes the sound when
profanity appears on the soundtrack. Most nerd types think the
gizmo works by using some sort of sophisticated voice-recognition
system. They couldn't be more wrong says its inventor _ it reads
along on the closed captioning and when it sees a naughty word, it
shuts off the sound for a couple of seconds. James Cummings. With
photo. (Dayton Daily News). 25TECHNOPADS _ Confessions of a PDA
carrier. Why those of us with palmtop devices just can't put them
down. (Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOTAX _ There've never been more options for doing your
taxes electronically _ there are Web sites, software suites and
other computer tools that can make it easier to get squared away
with the IRS. A look at those options. (Gallaga, Austin
American-Statesman). 20
</P>
<P>
   TECH-CENTERPIECE _ Imagine a financial secretary who keeps track
of your bills, pays them when due _ and lives on the Internet or
the hard drive of your computer. That's the promise of electronic
banking: to automate the routine chores of paying bills, checking
bank balances and balancing your checkbook. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) 25
</P>
<P>
   CELLPHONES _ Clueless about going wireless? We'll give you some
tips on what you should look for when picking a cell phone
provider. Plus, chart comparing seven major carriers in Atlanta on
such things as monthly fees, price of telephones, roaming chargest,
etc.. (Jerkins, Atlanta Journal-Constitution freelancer; not for
use by NYT clients). WITH PHOTOS and LAYOUT
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in the (f) financial and (l) lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Layout in the BUSINESS folder.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY_ Trojan horses may be running wild, tapping into
your hard drive. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 18
</P>
<P>
   TECHTOOLS _ Happy99 is a relatively benign virus in that it
doesn't destroy anything. But getting rid of it can be somewhat of
a challenge. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ CompuServe2000, the revamped Internet service, is
sleek, it's cheap and it's jam-packed with news from brand-name
partners like The New York Times, CNet, Marketwatch and WebMD.
(Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 18.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ It's best to learn about hacking to prevent being
hacked. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 15.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MEDIA _ What makes Silicon Valley companies so successful?
Writer Karen Southwick thinks she's figured it out. (Haddad,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 12.
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ Apple announced more than 1,500 new software
programs for the Mac have been released. That's good news, I guess,
except where do you find all these new titles? (Haddad , Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) 12.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT _ The Web can be full of lies, which is part of its
appeal. In a Web chat room, a short, lumpy unemployed person can
become tall, svelte and gainfully employed. And no one knows the
difference. (Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 16.
</P>
