<SLUG> BC-SCI-CIRCUMCISION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIRCUMCISION'S PAIN AND BENEFITS RE-EXAMINED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., N.C.)   (af)  
 By DEBORAH STEAD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ten months ago when their baby, Grace, was born, Leon Wynter and
his wife, Yvonne Parnell Wynter, were relieved to have a newborn
daughter rather than a son for one key reason: Like many parents,
they were at odds over circumcision.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it came up, my wife said, `No, I'm not going to let it
happen,''' said Wynter, a columnist for The Wall Street Journal and
a journalism professor at Baruch College in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Circumcised at birth like most American men, Wynter said he saw
no reason to question the procedure. Also, he said, he wanted his
child to be like him. But Ms. Wynter, an operations analyst at an
investment bank, was just as resolute. She believed circumcision
would cause ``great pain to the baby'' and was ``skeptical'' that
any health benefits were worth it.
</P>
<P>
   It is not just parents like the Wynters who differ on the issue.
The American Academy of Pediatrics, which issued a new circumcision
policy Monday, has had three different policies in as many decades.
In the 1970s, the academy said there was no ``medical indication''
for circumcision. In 1989, it reported ``potential medical
benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the 55,000-member academy has concluded that although there
are potential benefits, the data are ``not significant enough'' to
recommend routine circumcision.
</P>
<P>
   And for the first time, the policy says that if parents do
circumcise a son, for cultural, religious or medical reasons,
relieving pain is ``essential.'' Recent studies show that numbing
creams and injections are safe and effective, the report says.
</P>
<P>
   The new report, which appears in the March issue of the journal
Pediatrics, also scrutinizes the potential benefits of circumcision
cited 10 years ago: lower rates of infant urinary tract infections
and of sexually transmitted diseases and penile cancer in adults.
</P>
<P>
   Although uncircumcised baby boys have a fourfold risk of getting
urinary tract infections in the first year, the report says, that
means, at most, a one in 100 chance. And although uncircumcised men
_ especially those with phimosis, the painful inability to retract
the foreskin _ have three times the risk of developing penile
cancer, that risk is ``extremely low'' in America, where only about
9 of every 1 million men are diagnosed with the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The academy also reports that while studies suggest circumcised
men have a reduced risk of contracting HIV, the virus that causes
AIDS, ``behavioral factors appear to be far more important risk
factors'' than circumcision status.
</P>
<P>
   The re-evaluation of the 1989 policy was spurred by recent
research, said Dr. Carole Lannon of the University of North
Carolina School of Medicine and head of the academy's seven-member
Circumcision Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   A study reported in the Dec. 5, 1998, issue of The Lancet, for
example, followed 58,000 newborn boys in Ontario and found
hospitalization rates for first-year urinary tract infections were
7.02 per 1,000 uncircumcised babies, compared with 1.88 for
circumcised infants.
</P>
<P>
   And pain studies published in the Jan. 1, 1998, issue of
American Family Physician and the March 1, 1997, issue of The
Lancet, found that babies circumcised with analgesic cream cried
less and had less-elevated heart rates than those whose pain was
unrelieved. The studies also found that infants circumcised without
pain relief were more distressed than other babies when they were
vaccinated four to six months later.
</P>
<P>
   The re-evaluation, the statement said, was also prompted by the
debate on circumcision in medical and parental circles. In the
1960s, about 95 percent of American-born boys were circumcised
before leaving the hospital compared with about 60 percent today,
according to the National Center for Health Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, with large populations of Hispanic and Asian
immigrants, who do not usually circumcise, as well as vocal
anti-circumcision groups, the rate is just 36 percent. (The
statistics do not include infant boys circumcised in the Jewish
ritual of the bris.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents today question the need for circumcision much more
frequently,'' said Dr. Andrew Mezey, chairman of pediatrics at Beth
Israel Medical Center and St. Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   For the Wynters, the new policy is unlikely to settle the
debate. Wynter pointed to the finding that circumcision pain is
relievable. But Ms. Wynter said she would still oppose the
procedure, ``from a maternal and humane standpoint.''
</P>
</TEXT>
