<P>
   OLYMPICS
</P>
<P>
   OLY-IOC-EXPULSIONS _ LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ IOC must deal with
possible inaccuracies in the Salt Lake report as it decides whether
to expel members. (including Atlanta) to submit reports. (Roughton,
Cox News Service and Turner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in the (s) sports and (i) international categories.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-IOC-ATLANTA _ ACOG releases details of its letter to the IOC
on a lack of abuses by IOC members during the bid for the 1996
Games. As expected, Billy Payne said nothing was done wrong except
for gifts above the guideline limits and some extra plane tickets.
(Turner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in the (s) sports and (a) general news categories.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-USOC-SALTLAKE _ The USOC recommends reforms to the bid
cities process, which includes establishing an office of compliance
and electing IOC members for limited terms. The USOC may or may not
make the proposals releases its investigative report on Salt Lake,
which is expected to recommend changes on how American bid cities
are selected. The IOC's role in the scandal and its cleanup is
likely to be a focus of the Mitchell report. (Rosen, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in the (s) sports and (a) general news categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   LOCKHEED-UNION _ Lockheed Martin Aeronautical Systems said it's
willing to resume negotiations with union members at its Marietta,
Ga., plant to avert a threatened strike. More than 4,000 members of
Local 709 of the International Association of Machinists and
Aerospace Workers said they are ready to walk out after rejecting a
contract proposal Sunday. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (f) financial and (a) general news categories.
</P>
<P>
   CDC-TYPHOID _ The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention has
sent an urgent memo to state and territorial epidemiologists and
public health laboratory directors across the country about the
ties of frozen mamey fruit to salmonella typhi. Investigators are
trying to determine whether the problem goes beyond Florida. They
are studying processing, export and import points, and urging labs
across the country to keep their reporting of tyhpoid cases up to
date. Dr. Eric Mintz of CDC said there has no discernable increase
in typhoid cases nationwide. But he also said that the bacteria
thrives in a frozen environment, and that CDC is watching the
situation very carefully. (Donald, Palm Beach Post). 10-12.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-PRESIDENT _ As another round of officials visits the Texas
Governor's Mansion Monday to encourage its occupant to run for
president, we examine this unusual uncampaign strategy: if the
campaign can't leave home, the people come to the campaign? How
many states have sent delegations? Do the delegations represent
larger interests? Have other possible presidential contenders been
wooed in this manner? What do the GOP candidates think? (Herman,
Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCOFARMERS-PROTEST _ RALEIGH _ Tobacco farmers stage
tractorcade protest Monday. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WRIGHTFLYER-TESTS _ The fragile Wright Flyer reproduction
undergoes its first day of modern wind tunnel testing in
California. Will the questions surrounding its airworthiness be
immediately answered, or will these initial tests reveal little
about how the wood-and-fabric aircraft stayed aloft? (Gaffney,
Dayton Daily News).
</P>
