<HEADER>
A3455 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-OCTUPLETS-EYES-AR     03-01 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-OCTUPLETS-EYES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DOCTOR'S WORLD: STAVING OFF BLINDNESS IN THE TINIEST OF
INFANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(The Science Times) 
(HLW) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN, M.D.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a nurse holds the hands and head of one of the seven
surviving octuplets born in Houston in December, a doctor peers at
the back of the eyes through an ophthalmoscope. In assembly-line
fashion, the eye doctor examines each child. The aim is to seek the
earliest sign of a condition known as retinopathy of prematurity,
or ROP, resulting from abnormal blood vessel growth, and to use a
laser to prevent a detached retina, which can cause blindness.
</P>
<P>
   The octuplets were born nearly four months before the mother's
due date of April 1. Like other infants born many weeks too early,
they are at high risk of developing ROP in both eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 3.9 million babies born in the United States in 1996,
about 11 percent, or 400,000, were premature, up from 9.4 percent
in 1984. Federal health officials attribute most of the rise to
larger numbers of multiple births, which increase the risk of
pre-term delivery. Many multiple births, like those of the
octuplets, result from fertility drug treatment.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, medicine now can keep alive tiny babies who
would not have survived only a few years ago. Still, some become
blind.
</P>
<P>
   The surviving octuplets, who are now 10 weeks or older, remain
at the Texas Children's Hospital in Houston. The first was born on
Dec. 8 and the seven others on Dec. 20. All weighed less than 2
pounds at birth. The smallest, a girl named Odera who weighed 10.3
ounces, died on Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
   The seven survivors are doing well, hospital officials said,
although four are in serious condition and three are still listed
as critical. All but one are consuming a combination of formula and
breast milk. One is fed intravenously.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the status of their eyesight is uncertain and will
remain so until several weeks after they leave the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   In late January, Dr. David K. Coats and his wife and
ophthalmological partner, Dr. Evelyn A. Paysse, began examining the
surviving octuplets periodically, as they would any infant born
prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   Coats spoke in interviews about the general nature of ROP, but
not about the findings in the surviving octuplets because their
parents, Nkem Chukwu, the mother, and Iyke Louis Udobi, the father,
wanted no disclosures about their babies' eyesight.
</P>
<P>
   At least 55,000 babies born prematurely each year are at highest
risk for ROP, and an estimated 1,000 of them suffer severe visual
impairment or blindness from ROP. No one has precise figures, but
they would be much higher if pediatric ophthalmologists did not use
lasers or a freezing technique to try to limit the damage in
affected babies.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 percent of tiny infants develop a mild form of ROP that
generally will not impair vision, and 10 percent escape entirely.
But 10 percent do develop a severe enough form that threatens to
cause blindness from a separation of the retina from the wall of
the eye. It is this fraction that requires treatment to prevent a
retinal detachment.
</P>
<P>
   The more premature babies are, the more likely ROP is to
develop, making the odds much higher for two groups of the tiniest
premature babies _ those with an estimated gestational age of 28
weeks or less, and those with a birthweight of 3.3 pounds. Such
babies have up to a 35 percent risk of needing treatment to prevent
blindness.
</P>
<P>
   For a group of seven or eight babies who, like the octuplets,
were 25 to 27 weeks estimated gestational age at birth, the odds
are that one or two of them will need treatment for ROP, Coats
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is you do not know which one will develop ROP,''
Coats said.
</P>
<P>
   The laser and freezing treatments, though usually successful in
preventing blindness, involve an important trade-off. ``We tell
parents that they are sacrificing varying but significant amounts
of side vision to maintain what vision has already developed and to
prevent total blindness,'' Coats said.
</P>
<P>
   Most babies are born with about 20-400 vision, which generally
does not become 20-20 until about age 6 months.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Babies born prematurely also are at risk for vision loss from
other conditions like lazy eye. About 10 percent of the tiniest
babies will become extremely nearsighted and will have to wear
glasses with lenses as thick as Coke bottles for life, beginning in
the first year.
</P>
<P>
   Infants born months prematurely have immature eyes, and the
blood vessels that nourish the retina are often absent. Normally,
at about the fourth month of fetal life, blood vessels begin to
grow from the optic nerve in an orderly fashion until they reach
the outer limits of the retina. That usually occurs about the time
a full-term baby is born.
</P>
<P>
   At best, the blood vessels will continue to grow normally,
reaching the outer margins of the retina at term without requiring
treatment. But in some premature infants, development of blood
vessels goes awry and results in ROP. A prevailing theory is that
the immature retina produces a chemical that stimulates growth of
blood vessels. Why ROP does not develop earlier than a month after
birth is not well understood.
</P>
<P>
   ROP is the new name for what was called retrolental fibroplasia
about 30 years ago. At that time, doctors were detecting the
condition in its most severe form, after the retina had detached.
Doctors also discovered that the blindness resulted from a baby's
being given excessive amounts of oxygen. Doctors still believe that
oxygen plays a role, but they can better control the amount. And
they know that laser and freezing can prevent the retinal
detachment.
</P>
<P>
   The test to detect infants whose eyes show the most severe,
abnormal growth patterns, begins with a drop of a dilating drug in
each eye. An hour later, the ophthalmologist adds a drop of local
anesthetic to minimize the infant's discomfort during the
examination.
</P>
<P>
   Looking through an ophthalmoscope, Coats determines the maturity
of the retina by examining the optic nerve, which is a direct
extension of the brain, and other areas. Then he looks at the blood
vessels, studying their width and growth pattern and looking at how
far they have spread. He must also determine if there is a smooth
transition from the areas without blood vessels to those with them,
as it should be, or if there is a sharp border, as it should not.
</P>
<P>
   In reporting damage, the doctor describes it as on a clock: He
may pinpoint a problem between ``one and three o'clock.'' At the
end of the examination, Coats checks the infant's eye muscle
movements and reaction to a bright light. The examination takes a
few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   If the blood vessel growth is normal, Coats checks again every
week or so until the retina matures and the child is no longer at
risk for ROP.
</P>
<P>
   But if the blood vessel growth pattern goes awry, and the baby
is at high risk for developing irreversible blindness, treatment is
started within three days.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, ophthalmologists relied on written notes and their
memories in following the progress of development. Now Coats sets a
special camera made by the Massie Research Co., in Dublin, Calif.,
on top of the baby's eye and obtains photographs that are about the
same quality as what he sees through an ophthalmoscope.
</P>
<P>
   Treatment is recommended when the ophthalmologist sees abnormal
growth of blood vessels in at least five contiguous, or eight
non-contiguous, hour zones.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors can choose between two therapies, either a laser or
freezing technique. Neither treatment is aimed at the abnormal
blood vessels, but at the retina that has not yet developed a blood
supply.
</P>
<P>
   Each procedure takes from 45 to 90 minutes. It can be done by
the bedside or in the operating room under general anesthesia to
avoid dealing with a moving or crying child.
</P>
<P>
   Using a laser, Coats flashes a beam on the retina from 500 to
2,000 times in each eye, depending on the severity of the
condition. The laser beam is directed in a full circle at the
peripheral retina with the hope of stopping production of the
chemical growth factor.
</P>
<P>
   In the freezing technique, known as cryotherapy, the
ophthalmologist inserts a device along the side of the eye and the
bone, pushing it until it reaches the retina in the back of the
eye. Then the doctor continually freezes the retina until the
entire outer section of the retina is treated. The procedure does
not harm the muscle, sclera and other eye tissues.
</P>
<P>
   After treatment, a child with severe ROP will be left with only
a small amount of normal retina and a less severely affected baby
with a larger area. Laser or cryotherapy is generally a one-time
application. But treatment a second time is needed in about 5
percent of infants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a cure for this disease,'' Coats said. ``We have
an intervention, which will usually result in a good visual
outcome, but not always.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite treatment, about 12 percent of treated infants develop a
retinal detachment in one or both eyes. In general, the more
premature the baby, the more likely the outcome will be poor.
</P>
<P>
   If the retina detaches, doctors will perform other procedures to
reattach it. But, at best, such procedures restore only partial
vision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
