<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALLOUT FROM MOMS' WORK: ALMOST NONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(lh) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The largest long-term study to date on working mothers has found
that employment outside the home has no significant or lasting
effect on their children's development, adding to a growing but
murky body of evidence on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Six previous studies, in fact, had taken smaller dips from the
same pool of evidence and emerged with a mishmash of conclusions:
some finding that children are harmed when mothers work outside the
home; others finding benefits, and others showing no effect at all.
Dr. Elizabeth Harvey, the author of the new study, which was
published Monday in the journal Developmental Psychology, said her
work was aimed primarily at plowing through that ``puzzling''
statistical morass.
</P>
<P>
   Despite contradictions on details, Dr. Harvey, an assistant
professor of psychology at the University of Massachusetts at
Amherst, said that seven studies agreed on what she called the big
picture: All the effects found were relatively small and fleeting.
</P>
<P>
   The studies analyzed data collected for the National
Longitudinal Survey of Youth, which began tracking 12,000 male and
female subjects in 1979, when they were between 14 and 22 years
old. Since 1986, the annual interviews have included the children
of the women, a group that now numbers about 4,000.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Harvey drew on data through 1994 to assess what effect a
mother's employment status during a child's first three years would
have later on. She found that employment status itself seemed to
leave no mark one way or another. But the children of women who
waited the longest to go back to work had the fewest behavioral
problems at ages 3 to 4. The only lasting effect Dr. Harvey found
was that the more a woman worked, the more likely her child was to
have slightly lower language skills, although the gap fell within
the test's margin of error, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many variables that affect children's
development, including the quality of parenting, the parent-child
relationship and educational opportunities,'' Dr. Harvey said.
``These findings suggest that parents are in the best position to
judge what's best for their family, and should feel good about
making either decision.''
</P>
<P>
   _ JOHN O'NEIL
</P>
<P>
   Surprise Finding on Tamoxifen and Citrus &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In trying to explain why fruits and vegetables help prevent
cancer, some researchers cite flavonoids, which are chemical
ingredients that inhibit cancer cell growth. But a new study
suggests that tangeretin, a flavonoid in citrus fruits and certain
processed foods and dietary supplements, may sometimes be harmful
because it negates the benefits of tamoxifen, the breast cancer
drug. The finding came as a surprise, since in vitro studies showed
that tangeretin acted like tamoxifen to inhibit mammary cancer
cells.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from the University Hospital in Ghent, Belgium,
wanted to see if tangeretin could amplify tamoxifen's therapeutic
effect in mice with mammary cancer. Their study was published last
month in The Journal of the National Cancer Institute. One group of
the 80 mice drank water with tamoxifen, one drank water with
tangeretin, one drank water with both substances and the fourth
group served as a control. The tamoxifen group had significantly
less tumor growth than the others and lived an average of 56 weeks,
compared with just 14 weeks for the tangeretin-tamoxifen group.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers do not know why tangeretin suppresses cancer
growth in vitro but not in mice. But a likely reason, they wrote,
is that tangeretin interfered with the mice's immune response to
the cancer cells. Tangeretin suppresses the activity of natural
killer cells in the immune system, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a provocative study, the kind of thing one pays
attention to,'' said Dr. Larry Norton, director of the solid tumor
oncology division at Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in New
York. He said the findings needed to be duplicated, but he agreed
with the researchers that women should not stop eating citrus
fruits and drinking citrus juices while taking tamoxifen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've treated hundreds of thousands of women with tamoxifen,
and we take a detailed dietary history, and we haven't noticed a
trend in which women who eat citrus fruits have adverse effects,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Norton also agreed with the researchers' advice that women cut
back on tangeretin intake from other sources while taking
tamoxifen. Those sources, which have far more tangeretin than
fruit, include its dietary supplements and beverages, baked goods
and candy flavored with citrus peel oils.
</P>
<P>
   _ SUSAN GILBERT
</P>
<P>
   Mouths at Risk When Guards Are Out &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although mouth guards can prevent dental injuries that occur
during contact sports, a University of Minnesota study says that
few athletes are wearing them.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the 318 soccer players, basketball players and wrestlers
who participated in the study believed mouth guards could help
prevent injuries, but only 6 percent reported using them.
</P>
<P>
   Participants cited discomfort, breathing and speech impairment,
lack of retention, and peer pressure as reasons for disliking mouth
guards. The study appeared this month in The Journal of Public
Health Dentistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because most kids wore boil and bite mouth guards, they found
it hard to breathe,'' said Dr. Brent Kvittem, lead author and a
pediatric dentist in Minneapolis. He referred to inexpensive mouth
guards that were first boiled, and then, while warm and soft, were
placed in the mouth to mold the device to the athlete's bite.
``Boil and bite mouth guards don't stay in place very well. With
custom-made ones, that isn't as common.''
</P>
<P>
   Among study participants who did not wear mouth guards, one in
10 reported a dental injury, among them broken, lost or chipped
teeth, bruised or cut lips, and jaw injuries.
</P>
<P>
   None of the athletes who used mouth guards reported any
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We strongly recommend that athletes use custom-fitted mouth
guards,'' Kvittem said. ``If you bump a tooth, it's possible to
cause that tooth to die, which could lead to a root canal or crown
down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``If kids can prevent injuries now, it will save them cost and
involved treatment in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALISHA BERGER
</P>
</TEXT>
