<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTORS-UNION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIT OF AFL-CIO ANNOUNCES DRIVE TO BRING PHYSICIANS INTO UNIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Leaders of organized labor on Monday announced a
$1-million drive to unionize the roughly 300,000 doctors employed
by health maintenance organizations and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   John Sweeney, president of the AFL-CIO, said salaried doctors
need unions because the ``upheaval in the health care industry is
affecting their work.'' Nearly 300,000 doctors _ 50 percent of the
nation's 600,000 practicing physicians _ are in salaried positions
in hospitals and in HMOs, making them eligible for union
membership, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have told us very clearly they fear the trend towards
corporate takeover of health care, and they've told us they want
doctors making patient-care decisions,'' Sweeney said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Stern, president of the 1.3 million Service Employees
International Union, also described the organizing drive as a
battle for improved patient care, not just for better wages and
hours for physicians, in the era of managed care programs.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a press conference at AFL-CIO headquarters here,
Stern said doctors ``take their Hippocratic oath to heal seriously.
They're kind of tired of the hypocritical oath of corporate
management.''
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of doctors belonging to unions range between 35,000
and 45,000.
</P>
<P>
   About 15,000 of them will be part of the National Doctors
Alliance, a new umbrella organization unveiled Monday by the SEIU.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance will sponsor a new organization, the National
Doctors Alliance. It will be made up of the 9,000-member Committee
of Interns and Residents, and the 1,000-member United Salaried
Physicians and Dentists, both now part of the SEIU.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, an independent group, the 2,500 member Doctors
Council, which represents doctors primarily at municipal hospitals
in New York City, will join the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   With another 2,500 doctors organized in other units of the SEIU
also joining in, the alliance starts out with a grand total of
15,000 unionized doctors. Other unions also have organized
physicians into their ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Stern told reporters the SEIU will put $1 million into a
nationwide organizing drive. He declined to name specific initial
targets for organizers.
</P>
<P>
   Organizing doctors may prove to be a steep challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law exempts doctors in group practices or partnerships
who share in managerial decision-making. But the advent of the
managed- care system of health care in the past decade has blurred
the lines of who is an employee and who is a partner.
</P>
<P>
   As a class, doctors historically have viewed themselves as
professionals, distinctly different from the blue-collar workers
who generally are the targets of labor organizing drives. Even
under managed care, doctors' pay is in the six-figure range. A
recent survey of over 700 doctors in managed care pegged their
average yearly income at $130,000.
</P>
<P>
   At the press conference, Dr. Barry Leibowitz, head of the
Doctors Council, said doctors ``have always been very poor business
people.''
</P>
<P>
   As professionals who spend years in training before they can
actually practice, salaried doctors often work 60 hours a week or
more treating patients, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Nancy Dickey, president of the American Medical
Association, said that while the doctors' organization ``continues
to be deeply concerned'' about the impact of managed care on
medicine, ``we do not believe that traditional trade union
practices ensure the integrity of the patient-physician
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickey said the AMA is ``exploring ways'' to help physicians,
following what she termed ``a strict adherence to the highest
principles of professionalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Pisano, spokeswoman for the American Association of Health
Plans, the managed-care industry's trade group, said the group had
``no quarrel'' with doctors in salaried, non-managerial positions
attempting to organize into unions.
</P>
<P>
   The actual number of HMOs that employ doctors is relatively
small, she added, because most use a contractual arrangement that
precludes union organizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we're in an environment today where there's a high
level of rhetoric geared toward managed-care plans,'' Pisano said.
``We disagree with some of the conclusions put forward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
