<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, March 2, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A swath of light-to-moderate snow will fall across parts of
Wisconsin and the lower peninsula of Michigan Tuesday as
cyclogenesis, the process by which a low pressure system forms and
intensifies, commences over the southern Great Lakes region. Two to
five inches of snow are possible to the north and west of the path
of the low.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, showers and thunderstorms will develop across parts
of the western Gulf States and the lower Mississippi, Tennessee and
Ohio Valleys as a cold front stretching southwest from the Great
Lakes low lifts increasingly moist air streaming inland from the
Gulf of Mexico. A few storms may approach severe levels later
Tuesday afternoon or night, but severe weather will likely be
limited.
</P>
<P>
   Rain will arrive in the Pacific Northwest from northern
California to Oregon as a potent low pressure system approaches
from the Pacific. Winds blowing offshore over northwest Washington
will allow some weak sun through gathering high clouds. Clouds will
thicken Tuesday night and rain will arrive later. Thunderstorms are
possible later Tuesday and Tuesday night over parts of Oregon,
northern California and Washington as a pool of very cold air at
18,000 feet destabilizes the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Snow showers and snow flurries will coat the mountains of
northern New England as moisture wraps southward around a low
pressure system to the east of Canada's James Bay. Low clouds will
likely spill eastward over the mountains to parts of the Northeast
seaboard before gradually breaking up from southeast New York
northward.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Memorable Dryness
</P>
<P>
   Rain was scarce across the southern-tier states in February.
Only a trace fell at Tucson, Ariz. Only a trace fell at
Albuquerque, N.M., insuring the city's sixth-driest winter on
record. A mere one-hundredth of an inch of rain fell at San
Antonio, Texas, marking the city's second-driest February on record
and ranking this winter as the driest in city history. At Mobile,
Ala., it was the driest February since records began in 1855. In
the absence of a robust, moist southern branch of the jet stream,
parching high pressure ruled the southern-tier states for much of
the winter.
</P>
</TEXT>
