<HEADLINE>
`STOLEN YEARS': LIVING TO TELL ABOUT THE HORROR OF STALIN'S CAMPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(ms) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Half a century ago, the Soviet gulag was still thriving, with
jammed freight cars carrying political prisoners from Moscow and
Leningrad on a long journey to the mines and factories on the
eastern borders of the empire. For many the sentence proved fatal,
but in ``Stolen Years,'' a few of those who survived return Tuesday
night with memories of their time in the merciless cold and
demoralizing conditions, doing long days of back-breaking labor
with no prospect of release.
</P>
<P>
   These men and women deliver their memories directly to the
camera, without further documentation; the accompanying pictures
are mainly atmospheric. A voice of authenticity is added by Robert
Conquest, the British historian who exposed Stalinist atrocities
before that was altogether fashionable, and nothing that we hear
Tuesday night contradicts the mass of gulag testimony
post-Solzhenitsyn.
</P>
<P>
   The shared experiences began with sudden arrests, often of whole
families, on vague charges; the dungeonlike imprisonment, the short
sham trials and the ordained long sentences. Then came the
excruciating passage across the country to places like the gold
mines of Kolyma, a huge network set in the middle of the hard frost
of nowhere. Nature's afflictions were exacerbated by human nature;
robbery and rape by the camp's criminals, tough nonpoliticals who
served as surrogates to Soviet officials, were common.
</P>
<P>
   These prisoners seemed to have been selected from the
better-educated strata. One man survived by doing illustrations,
including a portrait of Stalin on view Tuesday night and slogans
reminiscent of those of Nazi camps: ``Liberation Through Honest
Toil.'' Another tells of keeping his sanity by writing poems while
in prison. ``I spoke with God,'' he says. Indeed, anyone's survival
remains a miracle under the conditions described here so vividly.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after years of hopelessness, in 1953 there came the
death of Stalin. One prisoner tells of hearing the music of Bach
and Beethoven over the camp's loudspeakers. ``The bastard was
finished,'' he rejoiced. ``And we began kissing one another.'' But
a woman confesses to weeping over Stalin: ``I never blamed him for
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the survivors says he was arrested when he was in his 30s
and was 47 when he was released. Now in his 80s, he says in what
can serve as an epitaph to this compelling horror of 20th-century
cruelty, ``They took away the filet of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast notes:
</P>
<P>
   `STOLEN YEARS'
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. Tuesday on PBS
</P>
<P>
   Neal B. Freeman, executive producer; Jennifer Law Young,
producer; Bruce Kenneth Young, director. Music by Alexey Kovalev.
Produced by the Blackwell Corp. and presented by South Carolina
Educational Television.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
