<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-JOBBIAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT EXAMINES PUNITIVE DAMAGES IN BIAS CASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court wrestled Monday with the question
of how ``egregious'' job discrimination must be for a victim to
receive high-cost damages beyond loss-of-pay compensation.
</P>
<P>
   The question arose in the case of Carole Kolstad, who worked in
the Washington, D.C. office of the American Dental Association
(ADA) and sued her employer after she was turned down for a
promotion in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   She sued under an anti-discrimination law that permits people
who suffer intentional discrimination to collect punitive damages
as well as back pay.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, she won a $52,718 back-pay award, but the
U.S. District Court judge in her case refused to grant punitive
damages, which are intended to punish the employer and deter future
misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the U.S. Court of Appeals here agreed with that
ruling, saying Kolstad needed to prove ``egregious conduct'' on the
part of the ADA in order to win punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist said during oral arguments
over the case, ``This statute is simply confusing.'' He added,
``Nobody can pretend that it's a clear guideline as to where a
court ought to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Other justices, including Antonin Scalia, criticized the appeals
court's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really understand what is meant by an egregious act.''
said Scalia, who then joked, ``I have it. Firing on Christmas Eve.
That would do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg, also having trouble with the term
egregious, said courts must not allow it to be defined by the
worker claiming discrimination. ``Punitive damages are not going to
turn on whether an employee is thin-skinned,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice David H. Souter suggested that the law sets a stricter
standard for awarding punitive damages because it requires proof
that employers who intentionally discriminated against someone also
knew they were violating the law.
</P>
<P>
   Kolstad's lawyer, Eric Schnapper, arguing against the appeals
court ruling, insisted that his client did not have to prove
``egregious behavior'' to seek punitive damages. He said she needed
to show only that the ADA ``intentionally'' discriminated against
her because of her sex.
</P>
<P>
   Schnapper said federal job-discrimination laws, which lay out
the standards for forcing employers to pay punitive damages, never
directly set ``egregious conduct'' as a hurdle that must be
overcome.
</P>
<P>
   Kolstad's boss ``knew he was breaking the law and, therefore, my
client should be allowed to try for compensation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Raymond C. Fay, attorney for the Chicago-based ADA,
argued that allowing Kolstad to seek additional damages would let
virtually everyone who proves intentional job discrimination seek
punitive damages. He said past cases show there is a ``tradition of
a more difficult standard of proof'' for such damages.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Stephen G. Breyer asked him if the very act of firing
people because of their sex or race, and knowing the action was
unlawful, might be considered egregious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It very well may be,'' Fay answered.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court's decision, expected in July, could clarify
employers' liability when they are found to have intentionally
violated Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, which bars
employment discrimination based on race, sex, national origin and
religion.
</P>
<P>
   If the court rules in Kolstad's favor, thousands more plaintiffs
in discrimination cases will be able to seek punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   Congress amended the 1964 act in 1991 to allow people who prove
they were victims of job bias to collect punitive damages if they
can show their employer acted with ``malice or with reckless
indifference'' to their rights. The amended law also limited awards
for punitive damages to $300,000.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Kolstad was the ADA's director of federal agency relations in
Washington when the association's director of legislation announced
his retirement in 1992. Kolstad and another ADA Washington office
employee, Tom Spangler, expressed interest in the job.
</P>
<P>
   When Spangler got it, she sued, contending that the ADA chose
Spangler before a formal selection process had begun and that the
choice was motivated by sexual bias against her.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit alleged that Leonard Wheat, who headed the
association's Washington office, told sexually offensive jokes at
staff meetings and sometimes used derogatory terms to refer to
professionally prominent women. Wheat denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   In awarding her back pay in 1995, a federal jury found that the
ADA had illegally discriminated against her. The trial judge
disagreed with the verdict but said he would uphold it. Yet he
refused to allow the jury to award Kolstad punitive damages and
held that she was not entitled to have the director's position.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 a three-judge panel for the U.S. Court of Appeals for
the District of Columbia ruled that the jury should have been
allowed to consider punitive damages for her. But later that year,
the entire D.C. Court of Appeals, in a 6-5 decision, sided with the
ADA, ruling that Kostad was not entitled to punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   To recover punitive damages, the appeals court said an employee
must show not only intentional discrimination but also ``egregious
conduct'' by the employer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
