<HEADLINE>
CEMETERY REMOVES FENCE DIVIDING HISPANIC, WHITE PLOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TYNAN, Texas _ A cemetery fence that briefly separated the
gravestones bearing German and Hispanic names was removed Monday,
ending a feud that sparked threats of a civil rights lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The five-foot-high border that divided plots marked Fonseca,
Lopez and Trevino from those marked Kuhnert and Dornbusch triggered
resentment when it was erected three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday morning, 30 people watched as metal-cutting shears
sliced through the chain links at the Waldheim Cemetery, located 3
miles south of the Bee County community of Tynan and some 45 miles
northwest of Corpus Christi.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good. Now we are one country, one flag and one
cemetery, which is what we believe in,'' said Irma Reynero, 32, of
Tynan, whose relatives are buried at the cemetery that dates back
more than 80 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this was very sad. We really shouldn't have been
treated this way,'' said Willie Garcia, 58, also of Tynan. ``Seeing
the fence come down gives you a different feeling in your heart.
They're treating us equal.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there for less than a month, the fence stood as a
slight to the Hispanics in this town of 175 people.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Waldheim Cemetery Association, which maintains
the white portion of the 4-acre burial ground, voted 22-3 to remove
fence that it had early approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shouldn't have happened,'' said Howard Salge, a farmer and
member of the association.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was peace and harmony prior to this, and given some
time, peace and harmony will return,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That harmony was disrupted when E.A. Murff, then-president of
the white cemetery association, installed the fence. Murff resigned
last week after the association voted to remove the boundary.
</P>
<P>
   He has declined to be interviewed but did pass by slowly in his
tractor Monday as the fence was being dismantled.
</P>
<P>
   One of the metal fence posts was planted in the gravesite on the
Hispanic side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a desecration of a grave to string a fence over a
grave, and then to put a post through it is unforgivable,'' Salge
said.
</P>
<P>
   The American G.I. Forum, an Hispanic civil rights organization,
threatened to file a federal civil rights lawsuit, giving urgency
to the decision to remove the fence and resolve the hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the G.I. Forum said he was ``very happy'' with the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything came out beautifully. We did this peacefully. As
you can see, the fence is down and out,'' said Xico Garcia,
commander of the Hector P. Garcia chapter of the G.I. Forum in
Corpus Christi.
</P>
<P>
   Salge said he and Diana Cavazos Taylor, who represents the
Hispanic cemetery association, will iron out other details,
including how much of the 4-acre plot each group owns.
</P>
<P>
   That could take some doing.
</P>
<P>
   One hurdle will be translating the minutes, covering the period
1912 to 1948, of the original cemetery association. The German
settlers wrote those minutes in their native language.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a deed for the whole cemetery but no separate deeds
for the Anglo and Hispanic portions, so legally, it's all one
cemetery,'' Salge said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, the old minutes of the cemetery association will
reveal what is commonly believed, that at some time they gave two
acres to the Hispanics,'' Salge said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With 86 years of history and custom, the only thing would be
to formalize it and get a clear understanding of who owns what,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
