<HEADER>
A3492 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWSSTAND-0302-COX     03-01 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND-0302-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This week: Two magazines look at racial issues
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Entertainment Weekly ($2.99) offers a thoughtful piece on the
criticism of racial stereotyping in the hugely amusing animated
television series ``The PJs.'' Spike Lee has called the send-up of
ghetto life ``hateful towards black people,'' but funkster George
Clinton, who wrote the theme song, says, ``I was raised in a PJ
(housing project) in Newark, and people like these cartoon
characters exist in the flesh.'' EW points out white stereotypes
that don't draw flak _ for example Hank Hill in ``King of the
Hill'' _ and the generational differences in black humor.
</P>
<P>
   -- Seeds of hate: Why did William ``Bill'' King turn from an
average burglar into a white supremacist? U.S. News &AMP; World Report
($2.95) takes a cursory look at the three-year incarceration of the
killer sentenced to die for the Jasper, Texas dragging murder, and
at the violent world behind bars in Texas prisons.
</P>
<P>
   -- Drawing fire: Once again, The New Yorker ($3) has generated
controversy (and publicity) with the power of the brush. The March
8 cover illustration, featuring a genial cop taking aim at
silhouettes of human targets in a carnival-style shooting gallery,
angered the Patrolman's Benevolent Association as ``grossly
offensive.'' In the gallery is a sign saying ``41 shots 10 cents,''
alluding to the Feb. 4 death of unarmed immigrant Amadou Diallo,
shot at 41 times by four New York officers in the vestibule of his
N.Y. apartment. The cover is by Pulitzer Prize-winning cartoonist
Art Spiegelman, who told the Associated Press, ``This was never
intended as an insult to the officers ... but as a warning sign of
how radically the (public's) perception of a police officer has
changed.'' Inside, don't miss the personal account of gambling
fever by brothers (and frequent New Yorker contributors) Frederick
and Steven Barthelme, who are charged with cheating a Mississippi
casino.
</P>
<P>
   -- Rx for circulation: Women and health gain the attention of
the newsweeklies this week: Newsweek puts out a special edition
($3.50) with 96 pages on menopause, breast cancer, aging,
osteoporosis, depression and other concerns. At the same time
(miraculously) Time ($2.95) illustrates a cover story on ``The
Truth About Women's Bodies'' with a lush, arms-crossed nude: (The
truth? Time knows, as well as Maxim and Details, that women's
bodies sell magazines.)
</P>
<P>
   -- Nonfat: A skinny but ambitious monthly publication, bluemilk
Magazine (call 404-815-9983 for information) grew out of an Atlanta
arts collective of the same name. The current issue offers
photographs of Butler County by Mark Wolfe, an excerpt from
``Bombingham,'' a novel in progress by Anthony Grooms, and
reproductions of artwork by a variety of Atlanta-based artists.
</P>
<P>
   -- Sorry doesn't cut it: A wonderful cover story on forgiveness
in the Utne Reader ($4.99), reprinted from the Family Therapy
Networker newsletter, tries to unravel an approach to
reconciliation in an age of false apologies. It's accompanied by
six sidebars, including a provocative defense of the death penalty
from one of the Unabomber's surviving victims.
</P>
<P>
   -- Space rocks: At up to $25,000 a gram, the rarest meteorites
are 2,500 times as expensive as gold. Collectors knew this when
they began stumbling around the farms of Portales, New Mexico last
summer, hunting for any one of several fist- and head-sized chunks
of space rock that made a flashy descent into this tiny town.
Describing one 37-pounder that dropped into Nelda Wallace's
vegetable garden, the Smithsonian ($4) says ``The impact sounded
like two cars colliding and raised a cloud of dust as big as a
house.'' The magazine of the Smithsonian Institute spins an
engaging tale of dealers waving large handfuls of cash, poachers
who steal from natural history museums, and other casualties of
meteorite madness.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
