<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TINKY-SALES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teletubby controversy sees Tinky Winky sales increase
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Lee
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tickle me Tinky Winky.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of the purple Teletubby are shooting up in some stores
since the Rev. Jerry Falwell accused the children's TV character of
being a gay role model.
</P>
<P>
   In the Atlanta area, the urge to bag the bag-toting Tinky Winky
is especially strong inside the Perimeter. Many adults are buying
the toys for themselves, with some stockpiling them as potential
collectibles.
</P>
<P>
   At the GPTV (Georgia Public Television) Store of Knowledge in
Lenox Square Mall, Tinky Winky has replaced Po, the red Teletubby,
and Laa-Laa, the yellow one, as the most popular. Tinky Winky toys
have sold out at FAO Schwarz, although there are four dozen each of
the other Teletubbies on the shelves. Outwrite Bookstore in Midtown
saw its Teletubby sales rise from about 25 toys in the two weeks
before Falwell outed Tinky Winky to 150 over the past three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are adopting Tinky Winky as their own. Some are getting
it as a protest. Some are getting it for their kids to make sure
they understand that for a televangelist to bring something like
this up is offensive,'' says Outwrite owner Philip Rafshoon.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Perimeter, Tinky Winky sells about the same as he
always has, several store managers say. On online auction site
eBay, the most popular Teletubby is the red one, Po. Certain
versions of the talking Po doll _ or, as eBay sellers are calling
her, potty-mouthed Po, for her allegedly off-color sayings _ are
being touted as the next hot collectible.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
