<SLUG> BC-PARENTS-SEX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEY SAYS CHILDREN WANT TO KNOW MORE ABOUT SEX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DIANA WALSH  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Even in an era of deadly sexually transmitted
diseases, parents still are so reluctant to discuss the facts of
life with their children that they leave them wanting more.
</P>
<P>
   While almost all parents of 10- to 12-year-olds have raised such
topics as alcohol, drugs and violence, two-thirds said they have
never talked to their children about what kinds of birth control
are available and 62 percent said they have never talked about how
to prevent pregnancy and sexually transmitted diseases, according
to a national study released Monday by the Kaiser Family Foundation
and Children Now.
</P>
<P>
   When they do talk about tough issues, parents get overwhelmingly
favorable marks from their children, with more than nine out of 10
children ages 10 to 15 saying they got good information from their
parents about AIDS, sex, violence and alcohol and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But half of all 10- to 12-year-olds said they wanted more
information on how to protect themselves against the AIDS virus.
Roughly one in four said they would like to learn more about how to
handle pressure to have sex, how to know when they are ready for
sex and how to prevent pregnancy and sexually transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are looking for information about topics their parents
aren't talking about,'' said Tina Hoff of the Kaiser Family
Foundation in Menlo Park, Calif. ``Sex really stood out in the
survey. Parents seem to be having a hard time talking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Children Now lobbies for policies on behalf of Children has
offices in Oalkand, Calif., Los Angeles and New York.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone survey of 348 children ages 10 to 15 and 880
parents of children ages 6 to 15 was conducted between Sept. 15 and
Oct. 13, 1998, by the by Princeton Survey Research and Associates
in Princeton, N.J.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
