<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-UNREST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NINE DEAD IN LATEST CLASH BETWEEN MUSLIMS AND CHRISTIANS IN
INDONESIA
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Nine people died Monday in a provincial
capital when the police opened fire on a crowd outside a mosque,
several witnesses told Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings followed a new round of clashes between Muslims
and Christians in the provincial capital, Ambon, on an island about
1,400 miles east of Jakarta that has been convulsed for two months
as sectarian violence has hopscotched across this far-flung nation.
</P>
<P>
   The witnesses said the police had fired at the Muslims after
they emerged from dawn prayers at a mosque on the outskirts of the
city. ``Suddenly we were attacked by police,'' one witness said.
``They were Christians.
</P>
<P>
   Police authorities did not confirm the shooting, and some
Christians in Ambon said the officers had fired only warning shots
after Muslims and Christians fought outside the mosque. Other
witnesses said a Christian mob had set fire to several houses owned
by Muslims in a nearby neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   More than 150 people have died in religious-based battles in
Ambon since January. Native Ambonese Christians resent Muslim
migrants who have come to their island from South Sulawesi seeking
work at a time of economic hardship.
</P>
<P>
   Although Indonesia is predominantly Muslim, the groups are
balanced on Ambon, with Christians concentrated in the city and
Muslims scattered in surrounding villages.
</P>
<P>
   While the mayhem in Ambon seems very far away, its echo has
resounded in Jakarta. Monday the chief of the armed forces
announced the formation of a special unit to respond to riots and
social unrest. The unit is to be dispatched wherever violence
erupts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to handle this problem,'' said the armed forces chief,
Gen. Wiranto, at the announcement ceremony in Jakarta. ``If not, it
could create disintegration and instability on the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Setting up a special unit to handle unrest may reflect a
recognition on the part of the Army that it has mishandled previous
demonstrations. Last November, Indonesian troops opened fire on a
student protest here, killing 16 people.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 students demonstrated Monday in Jakarta, calling on
the government to accelerate its investigation of Suharto, the
former president. The rally was peaceful, and the students traveled
to a second demonstration on a bus bedecked with banners as riot
police officers watched casually.
</P>
<P>
   Although the students have resumed almost daily demonstrations
against both Suharto and President B.J. Habibie, this no longer
feels like a city on the edge of calamitous disorder. But with the
economy still in a tailspin and the country in a political fever
with elections scheduled for June, people here warn that even the
most routine demonstration could spiral out of control.
</P>
<P>
   As the riots last May showed, social unrest can also skip from
one part of Indonesia to another, and officials here are watching
the unrest in Ambon carefully.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the violence remains local, it sends a bad message about
Indonesia at a time when foreign companies and investors have begun
to venture back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a reminder to everyone that there are a lot of
potential problems in this country,'' said James W. Castle, head of
a consulting firm here. ``We have to be aware that we're in a very
delicate situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Political leaders seem acutely aware of the problem. On Saturday
the government was supposed to announce the closing of as many as
40 banks, which would have led to at least 20,000 layoffs; but at
the last minute, the government delayed the announcement for two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they simply needed more time to decide which
banks to close, but the prospect of thousands of newly jobless
people hitting the streets played a part in the decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
