<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION GRADUALLY IMPROVING   AS THEY WIN ANOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MASSA, Italy _ The Revolution are learning some painful lessons.
And, nearly a month into their preseason tour, they appear to be
making progress. They took a hard-fought 1-0 victory over Alaniya
Vladikavkaz in an exhibition match Monday, their first win against
a top-division team since arriving in Tuscany.
</P>
<P>
   Joe-Max Moore provided the difference with a well-placed free
kick in the 36th minute after drawing a foul about 22 yards from
goal. And the Revolution finally displayed cohesion in their
defensive scheme, installed by Walter Zenga _ who chose to coach
and not play _ to keep the opposition from threatening in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   This was an encouraging performance by the Revolution, though
the reserves struggled mightily in the second half, as Alaniya
twice hit the post and Manny Motajo cleared off the line.
</P>
<P>
   The Moore-Giovanni Savarese strike combination started the
contest, but Savarese was stopped on an early foray when an
opponent grabbed him by the necklace, then departed after a
suffering a deep shin bruise in the 16th minute.
</P>
<P>
   But the midfield, sparked by the aggressive play of Paulo Dos
Santos and Ivan McKinley, kept the Revolution on the attack. Jair
made a steal that led to a Mike Burns free kick, sending Moore in
alone on the goalkeeper in the 32d minute. But Yuri Mandrakian, a
17-year-old goalkeeper for the Russian Olympic team, kick-saved
Moore's low shot.
</P>
<P>
   Four minutes later, Dos Santos led a counterattack on the right
and sent a pass across to Moore. After Moore was taken down, he
drilled a low free kick around a wall of six players from Alaniya
and two teammates just inside the far post.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started moving toward what Walter wants from us,'' Jair
said. ``It is still going to take some time, since we've only been
together for three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he wants us to stay compact, keep possession, work hard
defensively as a team. When we get the ball, we have to play our
soccer and try to score some goals, but the most important thing is
to not surrender any goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Alaniya, which is on a two-month offseason tour to four European
countries, won the Russian championship in 1996 and was eighth
place last season. The team includes four Brazilians, several
Georgians, plus national team players from Belarus, Lithuania, and
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution showed some combative qualities and enough
composure to overcome their relative inexperience in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walter wants to bring to the States the Italian mentality,''
Jair said. ``He took us to the Inter-Juventus game (Saturday night)
to help us understand the Italian way of playing. They take no
risks in the back and the midfield always stays compact.''
</P>
<P>
   The trip to Milan was profitable, except for the loss of Jair's
wallet to a borsaiolo (pickpocket) in the Galeria Vittorio
Emmanuele II before the game.
</P>
<P>
   Jair and his midfield teammates, though, were doing most of the
stealing on the field Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say I'm offensive-minded, so I've really had to prove I
can play defense,'' Jair said. ``It's been good for me because it
makes me a better player. I really want to play, and that means I
have to work very hard defensively. That's the only thing I'm
concentrating on right now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have a 2-3-2 record in the preseason. They will
travel to Sicily Friday . . . They plan to cut the roster to 22
players by Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
