<HEADER>
A3504 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      03-01 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CARTER, BEING IN THE ACTION IS JUST FINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When Anson Carter was ready to return to the Bruins
after missing 15 games because of a sprained ankle, he knew coach
Pat Burns wasn't going to give him spot duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a funny feeling he was going to throw me in the fire
right away,'' said Carter, smiling broadly. Burns did, and Carter,
who made his comeback against the Oilers in Edmonton Feb. 9, has
been rolling ever since. He has been back for eight games and in
the last three he has been a fixture on the top line with Jason
Allison and Dmitri Khristich.
</P>
<P>
   Left wing Sergei Samsonov missed a pair of games with a sinus
infection, opening a spot. Carter played so well in the first two
games that when Samsonov returned Saturday against the Capitals,
Burns kept Carter up there and spotted Samsonov with other
combinations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of weird,'' said Carter. ``I think anybody can play
with anybody and we've had to learn that because Burnsie has been
known to juggle lines every now and then. You have to be ready and
aware of what other guys can do so when you get into that
situation, you know what you're going to do the second you get the
puck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ally and Dmitri are pretty skilled guys. I have a pretty good
idea where to go without the puck and I think I know what I have to
do with the puck as well, so I'm not really too surprised. The
pressure is on us to perform and that sometimes brings out the best
in players, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter already had plenty of familiarity with Allison. The two
were together in Washington before coming over in the multiplayer
deal that involved Adam Oates two years ago, and they also played
in the minors together. When they were recalled to the Capitals to
be showcased, they were put on the same line. When they arrived in
Boston, they were put together.
</P>
<P>
   But last season, the chemistry among Allison, Khristich, and
Samsonov was so strong that the combination was not about to be
broken up.
</P>
<P>
   This year, with contract holdouts and various injuries forcing
Burns to juggle, Carter ended up with Allison out of necessity and
is glad he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only been a couple of games, but I know at the same time
that Sammy is breathing down my neck because he wants to get back
in his spot,'' said Carter. ``Competition brings out the best in
players so I want to try to play the best I can to try to stay
there and help the team as much as possible. I know Sammy's working
his butt off to try to get back on the line, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, I don't think anyone is concerned with who is
playing on what line. The main thing is to make sure we're bringing
our A game to the table and we're winning games.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter didn't figure it would be him to take Samsonov's spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I'd be on that line,'' he said. ``I thought
myself, Joe (Thornton) and (Cameron Mann) had a pretty good thing
going on the second line so it has been a surprise that I moved up
so quickly to the first line. But we're all just trying to make
sure we play our best games because we can't afford any setbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   If Samsonov's gift is his amazing ability to dangle, then Carter
is more of a strength player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know my job is to get in on the forecheck and try to create
loose pucks,'' he said. ``I'm one of the stronger guys on the team
and I can use that strength to my advantage down low holding on to
pucks and making plays. Dmitri is smart and strong and Ally has a
lot of patience with the puck.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last three contests, the top line has a combined 7 goals
and 16 points. Carter said there's still room for improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first period of the Washington game, we struggled as a
line,'' he said. ``I know I wasn't going. I was a little bit slow
getting to loose pucks and that can't happen on our line. I have to
get in there and create some havoc. So when Burnsie came in yelling
and screaming, I took it personally because I knew I wasn't going
and I had to get my butt in gear.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Samsonov played just nine shifts (7 minutes 29 seconds of ice
time) against the Capitals and appeared to be still bothered by the
effects of the infection. ``I'm feeling better,'' he said after
Monday's workout. ``Today was probably my best day. I felt pretty
good in practice. I was able to work out 100 percent. It's not an
injury where you can play through it. You just take your pills and
wait. But I feel much more alive. I don't have any more symptoms.
My first game back was a little different than my usual games. You
could tell I was having sinus problems, but it's getting better
each day.'' One noticeable difference is Samsonov's color; when he
was sick, he was pale as a ghost. ``I know,'' he said. ``I looked
like custard.'' . . . Samsonov and Allison are profiled on ``Be A
Player, The Hockey Show,'' on ESPN2 Tuesday at 8:30 a.m. The show
will be replayed Wednesday on the same channel at 1 a.m. . . . Ray
Bourque was given Monday off, and defenseman Grant Ledyard was off
skates because of a sore knee. He is listed as day to day. Steve
Heinze also missed practice in suburban Wilmington because of
illness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
