A3512 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAA-BUBBLE-COX     03-01 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-BUBBLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ACC could be humbled by upstart SEC teams in NCAA brackets
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``It's incomprehensible,'' Wake Forest's Dave Odom
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine it,'' Duke's Mike Krzyzewski said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be be totally unbelievable,'' Maryland's Gary
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   What has these ACC coaches so indignant? The growing possiblity
that their tradition-rich conference might get only three
invitations when the 64-team NCAA Tournament Field is announced
Sunday (6:30 p.m., CBS).
</P>
<P>
   It's ``On the Bubble'' time, when writers and announcers wear
out that term for teams that might or might not be good enough to
get one of the 34 at-large berths once the nine-member NCAA
selection committee finishes crunching the numbers in Kansas City.
Some of these ``bubble teams'' enter this week knowing that they
have to win one or two games in their conference tournaments just
to have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches are nervous as the ACC prepares to gather in
Charlotte for its 46th annual tournamen. Since the NCAA field went
to 64 teams in 1985, the ACC has never failed to get at least four
teams in the tournament. Only once, 1995, has it failed to get five
teams in.
</P>
<P>
   But the ACC has been a top-heavy league in 1999, dominated by
No. 1 Duke and No. 5 Maryland, which are a combined 27-1 against
the rest of the conference. Throw in North Carolina (22-8), which
is No. 9 in the current Ratings Percentage Index, and the bottom
two-thirds of the ACC is 3-33 against the big three.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, no other team in the ACC has a winning record in
the conference and every team but Wake Forest (7-9), is four games
below .500 or worse. Since 1984, 11 ACC teams have made the NCAA
field with losing conference records but only one (Florida State,
1998) was 6-10. That's why the ACC is a bit antsy.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches, however, think that the strength at the top of the
ACC should help, not hurt the league's chances of getting four
teams. Several coaches, in fact, believe the conference deserves
five teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just do the math,'' Krzyzewski said. ``You play six of your
games against Top 10 teams. If you lose those, you have to win
eight of your last 10 games just to go .500. That's really tough.''
</P>
<P>
   The ACC is still the No. 2 ranked conference in the country
behind the Big Ten and that should count for something, Odom said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still the only league in the country that plays a
complete round-robin schedule and then a conference tournament,''
said Odom. ``We're doing the things the NCAA asks us to do. We're a
total conference that takes on all challengers. If that's not good
enough, then maybe we have to re-evaluate how we're scheduling and
do some things that other conferences are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The general consensus is that if Wake Forest can beat N.C. State
again in Friday's second round of the ACC Tournament, the Deacons
probably will get into the field as the fourth ACC team. They do
have an 85-72 win over Maryland on Jan. 31 when the Terps were No.
4.
</P>
<P>
   But beating N.C. State for the second time in less than a week
won't be easy. The Deacons thumped the Wolfpack 74-45 in its
regular-season finale Sunday in Winston-Salem. And if N.C. State
wins Friday's game, it could get dicey. Before Sunday's game, the
Wolfpack (17-12) had an RPI rating of 53 and only one win over a
Top 25 team (Oklahoma on Dec. 23). Oklahoma is now 19-9 and has an
RPI rating of 43.
</P>
<P>
   Things are not so nerve-wracking over in the SEC, where five
teams apparently have clinched tournament bids. Four of the five
already have 20 wins and Florida (19-7) could get to 20 by beating
LSU in the first round of the SEC Tournament on Thursday. The
Gators also have respectable RPI of 29.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC still thinks it can get six in the tournament, something
it has not done since 1987. Its best bet is Mississippi, which is
18-11, although three of those wins came against non-Division I
teams and won't be counted by the committee. But Mississippi is
rated No. 19 in strength of schedule and a pair of wins against
Arkansas. The Rebels play South Carolina in the first round of the
SEC Tournament. If they lose in the second round to Kentucky, 19-12
just might be good enough to get in.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi State (17-11) appears to be a long shot with an RPI
of 102 and a No. 142 strength of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
