<SLUG> BC-SOC-INTSOCCER-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    International Soccer notes: Ronaldo probably out of action
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reports from Italy aren't giving a favorable prognosis to Inter
Milan and star player Ronaldo for Wednesday's key European
Champions' League clash at Manchester United (2:30 p.m., live,
ESPN2).
</P>
<P>
   The Champions' League, an annual tournament during the European
domestic season, features the continent's top clubs and is the most
widely followed soccer event in the world after the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The focus on Ronaldo, a Brazilian who has played only six full
matches for Inter this season because of recurring knee problems,
hasn't tempered a bit following his mysterious illness before
Brazil lost to France in the World Cup final in July.
</P>
<P>
   A Inter club official said it is ``99 percent certain'' Ronaldo
will not play, and Roberto Baggio and Ivan Zamorano also have been
banged up in recent games. The contest has other World Cup
overtones. Manchester's David Beckham and Diego Simeone of Inter
will meet for the first time since their confrontation during the
England-Argentina second-round match in France. Beckham, who is
engaged to Spice Girl Victoria Adams, received a red card after
lightly kicking Simeone, who fell to the ground in an exaggerated
fashion. Playing a man short, England was eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   England
</P>
<P>
   French pretty-boy David Ginola, more famous for tossing his
brunet locks in a shampoo commercial than anything he's done on the
pitch, is playing so well for Tottenham Hotspur that former Dutch
great Johan Cruyff, a master of hyperbole, is calling him
``probably the most exciting player in the world.'' . . . Aston
Villa, which led the Premier League for most of the first half of
the season, is 13 points behind Manchester United after a 4-1 loss
to lowly Coventry City on Saturday. . . .Chelsea midfielder Graeme
Le Saux could face disciplinary action after punching Liverpool's
Robbie Fowler hard to the ground in a 2-1 win by the London side.
Le Saux was not called for a foul because the referee did not see
the play. . . . The FA Cup quarterfinals start Saturday with
Arsenal playing Derby County and Barnsley facing Tottenham. On
Sunday, Premier League teams Manchester United and Chelsea clash,
while Newcastle it pitted against Everton.
</P>
<P>
   Italy
</P>
<P>
   C Milan's bid for the top of the Serie A table was dashed
Saturday in a 1-0 loss to AS Roma. . . . Lazio got the winning goal
on a free kick from Sinisa Mihajlovic in the 90th minute in a 2-1
win over Vicenza. . . . Fiorentina, tied with Parma for second, has
not won a game since losing scoring star Gabriel Batistuta to a
knee injury three weeks ago. Salernitana, close to being relegated,
tied the Florentine team 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Germany
</P>
<P>
   Olaf Marschall of Kaiserslautern, who has 10 goals, will be out
as long as a month with a knee injury. He'll miss this week's
Champions' League match with Bayern Munich and possibly Germany's
next two Euro 2000 qualifying matches. . . . Bayern's Mario Basler,
who has been out with the flu, has been cleared to play. . . .
Former national team coach Berti Vogts this week joins the board of
directors at Borussia Monchengladbach, which he led to European and
German supremacy during the '70s but currently is dead last in the
Bundesliga.
</P>
<P>
   Spain
</P>
<P>
   Barcelona and Mallorca, who lead the Primera Division, are
coming off tough weeks, crashing out of the Spanish Cup and losing
in league play. Barcelona lost 4-2 to Valencia, which is third.
Mallorca drew 1-1 with 10-man and cellar-dwelling Tenerife. . . .
John Toshack's second stint as Real Madrid coach got off to a bad
start Friday in a 3-2 loss to Real Betis. Toshack, who guided
Madrid in the early 1990s, was summoned after Guus Hiddink got axed
last week with the club in seventh place. . . . Atletico Madrid's
title hopes are long gone, but the club is in the UEFA Cup
quarterfinals and today hosts AS Roma.
</P>
<P>
   France
</P>
<P>
   Three clubs have a shot at reaching the last four of the UEFA
Cup today. Olympique Marseille plays Celta Vigo of Spain, Girondins
Bordeaux meets Parma, and Olympique Lyon travels to Bologna.
</P>
<P>
   Latin America
</P>
<P>
   Players for Brazilian club Santos, which Pele elevated to fame,
are miffed at allegations that they're under orders to commit
vicious fouls. Santos was whistled for 41 fouls in a match last
week, and has averaged 35 fouls and a red card through eight
matches in the Rio-Sao Paulo league. Coach Luiz Felipe Scolari has
admitted that the tactics often are deliberate: ``I'm stupid
because I tell the truth.'' . . . Troubled Colombian striker
Faustino Asprilla has been warned by his country's soccer
federation to keep his mouth shut. Asprilla, who scored two goals
in a 3-3 friendly draw with Germany in Fort Lauderdale last week,
complained that he had to fly economy class to Italy to be in
uniform for Parma, his Serie A club. . . . Popular Mexican club
Chivas of Guadalajara has started slowly in the winter (Invierno)
league, losing 2-1 to Morelia on Sunday. Chivas is in third place
in Group A. . . . Players in Argentina's first division delayed the
start of the Clasura (Closing) season for the third week in a row
with a strike protesting the suspension of play in two lower
divisions because of crowd violence.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Parker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
