<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CCE-FRANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    2 bottlers in France being sold to CCE
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In its first major acquisition of the year, Coca-Cola
Enterprises is buying two bottling operations in southern France
for about $100 million in debt.
</P>
<P>
   The move will allow Atlanta-based CCE, the world's largest soft
drink bottler, to distribute Coca-Cola drinks in all of France,
except on the island of Corsica.
</P>
<P>
   CCE said Monday it has signed a letter of intent to purchase the
bottling operations of Sud Boissons SA and Societe Boissons
Gazeuses de la Cote d'Azur. The two bottlers, owned by the Daurella
family, had combined operating revenue of $70 million last year,
selling 18 million cases of soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we first entered the French market in 1996, we have
increased per-capita consumption almost 30 percent,'' Henry
Schimberg, CCE's president and chief executive, said in a
statement. ``We believe these new territories offer the same
opportunity to generate investment returns and increase the
shareholder value that we found in the rest of France.''
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's trading, CCE's stock closed at $31.56 1/4, up 56 1/4
cents.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Co., which owns 43 percent of CCE and has been trying
to expand its reach in France, has been consolidating its bottling
among fewer companies around the world, so it can more effectively
control its expansion. CCE already is the sole licensed bottler for
Coca-Cola products in Belgium, Great Britain, Luxembourg and the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``This acquisition demonstrates our commitment to appropriate
expansion in Western Europe,'' Schimberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contiguous acquisitions typically offer some operating and
purchasing efficiencies,'' added CCE spokeswoman Laura Brightwell
Asman. Last year, CCE spent more than $2 billion to buy a dozen
U.S. bottling operations.
</P>
<P>
   The latest deal, which will be completely financed by issuing
debt, is subject to regulatory and board approval.
</P>
<P>
   It is expected to close by the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Coca-Cola Co. has yet to submit to the French
government a revised offer for Pernod Ricard SA's Orangina beverage
unit.
</P>
<P>
   Last year French officials rejected Coca-Cola's initial $885
million bid after rival Pepsico Inc. complained the acquisition of
Orangina, which also distributes Pepsi products in France, would
give Coke too much power and squeeze Pepsi out of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Unger writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
