<P>
   ELLISON NOVEL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ On June 19, Random House will publish, appropriately
enough, ``Juneteenth,'' the second and last novel we will ever get
from Ralph Ellison. Because Ellison's masterwork ``Invisible Man''
was published in 1952, and because his second novel has been
anticipated since he began working on it in 1954, it seems almost
cruel that the publisher will make us wait any longer for
``Juneteenth.'' By JEFF GUINN. Story has moved in ``e''
entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KELLY WILLIS-CD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ After a six-year gap between full-length CDs,
alternative-country heroine Kelly Willis has just released ``What I
Deserve,'' a marvelous country-rock CD that showcases both her
emerging talent as a songwriter and her lovely voice. By DAVE
FERMAN. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILMS-MITCHELL-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Unlike ``Grease'' or the ``Star Wars'' trilogy, the
seminal 1979 film ``The Warriors'' will not receive a grand
re-release. That's because ``The Warriors,'' besides being one of
the most influential action movies ever, was also controversial;
outbreaks of violence prompted a nervous Paramount Pictures to
remove the film from theaters while it was still making money. By
ELVIS MITCHELL. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   L I F E S T Y L E &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ The ``religious right,'' considered dangerous by some
liberal politicians and theologians, isn't all bad, one liberal
scholar of religion says. Religious conservatives have forced
Americans into deeper discussion about morality in politics,
personal life, family life and the original meaning of separation
of church and state, said Ron Flowers, director of the department
of religion at Texas Christian University. By JIM JONES. Story has
moved in ``l'' lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   C O M M E N T A R Y &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WRIGHT-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ It seemed to make superficial political sense to GOP
congressional leaders, looking for something popular with big
contributors and salable to voters, to promise an
``across-the-board tax cut.'' To the surprise of the plan's
promoters, the public began saying that instead of that tax cut,
they'd prefer applying the $63 billion federal budget surplus to
protecting Social Security and paying down the national debt. The
public is generally more sensible, more responsible and less greedy
than politicians might think. By JIM WRIGHT. Story has moved in
``k'' commentary category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
