<DOCNO> NYT19990301.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3526 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-GRASSROOTS-2TAKE     03-01 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GRASSROOTS-2TAKES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``GRASSROOTS'' PUSH FOR BUSH CAREFULLY CRAFTED AT HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When Gov. George W. Bush kicked off the 76th
session of the Texas Legislature last month, he said there was too
much to do here to be crisscrossing the country in pursuit of a
2000 presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   He never said he wouldn't bring the country to him.
</P>
<P>
   Without having to leave home, Bush has methodically assembled a
team of likely advisers, collected commitments from deep-pocketed
contributors and hosted delegations from several key states, all
urging him to run.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, it is a modern version of the ``front porch''
campaign that former Ohio Gov. William McKinley conducted in his
successful White House race more than 100 years ago _ but Bush is
using the back yard of the Texas Governor's Mansion as the setting
for some of his political pep rallies.
</P>
<P>
   A typical example was the pilgrimage to Austin last week by
Colorado Gov. Bill Owens, who grew up in Fort Worth, and U.S. Rep.
Scott McInnis, R-Colo. Flanking the governor, they urged Bush to
run and predicted he'll win if he does.
</P>
<P>
   McInnis, repeating what Bush aides have been saying for weeks,
denied there has been any orchestration of the ``Draft Bush''
movement that has gained ground among Republicans in Congress and
in a growing number of statehouses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The request is not coming from Texas. The request is coming
from the other direction,'' McInnis said. Owens added: ``He didn't
call us. We made the call.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Bush can count on loyal support and money without
ever picking up the phone, thanks to an extensive network of
friends and former associates of his father who are eager for him
to get in the race.
</P>
<P>
   But interviews, letters and published reports suggest that the
seeds of the ``grassroots'' movement to get Bush into the
presidential race were carefully planted long ago _ largely by Karl
Rove, the architect of Bush's political strategy and organization.
</P>
<P>
   Rove acknowledged coordinating the visits, but said a snowball
effect has taken hold. Now, states are cold-calling with offers to
send petitions and delegations to Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting calls from people saying we've got one, do we send
it to you?'' Rove said.
___
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 18, Bush's political office in Texas issued the
following news release: ``As a courtesy, we are forwarding two
press releases issued in South Carolina ... and New Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Both reported that sizable numbers of GOP legislators in those
states were calling on Bush to get in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Described as an isolated, spontaneous outburst of support, the
effort to round up support in New Mexico was, in fact, carefully
coordinated with Rove from Austin, according to the leader of the
effort there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called (Rove) and said, `If you guys want to do something
... give me a call, I'm ready to help,' '' said Colin McMillan, a
former assistant secretary of defense under President Bush. ``I
asked him what he wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(Rove) said, `Well, you might consider doing this,' ''
McMillan added, referring to the draft movement that snared more
than three-quarters of the Republicans in the state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, fax machines in Austin were whirring with the news
release from McMillan and the one from South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly one week later, Alabama weighed in, with Attorney
General Bill Pryor _ another Rove client and avowed Bush fan _
leading the charge. Pryor said he was inspired by what other states
were doing, and decided to ``follow the lead.''
</P>
<P>
   While he said he needed no encouragement from Rove, Pryor said
he has talked with the consultant about Bush, and he cited a kind
letter from the governor that he says compelled him to ``do
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Dated Jan. 29, the letter reads, in part: ``Karl told me of your
kind words of encouragement to run for President. If I decide to
seek higher office, I would very much appreciate your support.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying he would decide by spring, Bush asked Pryor to ``keep
your powder dry until then.''
___
</P>
<P>
   If Bush seems eager to keep in touch with potential supporters,
he is by no means alone.
</P>
<P>
   A year before he helped organize a group of legislators to jump
on the ``Draft Bush'' bandwagon, Iowa farmer Thurman Gaskill
remembers the excitement he felt after receiving a message from
another George Bush _ the former president _ congratulating him on
his election to a Senate seat there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He left a message on my machine,'' said Gaskill. ``It blew my
mind.'' Asked if he thought Bush was trying to woo him on behalf of
his son, Gaskill described the former president as a proud father
who would do anything ``appropriate to assist him in the political
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaskill is typical of the legislators who are helping organize
the nascent Bush 2000 campaign in the American heartland, and his
participation underscores the formidable network waiting to be put
into motion.
</P>
<P>
   His ties to the former president go back to 1980, when he
organized Farmers for Bush in the key state, which holds the
nation's first presidential caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   It was Gaskill and fellow farmer Tom Dorr, also a former Bush
political activist, who helped round up support among Republicans
in the Iowa Legislature for the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   The two also helped put together a trip to Austin to visit with
Bush and urge him to get into the race. Dorr said Bush officials
did not ``engineer it in any stretch of the imagination,'' and
described the group as ``just a bunch of old country boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Those country boys were nevertheless able to hitch a ride to
Austin on corporate jets provided by two major Republican
contributors in Des Moines _ trucking magnate John Ruan, head of
Ruan Transportation, and insurance baron Gerald Kirke, co-founder
of the firm Kirke Van Orsdel.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to reach Ruan or his spokesman were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   But in a measure of the insular and ironic world of politics, it
was Kirke's firm that provided corporate jet rides to John Sununu _
President Bush's former chief of staff _ after he was caught using
military planes for personal and political trips in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Another irony: Kirke was meeting with former Vice President Dan
Quayle, an announced presidential candidate, on the very day he
lent his plane to the Iowa legislators who came to Texas to visit
Bush. (He said the lawmakers reimbursed him for the flight, as Iowa
law requires).
</P>
<P>
   ``I was interested for them to get down there to find out what
this is all about,'' Kirke said, adding that he was asked by a
lobbyist to arrange the trip. ``I want to see what George Bush
stands for. I want to see him come out and be questioned.''
(MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   While Bush has publicly expressed a reluctance to get into the
race, in part because his twin teen-age daughters are skittish
about a national campaign, his state political operation has been
regularly mailing video updates to supporters across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   As far back as August, four months before his re-election as
governor, Bush mailed videos to out-of-state contributors and
supporters, said Mindy Tucker, a spokesman for the Bush political
office. Four have gone out so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes out to donors of $500 and up, and supporters who have
expressed an interest in the governor's activities,'' she said.
``It's probably 90 percent donors _ donors and interested
supporters.''
</P>
<P>
   Containing short political documentaries, campaign ads and plain
news footage, the tapes are the work of Austin media consultant
Mark McKinnon, a veteran of Texas Democratic campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The news clips on the tapes contain multiple references to
Bush's possible entry into the 2000 presidential race. McKinnon's
combination of heroic music, slow motion and a variety of film
formats _ including grainy 8mm clips from an old home movie camera
_ give the longer tribute pieces an unmistakable documentary feel.
___
</P>
<P>
   By bringing the early ``draft'' campaign to Austin, and mailing
out videos beyond, Bush has been able to line up support from the
comfort of his own mansion while honoring his commitment to work
hard on Texas issues.
</P>
<P>
   Aides say he'll form a presidential ``exploratory'' committee
within two weeks, and Bush has lined up a team of advisers. And
late Friday, Bush officials announced that delegations from three
more states were coming to visit.
</P>
<P>
   In 1896, William McKinley's political man, Mark Hanna, carefully
orchestrated a front porch campaign that brought thousands of
supporters to Canton, Ohio, avoiding a national tour that he
thought ``demeaned the office,'' according to a 1996 issue of
History Today.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Bush camp is using ``a combination of William
McKinley's campaign and the (draft) Colin Powell campaign that
never was,'' said University of Virginia political scientist Larry
Sabato.
</P>
<P>
   While the differences between 1896 and 2000 are as numerous as
the similarities, the parallels are not lost on Rove.
</P>
<P>
   Asked during a recent public appearance to describe a scenario
in which Republicans could retake the White House after eight years
of Bill Clinton, Rove effortlessly drifted back over 100 years for
an answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's 1896, not 1998,'' Rove said. ``All the guys from the
Civil War are dying off. ... There's a new economy rising.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forwarding to modern America, Rove says the ``governing
paradigm of the Cold War is gone ... a generation of leadership is
passing away ... there's a new economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not Bush is the candidate to seize the moment, and
become the candidate of change, is another question. While he is
able to capitalize both on his outsider status and his family's
deep political connections, that may not last forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long is it going to be before his Republican opponents
and/or Al Gore say, `Remember George Bush senior? Do you really
want to go back to those tragic, depressing times?' '' asked
Sabato, author of a book about end-of-century politics called
Toward the Millennium. ``His father is his greatest asset and his
heaviest burden.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-99 1839EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
