<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3535 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-HARASSMENT-HNS     03-01 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-HARASSMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVIDED JUSTICES TO TO RULE ON SEXUAL HARASSMENT, DAMAGES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court, in a case that could affect
thousands of lawsuits, appeared divided Monday as it considered how
invidious sex discrimination must be before federal law permits
punitive damages against an employer.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for discrimination victim Carole Kolstad and for the
Clinton administration, which is supporting her view, argued that
the 1991 Civil Rights Act allows victims of intentional bias to
collect punitive damages if a jury finds their employers
discriminated maliciously or with reckless indifference to their
rights.
</P>
<P>
   But an attorney for the American Dental Association, Kolstad's
employer, countered that punitive damages are available only in
extreme cases of intentional discrimination, such as when the
company showed an ``egregious'' disregard for the law.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, often splitting into blocs that defied their usual
ideological differences, seemed as divided as the attorneys as they
weighed when punitive damages are available under the 1991 act. For
example, conservative Justice Antonin Scalia and the moderate
Justice David H. Souter, generally on opposing sides in civil
rights cases, appeared united as they expressed the view that the
law permits juries to award punitive damages in many intentional
sex discrimination cases.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1991 law, victims of intentional sex bias can collect
punitive damages if a jury concludes that their employer acted
``with malice or with reckless indifference'' to their statutory
rights. The law also limits to $300,000 the amount of punitive
damages that a jury can award.
</P>
<P>
   The statute is essentially an amendment to Title VII of the 1964
Civil Rights Act, which prohibits job discrimination on the basis
of sex, race, color, religion and national origin.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, which
enforces anti-discrimination laws, reported that 24,454 Title VII
cases alleging sex bias were filed with the agency in fiscal year
1998, which ended Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Eric Schnapper, pressing the case for Kolstad, who was
passed over for a lucrative lobbyist position at the American
Dental Association, argued that the law states that victims of
intentional sex discrimination must prove only that the employer
showed a reckless indifference to their legal rights to collect
punitive damages. Companies that intentionally discriminate can
escape being assessed punitive damages if they sincerely believed
their discrimination was legal, the Seattle attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Schnapper noted that the law permits companies to
intentionally discriminate against women if being a man is a ``bona
fide occupational qualification reasonably necessary for the normal
operation of that particular business or enterprise.'' Legal
experts say that such a male-only job might include the starring
role in the television series ``Father Knows Best.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Solicitor General Seth Waxman, pressing the Clinton
administration's support for the woman, told the justices that the
law gives juries latitude to assess punitive damages against
companies that intentionally discriminate. The law sets
``explicit'' standards for punitive damages, including the reckless
indifference of employers, the Justice Department lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   But the arguments that the law is clear has lost in both the
federal district court and U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in
Washington _ a point not lost on Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist.
</P>
<P>
   ``This statute is simply confusing,'' Rehnquist said, noting
that the issue of punitive damages sharply divided the federal
appeals court, which ruled 6-5 against the woman. Punitive damages,
Rehnquist said, are generally reserved to punish companies for only
the most reckless behavior.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Stephen G. Breyer, in a comment supporting
Schnapper's position, said that intentionally discriminating
against a woman because of her sex is itself outrageous and perhaps
warrants punitive damages. ``I don't think there's a human being in
the United States'' who does not know that intentional sex
discrimination is illegal, Breyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Countering Schnapper and Waxman, the dental association's
attorney argued that punitive damages are available only for the
most serious violations of law. Historically, federal law, judges
and juries have limited punitive damages to instances when
employers showed an ``egregious'' disregard for an employee's
statutory rights, said Washington attorney Raymond Fay.
</P>
<P>
   However, Souter and Scalia disagreed, saying the 1991 law
mentions only reckless, not egregious, disregard. Scalia, a
stickler for remaining true to the words of a statute and not
trying to broaden their meaning, said Fay's reading of the act
brings confusion, not clarity, to the 1991 law.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you mean by an egregious act?'' Scalia asked. ``Can
you have a really egregious firing?''
</P>
<P>
   Fay responded that Congress in passing the 1991 law did not
intend to alter the historical standard that punitive damages be
awarded only in exceptionally severe circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The case the justices heard arose in the fall of 1992, when
Kolstad, then the dental association's director of federal agency
regulations, was passed over in favor of a man for a promotion to
director of legislative policy. Kolstad sued the association,
claiming she was rejected because of her sex.
</P>
<P>
   The federal district court jury ruled that the association
intentionally discriminated against Kolstad and awarded her $52,718
in back pay, but only after a federal judge held that the company's
behavior was not malicious enough to warrant punitive damages. The
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the district court's denial of
punitive damages, ruling that such awards are available only when
companies have committed ``particularly egregious violations'' of
the law.
</P>
<P>
   Kolstad then appealed to the Supreme Court. The justices are
expected to render their decision in the case, Kolstad vs. American
Dental Association, by July.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
