<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ISRAELIS, A NERVOUS DAY AWAITING RETALIATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The morning after an Israeli bombardment of
guerrilla targets in Lebanon, the northernmost residents of Israel
awoke Monday to a strange lull, unsure whether the conflict would
intensify or fade away.
</P>
<P>
   At Kibbutz Maayan Baruch, close to the border, some were tempted
into defying government orders to stay ensconced in bomb shelters,
like the teen-age boys who kicked a soccer ball outside in the
crisp air of late winter.
</P>
<P>
   At lunchtime, Amnon and Hannah Shamosh heard the kibbutz's
loudspeaker crackling, warning residents to report back to their
underground bunkers. Mr. and Mrs. Shamosh, who are in their 70s,
consider themselves too old to spend any more time in the drab,
chilly shelters.
</P>
<P>
   So they stayed put in their home, anxiously awaiting familiar
sounds: the buzz of Katyusha rockets, the menacing hum of
helicopters and the roar of fighter planes heading off on a bombing
mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone else is in their safe room, but we're here at home,
waiting for these machos to escalate the whole thing one more
time,'' Shamosh, a writer who has lived there for 52 years, said in
a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   The escalation never came. Everything remained quiet on the
northern front of Israel, where tens of thousands of Israelis
endure the simmering conflict in South Lebanon as a fact of their
daily lives.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's Cabinet decided not to act
unless the guerrillas of Hezbollah, or Party of God, attacked
first. By evening, the Iranian-backed Shiite Muslim guerrillas had
fired no rockets and ambushed no soldiers, and Israel's northern
residents were permitted to emerge from underground after 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Under international pressure to exercise restraint, Netanyahu
ordered no fresh attacks, and no unusual military buildup was
visible on the border. The prime minister did, however, promise
future strikes, although they did not seem to be imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue the battle against Hezbollah because they
continue the battle against us,'' Netanyahu said. ``I'm not going
to get into operational steps, but we have our planes well laid out
and our targets well chosen.''
</P>
<P>
   In retaliation for a week of guerrilla attacks that left seven
Israelis dead and for the firing of Katyusha rockets on northern
settlements, Israel unleashed one of its sharpest military
offensives since 1996 on Sunday night. Its warplanes traveled deep
into Lebanon to bomb guerrilla strongholds.
</P>
<P>
   The army chief-of-staff, Lt. Gen. Shaul Mofaz, almost seemed to
be declaring an invasion of Lebanon when he said on Sunday night
that Israel was prepared, if necessary, to continue assaults ``on
the ground, in the air and from the sea.'' But he was using a
military cliche to assert that the army would be as aggressive as
required.
</P>
<P>
   The army on Monday released Persian Gulf war-style footage of
the bombings to Israeli television, showing buildings exploding in
the crosshairs of the plane's scope.
</P>
<P>
   In Beirut, a Hezbollah spokesman, Ibrahim Moussawi, said that
the Israeli army had conducted about 12 raids. He said the eastern
part of the Bekaa city of Baalbek, which includes Hezbollah
headquarters, was ``physically damaged, but there were no
casualties.'' Hezbollah's construction company, Jihad al Binaa, was
expected move in quickly to repair the damage, as it usually does
to keep civilian morale from dropping.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Israeli army also bombed the underground bunkers of a
radical Palestinian group in Naame, a city just south of Beirut.
But Moussawi said it has been empty for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always do this one,'' Moussawi said, referring to
previous bombings of the same bunkers.
</P>
<P>
   Timur Goksel, the senior adviser for U.N. forces in Lebanon,
said there had been only one raid in the southern zone, calling it
``nothing out of the ordinary'' and ``nothing special.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, on the Hezbollah cable television station in
Beirut, the guerrilla group sought to capitalize on its military
successes. A roadside bomb early on Sunday killed four Israelis,
including a general and a journalist.
</P>
<P>
   After a Hezbollah anchorwoman, wrapped in a Muslim headscarf,
reported the raids on the Israelis, advertisements sought fresh
recruits _ anyone, of any religion, they said, who wanted to join
``the resistance.''
</P>
<P>
   With rockets, bombs, grenades and machine guns, Hezbollah is
waging a low-level war to push Israel out of southern Lebanon,
where it has maintained a nine-mile-deep buffer zone since 1985 to
protect its northern settlements.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week, Hezbollah has mounted a media offensive of
sorts. Last week, machine gun-toting guerrillas took several dozen
journalists on a tour of the front line in southern Lebanon. They
traveled by bus, albeit with blacked-out windows, sampled Turkish
coffee and croissants and watched a video of Hezbollah's
self-described ``greatest hits'' _including grainy footage of bomb
plantings and searches through rubble for body parts. (The video is
available for $10 from the cable station, Dar al Manar.)
</P>
<P>
   After the deadly bombing on Sunday, a convey of beeping mopeds
and honking cars drove through West Beirut, waving the yellow flag
of the guerrillas and cheering.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel on Monday, three of the four bombing victims were
buried. A funeral for the fourth, Brig. Gen. Erez Gerstein, will be
held on Tuesday. Gerstein, who headed the army's liaison unit with
the Israeli-backed South Lebanese Army, was the highest-ranking
officer to die in the southern Lebanon conflict in 17 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
