<HEADER>
A3542 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-01 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE INEVITABILITY OF GEORGE BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There is a growing sense in the Republican Party
and among the political pundits that Gov. George W. Bush is the
inevitable GOP presidential nominee next year even though he has
barely set foot outside Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Most GOP governors have already endorsed him, delegates at a
recent California GOP state convention embraced him in absentia,
party bigwigs and organizers are rushing to his side and the polls
show him the clear leader in a crowded nomination field. He beats
Vice President Al Gore, the putative Democratic nominee, in early
trial heats.
</P>
<P>
   Wow. And whoa.
</P>
<P>
   The caboose is getting ahead of the engine here, or at least the
conclusion, ahead of the process. The national political game is
notorious for its impatience, but this is runaway wishful thinking.
</P>
<P>
   There are reasons for it. Bush has by all accounts been an
effective and well-regarded governor in a large state rich in
campaign contributions. As the son of former President George Bush,
his lineage means instant name identification. He has the benefit
of his father's past experience and contacts.
</P>
<P>
   With two exceptions his possible rivals are a sorry lot. And the
public opinion surveys are signaling that unlike the others he may
be electable.
</P>
<P>
   But, again, wait a minute. Frontrunners don't always go the
distance. Does anybody remember President Edmund Muskie? President
George Romney? President Edward Kennedy?
</P>
<P>
   These men too looked like certain winners more than a year
before the primaries and the presidential conventions. But
eventually they actually had to campaign, explain where they stood,
counter their opponents' charges, avoid blunders and rally voters.
The result _ oops.
</P>
<P>
   On a national level Bush may be able to straddle the GOP's major
ideological divisions as he has in Texas, transcending the
religious right's mean-fisted grip on his party and appealing to
Hispanics and other groups traditionally undervalued by
conservatives. Or he may not.
</P>
<P>
   We do not know yet how, or even if, he proposes to do this.
</P>
<P>
   We do not know how the southwestern son of a defeated Republican
president will sell in Iowa, or New Hampshire, or elsewhere in the
country. His speaking style is roughly as exciting as Gore's. In an
era of little political privacy, he has suggested that in his youth
he was less than perfectly behaved.
</P>
<P>
   Although mostly composed of right-wing pipsqueaks, his potential
GOP competitors include two formidable moderate figures _ Elizabeth
Dole, a former two-time Cabinet officer, and Arizona Sen. John
McCain, a much-respected campaign finance reformer. Bush may well
be ahead in organizing and fund-raising, but that's just the
beginning. Texas Sen. Phil Gramm was wallowing in campaign money at
a similar early period before the 1996 campaign, but it did him
little good with the voters.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the ghosts of campaigns past.
</P>
<P>
   After his landslide re-election as Michigan governor in 1966,
George Romney instantly became the favorite for the 1968 Republican
presidential nomination. He didn't last through the first primary
in New Hampshire _ cut off at the knees by an unwise comment that
he had been ``brainwashed'' about Vietnam and by the quiet
maneuvering of that supposed has-been, Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   The next presidential campaign, in 1972, quickly did in a
Democratic frontrunner, Muskie, who had been the 1968 vice
presidential nominee. Before the primaries, Muskie not only led the
Democratic pack but beat President Nixon by 5 percentage points in
the polls. Then the press said he cried in New Hampshire (he always
insisted snowflakes had dampened his cheeks), and that was that.
The weakest candidate, George McGovern, won the privilege of being
wiped out by Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, Sen Edward Kennedy was the favorite of the Democratic
Party, which had already given up on a remote and inadequate
President Jimmy Carter. For months, the political spin touted
Kennedy as his party's popular savior.
</P>
<P>
   But when Kennedy finally ran, he couldn't articulate why he
chose to take on an incumbent Democrat. He split the party, lost
the primaries and handed a softened-up Carter over to a conquering
Ronald Reagan. And so, the pining for a second Kennedy presidency
for a decade and a half ignominiously died.
</P>
<P>
   Some frontrunners do succeed. This is not to dismiss Bush, but
merely to urge caution. Hold the horses a bit longer.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Hubert Humphrey in 1968, Governor Carter in 1976,
Gov. Ronald Reagan in 1980 and Sen. Bob Dole in 1996 sailed to
victory with only minor scares. Others barely fended off surprises
_ the classic example being former Vice President Walter Mondale in
1984, who didn't seal the Democratic nomination for president until
the last primary round.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
