<P>
   CHINA-U.S. (Beijing) _ Trying to infuse the troubled
relationship between the United States and China with a new sense
of direction, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright speaks sternly
to the authorities here about human rights but also encourages them
to move forward on joining the organization that governs world
trade. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-FASCISM (Moscow) _ How dangerous a threat is posed by
neo-fascism is one of the main questions under debate in Russia. It
is not difficult to make a comparison between Russia today and
pre-Hitler Germany _ a collapsed economy, an electorate that feels
bitter and betrayed, a weak central government. But for all the
scare talk, Russia's neo-fascist groups are still small and
marginal. Some experts maintain that they are creatures of the old
KGB, while others argue conspiratorially that they are used by the
authorities to whip up pre-election anxieties that will drive
voters back into the embrace of the political establishment. By
Celestine Bohlen. With graphic. 1,600 words. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   PA-RETARDED-ABUSE (Polk, Pa.) _ Doctors at Pennsylvania's
largest home for retarded people are charged with manslaughter and
other crimes in their treatment of residents. By Michael Janofsky.
1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   CREDITCARD-SHIFT (Undated) _ Your credit card company, and your
interest rate, may not be the one you think it is. Tens of millions
of Americans have been facing a stark choice _ to take new terms or
leave them _ as the credit-card business rapidly consolidates into
fewer and larger hands. About 32 million accounts were sold last
year, mainly by regional banks like PNC, Keycorp, First Maryland
and First Union. That is more than four times as many as in 1996.
Because many people have multiple accounts, the sales involved some
20 million consumers. The figures do not include transfers
resulting from mergers. By Robert D. Hershey Jr. 1,800 words.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-STATE-POLICE (Trenton, N.J.) _ A day after firing the head of
the New Jersey State police for making racially offensive remarks,
Gov. Christe Whitman defends her administration's response to
persistent charges that state troopers use ``racial profiling'' to
target black and Latino motorists and says she will move quickly to
restore public confidence in the force. By David Kocieniewski.
</P>
<P>
   TRUCK-SAFETY (Detroit) _ Federal regulators say the stiffness of
light-truck bodies, on top of their height, is responsible for
killing an additional 1,000 motorists a year. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-REPORT (Undated) _ A ``culture of gift giving'' starting at
the top of the Olympics led to the biggest scandal in the history
of the games, an elite ethics panel said. A commission headed by
George Mitchell, the former Senate Democratic leader, said reform
was needed from the International Olympic Committee on down to
avoid a repeat of the million-dollar bribery case that has
tarnished Salt Lake City's winning bid for the 2002 Winter Games.
By Richard Sandomir.
</P>
</TEXT>
