<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3548 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIGERIA-OBASANJO-ART-     03-01 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-OBASANJO-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGERIA'S PRESIDENT-ELECT IS A MAN OF CONTRADICTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NIGERIA-VOTE) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAGOS, Nigeria _ Gen. Olusegun Obasanjo, who will soon become
Nigeria's first elected president after 16 years of military
dictatorships, is an anomaly in this country's recent history, and
a man of apparent contradictions.
</P>
<P>
   One of eight generals to have ruled Nigeria since independence
from Britain in 1960, he is best known as the only one to have
given up power voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   On a continent where ethnic identity is a critical piece of
self-definition and has been the basis of countless conflicts, he
is trusted by Nigeria's northern Hausa-Fulani, while many of his
fellow Yoruba in the south look at him askance.
</P>
<P>
   Having caused resentment for governing with a strong hand before
1979, the year his first presidency ended, he also gained respect
after being jailed in 1995 as an outspoken critic of the military
dictatorship. He was released from prison only eight months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Regarded in the rest of Africa and in the West as a defender of
democracy, he is mistrusted by many Nigerians for his military past
and his links to powerful fellow retired generals who are believed
to have bankrolled his road to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   All those contradictions might prove to be both his strengths
and weaknesses over the next four years of his presidency. At 61 _
he turns 62 later this week _ he is a man at once free of the rigid
molds that have divided Africa's most populous nation and lacking
in the bedrock ethnic support that has been the foundation of most
politicians in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Having presented himself during the campaign as a safe bridge
between the present military government and a future civilian
administration, Obasanjo is to assume the presidency on May 29.
</P>
<P>
   After the end of his first presidency in 1979, Obasanjo
established a farm about 35 miles north of here, where he raised
pigs and cultivated bananas. He also cultivated the reputation of
an elder statesman, even as he has kept his image as a
short-tempered, gruff soldier. In a ``Who's Who in Nigeria,'' he
listed his hobbies as ``farming, table tennis, snooker, squash.''
</P>
<P>
   During an appearance on national television last week, he scored
points with the audience by alluding to a traditional, earthy
Nigerian stew made with ground melon seeds. It was a successful, if
sincere, version of President Bush's political use of pork rinds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know I like eating pounded yam, especially with egusi
soup,'' he said. ``And you know that I enjoy it more when I eat
with my fingers. It tastes better when you're able to lick your
fingers.''
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo was born in Abeokuta, about 60 miles north of here in
the heart of Yorubaland, on March 5, 1937. In the same city, within
a year of his birth, were born two other future Yoruba giants,
Moshood Abiola, the opposition leader and presumed winner of the
1993 presidential election, and Fela Anikulapo-Kuti, the creator of
Afro-beat music and social critic. The Yoruba, along with the
Hausa-Fulani and the Ibo, are one of Nigeria's three main ethnic
groups.
</P>
<P>
   A Christian, Obasanjo attended Baptist Boys' High School, along
with Abiola. He worked as a teacher for a year before joining the
army in 1958. After receiving training in Britain and India, he
rose quickly within the ranks. During the Biafran civil war, when
the Ibo tried to secede, he was put in charge of a commando unit
that obtained the surrender of a rebel leader, effectively ending
the fighting in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, after the longtime military ruler indefinitely
postponed a promised return to civilian rule, Gen. Murtala Muhammad
staged a coup and began a program to hand over power to civilians
in 1979. But after Muhammad was assassinated in a failed coup,
Obasanjo, his deputy, was named president.
</P>
<P>
   Domestically, Obasanjo stuck to the program of transition. And
in foreign policy, it was under him that Nigeria, emboldened by the
gush of oil money, began flexing its muscles. In international
diplomatic circles, Nigeria became the leading African opponent of
white-ruled regimes in South Africa _ Obasanjo was one of the few
prominent people to visit Nelson Mandela in jail _ Namibia and the
former Rhodesia, now Zimbabwe. It also became the center of
liberation movements whose leaders operated out of Lagos.
</P>
<P>
   After President Carter came to office with an emphasis on human
rights, the two leaders established a relationship that has lasted
to this day. Obasanjo visited Washington in October 1977. Half a
year later, Nigeria welcomed Carter, who became the first American
president to pay a state visit to a sub-Saharan country. Obasanjo
earned lasting esteem when elections were held in 1979 as planned,
and he stepped down for the civilian president, Shehu Shagari.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But to many of his fellow Yoruba, it was the biggest of many
perceived acts of betrayal. The elections had been close and
Obasanjo had called them in favor of Shagari, a northerner, over an
opponent who was a Yoruba.
</P>
<P>
   In Lagos and the rest of Yorubaland, Obasanjo is also remembered
for a violent crackdown on students protesting tuition hikes.
Soldiers also continued to use brutal tactics, and one of the most
famous cases involved the late Fela, his fellow native of Abeokuta
and one of the most vocal critics of the military.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, under Obasanjo's rule, soldiers burned down Fela's
compound in Lagos and threw his 77-year-old mother out a
second-story window. After his mother died of her injuries, Fela
wrote one of his most famous songs, ``Coffin for Head of State,''
which tells, in street slang, how he and his followers carried the
coffin and tried to present it to the general:
</P>
<P>
   waka waka waka waka we reach dem gate o.
</P>
<P>
   waka waka waka we put the coffin down waka.
</P>
<P>
   waka waka Obasanjo dey there with him big fat stomach.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, many Yoruba have not forgiven Obasanjo for the 1979
elections and his ties to the north. ``He's Yoruba, but he has
deceived us,'' said Afusa Oladunni, a 37-year-old civil servant, as
she voted on Saturday, in a typical comment.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Obasanjo earned northerners' enduring trust by
yielding power to one of their own. And he used the respect he had
earned outside Nigeria to carry out diplomatic missions for the
United Nations and the British Commonwealth across Africa. A decade
ago, he was considered for the position of U.N. secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is an African leader, with the possible
exception of Nelson Mandela, who is better known or respected by a
multiplicity of international organizations as Obasanjo is,'' said
Carter, who led a delegation of American election monitors.
</P>
<P>
   But Carter said it would be crucial for Obasanjo _ who will now
govern the country as an elected president and not as a military
ruler _ to overcome the distrust of the south. ``I think it will be
a handicap for him,'' Carter said. ``How he reaches out to the
groups who did not support him, especially in the south, will have
important consequences for him.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Gen. Ibrahim Babangida _ who is close to Obasanjo and
believed to have contributed greatly to his recent campaign efforts
_ annulled the results of a presidential election that Abiola, the
Abeokuta native and a billionaire businessman, was on his way to
winning.
</P>
<P>
   Abiola was imprisoned in 1994 for refusing to renounce his claim
to the presidency; Obasanjo angered his fellow Yoruba when he said
that Abiola was ``not a messiah.'' As Nigeria plunged into crisis
under the repressive regime of Gen. Sani Abacha, Obasanjo became an
outspoken critic of the military government and was himself
imprisoned in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   He was released only after Abacha's sudden death last June. In
the bewildering series of events that followed, Abiola died in
July, still under government detention. And a few weeks later, Gen.
Abdulsalami Abubakar, who had assumed power, announced a timetable
for elections.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement led to many calls inside and outside Nigeria
for Obasanjo to run for the presidency. He is, his campaign argued,
the only Nigerian capable of keeping this fractious country
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a great pity that, at every crisis, big or small, people
talk of Nigeria breaking up,'' Obasanjo said last July, four months
before declaring his intention to run. ``The enormous challenge
facing us now is to get beyond these mutual suspicions.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Obasanjo has yet to explain how he will meet that
challenge. But it is clearly the one he will face his second time
as president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
