<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUTCHISON BILL WOULD SNUFF OUT GOVERNMENT ATTEMPTS TO SHARE IN
STATES' TOBACCO FUNDS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ County judges from across Texas were on Capitol
Hill on Tuesday pushing legislation authored by Sen. Kay Bailey
Hutchison that would prohibit the federal government from sharing
in any of the tobacco settlement money negotiated by state and
local officials.
</P>
<P>
   The Hutchison bill, which is attracting broad support from
Republicans and Democrats, is to get a full airing late next week
in a hearing before the Senate Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But in the meantime, she told Harris County Judge Robert Eckels
and other Texas judges in a meeting that she hopes to convince
other lawmakers to sign on as co-sponsors of the bill to help
ensure ``that every dollar obtained by the states (in the tobacco
settlements) stays there.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has been trying since 1997 to share in
some of the hundreds of billions in payments negotiated in deals
between the states and the tobacco companies. The Clinton
administration has argued that it is entitled to some of the money
to help recoup Medicaid payments to the states for the treatment of
smoking-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government picks up about 50 percent of each state's
Medicaid costs. But despite the federal infusion of health-related
dollars, state and local officials argue that Washington is not
entitled to any money because it did not participate in litigation
that eventually led to all 50 states reaching deals with the
tobacco industry worth more than $246 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Texas, for example, is expected to receive about $2.2 billion
from tobacco companies, with an initial payment of about $450
million being made over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   Harris County, which includes most of Houston and is the most
populous county in the state with 3.1 million people, &UR;  &LR;  will
receive about $40 million this year, all of it earmarked for county
health care programs that cater to the indigent and working poor
who do not qualify for Medicaid or other kinds of health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are dollars that are going to indigent persons who have
nowhere else to turn,`` Eckels said. He added that federal attempts
to intervene in the state tobacco settlements to recoup Medicaid
payments could cost the county millions that have already been
budgeted for various health services.
</P>
<P>
   Eckels said Harris County health facilities now treat about
300,000 poor people a year who have no health insurance. But based
on the county's projected share of tobacco settlement funds in
coming years, county facilities will soon be able to provide
services to more than twice that number.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the federal government gets its hands on any of that
tobacco money ... it would completely change the kind of services
we're able to provide,'' Eckels said. He suggested that those
revenue losses would have to be made up somewhere else, possibly
from increased property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Senate and House rejected a tobacco bill last year
aimed at forcing tobacco companies to reach a settlement with the
federal government. A provision in that bill supported by Hutchison
would have prevented Washington from intervening in settlement
deals between the states and tobacco companies in an attempt to
recoup some of its Medicaid payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to allow that to happen. We're going to fight
it every step of the way,'' Hutchison told the judges Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Republican predicted that her bill would pass this
year because it is no longer part of a larger and more complicated
tobacco measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's become more of a states rights issue,'' said one
Hutchison aide, who noted that the senator's bill has been endorsed
by the National Governors' Association.
</P>
<P>
   Eckels agreed. ``I think there's a good chance that her bill
will pass. It's already got 38 co-sponsors, and its going be hard,
I think, for members to go against what the governors and their
local officials are telling them is in the best interest of the
counties.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
