<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3558 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-CASINOS-BOS &LR;      03-01 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-CASINOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE GAMBLERS BEAT PATH TO CONNECTICUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts residents spend an estimated $620 million
per year at Connecticut's two Indian-run casinos and visit the
facilities more than gamblers from any other state, according to a
report released this week.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Bay State residents patronizing Foxwoods Resort &AMP;
Casino in Ledyard, Conn., has grown by 9 percent in the past three
years, despite or perhaps because of, the opening of the Mohegan
Sun Casino, in neighboring Uncasville.
</P>
<P>
   ``Massachusetts residents are the single most important
ingredient fueling the economic engine of Connecticut's two
phenomenally successful casinos,'' said Clyde W. Barrow, director
of the University of Massachusetts at Dartmouth's Center for Policy
Analysis, which conducted the study. ``Other than federal income
tax payments, the money spent by Massachusetts residents at
Foxwoods and Mohegan Sun casinos is one of the greatest
out-of-state expenditures of Massachusetts personal income.''
</P>
<P>
   The report is sure to inflame the aleady intense debate over
whether to expand legalized gambling in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The UMass-Dartmouth study was commissioned by the Visions Group,
a consortium of business and community leaders who want to build a
world-class casino and resort on the North Shore's Salisbury Beach.
</P>
<P>
   But they are not the only interested parties looking to the
Connecticut casinos as proof that Massachusetts could become a
gambling gold mine.
</P>
<P>
   The Wampanoag tribe in New Bedford and the state's race tracks,
among others, are also pushing to open up the state to slot
machines or high-stakes bingo at a time when some Beacon Hill
leaders, including House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran, seem to be
warming up to gambling.
</P>
<P>
   However, Massachusetts residents, who have seen the Legislature
reject gambling measures in the past, appear to be beating a path,
rather than holding their breath.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 36 percent of the patrons at Foxwoods are from
Massachusetts, spending $469 million a year at what has become the
world's largest and most successful casino. About 28 percent, the
next largest group of Foxwoods' visitors, comes from within
Connecticut's borders.
</P>
<P>
   Bay State gamblers also make up about 23 percent of the vistors
at Mohegan Sun, spending about $151 million there each year. Only
Connecticut residents visited Mohegan Sun more, representing 48
percent of the patrons.
</P>
<P>
   The ``patron origin analysis'' was conducted between Feb. 11 and
Feb. 15 and is based on a sampling of 6,876 cars and 201 tour buses
at Foxwoods. Likewise, the study looked at the license plates on
6,517 cars and 183 tour buses at Mohegan Sun.
</P>
<P>
   The center completed a similar study in October 1995 at
Foxwoods, finding that 33 percent of its gamblers were from
Massachusetts. Mohegan Sun opened one year later.
</P>
<P>
   ``In just over three years, Massachusetts residents
patronization has grown by over 9 percent, while a new casino,
Mohegan Sun, in just over two years of operation, has seen
Massachusetts patrons comprise 23 percent of all its customers,''
Barrow said. ``Clearly, Massachusetts residents are voting for
gaming with their automobiles, buses and pocketbooks.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrow also said the recently announced $950 million expansion
by the Mohegan Sun casino underscores the belief that New England
may be the most ``underutilized'' gaming market in the country,
with an estimated $2 billion to $3 billion in annual discretionary
gaming revenue up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the No. 2 casino in a non-traditional gaming region to
make a nearly $1 billion investment in gaming expansion is unheard
of,'' Barrow added. ``Were this Las Vegas or Atlantic City, it
would be big news. For it to happen in the wooded hills of southern
New England, it is absolutely stunning news.''
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, Massachusetts residents are making 7.7 million
visits to the two Connecticut casinos, a number Barrows says will
grow.
</P>
<P>
   Mohegan Sun and Foxwoods are betting on it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
