<HEADLINE>
FOX ON THE SCENT OF LIVE TALES FROM THE CRYPT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Geraldo Rivera broke into Al Capone's vault to find an empty
bottle. A year or two later, on Halloween, William Shatner tried to
rouse Harry Houdini from the dead. Not logical, Spock could have
told him.
</P>
<P>
   So TV has a history of beguiling the gullible with deliciously
dumb stunts. But unlike most previous spectacles, Fox's over-gassed
pyramid scheme Tuesday night carries a sort of quasi-scientific
stamp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opening the Lost Tombs: Live From Egypt'' will feature a
``flashlight cam'' as Fox, host Maury Povich _ next week on Maury:
cross-dressing pharaohs _ and their Egyptian cronies traipse into a
5,000-year-old, previously undisturbed tomb on live TV.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's a three-hour tape delay for West Coast viewers.
Still, that's closer to live than anything Fox is likely to find in
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   Fox is conducting its crypt crawl with the blessing of the
government of Egypt, the Supreme Council of the Egyptian
Antiquities Organization and Zahi A. Hawass, pre-eminent
Egyptologist and undersecretary of state of Egypt's Giza Plateau.
</P>
<P>
   But without the blessing, one supposes, of the deceased ancients
who may find themselves on display.
</P>
<P>
   This could happen to any of us. Our mortal remains are peaceably
salted away for five millennia. Then some TV crew barges in for the
purpose of entertaining bored, overweight teenagers halfway across
the globe so ratings will be artificially boosted and local TV
stations can charge more for vaginal disinfectant commercials.
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly what's happening Tuesday night. Could be a
compelling argument for cremation.
</P>
<P>
   I can't profess expertise, but with Hawass leading the way, Fox
apparently will poke into several dark holes.
</P>
<P>
   It's something about the pyramid of Queen Khamerernebty II and
the sealed Tomb of the Unknown, in the vicinity of the burial place
of Kai, high priest to Senefru, Khafre and Tofu. Wait, sorry, it's
Khufu; Tofu's buried at Safeway.
</P>
<P>
   But however many syllables you want to wrap around it, it comes
down to Hawass, Povich et al. hoping to stumble onto a mummy.
</P>
<P>
   Not many decades ago, Egyptian mummies were so plentiful and
lightly regarded that they were burned for fuel. Now they're the
stars of TV specials.
</P>
<P>
   Count on Fox to milk this event for the whole two hours before
we get a peek at anything nifty. And because it's Fox, I expect
chatter about bloodcurdling ancient curses, as well as old movie
footage of giant mummies lumbering around and creeping out
mustachioed English actors.
</P>
<P>
   Are we scared, or what? Wouldn't it be great if they finally
busted into a tomb, a mummy sat upright with its arms extended and
Povich didn't stop running till he was aboard his plane in Cairo?
</P>
<P>
   But maybe you were expecting pure science? Go give yourself a
good whack on the instep and listen to executive producer Peter
Isacksen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not your mother's Egypt,'' Isacksen crowed in a recent
interview. ``I mean, we're going to show it in a really new,
inventive, Fox-like way.''
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned for ``World's Scariest Mummy Chases.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
