<SLUG> BC-GUN-BILLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL WOULD REGULATE FIREARMS AS A CONSUMER PRODUCT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A toy gun, gun control advocates like to point out,
is subject to more regulations than a handgun that kills.
</P>
<P>
   They say they hope that will change Tuesday with the
introduction of a bill to require the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco
and Firearms to regulate guns like any other consumer product, such
as drugs or cars, for the first time ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's outrageous that our government is powerless to regulate
this industry and is unable to warn consumers of the risks guns
pose,'' said Representative Patrick J. Kennedy, Democrat of Rhode
Island, who is co-sponsoring the bill with Senator Robert
Torricelli, Democrat of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, guns would be subject to consumer health and
safety regulations. ATF would be able to recall a gun model if it
is defective, set minimum safety standards, require warning lables
and recall a product that is defective or unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   Prospects for the bill's passage are dim in such a gun-friendly
Congress. But, as lawsuits mount against the gun industry, it is
important because it parallels the tobacco industry's fight to
simultaneously fend off legal action in court and a congressional
push to regulate its products.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control supporters hope the bill may eventually figure into
settlement discussions with the industry, even if it fails in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Not unlike the tobacco industry, the gun industry so far has
rejected attempts to impose consumer and safety regulations on the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're already a much more heavily regulated industry than
other industries out there,'' said Richard Feldman, president of
the American Shooting Sports Council. ``The last I checked you
didn't need a firearms license to sell a toy gun, and you didn't
need a background check or a fingerprint check to buy a toy gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Feldman said lawsuits don't stem from the production of faulty
products as much as from a gun's misuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will the ATF be testing to see whether children can bite the
trigger off a gun and ingest it?'' he asked. ``We have never been
sued for this. We get sued because the gun does what it is supposed
to do: it is fired, but in the wrong direction, so that it hurts
someone or some property.''
</P>
<P>
   But gun control advocates and others insist that the wave of
lawsuits claiming that firearms are faulty products and that guns
are a public nuisance and a health hazard has come about precisely
because of the absence of regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The American Bar Association pointed out, in a letter of support
to Torricelli, that the Governmental Accounting Office reported
that one-third of gun accidents that kill children could have been
prevented by requiring trigger locks and safety regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Kristen Rand, senior lawyer at the Violence Policy Center, a
Washington gun control group, pointed out that firearms kill more
Americans every year than all household and recreational products
combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first step toward ending the gun industry's deadly
immunity from regulation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Prospects for legislative action, however, are poor in a
Congress dominated by gun control opponents and National Rifle
Association supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``One wonders whether in a Republican-controlled Congress a bill
to give ATF the power to regulate the gun industry has a snowball's
chance in hell,'' said Carl T. Bogus, a professor of law and expert
in product liability at the University of Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the bill dies, gun control advocates say it is
essential to have Congress push for concesssions from the gun
industry _ especially in the wake of reports last week that
industry representatives already have begun preliminary discussions
with some of the plaintiffs in the lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Because the bill provides a ``benchmark'' for what constitutes
``real regulation,'' Rand said, it will help ensure that the
plaintiffs do not let the gun industry off the hook unless it
agrees to be regulated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-99 1911EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
