<HEADER>
A3570 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-PRESCRIPTIONS-     03-01 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-PRESCRIPTIONS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRTUAL DRUGSTORES MAY CHANGE THE FACE OF PRESCRIPTION DRUGS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)  
 &HT;    
 BY SUZANNE LEIGH  
 c.1999 Medical Tribune News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Face-to-face interactions between patient and pharmacist may
become a thing of the past with more people turning to the Internet
to take the bureaucracy out of healthcare.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of standing in line at drugstores and waiting for a
pharmacist to hand over prescription drugs, many patients are
opting to order medications online.
</P>
<P>
   Drugstore chains like Rite Aid and Walgreens established online
prescription refill services two years ago, enabling patients to
order drugs from the Internet and pick them up when they're ready.
</P>
<P>
   But now one company is claiming to go one step further in
customer convenience by allowing patients to order drugs and
receive a pharmacist consultation via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtual'' pharmacy Drugstore.com in Redmond, Wash., started
its online service last week (http://drugstore.com). The store
allows a patient to receive medications in the mail by filling out
information from the doctor's prescription. Customers create a
patient profile by completing online forms about medical
conditions, current medications and known drug allergies.
Drugstore.com pharmacists review the information, contact the
patient's doctor if necessary and alert the customer to the
processing status of the prescription.
</P>
<P>
   When the prescription is ready, customers pay by sending
credit-card information to an encrypted site.
</P>
<P>
   Questions to the pharmacist can be sent via e-mail or phone.
Medications are meant to arrive within five business days.
</P>
<P>
   Certain drugs that may be abused, such as morphine and
amphetamines, cannot legally be prescribed by e-mail or phone, and
are thus not available through online services.
</P>
<P>
   Drugstore.com boasts better prices than other pharmacies, thanks
to its lower overhead. A 30-day, 10 milligram prescription for the
antihistamine Claritin costs $58.50 plus $4.95 shipping from
Drugstore.com (shipping costs are free if total purchases are more
than $75). Rite Aid and Walgreens stores in San Francisco charge
$77.69 and $76.39, respectively. (Drug prices vary widely from
state to state.)
</P>
<P>
   Andy Stergachis, director of pharmacy services and quality
assurance at Drugstore.com, said the company aimed to provide a
higher level of care than that offered by community pharmacies.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the point of view of convenience and privacy we offer a
better service than most pharmacies. We ask the patient to describe
current conditions and speak to the doctor if anything suggests the
dose is not appropriate or there may be adverse reactions with
other prescription or over-the-counter drugs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stergachis added that an increasingly Web-savvy population means
that people want to use the Internet as a tool to take charge of
their health, shop around for good prices for prescription drugs
and speak to a pharmacist when and where it is convenient for them.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies are getting into the on-line prescription
business. Medicaledge.com in Lawrence, N.Y., started an online
prescription drug ordering service last month
(http://www.medicaledge.com). Customers place orders online and
then either fax in prescriptions or have their physicians call them
in. A second company, Express Scripts in St. Louis, is also about
to launch an online prescription Web site.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone welcomes the advent of online prescriptions.
Carmen A. Di Cello, chief executive officer of the Pennsylvania
Pharmacists Association in Harrisburg and the owner of two
pharmacies, said the Internet's invasion into prescription
medications represented a disturbing trend in patient care.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not selling books, we're selling medications. Patients
need a continuous face-to-face relationship with their pharmacist.
And the pharmacist should be developing relationships with the
physicians,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real problem is that drug companies are gouging the public
with inflated drug prices and pharmacies are under more and more
pressure to keep their prices low. Instead of initiatives like
Internet drugstores, we should be looking at why pharmaceutical
companies need to mark up their products by as much as 20 to 25
percent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many patients, especially older people taking a variety of
medications, require very careful monitoring,'' he said, noting
that one of his own customers mentioned that she had been taking
high doses of aspirin together with a prescription blood-thinner
drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I hadn't caught that, this woman could have bled to death.
It's the kind of situation that might not be picked up if a
customer's only contact with her pharmacist is over the Internet,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
