<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-STRIKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. JETS STRIKE IRAQI TARGETS FOR 3RD STRAIGHT DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A day after mounting an attack that Iraq said had
disabled an oil pipeline, American jets attacked a dozen targets in
northern Iraq on Monday. It was the most intense flurry of strikes
since four nights of American and British raids in December,
Pentagon officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to what the Pentagon described as Iraqi provocations,
American F-15E jets based in Turkey dropped more than 30
precision-guided bombs in an hour on an array of Iraqi air defense
sites including anti-aircraft artillery, communication centers and
radio towers, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third consecutive day of American air strikes in
Iraq, in a pattern of increasingly broad and aggressive attacks by
American and British jets patrolling the no-flight zones in
northern and southern Iraq in the wake of December's raids.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Defense William Cohen said Monday that American
jets ``may or may not'' have disrupted an oil pipeline between Iraq
and Turkey when they attacked a radio tower in northern Iraq on
Sunday, but that they had not set out to disrupt the flow of oil.
</P>
<P>
   He said the tower was a military target because it was used for
communications by Iraqi forces as they challenged American and
British jets patrolling northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``We responded to attacks upon our aircraft by targeting those
facilities that allowed the Iraqi forces to place our pilots in
jeopardy,'' Cohen said at the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqi officials seemed eager to draw attention to the damage to
undercut the Pentagon's statements that the repeated strikes _ on
average, every other day for two months _ have focused on military
targets.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq initially said the attack on Sunday had damaged a pumping
station, but on Monday, when Iraqi officials took journalists to
show them the damage, they took them to a radio tower. Images on
CNN clearly showed damage to the site, though the tower remained
standing. Iraq said that Monday's strikes had caused more damage to
the pipeline and killed at least one civilian.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline, which runs from Kirkuk to the Turkish port of
Ceyhan, carries more than a million barrels of oil a day, half of
what Iraq exports under a U.N. program that allows Iraq's
government to raise up to $5.2 billion every six months to buy food
and medicine. John Mills, a spokesman for the U.N. agency that
oversees the program, said the pipeline was shut down on Sunday
evening, reopened briefly and then shut down again. Communications
sites like the one damaged on Sunday are crucial to operating a
pipeline, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The length of the disruption depends on the extent of the damage
at the installation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said American jets would continue to strike as long as
Iraqi forces threatened them. Monday's flurry of strikes began, the
Pentagon said, when Iraqi radar sites tracked American jets, which
is seen as a possible prelude to an attack. Operating under orders
allowing them to strike any military targets, not just those that
challenge them directly, the jets pounded an array of military
sites near Mosul.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
