<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3579 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIGERIA-VOTE-ART-615&AMP;     03-01 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-VOTE-ART-615&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGERIA'S PRESIDENT-ELECT PROMISES COMMITMENT TO DEMOCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NIGERIA-OBASANJO) 
(ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAGOS, Nigeria _ Gen. Olusegun Obasanjo, who was officially
declared Nigeria's next president on Monday, pledged to foster
democracy in a country where years of corrupt military misrule have
squandered vast oil-wealth and restricted the freedom of one in six
Africans.
</P>
<P>
   Final results in Saturday's presidential elections showed the
retired general winning a decisive victory, with 63 percent of the
popular vote. But his rival, Olu Falae, seized on reports of fraud
and irregularities to dispute the results, although he did not say
how far he would take his challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome appeared to have been accepted by a nation weary
from 16 years of uninterrupted dictatorships and nine convulsive
months that, at times, threatened to irreparably widen the ethnic,
religious and regional fissures in Africa's most populous land.
Lagos _ a base for Falae and a city that has often expressed its
political displeasure with dramatic violence _ was quiet as night
fell.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly for Obasanjo _ who will inherit a country on the
verge of economic collapse, with the price of oil plummeting to
generational lows _ the United States, Britain and France issued
statements welcoming the election's outcome. Oil companies from the
three countries have billions of dollars invested in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   The vote now holds the promise of democratization for the
country's 108 million citizens, who make up a sixth of the
continent's population.
</P>
<P>
   ``Election is not the end of democracy,'' the president-elect
told reporters in Abuja, the capital. ``Democracy is a process.
Election is just one important event in the process, and democracy
under my own leadership will continue.''
</P>
<P>
   The election was peaceful but marred by what international
observers described as serious fraud and irregularities including
ballot box stuffing and inflated results in some regions. They said
irregularities occurred on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Most observers described the cheating as not significant enough
to change the election's outcome, especially given the wide margin
of victory. Former President Jimmy Carter, however, wrote to the
independent commission overseeing the elections that because of the
fraud, his team of observers could not ``make an accurate judgment
about the outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo acknowledged the existence of irregularities, but
called on Falae, a former finance minister, to accept the outcome
for the sake of national unity. In a letter to the election
commission, Falae urged it not to declare the election's final
results. ``We are convinced that we cannot accord recognition to,
nor accept results secured through such blatant subversion of
popular will,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Falae did not say whether he would pursue his challenge. But
there was little evidence that the outcome would generate the
outrage necessary to give momentum to a formal challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos State gave Falae 88 percent of its votes and only 12
percent to Obasanjo, the most lopsided margin of the 36 states and
the federal capital territory of Abuja. But even here, most people
interviewed Monday said they were tired of political fighting and
ready to accept the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not happy about the results,'' said Larry Sule, 33, a
banker, who shared the same birthplace, Abeokuta, as Obasanjo, and
who had voted for Falae. ``But I think we should accept the results
and allow Obasanjo to be sworn in in the name of the transition. If
there is a prolonged dispute, going to the courts, the military
might take it as an excuse to prolong their stay.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``The loser should accept it in the spirit of
sportsmanship.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lagos is dominated by the Yoruba, one of the three main ethnic
groups in Nigeria, and both candidates are Yoruba, but because of
his military past and his close ties to northerners, Obasanjo is
mistrusted by many Yoruba.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly here, the subdued reaction to the outcome was
in marked contrast to the enthusiasm heard among many voters on
election day. The acceptance of Monday's announcement seemed to
reflect the realization that in a country ruled by the military for
all but 10 years since independence in 1960, a transition to
civilian rule and genuine democracy could not happen overnight, and
that, as one taxi driver put it, the worst civilian government is
better than the best military government.
</P>
<P>
   Wellington Okotobei, 31, an engineer, voiced the widespread
belief in Lagos that powerful military officers had chosen Obasanjo
and imposed him on the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as it is,'' Okotobei said, ``we should accept the result.
We have to gradually phase these old people out of the system. A
democratic culture is difficult to mechanically put in place. It
has to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   During a weeklong campaign, Obasanjo presented himself as a safe
bridge between a future civilian government and military rulers
ever ready to seize back power. By contrast, Falae sold himself as
a clean break from the military past.
</P>
<P>
   According to the final results released Monday, Obasanjo, the
candidate for the People's Democratic Party, won 62.8 percent of
the popular vote or 18.7 million votes. Falae, who was the joint
candidate for two smaller parties, the All People's Party and the
Alliance for Democracy, garnered 37.2 percent or 11.1 million
votes. There were 53 million registered voters, though election
officials suspected only 40 million were genuine.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo's party also retained the dominance it had exhibited in
recent elections for local, statewide and national assembly seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy about it,'' said Jeji Jatay, 88, a farmer near
Abuja, which voted overwhelmingly for Obasanjo. ``I want an
Obasanjo government to help the poor and the farmers. By the grace
of God, the Obasanjo government will be a listening government.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
