<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3584 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SCANDAL-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     03-01 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SCANDAL-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 NEW YORK: ... IOC and USOC.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The commission specifically cited scholarships, medical expenses
and living expenses for IOC members and their families _ three
areas where Salt Lake organizers engaged in the most known abuses _
as potential trouble spots that should be banned by both the IOC
and the USOC.
</P>
<P>
   To strengthen the USOC's oversight of the site-selection
process, the commission urged the creation of an independent Office
of Bid Compliance; a prohibition on bid cities participating in
international assistance programs designed to help athletes in
other countries; and the strict application of rules for
international assistance the USOC itself provides.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about assistance to foreign athletes arose last month
in the ethics report on the Salt Lake effort. That report detailed
how $40,000 in USOC assistance money was used to settle a ``debt''
with a Sudanese IOC member who had voted to support staging the
2002 Winter Games in Salt Lake.
</P>
<P>
   Among the recommendations for the IOC was a proposal that a
``substantial majority'' of its members be elected by national
Olympic committees. It said there also should be more ``public
sector'' representatives and athletes chosen by fellow athletes.
Currently, members are chosen by the IOC itself, with Samaranch
exercising great authority over who is named.
</P>
<P>
   Once elected, IOC members should be subject to periodic
reelection and term limits, the commission said. Now, IOC members
can serve until age 80.
</P>
<P>
   To increase openness, the commission called on the IOC to make
its meetings public whenever possible; disclose the results of
yearly financial audits; and implement and enforce a comprehensive
conflict-of-interest policy and rules on disclosure of all gifts
offered to members.
</P>
<P>
   The commission also urged the IOC and the USOC to work
cooperatively to have the IOC designated a ``public international
organization,'' which could make its members subject to an
international anti-bribery convention adopted by 34 nations _
including the United States _ that took effect Feb. 15.
</P>
<P>
   As it now stands, because IOC members in nearly all cases are
not considered ``foreign officials,'' their actions in Salt Lake
City are not subject to prosecution under the primary US law
applicable in such instances, the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act.
If, however, the IOC were designated a public international
organization, that law could apply in future such cases on US soil.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear whether the IOC would consider the
Mitchell commission's report at a meeting March 17 and 18 in
Lausanne, Switzerland, where it is scheduled to consider reforms
and vote on the ouster of members accused of taking improper
payments.
</P>
<P>
   The commission did not review the practices of Olympic cities
other than Salt Lake, but Mitchell stressed that many of the
problems had been identified in a 1991 report to the IOC by
officials of Toronto's failed bid to host the 1996 Summer Games.
The Toronto report detailed reports of more than two dozen IOC
members violating rules on travel expenses and airline tickets,
among other alleged abuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``In strikingly prophetic language, they warned of the
consequences of such improper behavior,'' Mitchell said at the
press conference. ``The Toronto prophesy has come true.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Mitchell said he believed the damage done to
the Olympics was severe but not irreparable. Asked how his most
recent effort compared with his work in Northern Ireland, Mitchell
laughed and said: ``That was three and a half years. I hope this
doesn't take that long.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Mitchell on the commission were Kenneth Duberstein, a
former chief of staff to President Ronald Reagan; Donald Fehr,
executive director of the Major League Baseball Players
Association; Jeffrey Benz, a lawyer and former ice skater who is a
member of the USOC board of directors; and Roberta Cooper Ramo,
former president of the American Bar Association.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Powers of the Globe staff contributed to this story.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
HIGHLIGHTS OF THE REPORT ON OLYMPIC CORRUPTION &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the principal findings
</P>
<P>
   --The Salt Lake City bid and organizing committees improperly
disbursed things of value in a systematic manner to IOC members,
their relatives, and others to influence or reward a favorable
vote.
</P>
<P>
   --The USOC failed to exercise adequate oversight of the Salt
Lake City bid and organizing committees during the selection of
Salt Lake City as a candidate city and as the host city of the
Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   --The IOC's governing structure and policies did not effectively
discourage _ and as a result may have encouraged _ a culture of
improper gift giving in the Olympic Movement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Key recommendations
</P>
<P>
   --The IOC must make fundamental structural changes:
</P>
<P>
   1. A substantial majority of its members should be elected by
the National Olympic Committees, by the International Federations,
and by other constituent organizations. The athlete members should
be chosen by athletes. There should be members from the public
sector who best represent the interests of the public.
</P>
<P>
   2. Its members and leaders should be subject to periodic
reelection with appropriate term limits.
</P>
<P>
   3. Its financial records should be audited by an independent
firm, and the results of the audit disclosed publicly, at least
yearly.
</P>
<P>
   --Bid cities should be prohibited from giving to members of the
USOC or the IOC anything of more than nominal value, and from
directly paying the expenses of members of the USOC or IOC.
</P>
<P>
   --The USOC must strengthen its oversight of the site selection
process.
</P>
<P>
   --The USOC should request the president of the United States to
consider, in consultation with other governments, naming the IOC a
public international organization within the meaning of the Foreign
Corrupt Practices Act, as amended.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(SOURCE: Bid Oversight Commission Report)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
