<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3593 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDUCATION-SPENDING-BO     03-01 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-SPENDING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDUCATION REFORM LIKELY TO RENEW PARTY FRICTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senator Edward M. Kennedy is ready to bolster
education like never before, ratcheting up his lifelong commitment
to students with proposals to increase the number of teachers and
salvage flailing schools.
</P>
<P>
   There is one problem. Republicans are beating him to it.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two months after President Clinton urged Congress
during his State of the Union address to ``support what works and
to stop supporting what doesn't'' in education, Republican leaders
have vigorously heeded the call _ and in the process have sparked a
tug-of-war over the issue with Democrats, traditionally keepers of
the education gate.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert demanded a ``smarter partnership on
public education'' during his first weeks on the job. Republican
education bills are on their way in both the Senate and the House.
Last weekend, the Republican radio address was devoted to the
party's ``pursuit to improve education.''
</P>
<P>
   And Wednesday, in what may become the first real battle since
the end of impeachment, senators are scheduled to confront
``Ed-Flex'' _ a Republican-originated education flexibility program
designed to expand the power of local communities. It has support
in both parties _ and has been tested in a dozen states _ but many
Democrats, including Kennedy, are loath to see it sail through the
Senate unchecked.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many Democrats, fearing the legislation would allow
impoverished students to slip through the cracks, now find
themselves in an awkward position: wanting to put up roadblocks to
a popular education plan. Republicans, on the other hand, are
seizing on education as part of their post-impeachment strategy to
focus on issues _ and may, at least when it comes to Ed-Flex,
succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans ``are trying to have a quick victory, and they're
probably going to get it,'' according to Nina Shokraii Rees,
education policy analyst at the Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats are trying to hold onto this as their issue,'' Rees
said. ``Every poll I see puts Democrats ahead of Republicans on
this issue. But ... Democrats are probably going to have to be a
little more concerned, once Republicans realize how to talk about
education in a very compassionate and serious way.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet the Ed-Flex bill, co-sponsored by Senators Bill Frist, a
Republican from Tennessee, and Ron Wyden, a Democrat from Oregon,
is written in the language of practicality rather than compassion.
</P>
<P>
   At its core is a simple belief: Public schools that receive
federal funding should spend less time and money on conforming to
government rules, and more time teaching students. To that end,
Ed-Flex lets schools apply for waivers for regulations from seven
federal education programs, including Title I, in which schools
with disadvantaged populations receive government funds.
</P>
<P>
   First conceived by Congress in 1994, Ed-Flex was tested in six
states in 1996, then expanded to 12 states nationwide.
Massachusetts, one of the original six states, has ``taken great
advantage of it,'' according to Interim Commissioner of the
Department of Education, David Driscoll.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty school districts in Massachusetts have received waivers
since the trial run began _ most of them for Title 1 regulations.
Among them is Wareham, where four waivers have been granted since
1996, and where schools have been able to ``use money in the way we
feel is most effective without the red tape of federal
regulations,'' according to superintendent Wayne Lague.
</P>
<P>
   At the Minot Forest School in Wareham, for example, teachers
funded by Title I were once placed on a separate staff. Students
targeted as disadvantaged were singled out and removed from class
for remedial work.
</P>
<P>
   Now that federal rules are waived, however, the Title I funds
are used to boost the overall workings of the school _ and teachers
are blended into a single staff, allowing for smaller class sizes,
according to Lague.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Paul Cellucci, a Republican, has been a supporter of
Ed-Flex, and has ``chimed in and said it's been a successful
initiative here'' as lawmakers have sought to take it nationwide,
according to his education adviser, Mike Sentance.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats _ including Kennedy, the ranking Democrat on the
Senate Health, Education, Labor and Pensions Committee _ are not
opposed to the basic concept, and have voted for its trial runs. It
has enjoyed broad bipartisan support, including that of President
Clinton; that is one reason, members of both parties say, that
Republicans have chosen to use Ed-Flex as a vehicle for proving
their ability to get things done.
</P>
<P>
   But there are deep systemic flaws, Kennedy and others believe _
primarily, that without some alterations, the bill will fail to
ensure the funding actually serves disadvantaged students. This
week, as the bill comes up for debate in the Senate, Democrats plan
to attach as many as 12 amendments, which will have the practical
effect of delaying the vote on Ed-Flex.
</P>
<P>
   But to Kennedy, as well as Minority Leader Thomas A. Daschle,
there is little choice but to fight for the alterations _ even if
it will be perceived as an effort to stall a popular bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to provide the flexibility,'' Kennedy said,
using a phrase that has become central to the debate, ``we also
want some accountability.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
