<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3599 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN     03-01 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN MANAGER KNOW EVERYTHING AFTER 2 DAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Ken Lloyd _ a specialist in organizational behavior _ is a
columnist for the Los Angeles Daily News. His column moves Mondays
in the ``f'' financial news file. Send your questions to P.O. Box
260057, Encino, Calif. 91426 or by electronic mail to
LloydOnJobaol.com. Names will be withheld upon request.) 
By KEN LLOYD  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Q. Our new manager called us into a meeting on his
second day here and said he had seen enough and knows exactly what
to do. He then read a list of changes to be implemented
immediately. Some make sense, but others are pointless. We were
caught by surprise, and when we asked to meet with him again, he
said that he can't for a while because he's busy. What can we do
now? T.H.
</P>
<P>
   A. Although your new manager may have ``seen enough,'' it does
not sound like he has heard enough. In today's workplace,
unilateral decision-making tends to generate multilateral
resistance.
</P>
<P>
   However, before automatically concluding that the new manager is
practicing Paleolithic management, it is important to look at the
state of your company, as there can be situations where a more
authoritarian style may arguably be needed, if only for the short
term. For example, the captain of a rapidly sinking ship is not
well-advised to hold a staff meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that the only thing sinking in your company is the
spirit of the employees, you need to set a specific meeting date
with the new manager, the sooner the better. The idea of meeting in
``a while'' is simply a bad idea. You should get your calendar,
approach the manager toward the end of a good day, tell him you
appreciate some of the changes, and then ask him when the best time
is for all of you to meet to discuss the changes.
</P>
<P>
   Let him be the one who talks next. His reaction will tell you if
he is the kind of manager who solves crises or causes them.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I just finished interviewing a pleasant and affable young man
who seems qualified to work here. However, in reviewing my notes, I
did not write down very much, and I realize that I was doing too
much talking. Should I bring him back for a reinterview, and what
should I tell him? W.M. &QL; 
A. You can certainly bring this applicant back for a reinterview,
and there is no problem telling him that you are interested in
going into more depth in some of the work areas that were touched
upon during your initial meeting.
</P>
<P>
   However, before you rush to bring him back, it is important to
consider a few factors. Some studies have found that interviewers
like applicants in direct proportion to the amount of time that the
interviewers talk. Hence, many applicants are advised to get the
interviewer to do the talking, and your applicant may have played
this card.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, your interviewing style may have caused the
problem. If you meet with him again, the objective should be to
conduct a thorough work history, starting with his earliest jobs,
and moving all the way through the present. The questions should
focus on such issues as responsibilities, likes and dislikes, and
why he left each job. You can add work sample and job knowledge
questions as well.
</P>
<P>
   In the event that he attempts to interview you instead, politely
try to put him back on track. If he persists, that is data to
consider when determining if he is someone you would like to hire. &QL; 
Q. Although our meetings are supposed to follow a tight agenda,
they regularly get sidetracked by a staff member who focuses on
small-picture issues that relate only to her work. Our manager
allows this person to derail the meeting every time. It is
frustrating to sit through these irrelevant discussions. What can I
say that won't make me sound like I'm not a team player? S.B. &QL; 
A. A true team is open to the concerns, inputs and suggestions of
all the members, so if you fear voicing your ideas, you are not
really on a team in the first place. Most of the people who attend
these meetings are probably just as annoyed by your co-worker's
self-oriented behavior, and your manager's lack of responsiveness.
If this is the case, perhaps those two are the ones who are not
team players.
</P>
<P>
   You can discuss the situation with the small-picture employee,
but there is not much you can say that will cause her to step back
and see the big picture. She is comfortable with her behavior in
the meetings, and apparently the manager is, too.
</P>
<P>
   For this situation to change, you and some of your teammates
should suggest a group discussion to review the ways to make the
meetings more productive. One objective of such a discussion is to
reach a commitment to keep the meetings focused on group-related
matters, with individual matters being discussed in individual
sessions with the manager. This type of approach makes for better
meetings and better teams.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
