<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3605 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRENCH-HOUELLEBECQ-2T     03-01 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRENCH-HOUELLEBECQ-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS ABROAD: ROMAN A GRIPE STIRS FLAMES AMONG FRENCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Michel Houellebecq is an unlikely new star of French
letters. Slightly built, with thinning hair and a melancholic mien,
he chews nervously on a succession of cigarettes, mumbling when he
is not sighing or silent. He describes himself as a
manic-depressive who becomes excited only when he is writing. His
fiction, which he concedes is fairly autobiographical, reflects a
bleak and loveless world.
</P>
<P>
   Yet last fall, with the publication by Editions Flammarion of
his second novel, ``Les Particules Elementaires'' (``Elementary
Particles''), the 40-year-old Parisian suddenly found himself at
the center of ``l'affaire Houellebecq.'' The book was an instant
best seller, with sales exceeding 260,000 to date. But what turned
this success into an ``affaire,'' or scandal, was the passion and
venom with which the book's admirers and critics argued its merits.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides at least agreed on one thing: The book is a frontal
attack on the generation of '68, the French equivalent of the baby
boomers, the middle-aged politicians, businessmen, intellectuals
and the like who are now in power in France. For its fans the book
exposes the empty, confused and frustrated France spawned by the
failed dreams of the 1968 student-protest movement. And its
assaults on so-called ``political correctness'' (another American
import into the French discourse) apparently added to its appeal.
Houellebecq's targets, on the other hand, became his instant
detractors, variously denouncing the book as reactionary,
misogynist, nihilistic and pornographic.
</P>
<P>
   Houellebecq (pronounced WELL-beck) helped things along by giving
countless, often provocative, interviews to newspapers, magazines,
radio and television. When his novel was not short-listed for the
Prix Goncourt last November, he reiterated the familiar charge that
payoffs explain why Goncourt juries invariably reward books
published by three highbrow houses: Editions Gallimard, Grasset and
Seuil. And he later dismissed the winner, Paule Constant's
``Confidence pour Confidence'' (``Secret for Secret''), published
by Gallimard, as mediocre and boring.
</P>
<P>
   Other incidents kept tongues wagging. After a bizarre
interview-trial conducted by fellow editors of the literary review
Perpendiculaire, Houellebecq was formally expelled as a founding
member, prompting cries of McCarthyism. The owners of a New Age
campsite called L'Espace du Possible then sought to have ``Les
Particules Elementaires'' seized as libelous for describing the
camp as a kind of free love commune. The author agreed to rename
the campsite Le Lieu de Changement in future editions.
</P>
<P>
   The plot of the 394-page novel revolves around two half brothers
whose bohemian mother leaves them to be raised by separate
grandparents as she goes looking for the meaning of life through
sex and meditation. One brother, Bruno Clement, who spends his life
trying to satisfy his sexual obsession through masturbation and
prostitutes, ends up in a psychiatric hospital. The other, Michel
Djerzinski, who feels no sexual desire, culminates his career as a
molecular biologist by eliminating the need for sex and procreation
through human cloning.
</P>
<P>
   The book's generational element is that Bruno was born in 1956
and Michel, like Houellebecq, in 1958. Like the author, they were
children in 1968 and reached adulthood in the early 1980s when the
generation of '68 came to power with the election of France's first
socialist president, Francois Mitterrand. The generation's legacy,
the book maintains, is a France without vision, values or hope.
</P>
<P>
   Houellebecq had already sketched this disaffected view of French
society in 1994 in his first novel, ``Extension du Domaine de la
Lutte'' (literally ``Expansion of the Arena of the Stuggle'')
published in English this month under the title ``Whatever'' by
Serpent's Tail Press, a British company. This 155-page book follows
the narrator and a colleague as they travel the French provinces
giving training courses in computers. The colleague is consumed by
dismay that he is still a virgin at 28. The lonely narrator in turn
views the world with general distaste, a posture that a doctor
finally identifies as depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Officially, then, I'm in a depression,'' the narrator says in
Paul Hammond's translation. ``The formula seems a happy one to me.
It's not that I feel tremendously low; it's rather that the world
around me appears high.''
</P>
<P>
   This book was well received in France, selling a respectable
15,000 copies there and being likened by some critics to Albert
Camus' novel ``The Stranger.'' Houellebecq subsequently published
two books of poetry and one book of essays and interviews, winning
the Grand Prix National des Lettres in 1997. Only with ``Les
Particules Elementaires,'' though, did he become a household name.
(Alfred A. Knopf has acquired it for publication in the United
States.)
</P>
<P>
   Houellebecq attributes attacks on his new novel to the ``pure
and simple jealousy'' of writers not mentioned in an article in Le
Monde listing members of a new generation of literature. In Le
Figaro, this new generation was said to comprise a literary
movement it called ``deprimisme'' (``depressionism''), although
Houellebecq prefers to describe it as new realism.
</P>
<P>
   But some older writers of the '68 generation and intellectuals
who still see the world through the left-right prism also
criticized the book. For them, anyone opposed to abortion, sexual
freedom, environmentalism and European integration has to be
reactionary. In their case against Houellebecq, Perpendiculaire's
prosecuting editors even cited the fact that his expose of the
spiritual desolation of modern life won plaudits from a
conservative Roman Catholic publication.
</P>
<P>
   More intriguing, however, is why ``Les Particules Elementaires''
has proved so popular. The most obvious answer is that many French
share Houellebecq's dark vision of a post-idealistic,
post-ideological France gripped by malaise, unemployment and
growing insecurity, where materialism, hypocrisy and corruption
have long since replaced dreams of a better life. And if people are
looking for someone to blame, why not the generation of '68?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly in his fiction and in interviews, Houellebecq pours
scorn indiscriminately on leftists, rightists, feminists,
environmentalists and anyone who pretends to offer solutions.
``Killing off illusions makes us happier, to know that the past is
dead,'' he said in a recent interview in the offices of Editions
Flammarion. ``People with illusions are stupid. Those with
political illusions are not only stupid but dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   His (or at least his novels') obsession with sex as pornography,
prostitution or at best loveless coupling is in turn seen as a
denunciation of what has happened to human feelings. In his novel
he describes Bruno's visits to popular ``clubs echangistes''
(``exchange clubs'') where couples swap partners and engage in
orgies. But even there, he noted, commercialism is taking over. He
said he visited one club where most guests sat around watching
pornographic movies as a substitute for having sex.
</P>
<P>
   For him that is what sexual liberation has come to: alienation
and solitude. ``The first theory in `Whatever' is that sexual
freedom does not mean that people are equal when it comes to
seduction,'' he said. ``It annoyed me that everyone was talking
about sexuality and ignoring this essential point.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The personal nature of his writing has inevitably awakened
interest in its autobiographical content. He admits that much of
his fiction is inspired by his life, although he said that in ``Les
Particules Elementaires'' he sometimes identifies with Bruno and
other times with Michel.
</P>
<P>
   Born on the island of Reunion in 1958 to a mountain guide father
and a hippie mother who were soon divorced, he was raised by his
paternal grandparents outside Paris. ``What I felt was fear of my
father and disgust with my mother,'' he said in a published
interview three years ago. ``It's funny, but she never realized
that I hated her.'' In ``Les Particules Elementaires,'' Bruno's
final revenge is to urinate on his mother's grave.
</P>
<P>
   In high school, he recalled, there was ``a panoply of
incomprehensible political movements, leftists, environmentalists,
who awakened in me profound repulsion,'' no doubt setting the stage
for his rejection of traditional politics. The last time that he
voted, he said, was in a 1992 referendum; he opposed the Maastricht
Treaty creating a single European currency and accelerating
European political union.
</P>
<P>
   After studying agronomy at college, he could not find work. He
had begun to write poetry, which gave him some satisfaction, but he
was unemployed for 18 months before being hired as a computer
programmer, an experience that is reflected in ``Whatever.'' He
married, had a child and divorced. He began to drink heavily and
watch television addictively until, as with Bruno in ``Les
Particules Elementaires'' and the narrator in ``Whatever,'' he
checked into a psychiatric hospital.
</P>
<P>
   In the '90s, he worked as a computer expert in the French
Parliament, although he says working with computers is a lonely and
depressing activity. He is now on a leave from that job and, after
the financial success of his second novel, evidently has no need to
return. Last month he decided to settle in Dublin, where writers
have always felt at home (and where artists do not pay income tax).
</P>
<P>
   Still, no matter how much of a loner he considers himself,
Houellebecq cannot complain that he has not been heard by now. For
his fans he has assumed something of the aura of a guru, although
it irritates him that interviewers ask his views on everything.
``Sartre had opinions on everything,'' he said. ``I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Without sounding any less pessimistic, however, he seems to have
come to terms with his sudden fame. ``I have never published a book
without having the terrifying feeling that no one would ever talk
to me again after reading it,'' he said. ``But it is not exactly
what happens, so perhaps I can't really think that books are
worthless. I have at least done that. It gives me a tiny reason to
think a little more highly of myself.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
