</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SCANDAL-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GIFT CREEP' PRECIPITATED OLYMPIC SCANDAL, PANEL CONCLUDES 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (s, i and a coding; includes conclusions text table)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Olympic scandal was spawned by a pervasive
culture of ``gift creep,'' with presents from would-be host cities
growing steadily more extravagant while US and international
Olympic officials ignored or engaged in the abuses themselves, an
independent commission concluded Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, chaired by the former Senate majority leader, George
Mitchell, proposed reforms including stricter controls on
gift-giving by cities vying to stage the Games, greater public
accountability, and diminished contact between bid cities and
international Olympic decision-makers.
</P>
<P>
   The five-member commission also went beyond its mandate of
focusing on lapses by the United States Olympic Committee by urging
fundamental changes in the International Olympic Committee,
including new rules by which IOC members would be chosen, limits on
their length of service, and the adoption and strict enforcement of
travel, expense and gift rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``The credibility of the Olympic movement has been gravely
damaged,'' Mitchell said at a news conference in New York. ``Reform
must occur on the local, national and international level if that
credibility is to be restored.''
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference and in an interview afterward, the former
Maine senator chose his words carefully; despite its status as the
most prominent independent panel to review the Olympic scandal thus
far, Mitchell's commission cannot force change. Instead, it can
only hope to win changes by convincing the IOC, the USOC and other
Olympic organizers of their necessity.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, drawing on his recent diplomatic experience as a
peacemaker in Northern Ireland, Mitchell sidestepped a suggestion
that he was describing deep-rooted corruption. ``I prefer to use my
own words,'' he said in the interview. ``We believe that it was an
improper gift culture that was widespread and notorious and has to
be changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Deep in the report, however, the commission went a step further:
``The culture of improper gift-giving tolerated by the IOC is
potentially illegal and inevitably corruptive. . . . The IOC should
no sooner tolerate improper gifts by candidate cities to its
members than it would tolerate such gifts by athletes to judges.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Pound of Canada, vice president of the IOC and chairman
of its committee examining the corruption allegations, said he was
``not surprised'' that the IOC was part of the Mitchell
commission's review. ``We're not perfect by any means,'' Pound
said. `` We've always said the whole question is a two-way street.
Our investigation has shown a climate of major pressure on IOC
members.''
</P>
<P>
   Pound disputed Mitchell's comment that the IOC was part of an
``improper'' gift culture, as well as the commission's conclusion
that the gift giving was ``corruptive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have problems with the word `improper,''' Pound said. ``The
IOC is an international organization. It absorbs many cultures
where the giving of gifts is not only proper, but almost
essential.'' He added: ``I do not for a moment accept a broad-brush
characterization of the IOC having a culture of corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission stopped short of calling for the removal of the
IOC's president, Juan Antonio Samaranch, who has been widely blamed
for fostering a climate of Olympian excess. Apparently
acknowledging that Samaranch still reigns supreme over the IOC,
Mitchell said: ``We believe the emphasis should be on changing the
system, not on any individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Although much of the criticism was aimed at the IOC, the USOC
was hardly spared; the commission found that the USOC shares
responsibility for the abuses because it ``failed to exercise
effectively its oversight authority of the gift-giving practices of
the bid and organizing committee in Salt Lake City.''
</P>
<P>
   The report concluded that ``the USOC did not effectively monitor
the activities of the bid committee's board of trustees or
executive committee.'' The document said that from June of 1991,
when Salt Lake City launched its bid for the 2002 Winter Games, to
June of 1995, when it was awarded the bid, the USOC attended 1 of
23 meetings of the Salt Lake executive committee, and had no
representation on the board.
</P>
<P>
   Before June of 1995, only one senior staff person of the USOC
attended a meeting of the Board of Trustees. Nor did the USOC make
any attempt to audit bid committee books or records, nor did it
have any representatives working in committee offices, the report
added.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the report suggested that the USOC, by example, had
tacitly endorsed the excessive courting of IOC members. When Salt
Lake was competing with other US cities to win the USOC's
designation as a potential Olympic host, USOC rules prohibited its
members from accepting gifts worth more than $25.
</P>
<P>
   But on visits to Salt Lake, USOC members accepted lodging,
meals, car rentals, entertainment, airfare, ski passes and other
gifts with a total cost approaching $5,000, the commission report
said.
</P>
<P>
   The panel took pains to present the actions of Salt Lake
organizers in a broader context than an earlier ethics report that
focused solely on the city. For instance, the Mitchell commission
concluded that Salt Lake, on its merits, had earned the right to
host the Games. It also said the improper inducements were often
``triggered by a demand from the taker.'' What Salt Lake organizers
did ``was wrong. But, as we have noted, they did not invent this
culture; they joined one that was already flourishing.''
</P>
<P>
   USOC officials, who created the commission in December to assess
culpability and propose reforms, thanked the panel but withheld a
detailed response until a news conference scheduled for Wednesday
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent manipulation of the Olympic bid process in the
future, Mitchell's commission proposed that bid cities be
prohibited from giving IOC and USOC members ``anything of more than
minimal value.'' It also suggested that bid cities be banned from
paying the expenses of USOC or IOC members, which instead would be
paid out of central funds administered separately by the IOC and
USOC.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
