<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3613 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SNAKEBIT-THEATER-REVI     03-01 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNAKEBIT-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SNAKEBIT': IN THE PIT WITHOUT THE ANTITOXIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(ms) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If it sometimes appears as if all good plays book
passage to New York on British Airways, then take heart from the
all-American flight plan of ``Snakebit,'' David Marshall Grant's
finely observed, beautifully acted comedy-drama about the flaming
out of friendship and marriage in a deceptively sunny precinct of
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   It took several years for Grant, an actor best known for his
Tony-nominated role as an anguished Mormon in ``Angels in
America,'' to secure a production for this play, his first, but his
patience has been rewarded. Under the intuitive stewardship of the
director Jace Alexander, ``Snakebit'' renders Grant's brittle
characters with such insight and wryness that by the play's end,
you may feel that you've been assigned a seat inside their
uncomfortable skins.
</P>
<P>
   The four-character drama had a brief, well-received run in the
fall at tiny Grove Street Playhouse in the West Village; it
reopened Monday night in Union Square at the Century Theater, where
Dean Taucher's realistic mock-up of a sun-dappled bungalow looks
even better. The acutely balanced performances, too, have been
refined with age. David Alan Basche, Jodie Markell, Geoffrey
Nauffts and, especially, Michael Weston have sharpened the elbows
of these variously driven, drifting and dissatisfied souls, whose
proximity to one another seems only to intensify their sense of
anxious isolation.
</P>
<P>
   The events of ``Snakebit'' revolve around a weeklong stay in the
home of Michael ( Nauffts), a gay social worker, by his childhood
best friend, Jonathan ( Basche), and his wife, Jenifer (Ms.
Markell). The clearest source of tension in the household is
handsome, volatile Jonathan, a New York actor who, under
consideration for a part in a major action-adventure movie, spends
much of his time dialing his voice mail, shouting into the phone at
his agent's receptionist and bullying Jenifer, a fragile former
actress who frets continually over her inadequacies as well as over
the lingering illness of the 6-year-old daughter they have left in
the care of a relative in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Jenifer's worries about her daughter's health, it seems, can be
traced back a dozen years, to just before her marriage to Jonathan,
when she had a fling with Michael, becoming the last woman he slept
with. The couple's unloading of their problems, however, could not
come at a worse time for Michael, who is struggling with his own
anxieties and losses: his companion, Gary, a radio talk show host
who feigns swaggering heterosexuality on the airwaves, has
abandoned him for a younger man, just as Michael has decided that
he wants to adopt one of his clients, an abused teen-age girl.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the equitable, television-style apportionment of
traumas to the cast members that gives ``Snakebit'' its bite. This
is not ``E.R.'' transferred to a house off a freeway exit. Rather,
it is the play's uncompromisingly rueful picture of these mixed-up
30-somethings, whose harsh emotional lives have browned and thinned
out like unshaded California lawns, that provides the drama with a
suppleness undiscoverable in your average dramatic series.
</P>
<P>
   To Grant's credit, ``Snakebit'' has no cathartic scream-out, the
sort you imagine that Jonathan, the story's alpha-male, is spoiling
for. (The play takes such a dim view of direct conflict, in fact,
that Basche's character is made to seem patently boorish every time
he raises his voice.)
</P>
<P>
   The air of alienation that envelops the bungalow extends in
Grant's imagination to all of Los Angeles, a place for which he
seems to harbor little but contempt. ``This is the most unrelaxing
place I've ever been,'' Jenifer declares, as a leaf blower drones
angrily in the yard next door. Grant sees the deafening gardening
tool as emblematic of life in a ersatz city where meaningful
conversation is forever being drowned out, where all phone calls
involve stomach-churning business decisions, where natives like the
mysterious young man (Weston) who shows up on Michael's doorstep
one day speak in the tongue-tied cadences of the vaguely literate.
</P>
<P>
   There is no weak link in this cast. Nauffts is superb as a
decent man exhausted by disappointment and confused enough by life
to still be half in love with Jenifer, played to perfection by Ms.
Markell, who allows you to see with amazing clarity the gaps in
Jenifer's personality and marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Basche is the heavy of the piece, and he handles the role of
resident jerk with a suave relish. Only when he is called upon to
egg the other actors on to the next level of confrontation does he
become too strident; this may have come about as a result of
playing to the larger house. Weston has a variety of choice, funny
moments as the dorky visitor with a hidden agenda. His Valley-boy
flakiness makes him the type of Angeleno to whom New Yorkers love
to feel entirely superior.
</P>
<P>
   Grant is writing about a world with which he is on intimate
terms _ the sendup of Hollywood deal-making, encapsulated in
Jonathan's negotiations, is hilarious _ and he makes an audience
feel smart and entertained in that world, too. That is no small
feat. Whether these are the kinds of people you want in your life
is beside the point. Once you've seen ``Snakebit,'' they're there.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SNAKEBIT'
</P>
<P>
   By David Marshall Grant; directed by Jace Alexander; sets by
Dean Taucher; costumes by Elizabeth Roles; lighting by Renee
Molina; production stage manager, Kimberly Ann Berdy; production
manager, Joseph L. Robinson. The Naked Angeles production presented
by Hal Luftig, Daryl Roth and Ted Snowdon, in association with Roy
Gabay. At the Century Theater, Century Center for the Performing
Arts, 111 East 15th St.
</P>
<P>
   With: David Alan Basche (Jonathan), Jodie Markell (Jenifer),
Geoffrey Nauffts (Michael) and Michael Weston (Young Man).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
