<HEADLINE>
FRENCH, ITALIANS DEFY U.S. IN IRANIAN OIL DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Thumbing their noses at American opposition to
investments in Iran, a consortium of French, Italian and Iranian
oil companies announced Monday that they had signed a $998 million,
10-year contract to redevelop a giant oil field there.
</P>
<P>
   Elf Petroleum Iran, a subsidiary of the French oil company Elf
Aquitaine, will be the lead partner in the project, which also
involves a subsidiary of Eni of Italy and National Iranian Oil Co.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Elf Aquitaine, Thomas Saunders, said the company
expected no retribution from the United States under the Iran-Libya
Sanctions Act, which threatens sanctions against any country that
invests more than $20 million in either country.
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement reached last May between the United States
and the European Union, the Clinton administration agreed not to
apply sanctions against another French oil company, Total, which
proceeded with a $2 billion gas-exploration contract in Iran in
1997 in defiance of the American law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect the same treatment,'' Saunders said Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
