<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PRESIDENCY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH `MAKING UP MIND' ON WHETHER TO FORM EXPLORATORY COMMITTEE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush is expected to announce
Tuesday that he is forming an exploratory committee to raise money
for a possible presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told reporters Monday at a bridge dedication in San Saba,
Texas, that Tuesday he will answer the question of yes, no or
maybe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in the process of making up my mind as to whether I'll
establish an exploratory committee,'' Bush said later in Austin.
``Stay tuned. Something will be happening pretty soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Forming an exploratory committee with the Federal Election
Commission is a preliminary tool used by would-be presidential
candidates to allow them to legally raise money to gauge support
for a national campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still issue briefs, seeing what the politics are in
the different parts of the country, but raising money is the most
important aspect of an exploratory committee,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   With a shortened primary calendar that will require candidates
to campaign and advertise in several major media markets at once,
presidential candidates expect to need about $45 million to
compete.
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential nominee Bob Dole spent $42 million in
his 1996 primary campaign, according to FEC records. The governor's
father, former President Bush, spent $38 million in his 1992
re-election primary campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, North Carolina politicians met with Bush at the
Governor's Mansion to urge him to run for president and name
home-state native Elizabeth Dole as his running mate. Mrs. Dole,
wife of the 1996 nominee, recently resigned as head of the American
Red Cross to explore the possibility of running for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope Elizabeth Dole will be Governor Bush's running mate,''
said North Carolina state Rep. Bill Miner. ``There is so much
support for both Elizabeth Dole and George W. Bush that we wanted
to make a statement that we hope he is leading the ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Miner said the North Carolina lawmakers believe Bush should head
the ticket because he has a proven record of winning election and
re-election in Texas. He said Mrs. Dole has held only appointed
positions. Dole served as a Cabinet official in the Reagan and Bush
administrations.
</P>
<P>
   Bush called Mrs. Dole ``a fine, fine person'' whom he respects.
But he said he made no commitments to the North Carolina
delegation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They understand that should I decide to run, a fellow has got
to get nominated before he can even start thinking of naming a vice
president,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina Senate GOP leader Patrick Ballantine came out of
his meeting with Bush believing the governor will run for
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``My gut feeling is that he's going to run. I hope that's not
just wishful thinking,'' Ballantine said. ``I didn't hear him say
that he was going to run, but we're all praying that he does.''
</P>
<P>
   The North Carolina delegation delivered a letter from 15
Republican state senators and 38 of the state's 54 GOP House
members urging Bush to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also met with delegations from Connecticut and South
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the right message, the right definition of a
compassionate conservative to appeal not just in the South but in
the Northeast,'' said Connecticut House Republican leader Bob Ward.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina House Speaker David Wilkins noted that his state
will have one of the nation's earliest primaries, Feb. 26, 1999,
less than a year from now. He noted that South Carolina provided
former President Bush with a major victory on his road to the 1988
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Carolina is very much Bush country. It will be Governor
Bush country if he decides to run,'' Wilkins.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
