<HEADER>
A3616 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-DEBT-NYT &LR;      03-01 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-DEBT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAKING UNITY, 2 BANKS ACCEPT RUSSIAN REPAYMENT TERMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The unity of a key group of Western banks holding $15
billion in defaulted, short-term Russian treasury debt frayed on
Monday night after two of its members, including the leader, broke
ranks to accept a vaguely defined Russian repayment package of
rubles and new bonds regarded as nearly worthless.
</P>
<P>
   Both Deutsche Bank, which heads the group, and Chase Manhattan
agreed to the Russian terms, said to be worth about 5 cents on the
dollar, or one-twentieth of the face value of the investments.
</P>
<P>
   John Anderson, a Chase spokesman in London, said his bank had
agreed to exchange only its own holdings _ not those of its clients
_ for the Russian package.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank, by contrast, went ahead last Friday and agreed to
the Russian terms for part of the holdings owned by the bank and
some clients.
</P>
<P>
   Russia set off financial turmoil last August when it defaulted
on billions in treasury debt, about a third of that owed to
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Russian economy, in the meantime, continues to
unravel.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers said that there was never much expectation that Russia
would offer full repayment terms, but the terms accepted by
Deutsche Bank and Chase Manhattan weakened the power of the Western
bankers group to negotiate a better deal. Some members of the group
were particularly angry that Deutsche Bank had not informed them in
advance that it would accept a repayment offer they had all
rejected months earlier as too low.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank argued on Monday that there was no conflict of
interest between its position on the committee and its partial
acceptance of the Russian terms. The move, however, led to a
special meeting of the 19-member bankers group here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers said that the group was divided over the action taken by
Deutsche Bank and Chase in accepting the Russian package. But,
rather than force Deutsche Bank to quit as head of the committee,
the panel resolved to abolish the position altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of the banks opposed to Deutsche wanted to do
something to register their opposition, so the committee will go
forward without a chair,'' said one banker, who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Another said that Deutsche Bank had been prepared to quit if its
colleagues at the meeting had demanded this, ``but there was some
support for Deutsche's position.''
</P>
<P>
   The bankers said the division continued between those who
favored accepting Russian terms on the ground that ``if you are
going to have a bad deal, it's better to have it sooner then
later'' and others who wanted much tougher action against Russia,
including litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow's payment terms affect GKO treasury bills and OFZ Finance
Ministry bonds. Some members of the group oppose the terms, and a
banker who spoke on condition of anonymity said that there was
pressure on Deutsche Bank to resign as head of the committee,
particularly since it had agreed to Moscow's proposal without
keeping its partners informed.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank is also head of a separate, so-called London Club
of creditors owed $30 billion in unpaid Soviet-era debt, and there
was speculation that its position on that panel might now also be
called into question by other banks.
</P>
<P>
   The newest debacle is the latest in a long story. Earlier
negotiations collapsed in December, leaving creditors pressing for
better terms and complaining that Russia had not given a detailed
explanation of how any new bonds and ruble payments could be used.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians set a March 5 deadline for acceptance of their
offer with a final date of March 15. But creditors, arguing that
the Russian terms were worth as little as 2.5 cents on the dollar,
pressed for an extension to April 30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
