<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH EXPECTED TO FORM CAMPAIGN COMMITTEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush, who has been weighing a
potential presidential bid for months, is expected to announce
Tuesday he will form an exploratory committee that will enable him
to raise money for a potential White House campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a now-familiar scene played out on the lawn of the
Governor's Mansion, Bush picked up endorsements Monday from
Republican lawmakers in three other states for a possible race.
</P>
<P>
   State legislators from Connecticut and North and South Carolina
dropped by to urge the Republican governor to run for president in
2000. North Carolina is the home state of Elizabeth Dole, another
possible presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers said they got the same answer Bush has now given
countless other times: He's thinking about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My gut (instinct) is that he will run,'' South Carolina state
Sen. Patrick Ballantine said when asked later if he thinks Bush
will run. ``I hope that's not just wishful thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't hear him say that he was going to run. But we're all
praying that he does,'' Ballantine added.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is expected to edge closer to a White House run by
announcing which way he is leaning on the presidential question. He
is widely expected to say he is forming an exploratory committee,
but he wouldn't discuss his plans Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stay tuned,'' he said. ``Something will be happening pretty
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   A formal announcement on his candidacy, should such a decision
be made, isn't expected until after the Texas Legislature adjourns
May 31.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, lawmakers from around the country have made
their way to Austin to announce their support for Bush. The visits
have allowed the governor to amass a wide variety of endorsements
without having to leave the state to drum up support for a
potential candidacy while the Legislature is in session.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I'm in the process of making up my mind as to
whether or not I will take the process a step further,'' Bush told
reporters Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Those calling on the governor Monday cited similar reasons of
past endorsement delegations as to why they want him to run. They
also carried letters signed by a number of their fellow GOP
lawmakers who also want him in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe he is the best candidate, the best man for the job.
We believe he has the ability to bring everyone together,'' said
South Carolina House Speaker David Wilkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope he runs,'' Wilkins said.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina Rep. David Miner said he and other Bush
supporters aren't totally overlooking Dole in making their
endorsement for the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope Elizabeth Dole will be Governor Bush's running mate
... We hope he's leading the ticket, and we hope he will consider
Elizabeth Dole at the appropriate time,'' Miner said.
</P>
<P>
   And Rep. Robert M. Ward, minority leader of the Connecticut
General Assembly, said he believes Bush has the right message to
appeal to voters in the South and Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Monday's visits, along with those by other Republican
lawmakers, were spontaneous trips, not orchestrated events planned
by him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, when people express a desire to come down, it
requires a certain sense of coordination. I don't want people
coming to Texas, and I'm not available for lunch,'' Bush added.
</P>
<P>
   The out-of-state lawmakers said they had called Bush's
representatives wanting to know how best to show him their support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't asked to come. I asked if I could come,'' Wilkins
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
