<HEADER>
A3624 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOCKHEED-UNION-COX     03-01 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED-UNION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lockheed workers set to strike if negotiations break down
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Pat Stripling remembers the last strike at the
Lockheed Martin Corp. plant in Marietta, Ga. It happened in 1977
and lasted three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked the picket line with my dad,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Now Stripling, who followed her father into a career at the
plant, is ready to do it again, unless Machinists union leaders and
management come up with a better contract than the one rejected by
workers over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Dissent appears to have stemmed more from job security, benefits
and workplace issues than from 3 percent annual raises offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The icing on the cake looked good,'' Stripling said of the
deal, rejected by a 68 percent vote. ``The ingredients were bad.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the vote, union leaders on Monday sent a five-day
strike notice to plant management. That could trigger a walkout
next week by the union, which represents 4,200 of the plant's 9,200
employees.
</P>
<P>
   A strike at Cobb County's largest private employer, however, can
still be averted if the two sides quickly re-enter negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're willing to sit down and talk with them,'' said Susan
Miles, a company spokeswoman. ``We probably won't know anything
about (a timetable) for a couple of days.''
</P>
<P>
   If talks resume and continue after the five-day strike notice
expires, the union would then have the option of calling a strike.
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie Bruce, an official at Machinists Local 709, said if talks
resume the union ``will do everything we can to keep people at work
until we get another proposal from the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders had endorsed the tentative three-year deal, citing
the pay raises and a boost in retirement benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But Stripling said a plan to combine 24 job classifications into
nine was seen as a way to cut jobs. Another controversial item was
a switch to 10-hour-a-day, four-day workweeks for some employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of younger workers that would have day care
problems,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Stripling also said the retirement boost was seen as too meager,
and workers were leery of a tougher attendance policy because the
current policy hasn't been evenly enforced.
</P>
<P>
   Plant management is under pressure to boost productivity to
offset high costs and slow sales for the C-130J, an update of the
venerable airlifter built there since the 1950s. In January 280
workers, both union and nonunion, were laid off.
</P>
<P>
   Miles said the labor unrest so far hasn't affected operations at
the plant, which also leads development of the F-22 fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it comes at a sensitive time, as Lockheed Martin seeks to
persuade the Air Force to step up C-130J orders and grapples with
cost problems in the F-22 program.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative contract was reached last month in negotiations
that also included Machinists locals at Lockheed Martin plants in
Sunnyvale and Palmdale, Calif. Workers at the Palmdale plant also
rejected the deal, while it was ratified at Sunnyvale.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
