<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3631 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-EXPEL-BOS &LR;      03-01 0280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-EXPEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOC PANEL WEIGHING FATE OF 10 IN SLOC SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (s and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The International Olympic Committee's investigative panel, still
pondering the fate of 10 more members linked to the Salt Lake
payoff scandal after meeting last weekend in Switzerland, will make
its decision by the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, we've had a remarkable degree of consensus,'' said
Richard Pound of Canada, who chairs the six-man panel. ``But as far
as new expulsions are concerned, we haven't gone there yet. Where
the line is to be drawn _ that's the area we're wrestling with
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine IOC members have resigned or have been forced out, in the
worst case of corruption in modern Olympic history. Any other
guilty members are expected to be expelled when the full body meets
on March 17 and 18 at Olympic headquarters in Lausanne. ``Our hope
remains that we can deal with all of the cases at that session,''
Pound said.
</P>
<P>
   The second wave of alleged wrongdoers, which Pound wryly called
``The Gang of Ten,'' covers a wider spectrum of improprieties,
ranging from cash payoffs to Super Bowl trips to plane tickets to
Budapest for family members. ``They're not of such a severe nature
as the ones we saw in the first slice in January,'' said Pound.
</P>
<P>
   But since the IOC rules allow only for expulsion, warning or
exoneration of members, the panel has been wrangling over how to
weigh the various offenses. ``When the charter was drafted, nobody
gave any thought to nuancing the sanctions,'' Pound said. ``There's
no in between. That's what we're dealing with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-99 1940EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990301.0336 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3632 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-IOC-EXPULSIONS-CO     03-01 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-EXPULSIONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Additional members examined as IOC grapples with inaccuracies
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) General News and (s) Sports categories.)
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At least half a dozen more International Olympic
Committee members are under suspicion for improprities in the Salt
Lake City bribery scandal, the head of an IOC inquiry panel said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   After a weekend meeting at IOC headquarters in Lausanne,
Switzerland, the head of the six-member commission said they were
trying to reach a consensus on the fates of 13 members still under
investigation, as well as the ``half-dozen or so'' new names to
emerge in the widening scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The additional members were not identified in a massive Salt
Lake City's board of ethics report issued last month. However, the
ethics board sent documentation that could link them to
inappropriate gifts, said Dick Pound, the Canadian lawyer who heads
the IOC's investigation panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Salt Lake board of ethics indicated they had partial
information with respect to certain gifts and benefits,'' Pound
said. ``They sent some working papers. There are a half-dozen or so
new names that are not otherwise there. So we will ask them what
they are all about.''
</P>
<P>
   The additional names raises the total number of IOC members
under suspicion of misconduct in the bidding for the 2002 Winter
Games to 30, or more than a quarter of the 115-member organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very serious problem,'' Pound said. ``It is serious
for the future of the IOC, and if we don't get it right it may
start to spill out to the Olympics themselves. We are taking this
situation very much to heart. I regard it as a crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Pound said his panel will recommend changes in the
site-selection process, establishment of an ethics committee with
outside membership and even changes to the structure of the IOC.
Pound said the commission is considering term limits for IOC
members and further limits on gift-giving.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to look very carefully at the way we are
organized,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pound said he hopes to send the commission's recommendations to
the IOC's 11-member executive board and IOC president Juan Antonio
Samaranch by the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   The commission can recommend that members be expelled, warned or
exonerated. If accepted by the board, the proposals will go to the
full IOC session at a special general assembly March 17-18.
</P>
<P>
   Nine IOC members already have resigned or been ousted in
connection with cash payments, scholarships, free medical care and
other inducements offered by Salt Lake.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend meeting focused on the six new previously
unidentified members and on three additional members that remained
under investigation after the commission's own quick investigation,
as well as 10 new names that appeared in the Salt Lake report.
</P>
<P>
   Pound reiterated the IOC's support for its beleagured president,
although he opened the door to a possible early departure for the
78-year-old Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said all along it is very important to have the captain
of the aircraft at the controls as you are going through the
turbulence,'' he said. ``Once the crisis is solved, he may decide
to carry on for the balance of his his term and he may decide to do
something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Turner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
