<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3635 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANCOCK-AGENTS-BOS &LR;      03-01 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANCOCK-AGENTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANCOCK TO REVAMP SALES SYSTEM, REMOLD STAFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a bold move that could make insurers more like stock
brokerages and mutual fund `supermarkets', John Hancock Mutual Life
Insurance Co. said Monday it would revamp its sales system to
remold staff agents into modern financial advisers peddling a
broader array of products.
</P>
<P>
   The change marks the first time a life insurance company will
sign contracts with independent agents that officially allow them
to sell other companies' investment products. Many independent
agencies _ self-run businesses closely allied with a single insurer
_ illicitly vend other firms' products behind the backs of their
main sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock's move underscores the demise of the old-fashioned
in-house insurance agent, one of the best-known symbols of the
business. It also illustrates the pressure faced by insurers to
compete in a marketplace in which consumers increasingly demand a
wider selection of products from more than one company.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its change, Boston-based Hancock, one of the nation's
15 largest life insurers, will phase out its 850 career agents _
staff salesmen who sell Hancock-only products. Those agents in July
can either join the ranks of some 2,150 `general' Hancock agents _
independent contractors affiliated with but not formally employed
by Hancock _ or leave. Around five percent of career agents
probably won't make the transition and will leave Hancock, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   Driving Hancock's revamp is the fact that general agents are
less costly than in-house ones and can reach customers whom staff
agents cannot.
</P>
<P>
   Under Hancock's new system, housed under a new Hancock
distribution unit called Signator Financial Network Inc., customers
who walk into a Hancock-affiliated agent will not only be able to
buy life insurance and mutual funds, but also long-term care
insurance and annuities _ all manufactured or distributed by
Hancock and nine other insurers, including Metropolitan Life
Insurance Co. and Prudential Insurance Co. of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of agents are locked in the past,'' said Signator's
chief executive, Rob Marra. ``But people are more interested in a
variety of products and say to themselves, `I don't really need an
insurance agent, I need a financial adviser.' ''
</P>
<P>
   While Hancock's mutual fund arm has been selling other
companies' funds for years, the new system bolsters the array of
products Hancock will offer. ``It's the path many companies will be
taking,'' said analyst Arthur Fliegelman of Moody's Investors
Service. Hancock also sells insurance directly and through banks
and brokerages.
</P>
<P>
   While not yet comparable to mutual fund `supermarkets' such as
Charles Schwab &AMP; Co., Hancock's new system has a similar pattern.
It also resembles that of brokerages, which have moved to become
financial advisory outfits offering multiple products.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock hopes that more agent-financial planners will choose to
affiliate with Hancock, giving the company more access to new
customers. For their part, the agents are able to offer clients a
bigger variety of products, a major competitive edge for them.
Hancock and the agents split commissions generated from sales.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock, which oversees $120 billion in assets, will require its
career agents to acquire certification by one of three financial
planning accreditation organizations. Now, instead of a staff
salesman who sells a middle-income client a couple of insurance
policies throughout his lifetime and collects one-time fees,
Hancock affiliates will focus on wealthier customers _ those with
incomes of at least $75,000 who need advice as well as insurance.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, Hancock had nearly 8,000 career agents to its
current 3,000, of which one third are staff and the rest are
independent contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock plans to cast off its mutual form of ownership, in which
policyholders are nominal owners of the company, and issue public
stock in 2000. While Marra said Signator could in theory be spun
off and taken public some day, he said no such plans were currently
in the works.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-99 1942EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990301.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3637 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUCCI-LVMH-ART-2NDTAK     03-01 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUCCI-LVMH-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: is unacceptable.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   De Sole also sees sinister motives in LVMH's actions. Since Ford
and De Sole took Gucci public in 1995, sales have exploded, to $1
billion in 1998 from $264 million. At the same time, sales for
Louis Vuitton, the LVMH brand that Gucci most directly competes
against, grew only to $1.4 billion, from $1.1 billion. ``Clearly,''
De Sole said, ``there is great value on his part in just stopping
Gucci.'' He added, ``While Arnault was telling Tom and me how much
he loved us, he went to one of our shareholders and told them he
would have his `eyes and ears' on our board. I can't let them have
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Gucci shareholders agree with De Sole's foreboding and
several are almost apoplectic about LVMH's machinations. Sewall F.
Hodges, a senior vice president of Scudder Kemper Investments,
which holds 4 percent of Gucci, said, ``The risk posed by a
competitor on the board, particularly someone from LVMH, which has
shown it can't keep pace, is enormous.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnault scoffs at the notion that this a plot to thwart Gucci.
``Would you put $1.5 billion in something that you want to
destroy?'' he asked. ``I think what is happening is De Sole does
not want the pressure of being pressured to improve profit
margins.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford and De Sole say they would agree to work for LVMH if
Arnault made a ``fair offer'' for all the stock. De Sole gave
Arnault a dollar figure, which he would not disclose but which is
surely far higher than $68.875 a share, the market price as of
Monday on the New York Stock Exchange for Gucci's registered
shares, each of which represents one ordinary share.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in interviews both have said flatly that independence
would be preferable. And now, at least, both can barely conceal
their reluctance to work for Arnault. De Sole bristles at the
thought that he could learn from Arnault's management style,
pointing out that LVMH's total profit margins are 9 percent, well
below Gucci's 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Since there is no precedent under Dutch law for Gucci's stock
plan tactic, it is hard to predict how the court might decide. If
the five-judge panel rules in Gucci's favor, it would be hard for
Arnault to acquire more shares. Still, he has said that he will not
disappear. ``We'll be there a long time after Mr. De Sole
retires,'' he said. ``We are still Gucci's No. 1 shareholder.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the court does rule in Arnault's favor, he is likely to
continue increasing his stake and push through his nominations to
the board. It is questionable under such circumstances whether De
Sole would be asked to stay on. The once cordial relationship
between Arnault and De Sole is in shreds. ``Ask him if he will
stay,'' Arnault snapped, then softened and added: ``We'll try to
work with him. We'll give him a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Arnault still hopes Ford will stay on. ``He's
exceptionally good for Gucci,'' he said. ``Without him, it's less
of a good investment.'' Although Arnault and De Sole have had
several communications in person and by phone and fax in the last
two months, Arnault has yet to speak with Ford. ``I sent him a
memo,'' he said. ``He gave it to M. De Sole.''
</P>
<P>
   That raises the question of whether fashion's dynamic duo could
be split up. De Sole does not think it is possible. He says he and
the designer are ``best friends.'' When Gucci started getting red
hot, De Sole told his two daughters that tickets to the biannual
runway shows were too precious to give to family. They went around
his back to Ford, who let them in backstage and allowed them to
drape models and otherwise soak up the glamour.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, Ford confirmed the magic of the
relationship, saying he could not imagine working in the industry
without De Sole. But asked bluntly if he would quit if LVMH raised
its stake in Gucci, Ford paused. ``I'd have to evaluate the
situation,'' he said. ``Not only do I feel loyalty to shareholders,
but we have built this company. I hired a lot of these people. It
would be a hard decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford's position, clearly, is tougher than it appeared at first.
He enjoys an extraordinary amount of creative freedom for someone
whose name is not on the door of a fashion company. He designs
Gucci's women's collection, men's wear, accessories and store
layout, and he directs the company's advertising and public
relations.
</P>
<P>
   This would be hard to replicate elsewhere. For that matter, it
might be hard to replicate at LVMH. Arnault has made it clear that
he believes not every designer deserves to be so involved. ``It's
one thing to design fantastic clothes and hype them,'' he said.
``It's something else to meet the customer, look at shoes, buy
leather.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain. Arnault, who fought a brutal battle for
LVMH years ago, is not prepared to walk away even if all of Gucci's
talent does. ``We have already invested a lot of money,'' he
explained.
</P>
<P>
   Industry executives, used to sudden entrances and exits of
designers, foresee a diminished, though not finished, Gucci without
Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Gucci is an important resource at most luxury stores. ``We'd be
concerned if he left because Tom has given the brand the
personality that appeals to customers,'' said Dawn Mello, president
of Bergdorf Goodman, a subsidiary of Neiman Marcus. As head of
Gucci in the early '90s, it was Ms. Mello who set the stage for
Gucci's rebirth as a coveted brand, and who hired Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Still, plenty of companies thrive beyond their creators. In
fact, one need look no further than Gucci, which was founded by the
Gucci family in 1923. ``You look at great companies, and they go
on,'' said Michael Gould, chairman of Bloomingdale's, a unit of
Federated Department Stores. ``When people have a vision and they
build a business on a solid foundation, it will continue to grow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
