</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT TAKES UP CLASH OVER WORKPLACE-BIAS DAMAGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., S.C.) (nk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Eight years after Congress added teeth to the basic
federal law against discrimination in the workplace, the Supreme
Court on Monday took up one of the most important questions under
the expanded law: When can employees who have proved that they were
victims of discrimination win damages sufficient to punish their
employers?
</P>
<P>
   After years in which prevailing employees were entitled to no
more than back pay and reinstatement in their old jobs, Congress
provided in 1991 that those who proved intentional discrimination
were entitled to compensation for their pain, suffering and future
lost wages. Further, the expanded Title VII of the Civil Rights Act
of 1964 provided that employers who acted with ``malice'' or
``reckless indifference'' could be ordered by a jury to pay
punitive damages of up to $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   To that requirement for punitive damages, the federal appeals
court here, in a bitterly divided 6-to-5 opinion, last year added
another: that the employer be shown to have engaged in ``egregious
discriminatory conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   But a lawyer for a woman who won her sex discrimination case and
then lost her chance for punitive damages told the justices Monday,
``We don't think the courts are at liberty to add'' another
prerequisite.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Egregious conduct' is not a possible interpretation of any
provision in the statute,'' the lawyer, Eric Schnapper, told the
court.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration joined the appeal on behalf of
Schnapper's client, Carole Kolstad, who was a high-ranking
executive with the American Dental Association when she lost a
desired promotion in the organization's Washington office to a man
with less seniority. The evidence showed that Ms. Kolstad had not
been seriously considered for the position. The jury found
intentional sex discrimination and awarded her $53,000 in back pay,
but the trial judge refused to let the jury consider whether to go
further and award punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   Although a three-judge panel of the U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals for the District of Columbia overturned the punitive
damages ruling, the full court said the district court had been
correct in not sending the punitive damages claim to the jury,
because the evidence ``does not show the kind of egregious
discriminatory conduct necessary for the imposition of punitive
damages.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court's ruling on the standards for punitive damages
will affect a broad array of discrimination cases. In addition to
sex discrimination, Title VII covers discrimination on the basis of
race and religion, and a later federal discrimination law, the
Americans With Disabilities Act of 1990, borrowed the Title VII
language on damages. Discrimination claims under the Fair Housing
Act will also be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond its practical importance, the case, Kolstad vs. American
Dental Association, No. 98-208, also offers an interesting window
on the judicial process. Although those who call themselves
judicial conservatives often declare that it is a judge's job to
apply law rather than make law, it was the conservatives on the
appeals court who added the concept of egregious behavior to the
statute that Congress wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In the administration's Supreme Court brief on Ms. Kolstad's
behalf, Solicitor General Seth P. Waxman asserted that the appeals
court ``was not free to reconsider'' the congressional policy
judgment that ``all unlawful intentional discrimination undertaken
with malice or reckless indifference to federal law is inherently
deserving of punishment through an award of punitive damages.''
</P>
<P>
   During the argument Monday, Justice Antonin Scalia appeared
particularly frustrated by the inability of the defendant's lawyer,
Raymond C. Fay, to provide a clear definition of egregious conduct
in the context of the statute, or to say where in the law itself
the concept might be found.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you mean by an egregious act?'' Scalia demanded,
adding, ``The act only covers firing, not murder or torture or
anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Fay replied that an egregious act could be an act of
discrimination that puts the victim ``into a horrible mental
state.''
</P>
<P>
   That answer drew an intervention from Justice Ruth Bader
Ginsburg. ``Punitive damages doesn't turn on whether the plaintiff
is thin-skinned, does it?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Scalia then exclaimed: ``I have it! Firing on Christmas Eve.
That does it!''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the argument, when Fay complained that under the view
of Ms. Kolstad's lawyers, virtually all cases of intentional
discrimination would go to the jury on the question of punitive
damages, Justice Stephen G. Breyer asked him, ``Isn't that what the
statute says?''
</P>
<P>
   Working in the defendant's favor, however, is the Supreme
Court's general dislike of punitive damages, as expressed in a
number of recent decisions. Justice Sandra Day O'Connor and Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist both expressed concern Monday that the
law made an award of punitive damages almost automatic once the
fact of discrimination was proved.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy wondered aloud whether it would be
fair to subject a company to punitive damages for denying a job to
a pregnant woman in the ``good faith'' belief that it was in her
best interest not to undertake those particular duties.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a separate development at the court Monday, the justices
agreed to hear an appeal by environmental groups in a case that
could determine the usefulness of the ``citizen suit'' provisions
that are part of many federal environmental laws. In providing for
recovery of lawyers' fees and litigation costs, Congress intended
to expand enforcement of the laws by encouraging private suits
against environmental violators.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Friends of the Earth vs. Laidlaw Environmental
Services, No. 98-822, a company that was discharging mercury and
other hazardous waste into a South Carolina river changed its
behavior soon after environmental groups brought suit under the
Clean Water Act. Although the federal District Court in Columbia,
S.C., fined the company $405,000, the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, in Richmond, Va., ordered the case dismissed as moot
because there was no ongoing violation of the law. Under this
interpretation, plaintiffs lose the right to recover their fees and
costs if their success comes too soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
