<SLUG> BC-OPEN-RECORDS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL REVIEWING BILLS TARGETING MINORITY FINANCIAL RECORDS,
EXECUTIVE SESSIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JULIE MASON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A House committee is considering two open
government bills with potentially far-reaching implications for
minority contracting and executive sessions.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Robert Talton, R-Pasadena, filed a bill that would
repeal a measure passed in the 1997 Texas Legislature exempting
certain financial records of applicants to minority contracting
programs from public disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Talton, who said he filed the bill at the request of a
constituent, told the House State Affairs Committee on Monday that
any firm seeking government contracts should be willing to open
their books.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make my tax returns public, I have always done that,''
Talton said. ``I think that if you're going to do business with us,
you ought to have your open records.''
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, the 1997 law has allowed city officials to withhold
from public scrutiny the financial information supplied by
applicants to the city's Minority, Women and Disadvantaged Business
Enterprise program.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the law complain that firms benefiting from the
city's affirmative action contracting program have been able to
shield their financial status, giving fuel to claims the program
benefits wealthy contractors.
</P>
<P>
   But state Rep. Sylvester Turner, D-Houston, vice chair of the
House committee, noted that Anglo males who compete for city and
state contracts have no similar requirement to open their books to
public scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned that we are targeting specific businesses and
making them provide more information than others,'' Turner said.
``If it's such good government, let's get the same information from
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner noted that the 1997 law did more to ``even the playing
field'' by shielding such information.
</P>
<P>
   Roy McQueen, publisher of the Snyder Daily News, told the
committee that the Texas Press Association and the Texas Daily
Newspaper Association favor Talton's bill.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the bill include business groups, such as the Texas
Association of Mexican American Chambers of Commerce, and the Small
Businesses United of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The organizations claim that making such information public
again would allow competitors access to minority and women-owned
firms' financial information.
</P>
<P>
   They also claim that fewer firms will seek public contracts if
they are forced to make their tax returns and bank statements
public, and that such a requirement amounts to a penalty against
certified contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Another measure before the committee would require all
governmental entities to electronically record their closed,
executive sessions.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Arthur Reyna, D-San Antonio, said his bill is aimed
at prohibiting governmental bodies from discussing improper items
in secret _ rather than allowing public access to issues discussed
in executive session.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be no elected official who is afraid of having
their executive sessions recorded,'' Reyna said.
</P>
<P>
   State law allows elected bodies to go into closed session and
discuss real estate, personnel and litigation matters only, and
either record the meeting or follow a certified agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a very disciplined body not to discuss other matters
once they get into executive session,'' McQueen said.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Debra Danburg, D-Houston, concurred and added, ``I
think we all agree the certified agenda is completely bogus.''
</P>
<P>
   McQueen said the news organizations he represents do not
necessarily seek access to the real estate, personnel and
litigation matters discussed in lawful executive session _ rather,
they wish to deter unlawful discussions by requiring the use of
recording devices.
</P>
<P>
   Committee members, however, agreed the bill needs some
fine-tuning on how long such tapes would be stockpiled, and under
what guidelines the information they contain would be made public.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
