</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BISON-SLAUGHTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIAN TRIBES' PROTESTS AGAINST BISON SLAUGHTER INTENSIFY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wyo., Mont., S.D.) (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. _ As a few hundred people
watched beneath the snow-dappled peaks on the northern edge of this
park, Gary Silk, a Lakota Sioux, stripped to the waist. As he stood
in the numbing wind, in the shadow of the giant stone arch that
greets visitors here, other members of his tribe made two incisions
in his back with a surgical scalpel, inserted a stick in each
wound, and tied a buffalo skull to each stick with long ropes.
Then, as 100 or so Indians sang and drummed and played an eagle
bone flute, Silk danced around a large circle dragging the skulls
through the mud and grass behind him.
</P>
<P>
   After a half-hour of dancing, Silk stopped and someone sat on
the skulls. Silk grabbed a horse's tail and the animal pulled away,
ripping the sticks from his bloody wounds. Then, as people wept,
Silk joined the singing and drumming.
</P>
<P>
   The intense religious ceremony, performed this weekend for the
first time in 100 years, was part of a protest against the
slaughter of bison that leave Yellowstone Park each winter. While
two mild winters have allowed the slaughter to diminish, the
protest against the killing has increased.
</P>
<P>
   The herd of 2,400 in the park are consider the last free-roaming
bison, though domestic herds are found throughout the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Ranchers fear that when the bison wander out of the park and
onto state and federal land in Montana, where winter is less harsh,
they will transmit a disease called brucellosis to cattle. So,
under state policy, once the animals leave the park, they are
tested for the disease and if they test positive are either shot or
shipped to slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   The last two winters here have been mild, with little snow, and
few animals have left the park. So far this year 17 bison have been
shipped to slaughter, and 500 animals have been hazed back into the
park. Last year 11 animals were killed.
</P>
<P>
   But during the winter of 1996-1997 nearly 1,100 animals were
shot by state agents or shipped to slaughterhouses, inspiring the
latest intensifying round of protests.
</P>
<P>
   The Park Service has been inundated with mail and phone calls
imploring them to halt the killings, and a recent draft
environmental impact statement on the subject drew 65,000 public
comments. Environmentalists and animal protection groups have gone
to federal court to stop the killing, to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   This year members of a small group of animal activists called
Buffalo Nations moved near the park and tried to disrupt the
trapping and shipping of bison by blocking the capture and erecting
tall tripods out of logs in the path of the people loading the
animals. Several have been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   For the ceremony on Saturday, about 40 traditional Lakota made a
20-day, 507-mile pilgrimage, on foot, on horseback and in pickup
trucks, from their reservation in the Black Hills of South Dakota.
They were joined by some 60 other traditional Indian leaders from
around from the nation, including the Southern Ute, Apache,
Tuscarora and the Nez Perce.
</P>
<P>
   The Sioux, the Nez Perce, the Crow and other tribes all hunted
bison on the plains in and on the Yellowstone Plateau, and the
animal was central to the cultures, providing food, shelter and
clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our prophecy says that if the buffalo disappear, our people
will disappear,'' Joseph Chasing Horse, a Sioux spokesman, told
those in attendance. ``Pray for the children and the grandchildren
of the two-legged animals, for we know not what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the Montana Department of Livestock say they have
no alternative to the killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to save as many bison as possible,'' said Arnold
Gertonson, the Montana State Veterinarian. ``We hate to shoot them.
But we're protecting Montana's brucellosis-free status.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists and some scientists say bison pose no threat
to cattle and that there has never been a case of the disease being
transmitted in the wild. But a recent study by the National Academy
of Sciences found a small, but real, risk of transmission of the
disease to cattle.
</P>
<P>
   Some progress has been made toward creating more habitat for
bison outside of the park. On Feb. 11, the Church Universal and
Triumphant, which owns a ranch adjacent to the park, sold 6,000
acres to public ownership. And the U.S. Forest Service has arranged
to have 900 or so cattle that graze on public land west of the park
out of the area until a month after the bison are gone, which
should remove some of the risk of transmission. But that still
leaves 1,100 cattle on private land.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole issue has turned on about 2,000 cattle,'' said Jon
Catton, a spokesman for the Greater Yellowstone Coalition, an
environmental group in Bozeman, Mont.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
