A3644 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCOFARMERS-PROTES     03-01 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCOFARMERS-PROTEST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    N.C. tobacco growers demanding relief
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. _ Among the hundreds of hand-scrawled signs
hanging from tractors in Monday's motorcade of North Carolina
tobacco farmers, the message on Thomas Hall's green John Deere put
it simply:
</P>
<P>
   ``For sale.''
</P>
<P>
   The 40-year-old farmer from Black River, N.C., is trying to sell
all three of his tractors. He hopes to raise enough money to reduce
his $250,000 debt and have some left over to plant tobacco this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Without tractors of his own, Hall would need the help of a
neighbor, a humbling proposition for the fourth-generation farmer.
But, Hall said, ``I've got to do whatever I can to get rid of this
debt.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a frightening season for the growers of tobacco,
traditionally the South's most lucrative crop. But profits are
evaporating, and farmers are looking desperately for financial help
in an era when public sympathy for the tobacco industry is hard to
muster.
</P>
<P>
   The farmers' plight in North Carolina, the nation's largest
flue-cured tobacco producer, illustrates how the once-comfortable
lifestyle afforded by the golden leaf is disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our last chance, maybe our last stand,'' Keith Parrish
shouted at the early morning crowd of 1,000 farmers and their
families preparing for the motorcade of 500 tractors, lined up like
tanks headed into battle.
</P>
<P>
   Mounted atop the tractors, American flags and green banners
emblazoned with golden leafs whipped in the cold wind. ``We're not
greedy _ we're desperate,'' read one of the many signs plastered on
tractors.
</P>
<P>
   Fear and anger drove farmers to organize the slow-moving, noisy
parade that clogged traffic from the state fairgrounds to the state
legislative building in downtown Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco farming groups are seeking at least half of the $4.6
billion that the state of North Carolina expects to receive over 25
years from last fall's $206 billion national tobacco settlement.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina Attorney General Mike Easley helped negotiate the
historic settlement between 46 states, including Georgia, and the
four biggest U.S. cigarette makers. The companies agreed to pay
$206 billion in exchange for relief from states' lawsuits seeking
reimbursement for the costs of treating sick smokers.
</P>
<P>
   Easley proposed that half the state's share go to rebuild
communities hurt by tobacco's demise, and the other half to health
care programs. The state Senate approved that plan last week, and
the state House plans to take it up in the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Farm leaders are urging North Carolina's Legislature to
designate at least half of the $4.6 billion as direct compensation
to farmers and the holders of tobacco quotas, which gives farmers
federal permission to grow and sell the crop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want economic viability for farm families, not
re-development of North Carolina's landscape,'' read a petition
that tobacco farm leaders delivered Monday to the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the $4.6 billion, cigarette companies have pledged an
additional $2 billion to North Carolina tobacco farmers and their
communities. But farmers said they need more than $2 billion amid
declining cigarette consumption.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, the federal goverment has slashed by 35
percent the acreage of tobacco that farmers can grow. Farmers said
that translates roughly into a 35 percent reduction in their
income.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I survive this year, I'll be lucky,'' said Randolph County
farmer Grover Burgess, 62, who sold two tractors to raise money.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Burritt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
