<SLUG> BC-TRINITY-MIRROR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIRROR REJECTS TRINITY'S SWEETENED BID
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The Mirror Group PLC, which owns one of Britain's
oldest tabloids, rejected a sweetened offer of $1.53 billion on
Monday from Trinity PLC, the country's biggest regional newspaper
group, and said it was talking with a rival suitor.
</P>
<P>
   The developments escalated the probability of a takeover battle
in Britain's cutthroat newspaper industry.
</P>
<P>
   Uncertainty about the future ownership of Mirror Group, which
publishes both the daily and Sunday Mirror tabloids, increased
following the ouster of its chief executive, David Montgomery, on
Jan. 26 after a bruising public feud between him and board members
and stockholders.
</P>
<P>
   Mirror Group had shrugged off earlier offers from both Trinity
and and its rival _ Regional Independent Media, which is owned by
Candover Investment Trust, a venture capital organization backed by
George Soros, the financier, and a unit of Deutsche Bank.
</P>
<P>
   A previous offer from Trinity valued Mirror Group stock at 160
pence ($2.50) a share, or about $1.2 billion. Last January, Mirror
Group rejected an offer from Candover based on a share price of 200
pence. That offer valued the group at around $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Trinity said its latest offer of equity and cash valued Mirror
stock at 210 pence a share _ a premium of 3.4 percent over Monday's
closing price of 203 pence. Takeover offers in recent months have
pushed Mirror Group stock from a low of 136 pence last October.
</P>
<P>
   But in a statement, Mirror Group said Trinity's offer of 40
pence cash plus 0.35 percent of a Trinity share for each Mirror
share represented `'an inadequate premium for a change of
control.''
</P>
<P>
   Trinity said it was surprised at Mirror Group's response.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a regional British newspaper chain bidding for a
national newspaper would once have been unusual. But regional
chains have prospered in recent years as a result of cost-saving
consolidation, while the brutal competition among national
newspapers has been costly to them. Before his resignation,
Montgomery, the former Mirror Group chief executive, said the daily
Mirror had slipped to third place behind the Daily Mail and Rupert
Murdoch's top-selling Sun.
</P>
<P>
   Trinity, by contrast, said Monday that its profit last year was
up 43 percent, to around $101 million, on a 5.4 percent increase in
sales to $564 million, which analysts attributed to strong
advertising revenue. The figures slightly exceeded expectations.
Trinity's share price gained 2.5 percent, to 498 pence.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the two national tabloids, the Mirror Group publishes
several Scottish and regional newspapers and operates a cable
television channel, Live TV. But it is also burdened with debt from
the days of its former owner, Robert Maxwell, who drowned at sea in
1991. It later emerged that Maxwell had raided the Mirror's pension
fund to divert the equivalent of about $35.2 million into other
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery, who took over as chief executive in 1992, had been
widely credited with reviving the Mirror Group's fortunes, but, in
the process, lost favor among both institutional investors and
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   The Mirror Group said on Monday that it was still in discussions
with Regional Independent Media, which began talking with Mirror
last month. There were unconfirmed newspaper reports Sunday that
the Mirror Group was anticipating an offer worth $1.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Any deal must be approved by British competition regulators.
Regional Independent Media indicated Monday that it might await
regulators' approval before making a formal bid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
