<DOCNO> NYT19990301.0352 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3654 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEC-RULING-COX     03-01 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEC-RULING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge gives go-ahead to profit freeze
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A federal judge in New York Monday continued a freeze
of $2.5 million from the sale of stock in companies connected to a
Madison, Ga. man and a storefront on that small, east Georgia
town's Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the Securities Exchange Commission asked the U.S.
District Court to issue a temporary restraining order to keep
Glittergrove Investments from transferring abroad money from the
sale of Citron and Electronic Transfer Associates.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC claims Glittergrove and seven other offshore entities
are represented by Peter C. Lybrand, a 34-year-old Madison man
previously known as Peter C. Tosto.
</P>
<P>
   Tosto is somewhat of a mystery man. He has been working for more
than two years out of a Madison storefront connected to five public
companies whose trading was suspended by the SEC for 10 days Jan.
29.
</P>
<P>
   Press releases about the companies _ Citron, Electronic Transfer
Associates, Polus, Smartek and Invest Holdings Group _ list a phone
number that rings at 115 S. Main St. in Madison.
</P>
<P>
   Tosto has been elusive and does not answer repeated phone
inquiries or knocks on the door of his Madison office and
residence, a Victorian mansion down the street from his office.
</P>
<P>
   In stopping trading of his companies, the SEC questioned the
quality and quantity of information available to investors. On the
heels of a series of press releases, Citron's stock rose from $1.25
on Dec. 30 to $21 on Jan. 25. The SEC claims Tosto arranged for the
public sale of 30,500 Citron shares between Jan. 15 and 26. That
sale netted $886,000. The rest of the $2.5 million came from sales
of Electronic Transfer Associates.
</P>
<P>
   According to the SEC, before the federal agency could stop it,
$350,000 from the sale of Citron and Electronic Transfer Associates
was transferred overseas by Glittergrove, an Irish corporation that
Tosto represented in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The money was transferred to other overseas companies that Tosto
allegedly represented.
</P>
<P>
   Just one episode
</P>
<P>
   The Glittergrove case is one chapter of what could be a sizable
book on Tosto's history with securities regulators. Federal court
and agency documents reveal:
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1991, Tosto pleaded guilty in federal court to conspiracy
to commit wire fraud. The then-27-year-old received a three-year
suspended sentence with three months in a halfway house and 200
hours of community service.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1996, Tosto was permanently barred by the SEC from
associating with any securities broker, dealer, investment company
or investment adviser after his dealings with a Colorado company.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1997, after he had set up shop in Madison, Tosto was
ordered to pay a $1.1 million fine in connection with a kickback
scheme involving shares of San Diego Bancorp. However, he testified
that he didn't expect to pay more than a fraction of that. SEC
officials, reached Monday, could not confirm whether any part of
the fine has been paid.
</P>
<P>
   _ In May 1998, Tosto pleaded guilty to securities manipulation
charges in federal court in Manhattan. He is awaiting sentencing in
that case and is cooperating with the government. He was released
on his own recognizance.
</P>
<P>
   A low-profile figure
</P>
<P>
   Despite a central role in public lawsuits, Tosto exists mostly
in black and white. He does not return phone calls from reporters.
His senior picture is his only appearance in the 1982 yearbook of
West Babylon High School on Long Island, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with former business associates and Tosto's own
testimony in late 1997 offer some clues.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination in federal court in New York in December
1997, Tosto said that during 1996, he conducted a radio show and
put out investor newsletters. Tosto testified that agents with the
SEC and U.S. Attorney's office were aware of those activities and
finally told him to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Tosto's testimony under cross-examination came in a 1997 civil
case filed against him by a company named Advanced Lighting
Solutions Inc. and others to reclaim control of 10 percent of the
company. A settlement was reached, but it has not yet been carried
out, according to the president of the company.
</P>
<P>
   David Gothard, president of Advanced Lighting Solutions, said he
met Tosto about four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gothard and partner Bruce Gordon were trying to raise money for
their Las Vegas-based company. One way to do that is to buy a shell
company, a public company that has no operations. The private
company becomes public by merging with the public shell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had put the word out that I was looking for a shell,''
Gothard said in a telephone interview with The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. ``It's a small community. There's not a lot
of people who do this. They all talk. But after I got in bed with
this guy, I realized he's been around.''
</P>
<P>
   Gothard said his first hint of trouble came when he tried to
file the paperwork to sell shares of the company in New York.
Gothard said the state Attorney General's office told him some of
Tosto's history.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, Gothard said he went to Tosto's office on
West 30th Street in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to Peter, `How in the world? All this I'm hearing
here.' I said, `How do you sleep at night?'
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, 'Dave, I have immunity. They won't touch me.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Neither Tosto nor his lawyer, Steven Kaplan, could be reached
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clothier writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
