<SLUG> BC-MA-LIQUOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL TO ALLOW SUNDAY LIQUOR SALES ADVANCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A bill that would allow all stores to sell liquor on
Sundays has taken a major step forward, with legislators saying
current restrictions are not fair.
</P>
<P>
   The joint Government Regulations Committee recommended 8-7
Monday that the full House pass the legislation, which would give
all communities the option to permit package stores to open seven
days a week. Currently, only cities and towns within 10 miles of
the Vermont or New Hampshire borders have that choice.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Package Store Association has not taken a
position on the matter, lobbyists for liquor companies are laying
low, and mom-and-pop alcohol retailers are split _ mostly along
geographic lines _ on Sunday openings. But propelling the issue on
Beacon Hill is a Superior Court judge's ruling in August that the
current law is arbitrary.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Judge Margaret Hinkle came in a suit brought
against the state by North Shore package store owners who claimed
the law, enacted in 1990, put them at an unfair disadvantage to
stores closer to the border. The judge agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Daniel Bosley, House chairman of the committee,
had opposed the idea of seven-day operations, but he cosponsored
the new bill, saying the issue needed to be settled in wake of
Hinkle's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably would not have done anything if it weren't for the
court case last year in Ipswich,'' Bosley said. ``We need to
clarify the law. Since there are stores that have been open who
would suffer adverse impact, I filed a bill to open all the
stores.''
</P>
<P>
   Bosley and other lawmakers believe it would be wrong to pull the
plug on stores who can currently make Sunday sales. The solution,
he says, is to give all communities the option.
</P>
<P>
   Not all package store owners like the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Although those just beyond the 10-mile buffer established in
1990 near the northern border feel they are being hurt as a result
of the Sunday ban, those in Southeastern Massachusetts, for
example, do not believe they are at a competitive disadvantage
because stores in Rhode Island are closed Sundays too.
</P>
<P>
   The local option bill would require shop owners who choose to
open on Sunday to pay employees time-and-a-half and make work
voluntary on that day. Package stores could not open before noon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
