</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-PROFILING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL SEEKS EVIDENCE OF RACIAL `PROFILING' BY STATE POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Seeking to determine if hard data support persistent
anecdotal evidence of racial ``profiling'' of motorists, lawmakers
want to require the state attorney general to break down the race,
gender, and age of drivers involved in routine traffic stops.
</P>
<P>
   A bill filed Monday by Senator Dianne P. Wilkerson (D-Roxbury)
would commission a two-year analysis of the number of minorities
stopped by police officers in Massachusetts and investigate whether
the stops resulted in a search, an arrest, or a seizure of
contraband.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that needs to be talked about,'' said
Kristine Glynn, Wilkerson's legislative aide. ``People have called
in to report an abnormal amount of traffic stops for minorities,
mostly young black men,'' both in and outside the senator's
district, Glynn said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which would mimick studies requested in New Jersey and
Maryland, follows complaints by two black law-enforcement agents
who said they were harassed in separate incidents by Reading
police. In addition, the New Jersey State Police superintendent,
already under heavy criticism for alleged racial profiling by
troopers there, was fired Sunday by Governor Christine Todd Whitman
after a newspaper report in which he said minorities are more
likely than whites to be involved in drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkerson's proposal is backed by Representative Byron Rushing
(D-Roxbury). ``There is so much anecdotal information about this
that, inside the black community, it has gotten a name: DWB, or
driving while black,'' Rushing said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkerson's concerns also are shared by Representative Benjamin
Swan, a Springfield Democrat who has filed a bill to prohibit law
officers from the ``arbitrary'' investigation of people based on
race, age, gender, and several other criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Swan, who is black, says his family has direct experience with
unjustified traffic stops. His son, Benjamin Swan Jr., 39, a
computer specialist at Smith &AMP; Wesson in Springfield, said in an
interview Monday that he had been stopped three times for no
apparent reason.
</P>
<P>
   Rushing said he would urge Wilkerson to add a requirement that
police departments, on their own, begin compiling profiles of
motorists involved in traffic stops. Brookline police began the
practice two years ago, in response to concerns raised within the
community about the makeup of the 20,000 motorists stopped by town
officers each year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
