<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMAZON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMAZON.COM SITE TELLS USERS OF BOOK PROMOTION PAYMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Responding to complaints from customers, Amazon.com retooled its
popular online bookstore on Monday so that it would disclose when
publishers pay money to subsidize titles that are highlighted or
featured with favorable reviews.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle-based company used a note on its home page to invite
readers to ``learn about co-op placements,'' the jargon of the
publishing industry for advertising payments made to bookstore
chains or large independent stores to feature titles in prominent
sites in stores.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the term ``co-op placements'' might be unclear to the
average reader, David Risher, Amazon's senior vice president for
product development, said the company struggled over what term to
use and temporarily settled on the phrasing after consulting with
publishers. He said the company was still prepared to ``tweak'' the
wording to make it more clear.
</P>
<P>
   When the co-op placement icon is clicked, the viewer is offered
a list of more than 30 categories of books in which particular
titles have been subsidized by publishers. In the nonfiction
category, for instance, publishers paid to promote ``Perfect
Murder, Perfect Town,'' Lawrence Schiller's exploration of the
JonBenet Ramsey murder case.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon said it decided to make the disclosure after customers
expressed qualms about the practice taking hold at the online
bookstore, which had distinguished itself with its editorial voice
and staff recommendations. The concerns were expressed after The
New York Times disclosed the practice last month.
</P>
<P>
   Risher said the response of consumers to the disclosure of the
practice was ``almost surprising in its intensity'' and that many
consumers simply wanted the company to be more open about the
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end we only want to display the books that our
customers want to know about,'' Risher said, stressing that the
co-op dollars from publishers would not influence Amazon's choice
of books to highlight.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon's big online competitor, Barnesandnoble.com, has also
begun seeking co-op advertising dollars from book publishers. Its
system of alerting readers is more traditional, with advertising
promotions appearing only on the left band of its home page and
highlighted graphically as advertisements, according to Ben Boyd, a
company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times maintains links between its online book
review and Barnesandnoble.com, receiving commissions for sales.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
