<HEADER>
A3658 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-HUMMER-COLUMN-COX     03-01 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-HUMMER-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's not Atlanta, no way
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The people who brought you the Atlanta Olympics _
motto: ``We're Cleaner than a Tub of Lye, Y'all'' _ have made it
formal.
</P>
<P>
   After a long, hard look at themselves, they have concluded that,
yes, as a matter of fact, they are beyond reproach.
</P>
<P>
   ``No wrongdoing,'' Billy Payne wrote to Juan Antonio Samaranch,
as part of a response to the International Olympic Committee's
investigation of its grimy bid process. ``Atlanta won the games
`fair and square,' in an honorable manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Whew. What a relief to know that we were an island of purity in
a sea of corruption. Guess that pretty well settles that.
</P>
<P>
   Pardon the cynicism, but what other option is there? This
soul-search carried no weight. It came with no documentation,
ACOG's records still hidden away like J. Edgar Hoover's evening
gowns. It ultimately had all the meaning of a eulogy written in
advance by the dearly departed.
</P>
<P>
   It is a disservice to history to ask that we accept on faith
that the Atlanta bid process was perfectly clean, even as certain
IOC members came to expect the big favor and the serious grease
everywhere else. ``Take our word for it'' stopped being an
acceptable explanation several presidencies ago.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Atlanta effort was most exceptional, ethically
speaking, this continued secrecy and in-house arrogance makes
buying any of it awfully difficult. The natural question remains,
``What are they hiding?'' Not, ``Why can't we just move along?''
</P>
<P>
   More than that, though, this kind of institutional whitewashing
is a disservice to those who might actually want to fix the bid
process. Assuming the IOC is at all serious in its investigation,
it needs some facts to act upon. All the Atlanta response provided
was fluff. A little institutional methane was not exactly the fuel
for change called for here.
</P>
<P>
   You just know that Samaranch would love to sit on this, just
like his old buddy, Francisco Franco, taught him. Fight all
challenges right up to the moment he draws his last breath, that's
how the generalissimo handled such matters. Samaranch doesn't need
any more allies, witting or not.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, another report was issued, this by a United States
Olympic Committee ethics commission. (Atlanta, by the way, was
mentioned only once, in passing). It made several recommendations
for altering how cities are awarded Olympic Games, which probably
will get passed along to the IOC's in-basket.
</P>
<P>
   The ideas seemed to make perfect sense.
</P>
<P>
   Like allowing bid cities to give only cheap gifts, the kind the
media usually gets. They'll just love all those flimsy backpacks.
</P>
<P>
   Like permitting no receptions or galas. Let them eat take-out.
</P>
<P>
   Like regularly electing the IOC membership instead of giving
them job security a pope would envy.
</P>
<P>
   Like establishing an Office of Bid Compliance, to audit every
temptation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympic flame must burn clean once ag ain,'' the report
grandly concluded.
</P>
<P>
   By not opening themselves to any serious scrutiny, the Atlanta
organizers would seem satisfied with maintaining the current smudge
pot. That's the appearance, which does nothing with the problem but
give it a second wind.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing the Olympic movement needs now is more
self-congratulation.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hummer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Email: steve(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
