<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE A SCANDAL IN THE WIND
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR;  compared herself to  &UR; Princess Diana &LR;  in an
interview published in the Sunday Mirror of Britain. ``I was also
wronged by a man who said he loved me,'' said Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Although she admitted ``I'm not a princess in the royal sense,''
she said she sees herself ``in a similar situation. ... Remember, I
was in love with him. I was trapped, too. I had a lot of pressure
on me, and like Diana, I had nowhere to go, nowhere to hide.''
</P>
<P>
   She recalled the budding of her relationship with Clinton, when
she walked into his office in a short green skirt, and he
complimented her on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You like it?'' asked Lewinsky, to which she says he replied,
``I'd like to see what's underneath it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So I lifted my skirt and showed him, and he said, `Nice.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Mirror reporter  &UR; Andrew Golden  &LR; talked with Lewinsky in New York
as she was beginning her book collaboration with  &UR; Andrew Morton &LR; ,
who had previously written about Diana. It may have been Morton who
brought up the similarities, in an effort to put Lewinsky at ease.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; YOUNG MR. CLINTON IN ENGLAND &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Feminist ground-breaker  &UR; Germaine Greer &LR;  spoke at Warwick
University in England recently and told the story of a 1969
encounter with  &UR; Bill Clinton &LR; , who was studying in England as a
Rhodes scholar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was speaking at the Oxford Union,'' she said in the
Telegraph of London. ``There was an annoying red-faced American in
a seersucker suit arguing that equality in the workplace was all
that women really want. So I told him that what I really wanted was
the right to be hairy, the right to my own secretions and the right
to my own protuberances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was only much later I discovered who the red-faced American
was.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to say whether Greer's story was an altered version of
the one she told in 1992, when Clinton was first elected. She said
then that she had been expounding on the virtues of sex with
working-class men as opposed to sex with bourgeois men. During the
question period, she said, Clinton piped up with, ``In case you
ever decide to give bourgeois men another chance, can I give you my
phone number?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A PANTY IS A PANTY IS A PANTY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Parents of teenage basketball players in Pardeeville, Wis.,
have complained about a junior varsity coach who forced boys who
didn't play well to wear women's panties. A letter circulated among
parents said that one student was told that if he had to wear
panties three times, he would have to wear a brassiere, too.
</P>
<P>
   Coach  &UR; Mike Weinstock  &LR; said he had learned the panty drill while
he was a student at a Catholic school. ``It was used to teach an
aspect of rebounding,'' he said, ``and to put some fun into
practice.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Ginie Sayles &LR; ' book ``How to Meet the Rich'' (Berkley; $14)
provides the answer to a business problem: What kind of underwear
should you have on if your rich client invites you to the gym?
</P>
<P>
   ``Long boxer shorts in plain white cotton are classiest.
Naturally your comfort is more important, so plain white cotton
briefs are an alternative _ but stay away from bikini or thong
styles. Although a few patterns or pastels are OK, white is your
best bet because it can be kept spotless by adding bleach to your
wash load of whites. ... If you want to, you can buy your underwear
from Wal-Mart, Kmart or Target. Remove the labels, which is classy
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Phat Farm fashions is selling shirts made out of cloth
patterned with images of the face and body of the wife of owner
 &UR; Russell Simmons &LR; . ``It's a conversational print,'' Simmons told the
New York Times. He said his wife ``doesn't know that there's
underwear, too,'' which will hit the market in May.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOP STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A list of the 100 top works of journalism in the 20th century,
compiled by 36 judges under the auspices of the department of
journalism at New York University, gave the No. 1 ranking to  &UR; John
Hersey &LR;  for ``Hiroshima,'' published in 1946 in the New Yorker. No.
2 was  &UR; Rachel Carson &LR; 's ``Silent Spring''; No. 3 was  &UR; Bob Woodward &LR; 
and  &UR; Carl Bernstein &LR; 's Watergate reporting in the Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
