A3664 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-TORNADOES-COX     03-01 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-TORNADOES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    La Nina could mean more severe weather for Ohio
 &HT;    By Wendy Hundley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Twenty five years ago, as La Nina was disrupting
weather patterns around the globe, a killer tornado struck Xenia,
Ohio, leaving 33 dead and more than 300 homes destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, La Nina is back. And the tempestuous weather system may
again bring greater risk of severe tornadoes to Ohio and other
states, according to a study by Purdue University researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Agee, professor of atmospheric sciences, and graduate
student Suzanne Zurn-Birkhimer, analyzed tornado patterns state by
state from 1916 to 1996. When they compared El Nino, La Nina and
normal years, they found a number of states had more tornadoes
during La Nina years.
</P>
<P>
   El Nino, an unusual warming of the water in the eastern Pacific
Ocean, eased last May after disrupting weather around the world for
more than a year. But rather than returning to normal, the ocean
cooled sharply into a condition known as La Nina, the opposite of
El Nino.
</P>
<P>
   Certain areas _ including Indiana, western Kentucky, western
Tennessee, and Mississippi _ averaged almost twice as many
tornadoes during the La Nina years as in El Nino years. And the
tornadoes tended to be more severe, according to Zurn-Birkhimer and
Agee.
</P>
<P>
   Other states at risk are Mississippi, Tennessee, South Carolina,
North Carolina, Kentucky, West Virginia, Virginia, Iowa, Illinois,
Ohio, Michigan and Pennsylvania, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``The study has been done by a reliable source and, at this
point, no studies refute this,'' said John DiStefano, science and
operations officer for the National Weather Service in Wilmington.
</P>
<P>
   However, because weather is affected by many variables, ``you
could end up with a season that has fewer tornadoes than average,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   While 1974, when the Xenia tornado struck, was a La Nina year,
so was 1989 when Ohio was hit by only two tornadoes with winds
averaging 113 mph or greater, he said.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, in 1965 - a year that was not affected by La Nina -
there were 18 significant tornadoes in the state, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a statistical study,'' DiStefano said. ``It's not a
prediction. It's not a forecast.''
</P>
<P>
   La Nina could produce more tornadoes because it pushes the
subtropical jet stream north, bringing warm and moist air with it.
That change can provide the necessary threshold of heat and
moisture to build severe thunderstorms, said Zurn-Birkhimer, one of
the authors of the study.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the findings, no extra emergency precautions are being
undertaken, said Ed Kovar, executive director of the Miami Valley
Emergency Management Authority.
</P>
<P>
   As March ushers in Ohio's peak season for tornadoes, Kovar
advises residents stay tuned to radio and television for severe
weather warnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many people feel if they don't have a siren, they can't
hear a warning,'' Kovar said. ``But a radio or TV is just as good
as a siren.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the city of Dayton's proposed plan to deactivate its
emergency warning siren will leave a void in the system, ``it's not
as catastrophic as people think,'' Kovar said. ``A siren system is
an outdoor warning system. It's not meant to warn people indoors.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Hundley writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
