<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-GUATEMALA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US PASSIVITY DURING GUATEMALAN DIRTY WAR HIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The head of a UN-supported commission probing
Guatemala's dirty war blasted the United States Monday for training
the Central American country's forces in the arts of terror and
then turning a blind eye as it conducted a genocidal campaign
against the indigenous population.
</P>
<P>
   But Christian Tomuschat, a German professor of international law
who headed the three-member Historical Clarification Commission on
Guatemala, praised the Clinton Administration for declassifying
more than 1,000 secret documents that helped the panel do its work,
and for providing more than $1.5 million in financing for the
investigation. The commission was created by agreement between the
Guatemalan government and rebel groups in December 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not wish to say that the US government bears direct
responsibility for any act of genocide,'' said Tomuschat at a press
conference. But ``the United States knew perfectly well what was
going on. It raised no objection and it continued its support for
the Guatemalan army.''
</P>
<P>
   UN officials and human rights advocates say the 3,600-page
report released last week, based on 9,000 interviews and a trove of
US intelligence cables, represents the most thorough account of the
excesses of the Guatemalan military during its 30-year war against
Cuban-backed rebels.
</P>
<P>
   It found that the United States agencies knew far more about
atrocities committed by the Guatemalan army and its notorious death
squads than the US has publicly acknowledged. According to the
report, government forces were responsible for 93 percent of the
200,000 Guatemalans killed during the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``This the authoritative truth about what happened in
Guatemala,'' said Alvaro de Soto, a senior adviser to UN Secretary
General Kofi Annan, in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Senior UN officials said that courts inside or outside Guatemala
are now free to prosecute the military leaders who oversaw the most
brutal phase of the civil war _ including General Romeo Lucas
Garcia and General Rios Montt _ for the crime of genocide.
Tomuschat added that a national amnesty, established as part of the
country's UN-brokered peace process, does not shield the military
from answering for their alleged crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Tomuschat said in an interview that an intelligence cable
released by the United States documented the role of the Central
Intelligence Agency in helping the Guatemalan police plan the 1996
kidnapping of 28 leaders of the Communist party.
</P>
<P>
   The leftist politicians were never seen again.
</P>
<P>
   The report also charged a subsidiary of Coca-Cola Co. with
mounting a bloody campaign that led to the death of dozens of trade
unionists in the 1970s. Tomuschat said labor leaders at the
Coca-Cola factory in Guatemala were routinely kidnapped and killed
to crush a budding labor movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years the Coca-Cola subsidiary in Guatemala pursued
mercilessly the trade union movement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The administration of President Jimmy Carter severed links with
the Guatemalan government in 1977, but the report suggests that US
intelligence agencies maintained cordial ties with the Guatemalans,
providing them with intelligence on the bloody counterinsurgency
campaigns in the Guatemalan highlands.
</P>
<P>
   In one cable, the CIA described a Guatemalan army campaign in
the Ixil Triangle, an indigenous region in northwestern Guatemala.
At the time, US officials were officially barred from dealing with
the Guatemalan army, according to a senior US official.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commanding officers of the units involved have been
instructed to destroy all town and villages which are cooperating
with the guerrilla army of the poor and eliminate all sources of
resistance,'' the CIA cable stated. ``The army can be expected to
give no quarter to combatants and noncombatants alike.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite long-standing American support for successive military
governments, the Guatemalans didn't always view the United States
as their friend. When the United States raised concerns about
Guatemala's human rights record in 1993, the generals' apparent
response was chilling.
</P>
<P>
   A senior US official in Guatemala reported his suspicion that a
unit under the command of the presidential chief of staff, Col.
Juan Jose Marroquin, was responsible for killing several local
employees of the US Agency for Development in retaliation for the
US criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only last week,'' recalled a State Department Bureau of
Intelligence and Research report dated Nov. 21, 1983, ``three USAID
Guatemalan contractors were murdered, possibly as an example to the
US not to meddle in human rights issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The release of the report came days before President Clinton's
March 8 visit to Guatemala, but White House national security
spokesman David Leavy said he didn't expect the issue to come up
during the first presidential trip to Guatemala since Lyndon
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   He said the president's message was designed to bolster the
peace process, promote human rights, fight drug trafficking and
foster democratic institutions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have acknowledged previously that several Guatemalan
individuals with whom the CIA was associated carried out serious
human rights violations,'' said Leavy. ``And we have taken a series
of measures to ensure human rights in future intelligence
activities.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Security Archive, a Washington organization that
helped the commission obtain the classified documents, gave the
Clinton Administration high marks for cooperation. However, it
faulted the Pentagon for failing to provide any useful information
on Guatemala's human rights record.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
