<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3666 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-MARKETPLACE-ART-     03-01 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: COCA COLA HITS A ROUGH PATCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a speech in Chicago last week, the chairman and
chief executive of Coca-Cola Co. made references to several popular
films of different eras, including ``Being There'' and ``From Here
to Eternity,'' when describing his company's experience overseas.
</P>
<P>
   He left out ``Suddenly, Last Summer.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when Coca-Cola, long the paragon of American
consumer-products companies, began to feel the effects of a global
battering that is without recent parallel. Sales volumes have
fallen in many countries, profits are flat or falling, and the
company is trying to manage its way through more simultaneous
crises abroad than at any time since the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Brazil teetering on the edge and threatening to take
Mexico and the rest of Latin America with it, Coca-Cola's damage
control has moved into high gear.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning, Coke's chairman and chief executive, M. Douglas
Ivester is scheduled to make a rare appearance at a conference
hosted by Merrill Lynch for dozens of portfolio managers, who hold
the keys to billions of dollars in investment funds. Such
appearances are usually delegated to others, like the company's
chief financial officer, James Chestnut.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester, a 20-year company veteran and a principal mechanic
behind the Coke machine, is expected to try to reassure investors
at the Manhattan conference that the long-term outlook for his
company remains positive. After his scheduled remarks, he will
answer questions from those attending the ``by invitation only''
event.
</P>
<P>
   His message may be a tough sell. Even though stock analysts
acknowledge the organizational strength of Coke, they say most
investors are looking for more short-term security than the company
can provide. Last week, several Wall Street analysts reduced their
1999 earnings forecast for Coca-Cola to about $1.45 a share, down
sharply from the $1.95 estimate many had made before the company's
fortunes began to slide in August. It is also about the same as
what the company earned last year.
</P>
<P>
   The stock price, which is down nearly 5 percent for the year,
fell 25 cents Monday, to close at $63.625. It is off sharply from
its July high of $88. Ivester, whose normal travel schedule borders
on the frenetic, has been spending an unusual amount of time making
the company's case to his business peers. Last Thursday, during an
address to the Economic Club of Chicago, he spoke enthusiastically
about Coke's prospects. ``I have to chuckle sometimes when I read
that some analyst is fretting about our `global exposure,'''
Ivester told the group in his measured Georgia twang. ``I hate to
tell them, but that's the idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Capitalism, he went on to say in a speech that included various
movie analogies, ``doesn't usually begin with steel mills or
automobile plants. It begins with consumer goods. Even in
developing countries, many people can afford a Coca-Cola.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts beg to differ, especially when it comes to Brazil,
Coke's No. 3 market in case volume. ``Brazil is definitely a
challenge for them in 1999,'' said Jennifer Solomon, a beverage
analyst for Salomon Smith Barney, who is one of the few voices
urging people to invest in Coke now (her rationale is that the time
to buy Coke stock is when the company hits a rough patch). ``And
they didn't have a great 1998.'' Many analysts expect volume in
Brazil to fall five to 10 percent this year, particularly as people
feel they don't have the disposable income to shell out for pricey
American soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Because the currency has plummeted in value, even spectacular
growth in Brazil would be diminished on the balance sheet. Bill
Pecoriello, a stock analyst for Sanford Bernstein, predicts that
the real's downturn will reduce Coke's earnings more than the 6
percent he had originally forecast, given the rest of the global
risk facing the company. The company reported that currency
devaluation worldwide reduced earnings by 9 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Pecoriello expects case volume in Brazil to fall 13
percent this quarter, far worse than the 3 percent decline in the
fourth quarter of last year. Global volume will grow by 4 to 5
percent, he predicts, down from the 6 percent growth recorded last
year and well off the 7 to 8 percent growth target of Coca-Cola's
management.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Coke doesn't adjust marketing spending for the volume
shortfall, margins should come under additional pressure,''
Pecoriello wrote in a note to investors last week, referring to the
company's worldwide operations. He rates Coca-Cola stock as
``market perform,'' while Coke's chief rival, Pepsico, is rated
``outperform,'' the highest ranking. And while he predicts that
Coke's earnings for this year will come in at $1.46, he cautions:
``There's still risk in our numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Another analyst, Marc Cohen of Goldman, Sachs, said Brazil is
one symptom of what may be a very large problem for Coca-Cola.
``I'm growing increasingly concerned that the growth rate of the
company is slowing,'' he said, citing compound EPS growth of just
under 13 percent for the 1990s _ not the 15 percent the company has
repeatedly promised.
</P>
<P>
   In Colombia and Venezuela, volume is also in a downward spiral,
off more than 16 percent in the fourth quarter. And Colombia shows
signs of a shrinking demand for soft drinks overall, said Laura D.
Meizler, a Latin American beverage analyst for Salomon Smith
Barney. ``Substitute products have been growing,'' she said, noting
that malt drinks are among them.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for shareholders is that a personal appearance by
Ivester tends to have a soothing effect on the skeptical, who find
comfort in his command of the business and his breadth of
experience. ``One of the virtues of a 113-year-old company is that
we've traveled over bumpy roads before,'' Ivester declared in
Chicago. ``We have seen the movie before.''
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that around the world _ in Japan, Russia,
Germany, Colombia, Venezuela, South Africa, Brazil, to list just
the big box-office names _ the epic is only in the first reel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-99 2001EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990301.0362 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3667 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-REDS-CAMERON-COX     03-01 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-CAMERON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cameron shows promise
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ Mike Cameron swung at the first pitch thrown in
an intrasquad game Monday afternoon and grounded out.
</P>
<P>
   Bad, very bad.
</P>
<P>
   His next time, he doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Good.
</P>
<P>
   His third time he pushed a letter-perfect bunt past the
pitcher's mound and beat it for a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Good, very good.
</P>
<P>
   The affair was an intrasquad game involving the Cincinnati Reds
in Ed Smith Stadium on a postcard-type day witnessed by 900 fans.
</P>
<P>
   The game lasted eight innings, with a team managed by Dave
Collins playing a team managed by Donnie Scott to a 4-4 tie.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron, who is working often with Collins on The Art of Leading
Off , bunting, baserunning and outfield play, heard an earful from
Collins after swinging at Brett Tomko's first pitch of the game and
grounding out.
</P>
<P>
   Said Collins, ``I told him, 'Kid, that's a breath of fresh air
for their pitcher _ one pitch, one out. Nobody on our team knows
what he is throwing or how he is throwing. As a leadoff hitter, a
lot of times you have to take the count to two strikes. If you
don't do it, you'll find yourself hitting eighth.'''
</P>
<P>
   Collins knows. He was a leadoff hitter. He had superior speed.
He was a bunter. He was an outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron put himself back in good graces with his base-hit bunt
his third time up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has wheels, he has to use them,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jack McKeon, an observer for both teams, was pleased
with Cameron's bunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that was great and he has to try that at least once
a game,'' McKeon said. ``We knew when we got him he was quick and
he has to use it in games. On AstroTurf all he has to do is push it
past the pitcher and they aren't going to throw him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Cameron realizes he has to be more patient if he wants to beat
out Pokey Reese for the leadoff spot. It's something on which he
has to concentrate, ``Because I'm naturally aggressive and don't
want to be too passive. I plan to bunt according to the situation.
That one was a perfect time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Collins team trailed, 4-0, in the fifth, but Stan Belinda
gave up a two-run home run to Phil Hiatt. With the Scott team on
its heels, Cameron bunted for the hit. Then he tried to steal
second, but was thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was safe,'' he said. ``We'd just scored two runs and I
wanted to bunt and steal to keep things going.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an aggressive afternoon and McKeon was pleased. . .until
a baseball writer from Milwaukee walked into his office after the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't tell Phil Garner (Milwaukee's manager) that we're going
to turn our guys loose on the bases,'' McKeon said. ``We have some
runners this year. . .and we haven't turned Barry Larkin and Pokey
Reese loose yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The two teams Monday tried seven stolen bases with three
successes _ two by Chris Stynes and one by Mark Sweeney.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to be aggressive this year and turn 'em loose on
the basepaths,'' McKeon said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Hiatt's home run from the Collins team, catcher
Jayhawk Owens hit a two-run homer in the sixth that tied the game.
Cameron had two hits and Hal Morris had two hits.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Branson, Mark Lewis, Jason Hardkte and Rod McCall each had
two hits for Scott's team. Cameron, Aaron Boone, Sean Casey and
Dmitri Young were the only regulars who played, but Larkin, Reese,
Greg Vaughn and Eddie Taubensee are scheduled to play today's
intrasquad game.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Bere, who started for Collins, gave up three runs and five
hits in two innings, but two runs were unearned. Tomko, starting
for Scott, gave up no runs and one hit in two innings.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
