<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE LEADER TESTS PLAN TO CURTAIL SOCIAL PROMOTION IN TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A Senate plan to curtail social promotions of
failing students underwent a tough test of its own Monday from a
House education leader who says it should also require mandatory
kindergarten with a hefty $500 million price tag.
</P>
<P>
   A major overhaul, envisioned by state Rep. Paul Sadler,
D-Henderson, would radically alter the social promotions bill that
sailed through the Texas Senate last month and is key to Gov.
George W. Bush's legislative agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler, chairman of the House Public Education Committee that
grilled backers from the governor's office about the plan Monday,
plans to sponsor the bill in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Key for Sadler is that the Senate bill, which targets
kindergartners with reading problems for early intervention and
remedial help, leaves out 30,000 Texas children not enrolled in
kindergarten. Under Texas law kindergarten attendance is not
mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dealing with the lives of very small children. It just
seems to me we should take some time and think through this very,
very carefully,'' Sadler told two Bush aides testifying in favor of
the Senate bill.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler said many of the 30,000 Texas children who don't attend
kindergarten each year are likely among those who can't pass the
state's standardized test by grade three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we even know who these 30,000 kids are?'' Sadler asked,
wondering whether they are rural or urban, minority or economically
disadvantaged. ``How can we fashion a solution to the problem if we
don't know who the kids are? That's what has troubled me from the
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office, meanwhile, called Sadler's proposed
kindergarten initiative costly and said it should not be tacked on
as a condition of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe the social promotion bill should be a stand-alone
bill,'' Bush said at a Monday press conference. ``I do believe the
social promotion bill that came out of the Senate is a good strong
piece of legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadler would increase the price tag of the proposal from $203
million _ slated for extra remedial classes and teacher training _
by adding another $500 million to pay for 30,000 more
kindergartners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a $5.3 billion surplus. What difference does it make
_ if this is really the number one educational priority of our
state _ what difference does it make if it costs $200 million as
you've outlined or it costs $450 million?'' he said at the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Under Senate Bill 1, sponsored by state Sen. Teel Bivins,
R-Amarillo, mastery of grade-level academic skills are required by
third, fifth and eighth grades before a child is promoted to the
next level.
</P>
<P>
   It designates $203 million for teacher training and remedial
classes to help young children with learning difficulties. Help
would continue in the early school years in the hopes that fewer
children would fail the Texas Assessment of Academic Skills by
third grade. A child who still failed the test after three chances
would be subject to repeating third grade.
</P>
<P>
   Last week groups representing Hispanics and African Americans
argued that plan would discriminate against minority students.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Harold Dutton, D-Houston, was skeptical about low-income
parents' ability to participate in a grade placement committee
called for in the Senate bill. That provision would allow a
unanimous ruling of a parent, teacher and principal to promote a
child even after three failing grades on the TAAS test.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some cases, you might have to chose from checking on how
Johnny is doing in school or your job,'' Dutton said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Scott Hochberg, D-Houston, raised statistics he said have
shown children's TAAS tests improving over time even though they
might have failed in the earlier grades.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler said while 42,000 Texas students failed the third-grade
TAAS test in 1997, the failures dropped sharply to 32,000 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 10,000 student drop in a year's time is very significant. If
we continue at that rate, before this bill even goes into place,
we've eliminated the social promotion problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
