<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELPHI-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delphi reaches out to non-GM companies
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Delphi Automotive Systems on Monday made its first
public appearance since becoming an independent company last month
and let the world know that its prepared to do business with any
automaker, not just General Motors Corp.
</P>
<P>
   J.T. Battenberg III, Delphi's chairman and chief executive, said
the world's largest maker of auto parts is increasing its non-GM
business by 10 percent each year and expects that rate to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't work for General Motors any more. I resigned from that
company,'' said Battenberg at the Society of Automotive Engineers
International Congress in the downtown's Cobo Hall. ``We currently
do business with all the world's major manufacturers.''
</P>
<P>
   GM easily remains Delphi's largest customer, but Battenberg's
presentation to the international media was littered with
references to Delphi's business deals with GM's chief rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Those deals range from Delphi making sliding doors for 1999 Ford
and Toyota mini-vans to supplying advanced climate control
technology systems for DaimlerChrysler's Jeep Grand Cherokee.
Battenberg also cited major contracts that Delphi has received from
other major automakers, including a $550 million deal with Navistar
International and other truck makers to supply modular doors for
the North American and European truck market.
</P>
<P>
   Delphi and its automotive technology are accustomed to taking
center stage at SAE, but it was obvious that this year's
presentation focused on showing its employees and competitors that
it will survive without GM.
</P>
<P>
   ``Improving our operating performance through technology, or any
other means, obviously hinges on employee and union involvement,''
Battenberg said. ``To date, our unions have been very supportive.''
</P>
<P>
   Delphi employs 15,000 people at seven plants in the Miami
Valley, more than any other metropolitan area in the U.S. The
plants, make everything from engine mounts to brakes, and overall,
are in better financial standing that at any time in the past
several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Dayton-area plants have some key (labor) agreements in
place and by staying competitive the have a chance to produce much
of the technology seen here,'' said Guy Hachey, president of
Delphi's chassis division, which is headquartered in Kettering.
</P>
<P>
   The spinoff left Delphi, which generated $28.5 billion in
revenue last year, as the world's 25th largest company and
transformed the Dayton area from a GM to a Delphi stronghold.
Delphi, headquartered in Troy, Mich., has 200,000 employees and
operates 169 plants worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Since the spinoff, Delphi's stock has remained flat, hovering
around $18 per share. But Battenberg was quick to defend the
stock's performance on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   At a social event on the eve of SAE, Battenberg presented a
chart that showed Delphi's stock has outperformed any other
automotive supplier and the S&AMP;P 500 since the spinoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have held our own in what's been a down period for the
industry,'' Battenberg said
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The DAYTON NEWSPAPERS INC., DAYTON, OHIO
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-03-01-99 1848E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
