<P>
   DOCTORS-UNION (Washington) _ Leaders of organized labor announce
a $1 million drive to unionize the roughly 300,000 doctors employed
by health maintenance organizations and hospitals. John Sweeney,
president of the AFL-CIO, says salaried doctors need unions because
the ``upheaval in the health care industry is affecting their
work.'' By DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-JOBBIAS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court examines whether
people who win job-discrimination lawsuits need to prove that their
employer's conduct was ``egregious'' in order to collect damages
beyond any loss of pay. By MARK HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-TEXAS (Washington) _ Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas,
and Texas county judges talk about the need to keep federal hands
off the state's tobacco settlement money. By GREG McDONALD.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-PRESIDENCY (Austin, Texas) _ Gov. George W. Bush is
expected to announce Tuesday he will form an exploratory committee
to raise money for a potential presidential campaign. By R.G.
RATCLIFFE. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   PRISONS-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ Judge William Wayne Justice will
announce whether he will retain his oversight of the Texas prison
system or return control to the state. The state has argued that
conditions have improved dramatically, but lawyers for inmates says
problems with health care and brutality continue. By JOHN GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   PRISONS-RUIZ (Huntsville, Texas) _ David Ruiz, the inmate whose
name is synonymous with prison reform in Texas, has lived the past
11 years locked alone in a tiny cell 23 hours per day. It has
afforded him plenty of time to reflect on conditions behind bars _
conditions he played a key role in changing with the 30-page,
handwritten lawsuit he filed in 1972. By KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   CEMETERY-HISPANIC (Tynan, Texas) _ The fence that briefly
separated the burial markers bearing German and Hispanic names is
removed, restoring harmony to a rural area following the ethnic
tension and threats of a civil rights lawsuit that grew from the
chain-lick border. By JOHN MacCORMACK. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ A push to end promotions for
failing schoolchildren is facing a major overhaul in the Texas
House, where education leaders are calling for mandatory
kindergarten. The legislation, which seeks to make students pass an
exit test before moving ahead at certain grade levels, sailed
through the Senate. By POLLY ROSS HUGHES. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   OPEN-RECORDS-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ A House committee will
consider a bill repealing a measure passed two years ago that made
it possible for minority contractors to keep their financial
information secret. The panel also will consider a bill that would
require governmental entities to record their executive sessions.
By JULIE MASON. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL-BUSINESS NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BANKRUPTCY-FILINGS (Washington) _ The rise in bankruptcy filings
slowed last year, according to new government figures. The number
increased 2.7 percent, far lower than the 19.1 percent hike in
1997. The report coincides with attempts by some lawmakers to enact
legislation that would make it harder for people to eliminate all
their debts in Bankruptcy Court. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ In December, economists were saying
that the economy was going to slow in 1999. Bond investors liked
that news because a fast-growing economy can lead to inflation,
which erodes the value of long-term bonds. But lately, bond fans
have had a jolt. U.S. Treasuries in February suffered their biggest
monthly losses since 1980. By PAMELA YIP. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ There is a growing sense in the
Republican Party of the inevitability of Gov. George W. Bush's
presidential nomination, even though he has yet to campaign outside
Texas. Wait a minute. Remember President Edmund Muskie? President
George Romney? President Edward Kennedy? It's not over yet. By
MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ A committee appointed by the
Texas Supreme Court has proposed that judges be required to recuse
themselves from cases involving people who gave them illegal
campaign contributions. The mere fact that such a requirement isn't
already law speaks volumes about the potential for abuse inherent
in Texas' elected judicial system. By CLAY ROBISON. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Houston)_ Charles Barkley and Antoine Carr are
back. The Houston Rockets are counting the days until the return of
Rodrick Rhodes and Stanely Roberts. In the meantime, they return
home after another deflating loss to face another of the NBA's most
disappointing teams, the San Antonio Spurs, on Tuesday night. By
JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-SPURS (San Antonio) _ Expected to be among the elite teams
in the NBA this season, the San Antonio Spurs instead have emerged
as the biggest disappointment in the league with a 6-8 record.
David Robinson looks lost, Tim Duncan is suffering through a
sophomore jinx, and Avery Johnson has been out of sync all season.
By MICHAEL MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-HAMPTON (Kissimmee, Fla.) _ If Mike Hampton could put the
second half of his 1997 season together with the first half of
1998, he would be a 20-game winner. Yet Hampton hasn't been able to
put a full season of success together for the Houston Astros.
Hampton now believes the inconsistency is in his past, and that he
is primed for a breakthrough season. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
