A3674 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLENN-LEWIS-COX     03-01 0321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-LEWIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glenn honored in Ohio
 &HT;    By Tom Beyerlein
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The man who conquered the vast nothingness of space has now
conquered Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   NASA on Monday officially changed the name of the Lewis Research
Center in Cleveland to the John H. Glenn Research Center at Lewis
Field. A formal dedication ceremony is tentatively set for May 14.
</P>
<P>
   The seeds of the name change were planted by U.S. Sen. Mike
DeWine, R-Ohio, whose suggestion for honoring the first American to
orbit the Earth was approved by the Senate in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sen. DeWine felt it was certainly an appropriate and fitting
tribute to Sen. Glenn to name the NASA facility in the state of
Ohio for him,'' DeWine spokesman Charles Boesel said. He said the
change will ``recognize his achievements not only in space but on
Earth, too.''
</P>
<P>
   John Hairston, director of external programs at the research
center, said the name change underscores the center's hybrid nature
as a space and aeronautics site. ``It's a plus for us because it
gives us the visibility as a hybrid center,'' he said. ``This is a
great thing for northeast Ohio and for the NASA center.''
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1941, the center was named in 1948 for the late George
William Lewis, research director for the National Advisory
Committee for Aeronautics. Boesel said the name change was designed
to preserve the honor to Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of 10 NASA centers in the nation and focuses on
aeronautical propulsion, space propulsion, space power, satellite
communications and microgravity sciences in combustion and fluid
physics. The center uses 2,100 civil service employees and 1,500
contractors at the 24 major research labs on its 350-acre Cleveland
site and a 6,400-acre site in Sandusky.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Beyerlein writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
