<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3680 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRIGHTFLYER-TEST-COX     03-01 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHTFLYER-TEST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wright Flyer to get test
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNNYVALE, Calif. _ The wind tunnel where aeronautical
researchers are preparing to test a replica of the Wright Flyer is
like a gigantic cave.
</P>
<P>
   Walking through a large doorway into the test chamber, you feel
a cold wind blowing out of the tunnel. Once you're inside, the air
feels calm but cold. The wide floor curves upwards on each side to
form walls that arch high overhead. The room is 80 feet wide and 40
feet high, but special acoustical paneling makes it eerily silent.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the floor sits a wood and fabric wonder, a
close copy of the kite-like airplane the Wright brothers flew at
Kitty Hawk, N.C. on Dec. 17, 1903. Working around it is a small
group of volunteers, most of them dressed in blue jumpsuits adorned
with patches that say ``Wright Flyer Project.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting today, the group hopes to power up the giant wind
tunnel and start gathering scientific data that will tell them just
how well _ or poorly _ the Wright brothers' invention flew.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been looking forward to this for 20 years,'' said
project member Bud Chamberlain, a retired aeronautical researcher
who flew B-24 bombers in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The wind tunnel is a part of NASA's National Full-Scale
Aerodynamics Complex at the Ames Research Center here on Moffett
Field. It's the world's biggest wind tunnel facility. NASA is
cooperating with the Wright Flyer Project, which is an activity of
the Los Angeles chapter of the American Institute of Aeronautics
and Astronautics, an association of professional aeronautical and
aerospace researchers.
</P>
<P>
   The group had hoped to start testing Monday, but last-minute
adjustments required the flyer to be removed from its delicate
perch on the wind tunnel's pedestal-like ``sting,'' which supports
it and measures forces during the tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's going to be (re)mounting and checking out and getting
everything ready,'' NASA facility manager Pete Zell said.
</P>
<P>
   The tunnel was not running Monday, but its huge chambers were
open to the outside air, and natural atmospheric movements around
the complex caused breezes to flow through it, Zell said. The
enormous steel structure of the complex chills during the night,
making the air inside cold ``like an underground cellar,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Wright Flyer Project started when another Wright Flyer
replica built by the AIAA chapter perished in a fire in 1978. The
chapter decided to build a new replica and fly it at Kitty Hawk in
2003, the 100th anniversary of the Wright brothers' first powered
flights.
</P>
<P>
   Project members say the Wrights themselves knew their 1903 flyer
was not a stable flying machine. This model was built to find out
just how the original flyer handled. The data project members
gather from it will help them build another machine that visually
resembles the original machine, but with just enough changes to
make it safe to fly.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Grimm, a retired wind tunnel researcher who is a member of
the project team, said the flyer is unlike anything the NASA
researchers are used to seeing in their immense tunnel, which has
been used to test full-size models of fighter jets and other
aircraft at up to nearly half the speed of sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're used to working with metal airplanes, and here they
are with this fabric and wire thing,'' he laughed.
</P>
<P>
   The test itself is a simple task, Zell said, but mounting the
flyer is tricky. The flyer has a wingspan of about 40 feet and
weighs about 1,000 pounds, but it rests on a four-inch balance
about six feet above the tunnel floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of fun from the standpoint that it's so unique,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy R. Gaffney writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
