<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3681 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEACECORPS-TAFT-COX     03-01 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEACECORPS-TAFT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Peace Corps observances honor volunteerism
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Today's celebration of Peace Corps Day in Ohio
and across the rest of the country has personal meaning for Gov.
Bob Taft, who served as a volunteer in Tanzania in East Africa from
1963 to 1965 and is the first former volunteer to serve as a state
governor.
</P>
<P>
   Former Ohio Gov. Richard F. Celeste served as Peace Corps
director but was not a volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those opportunities that gives back far more to us
than we give to other people,'' said Taft.
</P>
<P>
   Taft will celebrate in Peace Corps fashion by reading to
students at Avalon Elementary School in Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing his favorite volunteering, which is reading to
kids,'' said Mary Anne Sharkey, Taft's communications director.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, nearly 10,000 current and former volunteers today
are scheduled to discuss their overseas experiences in classes
across the country to commemorate the Peace Corps' 38th
anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   More than 150,000 volunteers have served in 132 countries since
the Peace Corps began. Ohio, with 6,462 present and former
volunteers, ranks sixth among the states.
</P>
<P>
   Taft had lots more than reading and discussing to do as a
teacher in the Tanzanian town of Missungwi. He and another Peace
Corps volunteer and four Tanzania teachers ran a boarding school
for 200 seventh and eighth graders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I taught English, math, geography, art and coached the girl's
basketball team,'' said Taft. ``We took turns kind of being in
charge of the school.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no electricity or running water in the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had gas lamps, pressure lamps,'' recalled Taft, who had a
papaya tree in his front yard.
</P>
<P>
   Taft, who came to Tanzania after graduating from Yale, learned
to speak Swahili and also played goalie on a local soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't very good,'' Taft said.
</P>
<P>
   He also made friendships with the students that have continued
to this day. Taft still recalls Salvis Shiponya, one of the
school's brightest students, who invited Taft to his home for an
overnight visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out to visit and it was a little circle of huts,'' Taft
said. ``They had one bed in the place. They insisted that I take
the bed. They heated hot water for me.''
</P>
<P>
   As Taft prepared to leave, his hosts honored him with a valuable
present - a live chicken that Taft later would enjoy for a meal. In
planning for the trip, Taft had forgotten to consider the
hospitality he was likely to receive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really bring them a gift,'' said Taft. ``I had a
Swiss Army knife . . . I gave them my Swiss Army knife.''
</P>
<P>
   Taft rode his bicycle back to the school with the chicken on the
back in a cage, ``squawking all the way home.''
</P>
<P>
   As a college student at Yale in the early 1960s, Taft said he
was caught up in a ``very exciting time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a new president who was discussing volunteerism.'' Taft
said.
</P>
<P>
   That president was John F. Kennedy, a Democrat. Taft came from
one of the nation's most politically famous Republican families.
His great-grandfather William Howard Taft had been a Republican
president and chief justice of the U.S. Supreme Court. His
grandfather, Ohio Sen. Robert A. Taft, had been known as ``Mr.
Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Taft's father, Robert Taft Jr., had just been elected to the
U.S. House as a Republican when his son entered the Peace Corps and
later went on to serve in the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure my family was real delighted when I joined the
Peace Corps in 1963,'' said Taft. His father, however, ended up
going to Tanzania to visit his volunteer son.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great thing,'' said Taft.
</P>
<P>
   While the Peace Corps was inaugurated by a Democratic president,
it now is embraced by both parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is bipartisan,'' said Taft. ``I think it does
transcend politics.''
</P>
<P>
   While Taft is the first former volunteer to serve as a governor,
there are six former volunteers in Congress, including Dayton's
Tony Hall who served in Thailand. Hall is one of three Democrats.
The three others are Republicans. Donna Shalala, U.S. secretary of
health and human services, also served as a volunteer in Iran.
</P>
<P>
   It has been nearly 34 years since Taft, 57, ended his Peace
Corps service, but the memories remain fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think teaching, talking, being on my feet, trying to explain
things clearly to students who didn't know English that well, just
the opportunity to be of service, I think that was significant,''
said Taft.
</P>
<P>
   William Hershey writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
