<DOCNO> NYT19990301.0373 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3685 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRUCK-SAFETY-900&AMP;ADD-     03-01 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUCK-SAFETY-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGN OF LIGHT TRUCKS MAY CAUSE 2,000 EXTRA DEATHS A YEAR, STUDY
SUGGESTS
</HEADLINE>
  (fe) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The height and stiff frames of sport utility vehicles,
pickup trucks and vans are making them unusually deadly to people
in other vehicles on the nation's roadways and caused about 2,000
extra deaths in traffic accidents in 1996, federal regulators said
here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Releasing an extensive statistical study as well as the results
of crash tests, regulators said the design of these so-called light
trucks _ not just their weight, as auto makers have contended until
very recently _ posed dangers.
</P>
<P>
   The growing popularity of light trucks, which now account for
half of new vehicle sales, ``presents a growing safety problem that
needs to be addressed,'' said Thomas Hollowell, a senior researcher
at the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, at the
opening here on Monday of the annual convention of the Society of
Automotive Engineers, an industry trade association.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Martinez, the agency's administrator, did not attend the
convention but issued a statement here saying that ``today's
research highlights the fact that, regardless of weight, vehicle
design can play a major role in aggressivity.''
</P>
<P>
   Auto makers have said until recently that light trucks
inevitably cause more deaths in the vehicles they hit than cars do
because the light trucks weigh more, not because of their design.
Americans want to drive large vehicles, and big vehicles will
always outweigh smaller vehicles, the auto makers have said.
</P>
<P>
   But that attitude has begun to shift, and auto makers' safety
experts were far less critical of Monday's studies than they might
have been two years ago. ``I'm skeptical, but I need to go through
it,'' said Terrence E. Connelly, General Motors' North American
safety director, adding that ``there are factors that make trucks
less compatible with cars in a crash.''
</P>
<P>
   An aide to Connelly, Don Vander Lugt, presented a separate study
here concluding that at least when vehicles are struck in the side
by any vehicle, the stiffness, height, width and curvature of the
striking vehicle's front end were each more important than the
striking vehicle's weight. But GM officials continued to maintain
that weight was very important in frontal crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, regulators distributed the results of four
side-impact crash tests, their first effort to test what happens
when light trucks hit cars. They found that a Ford Explorer did the
most damage.
</P>
<P>
   In the test results released on Monday, a Chevrolet Lumina
midsized sedan, a Ford Explorer sport utility vehicle, a Chevrolet
S-10 pickup and a Dodge Caravan mini-van were each crashed at 35
miles an hour into the front, driver's-side corners of Honda Accord
sedans moving in nearly the opposite direction at the same speed.
</P>
<P>
   The Explorer again did the most damage while the Lumina did the
least, Hollowell said. The Explorer did more than three times as
much damage as the Lumina to the heads of the crash dummies in the
driver's seat of the Accord. The Explorer also did twice as much
harm to the chest and neck of these dummies, which were wearing
seat belts and were protected by air bags that deployed
successfully.
</P>
<P>
   Priya Prasad, Ford's top safety researcher, said the crash test
results were not grave. None of the crash dummies suffered injuries
from the light truck that are likely to be fatal, although some of
the dummies suffered potentially permanent leg injuries, he said.
Frontal collisions are less deadly than side-impact crashes.
</P>
<P>
   A videotape of the test also showed that the Explorer nearly
rolled over after hitting the Accord, teetering on two wheels for a
moment before coming down on all four wheels. Sport utility
vehicles roll over nearly four times as often as cars, according to
another study released here; spinal injuries from traffic accidents
usually occur because a vehicle has rolled over. Ford officials
said they would have to study the videotape before commenting.
</P>
<P>
   At a safety conference last summer Martinez alluded to the
possibility that light trucks were causing as many as 2,000 extra
deaths a year but did not discuss the relative roles of weight and
design. The death toll was confirmed for the agency by a
statistical study of traffic deaths in 1996 conducted by Hans
Joksch, a safety expert at the University of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The study looked at how many car occupants would have survived
if they had been hit not by sport utility vehicles, pickups or vans
but by cars that weighed as much as the light trucks that struck
them. The 2,000 extra deaths represent 5 percent of the 40,000
Americans who die annually in highway traffic accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Prasad estimated last April, using methods similar to Joksch's,
that there were 1,000 extra deaths a year.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, Ford took the first step in addressing the design
mismatches criticized by regulators. The company said its next
sport utility vehicle, which will be the world's largest, will have
hollow steel bars below the front and rear bumpers that are
designed to prevent the big vehicle from riding over cars in
collisions.
</P>
<P>
   Hollowell said on Monday that while regulators had not tested
the device, it was ``a step in the right direction.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A separate paper on Monday, written by two private researchers
with a grant from Ford, found that occupants of sport utility
vehicles on average fare no better than car occupants in crashes.
But belted occupants of sport utilities do somewhat better in
crashes than car occupants, belted or otherwise, while unbelted
occupants of sport utilities fare the worst because they are likely
to be thrown through windows if their vehicles roll over.
</P>
<P>
   The crash test involving the Caravan produced a surprising
result that, regulators said, was unrelated to their research into
vehicle compatibility in traffic accidents. The Caravan's passenger
side air bag heavily damaged the crash dummy's neck and probably
would have killed a real passenger. The agency used a dummy that
simulated a short woman; air bags have been killing about 20 short
women and children a year, while saving hundreds of lives annually,
according to regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Gruber McLean, a spokeswoman for DaimlerChrysler AG,
which makes the Dodge Caravan, said the company was worried about
the test's outcome and wanted to see the details. Only Dodge,
Plymouth and Chrysler mini-vans from the 1996 and 1997 model years
use the air bag system involved in the crash test, Ms. McLean said.
She added that the company was outraged that safety regulators had
waited eight months after the test before releasing the results.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
