<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETS CLOSE MIXED AFTER UNUSUALLY LIGHT TRADING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fresh signs of strong economic growth preyed on the
bond market again Monday, pulling down stock prices early, but
major market gauges pared their declines and closed narrowly mixed
on unusually light volume.
</P>
<P>
   A stronger-than-expected gain in the index of manufacturing
compiled by the National Association of Purchasing Management led
to wholesale selling in the bond market. In its survey, the
association said its index during February climbed to 52.4, the
first time the index had risen above 50 since last May. A reading
above 50 indicates growth in manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 1 9/32, to
94 2/32. Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction from the
price, rose to 5.66 percent from 5.57 percent on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in yields pushed long-term rates back to levels
last seen in August, before Russia defaulted on its debt
obligations.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the themes everyone talked about earlier in the decade
was that the bond market helped to self-regulate the economy,''
said Lou Crandall, chief economist at R.H. Wrightson &AMP; Associates.
</P>
<P>
   ``That whole mechanism was ignored in the second half of last
year,'' he said. ``The bond market ignored the ongoing strength in
the U.S. economy, and that stimulated absolutely stratospheric
performance in interest-sensitive sectors of the economy, like
housing. Now bond yields have gone back to levels where mortgage
applications will slow.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the deterioration in bond prices, fears about the
high prices of technology shares caused problems for stocks early
in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Then, to the surprise of some, the market rallied and closed
little changed.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 18.20 points, or
two-tenths of a percent, to 9,324.78. Hurt by a pounding in Intel
shares, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 2.17 points, or
nearly two-tenths of a percent, to 1,236.16. But the Nasdaq
composite index managed to rise 7.15 points, or three-tenths of a
percent, to 2,295.18. And the Russell 2000 index of smaller-company
stocks gained 2.13 points, or five-tenths of a percent, to 394.39.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market was reminiscent of that old Timex watch
commercial,'' said William Meehan, chief market analyst at Cantor
Fitzgerald. ``It takes a licking but keeps on ticking.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Allyn, director of listed trading at Jeffries &AMP; Co., said,
``We are still in this push-pull, rip-tear environment, where the
market has violent swings but doesn't end up going very far.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Big Board, a relatively sparse 699.5 million shares
changed hands. On the Nasdaq market, where volume has routinely
approached 1 billion shares lately, just more than 771 million
shares were traded.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, trading activity tends to pick up at the start of a
new month as pension funds and other institutional investors put
fresh money into their stock portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   But given the uncertainties about market valuations and the
state of the economy, analysts said, it was not altogether
surprising the pace of business has slowed.
</P>
<P>
   The bond and stock markets will pay particular attention to
Friday's employment report from the Labor Department. ``Who wants
to make a big commitment in front of the employment numbers?''
Meehan asked.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts are expecting the report to show a rise in nonfarm
payroll employment of 250,000, but they are bracing for a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers have come in above consensus for the last three
months,'' Crandall said. ``There would be a certain amount of
relief if we got through the report with no nasty surprises.''
</P>
<P>
   Worries about slowing sales of personal computers, set off last
week by a report from Compaq Computer, continued Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, the biggest maker of computer chips, led the S&AMP;P 500
index lower, dropping 2~, to 117 1/16 after Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette cut its ratings on the stock. Compaq fell 2, to 33\. And
IBM lost 1], to 168].
</P>
<P>
   But financial stocks, which have never fully recovered from last
summer's sell-off, did well. So did companies whose performance is
tied to a strong economy.
</P>
<P>
   Among financial stocks, Citigroup gained 2{, to 61\; American
Express rose 3, to 111{, and Chase Manhattan was up 1[, to 80}.
</P>
<P>
   Caterpillar, the world's largest maker of construction
equipment, was the best-performing component of the Dow. It gained
3|, to 49 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors, the No. 1 auto maker, gained 9/16, to 83. And
Alcoa, the world's largest aluminum company, gained ~, to 41].
</P>
<P>
   Not all technology stocks suffered Monday. Microsoft rose 1|, to
151}; Cisco Systems gained 1|, to 99 7/16, and Lucent Technologies
rose 1 5/16, to 102~.
</P>
<P>
   Many big Internet stocks also did well. Yahoo gained 6|, to
160[, and Amazon.com rose 4~, to 133.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
