<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3689 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-UNINSURED-2TAKES-N     03-01 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-UNINSURED-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENIAL AND FEAR: LIFE WITHOUT HEALTH INSURANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif.)  (mk) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Peggy Parraga, a part-time massage therapist from
Queens, divides her life into two phases: the time when she and her
family had health insurance, and now, when they do not.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago, she had a baby at Our Lady of Mercy Medical
Center in the Bronx, which accepted her managed care plan, offered
good prenatal care and even served her and her husband a
celebratory champagne dinner. In 1996, pregnant again but
uninsured, she could afford only a clinic at Elmhurst Hospital
Center, and endured a chaotic and unpleasant delivery by a doctor
she had never met.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Parraga said she used to be good about checkups for her
family. Now, her husband, a draftsman whose employer stopped
offering insurance several years ago, has aches and pains that he
cannot afford to have checked. ``It has really made a big
difference in my life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   To live without health insurance is to linger between denial and
fear. It means ignoring the little pains and dealing with the
unmanageable ones in a frantic way. It is knocking wood for good
health while knowing that the worst medical calamities can show up
at the most inconvenient times.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the uninsured cobble together an approach of avoiding
care whenever possible, and when it is not possible, using hospital
emergency rooms or pay-as-you-can clinics. Some of them resort to
sharing medications with other family members, and others just live
with an aching cough they hope will go away. Some choose their
medical battles _ say an annual mammogram _ and pay upfront for
them; others dodge their bills and hope not to get caught.
</P>
<P>
   And many young, single and healthy people, even those with
reasonable incomes, simply take a calculated risk that they will
never need to see a doctor at all.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the uninsured are not the poorest of the
poor, who tend to be covered by Medicaid, the government health
insurance program for the indigent. Indeed, of the 43 million
Americans without health insurance, 75 percent work at least part
time, but are not offered insurance through an employer or cannot
afford their contribution. And their numbers are swelling, as the
price of insurance rises _ especially for small businesses _ and as
more people move from welfare to jobs where there are few benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is particularly acute in New York, where 19.1
percent of the state's residents under 65 _ or roughly 3 million _
are without health insurance, compared with a national average of
17.6 percent. Three-quarters of them work. (The rest tend to be
students, children and early retirees.) And the ranks of the
uninsured are growing faster in New York than in the nation as a
whole.
</P>
<P>
   In part, this is because New York has a large working population
of illegal immigrants, and a plethora of small entreprenurial
companies, like those in the new electronic media, that are too new
and unstable to offer benefits. Further, New York is home to a
disproportionate number of people who toil in the visual and
performance arts, many of whom put together a living with part-time
or free-lance work without benefits. The state has about 1.5
million part-time workers, second only to California, according to
the federal Bureau of Labor Statistics. For many of the uninsured,
individual coverage can be prohibitively expensive, or too meager
to be worth the cost. Those costs vary wildly: $100 a month for
no-frills coverage to $400 a month and up for extensive benefits
similar to an employer's package.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am wary of the monthly expense,'' said David Wickland, who
works four days a week as an office temp and paints the rest of the
week in his Brooklyn studio. ``Anything that I could afford would
basically be for just the most minimal ambulatory care. At $100 a
month, I am unable to justify it. I don't go to doctors when there
is an option not to go.''
</P>
<P>
   For the occasional emergency, going without coverage can work.
Wickland, who earns roughly $33,000 a year, fell off a ladder
recently and fractured his femur. He called several clinics until
he was referred to the public Gouverneur Skilled Nursing Facility,
Diagnostic and Treatment Center, where a long wait and confusing
maze of transfers and paperwork finally resulted in care.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really chaotic,'' he said. ``People speaking several
languages were running everywhere; it was very mixed up. I had to
wait a couple hours in this waiting room, and it was strange to see
that people were in a lot of pain waiting for hours.''
</P>
<P>
   For $80 and a card that would allow him to come back for a
checkup, he considered himself a satisfied customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized that if something like that came up I would have
some place to go, and I was relieved it was available,'' he said.
``But it also made me leery about going on without health
insurance. There are certain things like teeth care, or a mole that
should be looked at, and I just can't go.''
</P>
<P>
   For people with complicated or chronic health problems, this
strategy often fails.
</P>
<P>
   Thai Brooks at first blush seems to be the perfect candidate for
scraping by without insurance. She is 27, lives with her mother in
Harlem and works 35 hours a week with disabled people, netting
about $1,200 a month. Checkups and annual dental appointments are
within her financial reach, and she is happy that she no longer has
to rely on Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   But her health problems are daunting: She has severe asthma, a
defective heart valve, a chronic gastrointestinal disorder and
anemia.
</P>
<P>
   Under Medicaid, she would go to a medical office at Mount Sinai
Medical Center in Manhattan for most of her ailments and for dental
care, and she took advantage of the hospital's cardiac care center.
</P>
<P>
   But now, she must pay $74 per visit to Mount Sinai, a figure
computed from a stack of pay stubs she dragged to a recent visit.
Visiting the cardiac center is out of the question now, as are many
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   So she borrows asthma drugs from her mother and has taken to
swallowing over-the-counter antidotes for her intestinal problems.
(``It makes things bearable.'') She hit her head recently and had
to go to the emergency room. In trying to come up with $600 to pay
for it, she has ignored a phone bill. ``I like working,'' she said.
``But it is frustrating because I cannot afford to get sick.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Mental health problems, which need constant attention, get
perhaps the shortest shrift. Yolanda Bako, who is 52, has worked as
an off-track betting clerk for three years. She works 20 hours a
week and until just recently was not eligible for insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Her medical home is Jacobi Medical Center in the Bronx, a public
hospital 12 blocks from her cramped apartment. The hospital offers
a clinic with a sliding scale of fees, where she goes for
everything from a sore throat to urinary tract infections to
depression.
</P>
<P>
   But getting good care for the latter has been the most
problematic. She has taken 20 different antidepressants in the last
few years, she said, and when she goes to Jacobi's psychiatric
clinic, a different doctor sees her each time.
</P>
<P>
   When she told one of them she felt suicidal, she was told to go
to the hospital's in-patient unit, where she said she was kept for
eight days and emerged without a diagnosis or plan. ``I was the
closest thing to a rational person there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Total bill: $14,000, none of which she could pay. Her bank
account was impounded, and she has battled her way through hospital
administrators and courts to sort out a payment plan, which she
admits she has not always honored. ``This is supposed to be the
cheapest hospital around,'' she said. ``I didn't understand how it
could be so high.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone interviewed said that in a pinch, the emergency room is
the place to head for care. ``They scold me,'' said Mrs. Parraga,
who sometimes takes her children there when they have high fevers.
``But I just can't sit home with a sick baby.''
</P>
<P>
   City hospital emergency rooms do not just offer a poor choice
for those who seek to use them as doctors' offices; they are a
severe drain on the system. When there are wages to garnish, as in
the case of Ms. Bako, it can be done. But more often, care for the
uninsured is written off as bad debt.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Luis Marcos, president of Health and Hospitals Corp., which
runs the city's 11 public hospitals, regularly cites the uninsured
as the largest economic drain on his system. Of the city's
uninsured population, 71 percent seek care through his hospitals
and clinics.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a health care world that all the philosophers these days
want to make into a competitive marketplace, these are nonpaying
customers,'' said James Tallon Jr., president of United Hospital
Fund.
</P>
<P>
   New York Gov. George Pataki recently vetoed a bill that sought
to enrich Health and Hospital Corp.'s charity pools by $100
million, and he has said he is interested in earmarking only a
small portion of the tobacco settlement money for the uninsured. In
the meantime, those without insurance take services they are not
equipped to pay for.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Baldwin sheepishly admits he is part of the problem. At
43, he stitches together a living of about $30,000 a year with
writing and roofing. While repairing a roof last year, he got a bad
splinter that became infected. He has yet to pay the $150 bill for
a tetanus shot at a hospital in Yonkers, near his home. The bill
has been turned over to a collection agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to live like that,'' he said. ``But I am not
making a lot of money right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of preventative care is largely viewed as one of the
most serious medical issues affecting the poor. The stories are
well known among policy- makers, like the women who show up in the
emergency room with horrible coughs and are diagnosed with advanced
breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But there is evidence that even people who can afford insurance
and choose to forgo it are missing out on preventative care. Adam
Coti, who is 30, estimates that he makes around $65,000 a year
between his two jobs as a Web page designer and a free-lance
circulation consultant, depending on how much work he gets.
</P>
<P>
   He is tilting toward one of the fastest-growing groups of
uninsured Americans: Households with annual incomes of $75,000 or
more accounted for half the increase in the number of the uninsured
last year, according to the Census Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Cotti's logic works like this: He gets an ear infection each
winter, which costs him roughly $150 after a clinic visit and a
prescription. This is cheaper than the $250 in monthly premiums he
was offered for a very basic insurance plan.
</P>
<P>
   But his father died of colon cancer, which is often hereditary,
easily diagnosed and curable if caught early with the recommended
annual test. ``My mother reminds me that I need to spend up to
$1,000 for a general checkup,'' he said. ``I don't believe in
skimping on that. It has to be done. I want to make sure that `one
of these days' doesn't turn into next year.''
</P>
<P>
   His greatest fear is a catastrophe. ``I am not looking for the
best insurance in the world,'' Coti said. ``I'll take a huge
deductible. But one out-of-control cabdriver mad at his dispatcher
hits the pedal, and I am in trouble. I go bike riding, and there
are a couple of steep hills where I live, and I think to myself,
`You don't have insurance.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Pearlman has come up with an unusual solution to the
expense of health insurance: When it comes time to go the the
doctor, she simply leaves the country. Ms. Pearlman, who works as
an adjunct professor at Columbia University and does free-lance
computer work, has been uninsured since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, she was on a writers' retreat in Merida, in the
Yucatan region of Mexico, when she had a dental emergency. What she
found was so fantastic, she said, that she decided to go back. She
has had dental work that would have cost $2,000 at home for $200,
and blood tests for $10. She has received checkups and the like
each of the six times she returned there, and twice went there just
to get some minor surgery. The doctors are first rate, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to discovering other health care systems in
other countries,'' she said. ``Because I have no hope of availing
myself to the care system in America.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
