<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THIS SCANDAL HAS NO LIFE IN THE PUBS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before a single page of another special report on the
Lewinsky-long Olympic scandal was unveiled on Monday in New York,
one could hear Bud Greenspan editing it all out of his next
documentary film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the Games as a higher form of the human spirit,''
Greenspan said after dropping by a midtown hotel to hear more about
the Olympic lowlifes who demanded bribes and purchased votes. ``The
number of people engaged in illegality and immorality is small. I'd
rather spend my time with the 90 percent that's good.''
</P>
<P>
   Juan Antonio Samaranch and George Mitchell, the former Senate
majority leader, are apparently not on Greenspan's list. Problem or
solution. Corrupter or reformer. To the eclectic filmmaker, they
are all bureaucrats in blazers, politicians in suits, all belonging
on the cutting-room floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about the athletes, always about the athletes,''
Greenspan said. ``The Olympics are two weeks in never-never land.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind what they have been revealed to be the rest of the
year. Never mind that Mitchell, as chairman of a U.S. Olympic
Committee commission, claimed on Monday that the Olympic movement
has been ``gravely damaged'' in the wake of the Olympics-for-sale
turpitude. In the view through Greenspan's lens, the athletes will
train, the networks will come. From Sydney to Salt Lake, the Games
will go on.
</P>
<P>
   If Samaranch and his International Olympic Committee really
wanted to make a statement that would resonate for decades, they
would expel every delegate who took a bribe and take the 2002
Winter Games out of Salt Lake. That would cost plenty, though, and
as Mitchell said, the Olympics are ``big business,'' an incongruity
that shrinks in the company of its ancient and long-dead ideal. So
unless the underwriting sponsors get religion and make more than an
obligatory stink, the IOC will graciously accept all these ethics
reports, and unilaterally make its own rules. The
bureaucrats-in-blazers, as always, will be left with the
responsibility of policing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that people around the world are just as concerned
as we are,'' said Mitchell, when asked why other bidding countries
might consider his committee's recommendations to better control
future bidding. ``We do not believe that Americans have a monopoly
on morality.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in New York, we have recently been distracted from our
duties as moral monopolists, fitting a certain coach-choker into
the Knicks' championship puzzle. And while this Olympic mess has
undoubtedly been a gut-wrenching experience in Salt Lake City, I
have not detected much local outpouring of anxiety. As sports
scandals go, let's be honest, this one isn't playing in the pubs.
</P>
<P>
   This last assertion cannot be proved, or polled, but Christopher
Russo, the Mad Dog on WFAN, sports talk radio in New York, is still
waiting for his first Olympic call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not one in all these months _ can you believe that?'' the Dog
barked on Monday on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Russo admitted that this has been a busy talk winter, with the
Jets, and Sprewell, and Roger Clemens. On the list of topics, he
rated the Olympic mess somewhere below the possibility of Rey
Ordonez hitting .260 this season for the Mets. NBC's Dick Ebersol
was a guest last week, and the Salt Lake story did come up. Not a
single caller took the cue.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one cares,'' Russo said. ``People are so used to scandals,
and this one doesn't have anything to do with New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Not like, say, the one that involves the city's mayor and his
inexplicable desire to build almost as many new taxpayer-financed
sports stadiums as there are crumbling schools. Donald Fehr, the
baseball union chief and a member of Mitchell's commission, was
nice enough to explain the difference between that kind of ``big
business'' and the Olympic, nonprofit sort, but I left the news
conference doing the simple math. A few hundred thousand dollars
worth of graft to get the Olympics does not equal hundreds of
millions to keep the Yanks.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the Mitchell report conveniently takes the
sanitized position that, in the final analysis, Salt Lake's
``superior presentation'' won it the Olympics, not the payoffs.
This eminently debatable opinion is made for talk radio, if only
anyone really cared.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan happens to be right. The Olympics are about the
athletes and their stories, about two weeks of television from some
exotic, never-never land. Olympians are the ultimate disposable
heroes, serving up a giant sports feast every two years, on paper
plates. When it's over, all we want is the garbage thrown out, and
hauled far, far away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-99 2022EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
