<HEADER>
A3696 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REPUBLIC-BANK-NYT &LR;      03-01 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBLIC-BANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLIC BANK TO ELIMINATE 560 JOBS IN REORGANIZATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Republic New York Corp., battered late last year by its
losses in volatile overseas markets, said on Monday it planned to
eliminate about 560 jobs, or about 7 percent of its work force.
</P>
<P>
   The bank said that 384 of the job cuts would be layoffs, while
127 positions would be eliminated through contract arrangements
that include new job offers for those employees. The rest of the
cuts would be through attrition and a hiring freeze.
</P>
<P>
   The job cuts are part of a broader reorganization over the next
18 months aimed at refocusing the bank on its global private
banking business and other niche businesses such as currency
trading. Republic said it planned to close its securities trading
and derivatives businesses and would take a pretax charge of $97
million in the first quarter to account for the reorganization. It
will also incur $7 million in pretax expenses in the quarter,
primarily related to ending some employee-benefit programs.
</P>
<P>
   Republic said the moves should result in about $42 million in
pretax savings this year. In trading Monday on the New York Stock
Exchange, shares of Republic rose 37.5 cents, to $45.6875.
</P>
<P>
   Republic is controlled by Edmond J. Safra, a legendary banker
whose family has been involved in the industry for more than 150
years, but who has been struggling with Parkinson's disease.
Safra's poor health has led to speculation that he might be
grooming Republic for a sale, something the bank declined to
comment on but which investment bankers and analysts consider to be
highly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are nephews in the family who are poised to assume
leadership, so I'd be very surprised if Edmond Safra is preparing
to sell the bank,'' said Judah Kruashaar, an analyst with Merrill
Lynch &AMP; Co. ``They're just trying to cut the fat out of a highly
paternalistic company.''
</P>
<P>
   Republic, which earned $117.5 million, or $2.07 a share, in the
first quarter last year, suffered more than $190 million in trading
losses in the third quarter because of errant bets on Russian
securities.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian losses were an unusual, though not unheard of, blow
for Republic, the nation's 19th-largest bank, with about $50
billion in assets. Safra, 66, who is also chairman of Safra
Republic Holdings SA, a private European banking unit of Republic,
owns 28.5 percent of Republic New York.
</P>
<P>
   Although Republic has a traditional consumer branch network in
New York, its more sophisticated businesses are in private banking,
precious metals trading and financial services it performs for
securities firms and highly volatile hedge funds.
</P>
<P>
   Republic said its reorganization would seek to expand its
private banking business, which has always thrived internationally
but has not grown as quickly as planned in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're in a cost-cutting and revenue-building mode,''
said Marni Pont O'Doherty, an analyst with Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods
Inc. ``The potential for Republic to generate better revenue growth
is there but they still have a way to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
