<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3699 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-USOC-SALTLAKE-COX     03-01 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-USOC-SALTLAKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Panel gives recommendations on Olympic gift-giving
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) General News and (s) Sports categories.)
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A commission formed to take a hard look at U.S.
cities' bidding practices for the Olympic Games placed the blame
for the festering scandal squarely on the International Olympic
Committee and suggested widespread reform to eliminate ``a broader
culture of improper gift-giving.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Olympic Committee ethics panel, chaired by former U.S.
Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, released a 53-page report
Monday that examined the ``troubling events in Salt Lake City and
other host cities'' and recommended ways to avert such abuses in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   Prohibiting gifts of more than nominal value, paying for travel
to bid cities through a central fund administered by the USOC or
IOC and establishing a national office of bid compliance are some
of the recommendations. The panel also believes that the IOC should
open its financial records to the public and that its members
should be subject to elections and term limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intense competition to host the Olympic Games coupled with
the multi-billion-dollar enterprise'' of hosting the Games ,'' the
report said, ``have exposed the weaknesses in the movement's
governing structures and operational controls.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said his committee did not investigate Atlanta's
winning bid for the 1996 Games because it was ``not essential for
the purposes for which this commission was created.''
</P>
<P>
   But he did criticize the IOC for not heeding a warning sounded
in 1991 by Toronto, which lost to Atlanta and complained of the
flaws in the process: ``The Toronto prophesy has come true. As a
result, credibility of the Olympic movement has been gravely
damaged.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Dick Pound, the IOC vice president who has been in
charge of the organization's internal inquiry, said that he does
``not for a moment accept any broadbrush characterization of IOC as
a culture of corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   Pound said he has not read the Mitchell report but will soon.
The IOC is under no obligation to adopt any of the reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there are some genuine suggestions for improvement,''
he said. ``We're not saying we're perfect by any means.''
</P>
<P>
   Pound said a ban on gifts would be considered. ``You could knock
off a lot of the problems by saying, 'No gifts,''' Pound said,
``but a golf shirt saying Salt Lake City doesn't seem to me to be
something to make the earth shake.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the panel found that Salt Lake City, in conjunction with the
USOC, did try to sway votes through a training program for Sudanese
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   In a hand-written note, Tom Wilkinson, assistant executive
director of the USOC, said that use of a grant to train the
Sudanese athletes did not look ``like a wise investment unless IOC
votes are involved!!!'' Later, he commented that ``a deal is a deal
and Sudan delivered . . . . May need Sudan again in future. Don't
burn bridges.''
</P>
<P>
   Afredo LaMont, the USOC's director of international relations
and protocol, resigned in January.
</P>
<P>
   The USOC's top officials will address the Mitchell report
Wednesday at a news conference in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Turanchik, leader of the joint Florida bid for the 2012
Olympics from Tampa, St. Petersburg and Orlando, said he and the
other seven hopeful U.S. cities are already operating under strict
controls by the USOC, which must approve each press release.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather have tight rules that were occasionally
burdensome,'' he said, ``than a wide open free-for-all.''
</P>
<P>
   Bid papers are due in 395 days, and the USOC will select its
candidate city in the fall of 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Rosen writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHLIGHTS OF USOC RECOMMENDED CHANGES
</P>
<P>
   PROPOSED: Prohibit bid cities from giving to IOC or USOC members
anything of more than nominal value, and from directly paying their
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   CURRENT: IOC members are prohibited from accepting gifts valued
at more than $150, and $50 for USOC members. Bid cities pay for all
travel.
</P>
<P>
   PROPOSED: The USOC should establish an independent Office of Bid
Compliance, prohibit cities from having or participating in any
international assistance program, strictly apply the criteria for
the award and administration of its international assistance fund
and strengthen its Bid Procedures Manual.
</P>
<P>
   CURRENT: There is no bid compliance entity; bid and candidate
cities have worked with the USOC in the international assistance
program, and sometimes initiated their own programs.
</P>
<P>
   PROPOSED: The IOC should elect a substantial majority of its
members nominated by outside sports organizations. Athlete members
should be chosen by athletes. Public sector members should best
represent the interests of the public. Members should be subject to
periodic re-election with appropriate term limits. Financial
records should be audited by an independent firm and the results
disclosed publicly. Appropriate gift-giving rules and strict travel
and expense rules should be adopted and vigorously enforced.
</P>
<P>
   CURRENT: The IOC elects its members at the recommendation of the
executive board. Members elected before 1966 serve for life; those
elected after 1966 serve until age 80. Only the IOC can expel a
member. All IOC financial records are closed to the public.
</P>
<P>
   PROPOSED: The USOC should request the president of the United
States to consider naming the IOC ``a public international
organization'' to make it comply with the Foreign Corrupt Practices
Act.
</P>
<P>
   CURRENT: The IOC is not subject to the Foreign Corrupt Practices
Act.
</P>
<P>
   PROPOSED: The IOC should not award the Olympics to any country
that has not taken steps to enact a law that applies the principles
of the Anti-Bribery Convention of the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development, signed by 34 governments, including
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   CURRENT: The IOC is not subject to the Anti-Bribery Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
