<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3701 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEEKS-DUKEREALTY-COX     03-01 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEEKS-DUKEREALTY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Indiana developer pays $1.7 billion for Weeks
 &HT;    By Sallye Salter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Weeks Corp., a Norcross, Ga.-based real estate
investment trust that has been rapidly growing in metro Atlanta and
the Southeast, is being acquired for $1.7 billion by Duke Realty
Investments Inc. of Indianapolis, a large developer. Both
specialize in office and industrial properties.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction is seen by some analysts as Duke's bet that the
Southeastern market, softened by increased construction, will
rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long-term these are solid markets, but the question is whether
Duke is buying markets that are on the way down or are they buying
at the bottom,'' said Kevin Lampo of Edward D. Jones &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks needed new markets and new capital if it were to maintain
its growth rate, said Jay Leupp, managing director and senior real
estate analyst at BancBoston Robertson Stephens. ``This gives
shareholders both access to Midwest and Northeast markets as well
as a stronger balance sheet with an investment grade rating.''
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Ray Weeks Jr. said his company has been talking with
Duke for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   The boards of both companies approved the deal Sunday, Weeks
said. Shareholders will vote in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks will become vice chairman, president and chief operating
officer and remain in Atlanta. Weeks Vice Chairman and Chief
Investment Officer Tom Senkbeil will become chief investment
officer for the new company, Duke-Weeks Realty Corp., based in
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks' shares, which have suffered from concern that supply will
outstrip demand for its properties, were down 18 percent over the
past 12 months. They rose $1 Monday to close at $28.
</P>
<P>
   The price will be 1.38 shares of Duke for each share of Weeks,
or $28.89 a share based on Duke's closing price Monday of $20.93
3/4. Duke will assume $254 million of preferred stock and $654
million of debt. Leupp said net asset value of Weeks' properties is
$28 a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duke's timing is very good,'' Leupp said. ``Duke is getting
better pricing in buying the entire Weeks portfolio than it would
trying to put it together in the private market one asset at a
time.'' The acquisition comes amid a 15-monthlong slump in REIT
stocks that has hampered their ability to raise capital for
acquisitions and development.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila McGrath, an analyst at Dresdner Kleinwort Benson, said
the deal could be the one that leads to a domino effect of a
long-anticipated consolidation in the REIT industry.
</P>
<P>
   Sallye Salter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Dow Jones News Service and Bloomberg News contributed
to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
