<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISONS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE REJECTS TEXAS' PLEA TO BE FREE OF FEDERAL SUPERVISION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See PRISONS-RUIZ) 
 
By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Constitutional rights of Texas inmates are
routinely violated despite 20 years of judicial oversight and
official promises to improve prisoner treatment, senior U.S.
District Judge William Wayne Justice ruled Monday, rejecting the
state's latest plea to be relieved of federal-court supervision.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said solitary confinement remains horrific for
mentally ill and other inmates; vulnerable prisoners are
unprotected from rape and assault; and guards rely on ``malicious
and sadistic'' excessive force to control the state's nearly
150,000 incarcerated offenders.
</P>
<P>
   But acknowledging gradual improvement in some facets of prison
operations, Justice said he found nothing unconstitutional about
medical and psychiatric care for inmates, even though it is at
times inadequate and negligent.
</P>
<P>
   Although prisons ``are designed to punish,'' Justice said when
someone is sentenced to confinement in the Texas Department of
Criminal Justice, ``an offender should not _ and must not _ be
sentenced to a term of enslavement by gangs, rape and abuse by
predatory inmates, or excessive force by prison employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General John Cornyn said the ruling, which followed
three weeks of testimony from prison officials, hired experts and
complaining inmates, would be appealed to the 5th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came in a class-action case filed in 1972 by inmate
David Ruiz, whose complaints led to sweeping changes in prison
conditions beginning in the late 1970s. By 1992, Justice said there
were enough improvements to warrant ending his oversight in all but
a few areas of prison operations, including use of force and the
solitary-confinement cells known as administrative segregation.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a 1996 federal law aimed at curtailing federal-court
jurisdiction over state prison systems, Texas legislators and
Cornyn asked Justice to reconsider his stance. But in his 167-page
opinion and accompanying orders, Justice said Texas has failed to
live up to its previous promises to end certain unconstitutional
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying inmates claimed they were repeatedly raped, beaten
and robbed without consequence; others claimed they were brutalized
by guards and ignored when they sought medical help. Several
claimed they paid gang members with commissary credits and sexual
favors to avoid victimization, with tacit approval of guards.
</P>
<P>
   Justice said the ``conditions of confinement in administrative
segregation; failure to provide reasonable safety for assaulted and
abused inmates and excessive use of force by correctional officers
in Texas prisons violate the Constitution of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge stated that the new federal law, known as the Prison
Litigation Reform Act, cannot be applied retroactively to the Ruiz
case. And even if it did, there are enough on-going constitutional
violations to justify his retaining an oversight role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jurisdiction of this civil action will be retained, until such
time as the court determines that full and complete relief from
these constitutional violations has been obtained for the plaintiff
class (inmates),'' his ruling said.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn, registering no surprise at the outcome, said he was
disappointed, though he believes the ruling was necessary to set up
a final showdown in appellate court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two months into my administration, we have succeeded in doing
what has not been done before _ and that is, getting a final
appealable decision on federal court oversight of our Texas prison
system,'' Cornyn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all along have felt this was a first step in a process that
would ultimately end at the Fifth Circuit,'' he said. ``And that's
where we head next.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means we lost this battle, but we are hopeful about
winning the war,'' Cornyn said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Board of Criminal Justice Chairman Allan Polunsky likewise
disagreed with Justice's conclusion, saying, ``enough is enough.
It's time to quit wasting time and money on this needless lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge Justice has held on to this case for a quarter of a
century. It is time for him to let go and stop what is from this
point on a totally unwarranted intrusion into the authority of the
Texas Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   Polunsky added, ``We feel strongly that Texas prisons meet all
constitutional mandates as a safe, clean and humane system, and in
fact in many areas exceed what is required.''
</P>
<P>
   The two state lawmakers who intervened in the case to press for
its termination heaped other criticisms on the judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge Justice has made it very clear through his past actions
that he feels the federal government can do a better job of running
our prisons than the state can,'' said Sen. J.E. ``Buster'' Brown,
R-Lake Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think it's realistic to believe we will ever totally
eliminate problems within our prison system. However, the bottom
line is we have been in compliance for years. It's time to end this
unfair oversight,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Culberson, R-Houston, who launched the legal quest
with Brown nine years ago, said ``the finish line is finally in
sight for the people of Texas to end all federal control over the
prison system.'' That finish line, he said, is the day when ``we
the people will run the prisons, not a federal judge and some
lawyers from San Francisco'' _ a reference to the California-based,
court-appointed attorneys for the inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Justice's bulky legal memorandum supporting his order said there
have been ``remarkable'' improvements in prison conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truly, much has changed,'' Justice wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, plaintiffs and defendants alike look back with horror
at the way the system used to be. Plaintiffs and defendants alike
may also look back with pride at how much the system has changed,''
Justice wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, transformation does not, in and of itself, a
constitutional institution make,'' he continued.
</P>
<P>
   The sprawling prisons' health-care system, which relies heavily
on hospitals and medical schools based in Galveston and Lubbock,
barely passed muster with Justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is determined that TDCJ's medical and psychiatric care
systems, while at times plagued by negligent and inadequate
treatment of members of the plaintiff class, are not so
deliberately indifferent to inmates' physical and mental health
needs as to be unconstitutional,'' Justice wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The extreme deprivations and repressive conditions of
confinement of Texas' administrative segregation units, however,''
do violate the Constitution's ban on cruel and unusual punishment,
he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, inmates ``still live under conditions allowing a
substantial risk of physical and sexual abuse from other inmates,
as well as malicious and sadistic use of force by correctional
officers,'' the judge wrote.
</P>
<P>
   And despite its ``institutional awareness'' of those conditions,
the prison system ``has failed to take reasonable measures to
protect vulnerable inmates from other, predatory prisoners and
overzealous, physically aggressive state employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the judge lauded the system's efforts to ``punish, reform,
and rehabilitate society's offenders.'' He wrote the system
``employs many conscientious public servants _ individuals who
recognize that prisons must not only punish wrong-doers but also
attempt to improve them.''
</P>
<P>
   He concluded by saying ``it is hoped that these same public
servants, in light of the evidence produced before this court,
recognize that similar improvement is required of the prison system
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
