<HEADLINE>
LOOKING FOR A BACKUP ROLE, KANELL VISITS REEVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Danny Kanell met on Monday with Coach Dan Reeves at the Atlanta
Falcons offices to discuss a free-agent contract that would make
Kanell the backup to the often-injured starting quarterback, Chris
Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   When Kanell was released by the Giants last month, he said he
admired Reeves' offensive system. Reeves said he was in the market
for a backup and felt Kanell would be a good fit. Kanell has said
he knows he will have to accept a reserve role wherever he signs.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at Giants Stadium, Brian Williams, the center who has
missed the last two seasons because of an eye injury, returned to
the locker room Monday, taking the first steps in a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave me goose bumps,'' he said. ``It's a dream come true.
My wife said I'm not allowed to complain about anything anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   After being accidentally poked in the eye at the 1997 training
camp, Williams suffered from double vision that prevented him from
playing. Giants doctors tried several surgical procedures and
treatments for a year, but Williams' vision did not improve enough
until late in 1998 when a final surgery corrected the most
debilitating problem in Williams' recovery _ double vision when he
looked up, as he would in a football stance.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the double vision has diminished by about 75
percent, which he felt was more than good enough to attempt his
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I have to get my body back in football shape,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants on Monday also worked out tight end Pete Mitchell, a
free agent who played for Jacksonville last season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
