<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: MERCEDES-BENZ CONSOLIDATES ACCOUNT AT OMNICOM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.J., Texas, Calif., Minn.)  (lh) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One of the most closely followed recent advertising
stories took another surprising turn Monday when Mercedes-Benz of
North America decided to consolidate its account at Omnicom Group
by hiring Merkley Newman Harty in New York and other shops that are
part of the Diversified Agency Services division of Omnicom to
handle marketing assignments with billings estimated at $125
million.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes-Benz made its decision just three weeks after the
fraying ties with its agency since November 1993, Lowe &AMP;
Partners/SMS in New York, finally broke with the dismissal of Lowe
and two affiliates, effective on April 30. The decision came after
a brief competition for the prestigious account that pitted Omnicom
against True North Communications, another giant agency company
that like Omnicom already works for the Mercedes-Benz parent,
DaimlerChrysler AG.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had detailed meetings with both partners,'' Joe Eberhardt,
vice president for marketing at Mercedes-Benz in Montvale, N.J.,
said in an interview at the company's glitzy flagship showroom in
midtown Manhattan. Omnicom, he added, ``offers what we are looking
for, a platform for us to move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision is indicative of the major trend remaking Madison
Avenue as huge agency companies like Omnicom offer increasingly
diverse services to meet the needs of multinational clients.
Merkley Newman will work with Omnicom siblings like Rapp Collins
Worldwide, handling duties like direct marketing; Alcone Marketing
Group, for promotions; Pentacom, for media buying, and the
Designory, for graphic design.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Mercedes-Benz joins a long list of automotive
brands looking to Omnicom agencies for creative work. They include
Dodge, Isuzu, Nissan and Volkswagen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very excited about this opportunity,'' said John Wren,
president and chief executive at Omnicom in New York, who joined
Eberhardt for the interview. The Omnicom agencies that already
handle automotive accounts include BBDO Worldwide, DDB Needham
Worldwide and TBWA Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is also a huge step up for Merkley Newman, a
creatively focused agency with billings estimated at $165 million,
which Omnicom spun off from the venerable Doremus &AMP; Co. in New York
almost six years ago. Merkley Newman will handle advertising,
creative services and strategic and account planning for
Mercedes-Benz vehicles sold in the United States and Canada _ an
account that immediately becomes Merkley Newman's largest, just as
DaimlerChrysler is Omnicom's largest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just couldn't be happier,'' said Parry Merkley, president at
Merkley Newman in New York. ``What else could I say?''
</P>
<P>
   Discussions will now get under way, he added, about such
``logistical implications'' as whether Merkley Newman will add to
its staff of 130 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Other Merkley Newman clients include BellSouth Corp., Citigroup,
Forbes Inc. and Mars Inc. The agency is hoping, Merkley said, that
Mercedes-Benz will not deem it a conflict that Merkley Newman also
handles the account of BMW motorcycles, sold by a principal
Mercedes-Benz rival, BMW AG.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of Merkley Newman also typifies the ability of
behemoths like Omnicom to manage their holdings for maximum
effectiveness. In May 1994, Merkley Newman was devastated by the
loss of what was then its largest client when IBM consolidated more
than 40 accounts at the Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide unit of WPP Group
PLC in New York. An independent agency the size of Merkley Newman
probably would have been forced to close, but Omnicom's resources
helped keep the doors open.
</P>
<P>
   ``It pays off in this kind of instance,'' Merkley said,
expressing how ``grateful'' the agency was ``for Omnicom's
support.''
</P>
<P>
   The comity generated by the broadening ties between Omnicom and
Mercedes-Benz is in stark contrast to the enmity stirred by the
dismissal of Lowe, part of the Lowe Group unit of Interpublic Group
of Cos. Interpublic is suing Marvin Sloves, the former co-chairman
of Lowe, hired as a consultant after he retired on Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The retirement of Sloves, long a favorite of Mercedes-Benz
management, was a principal reason for the dismissal of Lowe,
underscoring the continued importance of personal relationships
between clients and their agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were always happy with the creative end product that
Mercedes-Benz and Lowe put into the market place,'' Eberhardt said,
referring to himself and Michael Jackson, president and chief
executive at Mercedes-Benz.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact we parted ways was because of the challenges in the
process,'' he added. ``It became harder and harder to turn out that
great creative product.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about mounting industry speculation that Mercedes-Benz
wanted Sloves to join the agency that was awarded the creative and
strategic assignments, Eberhardt replied: ``Marvin Sloves has not
been a part of any discussions with True North or Omnicom. He was
never intended to play a role in this. He has a contractual
relationship with Lowe.''
</P>
<P>
   Wren and Merkley echoed those remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Sloves, reached at home Monday, said, ``I've heard nothing,
nothing, nothing from Omnicom.'' He also described himself as
``terribly sad'' that Interpublic would pursue legal action against
him, adding: ``As far as I'm concerned, I'm still a consultant at
Lowe. I don't want anything to happen to the agency. My name is
still on the door, at least for now.'' (The final ``S'' in ``SMS''
is for Sloves.)
</P>
<P>
   Nick Camera, vice president and general counsel at Interpublic
in New York, confirmed a report this week in the trade publication
Adweek that Interpublic had ``commenced proceedings against
Sloves'' regarding ``certain matters related to his employment and
consulting agreement.'' He declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Moses Silverman, a lawyer for Sloves, said that Interpublic was
seeking a hearing for breach of contract before the American
Arbitration Association as well as an injunction in New York state
Supreme Court prohibiting Sloves from soliciting Lowe accounts or
employees. Silverman said that a preliminary injunction had been
denied; Camera again declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   In offering Merkley Newman to Mercedes-Benz, Wren said, ``We
discussed the pros and the cons of all our national agencies.''
They also include GSD&AMP;M in Austin, Texas; Goodby, Silverstein &AMP;
Partners in San Francisco, and Martin/Williams Advertising in
Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made infinite sense to put Merkley forth,'' Wren said,
because of its location near the Mercedes-Benz office in New Jersey
and the agency's ``creative and other capabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   True North, for its part, offered the services of Foote, Cone &AMP;
Belding, which has automotive experience that includes work on the
Mazda account. True North, which continues working for
DaimlerChrysler on brands like Chrysler, Jeep and Plymouth,
declined to comment on the Mercedes-Benz decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
