<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-CONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONE'S SEARCH LEADS HIM TO ACUPUNCTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ David Cone was stationed along the left-field line
on Monday at Legends Field, lobbing a baseball to Roger Clemens.
Cone flipped the ball, he floated it and he even shot-putted it
from distances ranging from 30 to 90 feet. But he never fired the
ball with any vigor. Not even close.
</P>
<P>
   Cone is tiptoeing through another spring training with the
Yankees, which means there are renewed questions about his
surgically repaired right shoulder and about his 36-year-old arm.
Since Cone has been deliberate about his approach and creative
about ways to strengthen his arm, the intrigue about whether he can
continue to be a formidable pitcher for the Yankees merely
intensifies.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Cone is always testing different arm angles and grips,
he is also trying out different ways to keep his shoulder sound and
manage the pain he feels. He is undergoing acupuncture treatments
four or five times a week, he gets frequent massages, he has heat
applied to his shoulder, he exercises with a curved barbell
designed for pitchers and he is cautious about not overtaxing his
arm in any way. More than any Yankee, Cone is worth watching
because he is doing so much just to try to be himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always searching for a better way to work out the arm,''
Cone said. ``It's very tough to train a pitcher's arm and to
basically tell it to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Cone received extensive medical treatment on his shoulder
to pitch in the 1998 post-season, and since he has chronic
tendinitis, he is trying to discover the best methods for remaining
healthy. If that means having needles poked into his shoulder and
electrical currents sent through his body, Cone will do it. After
working 2,396 and two-thirds innings in his career, Cone admitted
that he ``will do anything'' to stay healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that I admire about him is he wants to keep
doing what he's doing,'' Manager Joe Torre said. ``I know he
researches and then gives it a shot. He's adventuresome. That's the
way he pitches. That's the way he's doing this.''
</P>
<P>
   But is Cone being adventuresome, or is he desperate? Cone
insisted that his arm ``feels fresh'' and that it is premature to
evaluate him based on Sunday's sluggish throwing session and on the
careful way he is treating his arm. After going 20-7 and pitching
207 and two-thirds innings last year, Cone had hoped that the
questions would vanish. But Cone is also realistic and, as he
experiments with practices like acupuncture, they might even
increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to find a way to stay strong in September and
October,'' Cone said. ``I have no doubts that I can still pitch and
be consistent and do what I did last year. It's a question of
holding up again. I'm trying to take steps now to insure that I'll
be able to hold on longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Acupuncture is Cone's newest method. This involves the insertion
of needles into specific points in the shoulder to stimulate the
immune system. Rather than just inserting the needles, the
acupuncturist might apply heat to the area or stimulate it with a
low dose of electricity. Cone spent Sunday searching the Internet
for an acupuncturist in New York so he could schedule appointments
during the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did quite a bit of research, almost to the point of
obsession in trying to define the problem I have and trying to find
measures to alleviate the problem,'' Cone said. ``I've done a lot
of research on acupuncture. It's no miracle cure, but I think it
can help control the tendinitis problem I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Mel Stottlemyre, the pitching coach, said that
Cone's health is always a concern, especially after he had aneurysm
surgery in 1996 and shoulder surgery in 1997, Torre said he was not
worried about Cone's methodical manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's caring for himself,'' Torre said. ``It's a good idea.
He's felt good every time he's pitched.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone ended his long-tossing session with Clemens before any
other pitcher on Monday. Once again, he was being different and
being careful. It is only March, but Cone wants to be pitching with
little pain in October. The Yankees want Cone to make it until
then, too, so they will be studying his valuable arm and his new
routines closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been hearing all these questions for the last six
years,'' Cone said. ``It's really nothing new for me. People
thought I was going to blow out a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
