<SLUG> BC-PARAGUAY-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARAGUAY PARALYZED BY POLITICAL CONFLICT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASUNCION, Paraguay _ This small landlocked country in the heart
of South America has just reached a major milestone in the life of
any nation: its first 10 years of uninterrupted democracy.
</P>
<P>
   But on the streets here there are no streamers, posters or other
reminders to suggest that the February anniversary brought joyful
celebration or even relief. Instead, the graffiti here feature
obscene gestures and demand that a handful of politicians across
the political spectrum be hauled off to jail.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict is paralyzing this poverty-stricken nation and
could bring the impeachment of the second popularly elected
president of the decade of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The clash grows out of President Raul Cubas Grau's defiance of a
Supreme Court order to send a close political ally back to prison.
The ally, Lino Oviedo, a retired general, is accused of leading an
unsuccessful coup attempt against President Juan Carlos Wasmosy in
1996, after Wasmosy had dismissed Oviedo and he refused to leave
the barracks. After Oviedo had won the primary for the governing
Colorado Party, Wasmosy had him arrested, and he was sentenced to
10 years in prison. Soon after he became president in August, Cubas
freed his friend by decree.
</P>
<P>
   The president's action was hardly a surprise. He had been
Oviedo's vice-presidential running mate in the elections last year
and became the presidential candidate only after Oviedo had been
imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
   Cubas, an uninspired speaker, appealed to voters as the shadow
of the former general.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a judge here refused to prosecute the president for
refusing to send Oviedo back to jail. But he sent the prosecutor's
case on to Congress, the first step in a possible impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is too early to say how the case will fare, Cubas
appears to be growing increasingly isolated. On Friday, the
ambassadors from most of Paraguay's regional trading partners met
him over lunch. But the Argentine ambassador stayed away.
</P>
<P>
   The American ambassador, Maura Harty, spent three hours last
Tuesday evening meeting with Vice President Luis Maria Argana. A
spokesman for the embassy denied that Ms. Harty had discussed a
possible Argana government and insisted that the meeting was
routine. But Paraguayans read the meeting as a highly visible show
of support for Argana.
</P>
<P>
   Paraguayans, new to the workings of democracy, are not sure
where the limits of the conflict lie. Some fear that it could set
off a move to hold power by force. Others say they believe that
Argana will maneuver to take over the presidency. Persistent street
demonstrations, although largely peaceful, have raised fears of
civil violence.
</P>
<P>
   The nation now has the trappings of democracy, with periodic
elections, a constitution and separate branches of government. But
there is little confidence in the independence of the courts and
the Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Paraguay regularly figures among the most corrupt countries in
surveys by organizations like Transparency International, which
issues annual reports. The official economy, at $10 billion, is
dwarfed by an underground economy centered on counterfeit goods,
arms and drug smuggling that is generally estimated at $12 billion
a year.
</P>
<P>
   Rosa Palau, who oversees a center that maintains archives from
the military dictatorship, said the crisis could drag on
indefinitely and inconclusively. ``This is an improvised country,''
Ms. Palau said.
</P>
<P>
   In the atmosphere of uncertainty, investment is at a standstill.
Stores remain virtually empty, and public works appear to have
stalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can people believe in democracy?'' Ms. Palau asked. ``How
can they believe in anything when the president simply decides to
ignore an order of the court and nothing happens?''
</P>
<P>
   The currency, the guarani, has lost 25 percent of its value in
the last month. Tax collections this year are 21 percent below
expectations, and international reserves have shrunk to less than
$800 million.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Alfredo Boccia Paz, a hematologist in Asuncion, said the
crisis seemed to have paralyzed the economy and spirits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can continue like this for a long time,'' Paz said. ``We'll
reach the end of the year poorer and with people still talking
about the same things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-99 2043EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
