<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3714 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREDITCARD-SWITCH-1ST     03-01 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDITCARD-SWITCH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKS SELL CREDIT CARD ACCOUNTS, AND SOME HOLDERS ARE HIT WITH FAR
HIGHER RATES 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Subs 5th graf to correct the number of accounts bought by Chase to
3.5 million, sted billion.)  (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(fe) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr. 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   First there was the 5.9 percent teaser rate. When that expired,
the interest rate on Tom Moore's PNC Bank credit card jumped to
14.4 percent. Finally it settled at 12.5 percent. Moore, an
illustrator who lives in the Park Slope section of Brooklyn, N.Y.,
was satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   But last week Moore was stunned to find that he was no longer a
customer of PNC, which is based in Pittsburgh, but of a bank in
Oklahoma he had never heard of. Not only that, but his interest
rate had been jacked up to 20.74 percent _ and 24.74 percent on
cash advances.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about the most odious business practice I've ever
seen,'' complained Moore, who is 46.
</P>
<P>
   Odious or not, tens of millions of Americans have been facing
the same stark choice _ to take the new terms or leave them _ as
the credit-card business rapidly consolidates into fewer and larger
hands. About 32 million accounts were sold last year, mainly by
regional banks like PNC, Keycorp, First Maryland and First Union.
That is more than four times as many as in 1996, according to R.K.
Hammer, who runs a card industry advisory firm in Thousand Oaks,
Calif. Because many people have multiple accounts, the sales
involved some 20 million consumers. The figures do not include
transfers resulting from mergers.
</P>
<P>
   Big buyers have included Chase, which bought 3.5 million Bank of
New York accounts last year, and Citibank, which bought AT&AMP;T's
Universal Card. Other buyers are Fleet Financial and Bank One,
which owns First USA, as well as some little-known companies.
</P>
<P>
   Except for low teaser rates guaranteed for, say, six months,
banks have no legal obligation to honor any rates cardholders now
pay and have shown little inclination to do so. But while it is not
unusual for rates to rise 6 or 8 percentage points, they could also
fall. ``It's the natural time to examine the risk and reward of
each'' account, Hammer said, and the result ``could be a repricing
up or down.'' And even when rates stay the same, penalties and
grace periods may change, sometimes to the consumer's benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gerri Detweiler, a credit-card specialist and consultant
to Debt Counselors, called it scandalous that consumers can so
easily fall prey to the wheeling and dealing of large institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your mortgage or car loan were sold, your rate would stay
the same,'' Ms. Detweiler said. ``That's not the case with credit
cards.'' When consumers see an account has been transferred, it is
very important to read the fine print because of a high probability
that the interest rate or some other terms have been changed.
</P>
<P>
   With an estimated 3.5 billion credit-card offers flooding
Americans' mailboxes each year, cardholders would have little
trouble taking their business elsewhere. Often, by paying a fee,
they are even able to transfer balances. But the banks, Ms.
Detweiler added, ``anticipate that a lot of new customers won't pay
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore acknowledged that a month or two earlier he had received a
mailing that may well have included a notification of the higher
rates but that he had not focused on it.
</P>
<P>
   Credits cards once provided a lush business for regional banks
like PNC, but many are fleeing it now, squeezed by the high costs
of uncollectible debt and a rising number of consumers who pay
monthly balances in full, depriving the bank of interest income.
And the cost is rising for the increasingly sophisticated computer
models that analyze customer usage patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, even at a time of unparalleled prosperity, there is no
letup in the record number of Americans filing for bankruptcy,
raising fears that a business downturn would send bad card debt
soaring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The card business is really becoming a business of scale,''
said Warren G. Heller, research director at Veribanc Inc., a
company in Wakefield, Mass., that studies and rates the nation's
banks. ``A lot of companies are recognizing this and throwing in
the towel.''
</P>
<P>
   Mortgages and automotive loans are routinely bought and sold,
but this has little impact on borrowers, since the rates cannot
change. But the new owners of credit-card business are free to
impose whatever interest rate the traffic will bear, subject only
to the handful of remaining state usury ceilings. They can also
shorten the time for making payments without interest charges,
eliminate grace periods for payments received a few days late and
raise penalties for late payment, now commonly as much as $29.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, there is no change in a customer's rate, said
David Robertson, president of the Nilson Report, an industry
newsletter in Oxnard, Calif. But it is also common for banks to
upgrade the type of account _ to platinum, for instance. Upgraded
accounts sometimes prove to be more expensive in terms of fees and
may carry higher rates as well, although they may offer more
services and the advantage of being with a bigger lender.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, Robertson contended, the industry's
ever-more-sophisticated ability to analyze account data has helped
it to tailor new products and cut costs, and these savings may
ultimately be shared with customers. ``This is certainly the heyday
of the credit-card business for the consumer,'' Robertson said.
``Never has there been a better time to find the card that appeals
to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore is one of those looking for a more-appealing card. After
learning of the sale of his account, he telephoned the new owner,
Direct Merchants Bank in Tulsa. A customer service representative
told him that his was one of a half million PNC accounts
transferred and that if he did not like the new terms, he could
close his account.
</P>
<P>
   He promptly canceled his card but must still pay the higher
interest rate on his $848 balance, which he hopes to pay off soon.
But if he had been running a balance too big to settle fairly
quickly, he would have been forced, with only a few weeks' notice,
to pay a much higher interest rate for some time unless he could
transfer it to a new card.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you build up a substantial amount, you may not be able to
pay it all,'' said Stephen Brobeck, executive director of the
Consumer Federation of America. He called it ``gouging'' when a
credit-card rate is raised sharply for no reason other than a
business deal between large institutions.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
