<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-TESTAVERDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS SIGN TESTAVERDE TO A GUARANTEED DEAL WORTH $19.47 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To no one's surprise, Vinny Testaverde officially
became the Jets' quarterback of the future on Monday, and he is
only 35.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde, whose strong performance last season was no less
surprising than the Jets', signed a three-year deal that included
an upfront bonus of $6.2 million and millions more in guaranteed
income _ an unusual development in a sport in which most contracts
are not guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, Testaverde signed for $19.47 million in a three-year
deal. Incentives, most of them based on team performance, could
swell the contract to $27 million.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Testaverde's base deal is almost 50 times what his
boyhood idol, Joe Namath, signed for as a Jets rookie in 1965.
Namath's headline-making $427,000, three-year contract included a
Lincoln Continental.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde's agent, Mike Azzarelli, laughed on Monday when asked
whether the quarterback who took the Jets to the American
Conference championship game in January would get a bonus car, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got him the Hawker instead of the Lincoln,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawker is a 10-seat jet plane that Testaverde bought for
several million dollars and will use in the off season to commute
from Tampa, Fla., to Jets workouts.
</P>
<P>
   Making those 40 workouts were important to Coach Bill Parcells,
who said it was a ``deal-breaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells especially wanted his quarterback to be part of the
hard work that often draws players even closer together.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that tough talk, however, Parcells' infatuation with
Testaverde was obvious. The coach enjoyed the finest quarterback
performance in club history with 29 touchdowns to only 7
interceptions. And the Jets finished atop their division for the
first time since 1969, when they were still part of the American
Football League.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Parcells and his salary-cap guru, Mike Tannenbaum,
came up with the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they cut Vinny after the first year,'' Azzarelli said, ``he
is still guaranteed $14,970,000. If they cut him after the second
year he is guaranteed $16,670,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Azzarelli said that the only player in pro football with similar
contract guarantees is Jake Plummer, who recently signed a $29.7
million deal with the Cardinals that includes a $15-million bonus.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Azzarelli said, Testaverde's contract could
theoretically be worth a grand total of $59 million, since it
includes an option for an additional four years.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets benefited in a way by making it a seven-year deal. That
allows them to prorate the signing bonus over those seven years.
Thus, the hit against this year's salary cap will be under $2
million, including Testaverde's salary. That could enable the Jets
to make a significant offer to Steve Atwater, the Broncos' Pro Bowl
free-agent safety.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-year-old Atwater visited the Jets last week and told
Parcells he was impressed with the coaching staff, whom he had met
during the Pro Bowl week in Hawaii. Atwater's agent, Steve
Schaffer, said he was waiting for the Jets to make an offer.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few years ago, signing a 35-year-old quarterback to such
a deal might have seemed ludicrous. But the current generation of
quarterbacks includes John Elway, who led the Broncos to a second
straight Super Bowl title at age 38, and Dan Marino, whose Dolphins
made the playoffs behind his 37-year-old arm.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde had bittersweet memories Monday. His father, Al, who
lived in Elmont, N.Y., not far from the Jets' camp, died recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last few weeks have been a roller-coaster,'' he said.
``The one thing I'm grateful for is that my father saw a great
season after I was away from the family for 11 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
