<HEADER>
A3718 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-IOC-ATLANTA-COX     03-01 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-ATLANTA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Payne denies wrongdoing in response to IOC
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) General news and (s) Sports categories.)By
Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Olympics chief Billy Payne reiterated Monday
his position that there was ``no wrongdoing'' in Atlanta's campaign
for the 1996 Games.
</P>
<P>
   In his response to an International Olympic Committee inquiry
into bid improprieties, Payne acknowledged exceeding the maximum
$200 guideline on gifts for IOC members, but characterized the
expenditures as gestures toward friends and ``within the range of
customary exchanges'' made by competing cities.
</P>
<P>
   Payne's response was made public the same day an ethics panel
appointed by the United States Olympic Committee recommended an
overhaul of the IOC and the site selection process.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, headed by former Senate Majority Leader George
Mitchell, decried a ``culture of improper gift-giving'' and said
gifts of any value to IOC members should be outlawed. It also urged
the IOC to elect rather than appoint its members and make its
financial records public.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's bid was free of improper inducements, scholarship
programs, associations with agents or excessive multiple visits by
IOC members or their families, Payne stated in a letter sent Friday
to IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won the games for Atlanta by establishing friendships _
that was our primary strategy from day one,'' Payne said Monday.
``Our work with the members of the IOC was based on personal
relationships and our desire to establish the necessary trust to be
awarded this magnificent event.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne's personal letter accompanied the U.S. Olympic Committee's
formal response to the IOC's investigation into the bid efforts of
candidate cities from 1996 through 2006. The USOC told the IOC it
has no plans to investigate Atlanta's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   IOC officials launched its investigation in the wake of bribery
allegations that tarnished Salt Lake City's winning bid for the
2002 Winter Games and snowballed into the worst scandal in Olympic
history. At least 24 IOC members have been accused of receiving as
much as $1.2 million in cash, scholarships, medical care and lavish
gifts during that city's bid.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Pound, an IOC executive board member heading the
committee's investigation, said Monday that 27 cities have sent
reports in ``varying degrees of detail.'' Those reports implicate
no members not already under scrutiny for improprieties in Salt
Lake City, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we expected . . . some of the same fish were feeding in the
same pond,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pound's six-member ad hoc committee spent two days reviewing the
reports from the cities that bidded for the Games. He said he hoped
the inquiry panel would wrap up its investigation in the next few
days and make recommendations to the IOC executive committee before
its general assembly meets March 17-18.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's two-month investigation into the Salt Lake City bid
was aimed at making recommendations for future bids. Salt Lake's
misconduct, Mitchell said, was ``part of a broader culture of
improper gift-giving in which candidate cities provided things of
value to IOC members in an effort to buy their votes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not excuse or condone those from Salt Lake City who did
the giving. What they did was wrong. But ... they did not invent
this culture; they joined one that was already flourishing.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the Atlanta bid has come under increased
scrutiny. The city's Olympic organizers continually have promised
they did nothing wrong in lobbying IOC members, but they have
refused to open their bid records to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The officials have acknowledged giving gifts that exceeded the
price guidelines, such as golf clubs, a sports coat, a bulldog and
extra first-class airline tickets so the children of some IOC
members also could visit Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta officials maintain the gifts did not violate IOC rules
because the limit was just a guideline and other bid cities were
doing the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, Payne acknowledged for the first time that some
IOC members came to Atlanta more than the single visit allowed
under IOC rules. But he contended the visits were stopovers on the
way to or from official visits to other cities, or came at the
request of Atlanta bidders seeking an IOC member to appear at
special functions.
</P>
<P>
   For example, organizers hosted 29 IOC members in two groups
before and after they attended their annual meeting in Puerto Rico
in September 1989. The entire group was invited, even though
several members had already made an official visit to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Those who made the side trip were treated to a demonstration of
the city's enthusiasm for the bid effort: the Aquatic Sports
Festival, a three-day U.S.-USSR swim meet; a water polo tournament
featuring the national teams of Cuba, Canada and the United States;
and a Labor Day 5K ``Run for the Bid.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne also said in his letter that some members brought more
than one guest with them at the expense of the Atlanta bid
committee_ another violation of bid rules. The additional companion
was, in each case, a member's child, he indicated. ``We believe
those visits were justified,'' he wrote the IOC president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe there was no wrongdoing on the part of the IOC
members or the (Atlanta bid committee) during the bid process for
the 1996 games,'' Payne wrote. ``Atlanta won the games 'fair and
square' in an honorable manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Turner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
