<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Web Sites That Track Portfolios  &HT;       
 By Arthur M. Louis  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I own 10 stocks and would like to start tracking them on
my home computer. I'd like to keep a record of the price I paid for
each stock and the number of shares, with automatic price updates
every day. I don't want to have to enter the price changes myself.
Is this feasible?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  It certainly is. There are dozens of Web sites that
offer the kind of portfolio-tracking mechanism you need. This is
another of those online miracles that would have been unthinkable a
decade ago but now are commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   If you are trading through an online broker, there's a good
chance it has a portfolio monitor. Palo Alto's E-Trade offers
portfolio tracking not only to its customers, but also to
noncustomers who register on its Web site at  &LR; www.etrade.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   America Online also provides a portfolio monitor. If you are a
subscriber, click on the ``Keyword'' icon and then type
``Portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   You also can track your portfolio on a number of free financial
Web sites. As good as any is the one maintained by Stockpoint of
San Francisco, at  &LR; www.stockpoint.com &LR; . Go to the Web site, take a
minute to get a user name and password and you're ready to rock 'n'
roll.
</P>
<P>
   Tapping 401(k) for a Home
</P>
<P>
   Q: I know that a person can withdraw up to $10,000 from an
Individual Retirement Account without paying the 10 percent penalty
if the money is applied toward the purchase of a first home. My
husband has $12,000 sitting in a 401(k) plan he opened with a
former employer. Can he withdraw $10,000 from the 401(k) to use
toward our first home, or must we roll the money into an IRA and
then withdraw it to avoid the penalty?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: As you suspected, you first must roll over the money into
an IRA. That's because the law doesn't permit penalty-free
withdrawals from a 401(k) plan for the purchase of a home.
</P>
<P>
   However, you can withdraw $10,000 from a 401(k) on the grounds
of financial hardship. You then must legitimize _ I hesitate to say
``launder'' _ the money for homebuying purposes by rolling it into
an IRA.
</P>
<P>
   Don't ask me to explain why Congress has forced you to go
through this cumbersome routine. I couldn't even guess.
</P>
<P>
   Although you can avoid the penalty by following the two-step
routine, you still must pay taxes at your normal rate on the money
you withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   Warning: Thanks to a new law, this happens to be the last year
in which you will be allowed to roll over 401(k) ``hardship'' money
into an IRA. If that 401(k) money is going to make the difference
between your buying a home or not, then you have fewer than 10
months to act.
</P>
<P>
   Buying Stock Directly
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am interested in buying stock directly from companies that
interest me, rather than paying brokerage commissions. I'd like to
find out which companies will sell to me and how to contact them.
Is there any single source that will provide this information?
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of MONEYBAG (63584 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR;  A: Try the ``Directory of Dividend Reinvestment Plans,'' from
Horizon Publishing. It costs $7.95, and you can order it online at
 &LR; www.horizonpublishing.com &LR; , or by snail mail at Horizon Publishing
Co., 7412 Calumet Ave., Hammond, Ind. 46324. The directory spells
out the pertinent details about each company's DRIP and gives
addresses and telephone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   There are 1,000 companies that will sell you stock directly.
However, in most cases you must buy your initial shares through a
broker. After that, you can increase your holdings by reinvesting
your dividends through the company. Most companies also will let
you send in extra cash to supplement your purchases.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy directly from companies only if your shares are
registered in your name rather than a broker's ``street'' name.
</P>
<P>
   While you won't incur brokerage commissions when you invest
through the companies, some of them charge processing fees of their
own. In some cases, those fees can exceed the cost of a
deep-discount brokerage commission. Bristol-Myers, for example,
charges a fee of up to $5 when you reinvest dividends, and up to
$25 when you make a supplemental cash investment.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, most online brokers charge less than $20 per trade
and some charge less than $10.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, about 100 companies let you buy shares
through their DRIPs at discounts ranging from 3 to 10 percent of
the current market price. That's something your broker won't let
you do.
</P>
<P>
   Another nice feature of DRIPs is that you can buy a fraction of
a share if the amount of your quarterly dividend isn't enough to
cover the price of a full share.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to moneybag(at
sign)sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
