<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-MARTINEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ HAS DOUBTS ABOUT BROTHER RAMON PLAYING IN BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ While Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette
acknowledged Monday that the team is close to signing the
surgically repaired Ramon Martinez, the pitcher's younger brother
and best friend, Pedro Martinez, said he still has reservations
about the former Dodger star coming to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still concerned about that,'' Pedro said Monday in the Red
Sox clubhouse, ``but it's up to him. He'll know what he will have
to put up with in Boston. I know I didn't feel good when they booed
me, and I don't know how he'll react. He's never been booed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy rehabbing and coming off an injury, I'm afraid people
will be expecting too much and trying to compare him to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not done yet. He could change his mind at the last minute
and go somewhere else. It would be great to play with him, but if
goes somewhere else, I'll be happy with that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon and Pedro Martinez pitched together for two seasons with
the Dodgers until Pedro was traded to the Montreal Expos after the
1993 season. The architect of that deal was Duquette, then with the
Expos.
</P>
<P>
   At one point last season, when asked if he'd like to be reunited
with Ramon, Pedro said that had always been his dream, but he
didn't want his brother coming to Boston and hearing boos, the way
Pedro did after a couple of rough outings. Martinez also reacted
negatively when several fans were hard on Bret Saberhagen during a
game in which he struggled.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Martinez, who won 123 games in 11 seasons for the Dodgers,
was off to an outstanding start last season (7-3, 2.83 ERA) until
injuring his shoulder. He underwent surgery to repair a torn
rotator cuff in his shoulder last June, and the club elected to
give him a $600,000 buyout rather than pick up a $5.6 million
option on his contract for the 1999 season. Martinez was eligible
to file for free agency, did not do so, but became one anyway when
the Dodgers did not tender him a contract.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez expressed anger at what he perceived to be Dodger
slights toward his brother, who won 20 games for LA in 1990, won 15
or more games in three other seasons, struck out 18 in one game in
1990, and threw a no-hitter against the Florida Marlins in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did he feel mistreated? They did mistreat him, like always,''
Pedro Martinez said. ``The guy gave his life to the Dodgers and
they didn't appreciate that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Ramon comes back and has a chance to be an even better
pitcher, so they will see that.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette and top aide Eddie Haas went to see Ramon Martinez
throw last month in the Dominican Republic, and were one of a
number of teams asked to submit a bid for the player's services,
even though he may not be ready to pitch until July. Sports
commentator Peter Gammons said he was told by officials of three
clubs that the Red Sox had offered Martinez, who turns 31 on March
22, $2 million for this season, $5 million for the year 2000. Those
officials said they believed Martinez would take that offer.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette would not confirm the figures, but indicated that the
sides were close to a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not quite there yet,'' Duquette said. ``If we were to
get a pitcher, certainly Ramon is a dependable starting pitcher.
We'd hope he would make a contribution at some point in the season.
This would be more for later on this year and next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kid is in pretty good shape and he's determined to come
back and pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez said he has not spoken with his brother since
Saturday. Among the other teams that expressed interest in Ramon,
he said, were the Padres, Cardinals, Indians, Angels, Rockies, and
Diamondbacks. The Dodgers also sent someone to see him throw in the
Dominican. Ramon Martinez only recently began to throw off a mound
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were going to practice this winter, there were always
two or three guys there to see him,'' Pedro said.
</P>
<P>
   New Red Sox reliever Mark Guthrie, who spent the last 3 1/2
seasons with Martinez in Los Angeles, said, ``He's as good as there
is when he's healthy. He's as hard to hit as Pedro is. They have
little bit different styles, but he can get it up there pretty
good. He makes it move, he cuts it, sinks it, and has a great
changeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's tough. The Dodgers picked up Kevin Brown. Ramon is the
same pitcher to me. And he's a warrior. He throws 130, 140 pitches
a game, or at least he did when he was healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a good guy in the clubhouse, respected by everybody.
He's a proven winner, and an easy guy to get along with.''
</P>
<P>
   There is an upside to Ramon Martinez coming to Boston, his
brother said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he plays with me, he has a pretty good chance of being
comfortable,'' said Pedro. ``We're best friends, and I think he'll
have a lot of fun playing with me. Now that he doesn't have
anything to look forward to in LA, why not?
</P>
<P>
   ``If he doesn't want to come over, fine. If he does, that will
be more than fine. Even then, I have my concerns. It's so late in
his career, he has been so good for so long and he's never been
booed before.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's OK. We'll put up with that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox have also been talking with the youngest of the
baseball-playing Martinez brothers, Jesus Martinez, a lefthanded
pitcher who last pitched in the Marlins' system. He is coming off
arthroscopic shoulder surgery, and Pedro said it might be in
Jesus's best interests to sign elsewhere. ``This staff is pretty
full,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette joked that perhaps Ramon should feel some urgency about
signing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Ramon wants to sign, he'd better hurry up,'' Duquette said,
``because in a couple of years we have to pay Pedro $12 million.''
</P>
</TEXT>
