<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Worried About Stocks? Try Buying Insurance  &HT;       
 By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Do you think stocks are so grossly overvalued that we might be on
the verge of a ferocious bear market?
</P>
<P>
   Do you fear that the Year 2000 crisis could disrupt the U.S.
economy indefinitely and wipe out much of your portfolio?
</P>
<P>
   Such concerns are common among stock investors these days _
particularly those who are getting up in years and wonder whether
they will be able to pass along a good-size estate to their heirs.
</P>
<P>
   When the stock market looks iffy, many investors prefer to keep
their assets in safe, slow-growing investments such as U.S.
Treasuries and money market funds.
</P>
<P>
   Few people realize that there is another safe alternative that
can protect your portfolio from plunges, yet allows you to profit
from any stock market gains.
</P>
<P>
   It is a form of term insurance called portfolio-protection
insurance, offered by three major insurers _ American Skandia,
Prudential and Sunamerica. It guarantees that your heirs will get
no less than you paid for your portfolio. If at the time you die,
the value your portfolio is less than the cost, the insurer will
make up the difference.
</P>
<P>
   One big drawback is that the insurance can be used only to
protect investments in mutual funds offered by the insurer itself.
You can't use it to protect other assets.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the mutual funds offered by Prudential and
Sunamerica have been poor-to-average performers over the years, and
American Skandia's funds are only a year or two old, according to
Russ Kinnel, a mutual fund analyst with Morningstar.
</P>
<P>
   For a $100,000 portfolio, the insurance costs $100 to $500 per
year, depending on the insurer.
</P>
<P>
   If you die during the year and the value of your portfolio has
sunk to $95,000, the insurance company pays your heirs the $5,000
difference.
</P>
<P>
   If, however, the value of the portfolio has risen to $105,000
and the insured dies, the insurance company pays nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance ``makes good sense'' for older people who
otherwise would be too scared to keep money in the stock market,
says Danville financial planner Richard DelMonte. It will protect
their portfolios on the downside while allowing them a
theoretically unlimited upside if stocks perform well.
</P>
<P>
   DelMonte figures that the insurance also would make sense for
people of any age who are gravely ill. They are eligible to buy the
insurance because the insurers do not require physical exams or
medical forms.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you knew you had only two or three years or less to live,
it would be a no-brainer,'' he remarks. ``You could invest
aggressively and still protect your heirs.''
</P>
<P>
   For healthy, young people, on the other hand, this kind of
insurance seems a dubious investment. They would pay premiums year
after year after year, and the benefits might not be worth the
cost.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of INSURE02 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  With the Sunamerica plan, you pay an annual premium equal to 0.2
percent of the covered assets _ $200 for a $100,000 portfolio _
regardless of your age.
</P>
<P>
   American Skandia charges 0.3 percent of assets, regardless of
age. Prudential charges 0.1 percent of assets for policyholders
under age 60, 2.5 percent for those under  &LR; between 60 and 70 and
0.5 percent for those ages 70 and older.
</P>
<P>
   The annual premium is based on the value of your portfolio when
you're renewing the policy. Because this is term insurance, you
won't build up any cash value. And if you don't pay the premium
each year, your heirs get zip.
</P>
<P>
   As time goes by, your coverage goes up a minimum of 5 percent a
year under the American Skandia and Prudential plans.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you start with a $100,000 portfolio and by the
second year its value has fallen to $95,000, your coverage
automatically will go up to $105,000. But your premium will be
based on $95,000.
</P>
<P>
   If, however, your portfolio has gone up to $110,000 at the end
of one year, your premium _ and your coverage _ will be based on
$110,000.
</P>
<P>
   The annual 5 percent step-ups continue until you reach age 80 or
until your minimum coverage is twice the initial investment _
$200,000 in this example _ whichever comes first.
</P>
<P>
   With the Sunamerica plan, the minimum coverage is stepped up by
only 4 percent annually _ also to a limit of twice the initial
investment. With this plan, too, the step-ups end when the
policyholder reaches age 80.
</P>
<P>
   In a normal year, the 4 and 5 percent annual step-ups won't help
much. That's because stock prices historically have appreciated by
an average of more than 9 percent per year, including dividends.
</P>
<P>
   So in an average year, a $100,000 portfolio would increase in
value to about $109,000. Boosting the basic coverage to $104,000 or
$105,000 wouldn't cover the full value of the portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   The Prudential and American Skandia plans have another potential
benefit: Once the value of your portfolio rises to a certain level,
your coverage can never go lower, no matter what happens to the
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if your original $100,000 investment shoots up to
$150,000 after one year, that becomes your minimum coverage for as
long as you continue your coverage, even if the value of your
portfolio later plunges. Any further gains also get locked in,
though you'll also pay a higher premium at renewal time.
</P>
<P>
   The step-up feature of the Prudential and American Skandia plans
lets you lock in huge portfolio gains, such as those enjoyed by
many stock-fund investors during the tremendous bull run of the
past four years.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of INSURE02 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The Sunamerica plan doesn't contain this extra protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do it because we felt it would be too confusing and
because we wanted to be able to provide coverage at a more
attractive cost,'' says a Sunamerica spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   If you find this kind of protection tempting, keep in mind that
this is basically disaster insurance and that the disaster may not
happen _ at least during your lifetime. In that case, you will have
squandered your premiums.
</P>
<P>
   People can never predict with certainty what the stock market
will do or where it will be on the day they die.
</P>
<P>
   The insurers don't know either, but their actuaries have sorted
through the historical evidence and calculated portfolio-protection
premiums that they think will profit the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did historical testing and believe that the pricing is
valid,'' says Michael Murray, vice president and national sales
manager of the American Skandia fund group.
</P>
<P>
   To put it another way, the insurance probably is overpriced for
most buyers.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to learn more about these plans, here are the
appropriate telephone numbers and Web sites:
</P>
<P>
   _American Skandia, (800) 752-6342,  &LR; www.americanskandia.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _Prudential, (800) 843-7625, Ext. 1205;  &LR; www.prudential.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _Sunamerica, (800) 858-8850, Ext. 5125;  &LR; www.sunamerica.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of INSURE02 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
