<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Sun Will Offer Chip Designs For Free  &HT;       
 By David Einstein 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Sun Microsystems will announce today that it is making the
blueprints for its microprocessors available to developers for free
over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The move _ a first for the semiconductor industry _ is designed
to spur an increase in the manufacturing of chips for new computers
and handheld consumer devices.
</P>
<P>
   Sun of Mountain View designs chips for its own workstations and
computer servers, as well as for devices like digital cameras.
</P>
<P>
   However, it does not manufacture them, relying instead on
outside sources such as Texas Instruments, IBM, NEC and Fujitsu.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, third-party manufacturers have had to pay Sun in
advance for the right to use and modify its technology. Under the
new arrangement, licensing fees will kick in only when a developer
takes a Sun-based product to market.
</P>
<P>
   Sun hopes that by not charging developers for access to its chip
designs, it will be better able to compete against MIPS and ARM,
which also design chips for small computing devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're MIPS or ARM, your business model is predicated on
getting money up front. But that kind of licensing has slowed the
market's growth,'' said Sun spokesman Russell Castronovo.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, ``there will be no risk to developers'
involvement. They can take a peek at the architecture without
making a commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   The new strategy is an extension of Sun's recent decision to
make its software technology available for free to developers.
</P>
<P>
   The company hopes this will promote the creation of new products
based on Sun's Solaris operating system and its Java and Jini
networking software.
</P>
<P>
   Sun said developers can register immediately for access to the
chip technology, which will be available for downloading in the
coming months.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 1 of SUN02 (67173 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
