<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCLUSIVE-COMMUNICATIONS-DEAL-469&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALCATEL SET TO ACQUIRE XYLAN FOR MORE THAN $1.7 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, France, U.K.)  (lh) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON and SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Expanding its presence in the computer networking market,
Alcatel of France, one of the world's biggest makers of telephone
equipment, has agreed to acquire Xylan Corp. for more than $1.7
billion in cash, executives close to the deal said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The companies intend to announce the agreement Tuesday, the
executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Xylan is a fast-growing maker of equipment for linking computers
in corporate and institutional networks and has been making inroads
into selling more complex gear to telephone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Alcatel, meanwhile, has been trying to expand beyond its roots
in traditional and wireless telephone systems and into the
blossoming data communications market. Acquiring Xylan would give
that effort a quick boost.
</P>
<P>
   The convergence of telephone and data technologies in recent
years has spurred an equally vigorous realignment among the
companies that make advanced communications equipment.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Lucent Technologies Inc., North America's biggest
maker of phone equipment, agreed to spend $20 billion to acquire
Ascend Communications Inc., a data networking player. And last
year, Northern Telecom of Canada acquired Bay Networks Inc. for
$9.1 billion. At the same time, Cisco Systems &UR;  &LR; Inc., the data
communications giant, has been trying to win business from the big
phone carriers that are Lucent's and Northern Telecom's traditional
customers.
</P>
<P>
   A deal between Alcatel and Xylan would be the second significant
acquisition in the communications equipment arena in two days.
Monday, General Electric of Britain said it had agreed to acquire
Reltec Corp. for about $1.7 billion in cash. General Electric of
Britain, which is not related to General Electric Co. of Fairfield,
Conn., is one of Britain's biggest manufacturing companies and is
looking to expand in the telecommunications equipment business.
</P>
<P>
   Reltec, based in Cleveland, makes products called digital loop
carriers, which expand the capacity of local telephone networks.
Reltec's shareholders, including Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co.,
which owns 81.5 percent of the company, would get $29.50 in cash
for each of their shares. General Electric of Britain would also
assume Reltec's debt of about $360 million.
</P>
<P>
   Kohlberg Kravis acquired control of Reltec for $475 million in
1995. The company initially offered stock to the public last year
at $29 and the shares rose as high as $49.125. But the company's
stock price suffered after it warned last year that its
third-quarter earnings would not meet analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Xylan's public shareholders are set to do better than Reltec's.
Xylan first offered stock to the public in 1996 for $26. Alcatel
has agreed to pay about $37 in cash for each share of Xylan,
executives close to the agreement said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Alcatel and Xylan declined to comment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Shares of Xylan rose 43.75 cents Monday, to $26.9375 in Nasdaq
trading. But there was a surge in demand Monday for Xylan call
options, which could become quite valuable after a deal is
announced. After failing to rise much above $20 since last
November, Xylan's shares have jumped by more than 30 percent since
Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   In acquiring Xylan, Alcatel would get more than technology. In
the data communications market a well-oiled sales force and strong
distribution channels can be as valuable as the latest hot product.
When Alcatel made its only previous significant data communications
acquisition, of Packet Engines Inc., a private company, last fall
for $315 million, that deal did not significantly enhance Alcatel's
sales force in the United States. But an acquisition of Xylan
would.
</P>
<P>
   Alcatel followed a similar strategy last June when it agreed to
acquire the DSC Communications Corp. for $4.4 billion. DSC was one
of Reltec's competitors in the business of selling digital network
gear to local phone companies. Alcatel acquired DSC largely to
inherit DSC's strong relationships with the U.S. local phone
giants.
</P>
<P>
   Alcatel is believed to have been advised by Lehman Brothers.
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, which was the lead manager for Xylan's
initial public offering, is believed to have advised Xylan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
