<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATTERNS: BADGLEY MISCHKA FILLS A VOID 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With all the sports-utility minimalism overrunning
fashion now, it should come as no surprise that there is an
unquenched thirst for dress-up daytime suits. Who, after all, is
thinking of the ladies who lunch? The omission has pushed Badgley
Mischka to add a daytime collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of sportswear designers didn't do a lot of suits this
year,'' James Mischka said. ``Everything was softer and about
putting different pieces together.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true. In an effort to stay au courant, pretty-suit
stalwarts like Oscar de la Renta, Bill Blass and Christian LaCroix
have been showing more youthful sporty mixes rather than tailored
suits.
</P>
<P>
   Like every Seventh Avenue designer, Mark Badgley and Mischka
know a void in the market when they see one. And they have filled
it beautifully: gray pinstripe suits with built-in curves and
feminine touches like gray ribbon on the sleeves; a demure, tweed
dress, and wool suits with opulent fur collars. Prices are $1,700
to $2,700. The clothes will be in stores, including Saks Fifth
Avenue and Neiman Marcus, in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're also trying to get a younger couture customer,'' Badgley
said, pointing to a white coat in double-face wool, tweed trousers
and black turtleneck. Several daytime dresses have evening-wear
counterparts and handbags to match. The handbag collection includes
a small tweed hobo bag with a jeweled butterfly about to take
flight, and a pouch, in burgundy velvet and jet, suspended from a
silver chain. The handbags cost $400 to $1,400.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very modern when the girl doesn't wear any
jewelry _ there's just the beaded gown, and the little bag is the
jewelry,'' Badgley said.
</P>
<P>
   LAUREN'S YOUTH MOVEMENT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The agreement announced on Monday by Polo Ralph Lauren to
purchase Club Monaco is not the only way the designer is going
after a young audience. Lauren is also about to court the newly
hot, hip and young customer (or the ``I know what you did last
summer'' audience) under his name.
</P>
<P>
   For fall, he will relaunch Ralph by Ralph Lauren, aimed at 16-
to 24-year-olds. If the name sounds familiar, it is because Ralph
by Ralph Lauren existed until last year as a hip bridge line. There
were several problems, though _ the first being that hip bridge is
an oxymoron. Second, when the bridge category _ essentially career
suits and jackets costing $300 to $800 _ began collapsing last
year, several brands, including Ralph, experienced difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than produce the collection under Polo Ralph Lauren, his
own company, as he did before, Lauren is relaunching Ralph as a
licensed collection under Jones New York. Jones has had remarkable
success with Lauren by Ralph Lauren, a less-expensive version of
Lauren's moneyed English style. The move is part of a wider
strategy by Jones, which also wants to reach a younger audience. A
few weeks ago, Jones purchased the Todd Oldham fashion business.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for Ralph will range from $19.50 for a top to $168 for a
jacket.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIAL ELEGANCE
</P>
<P>
   When women think about what to wear for the millennium, they are
not thinking about designers' visions of war and space-walking.
Millennial fashion is shaping up to mean sumptuous evening wear,
retailers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want to be dressed like space people,'' said Erin
Carmack, manager of fashion presentation for Neiman Marcus, which
has already seen an upturn in evening-wear business. ``It's taffeta
ball gowns _ the more elaborate, encrusted ball gowns that we
haven't seen in a while,'' she said, adding that Oscar de la Renta,
Badgley Mischka and Carmen Marc Valvo are going to be important
there.
</P>
<P>
   Women are buying for the at-home party and the over-the-top
gala, said Kenneth E. Downing, vice president of corporate public
relations for Neiman's. ``There's going to be a huge buildup to
it,'' he said. ``It's much more than one day.''
</P>
<P>
   At Saks, Badgley Mischka and Ralph Lauren are at the forefront.
``We feel it's an even more important category than it normally
would be,'' a spokeswoman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
