<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3731 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMBODIA-CRIMES-NYT &LR;      03-01 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-CRIMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. PANEL CALLS FOR INTERNATIONAL TRIBUNAL TO TRY TOP KHMER ROUGE
OFFICIALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A U.N. panel has recommended that a new
international tribunal be convened to try about a dozen senior
Khmer Rouge officials on charges of crimes against humanity while
they ruled Cambodia, according to diplomats and senior
administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   Under the recommendation, a separate Cambodian truth commission
would consider all other cases.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sign of the growing tensions between China and the
United States, the Chinese have told administration officials who
are actively lobbying for a tribunal that Beijing will veto the
idea if it is brought before the U.N. Security Council, these
officials said. The Khmer Rouge relied almost exclusively on
Chinese support during their reign that led to the deaths of nearly
two million Cambodians from 1975 to 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``China has always emphasized it defers to the domestic decision
of Cambodia,'' said a senior Clinton administration official who
spoke on condition of anonymity. ``The only way the Chinese will
not veto this is if the Cambodian government goes to the U.N.
Security Council and asks for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The recommendation for a tribunal was given to the Cambodian
prime minister, Hun Sen, last week, but will not officially be made
public for several weeks, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In contradictory statements over the last two months, Hun Sen
has alternatively complained that the world is at least a decade
late in condemning the Khmer Rouge, has given half-hearted support
for an international tribunal, and has questioned whether a trial
would lead to new violence.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Hun Sen has grown closer to China, signing
five new agreements in Beijing last month that provide Cambodia
with increased trade and economic benefits. Meanwhile, Foreign
Minister Tang Jiaxuan of China said last month in Bangkok that
Western nations, especially the United States, had come up with the
idea of trying the Khmer Rouge, which he said was inappropriate
since ``these are internal problems of Cambodia'' and should be
decided only by the Cambodians.
</P>
<P>
   ``China has outmaneuvered the United States once again,'' said
Stephen R. Heder, a Cambodia scholar at the School of Oriental and
African Studies in London. ``It's highly unlikely that Hun Sen can
be turned around. He's been prepared to have a trial or not have a
trial depending on the highest bid, and China and its friends are
willing to give him economic benefits, security guarantees and
general diplomatic support that the United States can't offer.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, however, does contain a way to circumvent a
possible Chinese veto. The proposed International Criminal Tribunal
for Cambodia could be put before the U.N. General Assembly for a
vote should it be blocked in the Security Council. But the five
permanent members of the Security Council, including the United
States, are wary of setting such a precedent.
</P>
<P>
   Written by three outside experts, the proposal for a Cambodia
tribunal includes innovations based on the experiences in
Yugoslavia, Rwanda and South Africa, among other countries,
according to officials. To set up the tribunal quickly and to save
money, the offices of the tribunal for the former Yugoslavia and
Rwanda would be used. The trial of the top dozen or more officials
would be held outside Cambodia, either at the Hague, in Manila or
in Canberra.
</P>
<P>
   The truth commission, which was the idea of Thomas Hammaberg,
the U.N. secretary general's special representative on human rights
in Cambodia, would be established in Cambodia and would allow
Cambodians to have a full airing of what went on in one of this
century's worst cases of mass murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good balance of the twin imperatives of justice and
national reconciliation,`` said Craig Etcheson, program director of
The International Monitor Institute and the former head of the
Cambodian Documentation Center. ``You establish a record through
the tribunal and at the same time you allow Cambodians to feel that
their suffering has been acknowledged and to find their way to
reach social reconciliation within their community.``
</P>
<P>
   Hun Sen also said he is reticent about approving a tribunal
because world powers ignored his requests for nearly two decades to
set up a Khmer Rouge trial, waiting until it suited the timetable
of other countries.
</P>
<P>
   From 1979 to 1991, Cambodia was hostage to the Asian cold war,
and the United States, among other countries, would not officially
acknowledge that the Khmer Rouge had committed mass killings for
fear of upsetting China. Thereafter, the Khmer Rouge signed a peace
treaty with the other warring parties in the Cambodian civil war,
and other countries were reluctant to upset Cambodia's delicate
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   It was only in 1997 that a real push began, stimulated in part
by Hun Sen and his then co-prime minister, Prince Norodom
Ranariddh. They petitioned the secretary general that June asking
``for the assistance of the United Nations and the international
community in bringing to justice those persons responsible for the
genocide and crimes against humanity during the rule of the Khmer
Rouge from 1975 to 1979.''
</P>
<P>
   Pointing out that Cambodia did not have the ``resources or the
expertise'' to conduct a trial on its own, Hun Sen argued in this
letter that ``only in this way can this tragedy be brought to a
full and final conclusion.``
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, however, Hun Sen overthrew Ranariddh and his
ardor for a trial has cooled ever since.
</P>
<P>
   There is little dispute over which Khmer Rouge leaders should be
tried and whether there is sufficient evidence to convict them. At
the top of the list is Nuon Chea, second to Pol Pot, the head of
the regime, followed by Ta Mok and Khieu Samphan. Nuon Chea and
Khieu Samphan turned themselves in to Hun Sen's government last
December and are living in a western Cambodian city with other
Khmer Rouge defectors. Ta Mok is at large in the jungles of western
Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence against the Khmer Rouge has been growing since
their government was overthrown in 1979 and has been collected
through the Cambodia Documentation Center under a grant from the
State Department in cooperation with Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   While Secretary General Kofi Annan has yet to read the proposal,
senior U.N. officials say he is worried about the precedent set by
the arrest in Great Britain of Gen. Augusto Pinochet, the former
Chilean dictator.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secretary general is listening to the Pinochet argument
that it is better to bury the mistakes of the past,`` said one
senior U.N. official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
