<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CREDIT CARD CONSOLIDATION HOLDS SOME SURPRISES
</P>
<P>
   Tens of millions of Americans have been surprised to find their
credit card rates rising after their accounts are sold to other
banks as the business rapidly consolidates into fewer and larger
hands.
</P>
<P>
   The new owners of credit card business are free to impose
whatever interest rate the traffic will bear, subject only to the
handful of remaining state usury ceilings. They can also impose
that rate on existing balances, shorten the time for making
payments without interest charges, eliminate grace periods for
payments received a few days late and raise penalties for late
payment.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBLIC NEW YORK TO CUT 560 JOBS
</P>
<P>
   Republic New York, battered late last year by losses in volatile
overseas markets, said that it planned to cut about 560 jobs as
part of a broader reorganization aimed at refocusing the bank on
global private banking and other niche businesses.
</P>
<P>
   FORD HIRES RIVAL EXECUTIVES
</P>
<P>
   Two senior executives from DaimlerChrysler joined Ford Motor,
the latest in a series of departures of executives from the former
Chrysler Corp. since its November merger with Daimler-Benz.
</P>
<P>
   REIT TO CHANGE ITS STRUCTURE
</P>
<P>
   Patriot American Hospitality said that it had agreed to a
financial bailout plan led by the investors Leon Black and Thomas
Lee, that its chairman and chief executive had resigned and that it
would convert from a real estate investment trust into a
traditional corporation. The new chairman and chief executive will
be James D. Carreker, above, who oversees Patriot's hotel
operations and developed its Wyndham chain.
</P>
<P>
   UNITY ON RUSSIAN DEBT FRAYS
</P>
<P>
   The unity of a key group of Western banks holding $15 billion in
defaulted, short-term Russian debt frayed after two of its members
broke ranks to accept a Russian repayment package regarded as
nearly worthless.
</P>
<P>
   RALPH LAUREN TO BUY CLUB MONACO
</P>
<P>
   Polo Ralph Lauren, the retail company, said it would acquire
Club Monaco, a Canadian-based retailer that sells designer
look-alike casual apparel, for $52.5 million in cash, an 18 percent
premium to Club Monaco's closing price on Friday. Shares of Polo
Ralph Lauren declined 43.75 cents, to $19.50.
</P>
</TEXT>
