<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3736 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILAN-FASHION-ART-NYT     03-01 1358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILAN-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PACE IS FEROCIOUS, AND LOGIC ELUSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(ms) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy _ In this aristocratic old city where fortunes have
been made from mere cloth, just about all the Milanese have fashion
on their minds, if not necessarily on their backs.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, what one hears as the Italian collections for fall
enter their third day, with an excruciatingly pretentious show at
Prada, is that fashion is spinning faster and faster toward a kind
of meaninglessness. It is not just the ferocious pace of change _
this season that all-important shoe, next season another one _ that
brings fashion perpetually to a dead stop in its own tracks. It's
that by being arcane and overly self-referential, it has pushed
itself into the margins of most people's lives.
</P>
<P>
   Five or 10 years ago, a designer could show a woman a new
proportion, a better fabric, and she could understand that _ even
approve of it _ because it brought honest change into her life. But
who could understand the logic of wearing, as Miuccia Prada
suggested on Monday, a squashed-toed, high-heeled shoe that made
even her models look deformed, as if they were walking pigeon-toed
on chewing gum?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the edge of fashion as we know it being really out of
fashion,'' said Tom Ford, whose show for Gucci is on Tuesday.
``Most women I know _ and this is a horrible thing to say as a
designer _ do not wear current clothing. They wear some amazing
thing they found in a flea market, maybe something from last
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Ford is one designer who has kept pushing things to
the uppermost limit, and he knows that. ``Fashion has become so
hyped, so big, and everything, as we know, has become so
homogenized and globalized, which we're partly to blame for,'' he
said over the weekend. ``But, now, in order to keep fashion alive,
things need to seem individual. Each piece in a collection needs to
have enough character of its own.''
</P>
<P>
   That's precisely the problem, Giorgio Armani said on Monday
morning before his streamlined Emporio show. ``Today, you can have
a style that is exalted in the press, but which is very different
from the reality of what people actually buy,'' said Armani, who
among high-fashion designers is one of the top two or three money
makers at retail. It irritates him that the fashion press seems to
get increasingly behind a single viewpoint. ``They say, `No
jewelry! No stockings!''' Armani added, looking nonplused. ``Why,
why? In the end, you will have nothing left. It's a snobbism that's
ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Milan shows have hit a kind of snag. Armani finessed all
that business about what's new by presenting a tightly edited
Emporio collection of sportswear separates _ slim trousers in nylon
or padded and quilted fabrics; shearling coats and parkas; layers
of hooded tops and cotton fleece; touches of sharp color, like a
peak of an electric-blue layer against charcoal. As a collection
with a lot of utility overtones, it wasn't earth-shattering, but it
was had a lot of polish, and Armani's models seemed to actually
enjoy wearing the clothes.
</P>
<P>
   And Prada? After several years of tremendous influence, Prada
now seems in danger of becoming a parody of itself. Many of Ms.
Prada's clothes were beautiful _ an olive-green suede jacket, for
instance, with leaf appliques, and a rustic-looking toggle coat in
a sage twill wool with appliques in leather. Some of her
hide-and-fur coats were intriguing as well, particularly a long
black belted fur coat with padded nylon sleeves unzipped at the
shoulders. But that's as far as one's patience stretched as Miss
Prada buckled long transparent coats with arty grommets over
leggings and bikini briefs. The torpor of it all.
</P>
<P>
   Narciso Rodriguez didn't have many ideas _ sculptured wool
sheaths, a fitted sleeveless top with a glaze of beading, a tunic
with slim trousers _ but they were all on the money. He translated
his mix of black and nude hues right down to his stilettos. But it
was his layering of a sleeveless fur top over a crinkly tunic and
taupe trousers that summed up his modern verve.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Lenny Kravitz was in town for Donatella Versace's
Versus show on Sunday, and the late-night birthday party she gave
afterward for Ingrid Sischy of Interview magazine, did nothing to
slow the frenetic pace. But Milan seems to like a frenzy, or at
least to accept it. On Saturday, the usual promenade of
well-dressed Milanese along the Via Montenapoleone, where the
fashionable stores are, reached such a crush that the police had to
keep cars out.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview before the Versus show, Ms. Versace said she was
taking a different approach with her secondary line: ``Before, it
was much younger and, in a way, much cheaper, in fabrics. What
really counts now is quality and distinction.'' Like Ford, she
favors a mix of items that a customer can adapt to her personality.
``I think of the Versus girl as someone who walks around changing
the channels of a radio,'' Ms. Versace said. ``A little
rock-and-roll, a little something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Versace's show was a tour de something, all right. It had a
tough, sharp sex appeal that wasn't vulgar _ unless you count a
sprinkle of glitter up the back seam of a pair of trousers. There
was a wink here to asymmetrical hemlines and a nod there to a
silhouette based on having something wrapped around the waist, like
a jacket. Ms. Versace veiled electric colors with black chiffon,
and casually mixed them with sequined skirts, lace-cut leather, and
photo-transfer prints. She made everything look easy without
forsaking her glam edge. Some slick cosmetic pink coats told that
story.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the stuff one sees at secondary shows is too
marginal, too hopelessly derivative for fashion editors to care one
way or the other. They're waiting for the big shows, Armani, Gucci
and so on, to give the collections tone, to create a kind of
glorified hook that everyone can hang on to and go swinging into
fall with. Bohemian glamour. Post-modern mayhem chic. They're
almost in cahoots in that way. In the meantime, one must go and see
what Domenico Dolce and Stefano Gabbana have cooked up at D &AMP; G,
and Gianfranco Ferre at GFF.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from some obi-like belts and white shirts, which are a
signature, Ferre seemed to have as much contact with this GFF
collection as vermouth passing over vodka. Which is to say it
appeared to be designed by young assistants, who apparently were
under the impression that nobody in this crowd had ever seen a Rei
Kawakubo or Yohji Yamamoto show. The cuts and proportions looked
very Japanese, as they say, from the high-waisted kimono coats in
rustic colors to uneven hemlines and some exquisitely hokey dresses
in white gazar furrowed with piano wire.
</P>
<P>
   To what end? Ferre is too solid a Milanese designer to get hung
up with this kind of karaoke couture, and as for the idea of taking
a plain jersey dress and attaching hanks of papery white fabric
along the seams _ well, don't ask. It brought to mind the agony of
seeing a gorgeous woman with a piece of Kleenex stuck to her heel.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone other than a fashion editor would probably look at the D
&AMP; G show and run screaming into the Sunday traffic. It was as if
Messrs. Gabbana and Dolce were literally dressing dolls. There were
rosebud printed tops in cotton underwear jersey, leopard boots and
aqua blue tights with butterflies on them, fuzzy minis in
rubber-duck yellow, a diaper pin holding closed a frumpy cardigan,
teddy bear appliques _ the whole thing thrown together with the
gleeful fury of a rotten little girl right before she decides to
set Barbie on fire.
</P>
<P>
   But it was fun. The designers caught the spirit, if not the
mentality, of young customers. They also made marvelous use of
denim, creating skirts and trousers with flies and pockets at both
the waist and hem, so that if a girl felt like walking on her
hands, her skirt, at least, would still be upright.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-99 2112EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
