<DOCNO> NYT19990301.0407 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3738 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UTILITY-BILL-COX     03-01 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTILITY-BILL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas plan would have customers foot bill for cleaner air
 &HT;    By Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas electric utility customers would get
cleaner air and get to pay for it, too _ as much as $1.4 billion _
under a proposal announced Monday by Sen. David Sibley, R-Waco, and
endorsed by Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Under Sibley's proposal, electric utilities that voluntarily add
pollution equipment could pass the
</P>
<P>
   costs of doing so along to customers.
</P>
<P>
   If enacted into law, the proposal could help areas that violate
federal clean air standards and those _ such as Austin _ near
violation from having to take such steps as limiting the expansion
of businesses in order to prevent more pollution problems.
</P>
<P>
   At most, Sibley said, the proposal would cost ratepayers less
than $1 a month, and could be as little 50 cents a month, depending
on the utility. To achieve the same reduction in pollution through
stricter automobile pollution controls, Sibley said, would cost
three times as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have an opportunity here, in a very cost effective
manner, to take some really
</P>
<P>
   significant strides in reducing the (pollution) emissions in the
state of Texas,'' Sibley said
</P>
<P>
   after a meeting of the Special Senate Committee on Electric
Utility Restructuring, which is
</P>
<P>
   considering opening the electric industry up to competition.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Bush said Sibley's proposal ``builds on the
early successes of our voluntary
</P>
<P>
   program to reduce emissions in Texas, and I hope legislators
will join me in strongly supporting
</P>
<P>
   it.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Austin area would benefit generally from cleaner air,
the proposal would not apply to Austin Energy and other city-owned
electric utilities because they are governed by their own
</P>
<P>
   city councils, not state government.
</P>
<P>
   Austin already has volunteered to meet the federal clean air
standards for the four units at
</P>
<P>
   Holly Power Plant and one at Decker Power Plant that are
``grandfathered'' from compliance because of their age.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do like this'' it's a real good deal,'' said
</P>
<P>
   Tom Smith, Texas director of Public Citizen, a public interest
group, founded by consumer activist Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Environmental Defense Fund said the
organization wanted more details before
</P>
<P>
   commenting on the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Sibley said he would provide details within a week as an
amendment to his bill to deregulate the
</P>
<P>
   electric utility industry.
</P>
<P>
   Sibley's proposal grew out of a recent joint report by the Texas
Natural Resource Conservation
</P>
<P>
   Commission and the Public Utility Commission of Texas, which
jointly studied the cost of upgrading the pollution equipment on
Texas power plants, including those grandfathered from the state's
permit program, which took effect in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   The commissions, whose analysis included 162 power plant units,
concluded it would cost about
</P>
<P>
   $1.4 billion to upgrade both those that had been grandfathered
and those in non-attainment and near
</P>
<P>
   non-attainment areas to reduce nitrogen oxides, a key component
in forming ground-level ozone, by
</P>
<P>
   about 70 percent. Ozone is a health hazard.
</P>
<P>
   The cost to the consumer would be about 82 cents a month for 10
years to retire the debt, the commissions estimated.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal figures into the deregulation bill because Sibley
would add the $1.4 billion to the
</P>
<P>
   so-called ``stranded costs'' that the utilities would collect
from ratepayers for plants that cost
</P>
<P>
   more to build than they would be worth in a competitive market.
Sibley's bill would allow the utilities to collect all those
stranded costs, now estimated at about $3.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Also, environmentalists have warned that competition could
encourage utilities to make heavier use of grandfathered plants
unencumbered by expensive pollution equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The utility would have to show that adding the pollution
equipment to an existing plant was better financially than simply
building a new plant, said Pat Wood, chairman of the utility
commission.
</P>
<P>
   Hight writes for the American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
