<SLUG> BC-BY-DESIGN-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY DESIGN: STAYING UNDER WRAPS
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy _ Scientists say the polar icecap is melting, but
designers on both sides of the Atlantic are under the impression
that next winter will be cold and blustery. At least it seems so
because they are showing styles that swathe the throat in toasty
warm fabric.
</P>
<P>
   Most coats and jackets come with turtlenecks or funnel necklines
high enough to cover the chin. Cowls on knitwear are so generous
they can be pulled over the head, like the original monks' cowls.
Anything collarless is shown with a scarf or muffler wound closely
around the neck.
</P>
<P>
   Even the bareness of strapless evening dresses is often balanced
by a woolly scarf, usually in wool or cashmere that matches the
dress but sometimes in a gutsier weight. Perhaps designers have
been inspired by the way women have made their own fashion
statements this winter, wrapping themselves in pashmina mufflers,
for both day and evening. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-99 2116EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
