<DOCNO> NYT19990301.0411 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3752 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GIANTS-COLLINS-NY     03-01 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-COLLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLINS HANDLES MEDIA BLITZ IN FIRST GIANTS APPEARANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Kerry Collins made his first public
appearance at Giants Stadium on Monday, a 15-minute,
stand-in-the-pocket performance that had the new Giants quarterback
earnestly answering questions about his drinking habits, his
passion for football, accusations that he once used a racial slur
and how he felt being the highest-paid backup in the National
Football League.
</P>
<P>
   It was a full docket for a debut. Although Collins did not
revisit a troubled past with relish, in his responses he did more
than backpedal and, in the end, it appeared he survived a
pressuring rush his first time out.
</P>
<P>
   By noon, Collins was off to find a New Jersey apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, who signed a four-year, $16.9-million contract last
month explained how he had convinced the Giants' management that he
was worth the risk, despite two declining seasons that included
many off-the-field woes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I'm tired of the negative perception of my life,''
Collins said. ``There have been some issues I've had to address,
stuff I've been carrying around for a long time, and I've taken the
steps to address them. They are things I'm still working on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy to take a long, hard look at yourself. But I'm
more comfortable now than I have been before.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to be more specific about what he learned in his
self-examination, Collins was forthright on two subjects, less so
on most others.
</P>
<P>
   ``My alcohol use is the thing that is brought up most often and
it's something that I looked at, along with other things,''
Collins, who was arrested for driving under the influence last
year, said. ``I feel alcohol may have played too much of a role in
my life. I feel that alcohol played a role in some of the problems
that have surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been evaluated and the doctors did not diagnose me as
an alcoholic. But my goal is to be the best quarterback I can be,
and alcohol plays no part in that. Alcohol is not going to play any
role in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to tell his side of the story in a 1997 incident when two
of his Carolina Panthers teammates accused Collins of using a
racial slur at a training party, Collins said it was something in
his past that he did not want to elaborate on.
</P>
<P>
   But Collins added: ``To my dying day I'll deny that I'm a
racist. People who know me know how I feel about things and know
the kind of person I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his fateful meeting with Carolina Coach Dom Capers
last October, the meeting that led to his release by the Panthers,
Collins essentially had no comment. Capers' version has been that
Collins said he no longer had the heart or desire to lead the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been enough said about that,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier on Monday, Giants Coach Jim Fassel said he had talked to
everyone involved in that episode and it did not prevent him from
supporting the Giants' decision to sign Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what happened,'' Fassel said. ``I'm comfortable with
all that.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Collins said that despite a contract that makes him the
highest-paid Giant in average annual salary by nearly $1 million,
he understood that he was the backup to the starting quarterback
Kent Graham.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was made clear to me from the first meeting with the Giants
that Kent was starting,'' Collins said. ``Everybody wants to play
but I realize there's a long road ahead of me. I've got a lot to
improve. That's where my focus is. I have to get better and see
what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham, who led the Giants to a5-1 finish last season when he
replaced Danny Kanell, was angry and shocked last month when he
heard the Giants had signed Collins. Monday, Graham said he met
with Collins in the Giants' locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is fine between us,'' Graham said. ``I've let my
feelings be known but it's time to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   As with other Giants, Graham said Collins' problems in Carolina
should not affect his welcome with his new teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'll have a fresh start,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 training camp incident sparked racial tensions in the
Panthers' locker room, but Charles Way, Sam Garnes and Ike
Hilliard, three black players on the Giants, said on Monday that
they did not believe Collins would be greeted coolly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard from guys who played with him down there that he's
not that kind of person,'' Way said. ``Everybody makes mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Garnes said: ``I don't have a problem with him. I'll judge him
for myself. I'm from the Bronx. I feel like I can look at somebody
and tell if they have evil thoughts in their head. I didn't feel
that way when I met Kerry.''
</P>
<P>
   Hilliard said: ``Kerry doesn't have to answer any questions from
me. He's here now and he's one of my teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins, who was advised by the Giants not to talk to reporters
for 10 days after his signing, did not linger on Monday in his new
workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things going on in my personal life took away from football,''
Collins said. ``I want to change that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-99 2122EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
