<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3753 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-REPORT-2TAKES-NYT     03-01 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-REPORT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL HEADED BY EX-SENATOR PROPOSES NUMEROUS REFORMS IN OLYMPIC
LEADERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
 (fe) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Citing a ``culture of improper gift-giving'' that has enveloped
the Olympic movement, a United States Olympic Committee commission
recommended a menu of reform on Monday that ranged from
democratizing the election of International Olympic Committee
members to public disclosure of its finances.
</P>
<P>
   The five-member panel, formed in December after revelations of
cash payments and gift-giving by Salt Lake organizers to IOC
members, concluded that the Games had suffered significant damage
and that their survival depended in part on the willingness to
adopt some of the reforms.
</P>
<P>
   In one of its strongest recommendations, the panel, chaired by
the former U.S. Sen. George Mitchell, called on President Clinton
to declare the IOC a ``public international organization'' and thus
make bribing its officials punishable under the Foreign Corrupt
Practices Act.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also concluded that the U.S. Olympic Committee had
done virtually nothing in its role of overseeing the Salt Lake bid
and recommended instituting strict rules governing the committee's
responsibilities, including an independent compliance committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Olympic movement has been badly damaged by the
revelations to date,'' Mitchell said, ``and while I don't believe
the damage is irreparable, it could have adverse implications if
they don't undergo meaningful reform.''
</P>
<P>
   The report by Mitchell, a Democrat from Maine, who was majority
leader of the U.S. Senate, was released 16 days before a special
IOC session in Lausanne, Switzerland, that was called for a vote on
an in-house investigation's recommendations to expel members and
reform some of its operations.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Pound, the IOC vice president who was chairman of his
organization's investigation, said: ``If this is what we have to do
to prevent this situation from happening again, then we'll look at
it. We're looking at everything we can do to reform this process.''
</P>
<P>
   Pound said he expected to release by the end of the week the
number of additional IOC members the investigative panel will
recommend for expulsion at the meeting. On Jan. 24, he recommended
six expulsions but still had three more to investigate. In
addition, 10 more members who were named by the Salt Lake
Organizing Committee's ethics panel are also under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working toward a consensus,'' Pound said. Of the 10 new
names cited by the Salt Lake Olympic Committee panel, Pound's panel
has spoken to three members in person and two more by phone and
received letters from the rest defending their actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to stop the bleeding by March 17,'' he said. ``Death
by a thousand cuts isn't much fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mitchell commission said the IOC's secretiveness and lack of
accountability fostered the Salt Lake committee's belief that only
financial largess would guarantee its ability to host the 2002
Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not excuse or condone those from Salt Lake City who did
the giving,'' Mitchell said. ``What they did was wrong. But, as we
noted, they did not invent this culture; they joined one that was
already flourishing.''
</P>
<P>
   The report said that the IOC missed a golden opportunity to
initiate reform eight years ago when the organizers of Toronto's
failed bid to host the 1996 Summer Games offered evidence of
financial abuses by IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   The Mitchell report described as ``prophetic'' a warning by the
Toronto group that visits by IOC members to bid cities are
precisely where ``the IOC runs the greatest risk of its image being
tarnished and its integrity eroded.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's commission came down harder on the IOC, recommending
a broad restructuring of the Swiss-based organization, than on the
U.S.O.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have an organization that is unaccountable,
secretive, self-perpetuating and oligarchical, you have created the
occasion for possible abuse,'' said Richard Hibey, counsel to the
commission.
</P>
<P>
   As the Pound investigation attempts to wrap up its work by March
17, one Olympic official who demanded anonymity said a part of the
IOC's defense of some of its accused members will be that Salt Lake
officials were so persistent in offering gratuities that there was
no choice but to accept.
</P>
<P>
   Willingly or not, the IOC members were part of a highly
organized gift-giving campaign that the Mitchell commission
believes was widely known to the trustees and executive committee
members of the Salt Lake bid and organizing committees. An
independent Salt Lake ethics panel investigation pointed fingers at
Thomas Welch, the former president of the Salt Lake Olympic
Committee, and David Johnson, a former senior vice president, as
the officials primarily responsible for the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mitchell commission called that conclusion into
question. ``It strains credulity,'' the report said, ``to believe
that so many responsible citizens could participate in such a long
and highly public campaign to influence IOC members and spend so
much money in the process but that only Messrs. Welch and Johnson
were aware of the improprieties surrounding these activities.''
</P>
<P>
   The other members of the commission were Donald Fehr, executive
director of the major league baseball players union; Roberta Cooper
Ramo, former president of the American Bar Association; Kenneth
Duberstein, President Ronald Reagan's former chief of staff, and
Jeffrey Benz, a lawyer and a former member of the U.S. figure
skating team. The commission relied mainly on documents to prepare
the report; it interviewed 11 witnesses, but many key players
refused to testify on advice of their lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   In its litany of reforms, the Mitchell commission sought to
eliminate the possibility that the missteps of the Salt Lake
officials could be repeated. Although its suggestions are
nonbinding, its recommendations for the IOC included these:
</P>
<P>
   _ Subjecting members to term limits, periodic re-election and
conflict-of-interest policies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Broadening the membership of the IOC with more public sector
members and more members elected by their national Olympic
committees or athletic federations.
</P>
<P>
   _ Opening meetings to the public whenever possible and requiring
an independent auditor to disclose its annual financial statements.
</P>
<P>
   _ Requiring that all IOC members' visits to Olympic bid cities
be paid for by the IOC or the member, and prohibiting candidate
cities from paying for IOC members' travel or accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   The commission also suggested specific reforms for the USOC,
including these:
</P>
<P>
   _ Barring cities from spending money on IOC members or any
international organizations from the time they are competing to be
the U.S. candidate city for the Olympics to the time they are the
organizing committee for the Olympcs and for two years after the
organizing committee work is completed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prohibiting any candidate cities from using grant money from
the USOC's international assistance fund, as the Salt Lake
committee did.
</P>
<P>
   _ Creating an office of bid compliance, to oversee the bidding
processes for potential candidate cities.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Olympic Committee is expected to respond to the report
on Wednesday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as the IOC investigates improprieties in past Olympic
bids, Billy Payne, the former head of the 1996 Atlanta Summer
Olympics, insisted in a letter dated last Friday and released on
Monday that ``we are unaware of any action on the part of the IOC
members or on the part of the Atlanta Organizing Committee that
cast doubt on the integrity of the bidding process.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne admitted that while some gifts to IOC members exceeded the
$200 limit for candidate cities, ``they were within the range of
customary exchanges during that competition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-99 2123EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990301.0414 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3755 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXCLUSIVE-URANIUM-WAS     03-01 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCLUSIVE-URANIUM-WASTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. PLANS TO BUILD PLANTS TO PROCESS TONS OF URANIUM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Ky.)  (sw) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Energy Department plans to announce this week
that it wants to build two plants, at a cost of nearly $200 million
each, that will gradually turn 1.5 billion pounds of depleted
uranium into marketable products or waste that can be safely
stored.
</P>
<P>
   The uranium is now stored in canisters that can leak and give
off toxic gas. The plants would process the uranium in a way that
officials hope could help pay for itself.
</P>
<P>
   The uranium, which is not highly radioactive, could be converted
into a form useful for wrapping highly radioactive substances like
reactor waste. The fluorine with which it is mixed could be sold
for industrial use in petrochemicals, glass etching or steel
processing, among others.
</P>
<P>
   The government spends millions of dollars a year to scrape and
paint the canisters in a losing battle against rust.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best thing that's happened in ages,'' said Donna
Goodman, a hazardous waste inspector with the Ohio Environmental
Protection Agency and one of a small group of specialists who have
been campaigning for better handling of the waste, leftovers of
production of uranium for nuclear power and for bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the waste dates from the Manhattan Project, the secret
World War II program to develop the atomic bomb, in the early
1940s. Some of the canisters, in fact, carry the Manhattan
Project's initials.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Goodman and others noted that it was not clear where the
money to operate the factories, estimated at $50 million or more a
year, would come from.
</P>
<P>
   Under a law passed last year, the federal government is holding
about $373 million for the factories. It is asking private
companies for their proposals to use the money to build them.
</P>
<P>
   The money was paid over the last few years by customers of
plants that were then owned by the government and that process
uranium for use in nuclear reactors, sorting out the type that
splits easily, uranium 235. In addition, after the government sold
those plants in a public stock offering last year, the new private
entity that manages them, the United States Enrichment Corp., paid
another $66 million to the government to handle the waste produced
after privatization.
</P>
<P>
   The ``depleted'' uranium that remains after most of the uranium
235 has been removed is almost entirely uranium 238, a material
that is mildly radioactive and toxic; it is mixed with fluorine, a
chemical that forms a compound with uranium that can be turned to
gas for processing. But the compound, solid at room temperature,
gives off a toxic cloud when it contacts water.
</P>
<P>
   Experts hope that private companies will propose using the $373
million to build factories that will whittle away at the inventory
over 20 to 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very interested to see what industry does propose,'' an
Energy Department official said. ``We're looking for industry to
give us ideas and input.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., who sponsored the law setting aside
the $373 million, said on Monday in a statement that he was
``encouraged that the Department of Energy has taken a first step
in soliciting industry interest to begin cleanup'' at two uranium
enrichment plants in Paducah, Ky., and Portsmouth, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   But McConnell said that Congress was still waiting for the
Energy Department ``to come forward with a detailed legislative and
budgetary proposal to solve this environmental nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, the Energy Department has avoided doing anything with
the waste by declaring that it was not waste at all, but assets,
despite the fact that there was no market for the material in its
current form.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only an asset if you change it to something else,'' said
one Senate aide with experience in the issue. ``Right now it's
hardly what we'd consider an asset, but we're going to make the
most of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials are eager to pay for at least part of the operating
costs by selling recovered materials. They point out that depleted
uranium is about 30 percent more dense than lead, and very good for
shielding highly radioactive materials like spent nuclear fuel,
even if the uranium itself is slightly radioactive.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Starmet, of Concord, Mass., has a plan to use
pellets of depleted uranium in place of the pebbles used to
strengthen concrete; the product, which it calls Ducrete, blocks
radiation three to four times better than the same thickness of
concrete, according to Donald T. King, manager of sales and
contracts at the company.
</P>
<P>
   But the uranium would have to be ``close to free'' to make the
product competitive in the marketplace, King said. He said that the
Energy Department might be willing to give the uranium away to be
free of storing it.
</P>
<P>
   The fluorine, on the other hand, could be worth hundreds of
millions of dollars. It makes up about a third of the inventory of
700,000 metric tons (about 1.5 billion pounds) and sells for up to
$1,500 a metric ton in some chemical forms.
</P>
<P>
   King said his company, which works with uranium-fluorine
compounds at the Energy Department's Savannah River Site near
Aiken, S.C., was already carrying out ``fluorine mining'' on a
laboratory scale and was working toward building a pilot-scale
plant.
</P>
<P>
   The department's announcement will ask companies like Starmet
what they would build, what chemical form the uranium and the
fluorine would take and how they would market the materials.
</P>
<P>
   But even the most optimistic experts believe that sales would
merely help offset operating costs, not cover them.
</P>
<P>
   One consultant who has worked on the matter and spoke on the
condition of anonymity said operating costs were a big problem.
``To say it's `not clear,''' the consultant said, ``is understating
it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
