   (NYT7) MOUNT VERNON, N.Y. -- March 01, 1999 --
SCI-AIDS-BLACKS-1, 3-01 -- The Rev. Franklyn Richardson, senior
pastor of the Grace Baptist Church in Mount Vernon, says families
in his congregation thank him for discussing AIDS. ``We want people
to understand that AIDS is not a sin, but a disease,'' he says.
``And like any disease, we want to talk about how to prevent it.
That is where sex education begins.'' (James Estrin/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- March 01, 1999 -- SCI-EARLIER-SPRINGS, 3-01
-- Botanists at research gardens have documented buds are appearing
earlier and leaves are falling later in the Northern Hemisphere.
This 11-day lengthening of the growing season was caused by warmer
temperatures, concluded the researchers, Dr. Annette Menzel, a
specialist in the study of forests, and Dr. Peter Fabian, who
specializes in climate, meteorology and forests. Their report
appears in the current issue of Nature. (Stephen Crowley/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) LOMA LINDA, Calif. -- March 01, 1999 --
SCI-SMOKING-CESSATION-2, 3-01 -- Dr. Linda Ferry of the Veterans
Affairs Medical Center works with a patient using smoking cessation
techniques. Dr. Ferry has used the anti-depression drug bupropion
to treat nicotine addiction. A new approach combining bupropion,
nicotine replacement and counseling, is sharply increasing the
chance of success among people who are trying to give up smoking.
(Michael Tweed/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) PALO ALTO, Calif. -- March 01, 1999 --
SCI-SMOKING-CESSATION, 3-01 -- Dr. David Sachs, director of the
Palo Alto Center for Pulmonary Disease Prevention, at the Smoking
Cessation Research Institute. Sachs is supportive of a new approach
combining bupropion, an antidepressant; nicotine replacement and
counseling in sharply increasing the chance of success among people
who are trying to give up smoking. (Darcy Padilla/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- March 01 1999 -- SCI-LOWCOST-ROCKETS, 3-01 --
Testing of the X-33, a prototype for the eventual successor to the
space shuttle, seen in this artist's rendering, is now more than a
year behind schedule due to technical problems. As wide as it is
tall, the low-cost, re-usable X-33 will take off like a rocket and
then glide back to earth intact. (NASA/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) STONINGTON, Conn. -- March. 01, 1999 --
AUTHOR-HOUSTON-BOS, 3-01 -- James Houston, author of ``Confessions
of an Igloo Dweller,'' in his house during a recent interview.
Following World War II and art school in Paris, he hitched a ride
on a medical emergency flight into the Canadian Arctic, landing in
a native settlement on the northeast coast of Hudson Bay. When the
plane departed, Houston stayed behind. ``I had found the place that
I'd been looking for,'' he writes in his autobiography. (Tom
Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) MOJAVE, Calif. -- March. 01, 1999 -- SCI-ROCKET-BOS, 3-01
-- A full size prototype of the Rotan rocket is assembled in a
hangar at the airport. The craft is a test vehicle for a new kind
of rocket that its supporters hope will mark a dramatic advance in
space-age history, opening up the space frontier to regular,
routine travel for tourism and commerce in much the same way that
the DC-3 opened up aviation. (Mark Wilson/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
