<HEADER>
A3760 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PA-RETARDED-ABUSE-2TA     03-01 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PA-RETARDED-ABUSE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MENTAL INSTITUTION SHAKEN BY DOCTORS' ARRESTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Ohio)  (nk) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POLK, Pa. _ The vast complex of handsome brick buildings sits
high on a hill and far off a two-lane rural road, providing an air
of mystery to the place, even a sense of foreboding.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, most days of the last 102 years have passed quietly
here in the northwest corner of Pennsylvania with few outsiders
ever knowing much about what happens inside the Polk Center, the
largest of the state's eight institutions for the mentally
retarded.
</P>
<P>
   Now they are beginning to learn. In a case reminiscent of
scandals of a generation ago, six doctors who worked at the center
were arrested on Friday on charges arising out of a two-year
investigation after three patients died in unusual circumstances in
1996 and 1997. Two doctors were charged with negligent care that
led to the deaths of three patients through misdiagnoses and
delayed treatment. Two of the three who died had been placed in the
center as children and had lived there for more than 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   A third doctor was charged with ``gross and reckless omission in
care'' that left a patient ``in danger of death,'' and all six
doctors were accused of improper care and abusive treatment of 21
other patients for sewing up lacerations without using anesthesia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very sad and disturbing case,'' said Mike Fisher,
the state attorney general, describing the results of an
investigation that began after the first death, almost three years
ago. ``These doctors were entrusted with the care of some of our
most dependent citizens,'' he said. ``Yet they broke that trust by
neglecting or abusing their patients, abuse that resulted in pain,
suffering, sickness and even death.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the doctors said Monday that they intended to plead
not guilty if preliminary hearings in the next several weeks
determine that enough evidence exists to try them.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Rosenfield, who is representing five of the doctors,
predicted that the state would fall well short of making a case,
saying, ``There was no criminal activity by any of these
physicians.'' Rosenfield characterized the prosecution as a
political gambit by Fisher to raise his profile for a future run
for governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a ridiculous charge,'' said Kevin Harley, a spokesman
for Fisher. ``It's nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprawling health-care complexes like the Polk Center, which
opened in 1897 as the State Institution for the Feeble-Minded of
Western Pennsylvania, are slowly becoming anachronisms. Recent
trends in housing and care for mentally retarded people include
placing them in small group homes or community settings near family
members.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Pagni, a spokesman for the state's Department of Public
Welfare, said that in 1966, when the need in Pennsylvania for large
institutions treating the mentally retarded was at its peak, more
than 13,000 people lived in 10 centers in the state. Polk, which
once housed as many as 3,500 residents, now has 576, some as young
as 30, others well into their 80s.
</P>
<P>
   Polk, a collection of more than 20 stately and well-kept
buildings, is also the biggest employer in the town, with 1,200
workers who commute from communities near Erie to the north and
Pittsburgh to the south.
</P>
<P>
   As the owner of the only restaurant in Polk, Laurie's Cafe _ one
of three businesses in town, along with Lori L's Beauty Shop and
Jimmy's Main Street Market _ Laurie Bowlin knows many of the Polk
employees from serving them lunch and dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Polk Center didn't exist, there would be no little Polk,''
Ms. Bowlin said, referring to the town of about 100 people. ``It's
a nice little place to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bowlin said townspeople had no idea any problems were
brewing at the center until last Friday, when television crews
began arriving in nearby Franklin to cover Fisher's announcement.
It was only then that the charges against the six doctors came to
light, coming out of the two-year investigation in which Fisher's
office sent in outside doctors to examine records and interview
other Polk personnel to learn what happened.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the actions taken against the doctors, state
officials said the investigation led to improvements at all centers
in Pennsylvania where the mentally retarded live, like new training
techniques for the staff, modernized communication systems and
better surveillance of residents.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The most serious of the criminal charges in the case were filed
against two of Rosenfield's clients, Dr. Cesar P. Miranda, 68, of
Butler, Pa., and Hyunchel J. Shin, 74, of Pittsburgh. Both face
felony counts of involuntary manslaughter and reckless endangerment
for actions leading to the deaths of three patients.
</P>
<P>
   Miranda and the four other defendants _ David R. Byers, 54, of
Waldron, Ark., Louka T. Makkar, 50, of Youngstown, Ohio, Samir M.
Moussa, 47, of Meadville, Pa., and Donald G. Stitt, 84, of
Greenville, Pa. _ face misdemeanor charges of assault and neglect
for using staples and sutures to seal wounds without the use of
anesthesia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these residents could not express pain or discomfort
to the doctors,'' Fisher said in a statement without elaborating.
``However, there is no excuse for circumventing normal medical
procedures. Just because they can't express pain doesn't mean they
can't feel pain.''
</P>
<P>
   The first of the fatal cases, which led to felony charges of
involuntary manslaughter, involved a 31-year-old woman, Deborah
Carnes, a patient of Miranda who investigators found was suffering
from respiratory problems, fever and low-blood pressure on July 19,
1996. The investigators said Ms. Carnes ``should have been treated
immediately'' with intravenous fluids and oxygen and transferred to
a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they found that Miranda had ordered Ms. Carnes to an
X-ray room. When her conditioned worsened, she was transported to a
hospital, but she died on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Eight months later, in March 1997, another patient of Miranda's,
Eugene Rozgonyi, died as a result of what investigators said was
``grossly and flagrantly negligent'' care. Investigators found that
Rozgonyi, who was 62 and had lived at the Polk Center for 55 years,
had abdominal pains throughout the day but was not examined by
Miranda until midnight, when Rozgonyi's temperature had fallen to
82 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Miranda kept him under observation for more than four hours with
no treatment other than measures to warm him before he was
transferred to a local hospital at dawn, investigators said. Given
a more thorough examination there, Rozgonyi was found to be
suffering from intestinal obstruction, hypotension and finally a
heart attack. He died six hours later, on March 7, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Shin was charged in the death of John Hoover, who was 60 and
lived at Polk for 53 years. Investigators said Shin delayed for
three weeks ordering a brain scan after he had recorded symptoms
that indicated that Hoover had severe damage to his brain, injuries
that led to his death on Aug. 20, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Another of Rosenfield's clients, Byers, was charged with one
felony count of reckless endangerment for errors in treatment of a
patient, Randall Miller, who was suffering in 1995 from pneumonia.
Investigators said Byers prescribed penicillin but it was
discontinued after several hours when the patient had an allergic
reaction.
</P>
<P>
   They said Byers failed to treat Miller with anything else, which
resulted in a worsening of his condition and a prolonged
hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   Miranda and Shin were dismissed from their jobs after the
investigators' reports reached the attorney general's office. Byers
quit, and Stitt retired, leaving only Mossa and Makkar working at
the institution on Friday, when they were suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Moussa, who is facing 16 misdemeanor counts for inserting
sutures without anesthesia in seven patients, was irate over the
charges. Speaking from his home in Meadville, he accused state
officials of engaging in ``a conspiracy'' in trying to rid Polk
Center of civil service doctors and replacing them with doctors who
work for a private health-care organization in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Moussa acknowledged the charges against him but insisted that
they did not violate any regulations, charging that even the
doctors from the health-care group did the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are just trying to sell our positions,'' Moussa said.
``They want to give our shop to a private agency.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward J. Sadosky, who was brought in as the institution's
director 18 months ago, said the state had signed a contract with a
private organization. But Sadosky denied any effort to run off
state doctors, saying, ``the investigation had absolutely nothing
to do with anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadosky added: ``We've done many things to fix the problems.
With a place this large, there are always issues to fix.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
