<SLUG> BC-MINIMED-SHARES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINIMED OPENS STRONG, THEN FADES FOR MILD GAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shares in medical devices maker MiniMed Inc.
opened up nearly 15 percent Monday, only to come quickly tumbling
back to earth for a one-day gain of just under 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The short-lived, opening bell boost came from a pile of weekend
buy orders prompted by news late Friday that a U.S. Food and Drug
Administration advisory panel had recommended approval of a MiniMed
blood glucose sensor for diabetics.
</P>
<P>
   But after opening at $97.875, the issue fell steadily as
institutional investors, perhaps better informed than individual
buyers, sold the stock, according to analyst Sam Chang at
investment bank Volpe Brown Whelan. Shares ended the day up $1.6875
at $86.9375, for a gain of 1.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of press over the weekend that talked about
this (glucose sensor) as the product that will revolutionize
diabetes,'' Chang said. ``As a result, a lot of people jumped on
the bandwagon. But the institutions realized this is still a niche
product, and sold into the strength.''
</P>
<P>
   The FDA panel said Friday it would recommend approval of the
sensor, but said Los Angeles-based MiniMed should conduct more
tests on the device. The FDA is not bound by the panel's
recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   The sensor, which can be worn for up to three days at a time, is
the first to provide continuous testing of diabetics' blood sugar
levels. The company hopes it will eliminate the need for finger
pricks that diabetics must now conduct up to three times per day to
draw blood for testing.
</P>
<P>
   If the FDA does approve the product, it will initially be only
for use in a physician office setting. A device for use by
consumers is still at least two years away, Chang said. In
addition, for even the office version to get approval, the FDA
panel recommended MiniMed conduct further tests.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the panel said MiniMed should further study use
of the device in minorities and people with Type II diabetes. The
bulk of previous test subjects were white, Type I sufferers.
</P>
<P>
   MiniMed officials said they were pleased by the panel's
recommendation and that they look forward to moving ahead on
development and marketing of the sensor.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
