u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCOLLISTER-OBIT-COX     03-01 0357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCOLLISTER-OBIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sports writer dies in crash
 &HT;    By Scott Marshall
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Veteran Atlanta Journal-Constitution sports writer Tom
McCollister died Monday in a two-car crash near his home in
Lilburn, Ga., police said.
</P>
<P>
   The crash occurred at 3:18 p.m. at the intersection of U.S. 29
and Rockbridge Road, said Jim Canupp, a Gwinnett County police
accident investigator.
</P>
<P>
   McCollister, who at one time was the sports editor for The
Atlanta Journal, covered all types of sporting activity during his
career. He recently transferred to the newspaper's Gwinnett bureau
after a three-year assignment covering NASCAR, said assistant
managing editor for sports Don Boykin.
</P>
<P>
   McCollister was an avid golfer who covered the PGA Tour for many
years. His writings included a book, ``Golf in Georgia,'' and he
was looking forward to covering the Masters Tournament in Augusta
again this year, as he had done several times in the past, Boykin
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom was an important part of the Journal-Constitution sports
department and the Atlanta sports community for many years,''
Boykin said. ``He was a terrific journalist, but an even better
person. He will be greatly missed.''
</P>
<P>
   McCollister, 61, was driving a red 1989 Toyota Camry north on
U.S. 29 when he merged into a left-turn lane to cross the
southbound lanes of U.S. 29 onto Rockbridge Road, Canupp said.
</P>
<P>
   McCollister turned into the path of a black 1978 Chevrolet
Camaro that was being driven south on U.S. 29 by Tanja Colleen
Franklin, 30, Canupp said.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin's car, which was traveling at about 40 mph, struck the
passenger side of McCollister's car, Canupp said. McCollister, who
police said was wearing an automatic shoulder harness but not a lap
belt, was rushed to DeKalb Medical Center, where he was pronounced
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin was listed in stable condition at DeKalb Medical Center
on Monday night, a hospital spokesman said. Her injuries were not
life-threatening, police said.
</P>
<P>
   No charges were filed in the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
