<HEADER>
A3774 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAIMLERCHRYSLER-DEFEC     03-01 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAIMLERCHRYSLER-DEFECTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAIMLERCHRYSLER LOSES 2 EXECUTIVES TO RIVAL FORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Two senior executives from DaimlerChrysler Corp.
joined Ford Motor Co. on Monday, the latest in a series of
departures of executives from the former Chrysler Corp. since its
merger last November with Daimler-Benz AG.
</P>
<P>
   When Daimler and Chrysler merged, the combination was presented
as a merger of equals. But the merger is increasingly viewed in the
auto industry as a takeover by the German company. The loss of
executive talent is particularly unusual in an industry in which
managers have traditionally worked their entire careers at a single
company.
</P>
<P>
   There are nine Germans and only two Americans among the
executives reporting to the two co-chairmen, Juergen E. Schrempp,
Daimler's former chairman, and Robert J. Eaton, Chrysler's former
chairman. The merger agreement also calls for Eaton to remain for
no more than three years before Schrempp becomes the sole chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas T. Stallkamp, DaimlerChrysler's president, said in a
statement on Monday evening that the departure of the two senior
vice presidents would not be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a competitive industry, and while we obviously hate to
lose any management talent, it is a reflection of the strength and
wide-ranging business capabilities that exist in our company,''
Stallkamp said. ``We continue to be confident that DaimlerChrysler
will become the best company in the industry and will offer
enormous opportunities to all our employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Shamel T. Rushwin, DaimlerChrysler's senior vice president for
international manufacturing and minivan assembly operations, will
become Ford's vice president for advanced manufacturing
engineering, effective Monday, Ford announced. Chris P. Theodore,
DaimlerChrysler's senior vice president for platform engineering,
is joining Ford to become its vice president for large and luxury
cars.
</P>
<P>
   Rushwin had helped keep DaimlerChrysler at the top of the
minivan market, while Theodore had a sterling reputation as a
planner of new vehicles. They are the latest in a long list of star
executives to leave. Robert A. Lutz, Chrysler's vice chairman and
the man credited with much of the automaker's success in the 1990s
through the introduction of new and more daringly designed models,
retired last summer before the merger; although he was more than a
year over Chrysler's retirement age of 65, the company had tried to
hold on to his expertise as long as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Pawley, Chrysler's executive vice president for
manufacturing and one of the most highly regarded manufacturing
executives in the auto industry, retired early at the end of last
year. And Stephen Harris, DaimlerChrysler's vice president for
public affairs, moved to General Motors Corp. last month.
</P>
<P>
   Ford executives were crowing on Monday evening. ``The experience
and expertise that Shamel and Chris bring to Ford will add
exceptional depth to an already strong team,'' said Jacques A.
Nasser, Ford's president and chief executive officer. ``They will
help in leading the company toward our vision of becoming the
world's leading consumer company that provides automotive products
and services.''
</P>
<P>
   Theodore succeeds Kenneth Kohrs, who will retire on June 1 after
more than 37 years with Ford, while Rushwin replaces Roman J.
Krygier Jr., who became Ford's vice president for engines and
transmissions on Jan. 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
