<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSORIASIS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FDA OKs Palo Alto Firm's Psoriasis Drug  &HT;       
 By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
A Palo Alto biotech firm will announce today that it has received
Food and Drug Administration approval to start selling a foam to
treat psoriasis of the scalp.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Wiggans, chief executive of Connetics Corp., said he
expects to start selling the foam under the brand name of Luxiq
within a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I got the (FDA approval) letter, I got on the phone
and hired 16 dermatology salespeople,'' Wiggans said.
</P>
<P>
   About 6.4 million people in the United States suffer from this
condition of severely dried and flaky skin. Approximately 200,000
new cases are reported annually. Most cases are reported among
Caucasians, with women slightly outnumbering men.
</P>
<P>
   Current remedies include a variety of creams and lotions, both
over the counter and by prescription. Luxiq would enter the market
as one of the prescribed remedies, competing with similar
prescription creams or lotions that can cost $50 to $100 per
canister. Wiggans said the competing creams leave the hair feeling
greasy. He said Luxiq will spray on like shaving cream and be
absorbed into the scalp with less telltale residue.
</P>
<P>
   Connetics, which currently has a staff of 85, lost $26 million
last year on sales of $9 million. But even before yesterday's FDA
approval was announced, the stock briefly flirted with a 52-week
high of $9.25 before closing at $8.88 _ a big jump for an issue
that traded at $2 in October.
</P>
<P>
   Wiggans attributed the recent stock momentum to Wall Street
interest in Connetics' research into a treatment for scleroderma, a
disease that creates scar tissues on the inside and outside of the
body. It can be life-threatening. Currently there are no effective
treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Wiggans said Connetics' stock started to ascend in December as
it became apparent the company would start the final, or Phase III,
round of clinical trials on a possible treatment for Scleroderma.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 1 of PSORIASI () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
