<HEADLINE>
RIVIERA BY YACHT  
 JAZZ IN SAN JUAN  
 SOUTH AMERICAN CRUISE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 7)
</HEADLINE>
  (af)  
 By JOSEPH SIANO  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. (italics)We would like to charter a yacht with a crew
(including a cook) for about a week to sail from Nice, France, to
Portofino, Italy. There will be six adults in our group. Can you
provide names of any yacht-chartering operations? _ Sandy Potholm,
Harpswell, Maine.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   A. Although you could find a yacht-chartering company in Nice,
you will probably have more success a little farther east in a
higher-rent neighborhood, Monaco, or a few miles to the west around
Antibes.
</P>
<P>
   One yacht company in Monaco is Camper &AMP; Nicholsons. Pierre
Hurel, its charter broker, says that the price will depend on the
vessel's size and whether it's a motor yacht or a sailing yacht
(the former is more expensive because of the fuel and larger crew
required).
</P>
<P>
   Hurel suggests that for six passengers and crew, you would need
a motor yacht between 65 and 111 feet. The smallest yacht would
have one double-bed cabin and two twin-bed cabins. The three-member
crew would consist of a captain-engineer, a cook-deckhand and a
steward.
</P>
<P>
   It would cost about $20,000 a week plus 20.6 percent value-added
tax. On top of this sum, you would need to send about 25 percent of
the base charter fee in advance to cover food, fuel and port
charges, or about $5,000 in this case; this amount is not subject
to the VAT.
</P>
<P>
   A 62-foot sailing yacht, he said, would cost about $14,000 a
week plus the VAT, or about $3,000, and provisions. It would
require a two-member crew: a captain and a cook-deckhand. For more
room, a 111-foot sailing yacht would cost about $37,000 for a week,
plus tax and provisions, and you would have a crew of six: a
captain, cook, mate, engineer and two others who are the nautical
version of flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   Hurel also suggests that you will enjoy your week along the
Riviera much more if you expand your selection in ports of call,
since it only takes 10 hours to go from Monaco to Portofino, and
the only place worth a stop along the way is San Remo, Italy. He
recommends adding Cannes, St.-Tropez and the picturesque Iles
d'Hyeres, just off Toulon. Or, he said, you could start in Monaco
and include Corsica as well as Portofino, although for this trip he
recommends a motor yacht because of its faster speed. You may
contact him at Camper &AMP; Nicholsons, (377) 97.97.77.00, fax (377)
93.50.25.08, on the Web: www.cnconnect.com.
</P>
<P>
   Kirsten Ringsing, charter broker at Fraser Yachts, (377)
93.10.04.60, fax (377) 93.10.0.97, in Monaco, said that you might
avoid the VAT if you can find a smaller commercially registered
yacht, but she could think of only two of these. She suggests a tip
of 5 to 10 percent of the basic charter fee, to be given to the
captain, who distributes it to the crew.
</P>
<P>
   In Nice, you can try Three-B Yachting, (33-4) 93.56.55.05, fax
(33-4) 93.89.66.00, where Dominique Poirier recommends either a
130-foot motor yacht for about $29,500 for a week, plus tax and
provisions, or a 75-foot motor yacht (about $22,400). Each has a
crew of eight. Fuel for the longer yacht will cost about $10,000,
the shorter about $5,900.
</P>
<P>
   Ask about the amenities each yacht offers, including
air-conditioning and water sports gear. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)I'm interested in attending the Heineken Jazz
Festival in San Juan. I know it's sometime in June, but I cannot
seem to find any information about dates, prices, performers and
sites. Can you help? Also, I'd like to rent a villa in San Juan. _
Barbara L. Fields, New York, N.Y.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   A. This year's Puerto Rico Heineken Jazz Fest will be June 10 to
13. All performances will be at Parque Sixto Escobar, at the
entrance to Old San Juan. The stage will be in a track and field
stadium alongside the beach; folding chairs will rent for $1.
</P>
<P>
   The first three days, performances will start at 8 p.m. On June
10, the lineup is the Afro Rican Jazz Ensemble and The Rippingtons,
featuring Russ Freeman. On June 11, there will be three performers:
the Charlie Sepulveda Sextet; the Jazz Messengers: the Legacy of
Art Blakey, with Randy Becker, among others; and Poncho Sanchez.
The next evening, Ralph Irizarri Timbalaye is scheduled (though not
yet confirmed), along with the Manhattan Transfer.
</P>
<P>
   And on June 13, a Sunday, the final concert at 5 p.m. will
include the Elaine Elias Trio.
</P>
<P>
   A ticket good for all four performances is $47.50; call
Entertainment and Marketing Group at (787) 277-9200, fax (787)
277-0552. Rico Sun Tours, (800) 844-2080, sells a package that
includes tickets, transportation to and from the concerts, a beach
chair and tours.
</P>
<P>
   For short-term vacation rentals, you can try San Juan Vacations,
(800) 266-3639; the Web site is www.sanjuanvacations.com. Or call
Palm View Realty, (888) 957-7256, www.palmviewrealty.com.
</P>
<P>
   Package tours that include the festival are offered by
Interisland Tours, (800) 245-3434, starting at $799 a person,
double occupancy, with round-trip air fare from New York, four
nights in the Hampton Inn in Isla Verde, tickets, chairs, transfers
each day and sightseeing. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)I would like to take a cruise to South America that
includes at least Rio de Janeiro and Buenos Aires, but I cannot
seem to find any. Do you know of some? _ Irving Greene, East
Brunswick, N.J.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   A. You just missed the boat, literally, for this season. Holland
America's Noordam is scheduled to depart Sunday from Valparaiso,
Chile, on a 16-day cruise around Cape Horn that includes the
Chilean fjords, a passage through the Strait of Magellan, Tierra
del Fuego, the Falkland Islands, Buenos Aires, Montevideo and Rio.
Its next cruise goes from Rio to Fort Lauderdale.
</P>
<P>
   But don't despair. You can start planning now for similar
cruises on the Noordam next year. The 1,214-passenger ship, which
entered service in 1984 and was renovated last year, is tentatively
scheduled to make six 16-day trips around South America, according
to Janis Goller, a Holland America spokeswoman, with departures
from Jan. 3 to April 8, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on departure date, you will either be going from Rio
to Valparaiso or in the reverse direction. Nondiscounted fares for
this year's cruise ranged from $4,385 to $7,555 a person, based on
two to a cabin, plus air fare from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Because you'll be sailing in the Southern Hemisphere, the time
of year when you are most likely to find South America cruises
available is our winter and spring. To get a better idea of exactly
what ships and ports of call will be available next season, see a
travel agent.
</P>
</TEXT>
