<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GILEAD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Gilead Buying NeXstar for $550 Million  &HT;       
 By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Gilead Sciences Inc. of Foster City said yesterday that it would
pay $550 million in stock and debt to acquire NeXstar
Pharmaceuticals Inc. of Boulder, Colo. Both biotech firms
specialize in infectious diseases and cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   Gilead would pay roughly $17.48 in stock for each NeXstar share,
a premium of about 27 percent over NeXstar's Friday close of
$13.81.
</P>
<P>
   Gilead plans to keep its name and management, while acquiring
revenues from two of NeXstar's marketable drugs and control over
the firm's 135-person European and Australian sales force.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Copithorne, an analyst with Prudential Securities in
New York, called the deal a ``mild positive'' for Gilead. Before
the merger, she hadn't expected Gilead to become profitable until
2001. But if Gilead gets NeXstar's $100 million in current
revenues, she thinks Gilead could head into the black a full year
earlier, earning 20 cents a share in 2000 instead of losing 55
cents that year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Copithorne said Gilead would acquire a European
sales force in one fell swoop. She said that could be crucial to
Gilead, which hopes to get U.S. Food and Drug Administration
approval later this year to sell a new anti-AIDS drug called
Preveon. It also will ask European drug regulators to OK Preveon
for sale. Having a European sales force would keep Gilead from
having to surrender a lion's share of the royalties to a European
partner, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Thomas Dietz with Pacific Growth Equities in San
Francisco also thought the deal made sense for Gilead but
questioned whether the Foster City firm overpaid.
</P>
<P>
   He said biotech firms generally sell for three to four times
their revenues when the purchaser is a large pharmaceutical
concern. The complicated $550 million deal, in which J. P. Morgan
represented the buyer and Morgan Stanley the seller, values NeXstar
at more than five times current revenues.
</P>
<P>
   But San Francisco investment banker Steve Burrill said it is
tough to armchair-quarterback such deals, especially if Gilead can
hasten its own profitability while controlling European sales of
its hoped-for AIDS drug.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of GILEAD02 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Gilead CEO John Martin will run the combined companies. NeXstar
Chairman and Chief Scientific Officer Larry Gold will report to
Martin. A NeXstar spokeswoman said no job cuts are planned
immediately, but analysts suggested that if the ax does fall, it
would most likely come down in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Gilead shares slipped 50 cents yesterday to close at $40.75,
while NeXstar jumped $1.31 to $15.13 after the deal was announced.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is subject to shareholder and regulatory approval.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
