<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Silicon Valley IR Consultant Settles SEC Insider-Trading Case  &HT;       
 By Mark Veverka  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Illegal insider trading isn't limited just to suits in boardrooms
and executive suites.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it can corrupt investment bankers, accountants,
lawyers, journalists, financial printers and, yes ... investor
relations professionals. In fact, a case involving one of their own
has Bay Area investor relations professionals _ folks who deal with
stockholders and analysts _ rocking on their heels.
</P>
<P>
   In a little-noticed story that nearly slipped through the local
news filter, Pleasanton investor relations consultant Lisa Herbst
agreed two weeks ago to settle an insider trading case with the
Securities and Exchange Commission. It is the first case against an
investor relations person pursued by the San Francisco office of
the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Without conceding guilt or receiving exoneration, Herbst agreed
to settle a case in which the SEC charged her with illegally
trading stock in three high-technology companies that were her
clients at various junctures. Between 1995 and 1998, Herbst
allegedly used nonpublic information to trade on Adobe Systems of
San Jose, Asyst Technologies of Fremont and Splash Technology
Holdings of Sunnyvale.
</P>
<P>
   As part of her settlement, Herbst agreed to return all profits
from her stock trades with interest and pay a penalty. Total
damage: $32,799.
</P>
<P>
   As if to emphasize the weight of the settlement, the money
Herbst owes is the same amount that she would pay if she had been
convicted in a trial, points out David Bayless, the SEC's top
administrator in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   His point is crystal clear. IR folks better think twice about
how and when they invest in their clients' stock. Or more
important, whether it's prudent to invest in a client's stock at
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is significant because it is against an IR person,''
Bayless notes. ``Companies have to have confidence and trust in
these people so that they don't steal information and trade on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But here's the capper: Herbst wasn't an unknown innocent, or at
least one would think that she was in a position to know better.
Herbst was a two-term president of the Silicon Valley chapter of
the National Investor Relations Institute, which subsequently has
voted to oust her as the top officer of that local organization _
one that is responsible for setting the standards of this
increasingly influential profession.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of STREET02 (75769 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``The SEC (settlement) was a surprise. (And) we felt that any
type of judgment made it difficult for anyone in a leadership
position to continue'' in such a role, says Carol Kaplan, acting
president of the Silicon Valley chapter of NIRI.
</P>
<P>
   Thus on February 19, the NIRI valley chapter's board voted to
toss Herbst from office and suspend her membership from an
organization in which she held a leadership post of some kind for
about 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the valley NIRI board needed to send a message that its
membership isn't rife with insider traders. But what's interesting
here is that Herbst refused the board's offer to resign. Kaplan
would not discuss the particulars of Herbst's dismissal.
(Incidentally, Herbst has requested a hearing on March 10 before
the national NIRI board to defend her membership in the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly enough, Herbst contends that her settlement in no
way demonstrates any admission of guilt. And therefore, she thinks
that she should still be president of the valley chapter of the
NIRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt (the board's) vote was unwarranted,'' says Herbst. ``As
in any case, there are two sides to the story.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Herbst, she can't tell her side of the insider
trading story. Herbst's consent decree with the SEC prohibits her
from commenting about her case.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, without going into greater detail, the allegations
laid out by the SEC make compelling references to trades that
Herbst made during sensitive time periods seemingly based on
privileged information.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Herbst, who runs her own one-person IR firm,
argues that she didn't have the deep-pockets to afford the hefty
legal bills that would have resulted from a protracted fight with
the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   ``A settlement is a settlement. But nothing is black and
white,'' Herbst says.
</P>
<P>
   So why did she settle if she implies that she wasn't guilty?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was somewhat naive at understanding the complete (SEC
investigation) process,'' Herbst says. ``This has been nothing but
a bad experience for me.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of STREET02 (75769 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  One thing is certain, no investor relations consultant or
executive should think that their stock trades are too small to
cross the SEC's radar.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
