<HEADER>
A3779 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-SEC-TOURNEY-COX     03-01 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SEC-TOURNEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Dome, big crowds enhance tournament
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the Final Four comes to the Georgia Dome in 2002,
the Southeastern Conference Basketball Tournament will have been
played there four of the last five years. And this year's SEC
event, set to begin with four games Thursday, is the second of
three straight years in which it will be played in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The increased frequency of the tournament's visits here has some
SEC members wondering, will Atlanta become the SEC Tournament's
permanent home?
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was up to me, we'd play it in Atlanta every year,'' said
South Carolina coach Eddie Fogler, when asked about the subject
Monday. ``There are no negatives about it. What Atlanta brings to
the table can't be beat. If you look at all the ingredients you
need for a tournament, they're all there.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not likely to happen, SEC Commissioner Roy Kramer said,
though he added Atlanta could be considered the tournament's
semi-permanent home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there will always be a desire to move the tournament
on occasion to the west side of the region and maybe we'll do that
every third or fourth year,'' Kramer said. ``But we'd like to keep
it in Atlanta as much as we can. Atlanta may not be the
(tournament's) permanent home, but it's definitely the anchor.''
</P>
<P>
   The SEC Tournament, which was played in Atlanta last year and in
1995, is already under contract to be played at the Georgia Dome
next year and in 2002. It will be played in Nashville, Tenn., in
2001 and, though negotiations are still ongoing, will likely go to
New Orleans' SuperDome in 2003, the same year it hosts the Final
Four, Kramer said.
</P>
<P>
   After that, he said, it will probably come back to Georgia. In
fact, there have been preliminary discussions about playing the
tournament in Philips Arena, the Atlanta Hawks' new home scheduled
for completion this year.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC wasn't always so infatuated with Atlanta. The tournament
has been played here just five times in the previous 40 seasons of
its existence, including the first two years at the Atlanta
Athletic Club in 1933 and '34. It was 53 years before it returned
and then it did not come back for another eight years. The four-day
event in 1987 at The Omni attracted just 105,616 spectators, 43,000
fewer than the previous year in Lexington, Ky., and 21,000 less
than the following year in Baton Rouge, La.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some concern in 1987 that the city (of Atlanta)
didn't care,'' said Brad Davis, SEC associate commissioner and
executive director of the tournament. ``But since 1995, everybody
realizes that's not the case. Atlanta has embraced this event and
made it bigger and better.''
</P>
<P>
   The tournament returned to Atlanta and moved into the Georgia
Dome in 1995 where it debuted to record-setting crowds. With
Kentucky and Arkansas meeting in the finals, it drew 250,301
spectators in four days, which remains the all-time attendance
mark.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said the tournament could break the record this year. ``If
we get a run on a few more tickets this week, it may be sold out,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   That should come as no surprise, Fogler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big Southeastern city located in a major transportation
hub that's easily accessible by car or plane,'' he said. ``They
have nice hotels and restaurants, plenty of entertainment, the best
facilities and the fans come out. What's not to like?''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean the tournament should remain in Atlanta
indefinitely, Arkansas' Nolan Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care much about it being in one spot,'' he said. ``I
enjoyed the rotation thing we were doing there for a while, playing
in New Orleans and Memphis. There are some advantages to having it
in one spot, certainly. But there are so many teams in our league,
I'm for rotating it around so all the fans get a chance to go see
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The construction of the Georgia Dome along with the expansion of
the SEC were important factors to its success here. Da
</P>
</TEXT>
