<SLUG> BC-HKN-DALLAS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOCKEY COMES OF OLD AGE IN DALLAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Dallas Stars are so old that ``Remember the Alamo''
is not merely a figurative expression. The veterans don't mind that
the National Hockey League will expand to 30 teams in two years
because they remember how hard it was for them to earn a job in the
six-team league. When the Stars signed a free agent named Hull last
summer, one of them said, ``Bobby may have lost a step, but his
slap shot will help us.''
</P>
<P>
   Derian Hatcher's father was in the locker room the other day.
Derian is the Stars' 26-year-old captain but his dad did not look
all that out of place among a few of Derian's teammates. In need of
an extra defenseman, the Stars last week hired the 38-year-old Doug
Lidster, a former Ranger who had retired last year. Stashing his
gear into his locker after practice last Saturday, Lidster looked
around and said, ``I fit right in.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Stars visit New York to play the Rangers on Tuesday and
the Islanders on Thursday, they will bring the league's oldest
roster, averaging more than 31 years of age. They also bring the
league's best record and its biggest expectations. In 58 games,
they are 38-11-9 and 7-1-1 in their last nine. Their longest losing
streak has been two games. On the road, they are unbeaten in their
last eight. Their goals against average is 2.00, lowest in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might not have the fastest team, but we can match fast
teams,'' Guy Carbonneau, who turns 39 this month, said earlier this
season. ``We might not have the strongest team, but we can play a
physical game. We might not be the best at any one thing, but right
now we're the best team.''
</P>
<P>
   When they played Detroit last spring in the Western Conference
finals, the Red Wings beat them in six games, on their way to their
second consecutive Stanley Cup championship. But it seemed to some
as if the craftier team in decline won over the better team
ascending. Apparently en route to their second consecutive
Presidents' Trophy for best regular-season record, the Stars'
biggest challenge might be to stay healthy and focused on the last
quarter of the regular season until the post-season tournament
begins in April.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Gainey, the general manager of Dallas and a former captain
of the Canadiens, has built a roster filled with veterans. Two of
them, Mike Keane, who arrived from the Rangers last spring, and
Carbonneau, were also captains in Montreal. Pat Verbeek was a
captain in Hartford. Brian Skrudland was a captain in Florida.
Brett Hull, Bobby's 34-year-old son, was a captain in St. Louis.
Carbonneau said, ``If Bob makes a trade and the chemistry is not
there anymore, he is the one who will have to pay for it. He's
going to try to make the right deal, but he also knows that
sometimes the best trade you make is the one you don't make.''
</P>
<P>
   And, sometimes, the best signings you make are free agents. They
compose a quarter of the roster, including Hull, Verbeek, Shawn
Chambers, Ed Belfour and Dave Reid. Although more than half the
Stars are older than age 30, the nucleus of the team is composed of
stars in their prime, such as Hatcher, the leading scorer and the
alternate captain Mike Modano, Sergei Zubov, Jamie Langenbrunner
and Jere Lehtinen, all between ages 23 and 28.
</P>
<P>
   Common among both older and younger Stars are strong
personalities, a challenge to Ken Hitchcock, a strong-willed coach
who was still coaching junior teams in Kamloops, British Columbia,
when many of his players were established in the NHL. ``These
people are set in their ways,'' Hitchcock said. ``So many strong
opinions. There is no coaching clinic for this.''
</P>
<P>
   In his four seasons with the team, Hitchcock has learned to
listen. Because he is so demanding in games and in practices, his
players demand off days and he allows them, at least five each
month, he said. ``Otherwise, I'm going to burn this group out,'' he
said. The veterans and even the 20-somethings bang on his door,
Hitchcock said, to give him free advice. ``Yinning and yanging,''
is what Hitchcock calls their ongoing negotiations. But even the
Stars have free-speech limits. When Hull joined the team last fall,
he brought the reputation of being hockey's version of Charles
Barkley, a talented man who sometimes says too much. Midway through
the season, when Hull complained to reporters about his ice time,
Hitchcock didn't have to respond.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   According to Jim Lites, the team president, the veterans told
Hull that such things were ``not done here'' and Hull stopped
complaining.
</P>
<P>
   Currently sidelined with a hamstring strain, Hull still leads
the team in goals with 26, despite playing a more restrained system
that includes defensive responsibilities. Craig Ludwig, a Stars
defensemen, said ``Hully played a free-wheeling kind of game'' in
St. Louis before joining the Stars and ``He probably didn't expect
to have that many goals with this kind of a system.'' As for Hull's
conversational skills, Ludwig said ``He never shuts up. That's his
character. But at least he plays the way everybody else does.''
Ludwig, who turns 38 this month, is the other alternate captain.
Hitchcock calls him and other veterans his ``glue guys.'' The coach
meets with the captains and team elders about twice a month, to
discuss everybody's gripes. Belfour, the goalie, said ``I have some
input, but, basically, I leave it up to the older guys. I don't
feel like I'm one of the older guys.'' He's a mere pup of 33.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to protect Belfour's goals-against average is to
keep the puck at the other end of the ice, Hitchcock said. To
accomplish this, he encourages his defensemen to join the attack,
not off the rush but rather after the forwards take puck possession
in the other end. He learned this, Hitchcock said, when the Stars
lost to the Wings in the playoffs. ``We decided after playing
Detroit last year to stop playing scared,'' Hitchcock said. So far
this season, they are 3-0 against the Wings. Describing the style
of extended puck possession in the attack zone, Hull recently said:
``It's almost like a football game. Whoever has time of possession
longest is going to win.'' This does not go unappreciated in
football country. ``The whole game seems to fit with the Texas
personality,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars make their share of mistakes, but teammates cover up
for each other, a common trait of good teams. They are able and
willing to block shots and to hustle on the backcheck. Although
they aren't heavily penalized, the Stars know how and when to play
mean. In the opening minutes against Pittsburgh on Friday night,
Verbeek barged through two checks and then exchanged swings with
Penguins goalie Tom Barrasso and Ludwig dropped Stu Barnes with an
elbow to the head. After both served their minor penalties, Verbeek
scored to spark the Stars to a 6-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got slashed, I got punched,'' Verbeek explained afterward,
ice bags on each elbow, a few stitches in his upper lip. ``I
reacted.''
</P>
<P>
   Such scenes are enjoyed by a fan base that is growing in hockey
sophistication in the sixth season since the team moved from
Minnesota. In some ways, the Texas culture, with oil and cattle, is
like that of Alberta, in Western Canada, where several stars come
from. Hatcher, one of several Stars from the ``Hockeytown'' suburbs
of Detroit, said ``It seems like every other person I meet is from
up north.'' Many migrated during the Rust Belt recession two
decades ago, from states round the Great Lakes. Hitchcock said the
transplanted Northerners ``are all coaching youth hockey, watching
it on TV and buying season tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's sellout was the 26th. in succession and a new, bigger
arena will open in two years. Lites said some fans used to cheer
when the team pulled its goalie for an extra attacker during a
delayed penalty, thinking it was a novel way of attacking. They
don't any more, but they do shout ``Stars!'' when it is heard in
the lyrics of the national anthem. And they cheer a film clip in
which Pee-Wee Herman sings ``The stars at night are big and
bright'' and a chorus of people in cowboy hats respond with ``Deep
in the Heart of Texas!'' Perhaps, by June, the Stars will give the
audience a great deal more about which to hoot and holler.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
