u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-SEAVER-NYT &LR;      03-01 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-SEAVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TIME ARRIVES FOR SEAVER TO MEET THE METS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ It seemed fitting that Jason Isringhausen
was the first person Tom Seaver approached in Seaver's new,
part-time, role as an ad-hoc pitching coach with the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   As Seaver had been in the late 1960s, Isringhausen, a few years
ago, was one of the organization's can't-miss kids. But because of
recurring arm troubles after an optimistic rookie season,
Isringhausen has since had little impact.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year-old right-hander, who had reconstructive elbow
surgery in early 1998, has not even pitched in a game since he
threw in winter ball in 1997. Even when he was healthy,
Isringhausen's work ethic and maturity had been questioned by
people in the organization. And Isringhausen will not begin this
season with the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   But there is little question that his talent is still there. And
so Seaver _ in a Mets uniform Monday for the first time since 1987
_ who had never seen Isringhausen before, gravitated to him almost
instantly to offer suggestions. It was as if a magnet had pulled
Seaver to Isringhausen.
</P>
<P>
   Mainly, Seaver said later, he had stepped in to encourage him to
slow down. First, however, the Hall of Famer asked permission.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Seaver won 311 games in the major leagues, had 3,640
strikeouts and won three Cy Young awards. But the 54-year-old, who
will also be a team broadcaster, had said at his introductory news
conference, and he reiterated Monday, that he is not the pitching
coach. And he does not want to get in anybody's way.
</P>
<P>
   Nonsense, said Bob Apodaca, who  &UR; is &LR;  the pitching coach and who
was a teammate of Seaver's a quarter of a century ago. ``I am
asking him his advice,'' he said. ``I'd be stupid if I let my ego
get in the way. That is why he's here.''
</P>
<P>
   Seaver had a little trouble getting to practice, since he was
with the organization before it moved its spring training to Port
St. Lucie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time I've ever been here,'' Seaver said a
little sheepishly. ``I did get lost, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, on his first day on the job, Seaver arrived at the
team's playing fields, in a golf cart, late. Once Seaver joined the
workout, Manager Bobby Valentine began to needle him
good-naturedly. ``It took about two minutes,'' Seaver said, when
asked how long it took to get comfortable again in his old No. 41.
``It was like I never left.''
</P>
<P>
   What Seaver will mostly do for the next week and a half is
observe. He admitted that he was not familiar with the Mets' staff,
and he will cram with Apodaca to get up to speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob knows I can help,'' Seaver said. ``I just hope I can help
the right way.''
</P>
<P>
   If it were up to Seaver, he would be merely another pitching
coach in camp. That, of course, is impossible. If Sandy Koufax _
who made a brief visit here last week _ was a distinguished
visiting professor, Seaver is like a professor emeritus, one who
has come back to his alma mater to supplement the teachings of the
department head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just feeling my way through,'' Seaver said. ``What to do,
what to say, when to say it.''
</P>
<P>
   First, though, he simply watched. When Isringhausen pitched,
Seaver struck a thinker's pose, leaning back against a fence, two
fingers from his left hand resting on his cheek. After a couple of
minutes, he stepped in to give some tips.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Seaver said that he does not think it is going to be
a problem being in the broadcast booth while serving as a part-time
coach. He sees no conflict between the two roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the interesting things about it,'' Seaver said.
``I'll be able to talk about what this individual is working on,
what he has not been able to comprehend, and why _ if the problems
are recurring _ he keeps making the same mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   First, though, Seaver simply wants to get to know the staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wonder about things like why a guy like Isringhausen would
have shoulder and elbow problems,'' Seaver said. ``And you don't
know why. His mechanics are pretty good. Very good, for that
matter. And he's got great stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, meanwhile, will get a chance to see Seaver pitch.
Valentine had some old films of Seaver's famous delivery digitized.
</P>
<P>
   ``To show how perfect he was,'' Apodaca said.
</P>
<P>
   Apodaca was fortunate enough to witness it firsthand in the
early 1970s. But while, as a rookie reliever, Apodaca had no qualms
about approaching Jerry Koosman or Jon Matlack, things were
different with Seaver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't talk to him unless he talked to me first,'' Apodaca
said.
</P>
<P>
   There was an unspoken respect for the best pitcher in the game.
And 25 years later, Apodaca is still a little bit in awe of Seaver.
</P>
<P>
   There is one thing, however, that has definitely changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I'm 50, I can finally tell Tom Seaver to go shove
off,'' Apodaca said, suppressing a laugh.
</P>
</TEXT>
