<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3788 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-PRESIDENT-COX     03-01 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PRESIDENT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Visitors come to endorse Bush run
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It's a political courtship encouraged, welcomed
and coordinated by a noncandidate who has done nothing to indicate
he does not like the attention.
</P>
<P>
   It reminds Georgetown University political scientist Stephen
Wayne of the draft movement that led Dwight Eisenhower into his
first government job that didn't come with a uniform. To Larry
Sabato, a University of Virginia political scientist, it brings to
mind William McKinley's successful ``front-porch campaign'' of
1896.
</P>
<P>
   Without declaring his candidacy, without getting out much, Gov.
George W. Bush's presidential pre-campaign has amassed key support.
And today in a move that will allow him to begin raising money for
the effort, Bush is expected to announce formation of a
presidential exploratory committee.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, political leaders from North and South Carolina and
Connecticut became the latest to enjoy a private lunch date with
Bush at the Governor's Mansion and then offer a public proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe he best represents the ideals and values of South
Carolinians,'' South Carolina House Speaker David Wilkins said
after lunch. ``We believe he is the best candidate, the best man
for the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush continued to play it close to the vest. ``Something will be
happening very soon,'' he teased.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, Bush aide Mindy Tucker confirmed that Jack Oliver
of Missouri, a key GOP fund-raiser, has been helping Bush test the
presidential waters. Oliver could wind up as Bush's campaign
finance director.
</P>
<P>
   The almost-daily parade to Austin of political leaders from
around the country indicates Bush is not discouraging anyone from
dropping by for a bite of lunch behind closed doors and a bite of
sound in front of the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we're not the first guys who've been here,'' Connecticut
GOP Chairman Chris DiPino said facetiously as he left the mansion.
</P>
<P>
   The peculiar nature of the Bush campaign has drawn attention
nationwide and taken on the feel of a nominating convention as
delegations make their feelings known. ``The home state of
Elizabeth Dole, we are proud to be here to give our commitment . .
. to Governor Bush that if he runs for the Republican nomination
for president we will support him,'' said David Miner, a North
Carolina state representative who brought a letter signed by 38 of
the 54 Republicans in that chamber.
</P>
<P>
   The North Carolinians want Dole, who has not announced her
candidacy, as Bush's running mate. Miner said Bush is a stronger
presidential contender because Dole has never sought elected
office.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to picking up support from Dole's native state, Bush
picked up some from his own. Ninety percent of the Republican state
lawmakers in Connecticut, where Bush was born, signed a letter
delivered at Monday's lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my colleagues in the House could have listened to him
today, they would know if he campaigned through the Northeast he
will do as well as he did here in the state of Texas,'' said Robert
Ward, Republican leader of the Connecticut House.
</P>
<P>
   Ward and the other visitors said they were not lured here by
Bush operatives. The Connecticut delegation thought a trip to
Austin would be a good idea after reading about other delegations
that have made the trek.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who wouldn't want to visit a lovely city like Austin?'' asked
Ward.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkins, South Carolina's House speaker, who brought a letter
signed by 59 of the 66 Republicans in his chamber, said, ``I wasn't
asked to come. I asked if I could come.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, they are spontaneous,'' Bush said of
the lunch meetings, adding that his staff has helped schedule the
meetings and that his political money is paying for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Spontaneous? Maybe. Productive? Definitely.
</P>
<P>
   Sabato, the Virginia political science professor, said there
hasn't been an effort like this one since Republican McKinley's
front-porch campaign in 1896.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of trying to out-talk legendary orator William Jennings
Bryan, McKinley, drafted for the GOP nomination, stayed home in
Canton, Ohio, and chatted with delegations that came to him.
</P>
<P>
   While he stayed home, party operatives advanced his campaign
around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That may be the closest thing to what's going on here,'' said
Sabato, ``assuming the leaders of the Republican Party can get the
rank and file to go along.''
</P>
<P>
   For McKinley, it worked out well, for awhile. He was elected in
1896 and re-elected in 1900. In 1901, McKinley was assassinated.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne, the Georgetown professor, said the Bush noncampaign
reminds him of the 1952 draft movement that turned Gen. Eisenhower
into a general election winner. Though historians believe he really
wanted the job, Eisenhower remained publicly indifferent as the
draft movement heated up.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne says the evidence indicates the Bush strategy is right on
target, so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason to declare early is to raise money and get
endorsements,'' Wayne said. ``It looks like he has the endorsements
now, and he is not going to have any problem raising the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabato said the don't-leave-home campaign has gone so well that
Bush might want to take it one step further.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he should do what Clinton did in '96,'' Sabato said.
``He never formally announced for president.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
