u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-GYROSCOPES-BOS &LR;      03-01 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-GYROSCOPES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STING OPERATION LED TO ARREST OF CHINESE SEEKING GYROSCOPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A Massachusetts manufacturer of precision gyroscopes
helped set up a federal sting leading to the arrest of Chinese
operatives accused of trying to smuggle military technology to
China, according to a criminal complaint filed in US District Court
in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Yao Yi, a Chinese citizen who allegedly tried to buy
sophisticated fiber-optic gyroscopes from the company, was arrested
in San Diego last week as he re-entered the country. He is being
brought to Boston by federal marshalls and will be charged under
arms export laws, officials said Monday. Another man, Collin Shu,
was charged in the scheme Feb. 11 in Boston after undercover
federal agents videotaped a meeting in which he allegedly said
China needed the gyroscopes for missile guidance systems and
military aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, some Washington officials believe that a concerted
effort is under way to smuggle US military technology to China to
improve its weapons systems. Last week the Pentagon issued a
detailed report to Congress on China's buildup of tactical missles.
The report said China still may be decades away from developing
technically superior missle systems. But it also said
less-sophisticated cruise and ballistic missiles ``will give
Beijing the `credible intimidation' it needs to accomplish
political and military goals without having to rely on overwhelming
force on force superiority.''
</P>
<P>
   The gyroscope matter came to light after the Massachusetts
manufacturer became suspicious of efforts by Yao and Shu to
purchase ``tactical grade'' systems that can be used for missle
guidance, according to the criminal complaint.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint did not name the company, but officials familiar
with the case identified the firm as Fibersense Technology Corp. of
Canton, one of a handful of contractors nationwide making the
gyroscopes. Fibersense would neither confirm nor deny that the
company was involved in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't comment one way or another about anything having to
do with that case,'' said Mike Perlmutter, a company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   According to the complaint, a Massachusetts company began
receiving orders from Yao and Shu in late 1997. One was on behalf
of Northern Jiaotong University in Beijing and claimed the parts
would be used for a ``super speed train navigation system.''
Another order was for Changsha Rail University in Hunan.
</P>
<P>
   An officer of the company told Yao such purchases required
special permission from the State Department because the gyroscopes
are on a government list of munitions technology that cannot be
exported without a license. Exporting items on that list to certain
countries, including China, is illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The company, at Yao's request, filed applications with the State
Department in May 1998 seeking clearance to sell the gyroscopes.
Both requests were immediately denied.
</P>
<P>
   Last August 6 the Massachusetts company received written orders
for the same kind of gyroscopes requested by Yao from a man who
identified himself as Winston Wang of Micro Techland, which he said
was a Montreal company.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Massachusetts company became suspicious because
none of them ``had ever heard of Micro Techland or Winston Wang,''
according to the complaint. Further, the order contained specific
prices and technical information a new customer would have no way
of knowing.
</P>
<P>
   A marketing director at the Massachusetts company told
investigators he also spoke by phone to someone with an Asian
accent claiming to be a Micro Techland official who said he was
placing the order ``for another company.''
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts company alerted US Customs officials, who then
set up a fake export firm. Undercover agents told Yao the company
would operate as a middleman in order to get around US export laws.
</P>
<P>
   Posing as officials from the export company, customs agents
recorded a series of phone conversations with Yao and Shu about the
illegality of the transaction and the fact the gyroscopes were
ultimately bound for China, according to the complaint.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, according to transcripts contained in the
complaint, Shu asked whether he could also obtain infrared sensors,
which are needed in some navigational devices.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Massachusetts company played a role in the sting,
taking phone calls from Yao and Shu as the pair apparently tried to
haggle over the price of the gyroscopes, according to the
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations with the dummy company dragged on for months. In
December 1998, Yao became impatient. He e-mailed the Massachusetts
company directly to say ``we are in eager need of'' the gyroscopes
and that money could be wired directly to the company's bank
account.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later Shu reached an agreement with the dummy export
company. He wired a portion of the $70,000 order to an account at
BankBoston, the complaint said. Shu was arrested last month after
attempting to pick up the gyroscopes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
