<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS TRY TO IGNORE SEEDING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With Selection Sunday looming and a desert road
trip remaining, UCLA stands on the brink of seeding satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   Strong finishes are essential to gaining a high seed, and the
Bruins (21-7, 11-5) have won six of their past eight. Their current
power ratings _ 20th in Sagarin, 15th in the Ratings Percentage
Index _ suggest either a No. 4 or No. 5 seed, with the potential to
rise or fall based on their performance at Arizona State and
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Although the NCAA Tournament selection committee uses an
undisclosed ratings formula and considers other factors _ some
subjective, some not _ the RPI and Sagarin rankings are usually an
accurate gauge of what to expect on Selection Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   That said, a sweep in the desert probably would solidify a No. 4
seed for the Bruins and possibly push them to a No. 3. If they get
swept, however, they'll likely be a No. 5 or 6 seed.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, they're trying not to think about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put too much energy into what seed and what region, you
can carry with you a feeling of disappointment,'' Bruins coach
Steve Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, UCLA won the Pacific-10 title by three games
and expected a spot in the West. Instead it was shipped to
Indianapolis to play Princeton and never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``That threw us for a loop,'' Lavin said. ``No one expected
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine from the line: UCLA shot 69 percent from the foul line
against Washington _ its best performance since shooting 81 percent
against Cal State Northridge on Dec. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep shooting them (in practice), and we're not talking
about it a lot,'' Lavin said. ``When you talk about it, it becomes
an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Guard Baron Davis was the most improved last week, hitting 10 of
13 to raise his season percentage to 61.2.
</P>
<P>
   The Farnham factor: Walk-on junior Sean Farnham started his
fourth consecutive game Saturday and continued his inspired play.
When asked what he'd have thought three months ago if told Farnham
would be a starter down the stretch, Lavin smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have guessed it had more to do with discipline: Six
guys late for the bus, or seven guys missed practice,'' he said.
``I wouldn't have guessed it would have come about by his
contributions.''
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: Forward JaRon Rush had 21 rebounds against the
Washington schools, raising his average to 8.0 in Pac-10 play.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins made 8 of 21 shots from 3-point range against
Washington State and 1 of 13 against Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In the past six games, UCLA has held its opponents to 39.3
percent shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins defeated the Washington schools by 56 points _ their
largest victory margin in a conference weekend in 21 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-99 2144EST &QL; 
