<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, MARCH 2
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-INTERNET-ADS-NYT (moved on Thursday, Feb. 25)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, Feb. 25,
about the blurring of distinctions between advertising and
editorial content on the World Wide Web referred incompletely to
two Web sites. On CNNfn's site, the travel page presents services
and promotions from a travel agency along with news articles, but
its editors say they feel the distinction is clear. On Baby Center,
where search results include promotions for advertisers, the
company notes that each result is labeled as editorial content,
sponsored information, or an opportunity to make a purchase.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SAFRICA-FEUD-NYT (moved on Friday, Jan. 15)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, Jan. 15,
about a new autobiography by F.W. de Klerk, the former President of
South Africa, misstated publication plans in the United States
because of erroneous information provided by a publicist.
Macmillan, which has published the book _ ``The Last Trek: A New
Beginning'' _ in Britain and South Africa, informed The Times last
week that the book is in fact to be published in the United States,
by its St. Martin's Press division on June 1.
</P>
<P>
   BC-IBM-INTEL-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Feb. 24)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Feb.
24, about how the International Business Machines Corporation is
addressing privacy concerns raised by a traceable serial number on
Intel Corporation's new Pentium III computer chip misstated Intel's
response to those concerns. Intel has suggested that computer
manufacturers install an on-off switch in each computer that allows
the user to hide the chip's serial number when the switch is turned
off. Intel has not suggested that manufacturers leave the switch
turned off.
</P>
</TEXT>
