<DOCNO> NYT19990301.0449 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3798 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MOVIE-TICKETS-NYT &LR;      03-01 0331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MOVIE-TICKETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$9.50 MOVIE TICKETS? VALLONE URGES A POPCORN PROTEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ City Council Speaker Peter Vallone, asked New Yorkers
Monday to stage a one-day boycott of movie theaters on Friday as an
expression of anger over ticket prices that were raised to $9.50
last week at some Manhattan theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``An absolute outrage,'' Vallone said Monday afternoon. ``It's
unfair. It's a mugging of the middle class. Do something else on
Friday. Anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   The $9.50 movie ticket, the highest in the nation, was
introduced on Friday at Loews, Cineplex Odeon and Sony Theaters in
New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone said he hoped that prices approaching $10 would stir
Manhattan moviegoers to action. But both he and Ed Koch, the former
mayor, acknowledged that an attempt by Koch to organize a boycott
bombed badly in 1988, when ticket prices rose to $7 from $6.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said I would picket as long as one person was behind me,''
Koch said Monday. ``I looked behind me when I got to the theaters;
nobody was there. So I bought a ticket and saw the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   The rise in ticket prices was defended by Lawrence Ruisi,
president and chief executive of Loew's Cineplex Entertainment
Inc., who said the ticket prices were raised to keep pace with
increasing operating costs. ``Mr. Vallone may be forgetting that we
don't keep all the revenue,'' Ruisi said. ``Half of it goes to the
Hollywood distributors.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket prices were raised at the chain's 425 theaters in 22
states and Canada. Prices increased to $8.50 from $8 in Chicago,
and to $7.75 from $7 in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The average cost of a movie ticket nationwide was $4.75 in 1997,
the latest year available, said David Lamb, an independent
financial analyst for the movie-theater industry. Movie theaters
have thin profits in general, Lamb said. ``You make it on the
popcorn, and the tickets, but the margins have always been slim,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-99 2149EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
