<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990301.0450 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3799 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-01 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WHEN in doubt, talk about the RPI and act like you know what it
means.
</P>
<P>
   Put your hand on your chin, raise one eyebrow professorially,
nod your head a lot, and talk about the Ratings Percentage Index.
</P>
<P>
   Say things like, ``You know, Factor One in the RPI is weighted
25 percent, and it's based on a team's winning percentage. Factor
Two is strength of schedule, and it's weighted 50 percent. Factor
Three is a team's opponents' strength of schedule against Division
I teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about the important if unofficial Factor Four _ quality
losses. Mention the College of Charleston a lot _ predict a No. 4
seed for the COC based on their S.O.S. (strength of schedule).
</P>
<P>
   Mention the Big Ten, Big East and Southeastern Conference as
big-timers. Talk about Stanford, UConn and Auburn as potential
threats. Talk about ``site-neutral wins,'' the ``mid-major
conferences'' _ the Missouri Valley and the Ohio Valley _ and how
they figure to make quite a splash in the Big Dance.
</P>
<P>
   You'll surely wow the casual college basketball fan and impress
those bracket-happy faithful who rear their heads around the water
coolers, like tax accountants, usually only in March.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to act like you really know everything there is to
know about the soon-to-be-released 1999 NCAA Tournament bracket,
these are the things you should say and do.
</P>
<P>
   But if you really want to know what the madness will be all
about this March, know this: This week's conference tournament
games might offer more intrigue, entertainment and suspense than
the NCAA Tournament once the bracket is set Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   This year, filling in the NCAA blanks will be fun. But
ultimately, the answer is Duke.
</P>
<P>
   To those who say Duke's unprecedented Atlantic Coast Conference
sweep is misleading because the conference allegedly is down, we
have only one thing to say. Humbug.
</P>
<P>
   Haven't you been paying attention the past 80 years? The ACC
always has been one of the best basketball conferences in America,
and nothing changed this year except the greatness of the team that
won it.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, we arrive at conference-tournament week and the brink of
the NCAAs not knowing exactly which teams will offer thrills and
last-second chills for the next month but certain it will be the
Blue Devils left dancing on the floor of Tropicana Field when all
is done.
</P>
<P>
   Hate to burst your bubble teams. Hate to put a damper on Dick
Vitale's diaper dandies. Certainly, we should all diligently fill
out the office pools and tune in for the madness, which never fails
to entertain.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, the suspense will be in the journey, not the
outcome. And maybe the best part of that journey, certainly the
most unpredictable, begins now.
</P>
<P>
   The case could be made that except for Duke's dominance, this
has been the most balanced, most unpredictable year in college
basketball in recent memory. Which is why, outside the ACC,
conference tournaments might be at their best, too.
</P>
<P>
   Some 300 teams enter conference tournaments with the dream of
making it into the March mayhem. Except for the bottom 100 or so of
those teams, there is legitimate hope of racking up enough upsets
to make the field.
</P>
<P>
   Look no further than the Big 12 or Western Athletic Conference
for evidence that anything could happen this week. Texas is the
team to beat in the Big 12, but with the league certainly balanced
at the top and the tourney in Kansas City, the likes of Missouri
and Kansas must be feared.
</P>
<P>
   In the WAC, Utah looks like it could cruise in, but New Mexico,
Tulsa, Nevada-Las Vegas and Rice are playing at their best.
</P>
<P>
   At conference tournaments everywhere from Richmond, Va.
(Mid-Eastern), to Shreveport, La. (Southland), to Ogden, Utah (Big
Sky), hope will spring eternal.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous questions will have to be answered. Can New Mexico, a
team in the Top 25 most of the season despite a low RPI ranking, be
invited to the NCAAs if it doesn't win the WAC tournament? Is
Auburn, at the top of the tough SEC, the real deal? Will the
talented Cincinnati Bearcats, whose four losses all came in
Conference USA play, survive the likes of Alabama-Birmingham,
Louisville and DePaul?
</P>
<P>
   Can quality Big Ten teams Minnesota, Purdue and Northwestern
advance far enough in their tournament to give their league a sixth
and maybe even a seventh NCAA Tournament team? Can upstart Miami
hustle to the Big East conference title and maybe earn a No. 1 or
No. 2 seed?
</P>
<P>
   Can bubble teams like Nebraska (Big 12), Wake Forest (ACC),
Rhode Island (Atlantic 10) and Ole Miss (SEC) impress enough to
land a bid? Can Western Kentucky, which carries a losing record
(13-15) into today's Sun Belt final against Arkansas State, pull
out the unlikely bid?
</P>
<P>
   Pay attention to it all. Enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road, we know what will happen in St. Petersburg, Fla.,
the Final Four host city that once was known as ``God's waiting
room'' because of its attraction to retirees. This year, in an
interesting twist, it will be the Devils' waiting room.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean it won't be fun getting there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
