<DOCNO> NYT19990301.0451 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3801 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CHINA-RIGHTS-NYT     03-01 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CHINA-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CHINA'S HUMAN RIGHTS RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, March 2: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A disturbing pattern is developing in the Clinton
administration's relationship with China. The more Washington seeks
to broaden its agenda with Beijing, the more harshly China treats
its democrats and dissidents. In the face of a new wave of
political repression in China, President Clinton and Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright must do more than repeat stale complaints
and then change the subject to trade. Americans will not support a
policy of engagement and improved relations with China if the price
is American inaction on human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Albright traveled to China this week just days after the State
Department published a withering report on repression in China. It
found that in 1998 Chinese leaders broke their promises to respect
international human rights conventions, held thousands of political
critics and religious activists in prison, tortured detainees and
tightened restrictions on the press. Beijing has been using long
prison sentences to crush the formation of independent political
parties.
</P>
<P>
   Albright talked bluntly about the dismal record in her meetings
with Chinese officials Monday, as she has done before. That seemed
sufficient when China's conduct was improving, but as President
Jiang Zemin has tightened controls on political expression in
recent months, the American criticism has seemed increasingly
hollow and ineffectual. Albright's words were further muffled by
the primary purpose of her visit, which was to advance the
administration's policy of building diplomatic links with China,
specifically by advancing Beijing's entry into the World Trade
Organization and preparing for a smooth visit to Washington next
month by China's prime minister, Zhu Rongji.
</P>
<P>
   Washington can act more forcefully on human rights by sponsoring
a new United Nations resolution on Chinese abuses in Geneva later
this month. Last year, for the first time since 1991, the United
States did not support a resolution condemning China before the
U.N. human rights commission in Geneva. The administration hoped
that this gesture would encourage Beijing to ease political
repression. American silence on the issue this year would be
unconscionable.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang and his fellow communist leaders fear social unrest. As
economic growth has diminished because of Asia's financial crisis
and Beijing's own incomplete economic reforms, political protests
have spread and the government has tried to intimidate those who
favor greater freedom and democracy. But as Clinton noted last
week, sooner or later China will have to realize that it ``cannot
purchase stability at the expense of freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   If the repression grows worse in the weeks ahead, the
administration may have to reconsider its commitment not to link
China's admission to the WTO to its human rights performance. For
now, the membership decision will depend on Beijing's willingness
to lower tariffs to international standards. Concerned that too
rapid an exposure to free trade will increase Chinese unemployment
and unrest, Beijing wants an extended transition period. Some
accommodation is reasonable. But the point of admitting China into
the WTO is to bring it more fully under the rules of the
international trading system. Excessively watering down those rules
to have an agreement ready in time for Zhu's visit to Washington
would be a mistake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-99 2151EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990301.0452 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3802 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENIORLOVE-AZR &LR;      03-01 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENIORLOVE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHALLENGE TO MARRIAGE OF EX-NAVAL OFFICER, 99, AND BRIDE, 38,
REJECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUN CITY, Ariz. _ (STORY ALSO MOVING IN ``A'' CATEGORY) Lorraine
DeJongh says it was love, not money, that led her to marry a
wealthy 99-year-old retired naval commander.
</P>
<P>
   And now a judge has paved the way for the 38-year-old caregiver
and her legally blind, wheelchair-using groom to cruise off into
the sunset together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sent here to do a job, which I did well, and the media
criticized me for falling in love,'' DeJongh said Monday after a
judge dismissed a petition for guardianship of her husband, Edward
Gamble, by his grandson.
</P>
<P>
   In the petition, Gary Gamble alleged his grandfather was
incapacitated and that the elderly man's estate of nearly $1
million was in jeopardy of being exploited by DeJongh.
</P>
<P>
   But the grandson agreed to drop the case and walk away with only
$17,779 after a psychological evaluation showed the elder Gamble to
be a ``fond spouse'' and competent to make financial decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``In short, my client did have to pay his grandson off in order
to get his grandson to leave him alone,'' said Edward Gamble's
attorney, Alisa Gray.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's settlement ends the final challenge to the
made-for-tabloids marriage that provided red-hot fodder for radio
talk shows, with hosts and callers alike questioning DeJongh's
motives for marrying a wealthy, ailing man more than 60 years her
senior less than two weeks after divorcing another Phoenix-area
man.
</P>
<P>
   Peoria Justice of the Peace Lex Anderson refused to marry the
couple Dec. 31 because he didn't believe Edward Gamble to be
mentally competent. The couple turned to Glendale Justice of the
Peace Quentin Tolby, who married the couple less than an hour later
after asking Gamble a series of questions to test his mental
awareness.
</P>
<P>
   The Maricopa County Attorney's Office then began looking into
the marriage, and concluded last month it is legal.
</P>
<P>
   DeJongh declined to comment further, other than to say she was
surprised by the media frenzy over her marriage. Edward Gamble also
declined comment, saying he is angry with the media coverage of his
marriage, his attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's completely surprised that his decisions have caused such
an uproar,'' Gray said. ``He feels that he is completely in control
of his faculties, and he just likes to be married. He is in love
with Lorraine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone assumes she's a gold digger and everyone assumes he
is out of his mind. That's been very frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   A Jan. 29 psychological evaluation said Edward Gamble was
thinking of DeJongh's honor when the couple tied the knot New
Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Gamble stated that he married her because she's fun to be
with, and they wed for companionship and affection, not for sex,''
said the report by a court-appointed psychologist, Dr. Pamela
Wilson of Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``He believes that if a man wants to `cuddle' with a woman, they
ought to be married, and is aware it's not really something you can
expect of paid caregivers,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the age difference and the fact DeJongh has been
married four times, Edward Gamble said ``he feels he's found the
perfect arrangement _ a woman who will provide the supportive care
he now requires, whom he finds enjoyable, attractive, and a good
cook, and who seemingly reciprocates his affection and interest.''
</P>
<P>
   The report called the groom ``feisty with a keen, dry sense of
humor'' and even commented on the couple's ``practical yet playful
style of interaction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He had her give him a few `smooches,' and winking at me after
she left, he said, `That was just for show!' '' Wilson wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The senior Gamble also said he decided to revoke his trust _
which gave Gary Gamble power of attorney over his estate _ not
because of pressure by DeJongh but out of ``increasing discomfort
with the way his grandson was handling his finances,'' the report
stated.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Gamble, who lives in Alabama, could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix attorney Paul Blunt, hired by Gary Gamble to investigate
the matter, said that the younger Gamble ``was just trying to
protect his grandfather, and unfortunately his grandfather doesn't
see it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretty well resigned to the fact his grandfather has
decided to favor someone else, despite what he's done for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation and psychological evaluation led the grandson
to drop his petition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We determined that it was best at this point to reach some
sort of an accommodation,'' Blunt said. ``We could argue the merit
of his (Edward Gamble's) decision, the morality of his decision.
That's not our place.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Gamble has two other grandchildren but hasn't had a
meaningful relationship with them, Blunt said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the settlement signed Monday by Maricopa County
Superior Court Commissioner Gary Donahoe, Gary Gamble was allowed
to retain $17,779 he distributed to himself from his grandfather's
trust, and Blunt was allowed to keep $12,000. The grandson also
agreed to turn over the warranty deed to Edward Gamble's Sun City
home.
</P>
<P>
   Also, a third-party trustee, Colonial Trust, was appointed to
oversee Gamble's estate, which, according to court records, is
worth $934,000.
</P>
<P>
   The couple now apparently plan to continue Edward Gamble's
favorite pastime _ taking cruises.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Gamble and DeJongh took a 59-day, $60,000 South
American cruise during which the captain performed a ``mock
marriage,'' complete with a celebration, court records show.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's genuinely fond of him. He definitely is fond of her,''
Gray said. &QL; 
Michael Murphy can be reached at 444-7126 or at
michael.murphy(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-99 2154EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
