<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV07-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON CALL WITH THE HIGHWAY PATROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 7)  
 (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The best way to avoid becoming a traffic statistic, according to
Charles F. Richmond of the Connecticut Department of
Transportation, is to check your tires before a trip. All five.
</P>
<P>
   If you bought your car used, you may have a spare with a leak or
without air, or a doughnut spare that does not match your wheel. Or
no spare at all. Richmond, who works for a highway-safety program,
spends seven hours a day on the road five days a week, along the
stretch of I-95 between Norwalk and Bridgeport. And tire problems
rank first among the difficulties he sees.
</P>
<P>
   Driving with underinflated tires is a big cause of flats, he
says, because they get damaged and blow out, particularly in summer
when they get hot. Then a defective or nonexistent spare turns what
might be a 20-minute delay into a serious problem.
</P>
<P>
   Richmond, who looks like a smiling Brian Dennehy, wears a
reflective vest and a Day-Glo orange cap and drives a heavy
custom-designed yellow truck that tows a long device to protect it
in rear-end crashes.
</P>
<P>
   But he still pulls into the breakdown lane warily, rooftop
flashers alight. Despite all, he fears being a pedestrian on a
turnpike. The impact absorber in back has saved him and the truck
once already.
</P>
<P>
   During the weekday afternoon shift I spent with Richmond, on
Feb. 11, we did not encounter a major crash _ only a minor one. But
he uttered an anxious ``Uh-oh, that's dangerous'' when he heard a
report to a colleague: ``Pedestrian on median strip, Exit 41.'' In
that area, the median is lined by concrete walls called Jersey
barriers.
</P>
<P>
   At the garage in Milford at the end of the shift, we met the
colleague, David Rodriguez. ``I thought he was dead, for sure,''
Rodriguez said, referring to the motorist. ``He got a flat on the
left rear, and he did everything OK. He pulled into the center
breakdown lane, as tight as he could, and while he was changing the
tire, some guy who wasn't paying attention hit his rear end and
there were five cars in it before it was over. The car shoved the
guy against the Jersey barrier. But he was OK.''
</P>
<P>
   The program Richmond and his colleagues work for is called Champ
_ Connecticut Highway Assistance Motorist Patrol. It began in April
1996 as part of a joint state-federal program to keep traffic
flowing on a 56-mile stretch of I-95 _ between the New York state
line and the exit for Branford, just east of New Haven _ that
carries 115,000 vehicles daily. Richmond sees his first job as
safety, but since that means clearing disabled cars, he also
eliminates lane blockages and rubbernecking, which slow traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy trucks are labeled ``Service Patrol,'' and the people
on patrol can talk to one another or headquarters in Bridgeport. At
headquarters, shared with State Police Troop G, 30 television
monitors display views provided by 91 cameras along the turnpike
and in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Richmond is a devotee of the cell phone. ``It has saved more
lives than the ambulances,'' he says. He urges those who drive a
lot to carry one. There is no charge for dialing 911; this number,
by federal law, can be dialed even when other service has been cut
off for nonpayment. And passing drivers can report accidents and
breakdowns they spot.
</P>
<P>
   If a tire goes flat on limited-access highways like Interstates,
Richmond says, get as far as possible from the traffic flow. ``Your
tire's shot anyway,'' he said. ``One in 30 can be repaired. So you
might as well drive on it to an exit if one is near. If you get
only to the breakdown lane, all it takes is one sleepy driver and
you've lost your whole car.''
</P>
<P>
   If the car has failed mechanically and will not move, Richmond
says, drivers who cannot call for help should hang a ``Get Help''
or ``Call Police'' sign in the window facing traffic. Then they
should stay inside the car with seat belts fastened. Passing cars
with cell phones will report the problem. He wishes that more road
atlases and maps would have a sheet printed with a ``Help''
message.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Richmond said that 50 percent of the mechanical problem he sees
are caused by broken timing belts. These belts, which keep the
valves opening in proper synchronization, essential to an engine's
operation, should be replaced after 60,000 to 70,000 miles, he
said, but many drivers have not read their owner's manual closely
enough to know this.
</P>
<P>
   On the shift I monitored, Richmond changed a right front tire
for a young couple in a small car. They had pulled up, but were
still inside when we arrived. Richmond used his heavy jack to raise
the car, lifted the spare on and, naturally, had to pump it up with
an air tank he fetched from the truck.
</P>
<P>
   The couple said they were headed to the next exit anyway and
would stop to buy a tire. Richmond was dubious. He called
headquarters: ``Problem 9, Solution 9,'' he reported, meaning
``flat tire'' and ``changed tire.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Bridgeport headquarters, these numerical reports are
collated. According to the January statistics for these 56 miles of
I-95, plus pieces of feeder highway, four trucks working two
daytime shifts took a total of 73 hours 27 minutes to deal with
problems. Of this, almost 21 hours was for 95 flat tires. Although
mechanical trouble led the listing _ 114 out of 545 incidents _
this took only 16 hours 51 minutes. The patrol seldom fixes engine
problems, and usually just gets the vehicle off the road.
</P>
<P>
   Unoccupied vehicles accounted for 100 reports, but these took
only three hours because the patrols simply leave cards saying
``Sorry We Missed You.'' The police later put a red sticker on the
side-view mirror, and the car will be towed if not removed
promptly; the owners pay for the towing and storage.
</P>
<P>
   Other significant problems on the log are ``out of gas,'' 47
reports; accident, 41; disabled vehicle or debris in the road, 37
reports each. The patrol carries enough gas to enable a car to get
off to a filling station. In crashes, it calls the police and tries
to get all the movable cars off the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not the way it used to be, that nothing should be
moved,'' he said. ``We need to clear the way and get traffic moving
before other crashes. Drivers can exchange information at the
bottom of the ramp just as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Disabled cars are pushed off. Debris is removed with a crane on
the truck; gas and oil slicks can be blotted up. The truck carries
water for radiators, jumpers for batteries.
</P>
<P>
   A real bane, Richmond said, is stray animals. The patrols have
to lead dogs off, which is sometimes tricky, even with flashers
going.
</P>
<P>
   Richmond does not recommend pulling onto the breakdown lane for
a routine cell-phone call; he considers it too dangerous. For those
regularly doing business while driving, he urges the no-hands cell
phone; otherwise, use a service area or drive down an exit ramp.
For his brief calls while driving, he uses cell phones with
programmed numbers, CBs and other devices.
</P>
<P>
   The patrols operate Monday to Friday, 6 a.m. to 6:30 p.m. Last
summer, a shift was added on Sunday evening to ease westbound
traffic. This year's plan is still being discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're in trouble on our highway in our hours,'' Richmond
said, ``just stay put. We'll be along pretty soon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
