<HEADER>
A3808 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COLD-CASES-935&AMP;ADD     03-01 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLD-CASES-935&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SQUAD IN HOT PURSUIT OF CRIMES GROWN COLD
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fernando Leon, a numbers runner with the nickname
Benny tattooed on his arm, was getting madder and madder at Grace
Meullins. The woman kept bothering him for the $700 that she said
he owed her daughter. Then she hit him over the head with a
flashlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stewed over it and he was drinking,'' Ronald Balzan, a
homicide detective, remembered later.
</P>
<P>
   People on the street said Leon had a frightful temper. He got a
gun, which he hid in a plastic bag, and went looking for Grace
Meullins near the old Brooklyn Navy Yard. He ran into the daughter,
Christina, and got into a shouting match. Her brother, Benjamin,
showed up, so Leon pumped two bullets into him. Christina ran
around the corner and tried to hide behind a garbage bin. He shot
her three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shot the guy right off the bat, killed him,'' Balzan said.
``She hid behind the Dumpster, cowering, begging for her life. But
he killed her, too.''
</P>
<P>
   This was on July 20, 1994. Leon got on a southbound bus at the
Port Authority and disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   And that, in the normal course of events, would have been that.
</P>
<P>
   But the case folder, No. 96,231, was forwarded to the Cold Case
Squad, a three-year-old detective unit of the New York Police
Department that chases down unsolved cases that the regular
detective squads lack the time or resources to deal with. While
crime is down all over the city, these detectives are dealing with
the residue of a more violent time.
</P>
<P>
   The squad caught Leon, who is doing 45{ years to life for the
double murder. Not only that, but in reinterviewing witnesses to
the crime, Balzan also uncovered evidence that suggested Leon had
killed another man in the Bronx more than 17 years ago, and he is
awaiting trial on that charge.
</P>
<P>
   Through a computer network that traces financial records, Balzan
found that someone who might have been Leon had been paid a few
hundred dollars working at a chicken processing plant in Jackson,
Miss. It was a lucky break, because Leon had kept a low profile,
below most record-keeping.
</P>
<P>
   But it seemed more like the right man when the plant manager
told him the man was ``a scary guy'' who drank and had a temper.
Leon, the detective said, was ``totally surprised'' when he showed
up to arrest him, and the woman he was living with was ``stunned.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife in Brooklyn _ she had given him the gun _ now told
Balzan about another murder in the Bronx, back when their baby boy
was just standing up in his crib. That would have been 1981, so the
detective sorted through old cases in the Bronx until he found the
murder of Dr. Victor Soto, 29, whose attacker chased him down,
stabbed him and cut his throat. Balzan was able to build a case
tying Leon to that killing, in which the tattoo was a clue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the luxury of time, the luxury of being able to
concentrate on these cases,'' said Capt. Raymond Ferrari, the squad
commander. ``In a regular squad, you always have a new rape, a new
murder coming through the door. Or you can have a high profile case
and have to use everybody. You can make the best plans in the world
and something will come through the door.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the unit was formed in February 1996, Ferrari said, it has
cleared 280 old homicide cases, 180 by making arrests on cases his
detectives had built, 61 by capturing suspects who had eluded other
detectives and 39 by ``exceptional clearance,'' usually meaning
that the suspect was dead. All told, he said, they had arrested or
caught 595 suspects.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1998 fiscal year, according to figures in Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's management report issued last September, the Cold Case
Squad selected 273 cases to investigate and cleared 122 by arrests.
Homicides accounted for 244 of the 273 cases, and 93 of those were
cleared. Three-quarters of the homicides had occurred within the
last eight years, but 20 percent were nine to 18 years old and one
was 28 years old.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Police Department says, there is a 90 percent
clearance rate for homicides. But Andrew Karmen, a professor at
John Jay College of Criminal Justice, said that figure was
artificially high because of the way the FBI keeps statistics. When
the homicides are counted for a given year, unsolved crimes from
earlier years are not included in the total, Karmen said, but old
crimes that have been newly solved are. Thus New York's figures are
improved by its success in solving old murders. He estimated that
the department was solving roughly 60 percent of current cases.
</P>
<P>
   The 36 detectives on the squad all have at least 15 years on the
force. The unit's lieutenants regularly visit other detective
squads to go through the files looking for possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``You pull out the old ones and read them through,'' Lt. John
Dove said. ``Maybe there's reluctant witnesses 10 or 12 years ago.
You see different things that might indicate there's meat on this
case. Every time I read through a case I might find something new.
Or there might be a certain kind of case that just sticks with you,
say a young girl was killed.''
</P>
<P>
   While it has traditionally been thought that most crimes that
are not solved quickly are rarely solved, the Cold Case detectives
say that this is not necessarily so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time goes by,'' Ferrari said, ``and sometimes time can be to
our advantage. It could be an area that was controlled by a drug
gang. But now that gang is gone, and a teen-age witness back then
could be a legitimate adult now, and willing to come forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Detective Thomas F. Mansfield added: ``Allegiances change.
Today's husband might be tomorrow's enemy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While technological advances like computer networks and better
DNA testing techniques have helped, Ferrari and the others said
that much of their success was old-fashioned police work, mostly
talking to people and getting them to talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you have to nurture them,'' said Detective Pat
Lanigan, recalling a case in Bensonhurst in which he talked to the
girlfriend of a drug addict who, it turned out, had stabbed his
dealer 15 times and cut his throat to steal $500 and eight bags of
heroin. The addict was dissuaded from stabbing the girlfriend in
the shower, to keep her quiet about the killing, only after she
pleaded that she was the mother of their child.
</P>
<P>
   ``She decided to give up the entire thing,'' Lanigan said.
``That poor woman, she just broke down to us. She said, `I always
wanted to to tell the police, but I was afraid.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the case was clinched by DNA evidence. Lanigan found
a down jacket the man had asked the girlfriend to wash. Although
the medical examiner thought the chances of its still having a
bloodstain were ``slim to none,'' the detective insisted it be
tested.
</P>
<P>
   But it was talking to the woman that provided the breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where experience comes in,'' Mansfield said. ``It's the
interaction with the witnesses. Sometimes you'll read a case file
and think, `I wouldn't have asked the question that way.' You're
building a data bank. Sometimes people will tell you something
important, and they don't even know they're telling you. But you
walk out of there knowing you just hit the gold mine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
