<HEADLINE>
AMWEST, ATTENDANTS STILL FAR APART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER CORBETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ America West Airline and its flight attendants union
can't even agreeon how much they disagree.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides appeared to be no closer to a contract agreement
on Monday despite information the company released Saturday
indicating that the wage gap had closed by $10.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over how far apart the two sides remain seems to
show that the Tempe-based carrier and the Association of Flight
Attendants Council 66 have a way to go before they agree on a
contract for about 2,400 flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   The union, which is threatening to strike after March 19,
remains $16.5 million apart on a contract with America West,
according to Jeff Zack, AFA communications director.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Garger, America West's vice president of labor relations,
figures the gap at $5.8 million. That's based on America West's
proposal of $68.7 million and the union's proposal of $74.5
million, Garger said.
</P>
<P>
   Those figures include the total new costs over the five years of
the contract. America West's labor costs for flight attendants
totaled $67.6 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   The union has never previously disputed the $68.7 million figure
that the company presented during federally mediated bargaining
sessions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The union listed the value of its proposal at $74.5 million in a
letter to flight attendants last week.
</P>
<P>
   Bill McGlashen, AFA Council 66 president, said the union does
not accept that the company's offer is worth $68.7 million in new
costs, and contested that figure during negotiations. He said
America West is including $10 million in costs that it would have
incurred even without this contract.
</P>
<P>
   He pegs America West's offer at $58 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``America West is throwing numbers around to attempt to confuse
the issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Garger said the company has been consistent in stating the
value of its offer. He accused the union of having a moving target
on what it wants in the contract.
</P>
<P>
   A Feb. 12 letter from America West Chairman William Bill Franke
to flight attendants mentions the company's offer of $68.7 million.
Each flight attendant also received a personalized letter dated
Feb. 22 in which the company spells out the details of how its
proposal would affect that employee.
</P>
<P>
   The union's letter to its members, dated Feb. 24, includes
information to clarify the company's offer but does not dispute the
$68.7 million figure.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the union and America West remain at odds on an
agreement and no negotiating meetings have been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Talks are expected in the final week before the strike deadline
on March 19 at 10 p.m. Arizona time.
</P>
<P>
   America West is offering an average pay increase of 44.7 percent
over the life of the contract, and the pay rates would be 90
percent of what Southwest Airlines pays its flight attendants,
according to Franke's letter.
</P>
<P>
   The company also is offering a $1.1 million signing bonus that
would be distributed by the AFA to the flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   America West's flight attendants have been seeking a contract
since 1994 when they voted for representation by the AFA. A
tentative contract was rejected in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Talks on the contract broke down in late January. The National
Mediation Board declared an impasse last month and set the March 19
strike date after a 30-day cooling-off period. &QL; 
Peter Corbett can be reached at 444-4815 or at
peter.corbett(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
