<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: GUESS WHAT CALIFORNIA IS DREAMING OF NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an Editorial Observer on Tuesday,
March 2: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ People who covet their neighbors' goods
always overestimate how much happier they would be if they got
them. This rule is particularly true when applied to spouses, and
perhaps giant TV satellite dishes. But it also works for
presidential primaries.
</P>
<P>
   California has long been dissatisfied with its June primary, and
envious of the states that vote earlier. California regards itself
as the Land of the Future, but picking presidential nominees after
most of the candidates have already crashed and burned made people
feel non-cutting-edge, a retro electorate. So the state
legislature, after some struggle, moved the date to March 7. You
would not believe how happy the California politicians think this
is going to make them. The place where a state senate campaign can
very easily cost $1 million believes it is going to turn into a
political New Hampshire. ``The voters will get a chance to meet the
candidates on a retail basis,'' the state Republican chairman told
his party convention here last weekend, calling up visions of
George W. Bush shaking hands at Orange County malls while Elizabeth
Dole hits a string of house parties in Chico.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Jones, the secretary of state, has been telling people that
on the day California pushed up its election all the Republican
presidential candidates ripped up their position papers and tossed
them in the wastebasket. And why? ``Because they were all written
for New York!'' Jones says triumphantly. ``Now they're going to
have to talk about our issues!'' New York has an early primary, and
Californians seem to believe that in 1996 Bob Dole and Pat Buchanan
were running around arguing how to get the PCBs out of the Hudson
River while Steve Forbes promised to personally finance the
construction of the Second Avenue subway tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the Republican presidential candidates showed up for
the state convention, and that was regarded as the first sign of
the glories to come. ``California's early primary is already having
results!'' announced a Sacramento anchorwoman triumphantly. Neither
Ms. Dole nor Bush made an appearance, and to be frank, some of the
contenders who did show up were not exactly tough to capture. But
they all competed to see who could make more frequent references to
the fact that California represents the future, or come up with the
most flattering way to describe the new primary. (Sen. John McCain
won with ``of transcendent importance.'')
</P>
<P>
   California Republicans needed all the bolstering they could get,
having lost the governor's race by more than 20 percent last
November. ``This crowd seems a little quiet and serious,''
Insurance Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush told the convention
dinner. This was perhaps because Quackenbush is, after Jones, now
the most important Republican elected official in the state. The
surviving Republican leaders continually vowed to regroup _ the
word ``unity'' was perhaps mentioned even more often than
``future.'' But when the presidential candidate Lamar Alexander
expressed his intense desire to ``see the California agenda as part
of the presidential campaign,'' he may have been the only one in
the room with any idea of what that agenda might comprise.
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt that the new primary is going to pack a wallop,
although not necessarily the one the parties have in mind. In
California, even candidates for governor barely bother to shake
hands or even hold campaign rallies _ the place is just too big for
the personal touch. What California has done, however, is to create
a stampede to the front of the election-year calendar. So many
states have moved or are moving their primaries to March 7 that
it's very likely the nominees will be chosen on that day, in an
incredibly expensive bicoastal war of TV advertising.
</P>
<P>
   In a campaign that's going to be as time-compressed as this one,
the candidates will stick to issues so general they will make
``compassionate conservatism'' look like a computer printout, and
attacks on the opposition so specific that someone's vote for a
2,000-page budget will be transformed into ``supported spending
$400,000 for midnight basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if the contenders are trading meaningless sound bites,
California is thrilled with the idea that they'll be trading more
meaningless sound bites here than anyplace else. ``We have finally
moved up to the front,'' rhapsodized Jones, who asserted, in a
burst of enthusiasm, that 25 percent of all Americans live in his
state. The primary that decides the presidential nominees might
come too early, cost too much money and be too driven by TV ads.
But on the plus side, as Smith pointed out, California is
``representative of the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
