</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUBWAY-BOMBING-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIAN GETS LIFE TERM FOR PLOTTING SUBWAY BOMB 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Palestinian immigrant convicted of plotting to bomb
the New York City subway was sentenced Monday to life in prison,
after bitterly denouncing Israeli treatment of the Palestinian
people and U.S. support for Israel.
</P>
<P>
   In sentencing the defendant, Gazi Ibrahim Abu Mezer, for his
plan to plant a powerful, nail-studded pipe bomb, Judge Reena Raggi
of U.S. District Court in Brooklyn said that ``whatever has
occurred in Mezer's life'' did not justify his desire to make
average New Yorkers ``bear the consequences of his hatred and
frustration.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes before Ms. Raggi, who could have chosen a lesser
sentence, imposed the life term, Abu Mezer recited a list of
grievances against the Jewish people, from Biblical days to the
present. He also maintained that it was ``a lie'' that the Nazis
killed 6 million Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Reading a statement in heavily accented English, Abu Mezer, 25,
a slight, bearded man wearing a Muslim skullcap, said, ``I lived
under the Israeli army occupation for 20 years, facing all kind of
suffering from the aggression of the Israeli army.'' He was
convicted in July of possession of the bomb, and of threatening and
conspiring to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Mezer, who was born and raised in the West Bank, arrived in
the United States illegally from Canada several months before he
was arrested with the pipe bomb in his Brooklyn apartment in July
1997.
</P>
<P>
   In his court statement, he said Palestinian land, houses and
businesses had been confiscated by the Israelis, including his
family's house. He said he and his relatives had been beaten and
arrested during the Israeli occupation of the West Bank, and that
as a teen-ager during the Palestinian resistance known as the
intifada, he had been twice arrested and tortured by Israeli
authorities, who wanted him to identify friends who had thrown
stones at Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   A defense lawyer, Lawrence F. Ruggiero, said Abu Mezer's past
experience, while ``not an excuse'' for the crimes for which he was
convicted, justified imposing a sentence less severe than life in
prison. Under federal law, there is no possibility of parole.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Raggi rejected this appeal. She noted the complex
circumstances that brought Abu Mezer to this point, and said, ``It
is always sad to see a human being _ a young man _ so consumed with
hatred.'' Nevertheless, she said, her task was to deal with the
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not to address public debate about either the domestic
policy of Israel or the foreign policy of the United States,'' she
said, adding that evidence at Abu Mezer's trial showed that the
police raid on his apartment, in which he was shot and wounded,
came ``literally hours before'' he planned to place the bomb in the
subway.
</P>
<P>
   In a case that generated nightmarish visions of another
terrorist attack in a city where the World Trade Center had been
bombed in 1993, the police and federal agents said Abu Mezer's bomb
could have killed scores of people.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors in the U.S. attorney's office in Brooklyn have said
they found no evidence linking Abu Mezer to any known terrorist
group.
</P>
<P>
   His courtroom account of having been tortured by the Israelis
could not be confirmed, and his older brother, Nour, said after his
arrest that ``he exaggerated a lot.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   During the trial, when Abu Mezer testified against the advice of
his lawyers, he said he had intended the bomb as a suicide attack
in which he hoped to kill as many Jews as possible, although he
maintained that the bomb was not to have been placed in the subway.
</P>
<P>
   But an FBI agent testified that Abu Mezer said after his arrest
that he had wanted to bomb a rush-hour train on the B line
``because there are a lot of Jews that ride that train.'' The line
passes through Brooklyn's Borough Park section, home to many
Orthodox Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Abu Mezer made no admissions, saying he planned to
appeal because his rights had been violated by ``government
misconduct.'' He also charged that his trial lawyers had not
diligently represented him and that one had even been ``working
with the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Raggi responded that she had been ``highly impressed by the
quality of lawyering'' he had received, in a case with
``overwhelming evidence'' of his guilt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
