<HEADLINE>
GUARD IN NASSAU JAIL BEAT A MENTALLY RETARDED INMATE, JURY FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal jury found Monday that a Nassau County Jail
guard had beaten a mentally retarded inmate in 1993, leaving him
with broken ribs and spinal fractures. The decision clears the way
for a broader civil-rights trial against Nassau County and other
jail guards.
</P>
<P>
   In his suit, the former inmate, Thomas Donovan Jr., 39, had
accused the guard, Salvatore Gemelli, a leader of the corrections
officers' union, of attacking him as he arrived at the East Meadow
jail. The beating, which Donovan said Gemelli administered with a
metal frying pan or pot, left him afraid that his life inside the
jail was in jeopardy, he testified.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict bolsters claims by critics and other former Nassau
County inmates that beatings were commonly administered by guards
at the jail. An inquiry began after the Jan. 13 death of Thomas
Pizzuto, 38, an inmate whose family says he was beaten by guards
and then left untreated for days. His death, which has been ruled a
homicide, is at the center of a wide federal investigation into
possible civil rights violations at the jail.
</P>
<P>
   In its unanimous ruling Monday, the jury awarded Donovan $65,000
in compensatory damages after spending an unexpectedly long time _
13 hours over two days _ in deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the 10-member jury will return to consider whether to
award Donovan punitive damages. After that, they will begin hearing
arguments in the second phase of the civil suit, in which Donovan
has accused Nassau County of failing to protect his constitutional
rights during his time in the jail.
</P>
<P>
   The jury's decision, which by law must be unanimous, was by no
means swift. On four occasions throughout the day, the forewoman
passed notes asking lawyers from either side to provide copies of
Gemelli's testimony and other documents from the case.
</P>
<P>
   At 2:15 p.m., after the jury sent Judge Allyne R. Ross a note
that asked, ``What if we can't reach a unanimous decision?''
lawyers weighed the notion of a hung jury. But the jurors finally
reached an agreement at 5:45 p.m. as Judge Ross was preparing to
send them home for the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand in awe of my son because of the bravery he showed
through this whole ordeal,'' said Donovan's father, Thomas Donovan
Sr., after the jury rendered its verdict. ``I could care less about
the money. I hope the good, decent guards now step forward. I want
that prison cleaned up.''
</P>
<P>
   Gemelli, 45, appearing crestfallen as he left the Brooklyn
federal courtroom Monday, and his lawyer, Chris P. Termini,
declined to comment after the ruling. Telephone calls seeking
comment from several Nassau County officials were not returned late
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In the trial, Gemelli testified he had no recollection of
Donovan or the night of beating. In a case where there were no
other witnesses to Donovan's beating, the jury had to decide on
Gemelli's liability by plodding through reams of documents and even
a secretly taped conversation between Donovan, who has an IQ of 58,
and police officers who asked about his injuries.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The junior Donovan did not appear in court Monday, staying
instead at the home of a family relative in Brightwater, on Long
Island, his father said. He had been taken to the county jail on a
child sexual abuse charge and later pleaded guilty to a
misdemeanor.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployed for the last several months, Donovan will soon begin
working as a chef's aide at a country club restaurant on Long
Island.
</P>
<P>
   Federal civil-rights statutes require Donovan's suit to be split
into two phases. The second part of the trial set to begin Tuesday
will focus on whether Nassau County is partly responsible for
allowing Donovan's rights to have been violated. That process is to
include allegations against other jail guards, including James
Tyrrell, who accompanied Gemelli to court Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Paul F. Millus, the lawyer representing the county, will attempt
to show that the county is not liable for Donovan's or other
inmates' beatings while inside the county jail. ``I think the law
will bear out that the jail doesn't guarantee safety 100 percent,''
Millus said before the jury's ruling Monday. ``No jail does. That's
not the nature of jail. Jails house violent people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
