<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS ITEMS ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 7) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Ferries Speed Bahamas Travel &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fast ferries are presenting new options to Bahamas-bound
travelers this year, as a company has begun service between Miami
and Nassau and another is planning inter-island trips starting in
July.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami-Nassau service, operated by Bay Ferries of Prince
Edward Island, Canada, uses a 300-foot catamaran called the Cat,
which makes a five-hour run from Miami to Nassau every day except
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The ferry, which sails in summer between Maine and Nova Scotia
and will be replaced by a sister ship, carries 750 passengers and
travels up to 50 miles an hour. It leaves the Port of Miami at 9
a.m., arriving at Nassau at 2 p.m.; the return trip leaves Nassau
at 4:30 and arrives at 9:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   There is a casino on board with slot machines, blackjack and
roulette. Other diversions include bingo, movies and a duty-free
shop. There is also a snack bar.
</P>
<P>
   Round-trip fares are $119, $59 for ages 3 to 12; one-way tickets
are $69 and $39. A total of $20 United States and Bahamas departure
taxes is extra. For reservations: (888) 635-9228.
</P>
<P>
   The inter-island service, by a new Nassau-based company called
Bahamas Fast Ferries, will connect Nassau with Eleuthera, a
90-minute trip, and with Harbour Island, which takes about 20
minutes longer. The 115-foot catamaran, being built in Connecticut,
will accommodate 170 passengers and will have a bar serving light
snacks. The fares will be $90 round trip for either island, and the
company expects to start taking reservations at the end of April,
at (242) 323-2166. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Early Bloom Won't Stop Wildflower Festival &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bluebonnets, the traditional harbingers of spring in central
Texas, are in bloom again. The redbuds are budding, the daisies are
dancing in the warm breezes and the sweet scent of mountain laurel
fills the air.
</P>
<P>
   And that is not necessarily happy news for travelers who visit
Austin and the Texas Hill Country to admire the spring wildflowers.
Because of unusual warmth so far this year, the peak for spring
wildflowers _ typically the last two weeks of March and the first
two weeks of April _ is about three weeks early.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the second week in March, I suspect we will have peaked
out,'' said Flo Oxley, botanist at the Lady Bird Johnson Wildflower
Center in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Central Texas is also unusually dry, which could reduce both the
number and the duration of blooms unless it rains soon. ``I still
think it's going to be a beautiful spring,'' Ms. Oxley said, but
added, ``Don't be disappointed if you don't see oceans and oceans
of bluebonnets.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be abundant pink evening primroses, coreopsis, and
Engelmann's daisies, she said, as well as gaillardia, prairie
verbena, wine cups, columbines and salvia.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted by the early arrival of the guests of honor, the Lady
Bird Johnson Wildflower Center, 4801 LaCrosse Avenue, Austin, Texas
78739, is planning its annual Wildflower Days Festival on four
weekends: March 20 and 21, featuring children's activities; March
27 and 28, focusing on native plants; April 24, a photo festival,
and a crafts show on May 22 and 23.
</P>
<P>
   Admission to each is $4, $2.50 for students and ages 60 and up.
The center is open Tuesday through Sunday, 9 a.m. to 5:30 p.m.
Information: (512) 292-4200, www.wildflowers.org.
</P>
<P>
   Peter H. Lewis &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   London Restaurants Show Off With Bargains &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Having recognized that London, for some time now, has become a
worthwhile destination for dining, the London Tourist Board has
organized a yearlong restaurant promotion. It starts Friday with
the city's first Restaurant Week, to run through March 21.
</P>
<P>
   The more than 200 restaurants involved in the program will serve
special prix-fixe menus and wine offers. There is no single set
price _ unlike New York Restaurant Week, in which lunch prices are
determined by the year ($19.98 in 1998, for example) _ but some
places will have meals priced at about $8 and $16, and all the
menus are expected to represent good value.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A listing of participating restaurants is available in a
supplement in the March 11 issue of the London Evening Standard
magazine, in the March issue of Where London, a magazine available
free in many hotels, and at www.londontown.com. Information:
(44-171) 872-5678 from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Among special events, a number of art exhibits involving food or
restaurants or both open on Friday, including an expanded display
of ``The Art of Cooking'' at the National Portrait Gallery on
Trafalgar Square.
</P>
<P>
   On March 16, Duncan Hamilton, a former chef who is London's most
famous ice sculptor, will give carving demonstrations at Trafalgar
Square. On March 21 in Soho, Greek, Dean, Frith and Bateman Streets
and part of Old Compton Street will become pedestrian malls from
noon to midnight, with cooking demonstrations, restaurants selling
their specialties, and entertainment. Florence Fabricant &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Poland's Grand Era Sweeps Into the U.S. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From 1572 through 1764, Poland was Europe's largest nation,
sweeping east to include what is today Lithuania and most of
Belarus and the Ukraine. It was the crossroads of trade between
eastern and western Europe, the Christian bulwark against the
Ottoman Empire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Land of the Winged Horsemen: Art in Poland, 1572-1764,'' which
began a five-city tour of the United States at the Walters Art
Gallery in Baltimore on Tuesday, puts that Baroque era on view.
Nearly 150 works _ from Old Masters paintings, to armor and
weaponry to Oriental rugs and liturgical objects _ depict Poland's
Golden Age.
</P>
<P>
   Drawn from the National Museum, the Royal Castle in Warsaw, the
Wavel Royal Castle in Cracow and more than 30 other museums and
churches, most have never been outside Poland. Many are national
treasures.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit begins with a section on Poland's elected monarchy,
including a jeweled crown, scepter and orb, a throne and a portrait
of Ladislas IV by Rubens and his studio. Next come galleries
devoted to fancy military regalia, armor, sabers and cavalry
trappings. There is also a Turkish tent captured when the Poles,
led by John Sobieski, defeated the Turks in 1683 in the Battle of
Vienna, which is illustrated in the show by a 17th-century
painting.
</P>
<P>
   The third section examines the lavish life of the Polish
nobility with examples of dress, tapestries, porcelain and
furniture. Finally, paintings, carvings, chalices and other
religious objects focus on religion, including a 17th-century
painting of Our Lady of Czestochowa, Poland's famous Madonna, in a
silver robe.
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate the opening, admission is free Sunday; there will
be shows of Polish folk dancers, rapiers engaging in a duel, and
puppet-making, paper-cutting and other festivities for children.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition will remain at the Walters until May 9. It then
travels to the Art Institute of Chicago (June 5 to Sept. 6), the
Huntsville Museum of Art in Alabama (Sept. 25 to Nov. 28), the San
Diego Museum of Art (Dec. 18 to Feb. 27, 2000) and the Philbrook
Museum of Art in Tulsa, Okla. (March 25 to June 18, 2000).
</P>
<P>
   The final showing of the exhibition will be at the restored
Royal Castle in Warsaw, which was destroyed by the Nazis in World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   The Walters Art Gallery, at 600 North Charles Street, in the
Mount Vernon Cultural District of Baltimore, is open Tuesday to
Sunday. Dated and timed tickets to ``Art in Poland'' are $10 for
adults, including an audio tour, with discounts for seniors,
children and groups. They are available at (800) 551-7328, on the
Web at www.ticketmasterwb.com or at the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (410) 547-9000 or www.thewalters.org. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Judith H. Dobrzynski
</P>
</TEXT>
