<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990301.0465 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3822 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-ROBINSON-HN     03-01 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-ROBINSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SAN ANTONIO _ David Robinson dressed quietly, knowing full well
what was about to come. The San Antonio Spurs, from whom so much
had been expected in the preseason, had played another lousy game
Sunday, losing by 14 points to the Utah Jazz, their bitter Midwest
Division rival.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The game, their second straight loss by a double-digit margin,
had dropped the Spurs to 6-8 on the season heading into tonight's
game against the Rockets at Compaq Center, and the media
surrounding Robinson's locker were demanding to know what was wrong
with the team.
</P>
<P>
   A devout Christian, Robinson knew he was about to go through his
own version of the Inquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson knew he was going to be a target for the media.
</P>
<P>
   And he knew why.
</P>
<P>
   It's because Robinson, a man who avoids swearing, had ironically
been branded with perhaps the worst four-letter word in
professional sports: soft.
</P>
<P>
   It has been whispered throughout his career, no doubt because of
the good-guy image Robinson projects through his faith and his
adherence to the principles he learned during his days at the Naval
Academy. But the worst part is that those whispers are now being
spoken aloud in his own locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``What frustrates me is that I hear it from other teams that our
team is soft,'' said former Rocket Mario Elie, who signed with the
Spurs as a free agent. ``How am I supposed to feel? Guys I play
against all the time saying, `Mario, you know your team is soft.'
It frustrates me, but I hear this. Guys are telling me this.
There's nothing I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because Robinson is the antithesis of the emotional Elie.
Where Elie is outwardly fiery and combative, Robinson rarely strays
from the stoic front he projects, which is why he is perceived to
be soft.
</P>
<P>
   The knock against Robinson is even more ironic since everything
else about him is about as hard as can be.
</P>
<P>
   You start with the hardbody physique, which looks more like an
anatomist's chart _ broad shoulders, bulging biceps and a waist
that seems impossibly small on a man who stands over seven feet
tall.
</P>
<P>
   But people look at that body and expect Robinson to be breathing
fire every second he's on the court.
</P>
<P>
   That weakness was supposedly illustrated last season when, after
being knocked unconscious by an elbow from Utah's Karl Malone and
falling face-first to the Delta Center floor, Robinson refused to
retaliate.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson just shrugs off the criticism, even though it stings
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to keep my perspective,'' he said. ``They (the media)
are on the outside looking in. I believe in doing things the right
way. I believe in working hard with this thing. I believe in the
commitment. They keep talking about passion, but to me, passion is
about commitment. It's about faithfulness; it's about being there
every day. It's about working your tail off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like in a marriage. You see, our society doesn't
understand about passion. They think passion is running around
growling at somebody or whatever, or cheating on your wife. But
that's not passion. That has nothing to do with it. What I'm
talking about is the faithfulness and the commitment to being
there, and fighting through times when it's not so good. And right
now is a time when it's not so good.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, not for Robinson or the Spurs. But he's not about to
rock the boat.
</P>
<P>
   No, that's not something Robinson learned during his days at the
Academy. It is more a byproduct of his faith, which is rock-solid,
and a value system that demands respect for authority.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear, however, that Robinson's faith in the Spurs' system,
the brainchild of San Antonio coach/general manager Gregg Popovich,
is evaporating. Popovich's system is designed to emphasize Tim
Duncan in the low post, meaning Robinson, not too far removed from
leading the league in scoring (1994) and taking home a Most
Valuable Player trophy (1995), has to spend much of his time off
the blocks or at the high post, where he is clearly uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost as if Mark McGwire reported to camp, only to be told
his new job would be to lay down bunts. Robinson's job now is to
move the ball around, play defense and rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he does it, even though it means getting criticized for his
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just the way the world is,'' Robinson said. ``People
like those flamboyant guys. They like the guys who don't like to
pass and do all the crazy stuff. That stuff, I guess, is more
interesting. I don't know. I could it doesn't bother me.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson bit his lip, in much the way he has been asked to bite
the bullet since Duncan came on board the Admiral's ship last
season. Still, Robinson is averaging 15 points, 10 rebounds and
three blocks per game this season, solid by anybody's definition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a time right now to point fingers,'' said Robinson of
changes he would like to have made. ``I think it's a time for us to
just dig down and figure out what we can do better. Personally, I'm
going to have to get some more post-ups and hopefully some more
transition buckets working. We have to talk about that stuff. We
just have to solve our problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't really point fingers at anybody. I just have to look
at myself and say, `How can I make this team better? What more can
I do? How can I get more shots or make this team more effective
offensively?'''
</P>
<P>
   Are the Spurs, however, asking what they can do to make Robinson
better?
</P>
<P>
   Everything seemed fine when San Antonio hosted Seattle on Feb.
24 and won a 99-81 blowout behind Robinson's 29 points and 17
rebounds. But the Sonics got their revenge two nights later with a
92-82 victory, and Sunday's loss to the Jazz represented the low
point of this young season for Robinson and the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming off two blowouts, it's real frustrating,'' Robinson
said. ``I thought after that first Seattle game that we had made
some progress and we were beginning to get a little confidence in
one another. It seems like we've kind of taken a step backward
after that game.''
</P>
<P>
   But Robinson intends to keep pressing forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think part of what is so great about winning and doing the
things (to win) and doing it right is the challenge of fighting the
uphill battle,'' he said. ``That's part of what's so awesome about
it. I think that right now we have a lot of questions to answer. No
question. But if we are able to overcome this, then it's going to
be that much better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be that much stronger having gone through some
of this garbage, questioning ourselves and really digging down deep
and saying, `Where is our team? We're 6-8. What are we going to do
right now?' I think that's really what this is all about. That's
the part about this game that I really love _ the challenge. Every
night you have a great challenge, stepping out there on the floor,
where you challenge yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge hill to overcome for me, and I want to overcome
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
