<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3823 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-STATE-TROOPER-1STL     03-01 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-STATE-TROOPER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER FIRING CHIEF, WHITMAN DENIES TROOPERS ARE BIASED
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Del., Md., Conn.) (Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to sharpen definition of profiling in
lede, add Whitman quotes, background on allegations against police;
ADDS new 13-14 grafs with Whitman commenting on Verniero's court
appointment, bgng `The governor dismissed suggestions ...; story
now in two takes) 
 (nk) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ A day after firing the head of the New Jersey
State Police for what she called racially insensitive remarks, Gov.
Christie Whitman on Monday defended her administration's response
to charges that state troopers use ``racial profiling'' to single
out black and Latino drivers in looking for drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said that the comments by State Police Superintendent
Col. Carl A. Williams, in which he suggested that certain minority
groups were disproportionately responsible for some kinds of drug
trafficking, were wrong. But she reiterated her contention that
there was no widespread practice of ``racial profiling'' by state
troopers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always made it very clear that I won't tolerate racial
profiling, and I believe he's telling the truth when he says that
it isn't tolerated or condoned,'' she said, referring to Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said she had resisted earlier calls for Williams' ouster
because he had cooperated with several measures intended to improve
race relations on the force and deter profiling by troopers.
Williams had expanded the State Police recruiting unit in an effort
to bring more women and minorities into the force, the governor
said, and after troopers shot three unarmed minority men last April
during a traffic stop on the New Jersey Turnpike, Williams agreed
to install video cameras in patrol cars to tape all traffic stops.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman also rejected suggestions from some civil-rights
advocates and Democratic lawmakers that the furor over racial
profiling and Williams's remarks could complicate the nomination of
Attorney General Peter Verniero to the state Supreme Court.
Verniero, who was nominated by Whitman to the court last week, has
been criticized, as the official who oversees the State Police
department, for not acting quickly or forcefully enough?? after the
turnpike shooting last April.
</P>
<P>
   Verniero has also been criticized for representing the troopers
in an appeal of a 1996 court case in which a state judge found
evidence of widespread profiling.
</P>
<P>
   Although Whitman's swift move to oust Williams was praised by
most civil rights leaders as an important first step, they
emphasized that more was needed to be done to address bias.
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes clear to us that the problems facing the State
Police are deep and pervasive,'' said the Rev. Reginald T. Jackson,
executive director of the Black Ministers Council of New Jersey.
``Colonel Williams is not just a superintendent but a veteran of 35
years, and it is difficult for us to believe that the thoughts
expressed in that interview have not trickled down to the rank and
file of the state police.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Democratic lawmakers Monday joined the Black Ministers
Council in calling for the state Legislature to delay its vote on
Verniero's court appointment until the U.S. Justice Department's
civil rights division completes an investigation, begun in 1996,
into profiling complaints against the State Police.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Williams and Verniero are equally at fault for
procrastination on the growing litany of profiling complaints, yet
one is out of a job and the other is poised for one of the most
coveted positions in the state,'' said Assemblyman LeRoy J. Jones
Jr.. a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Richard Codey, the minority leader, said that all 16
Senate Democrats agreed that the confirmation should wait. But
Republicans hold control of the Senate, with 24 seats, and all that
would be required for confirmation is a simple majority.
</P>
<P>
   Verniero issued a public statement Monday condemning Williams'
remarks as ``insensitive and inappropriate.'' But he declined to
discuss how the firing of Williams might affect his nomination to
the state Supreme Court, saying that he did not want to politicize
the process.
</P>
<P>
   The governor dismissed suggestions that Verniero should be
faulted for Williams' statements or that the lingering allegations
of profiling should stall his nomination to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anything said by Col. Williams is indicative of
the attorney general's response to these complaints,'' she said.
``He's done an excellent job.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said she believed Williams was correct when he stated
that there is no clear evidence that troopers engage in profiling,
but she said his public comments, published in The Star-Ledger of
Newark on Sunday _ that most drug traffickers are black or Latino _
were so insensitive that he had seriously damaged the credibility
of the department.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's a racist,'' Whitman said. ``But I don't
believe he saw how insensitive his comments were. That's part of
the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams' political demise came after 10 months of escalating
complaints that the state police use discriminatory and illegal
tactics to single out minority drivers in search of narcotics
traffickers. Williams, who was appointed by Whitman shortly after
she took office in 1994 after a decorated career as a trooper, has
steadfastly denied that the practice exists, and publicly bristled
last month when Verniero announced that the attorney general's
office would undertake its own review of the state police.
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview Sunday in the Star-Ledger, Williams
ridiculed the notion that police should not take race into
consideration when trying to search for possible drug couriers.
During the interview, he said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Two weeks ago the president of the United States went to
Mexico to talk to the president of Mexico about drugs. He didn't go
to Ireland. He didn't go to England. Today, with this drug problem,
the drug problem is cocaine or marijuana. It is most a member of a
minority group that's involved with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams declined a request for interviews on Monday, and Lt.
Col. Michael Fedorko, the acting superintendent, spent the day
meeting with top commanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's business as usual,'' said John Hagerty, a State Police
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey is not the only state to face allegations of racial
profiling. Delaware, Connecticut and Maryland's state police
departments have been named in lawsuits charging that minority
drivers are pulled over more often than white ones are.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Although the public fiasco caused by Williams' comments are an
embarrassment to Whitman, it also offers her a new opportunity to
seize the initiative in an issue that has dogged her administration
for nearly a year. After the shooting in April, the Whitman
administration ordered that patrol cars be equipped with video
cameras to record all traffic stops, and has expanded a recruitment
effort to bring more minorities and women onto the force.
</P>
<P>
   But a series of new allegations of profiling have continued to
emerge, including several from current and former troopers who have
filed discrimination lawsuits against the state police and say they
were trained to pull over drivers based on their race.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the growing public complaints in recent years, the State
Police have refused to release public details of the disciplinary
actions against troopers and have resisted suggestions that
troopers note the race of motorists they stop, making it difficult
to document patterns of racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Newark, Kevin Keenan, acting executive
director of the state chapter of the American Civil Liberties
Union, urged Whitman to create a database of the race of all
motorists stopped by troopers, and an ``early warning system'' to
ferret out troopers, as well as local police officers, who might be
racist, psychologically unfit, or dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   With the dismissal of Williams, who had become the most fiery
defender of the State Police, Whitman must find a more temperate,
politically sensitive leader for the 2,700-member force. The
governor said the list of potential candidates should include
civilians, as well as uniformed law enforcement officers, and
minorities, although she said she would not limit the search to
minority candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But civil rights leaders and representatives of black law
enforcement officers say it will take far more than a new commander
to remedy those a State Police culture that they say has
contributed to racial tension.
</P>
<P>
   William Buckman, a lawyer whose lawsuit led to a judge's finding
in 1996 that black drivers are 4.85 times more likely to be stopped
than whites on the southern half of the New Jersey Turnpike, said
that only the governor and the Justice Department can force the
insular police force to adopt the kind of changes that are
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Race is a major component of New Jersey State Police
thinking,'' Buckman said. ``The governor opted for spin control.
Something much more must be done than firing one state scapegoat.
It is about time for this historic and decades-old problem to come
to an end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
