<HEADER>
A3825 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-TUCKER-LEWINSKY-NY     03-01 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TUCKER-LEWINSKY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVING CHEEVER COUNTRY ITS GUILTY PLEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A little more than a year ago, Diane Straus Tucker had never met
her stepsister-to-be, a woman she had heard of only as Monica. But
it did seem odd to Ms. Tucker when she heard that Monica, who
seemed to have a good job at the Pentagon, was looking for a public
relations job at Revlon in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not having all the facts, right?'' Ms. Tucker recalled last
week. ``To put it mildly.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Jan. 21, 1998, the day the world first heard of Monica S.
Lewinsky, rolled around soon enough. That morning Ms. Tucker's real
sister was on the phone with a question: ``Do you know who Monica
Lewinsky is?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   She is, of course, the daughter of Marcia Lewis _ who married
Ms. Straus' father, R. Peter Straus, later that year.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tucker has since picked herself off her original 1780 floor
in Bedford, N.Y., and in an unrelated but utterly fitting career
development is now the editor in chief of the gossipy,
six-month-old Westchester Wag. The Wag is a free monthly, heavy on
local celebrities congratulating each other at benefit events, that
covers Westchester County's rich without shame. John Cheever would
have railed against it, but probably would have studied the party
pictures first.
</P>
<P>
   The Wag's cover is a hard-to-ignore bright red, white and purple
_ Ms. Tucker said she and her publisher wanted to avoid a classy
Town &AMP; Country look, and they have. It is available at bagel shops
and good restaurants, but only in Katonah, Mount Kisco, Rye and the
like. Ms. Straus says a letter to the editor in an upcoming issue
asks, in essence, ``Do you guys even know where Peekskill is?''
</P>
<P>
   She says yes. ``Take 684 to Exit 6, take a left on 35,'' Ms.
Tucker said, then confessed she needed to follow written
directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not for everybody,'' Ms. Straus admitted, ``but everybody
is reading it.''
</P>
<P>
   Or at least writing for it. Seema Boesky, Ivan's ex, has a Wag
column called ``Seema Says . . . .'' (``I feel I understand your
pain,'' she wrote in an open letter to Ms. Lewinsky in February.)
Lucie Arnaz, Lucille Ball's daughter and a recent Wag cover girl,
writes a column, too. (``Whatever Happened to Jean Harris?'' was
Ms. Arnaz's November offering. She answered her headline this way:
``Funny you should ask. She just called me the other day to thank
me for a contribution my husband and I had made to her Children of
Bedford Fund.'')
</P>
<P>
   Clearly The Wag will not be at the top of the list of pit-bull
publications supposedly making Hillary Rodham Clinton think twice
about running for the Senate from New York. ``We will never be
cruel, but we may occasionally be wicked,'' said Ms. Tucker's boss,
Mary Ann Liebert, who publishes 60 medical journals from The Wag's
Larchmont offices.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to Monica. ``I think she'll do something
with us,'' said Ms. Tucker, meaning that The Wag, too, will likely
get its Monica interview. In December, Ms. Tucker fought off
worries that she was capitalizing on her new stepsister and wrote
an exceptionally discreet column about her. ``Monica is a bright,
engaging and attractive young woman,'' she said. ``Who hasn't made
mistakes in their twenties?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tucker didn't go much further in an interview in her office
last week, but did say that she spent a week with Ms. Lewinsky at a
family get-together in the Adirondacks this past summer. ``She's
full of life, she's funny, she's smart,'' Ms. Tucker said. ``I
think the House managers overlooked the fact that a woman like
Monica can have her own motivation, and make up her own mind. Just
because she was doing this doesn't mean she was somebody's
puppet.'' Also: Ms. Lewinsky has a ``hauntingly beautiful'' singing
voice.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tucker, 47, was dressed in a pink jacket with a short black
skirt and looked like the very fit former national paddle tennis
champion she is. She is having a good time with The Wag. ``You
can't not read it,'' she said. ``It's like going to a dinner party
without having to polish the silver.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tucker grew up ``everywhere'' _ New York, Washington and
Geneva, where her father, who owns newspapers and radio stations in
New York and New Jersey, was an executive with the International
Labor Organization. Ms. Tucker went to the Brearley School on
Manhattan's Upper East Side and Sidwell-Friends in Washington, and
graduated in 1973 from Yale. Her first job was at New York
magazine, where she became an assistant to the managing editor. She
then moved to The Village Voice as an associate editor.
</P>
<P>
   She married a Yale classmate, Carll Tucker, in 1976, moved to
Bedford from Manhatan's Upper West Side in 1982, then raised three
children in a house once owned by her
great-great-great-great-great-grandfather, David Hays. Ms. Tucker's
mother, Ellen Sulzberger Straus, was the first cousin of Arthur
Ochs Sulzberger, chairman emeritus of The New York Times Company.
While at home with her children, Ms. Tucker started a catering
company, ``Oh, Cuisine,'' and also worked in her husband's
business, Trader Publications, which owns newspapers and magazines
in Fairfield and Westchester Counties.
</P>
<P>
   Recent Wag cover subjects have included Robert F. Kennedy Jr.
and Gov. George E. Pataki _ who grew up in, yes, Peekskill.
</P>
<P>
   Is the Wag, which prints 50,000 copies a month, making money?
Ms. Tucker's answer was Clintonian: ``It depends on how you count
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-99 2226EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990301.0469 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3836 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-CHANDLER-LADN     03-01 1596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-CHANDLER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOMINGUEZ HIGH SOPHOMORE STANDS TALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LOUIS JOHNSON  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ He was the principal subject of a widely
watched segment on the nation's most popular news television show -
60 Minutes - before ever stepping onto a high school campus.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, he will become the first high school athlete to ever
be featured in Vanity Fair magazine, and there are whispers that he
may actually grace the cover.
</P>
<P>
   He is 7-feet tall with model looks and is arguably the most
well-known boys basketball player in the country. And he's only a
16-year-old 10th grader.
</P>
<P>
   From the outside looking in, it may appear that Dominguez High
basketball star Tyson Chandler has the world in the palm of his
hands. But being such a highly touted prospect does have its
drawbacks, such as the pressure to fulfill expectations, which
always seems to coincide with fame and adulation for those who are
above the norm in their sport of choice.
</P>
<P>
   While most agree that his potential is unlimited, carrying the
burden of being one of the game's so-called `Next Great Big Men'
doesn't seem to faze Chandler, who feels his shoulders are broad
enough to handle the weight of expectations placed upon him by the
basketball world.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The expectations) might be unfair to a person that couldn't
take it, but I can handle it,'' Chandler said. ``I realize that
basketball is just a game, even though some people take it too
serious. Don't get me wrong, I love this sport. But to some people,
basketball is their whole life and if they don't make it, they have
nothing to fall back on. That's not me, and it won't be me.''
</P>
<P>
   Dons coach Russell Otis says that Chandler isn't your typical
star jock, and that he has remained a down-to-earth teenager
despite all the attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tyson comes from a real good family, and he really cares about
his teammates and people in general,'' Otis said. ``He just wants
to be as normal as possible. Sometimes, I think if he could do it
all over again, he'd make himself six feet, because he gets a lot
of attention due to his height and I don't think he enjoys it all
the time. But I wish I had a son like him, not because of his
basketball ability, but because of his attitude and demeanor about
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a 7-footer in high school will surely get you noticed, and
Chandler has been the center of attention wherever he plays. Otis
said that at times, its like traveling with a rock star.
</P>
<P>
   ``His persona is unreal ... I marvel at how people react to him
all the time,'' Otis said. ``But he always takes time to talk to
people, especially the smaller kids, and he treats everyone the
same.''
</P>
<P>
   (sub) It's in the genes
</P>
<P>
   To say genetics played a small role in Chandler's stature is an
understatement. His biological father, Frank Chandler, is
6-foot-10, and his mother, Vernie Threadgil, may only be 5-11, but
all of her brothers stand 6-4 or better.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Chandler played basketball at San Jose State in the early
70s, but Tyson doesn't credit his father's affection for hoops as
having an influence on his desire to play the sport. As a matter of
fact, Tyson admits to having a closer relationship with his
stepfather, William Brown, and didn't show much interest in
basketball until he reached the seventh grade, by which time he
stood 6-6.
</P>
<P>
   Once he became dedicated to basketball, Chandler began to play
on Nike-sponsored traveling teams for well-known youth coach Pat
Barrett, and between the eighth and ninth grades, he sprouted four
inches and stood 6-10.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler grew up in San Bernardino, and his decision to attend
Dominguez drew plenty of criticism from those in that area who had
hoped he would attend one of the local high schools. But Chandler
said he made up his mind as an eighth-grader to become a Don, and
he took advantage of a CIF rule that allows incoming freshman the
opportunity to attend any high school they wish, provided the
school district involved accepts the student.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to better myself, and I thought (Dominguez) would be
the best choice for me and it has,'' said Chandler, whose family
has since moved to Montclair, from which he commutes to Compton
daily. ``I don't think I could have gained anything by playing out
there. I think every day, playing against these guys in practice,
represents a bigger challenge to me than what I might have faced
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson also developed a very close relationship with Otis, whom
he calls a second father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach has been great on and off the court, and I know he won't
steer me wrong,'' Chandler said. ``I can ask some people a
question, and they'll tell me what I want to hear. But coach will
tell me what I need to hear, even if it might hurt my feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you see him screaming at players like Kenny Brunner,
Jason Thomas and Tayshaun Prince ... those guys were as good as
you'll find, and I knew I wasn't going to be an exception. I didn't
want to be treated any differently than anyone else coming into
high school.''
</P>
<P>
   (sub) The critics
</P>
<P>
   Chandler averaged 10 points, five rebounds and three blocks per
game as a freshman for a Dons team that won a fourth consecutive
CIF Southern Section title and would probably have captured a third
straight Division II state championship if not for an injury to
Prince.
</P>
<P>
   He's increased those numbers across the board this season,
averaging 14 points, eight rebounds and five blocks while leading
Dominguez to a 26-3 record and a No.9 national ranking.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who expect more on the offensive end of the
court from a player of his caliber, but according to Chandler,
anything he does offensively is simply a plus for his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a role on this team like everyone else, and my job is
to rebound, block shots, run the floor and intimidate people,'' he
said. ``It's not like there aren't guys on this team who can't put
the ball in the basket. As long as I get another team out of their
offense, then I'm doing my job. Maybe next year I'll take a more
assertive role on (offense), but what I'm doing this year is what's
needed for us to be successful now. I never look at the stats
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, who has been called a young David Robinson by scouts
who love the fluid way in which he moves on the court, said he
wants to pattern his game after NBA stars Kevin Garnett and
Shaquille O'Neal, both of whom he has met and had frequent talks
with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved the way Garnett played in high school, because he
could completely dominate a game without scoring a single point,''
Chandler said. ``And I like Shaq because he's so strong down low.
He just moves people without even trying sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Otis said there have been times when the 7-footer has tried to
do too much on the court, but noted Chandler has learned that he
has no one to impress but his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's only a sophomore, and the more he matures, the other
stuff (offensively) will come,'' Otis said. ``We've got some pretty
good high school players surrounding him, so there's no pressure
offensively. But he can dominate a game right now on the defensive
end, and he's going to learn how to dominate offensively as well.
Tyson has every post move in the book, he just doesn't know how to
transfer it from the practice floor to the game floor all the time.
When he puts it all together on a consistent basis, look out,
because it's going to be something to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Rumors have dogged Chandler from the day he started classes at
Dominguez. There was the widespread reports that he was headed to
Mater Dei after his freshman season they were still going around
after he refuted them in the Press-Telegram last February and the
one he hates the most, which has the star ticketed to the NBA right
out of high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never said I was going to go pro out of high school ...
that has never come out of my mouth,'' Chandler said. ``Some of the
people around me might have said it, but I never did. When people
say that, they're just questioning their own thoughts.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, who's a B-minus student, said he definitely plans on
going to college, and while he still has more than two years of
prep competition left and realizes that his mind could change, he
has put together a list of schools, with his current favorites
being Kansas, Arizona and UCLA, in no particular order.
</P>
<P>
   Winning over his critics would be nice, but it's not exactly at
the top of his agenda for the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think those guys have way too much time on their hands,''
Chandler said. ``I mean, if they can sit back and look at my game
and pick all the flaws out, that probably means they're not very
busy doing anything else. There's no way I can hide myself on the
court, because everywhere I go, I'm a marked man, and people are
going to try and shut me down. I never had a chance to build a
reputation, because everyone knew who I was before I even got to
high school. I had no chance to gain anything, all I could do was
lose the reputation I had.''
</P>
<P>
   Most scouts have Chandler ranked among the top five sophomores
in the country. But being the No. 1 player in his class isn't what
drives the Dominguez star, who is looking to achieve that goal and
and a little more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be the No.1 player in the country, regardless of
class, next year,'' Chandler said. ``I always tell myself that I
can do anything I want to do, and how much I better myself as a
basketball player and as a person is all up to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
