<HEADER>
A3837 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ORGAN-TRANSPLANT-TRIA     03-01 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORGAN-TRANSPLANT-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE DELAYS TRIAL OF 2 IN SCHEME TO SELL HUMAN ORGANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla.)  (mk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal judge has delayed the trial of two men who
were charged in a scheme to arrange the transplant of organs taken
from executed Chinese prisoners, questioning whether the defendants
were entrapped in the case, and expressing concern over the absence
of a crucial witness.
</P>
<P>
   When the arrests were announced last year, federal officials
said the case could provide the first evidence of what dissidents
have long described as a thriving trade in human organs in China,
and its reach to the United States, where it is illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The government charged the two defendants after the FBI mounted
a sting operation using information from the human rights advocate
Harry Wu about a conspiracy to sell the human organs. The two
defendants are Cheng Yong Wang, who has described himself as a
former prosecutor on Hainan Island, China, and Xingqi Fu, a Chinese
citizen who runs a laundry in Flushing, Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Wu's role in the case had already drawn fire from the defense,
which contended that he held a grudge against the Chinese
leadership and had set up the defendants to advance his agenda. Wu,
who has denied those allegations, was expected to testify at the
trial for the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   But the question of entrapment arose again after the defense
lawyers told the judge, Deborah Batts of U.S. District Court in
Manhattan, that they had discovered that a second government
informer had played a much greater role in the case than was
previously known, including orchestrating much of the illegal
activity charged against the defendants and pushing them to join
the conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   The government has disputed the defense's contention, and said
there was no entrapment in the case. But Batts said in court last
week that she was troubled that the second informer, a man named
Paul Risenhoover, described as an American long active in the
Chinese dissident movement, had left the United States and is now
refusing to return to testify.
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyers, who wanted to question Risenhoover, are now
asking that the charges against Wang and Fu be dismissed. Batts has
delayed the trial in order to decide whether it will be fair to
proceed without Risenhoover.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defendants have raised, I think, troubling and serious
issues regarding their rights, in terms of the unavailability of a
primary player in this series of events,'' Batts said.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the informer's ``not being available, compounded by
entrapment, compounded by active role in these things,'' she said,
``I think fairness requires the defendants to be able to confront
this man.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``He is essentially such a seminal and significant
and integral part of this case.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the U.S. attorney's office in Manhattan said
Monday that officials there would have no comment. The government
has filed secret court papers with the judge pertaining to
Risenhoover's role, the court docket shows.
</P>
<P>
   But last week in court, federal prosecutors told Batts that they
disagreed with the defense's contention that Risenhoover's presence
was critical, or that his testimony would even be admissible at
trial. The government made clear that it does not believe that the
defendants were entrapped in any way.
</P>
<P>
   Little is known about Risenhoover, who is about 30 and said to
be a native of Oklahoma. He was studying in China in 1989 at the
time of the student protests and deaths at Tiananmen Square, said
one person who knows him. He was described in court by a defense
lawyer as a fervent anti-Communist who is fluent in Chinese and
fears for his safety because of his strong opposition to the
Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyers had said they wanted to question Risenhoover
because records obtained from the government show he instigated the
scheme. They say he aggressively recruited their clients into the
conspiracy, then handed the case off to Wu, who informed the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Smith, the lawyer for Wang, the former Chinese
prosecutor, said in court that Wang had been in the United States,
seeking advice about how to get a visa, when he was referred to
Risenhoover, who said he was an immigration counselor.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that Risenhoover told Wang that he could get him a
visa, but in return Wang would have to use his former contacts as a
prosecutor in China to help arrange the transplants of organs from
executed prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme, as laid out by Smith, involved patients from Aruba
and did not involve the United States, meaning it was not illegal,
Smith said, according to a transcript.
</P>
<P>
   Smith told the judge that Wang never agreed to any activity that
was illegal in the United States, and that Risenhoover persisted in
drawing the defendants aggressively into the conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is entrapment, judge,'' Smith said. ``It is not a situation
where my client came to Risenhoover. It is a situation where
Risenhoover came to my client.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Monday night, ``I stand by the arguments I made in
court.''
</P>
<P>
   Fu's lawyer, Stephen Cohen, concurred. ``As I argued in court,
the unavailability of the informant denies my client his Sixth
Amendment right to confrontation. He's absolutely the crucial
player,'' Cohen added, referring to Risenhoover.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
