<HEADLINE>
CHANGE OF SCENERY JUST UP THE COAST 
SHADES OF SINATRA 
KITCHEN TROUBLE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill., Fla.)  (nk) 
 BY JAMES BARRON with FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Democrats were buzzing Monday about what President Clinton said
about one coast during a dinner party on the other.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner, on Friday, was given by Eli Broad, the billionaire
chairman of Sun America, the Los Angeles insurer. Some Democrats
quoted the president as saying he expects to live in New York after
he leaves the White House, whether or not Hillary Rodham Clinton
runs for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some chitchat that went, `For 22 years she's lived
where I wanted to live, and now I owe it to her, so if she wanted
to live in New York or run for the Senate, I'd do it,''' said
another Democrat who spoke on the condition of anonymity. ``It was
all very vague. He clearly indicated that he doesn't know what she
wants to do and that she hasn't made up her mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Shades of Sinatra &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hugh L. Carey, who was the governor of New York from 1975 to
1982, provided musical assistance at the Palm Beach Tavern in Palm
Beach, Fla., on Saturday. From his front-row seat, he sang along
with cabaret singer Eric Comstock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing he was chummy with Sinatra, I sang `How Little We
Know,' `Nice 'n' Easy' and `Witchcraft,''' Comstock said.
</P>
<P>
   Then Comstock struck up what he considers a quintessential New
York song, ``On the Sunny Side of the Street.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I gambled that he'd react to the line, `I'll be as rich as
Rockefeller,''' Comstock said, ``and he did react _ `Don't mention
that name.''' First Comstock substituted Malcolm Wilson, the
Republican whom Carey defeated for governor in 1974. ``Finally I
got it right: `If I never have a cent, I'll be as rich as Hugh L.
Carey,''' Comstock said.
</P>
<P>
   Then Carey asked for ``New York, New York.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed to want a Sinatra strut,'' Comstock said. ``He sang
so well that I let him modulate and finish alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitchen Trouble &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There were supposed to be 14 chefs from Charlie Trotter's
restaurant in Chicago in the kitchen of Roger Yaseen's apartment on
the Upper East Side on Sunday afternoon, putting together a dinner
for 16 guests.
</P>
<P>
   But by 6 p.m., only three members of the team, including
Trotter, had arrived. A chef de cuisine, Matthias Merges, and a
sommelier, Robert Houde, were delayed by bad weather. So was the
all-important cargo they were bringing: 20 boxes containing the
dinner (which had been painstakingly prepared, bagged and sealed on
Saturday), plus 20 copper sauce pans to warm it in and nearly 200
pieces of china to serve it on.
</P>
<P>
   Yaseen, an investment banker, had paid $12,000 for the dinner at
a benefit and memorial for the chef Patrick Clark last year. He had
invited his guests for 6:30 p.m., but when it became clear that
things would be running late, he called everyone and said to come
at 7:15 instead.
</P>
<P>
   By 8:30, the chefs and the food had landed at La Guardia
Airport, but the vans that were supposed to meet them were nowhere
to be found. They had to stand in a taxi line for an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Back at Yaseen's, the party _ including the restaurateurs Drew
Nieporent, Jean-Georges Vongerichten, Jean-Jacques Rachou, Sirio
Maccioni and Maguy Le Coze _ sipped Champagne and waited. Nieporent
thumbed through a directory of menus from a takeout delivery
service. Yaseen also had a seven-foot hero sandwich from
Manganaro's in reserve, just in case.
</P>
<P>
   Trotter kept his cool. ``Roger Yaseen has been made to wait in
every one of these people's restaurants, and now he's getting his
revenge,'' he said. ``There is no food.''
</P>
<P>
   But finally, starting around 9:15, with quail egg salad served
in quail eggs, there was food. Nine courses, five wines and three
pounds of fresh black truffles.
</P>
</TEXT>
