<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Wider Police Racism Reported
</P>
<P>
   A week after a report accused the Metropolitan Police Service in
London of ``pernicious and institutionalized racism,'' a new report
has found that police forces across Britain are failing to give
enough attention to racial matters. The report said police forces
were marginalizing the issue of race by not, for example, working
to combat racism among officers.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Ireland: Rights Panel Meets
</P>
<P>
   The five Protestant and five Roman Catholic members of the new
Northern Ireland Human Rights Commission met for the first time to
start compiling a bill of rights for the province. The commission
will have the power to investigate rights abuses and help people
bring complaints to court. The commission was set up as part of the
peace accord reached in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican: Toward St. Teresa
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II, yielding to appeals, granted a special
dispensation that speeds consideration for the sainthood of Mother
Teresa. The Vatican said he had agreed to waive the usual five-year
period after a person's death before beginning to examine a
petition for beatification, the intermediate stage toward
sainthood. Mother Teresa, founder of the Missionaries of Charity,
died 18 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland: Air-Crash Payouts
</P>
<P>
   After bitter complaints by relatives of some of those who died
in the Sept. 2 crash off Canada, Swissair will pay $135,000 in
compensation for each victim. Although the sum does not prevent
families from seeking larger amounts, Swissair has been buffeted by
nearly 24 lawsuits and by criticism from families dissatisfied with
its handling of claims.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Argentina: Menem `Retires' Again
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to end speculation that he might run for a third term
this year, President Carlos Saul Menem said the constitution would
not be changed to allow him to serve again. Menem has gone back and
forth on the question of his re-election several times in the last
two years. ``This is my last term,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Zedillo's Ratings Climb
</P>
<P>
   More Mexicans approve of President Ernesto Zedillo's handling of
his job than at any time since he took office in December 1994, the
newspaper Reforma said. In a nationwide poll, 65 percent said they
approved and 26 percent said they disapproved. In December 1995,
when the peso crisis was at its peak, 31 percent approved and 60
percent disapproved of Zedillo's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   South Africa: New Rights Panel
</P>
<P>
   A special unit has been set up to decide who should be put on
trial for apartheid-era rights abuses. Parliament was told that a
team is working through hundreds of cases to set up a way of
proceeding against those who failed to ask for amnesty from the
Truth and Reconciliation Commission or who were denied amnesty.
Among those who could face prosecution are President Nelson
Mandela's former wife, Winnie Madikizela-Mandela, and Mangosut
Buthelezi, leader of the Inkatha Freedom Party.
</P>
<P>
   Algeria: 12 Presidential Candidates
</P>
<P>
   Officials say 12 candidates have each gathered the required
75,000 signatures of eligible voters, allowing them to stand as
candidates in the presidential election on April 15, BBC News
reported. Eight will run as independents and four as leaders of
political parties in the race to succeed President Liamine Zeroual.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia, Eritrea: Cease-Fire Plea
</P>
<P>
   The Organization of African Unity called on Ethiopia and Eritrea
to agree on an immediate cease-fire, even as Eritrea reported that
fighting continued along their disputed border. Eritrea conceded
that it had been ousted from the Badme region, the main area of
contention, and would accept an OAU proposal for peace. Ethiopia
said it had not decided whether to accept the offer.
</P>
</TEXT>
