<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PRESIDENCY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOV. BUSH SET TO NAME EXPLORATORY COMMITTEE FOR PRESIDENTIAL BID
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c. 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush will announce Tuesday that
he will form an exploratory committee, clearing the way for him to
raise and spend money while evaluating a possible bid for
president, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on condition of anonymity, Bush officials said Monday
the governor will hold an afternoon news conference at the
Governor's Mansion to make the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had said Thursday that he would announce a decision within
two weeks concerning the presidential race, and there were
indications then that his first move would be to form an
exploratory committee. The governor isn't expected to announce a
final decision regarding his candidacy until after the Texas
Legislature adjourns May 31.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Republican legislators from North Carolina, the home
state of possible presidential contender Elizabeth Dole, delivered
a message to Bush Monday: ``Bush-Dole 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   In that order.
</P>
<P>
   Joining a chorus of state legislators urging Bush to run for the
White House, the lawmakers told reporters at an Austin news
conference that they liked favorite daughter Dole but wanted the
Texas governor to lead the GOP ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the home state of Elizabeth Dole, we're proud to be here to
give our commitment ... to Governor Bush, if he runs for the
Republican nomination,'' North Carolina state Rep. David Miner
said. ``We believe and we hope Elizabeth Dole will be Governor
Bush's running mate.''
</P>
<P>
   The commitments come on top of petitions from several other
states and add to a list of fast-moving developments that suggest
that Bush is already far down the road in putting together a
presidential campaign. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   _ Bush will tap fund-raiser Jack Oliver to help lead efforts to
raise money for a presidential bid, according to The Associated
Press. Oliver used strong ties to grassroots conservatives to raise
almost $3 million for Missouri Sen. John Ashcroft, who has decided
not to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   _ Twelve Republican governors signed a petition pledging their
support to Bush, and organizers say seven more will endorse him
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, in a pattern that has become increasingly familiar, GOP
delegations from legislatures in North Carolina, South Carolina and
Connecticut urged Bush to get into the race.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he or his staff had coordinated the visits, Bush
described them as ``spontaneous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously it requires, when people express a desire to come
down, a certain sense of coordination, so both of our calendars can
be coordinated,'' Bush said. ``I don't want people coming to Texas,
and I'm not available for lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he paid for the lunch out of political funds raised
for his gubernatorial campaign. He has not begun to collect money
for his expected national committee, which, unlike the state
operation, must abide by limits of $1,000 on contributions from
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Miner, the North Carolina state representative, was asked why
most of the Republican legislators from his state are supporting
Bush over Dole. He said it is partly because Bush has been elected
twice as governor while Dole, a former secretary of transportation
and of labor, had ``only served in appointed positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Calls to Dole's Washington office were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
