<HEADER>
A3987 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHL-COLUMN-LADN     03-01 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE REFS, MERRIER TEAMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Back in September, an NHL coach was asked his
opinion of the two-referee system the league was planning to
experiment with this season.
</P>
<P>
   The coach winced, then replied, ``It means twice as many
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   But through the course of the season, opinions changed as the
two main concerns with having two referees failed to materialize.
The extra body on the ice didn't crowd the terrain. And two
referees didn't mean twice as many penalties would be called,
killing the flow of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, much previously unpenalized clutching and grabbing
behind the play was eliminated in games with two referees, and it
is for this reason that games this season have had a better flow to
them than did games the last couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a system in which the game is a little shorter and a
little more under control, and those are things that the league has
been seeking,'' said Dallas Stars general manager Bob Gainey, who
was skeptical about the experiment before the season.
</P>
<P>
   A perfect example of the benefits of having two referees (a
system the league plans to implement in the playoffs) came in the
Los Angeles Kings' recent 2-2 tie at Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   Kings defenseman Doug Bodger was sitting on the bench watching
as Flames defenseman Derek Morris cleared the puck from the other
end of the ice. Suddenly, the play was directly in front of
teammate Mattias Norstrom and Theoren Fleury (still a Flame)
battling for the puck with everyone else at the other end of the
ice, including the lone referee that night, Stephen Walkom.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury grabbed Norstrom's stick, causing Norstrom to fall to the
ice. Fleury then picked up the loose puck and scored the tying goal
on a breakaway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told (referee Walkom), `He was holding the stick,''' Bodger
said. ``(Walkom) said, `I didn't see that.' I said, `That's because
you were too far back.' Maybe with two referees, that's a different
call.''
</P>
<P>
   Avs and Av-nots: Speaking of Fleury, the Sunday trade that sent
him to Colorado didn't enhance the Kings' chances of signing him
this summer. Denver is reasonably close to Calgary, where Fleury's
12-year-old son lives. And unlike the Kings, the Avalanche is a
Stanley Cup contender.
</P>
<P>
   By acquiring Fleury now, the Avalanche gets him for its Stanley
Cup run this season, and has his exclusive bargaining rights for
the next four months. Fleury has insisted he won't sign until
testing the open market, but who knows?
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side for the Kings, Fleury is not the only key
player Colorado must worry about signing this summer. Heading
Colorado's list is star center Peter Forsberg.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury recently said he rejected a four-year, $25-million offer
from the Kings that would have triggered a trade early last month.
It remains to be seen whether a similar offer from the Kings will
be enough to entice Fleury this summer, if he's even still
available.
</P>
<P>
   End of an era? Wayne Gretzky hasn't said anything to spur the
speculation, but there is some thought that hockey's all-time
leading scorer may be considering retiring following this season.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky, who turned 38 in January, will miss up to a month with
a back injury, the New York Rangers announced last week. He remains
among the league leaders in assists this season, but has scored
just eight goals and has an abysmal minus-21 defensive rating.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, when the Rangers visited Edmonton recently,
Gretzky gave his former boss, Oilers general manager Glen Sather,
an autographed stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thanked me for all the things I'd done for him,'' Sather
said. ``Pretty nostalgic stuff. I was thinking later, `Is this
Wayne's way of saying he's quitting?' I told Wayne he should just
quit the Rangers, move his family to Edmonton, put his kids in our
great school system, put them in our hockey programs. I told him
he'd have to play for free, for old time's sake.''
</P>
<P>
   Buying Lemieux: The Pittsburgh Penguins expect to lose more than
$20 million this season. Pittsburgh Mayor Tom Murphy said he will
not build a new arena for current team owners, but hasn't ruled out
building one if retired Penguins superstar Mario Lemieux ends up
buying the team with his group of investors, which appears more
likely than not.
</P>
<P>
   Women's clinic: The Kings and Iceoplex will host a women's
hockey clinic Wednesday, with sessions scheduled for 6:30-7:45 p.m.
and 8-9:15 p.m. The clinic will be conducted by Annie Camins, a
1998 finalist for the U.S. Women's Olympic team. Cost of the clinic
is $25, which includes a ticket to the Kings-Panthers game on Mar.
20.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (310) 419-3815.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
