<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-CAVS-265&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS FIND THE PERFECT ELIXIR FOR THEIR 2-GAME LOSING STREAK
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Knicks played a team in a bigger rut than
themselves Monday night at Madison Square Garden. And though they
went through their routine misadventures against the Cleveland
Cavaliers, Patrick Ewing and his desperate teammates finally seemed
to understand how to win a basketball game again.
</P>
<P>
   It began with pretty offense, ended with ornery defense and
produced an 85-78 victory before a crowd that alternated between
frustrated and euphoric _ depending on the possession.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks won their seventh straight at the Garden, but more
important extricated themselves from a two-game slump that had
featured two embarrassing losses on the road. The Cavaliers came
within 6 points in the final minutes, but the Knicks would have
none of a last-minute comeback on their home floor.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Childs pumped in a huge 3-pointer with 4 minutes 2 seconds
left, pushing the Knicks ahead by 76-66. And Larry Johnson
administered the final blow, pirouetting in the lane before softly
hitting a short jump shot with two minutes remaining that gave New
York an 80-72 lead.
</P>
<P>
   With the Atlantic Division lead at stake, the Knicks headed for
Miami and their third game in three days with renewed confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing scored 16 points, hauled down 12 rebounds and blocked 4
shots. Johnson added 16 points and Allan Houston contributed 15
points and 6 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland shot 43 free throws and was led by Shawn Kemp's 19
points and 10 rebounds. Derek Anderson added 15 points as the
Cavaliers, who were held to 29.6 percent shooting from the floor,
lost their fourth straight.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Just as the Knicks looked as if they were about to collapse in
the third quarter, the veterans _ Ewing, Houston and Johnson _
righted them from an extended slumber.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland had closed to within 4 points, 54-50, in the final
minutes of the quarter when Ewing scored from inside. Houston then
dropped in a 3-pointer with less than four minutes left and Johnson
executed a nifty up-and-under move, splitting the Cavs defense for
a layup.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, battling all night with the 6-foot-10-inch, 285-pound
Vitaly Potapenko, got behind the Ukrainian center for an easy
layup, which put the Knicks ahead by 65-52 heading into the final
period.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, a team playing its second of three games on
consecutive days _ the first time the Knicks have played three in a
row since the 1984-85 season _ was looking polished and poised,
less than 24 hours before playing the Heat in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks needed this game, having come off atrocious,
double-digit losses to Boston and Detroit over the previous three
days. The loss to the Pistons on Sunday was an 89-68 blowout in
which no one seemed to care and Johnson wondered aloud who would
provide the spark that Charles Oakley once provided.
</P>
<P>
   It could be reasoned that the Cavaliers needed it more, since
they had lost three straight. But a four-game skid in Cleveland is
exactly that, a skid. A three-game slide in New York is cause for
major introspection, a team crisis in the making.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jeff Van Gundy has been through enough of those to know
how distracting they can be. He lamented the effort the team gave
on Sunday, and wondered where the adrenaline would come from before
Monday night's game. He got some good news earlier in the day when
team doctors cleared Latrell Sprewell to practice, a development
that could lead to the team's shooting guard returning as the sixth
man as early as Friday in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy also received some good news on the floor from an
unlikely source, Dennis Scott, who had made 5 of 24 3-pointers
entering the game and played only five minutes in the loss to
Detroit. He finally found his range from the 3-point line, making
three from the same spot on the left wing in the second quarter,
the third one giving the Knicks a 39-26 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks appeared to be on their way to a rare blowout,
building a 16-point lead. But Cleveland went on a 12-4 run at the
end of the quarter to close to within 48-40 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   The usual culprits _ ragged offense, lethargic defense and no
rebounding to speak of _ sprouted in the second quarter and
remained through most of the third until the Knicks finally started
to play inspired ball.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp had controlled the middle early. He scored 9 points in the
first quarter, maneuvering his hefty frame inside for easy baskets.
Coming into training camp at about 300 pounds, Kemp was ridiculed
for gaining about 40 pounds in the off season. But his bulk has
enabled him to bang more inside. l
</P>
</TEXT>
