<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS DUO MAKES HISTORY IN OWN WAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Last week it was Pudge Rodriguez, hurting
nothing except his image, but why say something that stupid? ``I'm
not a team leader,'' was his answer for an unexcused, tardy arrival
at the Rangers' spring training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday it was Juan Gonzalez, also late for spring training,
but unlike Pudge, he had cleared it with team management. Another
difference was Juan being a charming diplomat as the media horde
peppered him with first-day questions.
</P>
<P>
   Score one for Juan. And made it an E-2 for Pudge.
</P>
<P>
   But after taking in both Juan-Pudge arrival scenes from a nearby
clubhouse locker, first baseman Rafael Palmeiro offered a new and
old slant to the latest adventures of the Rangers' golden boys.
New, because Rafael was in Baltimore the last five years. Old,
because Rafael was with the Rangers when Gonzalez and Rodriguez
launched their major-league careers in the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan is growing in his understanding of what the game is all
about beyond the field,'' said Palmeiro. ``But Pudge comes in here
the other day, talking out of frustration, and he says something he
doesn't mean, and he knows he doesn't mean it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Rodriguez did attempt to put a different spin on his
``I'm not a leader,'' gaffe. ``I meant I'm not the kind of guy to
be outspoken in \Rthe clubhouse\S,'' he said. ``If I'm gonna be a
leader, it's got to be on the field, or if someone comes to me for
advice, I certainly will help them.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not comfortable with that thing about putting a team
on my shoulders. I don't like having to tell people what they
should be doing. It's not for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   That explanation is acceptable, as opposed to the one last week,
which sounded foolish coming from a still young, but veteran star
player who makes $8 million a season. Rodriguez has been around
long enough to know better. Maybe he should be taking a read from
Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Pudge debuted in Arlington at age 19, Juan at age 20. Both
arrived hailed as ``the future of the franchise.'' Both have lived
up to the baseball billing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the incredible part,'' said Palmeiro. ``They've had
this huge spotlight on them from Day One, and with that comes a lot
of responsibility. At times, maybe they've disappointed, but I'm
not sure that any of us _ fans, media or other players _ fully
realize what we're seeing here.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro mentioned the duo of Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex Rodriguez
in Seattle. ``That's the only other organization in baseball,'' he
said, ``that has two homegrown players who, based on their careers
at the moment, are headed for the Hall of Fame. We are watching
history being made, but when you are this close to it, you don't
necessarily see it. And maybe they don't realize it, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Start adding up the combined MVP awards, all-star game
appearances, home-run titles, Gold Gloves, etc., and the Juan-Pudge
``homegrown'' duo is unmatched, save for the Seattle pair.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's unheard of in today's game is an organization keeping
two players together of Juan and Pudge's caliber,'' said manager
Johnny Oates. ``With Griffey and \RAlex\S Rodriguez there is now a
question of how long they stay together in Seattle. But look at
Pudge and Juan in Arlington.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, at age 29, has played eight major-league seasons and
been in the Rangers' system for 13 years. Pudge, at age 27, has
played seven seasons and been in the organization 11 years. And
this in the U-Haul era of players moving constantly.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey has spent 10 seasons with the Mariners, and Rodriguez
has been in Seattle three years, but both have talked recently of
taking free-agency walks in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The organization has grown up around Pudge and Juan, and
vice-versa,'' said Rangers hitting instructor Rudy Jaramillo, a
rookie-league coach for both players when they were 16 years old.
``Pudge and Juan have felt comfortable here throughout their
careers. The questions on both have always been there about
attitude and commitment. But both are still young, and because of
the talent they have, and the success they've achieved, the
spotlight gets bigger all the time. More is always expected from
both.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, coming off his second MVP season in three years, is
now praised for an ever-improving ``attitude.'' Pudge, however,
suffered a setback last week, meaning new doubts in that area were
raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pudge will be fine,'' said Palmeiro. ``No matter how long
you've been in this game, or how good you are, it's still a
learning process every day. And that includes even when you've
established Hall of Fame credentials, like Pudge.''
</P>
<P>
   A late arrival in Florida means zilch. But how Juan handled it,
compared to Pudge, said a little something about both.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
