<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-CELTICS-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN HORN'S SHOT AT BUZZER STOPS NETS' LONG SLIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Before Monday night's game, Nets Coach John Calipari
talked of going to church on Sunday and realizing that life is
bigger than a basketball game. He spoke of teaching his players to
believe in positive psychology and ignoring the pains in their
bodies, of just about anything of a spiritual and mental nature
that might help the Nets overcome. And finally, they did.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Van Horn rebounded Eric Murdock's missed shot and hit a
10-foot baseline jumper as the buzzer sounded to give the Nets a
99-97 victory over the Boston Celtics and end the club's grueling
six-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn, the Nets' star forward, had struggled in the final
minutes. Isolated in the post, he missed four baseline jumpers,
including one that was blocked by Paul Pierce, down the stretch,
and two free throws with 58 seconds left that could have put the
Nets ahead by 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting open looks and the ball was just short,'' he
said. ``That last shot was short too, but fortunately we got a high
bounce and it fell.''
</P>
<P>
   As for those missed foul shots, Van Horn, a 79 percent
free-throw shooter, said: ``I never miss those down the stretch.
But all that matters is that I made that last shot.''
</P>
<P>
   He also committed the foul that allowed Andrew DeClercq to make
a free throw and tie the game at 97-97 with 7 seconds remaining
after Chris Gatling's follow of a Van Horn miss had given New
Jersey a 97-96 lead. Following a timeout, the Nets went to Kerry
Kittles, who drove the lane, and found a wide-open Murdock on the
baseline. But Murdock, who had made a 3-pointer and two foul shots
in the last three minutes, missed, setting up Van Horn's rebound
and shot.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn released the ball with two-tenths of a second
remaining. He was wide open. The ball hit the side of the rim and
bounced about a foot in the air, before falling through.
</P>
<P>
   After Murdock had missed, a horde of players went for the
rebound and Gatling got a hand on it, directing it to Van Horn. ``I
was just trying to keep the ball alive,'' Gatling said. ``I just
got a little piece of it. And Keith was right there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did any team in this league deserve that ball to bounce and go
in more than us?'' asked Calipari. ``Come on now. It's amazing how
when you're losing games, the players are questioned and the coach
is questioned in a big way. And you should be when you're losing as
much as we're losing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets led by 89-83 with 4 minutes 55 seconds remaining but
Boston rallied to tie it at 95-95 and took the lead 96-95 on a
driving layup and free throw by Kenny Anderson with 49 seconds
left.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn and Kittles had 20 points apiece for the Nets,
following Kendall Gill's 23. Jason Williams had 16 rebounds and 10
points for New Jersey before fouling out late in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Antoine Walker led Boston with 21 points and Pierce added 20.
The Nets improved to 3-10 while Boston fell to 6-6 as its
three-game winning streak ended.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Nets led by as many as 12 points in the second quarter and
by 7 at halftime. But Boston, with its unceasing pressure on both
ends of the floor, closed the gap quickly, outscoring the Nets by
16-9 in the first half of the third period to force the game's
first tie at 57-57. Moments later, Dana Barros drove around Damon
Jones to give the Celtics their first lead (68-67) on a 13-foot
jumper.
</P>
<P>
   In what has been a rare sight this season, the Nets responded
nicely, going ahead by 74-71 at the end of the third on a 3-pointer
by Kittles.
</P>
<P>
   As they have done numerous times during their losing streak, the
Nets started off hot. Welcoming Boston's challenge to play at a
feverish pace, they scored the game's first 8 points, 6 of them on
dunks.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics, who missed their first seven shots, got untracked
midway through the quarter and pulled within 3 at 20-17 on a jumper
by Andrew DeClercq, but the Nets pushed the advantage back to 6
points heading into the second.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey built its lead by attacking Boston's pressure and
turning the Celtics' aggressiveness against them. The strategy
resulted in the Nets getting layups or dunks on 9 of their 12
first-quarter baskets.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn was the recipient of most of the gimmes, making two
dunks and two layups in scoring 10 early points.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly enjoying the up-and-down tempo, the Nets increased the
lead to double digits (37-26) on a five-foot running jumper by Van
Horn at the 5:40 mark. Though his team was in command, Calipari had
to be nervous about the final minutes of the half. The Nets had
dropped 14-point second-quarter leads in their last two losses and
in both games, the shift in momentum occurred near the close of the
half.
</P>
<P>
   A similar collapse appeared imminent when the Celtics put
together a barrage of slashing dunks and layups and then pulled
within 5 at 39-34 on jumper by Ron Mercer. But in displaying a
resiliency that has been absent for most of the season, the Nets
rallied to go ahead by 12 points before taking a 48-41 lead into
the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Van Horn, who had 14 points, Kittles played a
strong first half. The lanky shooting guard had been in a
season-long slump, shooting 32 percent from the field, but he made
5 of 7 field goals to score 10 points before the break.
</P>
<P>
   Walker and Pierce, the catalysts of Boston's victory at
Continental Arena on Saturday, scored 10 first-half points apiece.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
