<SLUG> BC-STUDENT-VIOLENCE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY INTERVENTION CUTS VIOLENCE, SAYS STUDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH TEICHROEB  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A University of Washington study that tracked 600
Seattle schoolchildren for a dozen years found that teaching social
skills and cooperation early to elementary students reduced violent
behavior, alcohol abuse and sexual activity, while boosting
academic performance.
</P>
<P>
   The study, released Monday by the UW's Social Development
Research Group, found that students who participated between first
and sixth grades ended up with better marks and fewer problems than
their peers through age 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows that what parents and teachers do in early grades
has long-term effects,'' said David Hawkins, the lead author of the
study and a social work professor at the UW.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a panacea, but it is something that we can do at a
reasonable cost to reduce violence and dangerous sexual activity
while helping children improve their academic achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   The program combined special training for students in basic
social skills and conflict resolution with giving teachers better
classroom management tools and offering parents classes in positive
discipline and other strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Children who hit other students were taught how to solve
problems peacefully, while teachers learned how to control their
classes without yelling. Parents developed new strategies for
setting limits at home and worked on helping their children develop
good study habits.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that by age 18, students who took part in the
full program were nearly 20 percent less likely to commit violent
acts and 38 percent less likely to drink heavily than students who
did not receive that training. Full participants also were 35
percent less likely to have caused a pregnancy or become pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Students in the full program averaged a 2.42 grade point
average, while children who did not receive any training averaged
2.18.
</P>
<P>
   Only 13 percent of low-income students in the full program
failed a grade, while 30 percent of poor children who did not get
that help were held back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found they were just more committed to getting an education
and more bonded to their school experience,'' Hawkins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of investment in the front end isn't just about
being touchy-feely _ it really can work.''
</P>
<P>
   The total cost for children in the full six-year program was
about $3,000 per student.
</P>
<P>
   The study was financed by several public and private
organizations, including the National Institute on Drug Abuse, the
federal Office of Juvenile Justice and Delinquency Prevention, the
Robert Wood Johnson Foundation and the Burlington Northern
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers began in 1981 when they assigned 600 elementary
students from 18 inner-city Seattle public schools to three
different groups.
</P>
<P>
   About one-third of the children were in the full intervention
group and received special training in social skills and
cooperative learning in first grade, and then again in sixth grade.
Their teachers received training throughout those years, while
their parents were also offered several classes.
</P>
<P>
   The students' training included everything from learning how to
take turns to empathizing with others' feelings and talking out
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't assume that all children have learned about how to
control aggressive impulses by the time they get to kindergarten,''
Hawkins said.
</P>
<P>
   In sixth grade, the students were taught ``refusal skills,'' or
how to say no without losing face with their friends.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers of students in the full program received five days of
professional development each year until the children finished
sixth grade. That training stressed classroom management skills,
including positive discipline, fostering teamwork and monitoring
all students' progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some teachers who weren't too excited about this at
first,'' Hawkins said. ``But by the end of the year, they were
saying it was their best class ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents also were offered two sessions of parenting classes
while their children were in elementary school. Just over 40
percent of those parents participated.
</P>
<P>
   Another one-third of students enrolled in the study did not
receive any special training until they were sixth-graders. Their
parents were offered classes during fifth and sixth grade, while
their teachers also received training.
</P>
<P>
   The final one-third of students, as well as their teachers and
parents, did not receive any extra training and acted as a control
group.
</P>
<P>
   Students were not told which of the three groups they had been
assigned to, and most did not know their status when they were
interviewed at age 18. Forty-five students could not be located for
the final interviews.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that students in the late intervention group,
who didn't get help until sixth grade, had more behavior problems
and less academic success than those who received help earlier,
Hawkins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a country investing huge amounts in locking people up
after they have been violent,'' Hawkins said. ``But we don't
seriously invest in them when we should.''
</P>
<P>
   A cost-benefit analysis of the study by an independent
researcher has found that the reduction in violent behavior alone
paid for the cost of providing the program, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Hawkins also cautioned that while the program reduced
violence, alcohol abuse and sexual activity, those behaviors were
not eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   For example, almost half the students in the full program did
commit a violent act during their school years.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that taking part in the program did not
significantly reduce drug abuse and cigarette smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins suggested that designing a program that would extend
into middle schools might produce even better results.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins and other researchers are continuing to follow these
students as part of another 800-student long-term study.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
