<P>
   SCI-SMOKING-CESSATION (Undated) _ A new approach combining an
anti-depressant, nicotine-replacement and counseling is sharply
increasing the chance of success of people who are trying to give
up smoking. By Holcomb B. Noble.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients. Photos
[NYT14,15) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LOWCOST-ROCKETS (Washington) _ An experimental rocket that
is at the heart of NASA's plans to develop a low-cost, reusable
vehicle that might eventually replace the space shuttle has fallen
more than a year behind schedule for its first flight because of
mounting technical problems. By Warren E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients. Photo
[NYT3) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EARLIER-SPRINGS (Undated) _ Separate studies using different
methods in the last three years have found that as the earth's
atmosphere warms, spring is arriving earlier and autumn is coming
later in the Northern Hemisphere. But much of the evidence has been
indirect. Now a direct examination of the actual behavior of plants
across Europe appears to confirm the earlier findings. By William
K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT6) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FEAR (Undated) _ An examination of what psychologists call
the fearful by nature. It's not a disease, but a temperamental
flavor. An essay by Natalie Angier.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OCTUPLETS-EYES (Undated) _ Doctors treating the seven
remaining octuplets are on the lookout for retinopathy of
prematurity, a condition that could leave them blind. While they
are all doing well, the status of their eyesight will be in doubt
for weeks. Doctors are using lasers to help prevent the retina from
detaching, but that carries the risk of limiting the victim's side
vision. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CIRCUMCISION (Undated) _ The American Academy of Pediatrics,
which issued a new circumcision policy yesterday, has had three
different policies in as many decades. In the 1970s, the academy
said there was no ``medical indication'' for circumcision. In 1989,
it reported ``potential medical benefits.'' Now, the 55,000-member
academy has concluded that while there are potential benefits, the
data are ``not significant enough'' to recommend routine
circumcision. By Deborah Stead.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-BLACKS (Undated) _ Ministers and imams in conservative
denominations with black parishes are beginning to talk about AIDS
to their congregations, though in limited ways. By Nadine Brozan.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients. Photos
[NYT7.8) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BREAST-CANCER (Undated) _ The American Cancer Society and
the National Comprehensive Cancer Network have published
breast-cancer treatment guidelines that they say are the first ones
specifically written to give patients information on
``gold-standard cancer treatment.'' By Denise Grady.
</P>
